<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE WAKES UP FOR CLOSER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the bulldozers warming up in the parking lot,
the Los Angeles Dodgers refused to throw any more dirt on
themselves during Sunday's final home game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   They know the winter will be busy, but they also wanted to send
the fans off with a smile. By beating San Diego 10-7 in front of
46,177 on Fan Appreciation Day at Dodger Stadium, they accomplished
that for one afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It started before the game when Dodgers players stood at the
entrances to greet fans. Some fans were angry at the club's poor
showing (74-82), some thanked the players for a ``memorable''
season. In all, 3,095,345 fans watched the club this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy just thought I was someone just standing around in a
blue shirt,'' said first baseman Eric Karros, who later tied a
career high with his 34th homer. ``One Padres fan said, `See you in
San Diego next year.' But I think most of them knew there was no
one more frustrated about this year than us.''
</P>
<P>
   One example of the Dodgers too-little, too-late season was the
power surge Sunday by Karros, Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi. Each
hit homers, just the second time that has happened this season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Karros, Sheffield hit his 31st home run and
second in two games. It gave him 37 RBI in his last 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's was a two-run shot in the fourth inning that gave
Dodgers rookie left-hander Jeff Williams a 4-1 lead. Williams
couldn't hold it, giving up a game-tying home run to Reggie Sanders
in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But for Mondesi, the afternoon was significant. He now has 32
homers and 92 RBI, both career highs. He also has 33 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe just as important? The boos, which hounded Mondesi
after his profanity-laced tirade last month in Montreal, have
subsided. Fans gave him Sunday's loudest cheers when he reached
home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good to see Mondy go out on a high note,'' said manger
Davey Johnson, whose club moved past San Diego into third place in
the NL West. ``It has been a long season for him, but he is showing
just the kind of player he is. We can all carry a good thought into
the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, who has two years and $20.5 million left on his
contract, could be traded during the offseason. So could Karros,
who will make $5 million in 2000, the final year in his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' home run, the highlight of a six-run seventh, was the
211th of his career, tying him with Steve Garvey for second place
and moving him within 17 of Ron Cey's all-time L.A. record. His 112
RBI also are a season high.
</P>
<P>
   Two players who were not in the starting lineup, Eric Young and
Devon White, might be elsewhere next season even though they have
years remaining on their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the Dodgers have $66 million in guaranteed contracts
for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be plenty of time to think about all that, but I
like a lot of the pieces we have here right now,'' Johnson said.
``It just felt good to send the fans home a winner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
