<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBANEZ HOMER IN NINTH SINKS ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With one swing, it was over for the Mariners _ the
game, the first tour of Safeco Field, and possibly a last look at
Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez as teammates in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Ibanez pulled the curtain, smacking a leadoff home run in
the bottom of the ninth inning Sunday to beat the Anaheim Angels,
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time to pack up the club and send it on to Texas,
Oakland and points unknown.
</P>
<P>
   After socking his game-winner, Ibanez stood in the clubhouse,
beamed over his good fortune and spoke of the future. At opposite
ends, Griffey and Rodriguez shrugged off possibilities beyond the
coming week, one cracking jokes, the other maintaining a stoic
posture, in the face of uncertainty over impending contract
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when you know when you're out of here, is when people
start asking for things _ `Hey, you all need those spikes?' ''
quipped Griffey, who sat in his white Mariners uniform for the
longest time before showering, addressing a steady stream of
well-wishers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stirring end to an emotional afternoon, one witnessed
by a crowd of 44,485 _ the Mariners' 30th sellout in 42 games at
Safeco Field, where they won 23 games. The club drew 1,816,504 fans
to the new ballpark and 2,960,803 counting Kingdome games,
averaging 43,250 at Safeco, 36,010 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Most were left wondering if they have to wait until the 2001
All-Star game to see Griffey and Rodriguez together again.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Seattle's superstars went hitless, though each provided
a run. They deferred lead roles to players in search of steady
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Capping his first full big league season in a big way, Ibanez
hit the first pitch to him by Shigetoshi Hasegawa into the
right-field seats for his seventh homer, 361 feet away. That gave
the Mariners a club-record 18 consecutive games with a long ball,
and third game-ender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about laying down a bunt,'' Ibanez said.
</P>
<P>
   His heroics made a winner out of hard-throwing reliever Tom
Davey (2-1), one of four rookies sent to the mound in a close game.
Davey did something virtually unheard of for a Mariners pitcher
since Randy Johnson left town _ he struck out the side in the top
of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   He succeeded Sinclair, who was as stubborn as Davey was
overpowering. The lefty entered in the seventh inning with a runner
on third and one out. Sinclair, acquired from Toronto with Davey in
a midseason traded for first baseman David Segui, fell behind Todd
Greene 3-and-1, battled him until he struck out the pinch-hitter
with his 11th pitch, then got an inning-ending grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts came after starter Robert Ramsay gave a clear
indication of his promise. Ramsay retired the first eight batters
he faced and permitted just five hits and two runs in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   As the pitching slowly falls into place for the Mariners, they
are left to ponder whether their big bats will be around to back
it.
</P>
<P>
   With no veto power over his trade prospects, Rodriguez said
there is ``obvious doubt'' whether he will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a situation like this, I have to expect the very worst,''
the shortstop said. ``I can't sit back and think it's pretty as
pink. The Mariners have to go out and make a shrewd business
decision. It will be interesting. I love Seattle, but I love
winning a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   If the decision is left in his hands, Rodriguez says he will be
in no hurry to determine his future, whether to re-sign with the
M's or choose another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait and see,'' he said. ``There's no timetable.
I could wait until after the year 2000 to make a decision if I have
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who has the right to nix any deal, was evasive about
his plans, other than to indicate that he is in full control of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my decision,'' he said. ``I'm going to talk it over with
my wife. It's cut and dried. First I'm going to play golf. When I
make up my mind, I make up my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   If only everything could be as easy as a Raul Ibanez homer.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
