<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-HOUSTONGP-HNS &LR;      09-27 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-HOUSTONGP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Paul Tracy was the Team Kool Green goat last year at Houston
because of a collision that almost cost teammate Dario Franchitti a
victory.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Tracy looked at the gold cowboy boot Sunday that was his
trophy for winning the second Texaco/Havoline Grand Prix of
Houston, he remembered that frustrating mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be holding this boot in my hand instead of having
it up my butt,'' Tracy said.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy didn't make any mistakes this year, finishing more than 13
seconds ahead of Franchitti to win the downtown street race and
make Team Kool Green undefeated in two trips to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a good day for the Newman/Haas team of Michael
Andretti and Christian Fittipaldi, who finished third and seventh,
respectively, in the race that bears the name of their team
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Tracy's day of redemption, and the only thing that
was going to keep the 30-year-old Canadian from winning Sunday was
a possible team order to let Franchitti move ahead of him to take
the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti is battling Juan Montoya for the 1999 CART FedEx
championship, and he could have gained an additional four points by
finishing first Sunday. Team owner Barry Green considered giving
the order to have Tracy let Franchitti go by, but Green decided
against it with three laps to go in the 100-lap event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I just hope we don't lose (the championship) by four
points,'' Green said. ``But Paul worked so hard. He deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti had no problem with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been different if I had been right on Paul's
gearbox,'' he said. ``Paul was dominating the race. There was no
way we should do anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy was asked what he would have done had Green asked him to
let Franchitti win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I would have said (simulating a static sound), `Sorry,
I can't hear you,''' Tracy joked.
</P>
<P>
   It still was a good day for Franchitti, who gained 16 points on
Montoya and pulled within 13 points of the top spot in the
championship chase with two races remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly helps things,'' said Franchitti. ``It's not
over yet. Things are looking a lot better than they did last week.
It's going to be interesting now.''
</P>
<P>
   Any chance Montoya had of clinching the FedEx championship came
to an end on lap 13 when the crowd of 45,000 watched him crash into
the stalled car of Helio Castro-Neves.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, who started on the pole, was leading the race and
turning onto the frontstretch when he couldn't avoid Castro-Neves,
who had slid into a tire barrier on Turn 10 a few seconds earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A full-course yellow came out a couple of seconds before Montoya
reached Turn 10, but it was too late. Montoya's right front tire
slammed into the left rear tire of Castro-Neves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a miscommunication,'' Montoya said. ``It has
happened before, and it will happen again. Nobody told me there was
an incident there. Nobody told me anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me there was a yellow, but I didn't know where. I
backed off, but the (Castro-Neves) car was right in the middle of
the track. I tried to hit the brakes and make the turn, but I
couldn't. It's really disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Montoya, Tracy said he was aware of trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew exactly where the car (of Castro-Neves) was,'' Tracy
said. ``They told me on the radio, and I already had begun to slow
down when I saw Juan hit him. I managed to get around both of them,
and then I told myself, `OK, now don't make any mistakes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Castro-Neves seemed more upset that he had caused Montoya to
crash than he was about his own car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for someone to hit me, because it was a bad
spot,'' Castro-Neves said. ``But the last one I wanted to hit me
was Juan. I'm so sorry. It was my mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``All weekend I was using second gear (on the turns), but
because the pace was so slow, I was using first gear. When I went
into Turn 10, I forgot and left it in second and went straight into
the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy knows the feeling. He was running second behind Franchitti
last year in Houston when the two cars collided, ending the day for
Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   Green was furious with Tracy for hitting Franchitti in an overly
aggressive move that could have cost Franchitti the race in the
rain-shortened event.
</P>
<P>
   That incident was one of the reasons Tracy was suspended from
the first race of the 1999 season, but he has managed to overcome
that handicap and have one of the best seasons of his career.
</P>
<P>
   With his second victory of the year, Tracy ranks third in the
points standings despite having sat out the first event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really feel redeemed by this,'' Tracy said. ``I feel
like I put in a lot of hard work and a lot of effort, both mentally
and physically over the winter, to do the things I needed to do to
turn my career around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've let go a lot of mental issues that I needed to let go.
It's enabled me to drive better and concentrate on moving
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy took a big step forward Sunday by erasing a ghost from the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say any place owes me one, but I got it right this
year,'' Tracy said. ``I think I've matured a lot as a racer, and it
shows. Today was my day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
