</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6989 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CYBERTIMES-INTERNET-T     09-27 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-INTERNET-TRENDY-IN-EUROPE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE'S INTERNET LAG: AN AMERICAN FABRICATION?
</HEADLINE>
  By BRUNO GIUSSANI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   GENEVA -- Attend a conference or read an article about the
Internet in Europe, and there will almost certainly be a reference
to estimates that Europe is two or three years behind the United
States when it comes to doing business online.
</P>
<P>
   Recently a magazine in the United States put the figure at five
years -- placing Europe in a time when Amazon.com was still just an
idea in Jeff Bezos's head.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet executives in Europe say the size of the gap has
been exaggerated. And some blame the perception problem on American
Internet companies that have made missteps in the European market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an urban legend,'' said Laurent Edel, the founder of the
Net Economy Workshop, which pairs technology start-ups with
investors. ``Look beyond Internet penetration rates, which are kept
artificially low by telecommunication costs, and you will realize
that European companies are less far behind than the press reports.
The market is heating up at incredible speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The European Internet scene may not have the hyped-up glamour
and the overnight billionaires of Silicon Valley, but it has other
elements that characterize the industry: thousands of energetic
young entrepreneurs that are turning business rules upside-down, a
booming venture capital industry to fund them, established
companies scrambling to keep pace, skyrocketing initial public
offerings and half a dozen new stock markets. New magazines like
Amsterdam-based Tornado-Insider cover the industry and its rising
stars, and successful high-tech networking events like Edel's
workshops and First Tuesday span the continent.
</P>
<P>
   According to the investment bank Broadview International, 155
European technology companies went public on Europe's stock markets
last year, compared with 147 American companies on United States
markets. In some sectors like online banking or mobile phones,
Europe is even ahead of the United States, with countries like
Italy and Finland counting more cell phone subscribers than fixed
lines. And while consumer Internet use may have been slow to take
off, European companies are making wise use of networking
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Europe still perceived as being in Internet limbo? Ola
Ahlvarsson, the chief executive of Result Ventures Knowledge, a
Stockholm-based Internet consulting firm, suggests that the
misperception may be the result of American companies' failures at
penetrating European markets -- and their inclination to blame
their problems on the high cost of telecommunications services and
an immature market.
</P>
<P>
   With the sole exception of Yahoo, American companies have indeed
had a harder-than-expected time establishing themselves in Europe,
even in the friendly British market. Freeserve, a startup company
offering free Internet access, took just six months to overtake
America Online's local service as the leading access provider in
Britain, forcing AOL to respond by offering its own free access
plan. AOL is also a distant second in Europe's other key Internet
markets, Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
   Portal sites like Excite and Lycos, which are among the top
sites in the United States, are barely noticed in Europe. The
online auctioneer eBay recently bought a tiny German auction site,
while Amazon.com bought online booksellers in Germany and Britain
last year, but these remain marginal operations for the American
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans think that the Internet and electronic commerce are
global,'' Ahlvarsson said in a phone interview. ``Well, more
surprises are ahead for them.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Europe has turned out to be a tough market for United
States companies to unlock is that most of them have underestimated
the importance of local conditions. The slogan ``think globally,
act locally'' may not capture the extent of the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you will have to think locally in each of the national
markets,'' said Fabiola Arredondo, a native of Spain who leads
Yahoo's operations in seven European countries.
</P>
<P>
   There are the obvious hurdles, for which most businesses are
more or less prepared: different currencies, tax regimes and trade
regulations. But there are also profound national characteristics,
both cultural and practical, that are too often overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   On the legal side, for example, the ability of companies to
gather and sell data on consumers is drastically limited by the
European Union's regulations on privacy protection. This makes it
difficult in some cases to take systems based on profiling, cookie
technology and other more sophisticated mechanisms and transfer
them to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Even registering an Internet domain name can be a long and
painful process in some countries, because companies are often
restricted to owning only one domain name, which must be approved
by regulatory authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a name that can be built into a brand can be tricky.
Ahlvarsson cited the example of a customer who was developing an
e-commerce site that offered gift ideas. He said the customer
``wanted to call it 'getgift.com,' which makes total sense in
English, but literally means 'go get poison for goats' in
Swedish.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly minor details like differences in mailbox sizes or
credit-card habits can also affect e-commerce operations. ``If you
charge a premium for guaranteed overnight delivery of books and
CDs, but the package doesn't fit in the mailbox of the customer and
goes back to the postal office waiting for him to pick it up, well,
one of your competitive advantages evaporates,'' said Ahlvarsson.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing and public relations copy is another pitfall a lot of
American companies have encountered. Europeans, unlike Americans,
are not used to aggressive marketing assaults. Merely translating
copy, while cost-effective, can result in a misfire.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, even English is different. ``What we discovered is
that the use of Americanisms in our British site, such as
'favorite' vs. 'favourite,' was not considered an Americanism by
our customers, but a spelling mistake,'' said Carl Leubsdorf, the
developer in charge of localizing parts of the Motley Fool's Web
site for Britain.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there are the cultural subtleties. Ikea,
the Swedish furniture giant, is one company that has interpreted
these well. Its sites for various European countries are in tune
with the local customer base: the Italian one is stylish, the
German is more traditional, and the Saudi Arabian site features a
reassuring father-and-son shopping scene. Ikea even gave up the
standard yellow and blue colors of its logo on the Danish site,
switching to red and white so as not to impose the colors of the
Swedish flag on the sensitive Danes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Content is much harder to transpose than anything else,'' said
Yahoo's Arredondo. ``We put all our energy into local teams and
local partnerships.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this fragmentation and diversity also makes it
difficult for European companies to target customers elsewhere in
Europe, which in turn creates additional business opportunities.
That is the niche Ola Ahlvarsson has found for his new company,
Result Ventures Knowledge, which assists Internet ventures trying
to expand across the continent by offering help and advice on
recruitment, management, strategic alliances, entry strategies,
office space and legal procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Larry Levy, chief executive of Protege, offers the
same services to American companies trying to replicate their
success in European markets. Levy's first piece of advice:
``Entering Europe is not about parachuting the products over here.
It's about transposing the whole operational chain into a series of
very different markets''
</P>
<P>
   Related Sites:
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com: http://www.amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   Net Economy Workshop: http://www.neworkshop.com
</P>
<P>
   Tornado-Insider Magazine: http://www.tornado-insider.com
</P>
<P>
   First Tuesday: http://www.firsttuesday.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   Result Ventures Knowledge: http://www.resultventures.com
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, Britain: http://www.yahoo.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   America Online: http://www.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Freeserve: http://www.freeserve.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   Excite: http://www.excite.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, Germany: http://www.lycos.de
</P>
<P>
   eBay, Germany: http://www.ebay.de
</P>
<P>
   Motley Fool, Britain: http://www.fool.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   Ikea: http://www.ikea.com
</P>
<P>
   Protege: http://www.protege.co.uk/
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Giussani at eurobytes(AT)nytimes.com welcomes your
comments and suggestions.
</P>
</TEXT>
