<HEADER>
A6996 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-27 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
YOU don't concede a 10-foot birdie putt when it's all square on the
last hole of the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   You don't take a knee in the fourth quarter of the Super Bowl
when it's first-and-goal with the score tied.
</P>
<P>
   Team Kool Green owner Barry Green did the right thing Sunday
afternoon. He didn't give the Texaco/Havoline Grand Prix of Houston
to the wrong guy.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't instruct Paul Tracy to ease his foot off the throttle
and concede the race to CART points-title contender and Kool Green
teammate Dario Franchitti, who was square in the middle of Tracy's
rearview mirror as this entertaining race wound to a close.
</P>
<P>
   It might not have been the best thing to do, and in the end it
might not prove to be the smartest thing. But it was the right
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy was too dominant to finish second. He was the one who had
it all on this day, everything working perfectly, every instinct
the right one, every move perfectly timed and his car running
without peer.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy earned this win, and he got it. Good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like it, but I like it,'' Green said of his decision
to leave Tracy alone at the front of the pack as he whisked to a
nearly 14-second win over Franchitti.
</P>
<P>
   Green's quandary was a captivating one throughout the day,
especially as Franchitti inched into second place after several
early troubles. Had Green instructed Tracy to allow Franchitti to
pass, Franchitti would have earned four more points than the 16 he
gained on CART season series leader Juan Montoya, whose
aggressiveness and miscommunication with Target owner Chip Ganassi
left Montoya scoreless on this day.
</P>
<P>
   Those four points certainly could prove to be the difference in
the season points race, considering Montoya still has a 13-point
lead on Franchitti with just two races remaining. The four points
might in fact cost Team Kool Green dearly in the end, considering
its intense rivalry with the Target team and all the money and
prestige that go with the season title.
</P>
<P>
   But Tracy was the best. He earned the trophy _ a golden boot _
one year after a bump and crash with Franchitti forced Tracy out of
the field and left him feeling embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be holding this boot in my hand,'' Tracy said,
``instead of having it up my butt.''
</P>
<P>
   It was nice that Green didn't rip the trophy out of Tracy's
hands for the sake of Franchitti, a move many other team owners
would have made without hesitation. Green knew this was Tracy's
dominant day, and neither Franchitti nor Tracy would have wanted
the race to end any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, I wouldn't (have wanted to give up the lead),'' Tracy
said, making mock static noises as if talking on the radio with
Green. ``I would have said, `I can't hear you. What? What are you
saying?' But I was never asked to let him pass, so I'm not going to
pull over on the side of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Franchitti: ``I was trying to catch him (Tracy), but he was
gone. If I was right up on Paul's gearbox, then maybe we would have
talked about it. But he was dominant. He just deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya's hard-charging style cost him dearly when he ran into
the broken-down Helio Castro-Neves on the 13th lap, and it soon
became clear just how dominant Tracy would be. With the
Target/Ganassi team out of sync and Montoya out of the race, no one
else could come close to Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   When informed that Ganassi said he didn't hear race officials
declare that Castro-Neves had run into the wall on Turn 10,
bottling up the tight curve, Tracy rolled his eyebrows and said,
``Maybe Chip was looking at his reflection in the monitor.''
</P>
<P>
   This indeed is an intense fight between the Target and Kool
Green teams, a season-long battle that both would dearly love to
win. But no matter how much those four extra points might mean in
the long run, Green wasn't about to take this race away from Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy broke from the second row into second place at the drop of
the green flag. When Montoya's car was disabled, Tracy took the
lead and extended it to three seconds in a matter of one lap. He
then extended the lead to eight seconds, then 14 seconds, then 20
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy ran smoothly the entire day, conserving fuel and running
hard, staying out of trouble and driving smartly while most other
drivers were forced into two pit stops and never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Green) realized it was my day,'' Tracy said. ``He
was happy to leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw the race should realize Green's non-call was the
right call. Franchitti pulled within 13 points of Montoya, and with
two races left he can still pursue the season title. But on this
day, the best driver and the best car won.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't have wanted it to end any other way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
