<HEADER>
A6998 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-27 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-UCLA STAR MCNOWN PASSES TIME IN NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ The visiting-locker-room doors swung open Sunday at
Network Associates Coliseum and a crowd quickly assembled around
the quarterback's cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Cade McNown hadn't gotten the Bears as far as midfield in
his only series in a 24-17 loss to the Raiders. But he was a
Northern California (and Oregon) kid who was schooled in Southern
California making his first appearance as a professional in the
Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Familiarity breeds fanfare and so it was starting quarterback
Shane Matthews was able to slip into the showers unbothered while
reporters stared silently at McNown's back as the former UCLA
standout stood in dress pants and power loafers, buttoning a dress
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   At length, somebody spoke up. Had McNown caught any of the
previous day's telecast of the Bruins' Pacific-10 opening loss at
Stanford, their first conference defeat since the first game of
McNown's junior year?
</P>
<P>
   Without missing a beat or a button, McNown said stiffly, ``I'll
talk with you when I'm finished dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course. When you're helpless to govern your playing time,
you have to control what you can.
</P>
<P>
   When McNown finally turned around, he was all smiles. From an
individual standpoint, he had every reason to be. Playing, as
scripted, in the Bears' first series of the second quarter, McNown
completed 3 of 5 passes for 38 yards. He looked confident and
comfortable and if it gnawed at his insides to get no more shots at
the end zone, his sideline demeanor didn't show it.
</P>
<P>
   He patted more backs than a politician at a fund-raiser, and
afterward, was every bit as diplomatic. Sure, he said, he was
pleased with his own performance. ``I'll tell you what though,'' he
added, ``the loss just sours anything I did personally.''
</P>
<P>
   The player who was being touted for the Heisman Trophy a year
ago at this time went on to laud Bears running back Curtis Enis and
kick returner Glyn Milburn.
</P>
<P>
   Until his coaches decide otherwise, that's McNown's job. He is
the NFL's highest-paid cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the sideline just trying to rev my teammates up,''
McNown said.
</P>
<P>
   It says here it's a good thing, for McNown to sit with his
engine idling for a spell. McNown's life since he entered UCLA has
gone by like scenery outside the window of a speeding car. It has
been a blur, from his first starts as a freshman to his last starts
for a national championship-contending team to his selection at No.
12 overall by Chicago in April's draft to his contract holdout to
the recent revelation that he, like 18 other UCLA football players,
had acquired a disabled-parking placard.
</P>
<P>
   When your life is going by so fast, perspective often is the
first thing to be lost. McNown has yet to apologize for having a
disabled-parking placard _ the closest he'll come is to say the way
he went about acquiring it was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He also has some amends to make with his new teammates and
football fans in Chicago after missing the first 11 days of
training camp while his agent squeezed every last dime out of the
Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, a little time out of the fast lane might do McNown a world
of good. It already appears to have benefited him. McNown is
getting smarter with every rep he takes. And he was wise enough
Sunday to scramble from any suggestion of a quarterback
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up to the coaches,'' said McNown, demurely leaving it
to others to point out how Matthews appears more nearsighted in his
choice of receivers than McNown, who really digs the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Matthews dinked the Raiders' defense nearly to death,
McNown completed the prettiest pass of the game, a 30-yard spiral
on a third-and-18 play from the Bears' 4-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   McNown released the pass with both feet in his own end zone and
it landed softly in the outstretched arms of Macy Brooks, who was
streaking down the right sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have been thrown any better,'' said Brooks, who
had Charles Woodson covering him like a tarp.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Raiders defensive end Lance Johnstone burst
into the Bears' backfield, untouched, and had McNown in his grasp
before the quarterback somehow spun free. His escape made an
impression on Raiders defensive tackle Darrell Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very surprised he didn't play more,'' Russell, formerly of
USC, said after posing for a postgame photograph with McNown. ``I'm
more scared of Cade than I am of Shane just because Cade's more
mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   When Russell's words were relayed to him later, McNown smiled
and said, ``That's very nice he says things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he stopped well short of agreeing. ``I just need to continue
to progress,'' he said. ``I just try to keep my mouth shut. I'm not
trying to push anything. I've just got to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but can he?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be patient for a little while,'' he said, then laughed.
``I guess that's not really patience, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
