<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLRING LESSON GIVEN AT FAIRPLEX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. _ Garrett Gomez is not one of the big-track
jockeys who stay away from little Fairplex Park for fear of the
sharp turns. He wasn't spooked by the fatal accident on opening
day.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez stayed away this season so he and wife Pam _ they were
married in June _ could honeymoon in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like bullrings,'' said Gomez, who used to make the hard
lefts at Maryland's Timonium racetrack, Nebraska's Fonner Park and
Chicago's Sportsmens Park. ``Bullrings teach young riders a lot.
You learn when to get in and when to get out. And if you don't (get
out of tight quarters), you get up brushing yourself off,
hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, on closing day of the L.A. County Fair season, Gomez
teamed with a Fairplex-loving gelding to stage a clinic on bullring
racing, he and 6-year-old Native Desert hugging the rail for 1[
miles to win the $100,000 Ralph M. Hinds Pomona Invitational
Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Bold Words and leading Fairplex rider Martin Pedroza finished 1\
lengths back in second. Mel Stute-trained Kona Wind came in fifth
in the six-horse field, leaving Stute and Paul Aguirre tied for the
training title with nine victories apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Native Desert, a California-bred 6-year-old claimed by trainer
Juan Garcia for $32,000 in 1996, ran his Fairplex record to 3 for
4, including a pair of sprint stakes victories in 1997. Lately he'd
been testing his cornering ability on the local turf courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure helps when you've got a horse like Native Desert who
does everything right,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez recorded his lone victory in only three rides at the
18-day fair. His scheduled races on Sept. 9 were canceled after
jockey J.C. Gonzalez was killed in an accident caused by a horse's
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have happened anywhere,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Pedroza, who rode 29 winners (to Iggy Puglisi's 23) to win his
second Fairplex title, received the first J.C. Gonzalez Memorial
Jockey Trophy in a winner's circle ceremony attended by some of
Gonzalez's family.
</P>
<P>
   Fairplex vice president for racing Neil O'Dwyer reported a
decline of about 4 percent from last year's track-record $108
million wagered at the meet. The seven canceled races accounted for
the approximately $3 million difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``After (the) tragic start, I truly believe 48 hours later
everybody had rallied and focused on the future,'' O'Dwyer said at
the top of the grandstand. ``The jockey colony pulled together on
and off the track, looked out for each other, and it made for very
safe racing.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-horse accident that killed Gonzalez had been the only
fall of the meet until Octavio Vergara went down _ not hurt
seriously _ in Sunday's 10th race.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: The Oak Tree association opens its 31st season at
Santa Anita Wednesday at 1 p.m. Pat Valenzuela, returning from
suspension after nearly two years, has four mounts on the nine-race
card. . . . Contributions are being accepted for a trust fund for
the 4- and 7-year-old children of David Hale, the Santa Anita,
Hollywood Park and Del Mar photo-finish equipment operator who was
killed in a highway accident Tuesday near Bishop. The address:
Cameron and Megan Hale Trust, c/o Julie Hale, 310 Fargo Road, San
Dimas, 91773.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
