<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-PATRIOTS-N     09-27 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-PATRIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS TOP GIANTS, 16-14 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ The New York Giants looked terrific on the
first possession of their game on Sunday night against the New
England Patriots. Unfortunately for the Giants, they had to play
the rest of the game. And they had no more tricks up their sleeve
until it was far too late.
</P>
<P>
   Another hapless offensive performance doomed the Giants at
Foxboro Stadium as they scored on their first drive of the game but
not score again until the game was all but over. Meanwhile, playing
too often, the Giants' defense eventually wore down.
</P>
<P>
   A relentless Patriots offense, led by quarterback Drew Bledsoe,
took advantage of a fatigued Giants defense to move into position
for three second-half field goals as New England remained
undefeated after three games with a 16-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants (1-2) lost for the second consecutive week after
winning their season opener at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who joined Tennessee as the only 3-0 teams, kept
pounding at the Giants. In the second half, New England was winning
the battle at the line of scrimmage and moved into position
methodically for each of its field goals, breaking open a game that
was tied at halftime, 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offense, which once again struggled mightily to move
the ball on the ground, did little against the Patriots' defense,
which pressured Giants quarterback Kent Graham throughout the game
and forced him into several hurried throws.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Giants scored a touchdown when they first had the
ball, they did not not score again until 1 minute 14 seconds
remained, when Tiki Barber caught a 1-yard touchdown pass from
Graham to cut the Patriots' lead to 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first drive I would have thought we would put a lot
more points on the board,'' said Graham, who completed 23 of 36
passes for 216 yards. ``But different things can break down. It's a
long season, and hopefully people will be patient with us. You have
to keep it in perspective. It's a 16-game season and we're 1-2.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants Coach Jim Fassel was miffed at his offense's inability to
move the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't honestly tell you exactly what was going wrong,'' he
said. ``There were different malfunctions at different times. I
think we came ready to play, and our approach to this game was much
better than last week. But we've got to get better or we're not
going to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe finished the game with 20 completions in 28 pass
attempts for 233 yards with no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the fourth quarter, an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty
on the Patriots' Tedy Bruschi gave the Giants the opportunity to
regain the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Graham had been sacked on a third-and-10 play but fumbled after
it was whistled over. In the ensuing scramble for the ball, which
was moot, Bruschi and Giants left guard Luke Petitgout tussled for
the ball. Bruschi then threw the ball at Petitgout, drawing a
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   With an automatic first down, the Giants moved into New England
territory, but Brad Daluiso missed a 41-yard field goal attempt
with slightly more than eight minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   A sequence midway through the third quarter illustrated how the
game's momentum had swung toward the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   On a fourth-and-1 at the Patriots' 40-yard line, the Giants
attempted a quarterback sneak over the right guard. It was the
second time tonight that the Giants had tried this play, and this
time New England was waiting for Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I got the first down,'' Graham said. ``With second
effort I was over the pile, over the line. It was a bad spot of the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants turned the ball over on downs, the Patriots
marched downfield on a Giants defense that was starting to look
fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were lucky to halt the drive at the 2-yard line. Adam
Vinatieri's 19-yard field goal gave the Patriots a 13-7 lead late
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri added a 41-yard field goal with just over three
minutes remaining that provided what proved to be the winning
points.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious from the beginning on Sunday night that Fassel
had designed a new offensive scheme for the game. He threw on first
down repeatedly, opened the game with two tight ends so that the
pass-catching tight end Pete Mitchell could get on the field and
started the game with a one-back formation that featured fullback
Charles Way.
</P>
<P>
   All of those things worked on the first possession but became
less effective as the game wore on.
</P>
<P>
   But the first drive, which was scripted, was the best the team's
offense has looked this season. The Giants came out throwing,
Graham trying to hit his favorite target, Amani Toomer, on the
first play. The pass was not complete, but Toomer drew a defensive
holding call, good for a first down.
</P>
<P>
   After Way rumbled for 4 yards, Fassel had Graham on the run in
the pocket, and Graham, while sprinting to his right, fired a pass
to Ike Hilliard for 27 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who has been quiet for most of the season, found a
seam in the middle of the Patriots' defense for 7 yards to extend
the drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' starting running back, Sean Bennett, ran for 1 yard
on the next play but was knocked out with a sprained right knee. A
play later, Graham, again on the move in the pocket, connected with
Hilliard again for 8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   A successful quarterback sneak on a third-and-1 moved the Giants
inside the Patriots' 10-yard line. After a 3-yard run by Way, the
Giants lined up for a second-and-6. LeShon Johnson, playing for
Bennett, lined up split wide on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   New England didn't send a defender out to cover Johnson. Seeing
this, Graham had the ball snapped quickly and threw to Johnson, who
caught the ball standing alone in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants struggled to duplicate the efficiency of that first
drive throughout the next two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was reasonably sharp, completing 12 of 16 first-half
passes, and he continued to develop rapport with Toomer and
Hilliard. But the Giants' running game once again was hopelessly
inept, averaging 2.2 yards on 26 rushing attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Way banged away, but there were few holes, and when
there were, it seemed the Giants backs were out of rhythm _ either
hitting the hole too soon or too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
