<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-STEELERSSPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS' QUICK START STUNS STEELERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Mike Holmgren was beginning to feel more than just
a little like the father to 53 belligerent kids.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks coach had harped on and harangued his new players
about getting off to fast starts, only to watch them stagger and
sputter in the first halves of their season-opening loss to the
Detroit Lions and their limp-from-behind victory last week over the
Chicago Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, after a week of heightened emphasis that at times
bordered on pleading, the message finally sunk in during the
Seahawks' stunningly easy 29-10 victory over the previously
unbeaten Pittsburgh Steelers in Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On the third play of the game, recently signed safety Merton
Hanks intercepted a Kordell Stewart pass that had caromed off
Steelers wide receiver Will Blackwell and returned it 23 yards for
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Four plays later, rookie Charlie Rogers retreated to catch Josh
Miller's 62-yard punt at the Seattle 6, only to return it a
club-record 94 yards for another touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Before their offense had even taken the field, the Seahawks were
up 14-0.
</P>
<P>
   Then, an instant before the first offensive snap, Jon Kitna
changed the play at the line of scrimmage before firing a 51-yard
pass to Mike Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   Before Holmgren could utter ``start fast,'' his team already
had. Finally and, as it turned out, unforgivingly.
</P>
<P>
   By the time this rout was over, the Seahawks had intercepted
five passes, Todd Peterson had kicked five field goals and the
Steelers had been rocked on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the game quickly, which we emphasized all week,''
Holmgren said after the Seahawks had pushed their record to 2-1 by
pushing the Steelers all over the field in their home opener that
was over by halftime, when half of the 57,881 fans had already gone
in pursuit of more satisfying activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great win.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the Seahawks' second victory after their
disheartening loss to the Lions, but their second on the road. The
Seahawks had not won successive road games since Weeks 4 and 6 of
the 1996 season, when they won in Tampa Bay and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going on the road and being able to come out with a win, it's
huge in this business,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers coach Bill Cowher still was reeling after the game over
how quickly the game had gotten away from his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threw the interception for a touchdown, then you turn
around and you can't make a third-and-inches,'' he said. ``You punt
the ball, and they return it for a touchdown. We never recovered
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the two plays that stuck out Sunday, because they
came so quickly and proved to be so decisive in a game where the
offense failed to find the end zone despite finding a way to roll
up 341 yards against a Steelers defense that entered the game
ranked second in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks didn't need anything more than Peterson's five
field goals because they got so much more from their maligned
special teams and especially their defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our defense played the most complete game I've ever
seen a defense play. Ever. Ever,'' said guard Brian Habib, who is
in his second season with the Seahawks after playing five each with
the Broncos and Vikings. ``Our defense basically won this game
today.''
</P>
<P>
   No play was bigger than Hanks' interception and TD return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped jump start us,'' Hanks said. ``That's what we were
trying to do. So that was big for us.''
</P>
<P>
   No play was longer than Rogers' punt return for a TD.
</P>
<P>
   The 94-yarder bettered the old record of 89 yards by Joey
Galloway in 1995, the rookie season for the club's leading receiver
whose holdout has now reached 59 days. Rogers' redemption return
also came two weeks after he muffed a punt return inside the 5-yard
line to setup a Lions touchdown in the opening-day loss to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Holmgren didn't cut me, he didn't even yell at me after
the play against the Lions,'' said Rogers, a fifth-round draft
choice from Georgia Tech. ``He just said, `Charlie, you're going to
be our punt returner all year and you've got to go out and make
plays.' This was just a way to tell the team I'm here to stay and
I'm going to make some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   But what made these big plays stand up were the little things
done by the defense and even the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Things like the defense harassing Stewart into such a horrendous
first-half showing that Cowher went to backup Mike Tomczak in the
second half after Stewart had completed almost half as many passes
to Seahawks (3) as he did to Steelers (7).
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like he did get frustrated, I kind of sensed it,''
defensive end Phillip Daniels said of Stewart. ``One time, I know
for sure that he threw the ball and he knew he threw an
interception. Before he even released it, he knew it was an
interception. He was frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is, we jumped on them, and it's hard to recover
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' offense also did things that frustrated the
Steelers, and even without trying.
</P>
<P>
   Things like burning up most of the 40-second clock in the huddle
before coming to the line and then getting the snap off with only
four or five seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did confuse them,'' Pritchard said. ``I noted that to our
coaches coming off the field. They were confused lining up. They
were confused matching up. They had to check to a lot of zone
coverages. I think that's the creativity that Holmgren brings.''
</P>
<P>
   The delay in breaking the huddle was not by design. But as
offensive coordinator Mike Sherman offered with a smile, ``We'll
take credit for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the ball was snapped, Kitna did a good job of getting it
off quickly to the right receiver at the right time. He completed
18 of 29 passes for 265 yards _ with Pritchard catching six passes
for 90 yards and Sean Dawkins grabbing five for 105 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna, like everyone else in the Seahawks' locker room, couldn't
help but shift the credit to where it rightfully belonged _ the
quick start.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we talked about all week to come out and start
fast,'' he said. ``It didn't matter if it was the offense, defense
or special teams. Whatever it took, we wanted to start fast.''
</P>
<P>
   That it was, in order, the defense, special teams and offense,
``That was huge for us,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
