<HEADLINE>
TRASHY YARD LANDS OLD LADY IN SLAMMER 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY DONALD BRADLEY   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Holly Steinhauser, an assistant city attorney
for Kansas City, says Frances Jane Todd is ``a sweet old lady.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Todd, 76, grandmother of 33, responds: ``Well, then why
did she throw me in the pokey?''
</P>
<P>
   Since Aug. 30, Todd has been the oldest inmate at Kansas City's
Municipal Correctional Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Her crime: a trashy yard.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser sued Todd on behalf of the city for numerous
nuisance violations. Ninety days after the verdict, because the
yard still had not been cleaned, a judge found Todd in contempt.
</P>
<P>
   And Todd found herself behind bars for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   When offered a color choice of jail suit, she chose green to
match her hazel eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She'll wear that suit every day until someone cleans up the
mess. So far, the grown relatives who live with her have been slow
to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Todd and Steinhauser are opposites in this case and, seemingly,
opposites in life. Todd works as a school bus monitor so she can
pay off her house before retiring. Steinhauser is a 29-year-old
attorney just starting a career in government.
</P>
<P>
   But they share a beginning. Both were born to farmers in the
Ozark hills. They come from a culture where people tolerate junk on
the porch, brush in the yard and a broken-down vehicle out front.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that Todd still lives that way and Steinhauser
has an office on the 27th floor at City Hall. Steinhauser's sole
duty as the city's first ``neighborhood-improvement attorney'' is
to go after chronic property code violators.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser sees the irony: Todd's house isn't much worse than
many where she grew up, including her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't feel bad about throwing her in jail,'' Steinhauser
said. ``She had every opportunity to do what she was supposed to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she won't get out until that yard is cleaned up.''
</P>
<P>
   Having explained the legal case, Steinhauser leaned forward in
her office chair and spoke of her true outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Four other adults, sometimes five, live in Todd's house in south
Kansas City. There is Todd's 41-year-old daughter, two grown
grandchildren, ages 19 and 23, and a family friend in his 40s.
Todd's 41-year-old son stays there part time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Able-bodied adults,'' Steinhauser calls them. She says it
would take the bunch two hours and a pickup to do enough work to
get Todd released.
</P>
<P>
   ``But getting this 76-year-old woman out of jail does not seem
to be a high priority for these people,'' Steinhauser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked them, `Why don't you clean this junk up so your
mother can come home?' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't do it. That's why this case is so egregious.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser can't get the relatives in court because Todd holds
title to the property.
</P>
<P>
   Todd's daughter, Shirin McCormick, accuses Steinhauser of
``nitpicking'' and says the complaint against her mother is highly
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   She contends the family has done almost everything Steinhauser
demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser says they haven't made a dent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, McCormick gave a tour of the property.
</P>
<P>
   In the driveway sat a broken-down, jacked-up 1988 station wagon
with a smashed front end. Milk jugs filled with motor oil lay under
the bushes. Used tires, rotten lumber, old plywood, concrete blocks
littered the back yard. Some clothes hung on the line; some had
blown into the weeds.
</P>
<P>
   And right in the middle of it all: a wooden dog house that
somebody had taken an ax to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've cleaned things up around here a lot,'' McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen it before,'' Jacque Elliot said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if her family was doing its best to bring her home,
Todd looked at the ground a long moment and then thumbed her inmate
identification bracelet before answering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she finally said. ``Maybe they are dragging their feet
a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all living there at my expense. I guess I ought to get
them to have a family reunion and pick things up so I can get out
of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd admits her home could use some sprucing up, but she says
her biggest crime is being a hillbilly.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in the mountains of northern Arkansas _ on a farm
near Calico Rock. It was fairly common for people in Izard County
back then to have a little junk sitting around the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever said nothing,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   She married and divorced the same man three times, and the
couple had nine children.
</P>
<P>
   The family gave up farming when her husband ``lost his shirt
trying to grow cotton on that hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they made their way to Kansas City. Todd would work
20 years for the Social Security Administration. In 1976 she bought
her yellow three-bedroom ranch home near 110th Street and Booth
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   She makes no apologies for the scuffed wood floor and the four
linoleum patterns patched together in the kitchen. Or for the 1971
calendar that hangs in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   She's comfortable. As is the beagle that sleeps on the porch and
the kittens that hop through the flower bed. And those aren't weeds
out back. They're greens. She cooks them, and her family eats them.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser grew up on a farm near Norwood, Mo., just a few
mountains north of Calico Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Most everybody's house in the area needed paint and some people
had the same broken-down truck in their yard for 30 years,
Steinhauser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down there, folks say, `Oh, that's just old Joe,'''
Steinhauser explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is Kansas City. You can't live that way in the big
city where people care about property values.''
</P>
<P>
   Her former business teacher at Norwood High School, Debbie
Shelton, used to take Steinhauser home from school. It was a
ramshackle farmhouse at the end of a two-mile driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton described Steinhauser as an outspoken overachiever who,
even in grade school, itched to escape the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser said she knew by the third grade that she wanted to
be lawyer. As a rebellious teen-ager, she moved out of her parents'
home during her senior year and worked part time at a shoe factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn real quick that being on your own is not all fun,''
she said. ``That's when I learned about personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do now is work with people who are irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she was hired in May 1998 to pursue property owners who
have long histories of code violations, the city lacked enforcement
muscle. Owners often paid fines but never fixed the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time cases come to me, these people have been given
every chance to clean things up,'' Steinhauser said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser's weapon is the civil lawsuit. She asks the court
for an injunction, which forces a defendant into a courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   If a judge agrees with Steinhauser, the homeowner receives time
to clean up the property. If no cleanup occurs, a judge can find
the person in contempt and order him or her to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser has more than 200 cases.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Jim Rowland is such a fan of Steinhauser's work
that he is searching for ways to hire more attorneys like her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
