<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YARD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRASHY YARD LANDS OLD LADY IN SLAMMER 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY DONALD BRADLEY   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For far too long, Rowland said, the city had
been powerless against homeowners and landlords who trashed
residences at their neighbors' expense and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holly is a great example of how to fight back,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Todd was filed Oct. 2, 1998. She was in jail 10
months later.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauser said, ``It shows how serious we are and how far we
are willing to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Her boss, City Attorney Walt O'Toole, said Todd had the means to
clean up her property and failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jail is the remedy the court provides,'' O'Toole said.
</P>
<P>
   Todd isn't bitter at Steinhauser.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's real nice,'' Todd said. ``She's a conscientious person
who's trying to do her job. Maybe I just don't fit in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Could be, her daughter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom is used to the country where folks leave you alone,''
McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Todd rises at 5 a.m. at the correctional institution
and leaves an hour later for her job as bus monitor for the
Grandview School District. Her bus serves the district's
special-needs children. She's known some of them several years and
watched them grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a great lady and the kids like her,'' said Chuck
Cornforth, the district's director of transportation. ``She shows
up every day on time _ even now.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd returns to jail about 6 p.m., changes into her green suit,
visits a little and gets ready for bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those beds are hard,'' she said. ``If that pad _ I won't call
it a mattress _ ever had any buoyancy it was a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bones are achy.''
</P>
<P>
   But being an inmate isn't so bad, she said. The people who work
at the correctional institution are friendly. Some even call her
``Grandma.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Leazer, director of inmate services, said some employees
suggested that inmates assigned to ``community service'' be sent to
clean up Todd's yard.
</P>
<P>
   Leazer told them that wouldn't be a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   So for now, there is no end in sight to nights on a hard bed.
But Todd can dream.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is time to leave the city behind. Maybe a small house
in the country would bring peace. A porch for the dog and a place
to grow the flowers she loves.
</P>
<P>
   She nodded and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, if I ever get out of the pokey, I may just head
south.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
