<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWIN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVER DIES AFTER SATURDAY CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ One of the two drivers involved in an
accident during Saturday night's Speed Truck Challenge race at
Irwindale Speedway has died.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Cowherd, 49, of Phoenix, Ariz., was pronounced dead less
than one hour after he and Shawn Davidson of Mammoth Lakes were
involved in a crash entering the first turn of the eighth lap of
the scheduled 50-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the race, the main event on the program, was
canceled following the mishap.
</P>
<P>
   Cowherd died from head injuries suffered in the accident, which
occurred shortly before 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   He was treated by a doctor and paramedics at the track and was
then taken to Santa Teresita Hospital in Duarte. He was pronounced
dead at 11:25 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Cowherd is survived by his wife and three children.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, who was flown by helicopter to Huntington Memorial
Hospital in Pasadena, was treated in the emergency room and
released early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts go out to Keith's family and friends,'' said Robert
DeFazio, general manager of the track. ``We are all very saddened
by this loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The race involved stock racing cars with fiberglass bodies built
to resemble pickups. Cowherd and Davidson each were driving
Chevrolet S-10 pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers in the race wore fireproof suits and helmets and were
constrained by five-point seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   The fatality was the second this year at the newly opened
speedway. Driver Casey Diemert, 23, died in March while practicing
for opening night at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's accident occurred when Cowher and Davidson, running
sixth and seventh at the time, came together and became entangled.
Cowherd's truck slammed into the infield wall, while Davidson hit
the outside wall. Davidson, whose vehicle caught fire momentarily,
quickly climbed out of his vehicle and collapsed on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Cowherd needed to be removed from his vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The accident sent what was left of the crowd of 5,254 into a
stunned silence and the remaining 42 laps of the race were
canceled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7012 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-CUP-HNS &LR;      09-27 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-CUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BROOKLINE, Mass. _ A monster putt. A monster comeback. Heroes as
big as Texas. And a celebration to match.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were all part of the United States' astounding comeback to
win the 33rd Ryder Cup on Sunday at The Country Club as Justin
Leonard's 45-foot putt on the 17th hole completed an unprecedented
rally that was equal parts shocking and relieving for the heavily
favored red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. squad took the Ryder Cup from the Europeans 14{ to 13{,
winning it for the first time since 1993. They won 8{ points in the
12 singles matches Sunday, erasing Europe's four-point advantage
after the first two days.
</P>
<P>
   And the reclamation had a heaping portion of Lone Star history
to it. Though it ranks below ``Remember the Alamo'' in historical
significance, Sunday's relentless pounding of sensational golf
shots was generated in part by that crucial piece of Texas history.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's Ben Crenshaw enlisted the help of Gov. George W. Bush,
who during a team meeting Saturday night read a speech by William
Barrett Travis about the famed battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great speech, great words,'' Crenshaw said. ``And
believe me, the first line of it _ `We were besieged by the enemy,'
_ we were at the time. And against some pretty insurmountable odds.
But darned if we didn't pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team swept the first six matches Sunday in singles
competition, then Dallas' Leonard rolled in the huge birdie putt
that clinched the Cup. Actually, it wasn't clinched until Jose
Maria Olazabal missed his birdie try to give Leonard the 17th hole,
a 1-up lead in their match and a guaranteed half-point, which was
all the U.S. team lacked to win the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans commenced partying like it was 1999, forcing
Olazabal to wait until the celebration died down before getting a
chance to stroke his potentially tying putt. Olazabal missed, and
the Cup was back in U.S. hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like there was a force pulling us together,'' Crenshaw
said. ``I don't know why it happened. But I do know how it
happened. These guys made it happen. They are very, very talented.
And they never doubted one time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had been written off as impossibly behind after
falling in arrears 10-6 after Saturday's matches. No team ever had
overcome more than a two-point deficit on the last day in the first
32 Ryder Cup competitions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team members were staring at the ignominy of being on
the wrong end of the biggest upset in golfing history. They were
the self-described 12 greatest players on the planet. And when it
was done, it was hard to dispute that the Americans were the
greatest team of individuals ever assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Their trip to destiny was wild. It was staged with a relentless
pounding of outstanding shots. Crenshaw had loaded the first half
of his singles matches with his strongest players, and Tom Lehman,
David Duval, Tiger Woods, Phil Mickelson and Davis Love III rolled
up big early leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first four or five matches had to go out in a good fashion
in order to breed a chain reaction for the rest of the team,''
Crenshaw said. ``And it happened like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, it became a matter of scratching out 2{ more points
in the final six singles. Buoyed by the early showing of their
teammates, the players in the last six singles responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to the course about the time the first group was going
off,'' said Jeff Maggert of The Woodlands, who was in the final
pairing Sunday. ``You could see the 1s turning to 2s and 3s and 4s
on the scoreboard in our favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Europeans) definitely thought about that, for sure.
When you look at a scoreboard and see that, then you know there's
more pressure on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Said European captain Mark James: ``They came out screeching.
And then it got to the stage where I thought we must hole something
out and they must stop holing them. Then they holed a lot more. We
were outplayed. They rode the streak tremendously well.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pate won his match against Miguel Angel Jimenez 2 and 1
for America's 13th point. Then Jim Furyk ran away from Sergio
Garcia for a 4 and 3 victory. That left the U.S. team a point away.
Paul Lawrie had dispatched Maggert for Europe's first point.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the U.S. team was tied in each of the remaining
three matches with holes quickly running out. A half in any of
those matches would assure the Cup for the U.S.; Europe needed only
to win 14 points to retain the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   First, Mark O'Meara couldn't hold on to his match as he bogeyed
the final hole to give Padraig Harrington a 1-up win, leaving the
U.S. ahead 14-12.
</P>
<P>
   That left all the drama on the 17th green. With Colin
Montgomerie and Payne Stewart standing back in the fairway in an
all-square match as the last group on the course, they watched
Leonard ram his putt up a ridge and into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   As the hysteria quieted and Olazabal missed, it meant the worst
Leonard could get was a tie in his match and the half-point needed
to win the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   He lost the 18th hole when Olazabal birdied, but the damage was
done. Stewart conceded birdie to Montgomerie on the 18th to provide
the final score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been extremely difficult not just for me but for my
colleagues as well,'' said Montgomerie, Europe's team leader. ``We
came in here as massive underdogs at the start of the week, massive
underdogs. What we did the first two days was almost
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans were too good Sunday. It was play like
Leonard's that typified the Yanks' grit. He was four holes down to
Olazabal with seven to play. But Olazabal made bogeys at the 12th
and 13th to wedge open the door for Leonard. Then Leonard birdied
the 14th and 15th, and the match was even.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you win a hole or two in a row, the momentum
shifts,'' Leonard said. ``And even though I was still 2 down, I
felt like I was in the driver's seat going up to the 14th.''
</P>
<P>
   As were the Americans, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew how good it would feel to win the Ryder Cup,''
Woods said. ``We did it the right way, with heart and
determination.''
</P>
<P>
   And great play. Not to mention a Texas touch to the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Ben being captain and Justin's comeback, it's a great day
for us Texans,'' Maggert said. ``We've got a lot of great golf
history in Texas, and this is another piece of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
