<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-FAMILY (Dili, East Timor) _ One family's story offers a
look inside the extraordinary three-week spasm of violence in East
Timor during which irregular militias supported by the Indonesian
military sought to annihilate an entire territory and its people.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (London) _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former Chilean
dictator who has called himself ``the only political prisoner in
England'' since his arrest here nearly a year ago, begins finding
out this week whether he must go to Spain to face charges of crimes
against humanity. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRANSSEXUAL-TEACHER (Antelope, Calif.) _ After a sex change, a
teacher is barred from his school. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-RECRUIT _ The Army and Air Force face significant
shortfalls in recruiting numbers in what the Pentagon fears is a
worsening trend that is chipping away at national security. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-GUIDES _ The federal government is mailing out 36
million guides this month aimed at educating the nation's elderly
on the increasingly complicated world of health care. The guides
are the result of months of market testing, focus groups, expert
reviews and survey research, much of which discovered that the 39
million Medicare beneficiaries have only a sketchy understanding of
the basic Medicare program, let alone the managed care
alternatives. By Robin Toner.
</P>
