<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF--BLINEBURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Justin Leonard's putt crossed 45 feet and an
ocean of emotion wider than the Atlantic that, along with quite a
few centuries of cultural diversity, separates the two sides in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   It climbed the hill, broke right, rolled straight into the
center of the cup and touched off the wildest scene on a golf
course since Rodney Dangerfield teed it up in Caddyshack.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard bolted toward the front of the green like a drum major
on amphetamines, and a band of delirious American players, caddies,
wives and girlfriends fell in behind in a victory conga line.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the genteel game of golf?
</P>
<P>
   Only if what is on the line is the Ryder Cup, a historic and, of
late, compelling competition that is equal part sports, patriotic
fervor and theater.
</P>
<P>
   Where else can you get the automatons of the PGA Tour to let us
know they sweat and bleed just like humans?
</P>
<P>
   There was Tiger Woods, wearing his rally cap backward and
squinting through his sunglasses, willing on his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   There was usually stoic David Duval finishing off a cleaning of
Jesper Parnevik's clock by pumping his fists and cupping his ear to
incite more of the crowd's roar.
</P>
<P>
   There was the U.S. team swarming over the lush grass of The
Country Club like a plague of locusts to swallow up a 14{-13{ win
to complete the greatest last-day performance in the history of the
event.
</P>
<P>
   And there ultimately, and so dramatically, was the skinny Texan
Leonard ramming home a putt from just inside the Rhode Island
border that enabled him to come from four holes down to tie Jose
Maria Olazabal and clinch the Ryder Cup for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many heroes Sunday. Hal Sutton, the veteran who
had not qualified for Ryder Cup play in a dozen years, finished a
strong effort by getting 3{ points for his team. Tom Lehman set the
tone by coming out strong in the first match of the day to defeat
Lee Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   And Jim Furyk put a wet blanket over the Spanish firecracker
Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Leonard, who halved his duel with Olazabal and still
never has won a Ryder Cup match outright, hitting the long dream of
a putt that will be replayed longer than any shot he has ever made
in a successful career, which includes winning the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I was trying to make it, but I don't know if I was
really expecting to make it,'' Leonard said. ``The first thing I
wanted to do was to get it close.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's day, down four to Olazabal with just seven holes to
play, was representative of the rally that saw the U.S. team come
out of what seemed to be a too-deep 10-6 hole entering singles
play. No team in the event's history had come that far back.
</P>
<P>
   But who knew the entire European continent was going to turn
into the Oilers at Buffalo? And who knew the U.S. team could almost
fulfill the prophecy of their captain/historian/seer Ben Crenshaw
and nearly ``whitewash'' the Europeans?
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw pulled out every motivational tool in his bag to stoke
the fires of his boys. There were Saturday night speeches that
quoted William Barrett Travis at the Alamo and Crenshaw's golf
mentor, the late Harvey Penick.
</P>
<P>
   There were pats on the back, talk about fate and even a history
lesson about No. 17 itself, the site at The Country Club where a
neighborhood kid named Francis Ouimet sank a pair of 20-footers in
the 1913 U.S. Open to upset golf legends Harry Vardon and Ted Ray
to become one of the game's immortals.
</P>
<P>
   You weren't sure if Crenshaw was writing the script for a
miracle finish or an episode of The X Files. Nevertheless, it all
worked.
</P>
<P>
   Westwood and Darren Clarke couldn't get Europe the one point it
needed out of the first two slots, then what had been the dynamic
team of Garcia and Parnevik fell flat individually.
</P>
<P>
   And the U.S. team became a boulder rolling down a hill.
</P>
<P>
   What is interesting is that by underperforming on the first two
days, the self-proclaimed ``12 best players in the world'' turned
the tables and set themselves up to be the come-from-behind
feel-good story. Kind of like Microsoft being cheered for its stock
price rising.
</P>
<P>
   What made the aftermath tense was the Europeans expressing
``disgust'' at the U.S. frat party around the 17th green while
Olazabal still had a 25-foot putt to halve the hole.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it all so incredibly delicious is that in the last
seven meetings, the sides have won three each and tied once, and
the combined point total is 98-98 heading to The Belfry in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't golf. It's the Ryder Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
