<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T GIVE UP ON MATADORS JUST YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ In these days of instant gratification, where
most food is served fast and the remote control allows us to zoom
through several TV channels in a matter of seconds, it would be
easy to bury the Cal State Northridge football team.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors have lost two consecutive games. Defensively,
they've given up 119 points and 1,225 yards in those losses. The
57-point drubbing at Kansas two weeks ago was the second-worst in
school history.
</P>
<P>
   Then Eastern Washington set a team record with 456 rushing yards
and beat CSUN 48-41 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it is tempting to criticize the Matadors, or even
worse, to think ``It's the same old CSUN,'' because, after all,
isn't this a program that entered the season 43 games under .500?
</P>
<P>
   This is a new era in Northridge. Thanks to last year's promising
season, when the Matadors were less than a minute away from winning
a share of the Big Sky Conference title, the bar has been raised.
The team closes most of its practices by calling itself ``Big Sky
champs.''
</P>
<P>
   But let's look at reality.
</P>
<P>
   Put the ugliness of these back-to-back losses aside. CSUN lost
its head coach and offensive coordinator in July. The remaining
staff lost almost two weeks of work this summer when the coaches'
office was locked during the school's internal investigation into
the program.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't the mass exodus of players some predicted. Wide
receiver Anthony Ramos, who transferred to Washington State, was
the only prominent Matador to leave. But Ron Ponciano's firing put
doubt in many players' minds about the university's support of the
football team.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were picked to finish eighth, next to last, in a
poll of the conference coaches.
</P>
<P>
   So what were they doing pushing talented and experienced Eastern
Washington into the last minute on Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   Let's not bury the Matadors. Let's praise them.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sophomore quarterback Marcus Brady, after two so-so efforts
to start the year, completed 36 of 49 passes for 484 yards and five
touchdowns; Eastern Washington simply could not defend him and he
didn't throw an interception.
</P>
<P>
   __ Senior wide receiver Aaron Arnold caught 10 of Brady's passes
for 130 yards and became the school's all-time leader in receiving
yards on a 33-yard pass that set up Brady's 7-yard touchdown pass
to Drew Amerson that pulled CSUN within a touchdown, 41-34.
</P>
<P>
   When Arnold came into the program in '96, he was so raw some of
the coaches didn't think he could play in college. This year he was
a preseason Division I-AA All-American candidate.
</P>
<P>
   __ Shawnbay Jones, a defensive lineman, had a team-leading 12
tackles against EWU, including a sack in the third quarter that
almost sent Eagles quarterback Chris Samms to the locker room with
an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Eagles had 271 yards rushing in the first half. But a few
adjustments by the coaches and inspired play by Jones, backup
noseguard Sean Beard and linebacker Cos Abercrombie, held the
Eagles to 40 yards in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   __ Most important, CSUN fought Eastern Washington until the end
without senior running back Jaumal Bradley, who didn't play because
of tonsillitis. Even though Bradley has become one of the
conference's top tailbacks, he is also the team's leader, its
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie, Arnold and Brady made no excuses for Bradley's
absence.
</P>
<P>
   As the players filed out of the cramped visitor's locker room
Saturday night, Arnold pointed out that there is hope for the
Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic about the rest of the season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold should know, because in the four years he's been at
Northridge, he's seen the Matadors consistently prove their critics
wrong. He knows a season isn't over after three games. &QL; 
REPORT CARD &QL; 
Game: 3 &QL; 
Result: Eastern Washington 48, CSUN 41 &QL; 
Record: 1-2 &QL; 
This week's GPA: 2.41 &QL; 
Cumulative GPA: 2.44 &QL; 
QUARTERBACK &QL; 
Marcus Brady is back. After subpar performance against Kansas,
Brady showed why he could be the Big Sky's premier QB. He completed
73 percent of his passes (36 of 49) for a personal-best 484 yards
and 5 TDs, with no INTs. Orchestrated nine-play, 85-yard drive at
the end that took only a minute and a half. Bravo. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A &QL; 
RUNNING BACKS &QL; 
Starter Jaumal Bradley didn't play because of sickness and it
showed; Brady was leading rusher, with 29 yards. Alan Taylor, who
started in place of Bradley, had 21 yards and DeJuan Gilmore wasn't
much better, with 23. To be fair, these guys didn't have much room
to work with. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C- &QL; 
RECEIVERS &QL; 
The play of AA (Aaron Arnold) could have earned this position an A,
and Terrence Jones (six receptions, 138 yards, two TDs) was even
better. But two lost fumbles by Drew Amerson, including a
heartbreaker at the end of a 22-yard catch deep in EWU territory in
the fourth quarter, cannot be overlooked. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B+ &QL; 
OFFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
Decimated by injuries, this unit was average. Brady was sacked four
times, pressured many times and hit hard after several passes.
Created nothing for the running backs, even though EWU's defensive
line was smaller. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C- &QL; 
DEFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
Horrible in the first half, inspired in the second. Eastern
Washington has one of the best offensive lines in the Big Sky, but
456 rushing yards is inexcusable. Some of those holes opened up for
EWU running backs were wide enough for two players to run through. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C- &QL; 
LINEBACKERS &QL; 
Brennen Swanson was double- and triple-teamed, and he wasn't really
a factor despite six unassisted tackles. Cos Abercrombie woke from
his two-game slumber and had a season-high 11 tackles. Jack Heaslet
had his first INT as a Matador on a horrible throw by EWU's Chris
Samms. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C &QL; 
DEFENSIVE BACKS &QL; 
Samms, filling in for injured starter Fred Salanoa, was no factor
and the Eagles ran the ball 61 times. Was run-support a priority?
It didn't appear to be. Too many missed tackles and sometimes EWU's
RBs ran right by the DBs. Free safety Rahman Sparks (12 tackles and
1 sack) played well. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   D &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL; 
Terrence Jones' 86-yard kickoff return for a TD to open the game
was CSUN's first since 1991. Jones needs to be smarter on punt
returns, though; he had his second negative return in as many
games. Ethan Beck averaged 45 yards per punt. K Derek Brown missed
an extra point, which could have been devastating if the Matadors
had tied the game in the last two minutes. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B+ &QL; 
COACHING &QL; 
These guys are trying, but it's hard to look good when CSUN brings
only eight healthy offensive linemen and is without promising
strong safety Hassan Abdul-Malik (pulled hamstring). Those excuses
aside, adjustments need to be made to get Swanson free and get the
penalties (33 in three games) under control. &QL; 
Grade: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
