<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     09-27 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MILWAUKEE _ If the Astros are to hold on and reach the playoffs,
they're going to have to do it the hard way.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros' drive for a third straight National League Central
title is no longer a sure thing. Neither is making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They continued their late-season tailspin Sunday, completing a
disastrous road trip with an 11-3 loss to the Milwaukee Brewers at
County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros lost for the sixth time on the nine-game road trip,
reducing their lead over Cincinnati to a half-game in the NL
Central and setting up a two-game showdown between the clubs
beginning Tuesday at the Astrodome. The Reds rallied past St. Louis
7-5 in 12 innings Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of those days you have during the season, but you
hate to have them at this juncture,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said. ``Our pitching was really poor, and our hitting wasn't that
great, either. We got a lot of hits but not many runs. It was a
terrible trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Righthander Scott Elarton (9-5), pitching in arguably the most
important game of the season to date, was gone by the fourth
inning. The Astros' bullpen was equally ineffective. Offensively,
the Astros stranded 11 baserunners.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee built an 8-1 lead after only four innings en route to
a 16-hit assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching and offense on this trip was either real good or real
bad. Never together,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell said.
``That's why we've been struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Brewers _ the Astros' third straight sub-.500
opponent on the trip _ played the spoiler's role. Marquis Grissom
went 4-for-6 with a home run, three runs scored and five RBIs, and
rookie righthander Kyle Peterson (3-7) held the Astros to two runs
over six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting because it was against a team in the middle of
the pennant race,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, who has provided a lift for the rotation as the No. 4
starter in the second half, suffered through his shortest outing
since becoming a starter July 3. He gave up five runs and seven
hits in 2 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers tagged Elarton for four runs in the second inning.
Jeromy Burnitz led off the inning with a double, and Geoff Jenkins
singled. Ron Belliard's single scored Burnitz, and Brian Banks
singled to load the bases. With two outs, Grissom delivered the big
blow with a three-run double that rolled to the left-center-field
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Cirillo led off the third inning with a home run _ his 14th
of the season _ off Elarton to put the Brewers ahead 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good warming up in the bullpen,'' Elarton said. ``I
came out thinking I had pretty decent stuff, but then I realized
pretty early I didn't have anything to put anybody away with. My
fastball was pretty straight. My breaking ball and changeup were
flat. It's hard to pitch with that kind of stuff. I battled as long
as I could. It just wasn't meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton said there was no extra pressure on the mound with the
Astros fighting to stay atop the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an important game. I knew that,'' he said. ``I'd rather
pitch in a really important game than a game that really has no
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Holt, who replaced Elarton, had his second rough relief
outing of the series. Holt allowed three runs and two walks over
two-thirds of an inning, including a two-run double by Jenkins in
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom added a solo home run in the fifth off Brian Williams to
extend Milwaukee's lead to 9-1, and had an RBI double in the
seventh. Grissom entered the game in a 0-for-10 slump.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spiers, who was attacked by a fan in right field Friday
night, started in left field Sunday and had a run-scoring single in
the third. Russ Johnson had an RBI pinch-hit single in the sixth,
and the Astros scored their final run on a bases-loaded walk to
Ricky Gutierrez in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a bad trip for us,'' Gutierrez said. ``We didn't play
good baseball. We didn't do anything really good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
