<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-YESTER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FABULOUS FINISHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from
the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   __ Sept. 27, 1973: The Angels' Nolan Ryan strikes out
Minnesota's Rich Reese to break Sandy Koufax's major-league,
single-season record with 383 Ks.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sept. 28, 1951: Los Angeles Rams quarterback Norm Van
Brocklin, starting in place of injured Bob Waterfield, becomes the
first in NFL history to throw for more than 500 yards as he amasses
554 yards in a 54-14 win over the New York Yanks. Four of the five
TD passes go to Elroy ``Crazylegs'' Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sept. 28, 1974: The Angels' Nolan Ryan throws his third
career no-hitter, 4-0 against Minnesota. He strikes out 15.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sept. 28, 1988: The Dodgers' Orel Hershiser breaks Don
Drysdale's major-league-record streak for consecutive scoreless
innings _ 59 _ by going 10 in his final regular-season appearance
in San Diego. Although it didn't count toward the record, Hershiser
actually ran the streak to 67 innings when he blanked the New York
Mets for eight innings in Game 1 of the NLCS. (17)
</P>
<P>
   __ Sept. 29, 1976: Tommy Lasorda is named manager of the Dodgers
when Walter Alston announces his retirement after 23 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sept. 30, 1984: On the final day of the regular season, the
Angels' Mike Witt throws the only perfect game in team history in a
1-0 win at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 2, 1963: Sandy Koufax fans 15 New York Yankees in Game 1
of the World Series in a 5-2 Dodgers win.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 2, 1965: Sandy Koufax ends the season with a record 382
strikeouts in the Dodgers' 3-1 win over Milwaukee, which also
clinches the National League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 2, 1966: Sandy Koufax records career win No. 165 _ which
turns out to be his last _ in a 6-3 decision over Philadelphia as
the Dodgers clinch the NL title before heading into the World
Series (and a four-game loss) against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 2, 1977: Against Houston's J.R. Richard, Dusty Baker
hits his 30th home run, joining Steve Garvey (33), Reggie Smith
(32) and Ron Cey (30) as the first foursome to hit 30 homers for
one team in a season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 3, 1993: The Dodgers eliminate the Giants from the West
Division race with a 12-1 win at Dodger Stadium. The highlights:
two home runs from Rookie of the Year Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 3, 1974: Jerry West announces his retirement as a Lakers
player with 25,192 points.
</P>
<P>
   __ Birthdays: Tuesday: Former USC star tailback Anthony Davis
(47). Friday: Former Angels star Rod Carew (54) and former USC
baseball star Mark McGwire (36). Saturday: Former Dodgers star
Maury Wills (67). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
