<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NJ-BRIDE-SHOT-1STLD-W     09-27 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BRIDE-SHOT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BOYFRIEND KILLS BRIDE ON WEDDING DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bride-to-be was shot dead in front of her family on Sunday by
a former boyfriend who walked uninvited into her New Jersey home as
the family was about to leave for the wedding, the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   The former boyfriend, dressed as if for a wedding, walked in
about 4 p.m. as the woman was posing for a final round of
photographs, pulled a gun out of a briefcase and shot her
repeatedly, prosecutors said. He was immediately restrained by the
bride's brother, who held him until the police arrived, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   As a white Rolls-Royce and two stretch limousines for the
wedding party idled outside the home that the woman, Gladys Ricart,
39, shared with her 20-year-old son and her mother, the gunfire
sent a houseful of guests scrambling for cover, hiding in closets
and running down to the basement, said the Bergen County
prosecutor, William H. Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   The former boyfriend, Augustin Garcia, was arrested at the scene
_ a quiet street in the small Bergen County town of Ridgefield, and
was expected to be charged with murder, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a neighbor who heard her dog bark came out to
see what the commotion was about and saw bridesmaids in light green
and champagne dresses running onto the lawn. ``They ran over to my
steps and sat down, and they were crying,'' said the woman, who
would not disclose her name.
</P>
<P>
   A flower girl for the wedding was whisked into a neighbor's
house to get her away from the violence, the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ricart's fiance, James L. Preston, 36, of Brooklyn, was to
meet her for the ceremony at the Church on the Hill in Flushing,
Queens, and was not present when the shooting occurred, the
authorities said. A message left on Preston's answering machine
Sunday night was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ricart and Garcia, 47, of North Bergen, N.J., had dated for
about six years and had broken up nine months ago, Schmidt said.
``She terminated the relationship and had no desire to resume it or
have contact with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question, Schmidt refused to say whether Garcia
had been stalking Ms. Ricart or whether she had an order of
protection against him. Rafael Heres, a relative of Ms. Ricart's
who was at the house, told a local television stateion that Garcia
was deeply troubled. ``We already knew the guy's background, and we
figured that the phenomena would occur,'' he said. ``He was a
little negative. He couldn't accept rejection.''
</P>
<P>
   Another family friend, Fior Martinez, told reporters that Garcia
had left 100 roses on Ms. Ricart's lawn last week. Ms. Ricart had
met Preston about four months ago, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the shooting, Ms. Ricart was standing on her lawn
on Elizabeth Street, a sycamore-shaded block of tidy houses in a
town of 10,000 people five miles west of New York City, posing for
pictures and waving to neighbors. She was wearing a lacy white gown
and a silver tiara and was flanked by nine bridesmaids and three
flower girls, said Janet Donnelly, who lives across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked absolutely gorgeous,'' Ms. Donnelly said. ``She
seemed nervous, but that's normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon Ms. Ricart and the photographer went back in the house, Ms.
Donnelly said.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Garcia apparently drove up in his black
sport utility vehicle, parked and walked into 825 Elizabeth, a
two-family, brick-faced home where Ms. Ricart lived with her son,
Davis Ricart, and her mother, Anna Rosario, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the guests recognized Garcia when he entered, Schmidt
said. He would not say whether they asked Garcia to leave. When
Garcia found Ms. Ricart modeling her wedding dress for the
photographer, he shot her ``several times,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   The bride's brother immediately took the gun, a five-shot,
.38-caliber revolver and held Garcia at gunpoint until the police
arrived, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He grabbed the gun away as the gunman was reloading,'' Schmidt
added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Donnelly said she ran back outside when she heard noise and
saw confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were running around screaming,'' she said. Ms. Ricart's
distraught mother collapsed in the middle of the street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
