<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS THANK FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was Fan Appreciation Day at Dodgers Stadium
Sunday, and the team gave away many lovely parting gifts team
merchandise, barbecue grills, televisions, vacations to Europe,
free dinners, autographed jerseys, and cars, the latter perfect for
a quick getaway.
</P>
<P>
   The question is who's departing, if anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers' 10-7 win over the San Diego Padres was
their home finale in a season that went wrong early and never
showed a flicker of life. The win Sunday was their seventh in their
last nine games, but they will still finish the year well under
.500, their worst season since the 63-99 1992 disaster. They also
posted only their fifth losing record at home in 41 years.
</P>
<P>
   Given the changes of last year and the high expectations of this
year, only the naive would think the same team will return in 1999.
But it would also be naive of Dodgers management to think all three
million fans are going to return in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers fans are a laid-back, patient lot. The Dodgers managed
to draw three million fans for the 14th time despite it being year
two of the Fox era (error?) and a year removed from the Mike Piazza
fiasco. That may be the club's best stat of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the team shouldn't press its luck. These fans have opinions,
and they've been paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   June Blaine of Beverly Hills, who has been attending Dodgers
games since the team played in the Coliseum, said her first
priority is financial. ``Don't raise the ticket prices,'' she said,
clutching her $6 general admission ticket. ``And don't trade Eric
Karros. That last trade (Mike Piazza) was a real blooper.''
</P>
<P>
   Serg Talavera of Wilmington would like the team to return to the
good old pre-Fox days and allow mellow tailgating in some parking
lots. He and several friends were enjoying the noon sunshine before
finding their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Talavera also appeals for some patience regarding Raul Mondesi,
whose midseason blowup turned the old rousing ``Rauuuuul'' cheer
into boos. ``I don't want to see Raul traded,'' he said. ``He
helped the Dodgers a lot over the years. It bothers me that more
people don't appreciate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabrina Wind of Santa Monica has been a rabid Dodger fan for
only five years, but the Piazza trade still left a mark. ``I felt
like a heartbroken 11-year-old when they traded Piazza,'' she said.
``If they traded Karros, it would seem like the end of tradition.
He was my first real crush as fan.''
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, she would like to see a change of personality on the
field. ``I'd like to see a team that plays well together, where the
personalities are well-matched,'' she said. ``And a team that has
some fun. They haven't looked at all this year like a team that was
having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   If three million fans is the best stat, Ms. Winds' no fun
observation may be the most accurate assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The other facet of Fan Appreciation Day was the players and
coaches greeting fans at entrance gates and thanking them for their
support. No one reported any rude remarks. ``They were very
gracious,'' said manager Davey Johnson. ``Nothing unkind was
said.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them thanked me for the season,'' said Karros. ``Some
wished me well during the offseason. And some fans thought I was
just some guy wearing a blue jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also one Padre fans who told Karros ``We'll see you in
San Diego next year,'' a reference to the first baseman being
traded to his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Perot will support NAFTA before the Dodgers and Padres make
a trade. But despite going into the last week of the season with a
career-high .299 average, a career-high 112 RBI and career-equaling
34 homers, he might not be back.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson wants a left-handed bat, and Karros has eminently
more trade value than Mondesi or Gary Sheffield, who both make $9
million-plus a year.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Mondesi would make more sense. His numbers look as good
as Karros' 32 homers, 92 RBI, 33 stolen bases but no one would say
he had a great season, least of all the fans who turned on him. If
they don't deal him, they'll have to worry anew about fan reaction
in '00.
</P>
<P>
   But a Mondy deal has financial complications, and clubhouse
complications, since Sheffield has come out against a Mondesi
trade. Plus, Mondy could very easily go somewhere else and finally
turn in that monster season everyone's been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   As frustrating as the '99 season has been, the offseason could
be more of the same. Johnson and G.M. Kevin Malone would love to
dump some of their ill-fitting pieces, but there may be no takers.
They could end up like a garbage scow with no place to dock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a frustrating year, especially when you consider the
expectations for this club,'' said Karros. ``It wasn't what we
wanted it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros, Mondesi and Sheffield will finish with 30 homers and 90
RBI or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have good numbers in a season like this,'' Karros
said. ``But it shows how much of a team game it is and all the
different factors that go into winning. And that's how you're
identified, as a winner or a loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans should know that no one is more frustrated about
losing than the people in this (locker) room.''
</P>
<P>
   They know. They even understand. The question is for how long?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
