<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP NEXT: COIT TOWER BY VIAGRA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Assorted gems, nuggets, pearls, jewels and the
occasional lump of coal:
<P>
   --``Does everything have a price now?'' asks Supervisor Michael
Yaki, referring to a proposal to sell advertising space on the
Golden Gate Bridge one day per month. ``And what's next? Half
Dome?''
</P>
<P>
   (Michael's hair by Vidal Sassoon.)
</P>
<P>
   Bulletin: Yosemite Inc. has announced a plan to cover park
revenue shortfall by renting Half Dome to advertisers. The park has
agreed to rename the monolith Chrome Dome and allow it to be used
as a dramatic before-and-after ``nature billboard'' co-sponsored by
Rogaine and Chia Pet.
</P>
<P>
   --``I saw Steve Young on a TV commercial talking to a bunch of
cows,'' e-mails Bolling. ``Does this mean he's going to be put out
to pasture?''
</P>
<P>
   You might be on to something, Bolling. In last week's game,
Steve did spend a lot of time on all fours with his nose in the
grass.
</P>
<P>
   And not to nitpick, but it's ``herd'' of cows, ``bunch'' of
horses.
</P>
<P>
   --Walking past In-Jean-ious on Castro, Steve Abney stopped to
read the T-shirts in the window. He liked, ``My parents told me I
could be anything, so I became an ass_.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in XL, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Don Novello reports that his Right Field Home Run Swimming Team
- dogs who will fetch homer balls from China Basin outside Pac Bell
Park _ is coming along swimmingly.
</P>
<P>
   Except: ``I'm training my own dog, Lassie Molinari _ half
dachshund, half Chihuahua. He's small (11/2-inch inseam), and I
doubt if he'll ever be able to get a baseball in his mouth. He's
trying, but so far he can only open his mouth as wide as an English
muffin.''
</P>
<P>
   Possible solution: a large wad of bubble gum stuck to Lassie's
forehead.
</P>
<P>
   _How about allowing ads on the Golden Gate Bridge, but only on
the underside.  &LR; Hello there, sailor. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Baseball revives the Dead? Bob Weir and Phil Lesh will sing the
National Anthem at the final Giants' game at 3Stick Park. Does this
mean that the Dead, scattered like a dandelion since Jerry Garcia's
death, might finally reunite for a millennium New Year's Eve gig?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible,'' says Dead spokesguy Dennis McNally. ``None of
them are committed elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   _A tip you won't get from Martha Stewart: Muni and the mayor are
trying to catch workers' compensation cheaters with hidden cameras
showing the cheats off the job doing stuff their disability does
not allow them to do.
</P>
<P>
   Former private eye Ron Cameron suggests this old trick: If the
guy (or gal) is out of work because he can't bend down (bad back,
etc.), pour half a can of motor oil under the person's car.
Revealing photo-op ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor: ``I hear the Giants' ballpark will be named for Dolores
Huerta (co-founder of the United Farm Workers Union),'' says
e-mailer Sarah. ``They're going to call it Huerta Park.''
</P>
<P>
   _A Los Angeles charity mailed a form plea to the Trinity
Episcopal Church on Bush Street. It was addressed to Ms. Trinity
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Rector Robert Cromey says, ``Perhaps Trinity is the new yuppie
baby name to replace Brittany.''
</P>
<P>
   --Signs of tension around The Chronicle Building: Someone posted
a note to the vending machine stocker: ``Please avoid snacks that
yell `kid' at us. No children work here. Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Note taped to that note: ``Yeah, only old fogies work here.
Leave us prunes and horehound candy, dagnabbit!''
</P>
<P>
   --Misc. sightings ... At McDonald's in San Carlos (thanks, Dan
Morafka): ``Warning: Stay off all Playland equipment if you are
over 4 ft. tall or under 3 years of age.'' ... At 17th and Florida
streets, a house covered with graffiti, including this in black
marker (Rick Popko): ``It's weak to tag someone's house.'' ... At
the Cannery, in the office of the Redwood Empire Association
(tourist marketing), the phone is answered by Cedar Kennan. ...
License plate on black Lexus: (Heart) PLSTX. Walt Giachini says,
``It has to be either Dustin Hoffman or Mrs. Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   --Jackson Best, 10, opens his Lunchable at New Traditions public
school and instantly wins $1,000, a TV set, a Nintendo system, a
Gameboy system and a party for 25 friends at Planet Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   So there's absolutely no point in Jackson continuing his formal
education.
</P>
<P>
   Says mom Beverly Best, ``I get rewarded for being too lazy to
make lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   --Watching the CNN coverage of the Big One in Taiwan, Lou
Bristol noted that Taiwan also had a Big One back in '06. Says Lou,
``Maybe we got Lotta's Fountain fixed just in time.''
</P>
<P>
   --Java the Hip: Coffee server Lloyd at Peets on Potrero has
taken a moral stand: ``I will not wait on anyone who is actively
talking on a cell phone. I skip to the next customer. This bugs
them and some even throw little tantrums. But since  &LR; I  &LR; have the
coffee. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Hereby awarded: This column's ``S.F. Coffee Server of the
Month'' plaque.
</P>
<P>
   --Online goodies: For $69, you can order a vial of drug-free
urine and a device to hide it on your body, to beat that pesky
employment drug test (if you're applying for a job as an airline
pilot, please ignore this).
</P>
<P>
   But so far, even cyberworld has limitations. If you're required
to give a stool sample, it's strictly BYO.
</P>
<P>
   --Dan Quayle drops out of the race. Yes, the Republicans are
frantically tossing deck chairs off the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   --Two Naval airmen were caught shooting and killing seven
pregnant cows in western Nevada. A county sheriff, Bill Lawry,
said, ``We asked them why they shot the cows and their answer was,
`Because.' We asked them `Because why?' and they really couldn't
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you suppose an acceptable answer would have been?
</P>
</TEXT>
