<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELLSIDE-COMPUTERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DIRECT PC SALES ARE INCREASING
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Brands sold through local dealers still top the
charts in U.S. personal computer sales to consumers, but analysts
foresee an increasing share going to companies that sell directly
to users over the phone and the Web _ notably Dell and Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Compaq, which still markets most of its PCs through
dealers, held on to the No. 1 position, but Gateway finished the
year less than 1 percentage point behind, according to data
provided by IDC analyst Gabrielle Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, Compaq and Gateway will most likely hold on to the top
two slots in the U.S. consumer market, analysts say, but Dell,
Gateway's longtime arch-rival in direct sales, is coming on strong.
Since August 1997, when Dell launched its first concerted
consumer-marketing campaign, its unit sales in this category have
been growing at a rate of 80 percent year-over-year, the company
says.
</P>
<P>
   By the second quarter of this year, the most recent for which
data are available, Dell had climbed to fifth rank in U.S. consumer
sales, according to IDC's Griffith; another analyst, ZD InfoBead's
David Tremblay, also had Dell in seventh position a year ago, but
his data show it climbing all the way to fourth in the most recent
quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 0352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 03:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7055 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DOMASH-COLUMN-SFCHRON     09-27 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMASH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MOMENTUM INVESTORS HAVE A NEW TOOL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By HARRY DOMASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Investors using the Web to research stocks have
a new tool to help them gain insight into consensus earnings
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   First, some background.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote a column back in June describing how momentum investors
could use information on Yahoo's research page to determine whether
a stock is likely to outperform or underperform the market in the
weeks leading up to release of quarterly earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum investors, you may recall, look for trends in analysts'
consensus earnings forecasts. They're trying to spot stocks likely
to experience further increases in earnings forecasts or that are
likely to jump when the company reports earnings that are greater
than expected _ what's known as a positive earnings surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Negative surprises (earnings less than forecast) generally drive
a company's stock price down, often sharply.
</P>
<P>
   I used two stocks in the June column to demonstrate the
approach: Qualcomm and Parametric Technology. Our analysis
predicted good times ahead for Qualcomm and bad news for
Parametric. How did our predictions turn out?
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm's June quarter earnings came in at 75 cents per share,
12 cents higher than estimates. Analysts responded by increasing
forecasts for the current (September) quarter from 63 cents to 75
cents per share. Qualcomm's share price responded accordingly,
soaring more than 74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to our prediction that Parametric did not have much of
a chance of a positive surprise, it did manage to report June
quarter earnings 1 cent above consensus forecasts of 16 cents. That
didn't stop analysts from reducing estimates for the September
quarter to 17 cents, from 24 cents. Despite the drop in earnings
forecasts, Parametric's share price is up about 4 percent since the
column was published.
</P>
<P>
   I'm bringing all this up because Quicken (www.quicken.com)
recently added a new page to its site called ``Analysts'
Estimates.'' Quicken and Yahoo both get their data from Zacks
Investment Research, a Chicago area company that compiles analysts'
reports. Quicken's new page has everything Yahoo has, plus a new
feature: EPS Estimate Distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Let me explain how analysts' consensus forecasts are computed
before I go into the details. You would think, in this age of
supercomputers, the consensus numbers would reflect some sort of
sophisticated statistical processing of the forecasts. Some
companies do that. However, the published consensus forecasts, the
numbers that determine whether a company's earnings are a positive
or negative surprise, are simple averages.
</P>
<P>
   For example, say four analysts publish earnings forecasts for
Embalming.com. Three of the analysts predict Embalming.com will
earn $1 per share, and the fourth thinks the company will break
even, that is, show no profit or loss.
</P>
<P>
   The average of the four estimates is 75 cents. One thing you
know for sure, Embalming.com isn't going to earn 75 cents! Either
the analyst forecasting zero earnings knows something the others
don't, or he or she hasn't been paying attention. We don't know who
is right, but this is a completely different state of affairs than
if all four analysts were predicting 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at some real examples.
</P>
<P>
   Click on Investments on Quicken's home page, and then enter PTX,
the symbol for Pillowtex Corp., a manufacturer of home textile
furnishings, in the box under Quotes &AMP; Research. Select Analysts,
and then push Go (if your screen displays price quotes instead of
analyst ratings, select Analysts' Estimates from the menu on the
left).
</P>
<P>
   Scroll down until you see both the Consensus EPS Estimates and
the EPS Estimate Distribution on your screen at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus (average) of the six analysts' reporting estimates
for Pillowtex is 26 cents per share for the September '99 quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, look at the chart labeled ``This Quarter-09/1999,'' showing
the distribution of the six estimates. We see that four analysts
said 25 cents, one forecast 26 cents and the sixth predicts 28
cents. Four out of six analysts are saying Pillowtex will earn 25
cents per share in the September quarter. If they're right,
Pillowtex will come in below consensus and the share price will
probably drop.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus forecast for the fiscal year ending December '99
is $1.61 per share. Look at the chart labeled ``This
Year-12/1999.'' Five of the six analysts reporting forecasts say
Pillowtex will earn $1.55 or less, at least 6 cents below
consensus. The average of those five forecasts is only $1.44, but
one lone analyst saying $2.47 per share brought the consensus up to
$1.61.
</P>
<P>
   Look up Hutchinson Technology (HTCH), Oakwood Homes (OH), KN
Energy (KNE) and Progressive Corporation (PGR) for examples of
other companies in similar situations.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at a company where the consensus forecast looks too
low. General Growth Properties, symbol GGP, is a real estate
investment trust specializing in shopping centers. The consensus
forecast for the September quarter is 95 cents, and the
distribution is consistent with the consensus. But look at the
fiscal year ending in December. The consensus forecast is $3.76,
however, the distribution reveals nine of the 10 analysts shown are
predicting $3.81 or more. One forecast at $2.75 is dragging the
consensus down to $3.76. General Growth Properties will report
annual earnings well above consensus forecasts if these nine
analysts are close to the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies I noticed with similarly low consensus forecasts
are Lehman Brothers Holdings (LEH), Georgia-Pacific (GP) and
General Dynamics (GD).
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the distribution of earnings estimates sounds good on
paper. However, I only recently discovered this feature on Quicken,
and I have no idea how the scheme works in practice. I suggest you
put this column away for three or four months, and then see how
stocks like Pillowtex, that looked like candidates for lowered
earnings forecasts or negative surprises, performed compared to
candidates for positive surprises like General Growth Properties.
</P>
<P>
   All of the estimates quoted in this column were observed last
Tuesday. The estimates are updated weekly, so you may see different
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Domash lives in Aptos, Calif., and publishes the Winning
Investing newsletter. You can read his columns at
www.winninginvesting.com or contact him at
hdomash &LR; winninginvesting.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
