<SLUG> BC-COUNCIL-ECONOMY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA ECONOMY GETS HIGH MARKS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Bay Area is winning big in the
new global economy, according to a report issued today (September
27) by the Bay Area Economic Forum and Bay Area Council.
</P>
<P>
   The report by McKinsey &AMP; Co. compared the nine-county Bay Area
to only seven comparable metropolitan areas _ Boston, Charlotte,
Houston, Los Angeles, New York, Phoenix and Seattle. Based on
McKinsey analysis of government and industry data and media
reports, the report found that the Bay Area has a statistical edge
in certain areas:
</P>
<P>
   --In computers, electronics and telecommunications, the area
produces from $16,000 to $52,000 more in annual revenues per
employee than second-ranked regions.
</P>
<P>
   --The Bay Area also ranks first in productivity in more
traditional areas of the economy, such as retail and wholesale
trade and &LR;   &LR; business services, and second in banking and finance
behind New York.
</P>
<P>
   --The Bay Area is second only to New York in its number of
Fortune 500 headquarters. Despite recent high-profile acquisitions,
the Bay Area has 26 Top 500 companies compared to 24 in 1995. New
York has 50.
</P>
<P>
   --The Bay Area has moved to first place in income per capita at
$38,300, compared to $35,900 in New York. In a similar study three
years ago, it trailed New York.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the good news, the Bay Area has some negatives:
</P>
<P>
   --It has the second-highest cost of living, due largely to
soaring housing prices and the high cost of labor compared to other
regions. Median prices for existing homes in the Bay Area are at
least 50 percent higher than in any of the other seven regions.
</P>
<P>
   --Traffic congestion has worsened and the Bay Area ranks second
only to Los Angeles in gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   --The Bay Area leads California in K-12 school educational
performance, but reading skills and class size are ``dismal''
compared to other cities outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   The new economic study also makes the following observations:
</P>
<P>
   --Northern California is home to more than 31 percent of the
nation's multimedia firms.
</P>
<P>
   --In 1998, 8,280 patents were issued in the Bay Area, more than
double the number issued five years earlier and more than twice as
many as in Boston, the second-ranking region.
</P>
<P>
   --Santa Clara County, the heart of Silicon Valley, has increased
employment at the rate of 23 percent a year between 1993 and 1998
and has more than 94,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   --Bay Area banking and finance employment grew 4.5 percent
annually between 1993 and 1998, but most of this growth was before
1995 &UR; . &LR;  Since then, the region has added only about 2,000 jobs, as
many banks have merged.
</P>
<P>
   --Tourism is a $5.5 billion annual business in the Bay Area.
Perhaps surprisingly, more than 55 percent of trips to the region
are business-related.
</P>
<P>
   --Retail trade in the Bay Area, including the Internet, has the
second largest number of employees after Chicago. Seventy-one
percent of them are clustered in Alameda, San Francisco, San Mateo
and Santa Clara counties.
</P>
<P>
   The full report is available online at www.bayeconfor.org and
www.bayareacouncil.org under ``Publications.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
