<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A FLASH, GORDON IS GONE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ladies and gentlemen . . . now pitching for the Red Sox
. . . Tom Gordon!
</P>
<P>
   Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   It will go down as one of the greatest comeback moments that
never was. Red Sox closer Tom ``Flash'' Gordon, who hasn't pitched
for the team since elbow woes put him on the shelf three months
ago, raced in from the bullpen Sunday, intent on pitching the ninth
against the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The Fenway legions roared in approval when they realized Gordon
was returning to action. It was one of the more heartfelt and
spontaneous ovations of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon got to the mound, resumed his warmup tosses, then saw
manager Jimy Williams coming out to talk with home plate umpire
Bill Welke. Williams had to inform the ump that he'd summoned a
pitcher who had not yet been activated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jimy first said it to the ump, I thought it was a joke,''
said Gordon. ``Then I realized, and I was like, `Wow, this is
serious.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Before you could say ``Dr. James Andrews,'' Gordon was gone. In
a Flash. As bewildered fans stood and applauded, Flash walked to
the dugout and tipped his cap. It was one of the most bizarre
non-appearances in the long history of Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear who made the mistake, but Williams took the
fall. The righty was on Williams's pregame lineup card as an extra
pitcher, but during the game, Sox officials in the press box
maintained that Gordon had not been activated. General manager Dan
Duquette called Williams in the dugout when he saw Gordon going to
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't Williams know what Duquette knew?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed up. How's that?'' said Williams. ``I was under the
understanding that he was to be activated. I should have
double-checked, and I didn't. I'm not in this to embarrass anyone.
I came up here to the clubhouse and apologized to him. I accept the
responsibility. It's my fault for not double-checking.''
</P>
<P>
   Orioles manager Ray Miller said, ``I don't understand how it
could happen. On weekends, you just call a machine (to activate a
player). He was on my lineup card, and the ump came over and
apologized to me. I know Jimy was pretty hot about it. If he'd
pitched and I found out about it, I'd have protested.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I made the call,'' said Duquette. ``If we won the
game (the Sox lost, 8-5) and used an ineligible player, the game
would be at risk. We wanted to be in a position for the win to
stand up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clubhouse, Red Sox players had a little fun with the
crowd of reporters around a man who did not play in the game. Bret
Saberhagen yelled to Nomar Garciaparra, ``Hey, maybe we got to make
a list _ bring in the mail, drop off the dry cleaning, activate
Flash!''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who has pitched in Trenton, Cape Fear, Fort Myers,
Augusta, and Pawtucket on his comeback trail, was not angry about
the mixup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just felt good, even though I didn't pitch,'' he said. ``I
felt good in the bullpen, and I think I sprinted to the mound
faster than normal. I'm disappointed I didn't have a chance to face
any batters, but I proved something to myself. I believe I'm ready
to pitch again. When it's time for me to pitch, I'll pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   He was touched by the reception from Red Sox Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're unbelievable fans. I felt like I was loved. The fans
cared about me and made me feel like a part of Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Flanagan, a former Cy Young winner and now a broadcaster
with the Orioles, recalled another non-appearance appearance at
Fenway a couple of decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Sammy Stewart and Tim Stoddard, both righties, warming
up in the bullpen, and Earl (Weaver) came out and called for the
righty. Stoddard came, and when Earl saw him he said, `I don't want
you; I want Stewart!' Stoddard told him, `That's fine, but I'm not
going back to the bullpen. I'm tired.' So he just came into the
dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the ninth, the Orioles did it again Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out and called for a lefty and raised my left arm,''
said Miller. ``And then here comes (righty Mike) Timlin. So I had
to yell for (Jesse) Orosco. And I was thinking, `What's going on
around here today?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette and Williams weren't sure if Flash would be activated
for Monday night's regular-season home finale against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'd better double-check,'' said the manager.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
