<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 05:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-ORIOLES-BOS &LR;      09-27 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER LATE THAN NEVER FOR ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The final pitch of the game from Orioles closer Jesse
Orosco seemed to glide across home plate so smoothly, you wonder
why Troy O'Leary didn't swing hard and drive the ball to the
deepest part of Fenway Park. Instead, O'Leary, who represented the
tying run, watched helplessly as umpire Bill Welke called him out
on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles win.
</P>
<P>
   As the days of the 1999 season begin to dwindle down to a
precious few, we've seen a lot of fantastic finishes by Baltimore,
even though the team was officially eliminated from the American
League wild-card race despite an 8-5 victory over Boston Sunday
before a crowd of 32,115. The Orioles have 16 victories in their
last 18 games. But does it matter? Is the team that was picked in
many preseason polls to win the AL East prepared to look in the
mirror and say it gave all it had?
</P>
<P>
   It is.
</P>
<P>
   ``People might think we're (playing) unconscious now,'' said
Orosco, who picked up his first save despite a club-high 63
appearances. ``But we are a pretty good ballclub. It just took us
too long to get going. We got off badly out of the chute and set
ourselves way back. If we could have played .500 against teams like
Toronto (1-11) and Cleveland (1-9), we could have been in
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won more games this month than we did in April, May. But
things didn't work out. We're not going to make jokes out of
ourselves. We've played our hearts out to the end, and I'm glad
we're salvaging a season. I just wish it could be July or August
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   To the average fan at Fenway Park, it was a day of
disappointment as the Red Sox lost again, even though they gained
ground in terms of clinching the wild-card spot. But their
frustration is no greater than that of the Orioles. Boston closes
out the season beginning Friday at Camden Yards, while only
bragging rights are at stake for the Birds.
</P>
<P>
   But first comes a series finale Monday night against Boston ace
Pedro Martinez. Next, Baltimore makes a pit stop in New York before
heading home. There is little chance the Orioles, at 77-78, can
catch third-place Toronto (79-77). It shouldn't be like this, but
it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been a frustrating year,'' said Orioles shortstop
Mike Bordick. ``We all thought we could play better, but
unfortunately, it's a little late. Still, we're proving to
ourselves we can play competitive baseball. The good thing about
this is that going into the offseason, we know that most of us will
be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordick assumes a lot. Management has yet to determine whether
the club that has gone 41-27 since the All-Star break is the team
of the future, or whether it's the club that began the year at a
36-56 clip. Nobody knows for sure. Not even manager Ray Miller,
whose head was definitely on the chopping block before the recent
surge. Miller isn't even thinking about the future. There are games
to play and races to act as spoiler in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing good in the second half,'' said Miller.
``We've had trouble in the bullpen, but the rest of the club has
been outstanding. The bullpen guys today weren't pretty, but they
got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what has happened to our season. But you can't make up
for anything. But I also don't think you manage or play a game
worried about the past or the future. These days, you better be
prepared to do the best you can to win because this is the big
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their lowly finish this season, the Orioles are still a
club that can frighten you even with two starters _ Delino
DeShields and Cal Ripken _ missing with injuries. It is no fun to
face a lineup that includes Brady Anderson, Bordick, B.J. Surhoff,
Albert Belle, and Charles Johnson. Belle is particularly annoying
in that he beats your brains out and doesn't even have the decency
to smile. Of course, he only would get booed by the Fenway
Faithful, so here he isn't missing anything.
</P>
<P>
   Belle hit a two-run homer, stole a base, and made a couple of
nice catches to hurt the Red Sox Sunday. Bordick had a key double.
The Orioles overcame a decent outing by Tim Wakefield by scoring
seven unearned runs off his knuckleball. They got a well-pitched
game out of rookie Jason Johnson. That's the way the Orioles used
to beat teams. Maybe they will again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked pretty dreary at first,'' said Miller. ``But our
guys made a good adjustment (to his knuckleball), waiting longer
and not trying to charge out there too soon. Johnson pitched well.
Boston fought back. That's why they are a good club. Jesse made the
pitch when he had to. That's what we have to do to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles certainly had trouble doing that before the break.
Miller didn't hesitate to pinpoint the blame: pitching. The bullpen
had 20 of its 27 blown saves in that period. Of those failures, 12
came in the eighth and ninth innings. The Orioles have great
starting pitching in Mike Mussina, Scott Erickson, and Sidney
Ponson. Johnson might be the next star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get the pitching straightened out,'' said Miller,
a longtime pitching guru and former Orioles pitching coach. ``I've
been here since the first day in 1997, and we haven't had a fifth
starter yet. This year we might come up with one. That should help
the bullpen. Our team ERA has dropped, but you can't change what
happened the first two months of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty good'' progress is not the Orioles' way. They have a
new catcher in Charles Johnson, fresh from the National League. He
struggled in the beginning, too. But lately he's been the backstop
we'd all heard about.
</P>
<P>
   Miller knows his players, particularly in the bullpen, must go
out and prove themselves every day. Closer Mike Timlin has
rebounded and now has 27 saves. The rest of the staff has only six.
The Orioles must do better.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Oriole way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
