<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYNE, REDMAN DROPPED BALL IN HEISMAN RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The first month of the college football season is in
the books, and it's time to take stock of the race for the Heisman
Trophy to start separating the pretenders from the contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates seemed to fall out of contention for the Heisman
over the weekend when the Ron Dayne Train was derailed in
Wisconsin's 21-16 loss to Michigan, and Louisville's Chris Redman
was upstaged by Oklahoma quarterback Josh Huepel in a 42-21 loss to
the Sooners.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, who needs 1,105 yards to break Ricky Williams's Division
1-AA rushing record, has stumbled of late, as have the No. 20
Badgers. In a 17-12 loss last week at Cincinnati, Dayne committed a
fumble as he was plowing toward the end zone for a go-ahead TD.
Saturday against the Wolverines, Dayne did a disappearing act in
the second half when the Badgers took to the air in the final 10
minutes in a desperate game of catchup.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne rushed 22 times for 88 yards, all in the first half. He
was held for no yards on eight carries in the second half, twice
failing to convert crucial first downs as the Badgers had an
eight-game home winning streak snapped.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dayne Train expects to arrive at the Downtown Athletic
Club in New York in December, he'll have to take the subway.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what impact the Wolverines had on Dayne's Heisman chances,
Michigan linebacker Ian Gold told the Detroit Free Press, ``I could
care less. Heisman, Schmeisman.''
</P>
<P>
   While Redman became the 14th passer in NCAA history to throw for
more than 10,000 career yards, pushing his total to 10,198 after
completing 24 of 49 passes for 292 yards and 2 touchdowns, Redman
was outgunned by Huepel, who threw for a school-record 429 yards
and five touchdowns to pin the tailspinning Cardinals (2-2) with
their second loss in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Six times in the first half, Louisville had chances from inside
the Oklahoma 37, but the team managed only 13 points. It wasn't
enough to sustain Redman's Heisman hopes or withstand Oklahoma's
aerial assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good in the second half,'' said Louisville coach John
L. Smith, ``but as time went on and the more balls they threw in
the air, the worse I felt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the other contenders? Florida State's Peter Warrick
bolstered his chances by helping the No. 1 Seminoles (4-0) to a
42-10 romp at North Carolina. Warrick had four catches for 103
yards and a 75-yard punt return for a touchdown that highlighted
FSU's 28-0 first quarter eruption.
</P>
<P>
   How 'bout that Drew Brees? The Purdue quarterback rallied the
No. 13 Boilermakers (4-0) to a 31-23 victory over Northwestern by
completing 32 of 50 passes for 405 yards and three TDs, including a
99-yarder to Vinny Sutherland with 6:20 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget Chad Pennington. Playing the entire game with a
painful thigh injury, the Marshall QB led the No. 22 Thundering
Herd to a 34-0 romp over hapless Temple by passing for 405 yards
and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showdown Saturday was oh-so-sweet for Washington coach Rick
Neuheisel, who recorded the first win of his career as the Huskies
coach against his former Colorado team, 31-24. The pregame tension
was palpable on both sides after Colorado coach Gary Barnett and
Neuheisel had waged a bitter war of words. Barnett accused
Neuheisel of tampering when it was learned he had contacted several
Colorado players. Neuheisel, though, admitted calling his former
players to personally bid his adieu. Saturday in Seattle, Neuheisel
got the chance to do so again, hugging, greeting, and encouraging
his former players afterward. ``It was nice to at least say _
legally _ good luck to them,'' said Neuheisel, somewhat
sarcastically . . . Auburn coach Tommy Tuberville, who had gone 0-4
vs. the Tigers before leaving Mississippi to take over at Auburn
last November, was stung by his former team when Ole Miss scored a
24-17 victory in overtime, marking the Rebels' first ever win at
Jordan-Hare Stadium . . . Oregon staged a wild 33-30 victory in
triple overtime against Southern Cal that wasn't decided until
third-string kicker Josh Frankel converted a 27-yard field goal as
the game lapsed into midnight. Frankel entered in the third
overtime after starter Nathan Villegas injured his knee on a field
goal that made it 23-23 with 33 seconds left and backup Dan Katz
missed a 33-yarder that would have won it in the first OT. But that
wasn't the crazy part. That came at the end of regulation after USC
had taken a 23-20 lead, but missed the extra point. The Trojans
were hit with a 15-yard penalty for unsportsmanlike conduct when
Faaesea Mailo ripped his helmet off to celebrate Chad Morton's
1-yard run. A chip-shot PAT turned into a 35-yard attempt that went
awry when the snap sailed over the holder's head. On the ensuing
kickoff, USC pounced on an Oregon fumble and threatened to expand
its lead, but the Trojans came away empty-handed when kicker David
Newbury missed a 30-yard attempt. The Ducks then gained possession
and drove to the USC 8, where, after three unsuccessful tries at
the end zone, Villegas connected on his tying attempt that sent the
game into OT. USC lost quarterback Carson Palmer just before
halftime with a broken collarbone. He will be out a minimum of six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So who are the winners and losers among first-year coaches after
the first month? The winners: June Jones has Hawaii at 4-0 after
the Rainbows snapped a 26-game losing streak on the road with a
20-0 victory at Southern Methodist. It also was Hawaii's first
Western Athletic Conference road victory in 15 games. And Oklahoma
coach Bob Stoops has the Sooners off to a 4-0 start, good enough
for the No. 23 spot in this week's Associated Press poll. The
losers include Lou Holtz, who has started 0-4 for the first time in
his career when South Carolina sustained a 17-10 loss to
Mississippi State. Then there is Baylor coach Kevin Steele, whose
team continues its tailspin after a season-opening 30-29 overtime
loss at Boston College. The Bears then had victory wrested away
against Nevada-Las Vegas when they lost on a freakish 100-yard
fumble recovery as time ran out. They got drilled by Oklahoma,
41-10, two weeks ago, and on Saturday they dropped to 0-4 _ marking
their worst start since 1978 _ by suffering a 62-0 thrashing
against visiting Texas. ``Some players are still thinking about
Boston College,'' said Baylor defensive back Daniel Wilturner. ``We
have to put this behind us. We have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
