<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 05:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-GRAHAM-BOS     09-27 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-GRAHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST START FIZZLES FOR FRAZZLED GRAHAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They made their first scoring drive look
easy. Almost too easy. Giants quarterback Kent Graham complemented
solid running by fullback Charles Way by completing 5 of 6 passes
for 50 yards, including a 6-yard touchdown toss to wide-open
running back LeShon Johnson. Ten plays, 66 yards, 5:50 elapsed. One
frighteningly impressive showing by the Giants offense Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to mix up a few formations early on, which kept (the
Patriots) off balance, I thought,'' said Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the remainder of the Giants' offensive output brings two
words to mind:
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   Graham and company seem about as confused about that as the
Patriots were on the first drive. They did manage to move the ball,
but not for long, until late in the fourth period, when their
hurry-up offense produced a 1-yard touchdown pass from Graham to
Tiki Barber with 1:14 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, New York was woeful at best. ``Maybe we need to go
to four wides and play the two-minute (offense) the whole game,''
said New York coach Jim Fassel. ``We just malfunctioned at
different times and weren't getting the chunks (of yardage) like we
did early. There's enough mistakes here or there to make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham completed 23 of 36 passes for 216 yards and two
touchdowns but led his team to just four passing first downs and a
36 percent third-down efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   How does a guy go from looking like John Elway on the game's
first drive to Scott Zolak the remainder of the game? Credit the
Patriots defense for keeping Graham on the run throughout and
preventing him from standing back in the pocket and looking for
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   In a running attack that mustered a total of 57 yards, Graham
was the team's No. 3 rusher, gaining 12 yards on six carries. He
would have had more than that, but he did most of his running east
to west, eluding tacklers and trying to salvage broken plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to scramble and make some plays,'' said Graham.
``They were playing man-to-man, and they have good cover guys, so I
was trying to buy some time and give our guys a chance to get open.
There were times when it worked. On the first drive, I was able to
scramble a few times and make some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the Patriots, Graham said, made a minor adjustment, and it
paid off for New England in a major way. ``They kept playing us by
bringing some corner blitzes on us (early), and we took advantage
of it,'' he said. ``But they got away from that as the game went on
and just tried to play us even up because they were getting hurt by
the biltzes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants couldn't mount a successful running game to stretch
the Patriots defense. ``We just have to keep working at it,'' said
Graham about the Giants running game. ``It's a tough thing. It's
tough to run the ball in the National Football League, and we
understand that. We just have to keep working at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Giants will learn to execute better on short-yardage
plays. With 6:50 left in the third quarter, the Giants drove to the
Patriots 41-yard line, and on fourth and less than a yard, Graham
tried a quarterback sneak but was stopped by Tedy Bruschi and
Willie McGinest for no gain.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham begged to differ with the officials' consensus that
the Patriots had stopped him. ``I thought that was pretty
controversial there, because I thought on the second effort I was
over the line,'' said Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I fell over the pile, I knew I was over the line, and I
thought I had it. The ref didn't see it that way. That will be
interesting to look at it on the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants play Philadelphia next week, and between now and then
they must find a way to get their inept offense going. ``The way we
came out in the first series,'' said Graham, ``I would have thought
we would have put more points on the board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
