<HEADER>
A7082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BRUSCHI-     09-27 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BRUSCHI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT TEMPER GETS BETTER OF BRUSCHI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Tedy was ready.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots and Giants were well into the fourth quarter Sunday
night, and the locals had the enemy stopped. Then they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   It was third and 10 from the New England 40, and the Patriots
were coming hard after quarterback Kent Graham. Chris Slade had him
sacked, and then things got a little crazy. The ball, which had
been blown dead anyway, was loose, and Bruschi ended up with it as
he was being tackled by guard Luke Petitgout. Then Bruschi lost it.
Just lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Bruschi, on his back, threw the ball at the Giant and ended up
with a 15-yard penalty for unsportsmanlike conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Giants had another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Bruschi warily headed for the defensive huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected when I got back to the huddle to get a tongue
lashing, really, from every single one of them from Slade all the
way to Chris Carter,'' Bruschi said. ``The guys sort of looked at
me, and I called the defense for the next play, and they had the
look in their eyes like, `let's move on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they weren't exactly thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little bit from the guys,'' Bruschi said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly it was the we've-still-got-a-job-to-do approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to see that,'' Bruschi said. ``I was glad to see
they didn't lose their focus because of my mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   No question, he said, it was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lost my composure,'' Bruschi said. ``That's something I
don't normally do. I pride myself on keeping my composure out
there. I thought I was tackled late, but that doesn't matter. I
just lost my composure, and luckily I dodged a bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   He and the defense stayed out and stopped the Giants again,
helped when Brad Dalusio missed a 41-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whew,'' said Bruschi, letting out a breath, when asked how it
felt to see the field goal go wide.
</P>
<P>
   The defense gave up a touchdown on New York's first and last
drives but little in between.
</P>
<P>
   Bruschi was in the spotlight several times.
</P>
<P>
   On the play just before his penalty, Graham threw the ball into
the end zone looking for former Boston College standout Pete
Mitchell. Bruschi was there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like I was covering him all night,'' Bruschi said.
``He ran an up, ran an out and back in, and all of a sudden he was
in the end zone, and there I am with him. I saw the very familiar
big eyes. You know, he got the big eyes like the ball was coming,
and I said, `Oh, oh, here we go.' I looked back and saw the ball
and just knocked it down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, trailing, 10-7, the Giants went for a first
down at the Patriot 41. On their touchdown drive in the first
period, Graham had kept for a yard on third and 1.
</P>
<P>
   From the 41, they tried the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it once before,'' Bruschi said. ``If you let them do
it twice in a game, you're really not thinking. I figured that was
the play they were going to do and just took a shot at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie McGinest clogged things up down low. Bruschi and Andy
Katzenmoyer came in up high. The Patriots held, and the offense
went back the other way and pushed the score to 13-7 with an Adam
Vinatieri field goal.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, despite the ``one glaring penalty'' that coach
Pete Carroll talked about, the Patriots and especially their
defense had done enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, by the way, had the same read as Bruschi on the
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse,'' Carroll said. ``Tedy will be the first
one to tell you he just blew it. He just lost his head, and that's
not OK. Just look at how costly it could have been. But we came
back and stopped them. That was a glaring error.''
</P>
<P>
   And one Carroll doesn't expect to see repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a guy who understands the game as well as anybody,''
Carroll said. ``I trust him that he'll figure it out and this won't
happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
