<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS DEFENSE TAKES STRIDES IN LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots were either ultra-conservative
or smart in their offensive game plan Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. They
apparently did not plan to score 50 points against the New York
Giants, who surrendered that many to Washington last week, but were
efficient enough to take command in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Giants anticipate allowing touchdown after
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they expected to play the team that got beat
last week,'' Giants defensive end Mike Strahan said of the Patriots
after a 16-13 loss. ``I think they did show respect for us, and we
showed respect for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they have an unstoppable offense _ I haven't
seen that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offense certainly seemed stoppable but performed
well enough to maintain the lead for most of the first half. But
the key was the Giants' defense, which had recovered nicely in the
last few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make the big plays defensively,'' Strahan said.
``But that will come with time. We just have to stay together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at that last field goal they got, and if we stop
that, we'd have won by a point. You always think about things like
that. Tonight, 16 points was just too much. Next week, we could
give up 7 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to a hostile environment, and now we're 1-2 and
we're behind the 8-ball, so it's back to the drawing board. But
personally, I don't plan on being 1-3.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Giants missed a field goal which might have changed
the complexion of the game. And the Giants actually did succeed in
the most crucial of situations by stopping the Patriots on the
2-yard line late in the third quarter, when the game could have
turned into a New England rout. Instead, the Giants remained in
contention. On their next possession, they had a chance to cut into
a 13-7 deficit, but Brad Daluiso missed a 42-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging by last week, the defense did pretty good,'' said
cornerback Jason Sehorn, playing his first game in more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn, who was injured during a special teams incident during
the 1998 exhibition season, was below full strength. But Sehorn
also earned the respect of the Patriots, judging by the short
patterns receivers ran against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to remember what a quick slant is,'' Sehorn said.
``I wasn't worried about the deep stuff because that is just
athletic ability. I just wanted to take away the `go' route. They
could have the 8-yarders but not the 80-yarders. If they were going
to beat me, they were going to have to dink it down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn, though, appears prepared to become a factor, possibly
the ``big play'' ingredient the Giants have been lacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy to be playing a game,'' Sehorn said. ``After
a year and a half off, it was nice. But there were a lot of moments
that let me know I'm not quite where I want to be. In the fourth
quarter, they started to run slants on me. But the game went pretty
much like I thought it would.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
