<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     09-27 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS NOT IMPRESSED WITH THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Undefeated and unimpressed. That's what your
New England Patriots are this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're winning, but it's not to our liking,'' safety Lawyer
Milloy said late Sunday night after his team had moved to 3-0 with
a tight, 16-14 victory over the New York Giants that was
highlighted this time by withering defense rather than overheated
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be 3-0 but the way we're playing we're not even
good yet. We want to dominate. We haven't dominated anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy is right about that. They have yet to dominate anybody,
but then again they have yet to lose to anybody either and in the
NFL that is what counts. Pro football is a bottom-line business.
It's about winning above all else and so far, above all else, the
Patriots have found ways to win.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday &UR;  &LR; night they did it with just enough Drew Bledsoe (20 of
28 for 233 yards) and Terry Glenn (five catches for 95 yards,
including a 45-yard deep slant that helped break the game open) and
more than enough defense to stuff the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy and Co. allowed New York to march 66 yards on its opening
drive to take a 7-0 lead, but that was in large part because the
Giants' hurry-up offense led to the defensive calls coming in late
and causing New England some confusion. Once that was solved, the
defense shut down the Giants until their second scoring drive, a
stretch of 46 minutes and 58 seconds during which New York was
forced to punt five straight times, was stopped on downs once, and
then missed a field goal before scoring a touchdown with 1:14 to
play that was meaningless to everyone but the gamblers in the crowd
who took the points and the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between those two scores was just enough offense to
carry the day and more than enough defense to keep things under
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be 3-0,'' Bledsoe said. ``We had to do it in
somewhat dramatic fashion but to be 3-0 at this point is a good
feeling. At the same time, it's only three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could make it easier on ourselves (in the future). We can
play better. We realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   For as long as they do realize that, these Patriots will be very
dangerous to everyone they play. The moment they forget is when the
trouble will begin.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the pattern the past two years. Fast start. Stall
out. Desperation sprint to the finish line to get into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a pattern Milloy was thinking about Sunday &UR;  &LR; night as he
contemplated his team's third straight fast start under Pete
Carroll, a start this year in which they have won by margins of 2
points, 3 points, and 2 points, which means they're not winning by
much but they're winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our adversity the last two years prepared us,'' Milloy said.
``It's a long season. We've always been strong at the start. But we
saw what can happen in the fourth or fifth or sixth week when
people start to get hurt. We know how good we can be at the end if
we stay healthy but we're a long way from the end.''
</P>
<P>
   They are, but they're close to being 4-0 for the second time in
three years because Sunday they play the Browns in Cleveland and
frankly, if the plane lands safely, that should be about all it
takes to ensure they will be undefeated when they head for Kansas
City to open the second quarter of their season. But if they are
still unblemished then, it seems they will go there with a far
different attitude than the last two years. An attitude that both
recognizes what they have done thus far (which is nothing
significant) and what they are capable of doing (which is something
very significant).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important to us to realize we're 3-0 and to
evaluate very clearly and be very truthful about it,'' Carroll
said. ``We all know we have better football ahead of us. We've won
ugly. We've won sloppy. Winning is what it's about but we got to
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to be better than 3-0 when you've only played
three games but it bodes well for the future that this edition of
the New England Patriots seems to realize it's possible to be
better.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, to get where they want to go in January, it also will
be necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 0515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
