<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 05:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7086 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GIANTS-B     09-27 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GIANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS PERFECTLY ACCEPTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots are 3-0 and the Jets are 0-3.
Who would have thought it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I did,'' said New England receiver Shawn Jefferson. ``I knew
we were capable of 3-0; I don't know about their team. That's not
my concern, but we have so much talent in here that I knew we could
beat these teams. Tonight we won the game a different way. We knew
they would be tough, but we just took what the defense gave us.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Giants defense didn't give too much. Not nearly as much
as it gave the Washington offense last week when it allowed 50
points, but enough for the Patriots to take a 16-14 win before
59,169 Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots lead the Miami Dolphins, who were off this week and
are 2-0, by a half-game in the AFC East. The Bills and the Colts
are 2-1 and the Patriots have a chance to go 4-0 for the second
time in the last three years when they visit expansion Cleveland
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to play us tough and that we couldn't
hang a big number on them,'' said quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who
went 20 of 28 for 233 yards with no touchdowns. ``We're fortunate
that we don't play in the same division as the Giants because
they're a tough team. We've had to fight right down to the end
(against) all of these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But while there was a sense of happiness in the Patriots' locker
room, there also was a dose of reality. The Patriots still have
room to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can make things easier on ourselves and we know that,''
said Bledsoe. ``In order to get to where we want to be we have to
play closer to our potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell also left the locker room
feeling unsatisfied, even though the Patriots allowed a
first-quarter touchdown to the Giants and not another until the
final 1:14 of the game when Kent Graham hit Tiki Barber on a 1-yard
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate to come away with the win,'' said Sidwell.
``We can say what we want, but right now we're not playing a
high-quality brand of defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again the game came down to Adam Vinatieri, whose third
field goal of the night, from 41 yards with 3:12 remaining, sealed
the win. Well, almost. Playing a softer defense, the Patriots
allowed the Giants to drive 70 yards to make it interesting at
16-14.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Coates recovered the ensuing onside kick and the Patriots
let the clock run out.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had to come from behind again, as they had the
first two weeks, but this time only from a 7-0 deficit after the
Giants' first possession of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Patriots is that they reduced their
penalty total from last week's 15 to three, though an
unsportsmanlike penalty for taunting by Tedy Bruschi nearly killed
the Patriots in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bruschi had broken up a Graham-to-Pete Mitchell toss in the end
zone when he got a hand on the ball at the last moment. Then his
temper got the best of him. After being in on a sack of Graham on a
third-and-10 at the Patriots 40, the ball came loose from Graham
after the play was dead. Bruschi came up with the ball and guard
Luke Pettigout then pounced on Bruschi, who threw the ball at
Pettigout.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots escaped when Brad Daluiso missed a 41-yard
field goal attempt wide left when a high snap gave Troy Brown time
to disrupt the kick.
</P>
<P>
   Bruschi breathed a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had dodged a bullet,'' Bruschi said. ``I'll never do
that again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to win games like this,'' said offensive
lineman Bruce Armstrong. ``We thought coming in it might be a trap
game, but somehow we got it done. I think we could have scored more
points, but it's another game off the schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their conservative game plan, the Patriots didn't run
the ball very well as the Giants held Terry Allen to 50 yards on 20
carries.
</P>
<P>
   The patient Patriots took control of the ball at the 32 late in
the fourth and ate the clock. With 3:17 left, Lamont Warren was
stopped for no gain, setting up the clinching field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Following a 7-7 deadlock at the half, the Patriots made
adjustments and shut down the Giants. They got the ball back,
drove, and Vinatieri kicked a 38-yard field goal to give the
Patriots a 10-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   New England's defense had its finest moment on the Giants'
second possession, after Barber's 36-yard return to midfield. The
Giants faced a fourth and 1 when the middle of the Patriots' line,
led by Henry Thomas, along with Bruschi, stopped Graham on a run.
The Patriots took over on downs on their 41.
</P>
<P>
   New England put together another patient drive to boost its lead
to 13-7. Bledsoe hit Terry Glenn (five catches for 95 yards) on a
slant for 16 yards and a nifty run by fullback Tony Carter produced
9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe found Coates with a 10-yard pass and he dragged a few
bodies an extra 4 yards to the 20. Bledsoe then found Brown for 11
yards to the 8. On third and 1, Bledsoe dropped back and appeared
to be going to either Carter or Coates, but Carter fell down and
the pass to Coates, who was being mauled, was out of reach. They
settled for a 19-yard field goal by Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants drove 66 yards in 10 plays on their first possession
of the game. Like the Jets and Colts, the Giants went right after
Ty Law. Graham hit Ike Hilliard for 27 yards to the Patriots 30.
Five plays later, Graham again found Hilliard over Law for 8 yards
on a second and 9 to the Patriots 10, and three plays later Graham
tossed to a wide open LeShon Johnson on the left side for a 6-yard
touchdown with 7:48 remaining in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until its fourth possession, early in the second
quarter, that the Patriots offense started to click. And it did so
in a big way. Bledsoe went up top to Glenn, who beat Phillippi
Sparks on a post to the middle of the field and made a beautiful
leaping grab at the 2. Two plays later, Allen busted through the
line from the 1 for the score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
