<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL AT QB: IT'S BLEDSOE OVER GRAHAM 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ This game was a perfect illustration of the
National Football League heading into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The team with the better quarterback wins.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be the team with the best defense won.
</P>
<P>
   But not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants had the better defensive team Sunday night
at Foxboro Stadium, but went home on the short end of a 16-14 score
because the Patriots had Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe vs. Kent Graham. The Patriots fans will take that every
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants came in here near the bottom of the league in
offense. In their first drive of the night, which put them ahead,
7-0, they lost their top runner, Sean Bennett, to a knee injury.
They already had lost Gary Brown, who had been their top back, to a
knee injury in preseason. Without them, the Giants didn't have
enough speed in the running game for it to be a concern of the
Patriots, who could concentrate on stopping a Giants pass offense
that is just average.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team could run the ball, both averaging 2 yards per
carry.
</P>
<P>
   This put the game squarely in the hands of the quarterbacks.
Bledsoe had the tougher assignment. Even though the Giants gave up
50 points last week to the Redskins, they are a good defensive team
with a solid game plan.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator John Fox had the New York defensive backs
jamming the New England receivers as they started into their
passing routes, throwing the timing that is so critical to the
Patriots' offense out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was more hesitant than he has been all year, but once he
figured it out, he started to hurt the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   He played well in the first half, completing 10 of 15 passes and
setting up the only New England touchdown with a well-executed
45-yard bomb to Terry Glenn that carried to the Giants 2-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   On the play, Glenn was set to the right, with Shawn Jefferson in
the slot. Jefferson ran a slant into the middle of the field, tying
up safety Sam Garnes. Meanwhile, Glenn ran right at cornerback
Phillippi Sparks, backing him up, then suddenly making a quick move
to the middle of the field, which was wide open. This was a
first-down pass and Bledsoe enjoyed his greatest success in
first-down situations, when the Giants were looking run.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe controlled the game in the second half. He marched his
team into Giants territory three straight times. They couldn't get
the TDs, but settled for three field goals, which were the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Armstead played a super game for the Giants, collecting 11
tackles, several behind the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants offense couldn't make the big play.
</P>
<P>
   Graham opened well, connecting on all five of his passes in the
first drive that ended with a touchdown and a 7-0 Giant lead.
</P>
<P>
   New York wouldn't score again for another 52 minutes when they
got another touchdown in the final two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Graham had 136 of his 201 yards passing in these two drives,
which means that in between he threw for just 65 yards. In the
third period, the Giants had just 16 yards total offense.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is mobile, but erratic. Time and again he would move
around the pocket, making room for himself to either run or throw.
Meanwhile, receivers often were getting open, but by the time he
set himself to deliver the ball, those openings were gone.
</P>
<P>
   The most critical play came in the opening minutes of the fourth
quarter. The Patriots were nursing a 13-7 lead, but the Giants had
the ball on the New England 40, second and 10.
</P>
<P>
   Graham went back to pass and scrambled to his right. The entire
right side of the field was open. He could have walked it 30 yards
deep into Patriots territory. Meanwhile, tight end Pete Mitchell
had gotten wide open behind Tedy Bruschi at the goalline. Graham
threw the ball too late, allowing Bruschi to recover and tip the
ball away. If the ball was delivered on time, it was a touchdown
and a New York lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have won three games, by 2, 3, and 2 points. Next
stop is Cleveland, where they should go 4-0 against a hapless
Browns team. One of their toughest tests of the season follows, at
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, all the Patriots have is a passing game. They can't
run the ball, and they can't get a pass rush without blitzing and
leaving themselves vulnerable in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   The trifecta of Bledsoe, Glenn, and Ben Coates is the best in
the league. Glenn had five catches for 95 yards. Coates had several
in clutch situations. But they'll need help from others as they get
into the heart of their schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
