<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Oct. 3)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Sept. 18 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE,
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE REEF, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.) Searching
</P>
<P>
   for a jeweled amulet in the depths of the Caribbean,
</P>
<P>
   a woman deals with mysteries and romance.
</P>
<P>
   3. WHEN THE WIND BLOWS, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $7.99.) A girl helps a widow and an FBI
</P>
<P>
   agent uncover a deadly plot.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE LOOP, by Nicholas Evans. (Dell, $7.99.) A biologist
</P>
<P>
   faces professional and romantic problems when she
</P>
<P>
   tries to protect wolves in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   5. RAINBOW SIX, by Tom Clancy. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   John Clark, heading a task force, probes terrorist
</P>
<P>
   incidents.
</P>
<P>
   6. UNSPEAKABLE, by Sandra Brown. (Warner, $7.99.) A
</P>
<P>
   psychotic killer, returning to his Texas hometown
</P>
<P>
   to wreak vengeance, uses a troubled widow as his pawn.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE WILDFLOWERS: Misty, Star and Jade, by V.C. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $3.99 each.) The first three novels in a series
</P>
<P>
   about troubled girls from broken homes.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE COUNTESS, by Catherine Coulter. (Signet, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A Gothic novel about a rich young woman whose life is
</P>
<P>
   threatened as she seeks Mr. Right.
</P>
<P>
   9. STILL WATERS, by Tami Hoag. (Bantam, $7.50.) A woman
</P>
<P>
   who is a newcomer to a small Minnesota town faces
</P>
<P>
   suspicion that she has committed murder.
</P>
<P>
   10. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   11. REMEMBER SUMMER, by Elizabeth Lowell. (Avon, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   An Olympic equestrian finds herself falling for a man of
</P>
<P>
   danger and intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE PILOT'S WIFE, by Anita Shreve. (Back Bay/Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) After learning that a plane flown by her husband
</P>
<P>
   has exploded, a woman tries to unravel the secret life
</P>
<P>
   he led.
</P>
<P>
   13. SUMMER SISTERS, by Judy Blume. (Dell, $7.50.) Two
</P>
<P>
   young women from very different backgrounds come of
</P>
<P>
   age on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   14. PROMISE, TEXAS, by Debbie Macomber. (Mira, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Every kind of romance invades a town in the heart of
</P>
<P>
   Texas.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) FIELD OF THIRTEEN, by Dick Francis. (Jove, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen stories of suspense.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) POINT OF ORIGIN, by Patricia Cornwell. (Berkley,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Kay Scarpetta battles an old enemy, a serial
</P>
<P>
   killer resuming her crimes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) An Irish-American writer recalls his childhood
</P>
<P>
   amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $14; Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of
</P>
<P>
   the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   4. MIDNIGHT IN THE GARDEN OF GOOD AND EVIL, by John
</P>
<P>
   Berendt. (Vintage, $12.) The mysterious death of a young
</P>
<P>
   man in Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Perennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   6. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   7. JOHN F. KENNEDY JR.: A Life in the Spotlight, by
</P>
<P>
   Michael Druitt. (Ariel/Andrews McMeel, $14.95.)
</P>
<P>
   An updated version of an illustrated biography.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   9. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10. INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   11. A RAGE TO KILL, by Ann Rule. (Pocket Star, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of 10 cases in which men and women felt
</P>
<P>
   impelled by rage to murder innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   12. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) Life in the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   13. OPHELIA SPEAKS, by Sara Shandler. (Harper Perennial,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) Dozens of girls, ranging in age from 12 to 18,
</P>
<P>
   discuss their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE GIFTS OF THE JEWS, by Thomas Cahill. (Talese/Anchor/
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, $14.) What Western civilization owes to an ancient
</P>
<P>
   nomadic tribe.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, by Laura Schlessinger and Stewart
</P>
<P>
   Vogel. (Cliff Street/Harper Perennial, $14.) The significance
</P>
