<HEADER>
A7112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      09-27 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sept. 26, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-TERRORISM-REVIEW (Moscow) _ It would be easy to say that
it is Russia's turn for an Islamic extremist problem. This month's
bloody invasion of Dagestan by Islamic guerrillas and the
subsequent bombings of Russian apartment houses, now widely
ascribed to them, seems most of all the harvest of a Russian-sown
whirlwind. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FATIGUE-REVIEW (Washington) _ Clinton fatigue is
essentially a catch-all to describe a general sense that people
have had enough of Bill Clinton. It was bound to happen. With the
explosion of 24-hour news on television and the Internet, Clinton
has been more in the face of Americans than any of his
predecessors. The Clintons, still craving the spotlight, do not
seem to have learned the oldest trick in show business: Always
leave them wanting more. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SUITS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Lawyers at the Justice
Department, at the same time they were trumpeting a sweeping civil
lawsuit last week against the tobacco industry, mentioned almost as
an afterthought that their criminal inquiry was dead. Officials
never provided the precise reasons for dropping the investigation.
By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BUSING-REVIEW (Undated) _ The traditional enemies of
busing to achieve school integration were once easy to spot: angry
white parents glaring at little black boys and girls stepping off
the bus at a new school. But as desegregation plans have fallen by
the wayside in so many schools districts it is not whites alone who
have favored its demise. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   LONGEVITY-TACTICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Is there anything you can
eat that might make you live a lot longer? The answer is yes, but
it's not entirely pleasant. By Nicholas Wade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORWELL-COMMUNISM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Animal Farm,'' the famous
1945 fable is, of course, George Orwell's take on what he called
``the Soviet myth'' of the Bolshevik Revolution and its corruption
of the ideal of Communism, but his other writings as a whole are
less tough on Napoleon/Stalin than on left-wing Western apologists
for the dictator and his regime. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS-CAMPAIGN-REVIEW (Washington) _ The way Republicans
were acting last week it was almost as if some of them could not
decide which was more uncomfortable: having Pat Buchanan leave the
party or John McCain stay in it. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BILLIONAIRE-CHILDSUPPORT-REVIEW (New York) _ To the delight of
New Yorkers disgusted by the spectacle and to the dismay of New
Yorkers dazzled by tales of fairy-tale opulence, the child support
battle between Patricia Duff, a multi-millionaire Democratic
fund-raiser, and her ex-husband, the billionaire Revlon chairman
Ronald O. Perelman, concluded last week. Now a judge who brings bag
lunches to court will decide whether to grant Ms. Duff's request
for $1.6 million a year in child support. By David Rohde. (With
graphic)
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-ASIA-REVIEW (Sydney, Australia) _ For more than two
decades, Australia has been trying to promote itself as part of
Asia. Now, in East Timor, it has found out how unnerving that
concept can be when put to the test. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW (Istanbul, Turkey) _ When Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit of Turkey meets with President Clinton and
congressional leaders in Washington this week, there will be much
talk about earthquake relief, geopolitics, and obscure though
important matters like trade arbitration and oil pipeline routes.
But on Capitol Hill and elsewhere in the United States, those
matters pale into insignificance. There the great question is at
once simpler and more complex: How democratic is Turkey? By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
