<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7114 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-THIS-WEEK-REVIEW-NY     09-27 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THIS-WEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A POWERFUL EARTHQUAKE DEVASTATES TAIWAN
</P>
<P>
   An earthquake registering 7.6 on the standard seismic scale left
more than 2,000 people dead, thousands more hurt, and more than
100,000 homeless in Taiwan. Days later, amid strong aftershocks and
lingering power outages, rescuers continued to search for survivors
trapped in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Hit hardest were the central and northern regions of the island,
where high-rise buildings collapsed and roads and bridges crumpled.
</P>
<P>
   With many businesses shut and semiconductor production
disrupted, economists were predicting a slowdown in the island's
economic performance as well.
</P>
<P>
   _ Calvin Sims
</P>
<P>
   A CALL TO ARMS FOR HUMAN RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan broke with a tradition of merely
summing up a year's work of the United Nations when he opened the
General Assembly debate and called in unambiguous terms for the
right of the organization to intervene anywhere when civilians are
put in mortal danger by their own governments or by civil wars. His
message: Leaders can no longer hide behind borders, using national
sovereignty as a shield against the world. France's foreign
minister, Hubert Vedrine, spoke for many leaders gathered at the
United Nations when he said that Annan had opened a profound debate
that will go on for years, and one that creates a new philosophical
divide between the developed nations and the third world.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Crossette
</P>
<P>
   AN EMOTIONAL VISIT TO BERLIN BY BARAK
</P>
<P>
   Germany may be ready to call itself a ``great power'' again, as
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder did recently, but it still worries
more than any other nation about its image. So the fact that the
first state visitor to Berlin since the German government moved
there last month was Ehud Barak, the Israeli prime minister, had
great symbolic importance. The visit gave Schroeder the occasion to
say that there could be no end to the process of remembering Nazi
crimes, as he stood with Barak at the former Sachsenhausen
concentration camp near Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli prime minister warned of the danger of neo-Nazism
but said he had ``no reservations'' about the move to Berlin and
was confident about Germany's democratic institutions. That was
precisely the message Germany wanted as its government starts work
in Berlin 54 years after the collapse of Hitler's Reich.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roger Cohen
</P>
<P>
   AN ART WAR IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph W. Giuliani drew a new line in New York's mayoral sand.
Fresh from his battles to tame New York's pedestrians, drivers who
cause gridlock and mosquitoes, he waded into the slippery waters of
artistic expression, vowing to cut city subsidies to the Brooklyn
Museum of Art if it doesn't cancel a ``sick'' exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The museum acknowledged that the show _ including a Virgin Mary
adorned with elephant dung _ is strong stuff, warning in promotions
that it ``may cause shock, vomiting, confusion, panic, euphoria and
anxiety.'' But mayoral intrusion, the lawyer Floyd Abrams warned,
``is at war with the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hubert B. Herring
</P>
<P>
   FOR ONCE IN WASHINGTON, HUMILITY TAKES A BOW
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a wonderful, swift decision on this,'' Werner
Gundersheimer, the president of the National Humanities Alliance,
said after the White House decided to turn down an invitation for
the president of the United States to pose as a scholar.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation had come from the National Endowment for the
Humanities, asking President Clinton to deliver the annual
Jefferson Lecture. For 27 years, it had been given by one of the
nation's leading scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarly community reacted with dismay at the thought of
introducing politics into what has always been an intellectual
event. Objections were raised by both Clinton's supporters and his
antagonists.
</P>
<P>
   One antagonist, William J. Bennett, who headed the endowment
under the Republicans, said, ``Sense prevailed,'' and added: ``This
is about scholarship. The president, whatever he is, is not a
scholar. I don't think that even he thinks he is.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Irvin Molotsky
</P>
<P>
   A STORM'S HARSH AFTERMATH
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, the monster hurricane that started rolling up the
Atlantic Coast two weeks ago, lived up to its billing in pummeling
shoreline homes, harbors and boats. Chickens and pigs too, posing
an unanticipated kind of health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's wake of rising, rain and tide-bloated rivers left
much of eastern North Carolina's vast farming country flooded,
along with parts of New Jersey, New York, Florida and Virginia. By
the weekend, it had been blamed for more than 60 deaths, more than
40 of them in hardest-hit North Carolina. Water, a greater evil in
this storm than wind, also posed an environmental and public health
disaster of leaking industrial chemicals and animal wastes.
Officials said the storm had drowned 1 million chickens and turkeys
and 110,000 hogs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter T. Kilborn
</P>
<P>
   SERBIAN OPPOSITION FALTERS
</P>
<P>
   As Serbs began a faltering new round of demonstrations to oust
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, the Kosovo Liberation Army
agreed, in extended negotiations that involved concessions by NATO,
to ``transform'' itself into a smaller, civilian Kosovo Protection
Corps. But the group, with new insignia, retains rights to bear
some sidearms, has access to helicopters and keeps the structure of
a paramilitary force. Serbian opposition leaders believe that
NATO's inability to protect Serbs in Kosovo has helped Milosevic
consolidate his political position in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven Erlanger
</P>
<P>
   FAMILIARITY STOPS THE PRESSES
</P>
<P>
   John Paul Jones famously declared ``I have not yet begun to
fight'' but last week Grove/Atlantic gave up the ship, killing a
disputed new biography of the American naval hero amid allegations
of copyright piracy. The book, which had taken the hero's most
famous line as its title, was by James Mackay, a prolific Scottish
author of some 160 titles. But it was termed ``a spectacular and
sustained act of plagiarism'' by a Columbia University history
professor, David Armitage, who found that it mirrored a 1959 Jones
biography by the late naval historian Samuel Eliot Morison. The
inquiry was undertaken after The New York Times raised questions
about close similarities. It was not a new issue for Mackay, who
has already been attacked for plagiarizing biographies of Alexander
Graham Bell, Mary Queen of Scots, Andrew Carnegie and Sir William
Wallace, the 13th century warrior celebrated as ``Braveheart.''
Before his phone line in Glasgow went dead last week, Mackay denied
any copying. ``There are only a certain number of words in the
English language,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ralph Blumenthal &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
