</P>
<P>
   Floyd, the monster hurricane that started rolling up the
Atlantic Coast two weeks ago, lived up to its billing in pummeling
shoreline homes, harbors and boats. Chickens and pigs too, posing
an unanticipated kind of health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's wake of rising, rain and tide-bloated rivers left
much of eastern North Carolina's vast farming country flooded,
along with parts of New Jersey, New York, Florida and Virginia. By
the weekend, it had been blamed for more than 60 deaths, more than
40 of them in hardest-hit North Carolina. Water, a greater evil in
this storm than wind, also posed an environmental and public health
disaster of leaking industrial chemicals and animal wastes.
Officials said the storm had drowned 1 million chickens and turkeys
and 110,000 hogs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter T. Kilborn
</P>
<P>
   SERBIAN OPPOSITION FALTERS
</P>
<P>
   As Serbs began a faltering new round of demonstrations to oust
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, the Kosovo Liberation Army
agreed, in extended negotiations that involved concessions by NATO,
to ``transform'' itself into a smaller, civilian Kosovo Protection
Corps. But the group, with new insignia, retains rights to bear
some sidearms, has access to helicopters and keeps the structure of
a paramilitary force. Serbian opposition leaders believe that
NATO's inability to protect Serbs in Kosovo has helped Milosevic
consolidate his political position in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven Erlanger
</P>
<P>
   FAMILIARITY STOPS THE PRESSES
</P>
<P>
   John Paul Jones famously declared ``I have not yet begun to
fight'' but last week Grove/Atlantic gave up the ship, killing a
disputed new biography of the American naval hero amid allegations
of copyright piracy. The book, which had taken the hero's most
famous line as its title, was by James Mackay, a prolific Scottish
author of some 160 titles. But it was termed ``a spectacular and
sustained act of plagiarism'' by a Columbia University history
professor, David Armitage, who found that it mirrored a 1959 Jones
biography by the late naval historian Samuel Eliot Morison. The
inquiry was undertaken after The New York Times raised questions
about close similarities. It was not a new issue for Mackay, who
has already been attacked for plagiarizing biographies of Alexander
Graham Bell, Mary Queen of Scots, Andrew Carnegie and Sir William
Wallace, the 13th century warrior celebrated as ``Braveheart.''
Before his phone line in Glasgow went dead last week, Mackay denied
any copying. ``There are only a certain number of words in the
English language,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ralph Blumenthal &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 0838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 08:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7115 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-RUSSIA-TERRORISM-RE     09-27 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RUSSIA-TERRORISM-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MOSCOW, A WHIFF OF TERROR FROM AFAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be easy, and to some tempting, to say that it is
Russia's turn _ that after years of Soviet gloating over Islam's
attacks on the West, that after the KGB's goading of proxies like
the East Germans to arm Middle Eastern terrorists, that after the
brutal destruction of Chechnya in the civil war three years ago, it
is well past time that Russia had her own Islamic extremist
problem.
</P>
<P>
   It also might be true. This month's bloody invasion of Dagestan
by Islamic guerrillas and the subsequent bombings of Russian
apartment houses, now widely ascribed to them, seem most of all the
harvest of a Russian-sown whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, though, is that the latest uprising in Russia's
Caucasus is not merely the Kremlin's problem _ not any more than
the collapse of Lebanon was just an Israeli migraine. Lebanon was a
geopolitical running sore, an imploded state that threatened for
years to destabilize even prosperous and militarily robust nations
like Israel, whose problems would then ripple out to the wider
world as well.
</P>
<P>
   Envision Dagestan's bad neighbor Chechnya, from whence the
guerrillas sprang, as the Lebanon of the Caucasus: another imploded
state, its government a husk, its real rulers Islamic militias
intent on expanding their political and religious influence. Then
substitute Russia for Israel, and the potential for trouble is
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the goal of the operation was the occupation of
Dagestan,'' Alexander Iskandaryan, director of Moscow's Center for
Caucasian Studies, said in an interview. ``It seems to me that the
goal is the destabilization of Dagestan _ and, perhaps, of Russia
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The parallels between Chechnya and Lebanon, Russia and Israel
are, of course, anything but exact. The Chechen militias that
invaded Dagestan almost certainly are backed by radical
fundamentalists in places like Saudi Arabia and Pakistan _ the
Saudi-born terrorist Osama bin Laden, Russia charges, or wealthy
troublemakers like him. But unlike the situation in Lebanon, where
the militias often acted as proxies for various Middle East allies,
including Iran and Syria and Israel itself, the evidence that
foreign governments are feeding the Chechen-led insurrection is so
far slight.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Russia Israel. Russia is not encircled by enemies devoted
to its destruction, and the notion that a few thousand rebels could
overwhelm an 11-time-zone colossus is ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they might not need to. Russia today, like
Israel 20 years ago, is divided and deeply uncertain about the
future, if for different reasons. Israel's biggest worries then
were external, while Russia's today are of its own making: domestic
havoc has stripped people of the sense that their economy, their
politicians, their law and order _ even their territory _ are under
control.
</P>
<P>
   So impotence in the Caucasus can be just as unnerving to
Russians, or even more so, as was frustration in Beirut to
Israelis. And Russia clearly has been unnerved.
</P>
<P>
   Military leaders have responded to the Chechen insurrection in
outsized fashion, by pouring thousands of troops into Dagestan and
ordering that a deep trench be dug along the Chechen border _ a
Berlin Wall, of sorts, but intended to keep people out rather than
in. On Thursday and again on Friday, Russian jets bombed the
Chechen capital of Grozny, destroying petroleum terminals and radar
installations that Russian strategists said aided rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the week, a deputy chief of the general staff assured
citizens that the Kremlin had learned the bitter lessons of its
defeat in the Chechen civil war and had no plans to repeat it. But
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, in Kazakhstan, swore to ``pursue the
terrorists everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You will forgive me,'' Putin said, invoking an old military
saying, ``but if we catch them in the toilet, we will rub them out
in the outhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as they go, analysts here say, such threats are not
entirely unjustified: The rebel invasion seems mostly unprovoked.
The trouble is that military action alone is a prescription for
further instability, and Moscow so far has no other notion of how
to cope with an internal insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Russia lost Chechnya _ permanently, it seems _ by dint of force.
Russians subjugated the region in the 19th century, and Stalin
ensured lasting hatred by forcibly marching virtually the entire
population of Chechnya to Kazakhstan in a failed attempt to forever
Russify the area.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its shared border, Dagestan is not another Chechnya _
not yet. Its residents mostly practice a more traditional form of
Islam and see themselves as part of the Russian Federation. Indeed,
Moscow responded to the Chechen incursion by handing out rifles to
Dagestan's young men.
</P>
<P>
   But in other ways, Dagestan is ripe for infection with the
Chechen virus.
</P>
<P>
   Its economy has been ravaged by Russia's depression and
Chechnya's civil war, and the majority of people are unemployed and
uneducated. The birth rate is high and the youth, idle and
rootless, are prime targets for the strict anti-establishment
tenets of the Chechen fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Dagestan government, a rickety alliance of nearly 40 ethnic
leaders, is rotted by corruption. And economic dislocation has
pushed ethnic groups into each others' territories.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Moscow's politicians have shown neither the inclination
nor the financial means to bring about the economic and educational
improvements that might prevent radicalism from taking root. Air
strikes and troops have kept the rebels out, but only at the cost
of destroying towns along the Chechen border and creating still
more poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And that is a dangerous prescription, because for Moscow, the
stakes are much higher than mere control of chunks of territory in
regions much of the rest of the world has never heard of. The
Caucasus is Russia's geographic buffer against Iranian
fundamentalism and its principal window on the Black and Caspian
Seas, with their oil and access to the Mediterranean. But it is
also more.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Caucasus through which Russia has sought to project
power for the last 150 years. Its loss would sap the steadily
draining reservoir of national will, with unpredictable political
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 0839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
