<P>
   ``The history of this century shows this is really a unique
phenomenon,'' said Michael Beschloss, the presidential historian.
``You have both the disquietude of the president in office plus the
added element of him having been there all those years.'' He
contended that while people would be uneasy about a third Clinton
term, if he were allowed to run again, they would not have had such
qualms with other two-term presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no Eisenhower fatigue in 1960,'' Beschloss said.
``He would have been elected to a third term by a huge landslide.''
Ronald Reagan might have been elected to a third term as well; many
Republicans said they viewed President George Bush's tenure as the
third term of the Reagan administration. Other modern presidents
were not as popular, perhaps not so much because of general fatigue
but because of catastrophic events that undermined their
presidencies. President Lyndon B. Johnson, unable to climb out of
the Vietnam War, did not dare seek re-election. President Richard
M. Nixon did, but was soon forced from office by Watergate. Jimmy
Carter was the beneficiary of Watergate fatigue, but could not
survive the malaise of a foul economy and the Iranian hostage
crisis when the sunnier Reagan came along.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are delighting in their diagnosis of Clinton
fatigue. Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas said former Sen. Bill Bradley
has crept up on Gore in polls in some states because ``he doesn't
have the baggage of the Clinton presidency around his neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ferment about fatigue may be overblown, stirred up by a
restless press and pundits longing to begin the millennium with a
fresh presidential story line instead of what has seemed the
inevitable faceoff between Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
In addition, critics of Clinton and Gore may find it easy to lump
the administration's troubles under the ``fatigue'' umbrella _ and
try to drag Gore down with them.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Fred Steeper, the pollster for Bush, the
Republican front-runner, said: ``Fatigue is too weak a concept to
fit the public attitudes about the White House. I call it Clinton
disgust.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every voter may be so disgusted. Polls show evidence of a
Clinton fatigue, but one that is not particularly potent. Clinton's
robust job approval ratings have barely budged.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not entirely clear that Clinton fatigue is ailing
Gore. In a Washington Post/ABC News Poll this month, 53 percent of
respondents said they were ``plain tired'' of Clinton, but 45
percent disagreed with that statement. Respondents were evenly
split over whether Gore was too close to the president ``to provide
the fresh start the country needs.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Gore may not be electrifying Democrats for reasons
that have nothing to do with Clinton. It has always been a struggle
for anyone in a president's shadow to develop a distinct persona
early in a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York said in his
endorsement of Bradley last week, ``We'd have to go back to Van
Buren to find a vice president who succeeded to the presidency.''
He corrected himself after audience members reminded him that
George Bush succeeded Ronald Reagan. Still, that is two vice
presidents elected to succeed a president since 1836.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Clinton fatigue, Frank Newport, editor-in-chief of
the Gallup Organization, said: ``I scratch my head. It's an easy
phrase to use. But I'm inclined to look more at the candidate, that
Gore is doing poorly because of Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael D. McCurry, Clinton's former press secretary, rejects
the concept of Clinton fatigue because, he argued, the public is
too disengaged to be fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how, suddenly, people have turned a switch
in their head and said, `I'm tired of Bill Clinton,' '' he said.
``They've spent seven years with this president. He's not in their
face because most people are checked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the characteristics that people say trouble them about
Clinton _ notably his morals _ do not trouble them about Gore. Just
the same, voters do not give Gore much credit for what people see
as Clinton's accomplishments, like prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The fatigue factor is so tough to gauge that Clinton and Gore
seem uncertain how to grapple with it. Gore is constantly recasting
his relationship with Clinton. First he played loyal lieutenant,
boasting about Clinton-Gore accomplishments. Then he stopped even
mentioning Clinton by name. Then he bluntly condemned the president
for personal transgressions. (Cynics suspects that that was a ploy
hatched with a White House wink to allow Gore to break out on his
own.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of one day last week, Gore seemed to shift his
pitch several times. At one point, he criticized his
administration's performance, saying, ``I'm not satisfied.'' Later
in the evening, at an event with the president, he softened,
saying, ``We've been doing a lot of things right, but it is time to
start a wave of change in this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore should not necessarily take personally the
cries of fatigue. ``You can only imagine what the Roosevelt fatigue
was like!'' said James Carville, an architect of Clinton's campaign
in 1992, recalling the 12-year tenure of Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of F.D.R., Gore can take comfort, for voters, far
from fickle, chose continuity over a fresh face: Taking on
Roosevelt in 1944, Thomas E. Dewey assailed the three-term
incumbent for surrounding himself with ``tired old men in
Washington.'' But a tired old man won re-election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 0840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
