<HEADER>
A3116 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-ORWELL-COMMUNISM-RE     09-27 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ORWELL-COMMUNISM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORWELL'S 2-LEGGED MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Readers of a certain age should have no trouble alerting young
viewers to the identities of the main characters in the new version
of ``Animal Farm'' to be telecast on TNT on Sunday, Oct. 3: That
show pig, Old Major, is a stand-in for Lenin; that vicious-looking
porker, Napoleon, can be nobody but Stalin, and that sometime
comrade, Snowball, soon to be on the trot from Stalin, is Trotsky.
</P>
<P>
   The famous 1945 fable is, of course, George Orwell's take on
what he called ``the Soviet myth'' of the Bolshevik Revolution and
its corruption of the ideal of communism, but his other writings as
a whole are less tough on Napoleon/Stalin than on left-wing Western
apologists for the dictator and his regime. They, more than Russian
propagandists, drew his fire.
</P>
<P>
   In a preface to the 1947 Ukrainian translation of ``Animal
Farm'' (for Soviet exiles) Orwell, a lifelong socialist, explained
that he got the idea from seeing a 10-year-old boy in an English
village whipping a huge cart horse (the model for the strong but
stupid Boxer): ``It struck me that if only such animals became
aware of their strength we should have no power over them, and that
men exploit animals in much the same way as the rich exploit the
proletariat.''
</P>
<P>
   Orwell attributed his book's rejection by several major British
publishers to editors with a soft spot for communist claims to a
nonexploitive society and a disinclination to criticize a wartime
ally. In 1944, he wrote to T.S. Eliot of the ``imbecile suggestion
that some other animal than pigs might be made to represent
Bolsheviks.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what his parable conveys, Orwell did not credit the
contention among admirers of Lenin and Trotsky that perverse
developments in the Soviet Union dated from the ascendance of
Stalin. He wrote in a 1946 magazine article that ``all the seeds of
evil were there from the start'' and that things would not have
been substantially different if Lenin or Trotsky had remained in
control.
</P>
<P>
   He even found a conciliatory word in the introduction to the
Ukrainian translation of ``Animal Farm'' for the Stalin gang's
``barbaric and undemocratic methods,'' on the grounds that with the
best of intentions they might have had difficulty acting otherwise
under the pressing conditions after the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Orwell saw it, that excuse was not available to Western
writers, whose job was not to concoct apologies for a murderous
regime but to expose it. And that, he charged repeatedly, was what
many on the British Labor Party's left wing failed to do from the
1930s through the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   He found them succumbing to a theory he described as
``catastrophic gradualism.'' Propagated by defenders of the Soviet
Union in all its ugliest manifestations, this theory held that
purges, deportations and the secret police were the price of
progress. If the advance toward the communist millennium
nevertheless turned out to be slow or imperceptible, that was laid
to ``human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular (and Popular Front) formula, he noted, was ``You
can't make an omelet without breaking eggs.'' However, he added, if
someone replied, ``Yes, but where's the omelet?'' the answer was
likely to be ``Oh well, you can't expect everything to happen in a
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year after the publication of ``Animal Farm,'' Orwell
attended a meeting of Britain's Pen Club, where his opinion of the
sorry condition of much of British socialism was confirmed.
Moscow's purges of old comrades were cheered, and there was no
breath of criticism for the regime.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, he came down hard on writers who had betrayed
their vocation. Not long after the Pen Club meeting, in an essay
called ``The Prevention of Literature,'' he wrote, ``The fog of
lies and misinformation that surrounds such subjects as the Ukraine
famine, the Spanish civil war, Russian policy in Poland and so
forth is not due entirely to conscious dishonesty, but any writer
or journalist who is fully sympathetic to the USSR _ sympathetic,
that is, in the way the Russians themselves would want him to be _
does have to acquiesce in deliberate falsification on important
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   It exasperated him that even when it came to strictly literary
judgments, left-wing philistines hewed to the Soviet line. They
attacked ``highbrows'' and relied on a version of political
correctness as a cultural guide: ``X is a political enemy:
Therefore he is a bad writer.'' So much for the likes of Eliot and
other modernists whose work he admired.
</P>
<P>
   In his indictment of the writer who succumbed to pressure or
incentives to adjust his opinions and ``switch his allegiance at
exactly the right moment'' in accord with the political winds from
the East, as many did in concocting rationalizations for Soviet
flip-flops regarding Hitler's Germany, Orwell observed, ``He must
either tell lies about his subjective feelings or else suppress
them altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that such is the road to a writer's destruction: ``Not
only will ideas refuse to come to him, but the very words he uses
will seem to stiffen under his touch.''
</P>
<P>
   That, taught Orwell, a staunch supporter of the democratic left
and of the sanctity of the word, was the inevitable price of
totalitarianism. The certain punishment for those on the fellow
travelers' farm: ``Good writing stops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
