<SLUG> BC-R-REPUBLICANS-CAMPAIGN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MCCAIN MUTINY  
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. (The Week in Review) 
(js) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The way Republicans were acting last week it was
almost as if some of them could not decide which was more
uncomfortable: having Pat Buchanan leave the party or John McCain
stay in it.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Buchanan, McCain, the senior senator from Arizona, has
said he is a Republican through and through with no interest in
making a third party bid for the presidency. Yet as he wages his
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination he has a way of
casting a searing light on his party.
</P>
<P>
   Take McCain's call for Republicans to stand ``on principle'' and
bid Buchanan goodbye because of his isolationist views on World War
II and questions about whether Hitler was a threat to the United
States after his air force was defeated in the Battle of Britain.
The senator was met with either disagreement or cautious silence by
the other Republican presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a bye on this,'' a spokesman for Elizabeth Dole said
initially. It took another day for Mrs. Dole to say Buchanan's
comments ``are grossly insensitive to those Americans who gave
their lives and those veterans who fought and suffered greatly to
preserve freedom in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, an aide to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said
America's soldiers ``were fighting for freedom.'' Then, on Friday,
Bush himself urged Buchanan not to bolt the Republican Party,
saying ``I'm going to need every vote I can get among Republicans
to win the election.''
</P>
<P>
   The hesitation baffled other Republicans. ``It seems a moment in
which the Republican Party can rid of itself of the unfair
characterization of being extremist,'' said Marshall Wittmann, a
political analyst at the conservative Heritage Foundation. ``Yet
there's a bewildering reluctance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the fracas that ensued last week when an array of
conservative groups including Americans for Tax Reform, the
Christian Coalition, the National Rifle Association and the
National Right to Life Committee journeyed to two key primary
states to denounce McCain for his campaign finance bill, which
would ban unlimited and unregulated donations to political parties.
Usually these are groups that are treated with reverence by
Republicans because they can mobilize conservative voters. But the
McCain campaign fired right back at the critics, noting that some
of them are lobbyists paid by companies and business interests that
make so-called soft money donations.
</P>
<P>
   Grover Norquist, the head of Americans for Tax Reform, was
philosophical, saying that while Buchanan and McCain ``both have
assets for the party they are each running for president in an odd
way.'' He said McCain ``has been seeking editorial approval from
The New York Times and The Washington Post at the expense of the
Republican base.'' And Buchanan ``thinks you can run for president
without the business community,'' Norquist said. ``That's odd,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, who is the national co-chairman of
the McCain campaign, said: ``John McCain is just being John
McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those less happy with the kinds of waves McCain causes
in conservative ranks it could be the beginning of a long few
months. After all, McCain does not even make his candidacy official
until Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 0844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
