<SLUG> BC-R-TURKEY-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GROUNDSWELL FOR MORE HUMAN RIGHTS  
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(js) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ When Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit of Turkey
meets with President Clinton and congressional leaders in
Washington this week, there will be much talk about earthquake
relief, geopolitics and obscure though important matters like trade
arbitration and oil pipeline routes. But on Capitol Hill and
elsewhere in the United States, those matters pale into
insignificance. There the great question is at once simpler and
more complex: How democratic is Turkey?
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that Americans think about Turkey, this is the
question they most want answered. They want Turkey to stop jailing
people for giving speeches or writing articles, and to grant its
citizens the level of freedom enjoyed by most Americans and
Europeans. Otherwise, no matter how much progress is made on
international issues, Americans will continue to group Turkey with
Peru, Malaysia, Belarus, Zimbabwe and other quasi-democracies where
human rights have been pushed aside in favor of what ruling
autocrats consider issues of national security.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey has built a vibrant economy, given equality to women and
created a remarkably open society. Yet precisely because the nation
is so Western-oriented, its people have become impatient for full
Western-style democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish military commanders still enjoy the right of veto over
important government decisions. A highly conservative political
elite enforces laws that restrict free expression and other civil
rights. Nonetheless, Ecevit and his aides come to Washington with a
relatively good human rights story to tell. ``They clearly have
more to show in terms of actions, laws, decrees and actual shifts
on the ground than any other recent government of Turkey,''` said
one Clinton administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Government-sponsored assassins who terrorized the mostly Kurdish
provinces of southeastern Turkey for years seem to have packed
their guns away. Radio stations there are now allowed to play
Kurdish music. The Parliament has approved a repentance law for
Kurdish rebels, albeit a highly limited one. In Turkish prisons,
according to Sir Nigel Rodley, a U. N. investigator, there has been
``a reduction in the incidence of the more brutal forms of
torture.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement reflects Turkey's dilemma. Its human rights
record, not just regarding torture but in all important areas, is
better than it has been in years. But it still falls short of what
the West considers to be minimum standards.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the greatest pressure for improvement in Turkey's
human rights climate comes not from Washington or European
capitals, but from within Turkey itself. Millions of Turks, many of
them outraged by the state's failure to react effectively to last
month's earthquake, have begun demanding sweeping reforms and the
repeal of laws that restrict democracy. Even some senior
politicians have joined the chorus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey understands more clearly than ever how urgent it is for
us to create a civil society built on democracy and social
justice,'' said Mehmet Ali Irtemcelik, a cabinet minister
responsible for human rights and relations with Europe. ``We must
bring our country to the level of modern civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Although these views are widely shared, many powerful figures
still resist them. This week, President Clinton will probably
encourage Ecevit to embrace the reform movement and overrule those,
including military commanders and senior members of his own
coalition government, who fear its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   This autumn will be full of challenges for Turkey. In November
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which
places human rights at the top of its agenda, will hold a summit in
Istanbul. A month later the European Union, which has also looked
skeptically at Turkey's human rights record, will decide whether to
make the nation an official candidate for membership.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit is acutely aware that the world is watching to see how he
deals with a handful of high-profile human rights cases.
Foreigners, along with millions of Turks, will be thrilled if final
decisions are made to punish police officers who tortured teen-age
prisoners in Manisa in 1995, others who beat the journalist Metin
Goktepe to death in 1996, and prison guards who killed 10 Kurdish
prisoners in Diyarbakir following a riot that same year.
</P>
<P>
   This month one of Turkey's best-known prisoners, the pro-Kurdish
sociologist Ismail Besikci, was released from prison. He was warned
that he would be sent back to prison if he again violates laws
against publishing subversive opinions, but his release was
nonetheless welcomed by human rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Other prisoners whose cases have attracted worldwide attention
include Akin Birdal, head of the country's largest human rights
group; Leyla Zana, a Kurd who is a former member of Parliament and
whose supporters in Europe and the United States have made her
probably the most famous Turkish citizen in the world, and the
blind lawyer Esber Yagmurdereli, who has been convicted of
supporting terrorism on the basis of evidence that human rights
groups say was fabricated. Yagmurdereli has spent 16 of his 54
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that the human rights situation in Turkey is
improving,'' he said in a telephone interview from prison. ``It's
the result of several factors, including a lull in the Kurdish war,
improved relations with the European Union, and the better climate
that has followed the earthquake. But in truly democratic
countries, people are guaranteed basic freedoms. That still isn't
the case here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
