<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-CO     09-27 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Everyone seems to be looking for a tip
 &HT;    For release Sept. 29, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It caught me by surprise. As I stood at the take-out window of a
popular barbecue haunt, one of the counter men thrust a quart-sized
styrofoam cup toward me. Scratched in red were the words ``Tips
Please.''
</P>
<P>
   I declined.
</P>
<P>
   Soliciting for tips has become a cottage industry and, to me,
ranks high in the bad taste bracket. The day prior to my encounter
with the counter man, I received an unconventional renewal notice
from my local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The invoice, in addition to the cost of the newspaper for
another year, left a space for what it called ``Carrier Tip.'' It
was marked ``optional,'' but I wondered if I gave a tip there,
would my newspaper carrier stop sending me insincere Christmas
cards with his or her home address on a return envelope?
</P>
<P>
   Walk into donut shops these days, and there's a tip box _
usually handmade _ atop the counter where the donuts and coffee are
passed across to you. Places such as McDonald's and Burger King
are, thankfully, havens from such tip appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, I charged dinner at a national chain seafood
restaurant. When my credit slip came for me to sign, there was
incremental information on it. It told me how much to tip if I
wanted to tip 15 percent, how much at 20 percent and how much at 25
percent; right on down to the penny. The restaurant likely thinks
it is providing a service but I was alienated.
</P>
<P>
   Before anyone in the food service industry starts calling for my
head, let me say that I am a 20 percent tipper. Most food servers
are horribly underpaid and dependent upon tips. I start at 20
percent and only if the service is sour do I reduce it to 15
percent. There are times when I tip more but I don't want my wife
to know that.
</P>
<P>
   My take on tipping and food service is that the server is my
representative in the restaurant's kitchen. I tell the server what
I want, declare what I don't want _ raw onions, mayonnaise,
well-done meat, etc _ and that person takes the order to the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   It is his or her obligation to see that the chef honors my
wishes. I don't want to be served a sandwich with mayonnaise on it
when I have told the server I did not want that. ``Oh, I told the
chef not to put mayonnaise on it,'' the server likely would
counter, fending off accountability. ``Not good enough,'' my
thought process goes, ``you should have checked it yourself _
you're working for me; i.e. tips.''
</P>
<P>
   Anytime you have to send something back, the server has failed.
The size of the gratuity should be based on that criteria.
</P>
<P>
   With take-out joints, it's entirely different. These people do
not serve you in the manner of restaurant servers. They slip some
donuts into a bag and hand it to you. Or they put some spare ribs
into a styrofoam box and slide it across the counter. There's no
personal service involved. Most of the time, you really don't know
what you have (or don't have) until you get it home and open the
bag. At times, what you ordered and what you received are
unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   As for my newspaper delivery person _ the 5:30 a.m. type _ I've
never seen him or her in my life but still respond to the vaguely
obscured Christmas card appeal with a financial gift _ but not at
subscription renewal time too.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how or where, the idea of tipping for everything
came into being. I strongly suspect the Europeans as they have
built in a percentage service charge to your restaurant bill.
Tipping is not an option there; only the prospect of leaving
additional funds following excellent service.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder at bosses who allow their employees to display crude
tip containers on the counter, or add the option as part of a
formal invoice. It does not enhance the image of the establishment
_ and also indicates that the people who work for them are not
being paid well enough to get by on just their salaries. So they
beg.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
