<HEADER>
A7155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX     09-27 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Another slap at the presidency
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's sometimes the oddments of news that tell us what's really
going on _ buried stories, perhaps draped over an appliance-sale
ad.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton has dropped out as next year's Jefferson
Lecturer on the Humanities, selected by the National Endowment for
the Humanities.You probably didn't know he'd even been scheduled to
speak. Few did.
</P>
<P>
   But his retreat under fire tells us something very large, and
not very pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   It tells us that the hatchet-job partisanship of the '90s has so
hacked up the presidency no occupant of it may any longer be taken
as speaking from it with other than degraded motives.
</P>
<P>
   Academia went quite bananas at the prospect of Clinton taking a
lectern occupied in the past by historian Barbara Tuchman, poet
Gwendolyn Brooks, novelist Robert Penn Warren and other
intellectual swanks.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the scholarly community has little to engage it, outside
faculty-lounge spats and scrounging space in esoteric journals. The
chance to boo a president off stage as an unworthy, jumped-up
Arkansas pig farmer offered high drama. It is an indignity,
apparently, to be addressed by the president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural right's umbrage king, the ever-appalled William
Bennett, sputtered boilerplate outrage, too: ``This is horrible,
corrupt, but it fits the pattern of this administration. ...
Clinton has not only been corrupted; he has corrupted all of those
around him, and this is an example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew. Hey, the guy was just gonna give a little talk, and on an
occasion exceeded in its importance only by its obscurity. Western
Civilization does not hang in the balance here.
</P>
<P>
   And Republicans suspect the invitation as a political payoff by
the endowment chairman, a Clinton appointee. Maybe William R.
Ferris IS a suck-up, but he said he thought that starting a
tradition of presidential lecturers would raise the visibility of
the annual Jefferson series and set up a nice chance for presidents
to speak away from their usual agendized forums.
</P>
<P>
   It WAS a good idea, or ought to have been. Asking our presidents
for once to think out loud with us, rather than just pitching us,
would cool the fevers of politics and allow for a welcome civic
moment. Some, of course, would abuse the platform or dog it,
sloughing the chore off to staff hacks. Even that, however, would
be telling.
</P>
<P>
   But we're having none of it. The relentless partisanship of
recent years has cost us the ability to understand a president as
ever representing the presidency, as opposed to the politics that
got him to it. To occupy the office is not to be enlarged by it but
to be diminished in it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself contributed to this slide. But the hardball
campaign to demonize him, and to deny Clinton the presidency in
substance if not in form, began with his election, not his
misadventure. That campaign is waning now, in self-satisfaction.
But it has cost the rest of us some measure of our sense of
community beyond partisanship and has left us, in poor recompense,
only muddled disillusion.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
