----------------------------------------------------3. GET READY,
HERE COMES THE EXOATMOSPHERIC KILL VEHICLE By Peter Maass - From
The New York Times Magazine America is preparing for a nuclear war
again. Within the Raytheon Missile Systems factory, on the
outskirts of Tucson, Ariz., the top ballistic technicians are
putting the final touches on a weapon that is supposed to protect
America from Armageddon. It is called the Exoatmospheric Kill
Vehicle and it is supposed to fly through space at 4,500 miles an
hour, hit its target's warhead and obliterate it. (Peter Maass is
the author of ``Love Thy Neighbor: A Story of War,'' about covering
the war in Bosnia.) 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   4. GERMANY'S INTERNET POLICE: IT IS NOT EASY TO PATROL THE WEB -
From Der Spiegel - 1,000 words Since the beginning of the year, a
20-member unit of Germany's federal investigative police has been
patrolling the Internet, looking for evidence of kiddy pornography,
software piracy, money-laundering, data theft, credit card
swindlers, unlawful drug sellers or illegal neo-Nazi Web sites.
What they find is shocking -- Internet sites portraying the sexual
abuse of toddlers, for example. But doing anything about it, the
Germans have found, is not an easy matter. More and more,
governments are wrestling with ways to control the amorphous,
fast-growing giant known as the Internet without strangling it to
death. So far they have had little success. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------------------------------------5. MAN EMERGES,
STILL BREATHING, AFTER E-CAVE CONFINEMENT By Matt Richtel - From
The New York Times E-Commerce - 1,700 words E-commerce has
revolutionized the selling of books, compact disks, travel and
financial services and computer hardware and software - commodities
shoppers don't need to squeeze and prod to get a handle on. But
will the on-line bazaar work for everyday survival? In an attempt
to find out, writer Matt Richtel sealed himself into an E-cave. For
five days, he ordered all sustenance and entertainment from the
Net. He survived, but will he ever be the same? Here, he offers his
diary. 
