<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-INSPIRES-PERKS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHT LABOR MARKET INSPIRES HEFTY PERKS
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photos of women working out and a man with his
baby) 
 By MARGARET ANN MIILLE 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, Michael DiPaolo was weighing competitive job offers
from technology companies in the South and Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   That Cheetah Technologies was launching a subsidized day care
center this summer at its Bradenton, Fla., offices made his
decision easier. He started his new job as associate product
manager there two days after his son, Michael, was born.
</P>
<P>
   ''I liked the company anyway, but that kind of put it over the
top,''DiPaolo said.
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't hurt that Cheetah, which makes monitoring
equipment and software for the cable TV and telecommunications
industries, recently opened a fitness center on site and plans to
open a cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the best thing was day care,'' said DiPaolo.
</P>
<P>
   ''At lunch, you can go play with your kid for a half an hour,
and you get perspective _ if you're having a bad day you realize
it's not that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Cheetah, many employers realize that in today's tight labor
market, helping workers juggle the hectic demands of work and
family can reap big payoffs not only in snaring qualified workers,
but in keeping them.
</P>
<P>
   While salaries and signing bonuses remain key executive
bargaining chips, more companies nationwide are experimenting with
a smorgasbord of perks _ flexible schedules, day care for children,
elder care for parents, gyms, massages, subsidized meals and
financial, concierge and counseling services.
</P>
<P>
   In today's shrinking work force, they want to be employers of
choice. A family-friendly philosophy called work-life management
has largely replaced the traditional view that professional and
personal lives orbit independently.
</P>
<P>
   ''It comes down to recruitment and retention,'' said Robin
Hardman of Families and Work Institute, a New York independent
research firm.''By and large, it's for bottom-line reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm's research indicates that happy workers are productive
workers, and they tend to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 Families and Work Institute study of 1,057 companies and
nonprofits with more than 100 employees found that those in
supportive workplaces are more satisfied with their jobs, more
loyal to their companies and more inclined to remain there.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, workers in less supportive sites have more stress,
worse moods and less energy away from work. And when jobs
compromise personal and family well-being, problems at home
boomerang at work, impairing job performance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Life is more complicated today,'' said Hardman. ''Everyone is
trying to do a lot more things at once.''
</P>
<P>
   And not just Americans. Workers worldwide seek more balance
between careers and personal lives, according to a poll of more
than 10,000 people conducted by Gemini Consulting and Yankelovich
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the United States, Europe and Japan said they value
balance the most _ only Russians said decent wages are more
important. French employees are the happiest; Japanese, the
unhappiest.
</P>
<P>
   ''Workplaces today need more flexible employees just as much as
employees need more flexible workplaces,'' Hardman said.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the traditional 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. routine is only one of
four schedules available since last year to nearly 600 FCCI
Insurance Group employees in the Southeast region.
</P>
<P>
   Employees can choose the starting time of each eight-hour day
during a flexible five-day work week, work four 10-hour days or
take the 10th day off after toiling 80 hours within nine days.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, these arrangements have their limits.
</P>
<P>
   ''It needs to be reasonable for what the job is,'' said Suzanne
Mitchell, FCCI public relations director. ''You have to figure out
what works best for you personally and what works best for your
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said some workers were happy to flee the 8-to-5 grind,
only to later want it back.
</P>
<P>
   ''They discover it really suited their needs,'' she said. ''Some
tried a flexible schedule, but decided a more disciplined one was
better for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Flexibility may take additional forms at FCCI. Under discussion
there are job sharing and telecommuting; the latter has been tried
on a limited basis.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of things on the drawing board, but a lot of
things get explored but not pursued,'' she said. ''We are not
satisfied that we are done.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Staff Leasing in Bradenton has found that the way to
the hearts of its approximately 700 employees is through their
stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, the public employer organization has
subsidized hot lunches. Last year, it stepped up the frequency of
the offering from three to five times weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hall, vice president of investor relations, said that up
to 150 workers daily partake in the meals, for which the company
pays half. The ritual builds morale by encouraging them to mingle
up and down the corporate ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ''It allows them the chance to interact with other departments,
to have lunch with the chief financial officer or the president of
the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's on-site day care, subsidized lunches, flexible
schedules or on-site gyms, employers nationwide are realizing they
need to offer more than just a paycheck. Said Gordon Greenfield,
vice president of corporate development for Cheetah Technologies,
''In today's market, you can't really keep people if they don't
like where they work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Margaret Ann Miille writes for the Sarasota Herald-Tribune in
Florida.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
