<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEWORK-REFRESHER-COURSE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOMEWORK REFRESHER COURSE FOR PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
  By ROSANNE ROSEN 
 c.1999 Rosanne Rosen 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that school bells are ringing again, it may be a good idea
for Mom and Dad to take a homework refresher course.
</P>
<P>
   Helping with homework is one of the most effective ways parents
can enhance a child's education, according to James Keogh, author
of ''The Secrets to Good Grades.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation for homework skills must be laid in the early
grades. By the time students reach high school, they should already
know how to manage their time and homework as there is a direct
link between well-completed homework and scholastic achievement at
the middle-and high-school level, says Harris Cooper, a psychology
professor at the University of Missouri at Columbia, and the author
of ''The Battle Over Homework,''
</P>
<P>
   With so much riding on homework, this is one refresher course
moms and dads need to pass with flying colors.
 &UR; Lesson 1: Becoming Your Child's Homework Coach &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ''I think if the parent takes on the responsibility of a coach,
kids will pick up on the attitude that homework is important,''
Keogh says.
</P>
<P>
   What homework coaches do is motivate, monitor and mentor. They
must set rules, establish routines, offer support, extend
encouragement, act as a role model, give assistance, provide
necessary materials and create an environment that is conducive for
learning.
 &UR; Lesson 2: Understanding the Importance of Homework &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The National Education Association says homework helps kids
learn, extends periods of learning, links home and school and
improves comprehension of material and raises grades. Assignments
provide an opportunity to review lessons presented in class, catch
up on missed concepts, test knowledge and practice important
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Studying outside of school teaches children time management,
independence and autonomous learning, self-discipline, persistence,
organization and self-reliance
 &UR; Lesson 3: Accepting the Role of Parental Participation &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it take takes time and patience after a tiring day,
but helping your children with their assignments sends a message
that they are important, as is their homework. It also provides a
time to show interest in what children are learning, ask them
questions and monitor their developmental level.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney S. Zentall, Ph.D., professor of special education and
psychological sciences at Purdue University and author of ''Seven
Steps to Homework Success,'' says you should enjoy younger
children's receptiveness to help. When kids get older, they view
parental involvement more like interference.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Zentall advises parents to ask junior high or
high-school students if they are amenable to parental help or if
they would prefer the help of a tutor, classmate or older sibling.
 &UR; Lesson 4: Learning How Much to Help &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree that helping children with homework doesn't mean
providing them with the answers. The goal of parental participation
is to develop an independent student who can separate from the
parent and feel that their work _ good or bad _ is their own,
Zentall says.
</P>
<P>
   ''Independence is a gradual process. Children rely upon parents,
but then must transfer that reliance to their peers, the librarian,
their teachers and things they can carry around with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, educators recommend parents ask leading questions,
make suggestions and break down complex problems into smaller
units.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important roles for a parent, Cooper says, is
maintaining the child's interest, alleviating frustration and
demonstrating that they have learned something.
 &UR; Lesson 5: Offering Rewards or Giving Punishments &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There is not one perfect solution to the homework battle many
parents engage in weekly. However, Zentall recommends coaxing
children into completing homework that is frequently tedious and
boring by offering incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ''Incentives are not bribes. They are things to look forward to
like breaks or favorite TV programs,'' she says. ''If you watch
children and see what they prefer to do when they come home from
school or ask them, you will find out what they prefer doing over
homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Zentall conducted a study that revealed a list of
five-minute activities kids said they would rather do more than
their homework. Clean their room, walk the dog and talk to mom were
frequent answers.
</P>
<P>
   Providing incentives are more important when time spent on
homework increases.
 &UR; Lesson 6: Preparing the Proper Atmosphere &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The general rule for parents is to provide a work space where
children can readily focus on their homework. That doesn't
necessarily mean in a quiet room or at a desk, however.
</P>
<P>
   Zentall has researched the affects of distractions for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''There isn't one way to do homework,'' she says. '' Let the
child figure out how to work. Some work better in stimulating
environments some in more barren. A lot depends on the nature of
the task and individual differences. Some data shows children work
better with music in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if homework done on the floor or in front of the TV is
full of errors, then it's time for the child to work in an
atmosphere with fewer distractions.
 &UR; Lesson 7: Practicing Modeling and Making Choices &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The most important part of this lesson is discovering how to
imbue your child with the value and pleasure of lifetime learning.
This could be as simple as taking an educational trip to a historic
site or as difficult as making critical choices.
</P>
<P>
   Use of time that reflects priorities is No. 1. Parents need to
stop over-scheduling children, Cooper says. They become bogged down
with so many activities they either run out of time for homework or
are too tired to do it. The Institute of Social Research at the
University of Michigan reports that American students spend more
time playing sports than doing homework.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a current trend of thought is parental modeling that
requires Mom and Dad set the example. For instance, parents should
read, write a letter or balance their checkbook and forego
television _ forbidden to their children _ while homework is in
progress.
 &UR; Lesson 8: Identifying Homework Overload or Trouble &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Although homework time has doubled for U.S. students since 1981,
it is still significantly less than in many other countries. The
National Education Association reports an average of 134 minutes a
week of homework for grade-school kids and 3 1/2 hours a week for
middle-school students. A first grader in Taiwan does seven times
as much homework as a first grader in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So before parents jump to the conclusion that teachers are
piling on unreasonable amounts of work, do some research: Find out
the school policy on homework and pay attention if a child is
wasting time, goofing off or cramming a week's worth of assignments
into one night, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   To determine whether children are dealing with overload or
learning problems, experts say don't hesitate to communicate with
teachers and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Informed, participatory parents extend their power beyond the
help of an immediate homework lesson, Morgan said. They affect
their children's future accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rosanne Rosen writes from Columbus, Ohio.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
