<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, Sept. 27, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLITICS NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELIZABETH-DOLE (Anaheim, Calif.) _ Presidential candidate
Elizabeth Dole likes to tell the story of a young girl, maybe 10 or
11, who came up to her recently with a complaint: ``But I wanted to
be the first woman president,'' said the girl, worried that Dole
would steal her dream. But some political strategists and GOP
insiders say the young girl may have nothing to worry about. By
ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL-SNOOPING (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Gov. Gray
Davis is considering a bill that would outlaw the monitoring of
employee computer e-mail unless management first produces a written
policy everyone is told about. It would be the first such law in
the nation. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   70S-RADICAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Susan Saxe was the quiet kid who
penned her high school class poem in 1966 and went on to graduate
magna cum laude from Brandeis University in Waltham, Mass. But it
was not long after graduation that the anti-war activist was
arrested as a party to a bank robbery in which a Boston policeman
was killed. Today, the ex-convict's social action continues at a
Philadelphia Jewish organization. By EDWARD FITZPATRICK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CELL-TRANSPLANT (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ A champagne cork
popped as a dozen family members and friends gathered around
Maribeth Cook to toast the homecoming of the world's first stroke
patient to receive an experimental fetal pig brain cell transplant.
By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   With CELL-TECHNIQUE.
</P>
<P>
   GOOSENECK-LAMPS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The most common light for home
tasks or reading is the gooseneck lamp, named for its flexible
neck. Because they are so handy, they can be used in any room in
the house, from a home office to a nightstand. They are most
commonly used next to a favorite reading chair and have been a dorm
room or bedroom staple for students. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AMERICANS-WORK (San Francisco) _ When the International Labor
Organization reported this month that Americans now work the
longest hours in the industrialized world, the statistics were a
little misleading. The real situation in the United States is even
more extreme. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   SF-ECONOMY (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco Bay Area's
economic performance, including its outstanding labor and capital
productivity, remains the envy of the world, but the success is
seriously threatened by challenges that could cripple the ability
to sustain prosperity and preserve quality of life, a new study
reports. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT-AUTUMN (West Dover, Vt.) _ The sign on Route 9 in
southern Vermont welcomes visitors who have driven into the
mountains, coming from Bennington to the Mount Snow-Haystack
Region, ``a four-season resort.'' But this time of year would not
be included in any seasonal category and it's my favorite of the
nonseasons, a mellow cider to July's lemonade. By JANE GOTTLIEB.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The hype isn't working. With the
millennium less than 100 days away, travel agents and tourism
officials say there are still plenty of openings for hotels and
cruises. By DANIELLE FURFARO.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-TUBE (London) _ On my recent visit to London I realized,
once again, that I still don't have the foggiest idea where
anything is. The problem is that the London I know isn't the London
of clock towers and double-decker buses and leafy green parks. The
London I know is an alternative, underground London, with its own
idiosyncratic coordinates and geography. The London I know is the
London of Harry Beck, who designed the map of the London tube. By
JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-WILLIE-McCOVEY (San Francisco) _ Willie McCovey is coming
home. Before an enthusiastic Candlestick crowd. As an employee of
his longtime team. As arguably the most popular Giant in San
Francisco franchise history. By JOHN SHEA.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS (Oakland, Calif.) _ Lance Johnstone was asked if he
could have seen any of his previous Raider teams committing five
turnovers and nine penalties and winning. It didn't take him long
to dismiss the notion as madness. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Every hotel room in town has
been full on weekends for months at South Lake Tahoe, the roads
jammed, with some of the drivers certifiable lunatics. But from
Angora Peak, looking down across cobalt-blue Lake Tahoe, circled by
miles of forest and the granite mountain rim, it can seem as if you
are the only person on earth. Yet only a few miles separates these
two universes. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The next millennium is less than
100 days away, and already it's a bore. The future is always a
disappointment when it arrives. In an age of mega-hype, the future
is a disappointment in advance. We know we're never getting world
peace, colonies on other planets, food in convenient squeeze tubes
or those personal jet packs we were promised long ago. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The upcoming race between
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani to represent New York
in the U.S. Senate is attracting as much interest outside New York
as in. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ The recent lawsuit filed by the
Department of Justice against the tobacco industry has politics
written all over it, coming, as it did, more than halfway through
President Clinton's last term and on the heels of tobacco's
multibillion-dollar settlements of similar state suits seeking
recovery of tax dollars spent on smoking-related health care. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
