<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7279 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-E-COMMERCE-POP-MUSIC-     09-27 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-POP-MUSIC-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FLUX IN POP MUSIC HAS A DISTINCTLY DOWNLOAD BEAT TO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This is a special ``one-shot'' feature culled from E-COMMERCE,
a special stand-alone news section from The New York Times that
explores how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By SUE CUMMINGS 
 c.1999 The New York Times Co.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   A lot of words have been used to describe David Bowie, but
``conventional'' is not one of them. So it is probably not too
surprising that on Sept. 21 Bowie released his latest album _
``hours ...'' _ not in record stores but on the Internet. Just
download in Liquid Audio or Microsoft Audio 4.0.
</P>
<P>
   Bowie is the most well-known artist trying to sell _ for about
$18, the list price of a compact disk _ a full-length recording in
a download format providing copyright protection.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure how many people will pay that much for an
unpackaged data file, even if it is the creation of a legendary
rocker, and skeptics have suggested that the album's title refers
to how long the download will take over an average modem.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reaction, Bowie's experiment is a response to
changes throughout the music industry brought on by the popularity
of MP3. Artists of every stripe are using the Internet to
distribute audio in hopes of establishing a following, reviving a
career or promoting new work.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, the Internet has seen an explosion of legally
downloadable music by prominent artists. New music is now regularly
appearing on-line from the major labels, which have co-opted the
digital download trend as a direct-marketing gambit.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter of 1999 is expected to see a record number of
famous performers offering free audio samples on-line to entice
holiday purchases. The Red Hot Chili Peppers, Creed and Def Leppard
recently began new albums with on-line previews designed to build
anticipation before their release dates.
</P>
<P>
   As Chuck D of the rap group Public Enemy said in a recent
interview: ``The Internet happened to be a dog. You either pet the
dog, or let the dog bite your leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, it was not so easy for the artists who early on
made their music available for downloading. At the time, Public
Enemy and the Beastie Boys fought their labels' demands to remove
MP3 files of their music from their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Recording Industry Association of America, the
music industry trade group, was tracking down unauthorized MP3
distributors and formed the Secure Digital Music Initiative to
establish standards for protecting copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were this big band endorsing this thing the industry was
trying to be united against,'' Mike D (aka Mike Diamond) of the
Beastie Boys told The Wall Street Journal in December.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck D _ Carlton Ridenhour _ put it more bluntly on
Sonicnet.com: ``The execs, lawyers and accountants who lately have
made most of the money in the music biz are now running scared from
the technology that evens out the creative field and makes artists
harder to pimp.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beastie Boys agreed to remove their MP3 files, live tracks
recorded on tour, in December. But by April, their label, Capitol
Records, had approved release of the group's remixes and video on
its site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beastie Boys are a good example of the industry's shifting
mind-set on the Internet,'' said Hillary Rosen, the president and
chief executive of the Recording Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   They started out posting MP3 files on their Web site, ``and
getting a bit of hype out of having this public fight with their
label,'' she said. ``Their contract is up this year; they could
have done anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, they signed a new deal with Capitol for a $30 or $40
million advance,'' Rosen said. ``They found that the existing
system had a lot of advantages for them _ No. 1, that they got a
lot of cash up front.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, on-line proponents were saying that digital
downloads would eliminate the need for record companies by allowing
artists to take music directly to audiences. Instead, the rise of
downloadable audio has spawned new companies like Emusic.com,
Mp3.com and Atomic Pop that are pioneering Internet strategies for
artist development, marketing and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Al Teller, the founder and president of Atomic Pop, an Internet
label, is a former chairman and chief executive of MCA and
president of CBS Records. He speaks for underground and developing
artists when he says, ``There's an enormous frustration with how
many artists get lost in the system and the cost of doing business
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Teller pursued Public Enemy after hearing of the group's
differences with Def Jam Records over offering music for download.
Atomic Pop then put the group's album ``There's a Poison Goin' On''
on sale through download in May, two months before the CD went to
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Atomic Pop, like other on-line labels, does not require artists
to sign long-term contracts or relinquish ownership of their master
recordings. Rather than offering artists an 8 percent to 12 percent
royalty on sales, as the major labels do, on-line labels give
artists a 50-50 net profit split.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement eliminates exceptions like ``free goods'' (CDs
given away for promotional purposes) that major labels use to
whittle away the base on which royalties are applied. Business
expenses for artist and label come off the top and must be
documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my mind, it's much more favorable to the artists,'' said
Richard Grabel, a music lawyer with Grubman, Indursky &AMP; Schindler
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Another frustrated performer was Greta Gaines. A former champion
professional snowboarder and an aspiring singer-songwriter, Gaines
signed with Giant Records in 1995. Soon afterward, Giant was
reorganized and renamed Revolution Records. New executives replaced
those who had promised to support Gaines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed the faith and guidance of people who loved my
music,'' she said. ``They said, `If you don't sell 250,000 units on
your first single, you're out of here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gaines completed an album for Giant/Revolution that was never
released and asked to cancel her contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so damaging to me for so many years,'' she said.
``Nobody would touch me.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued to write and perform music, however. Three months
ago, while preparing to release a debut CD on her own label, she
posted three songs to Mp3.com as an experiment. The site, which
does not charge for the service, also enables artists to get E-mail
directly from visitors who download their music.
</P>
<P>
   Gratified and surprised by listeners' responses, Gaines quickly
revamped her postings to better represent the new album.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Mp3.com called to tell her that Alanis Morissette and
Tori Amos had selected her to open on their tour, sponsored by the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Now her single, ``FireFly,'' is getting limited airplay at adult
album alternative radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I start selling records and my song starts doing well,''
she said, ``it will be a complete revolution in the odds an artist
has'' of hitting it big.
</P>
<P>
   Gaines says she will not sign with a major label.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go on to have a major rock career, it will largely be
based on the Internet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sue Cummings is editor in chief of MJI Broadcasting's new
media division.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
