<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7282 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-E-COMMERCE-FEEDING-FR     09-27 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-FEEDING-FRENZY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEEDING FRENZY MADE FOR CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This is a special ``one-shot'' feature culled from E-COMMERCE,
a special stand-alone news section from The New York Times that
explores how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By SAUL HANSELL 
 c.1999 The New York Times Co.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It's hard not to look at all the money being made on Internet
stocks and wonder, ``How do I get my share?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you could bet your life savings on a company started by
teen-agers that has never had a dime of profit, with a stock that
seems to follow the course of the Coney Island Cyclone.
</P>
<P>
   Or take that recipe that was always such a big hit at the bake
sale, open SuperFudgeBrownies.com, and then sell stock to all your
friends on the PTA.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you could plan to do all your Christmas shopping on
the Internet. Many Internet companies, and their investors, are so
desperate to get big fast that they are almost willing to bribe
people to shop with them. So the savvy cyberconsumer can find sites
selling all sorts of items at or below cost, or with free shipping
or all sorts of other giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   Competition has already driven prices for digital video disks
on-line to as much as 40 percent below the suggested retail level.
In many cases that means the price is well below the wholesale
cost.
</P>
<P>
   And enough $15 coupons and free shipping deals have been fired
in the bitter war between Drugstore.com and Planetrx.com that
customers could well hoard a year's worth of free shampoo or
toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   You name it and someone has started a Web site to sell it:
Autoweb, Furniture.com, Ebags, Pets.com, even Partyjunk.com,
scheduled to be introduced this fall, for children's party favors.
There are thousands more, and nearly all of them are planning to
lose money for years.
</P>
<P>
   For on-line buyers, these good deals are still mixed with a lot
of frustration. It's often hard to find a site that sells what you
want. When you do, the sites can be slow and hard to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   If you place an order, too often the merchandise is not shipped
correctly, intact and on time. And there is nothing that Silicon
Valley has invented to let you tell by looking at a computer screen
whether the sweater will be scratchy or what the color really is.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by Jupiter Communications, a New York research firm,
found that the portion of buyers who said they were very satisfied
with their on-line shopping dropped to 43 percent this year from 63
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the qualms, more people are spending much more
money on-line every month. On America Online, only 37 percent of
its members had made an on-line purchase as of June of last year.
Today, it is up to 62 percent, or nearly 11 million shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter estimates that consumers will spend $15 billion in 1999.
Of that, $6 billion will be spent this Christmas, double what was
spent last year.
</P>
<P>
   For both business and Wall Street, the question now is: How big
can this get?
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs recently told clients it estimated that
ultimately 15 percent to 20 percent of the nation's retail sales
could flow over the Internet. And in many ways,
business-to-business electronic commerce is having an even bigger
effect and doing it faster, as everything from cattle farms to
steel mills use the Web to link to suppliers and customers.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder investors are backing companies that look like they
are growing fast, rather than those that are making a profit. To be
sure, there may be a touch of irrational exuberance causing the
stock market to value Etoys at $5.2 billion, far more than the $3.4
billion value of Toys ``R'' Us. Never mind that Toys ``R'' Us sells
400 times more toys than its upstart rival.
</P>
<P>
   Look behind all the technical wizardry of the sites, however,
and you'll see a lot of businesses that are staying together on
little more than packing tape and a prayer. After all, it's much
easier to make a pretty Web site, and advertise it on America
Online, than to make sure you have the goods the site is offering
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a wake-up call for everybody,'' said Katherine
Borsecnik, the senior vice president in charge of America Online's
shopping area. ``People weren't prepared for the volumes that
peaked about a week before Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Wainright, now the chief executive of Pets.com, said she
learned her lesson when she spent a year running Reel.com, an
on-line video store that was having trouble keeping track of its
inventory and shipping orders on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got there, we had 50,000 customers, and 50,000 were mad
at us,'' she said. Reel has since been sold to Hollywood Video.
</P>
<P>
   Starting over at Pets.com early this year, Ms. Wainright
replaced the company's computer system with one that can handle 30
times its current volume. She leased a 120,000-square-foot
warehouse to stock everything and she is hiring three shifts of
people to staff it around the clock this Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, people were really excited to try something
new,'' she said. ``But this year, the customers are completely
unforgiving. They are not going to give you a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall will also mark the debut of services known as
electronic wallets that are meant to speed on-line shopping by
automatically sending previously entered information about the
shopper _ like credit-card numbers and shipping address _ to the
store.
</P>
<P>
   Last Christmas, many people who tried to shop on-line found an
even more basic problem: They couldn't find anyone selling what
they wanted to buy. In some cases that was because they didn't know
where to look.
</P>
<P>
   But by this year, the big Internet guides, including America
Online and Yahoo, will introduce new services that allow shoppers
to search for a specific item at hundreds of on-line stores and see
on one screen who carries it and what their prices are.
</P>
<P>
   Security is another main concern that, according to surveys of
Internet users, is keeping people from shopping on-line. With so
many sites appearing every day, it is hard to know the reliable
merchants from the fly-by-nights, so many people are wary of
sending their credit card numbers to anyone on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But a healthy suspicion, said David Medine, the associate
director of the Federal Trade Commission, should make people more
willing to use credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should always use their credit cards when they buy
on-line because of the strong consumer protection laws that let you
dispute charges on a credit card bill,'' Medine said. The most
consumers will pay in case of fraud is $50.
</P>
<P>
   That said, shoppers should have a field day.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Saul Hansell is a reporter for the Business Section of The New
York Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
