<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7284 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-E-COMMERCE-SURVIVAL-T     09-27 1782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-SURVIVAL-THROUGH-THE-NET-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN EMERGES, STILL BREATHING, AFTER E-CAVE CONFINEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This is a special ``one-shot'' feature culled from E-COMMERCE,
a special stand-alone news section from The New York Times that
explores how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MATT RICHTEL 
 c.1999 The New York Times Co.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It is a Sunday night, and I have just sealed myself into an
E-cave. For the next five days, I will order all sustenance and
entertainment from the Net. I will hunker down in a bachelor pad in
Palo Alto, Calif., armed with credit card and mouse.
</P>
<P>
   I click my way to the checkout aisle of Webvan, an on-line
grover, to schedule a delivery time. Tomorrow morning would be
great. Then, crisis. I'm told that deliveries are first come, first
served. Webvan can deliver the same day, but the next available
appointment is Wednesday night. By then I could walk to the nearest
market and back _ on stilts.
</P>
<P>
   Will the on-line bazaar work for everyday survival, and as a
means for daily upkeep of heart, soul, body, mind and, foremost,
stomach?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONDAY: LEARNING TO ORDER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his quest for food, primitive man faced the woolly mammoth. I
face slothlike delivery schedules. Undaunted by my Webvan
disappointment, I set out on Monday morning to hunt and gather
21st-century style.
</P>
<P>
   A Web search turns up 69 sites offering ``grocery delivery,''
including Groceronline, Netgrocer and Electrolley. I pop into and
register at several sites, then head down the virtual aisles.
</P>
<P>
   But each time I go to check out, I learn delivery is either not
available in my area or will take three to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, I change strategies. I search on ``food delivery, Palo
Alto'' and am led to Waiters.com, a service that takes on-line
orders for local restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   At one spot I know, the Good Earth, I point and click through
the menu. But I make rookie E-commerce errors, neglecting, for
example, to complete registration forms.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later my $32 order arrives. Hungry and having not seen
another human being in nearly 24 hours, I practically hug Louis,
the Waiters.com driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were you,'' he says, ``I would have ordered over the
phone. It's easier.''
</P>
<P>
   If he only knew. All day, I have battled not just delivery
schedules but a debilitating injury. I have hurt my left pinkie. I
jammed it in a recent basketball game, and it's swollen and purple,
like a mini-eggplant.
</P>
<P>
   I divine an answer: the cybermedic. A search for ``medical
advice'' returns the names of dozens of doctors who offer virtual
consultations. I even find a specialist, a sports orthopedist named
Stuart Zeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people dread going to the doctor,'' his site says. ``It
can be expensive, inconvenient and stressful.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Zeman's alternative is an E-mail consultation for 10 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is he inexpensive, he's also concise. You get one
paragraph to describe your malady, and the virtual physician's
response runs only a few lines. (Somewhere, an HMO executive is
taking copious notes.)
</P>
<P>
   And so by the end of the day, I have scored several small
E-commerce victories, including the fact that late in the
afternoon, I have discovered an on-line grocer called Peapod. I
arrange for a Tuesday delivery.
</P>
<P>
   When I go to bed, I have fed my brain with food, and I have
tended to my corpus with medical advice. Tomorrow, feeling more
seasoned in the ways of E-commerce, I will feed my soul. I will buy
a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TUESDAY: LIVING ROOM IS PERFECT FOR SINKING A 9-FOOTER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, not an entire golf course, but at least an indoor putting
green. This will permit me to test my E-commerce mettle, alleviate
the boredom that accompanies an on-line, in-house lifestyle and
address one of life's pressing concerns, improving my golf game.
</P>
<P>
   My search-engine request on Yahoo spits out nearly 40 possible
merchants, with names like Eagle Putting Greens and Chip-n-Putt.
</P>
<P>
   I settle on a shop called Big Moss Golf. This is partly because
it feels like a local store and partly because it promises to bring
my handicap out of the stratosphere. And partly because it has a
toll-free number for customer service, and I'm starting to get a
little lonely in the E-cave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to work that out yourself,'' Tony Terisco says.
He's the owner of Big Moss Golf who sells me on the Big Moss
Original, a $159, nine-foot-long piece of carpet simulated to feel
like grass with a golf hole at one end.
</P>
<P>
   It dawns on me that it may be even more instructive to play
actual golf. But I'm in no mood to quibble. I pay an extra $30 for
overnight delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, I receive a house call from my on-line doctor, Stuart
Zeman. ``You must get an X-ray,'' he prescribes in no uncertain
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Leave the house? Never!
</P>
<P>
   I decide to seek a second opinion. I fire off an E-mail to Dr.
Michele Moore, who runs a site called www.askyour familydoc.com.
She will give me a virtual bedside counsel for $25.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEDNESDAY: AN ON-LINE WARRIOR VICTORIOUS IN BATTLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Help. Send Prozac. Otherwise, I may torture and kill my
neighbor, who has been practicing the piano for hours.
</P>
<P>
   But I will combat her, E-commerce style. My weapons are earplugs
and aspirin. My destination is pharmaceutical sites. I settle on
Planetrx.com and Drugstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   I register at each site and check their delivery schedules. Then
I engage in a bit of hard-core price comparison. I open two browser
windows and compare the sites side by side, checking response time,
prices and product information.
</P>
<P>
   The arrows favor Planetrx. Minutes later, I ``walk out'' with
earplugs and Advil, opting for overnight delivery for an additional
$10. While I'm at it, I check out the stores' aisles of bandage
tape for my injured digit. Drugstore.com offers eight pages of
athletic tape and gauze products.
</P>
<P>
   This is when I realize I've E-volved into a wily E-commerce
veteran. I'm in and out of the drugstores in 10 minutes, far less
than it would have taken to drive to a pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with success, I endeavor an E-commerce challenge with an
Olympic degree of difficulty. I'm going to use my modem to get my
cat to stop throwing up. I've tried the normal remedies, like
giving her soft foods and beer, but frankly, I inherited the cat
from an ex-girlfriend and I never could figure her out _ the cat, I
mean.
</P>
<P>
   I find a veterinarian to consult by E-mail. But then I ascend
further, pinpointing a service that in and of itself may illustrate
just how far this new commerce medium has come: Kay Cox, on-line
pet psychiatrist, www.getnet.com/petcouns/.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, a self-proclaimed ``pet therapist and talent scout,''
offers on-line consultation for $40 an hour. I send her an
electronic missive and assure the cat it will be OK.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, my own psychological salve has arrived _ my putting
green. John Tuggle, the UPS deliveryman, takes one look at me and
says, ``I think you need to get out of the house and go to the
shopping mall.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THURSDAY: THE MOMENT OF TRUTH _ SEARCHING FOR LOVE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' say it's hard to meet good people these days. ``They''
say it's tough to find a soul mate amid the cacophony of modern
life.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they've never met Kitten664.
</P>
<P>
   This is the woman I am paired up with by Matchmaker.com. The
on-line service concluded we may constitute a love connection by
comparing our answers to about 50 questions like personal hobbies,
income, height and weight and reading habits. Kitten664 and I
matched on 54 percent of our answers.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, we're both 5 feet 8 inches tall and weigh 160 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It's true: I soon realize that among the criteria the company
matches are our height and weight, which doesn't seem like a
quality that either sex typically wants in a mate.
</P>
<P>
   In a second attempt at a dating service, I fill out a
questionnaire on a site that promises to help me find my soul mate.
But when I finish, it takes me to an advertisement for free,
on-line pornography.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think this is a site I'd like to bring home to my
mother.
</P>
<P>
   But there is good news on my penultimate day in the E-cave. The
swelling in my pinkie has gone down. This is partly thanks to
E-mail from Dr. Moore, who advocates icing and elevating the
finger.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I've ordered lunch with ease from Waiters.com _ without
even needing to register because my registration is already on
file.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the cat has quit vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FRIDAY: A LITTLE WISDOM GLEANED FROM LIVING LIFE ON-LINE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just when I am feeling as if I may never need the outside world
again, fate intervenes. My office calls and tells me I must go on
an urgent assignment. My week in the E-cave is cut short.
</P>
<P>
   I reflect on the four days gone by. I have discovered that with
a little practice and experience, the Net can yield some powerful
dividends. Product information and diversity are unparalleled.
Plus, there is extraordinary capacity to compare prices.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the downside. The on-line experience can be an
isolating one. Some very important sense of community develops from
shopping in the flesh, despite the hassles of driving, parking,
fighting crowds and arguing whether you really have 10 or 11 items
in the express lane.
</P>
<P>
   There are other bugs, too. Like sometimes an E-commerce site
just freezes up. It's like walking up to a sales clerk in a store,
asking a question, then having him glower at you before turning
around and walking away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm talking to you,'' I shouted at one point during the
week to a frozen site.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, I conclude there are two basic and unassailable
tenets of the E-commerce life: (1) you can order anything under the
sun over the Net _ and in greater selection than in any other
single venue on the planet, and (2) plan ahead, or you'll starve to
death.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Matt Richtel is a reporter for the Business Section of The New
York Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
