<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blurring fact and fiction
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ ``Sometimes I just want to pop that smarmy
Alexander Hamilton right in the nose. `Calculate the interest on
THIS, Mr. Treasury Secretary.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson jabbed at the air in a good approximation of a
right to the jaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't twist your wig, Tom,'' I advised. ``Hamilton will get
his someday. I have this feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   He sighed and kept walking.
</P>
<P>
   OK, you caught me. That didn't happen. I am a little younger
than 200 years old _ thank you for noticing _ but something like
that could have happened to someone. Hamilton knew how to get
someone's goat.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, I didn't have the pleasure of hanging out with
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Edmund Morris didn't have the pleasure of hanging
out with a young Ronald Reagan, either. Yet Morris, the official
biographer of Reagan, did write, in first person, about brushing
against The Gipper in 1926 when he was only a mere Gipplet. And
when Morris was still about 14 years shy of being born.
</P>
<P>
   Morris tells of several other encounters between the young
Reagan and his fictional self in his new book. This sounds just a
little strange for a biography, stacked with other biographies in
the part of the library we laughingly call ``nonfiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The weird thing is that Morris enjoyed an advantage most
presidential biographers only dream about _ he got to hang out with
his subject. Still, he had to resort to fictions to flesh him out.
Why?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because he had been spoiled. Morris landed the Reagan
biography job because he had written a vivid, Pulitzer
Prize-winning portrait of Teddy Roosevelt. Without meeting
Roosevelt, he made him feel alive and intelligible. I came away
from the book with the artfully constructed illusion that I knew
TR. (That's not a narrative device. I really did read the book.)
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt helps a biographer along. He was more than articulate,
he was what journalists admiringly term A Quote Machine.
</P>
<P>
   He labeled the muckraker, boasted of being ``as strong as a bull
moose'' and spoke softly and carried a big stick. He scolded the
``malefactors of great wealth,'' deplored the ``lunatic fringe,''
and promised ``a square deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The man hardly stopped for lunch. A biographer is left running
breathlessly behind him, scooping up the best and most vivid of his
endless explanations and amplifications of himself, his ideas, and
his many, many enthusiasms.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a living Reagan is a harder subject than a dead
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   People who adore Reagan's politics and were charmed by his
manner nonetheless found him in person to be baffling, distant and
strangely uninvolved with folks around him.
</P>
<P>
   Like many an actor, he was at his best viewed at a distance. At
a place where his hair color didn't look so strange. Where the
makeup didn't seem so stagy. Where the stage's chalk marks weren't
so apparent and the cue cards unseen. The sixth time he cocked his
head and dabbed at his eye, one appreciated the art of real pro
rather than the emotions of a real person.
</P>
<P>
   Or that's what I thought. I only saw him once (in real life, not
as a narrative device). He had an amazing way of looking through
everyone in the room and directly into the television cameras in
the back row.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the video was vastly superior to being there. I felt like
I had visited Disney's Hall of Presidents.
</P>
<P>
   A dead Roosevelt spoke forcefully and directly. A live Reagan
changed the subject with a quip. A dead Roosevelt was the stuff of
movies. A live Reagan was the staff of movies. Roosevelt had a way
of filling a room. Reagan had a way of filling the screen.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Morris was driven to extreme measures. I suspect the
media-intense politics of our age is going to be rough going for
other biographers. Even those who were on the scene. Even those who
get to view all the video.
</P>
<P>
   Morris may not be the last writer reduced to pretending he
really knew what was behind the screen. Media Age politics probably
will drive others to even stranger devices.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is associate editor at The Daytona Beach News-Journal.
E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
