<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toledo airport puts fun back in flying
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO EXPRESS AIRPORT, Ohio _ Stand-up comedians and hapless
politicians love to crack bad jokes about Toledo. They don't do it
to be mean, they do it to be funny _ but they're not. They feel
safe asking dumb questions like, ``How many Toledoans does it take
to screw in a light bulb?'' because they figure everybody in the
audience is from somewhere else. Like all of northwest Ohio is
still crawling out from under the glacier and trying to figure out
how the wheel works.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's time for the jokes to stop, because things are pretty
cool around here. Toledo has a downtown that is showing signs of
coming back to life in spite of the contemporary curse of all
cities _ sprawling look-alike malls _ and it even has a river
running through it.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has an airport, too. It's not exactly LAX or Atlanta's
Hartsfield, but most of us who use it regularly count that as a
real blessing. We have a
</P>
<P>
   couple of jetways and an escalator, and the only line I've ever
waited in at security was behind a lady with a bag of apples that
got away from her and wobbled
</P>
<P>
   through the x-ray machine, one Granny Smith at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers don't fly into Toledo Express to connect with British
Airways to London or a nonstop to Okinawa. The way I figure it,
three kinds of folks
</P>
<P>
   frequent the Toledo airport: those who live here and are going
somewhere, those who have been somewhere and are coming home, and
those who come just to watch the airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo Express has no trams, no moving sidewalks, and best of
all, no parking garage. There is no multilevel facility with a cute
name like Miami
</P>
<P>
   International's ``Flamingo Garage'' nor are there signs
reminding the visitor he has just left his pickup in Section 3EEE,
Level 2, Aisle 8, Section 27-A,
</P>
<P>
   Green _ a system devised by port authorities to trick the unwary
motorist into believing he's going to be able to locate his truck
in less time than it takes to fly to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the terminal, nothing is more than a three minute
walk from anything else, and the airport bar is centrally located _
just in case. Never have I sat on an airplane that lingered on
Toledo's ramp for 30 minutes waiting for a gate, or had the captain
announce we were 23rd in line for takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's airport is fun _ just like airports used to be. The
only thing missing is a restaurant. There's one there, but I don`t
think anyone eats in it. And that's too bad because I remember the
days when airports boasted some really fine dining. Even folks who
weren't going anywhere would go there just
</P>
<P>
   for the food. Watching airplanes was a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's old airport, the one back in the '50s that looked like
a WW2 Quonset hut, had a restaurant that served up shrimp remoulade
and pecan pie that folks would drive all the way across town for.
Chicago's Midway Airport had a dining room that looked like
something straight out of a Bogart/Bacall movie. Mysterious men in
cufflinks and ladies with hats that covered one eye, ate there
between planes bound for exotic places. And at Louisville's
Standiford Airport, the restaurant served up a fried chicken dinner
that drew the city's Sunday after-church group.
</P>
<P>
   For me, Toledo's airport is the best of two worlds. I can take
life easy in the village I call home, insulated from the hurry-up,
push 'em around world on the outside, but when the need for speed
overwhelms me, it's a 37-minute drive on the turnpike to Toledo
Express. In five minutes I can park, unload my bags
</P>
<P>
   and be standing in front of the ticket counter, flashing my
passport and promising the agent that my suitcase has not left my
sight since I packed it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who's tried it lately knows that air travel is no longer
fun. Airports are zoos and airline employees act like they've
forgotten who's paying their salaries. If it weren't for Toledo
Express, I think I'd give all of my business to Amtrak.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or e-mail:
eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
