r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX     09-27 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cooperation, preservation, public investment _ all paid off
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Crossing the Platte River on foot, I was reminded
foggily, and without tune, of a line from some song _ some guy
writing about coming home ``to a place he'd never been before.''
That guy ... That guy...
</P>
<P>
   Oh. John Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Ahem. How oddly, and perfectly, the words fit. This was my first
time across the Platte on foot. That's a personal news bulletin.
I'm a Denver native. I've crossed the Platte countless times _ on
wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this was a place to which I'd not been:
</P>
<P>
   Hike-bike paths along a once-blighted creek and railroad tracks,
though a one-time hobo junction that's now a beaming nightlife
district, on the outskirts of a downtown hub that in this decade
has cut a 70 percent office vacancy rate in half.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion for the walk was a gathering of editorial writers
from across the nation, with urban revitalization as a theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was this place like before?'' newcomers asked me about
the 16th Street Mall and the Lower Downtown _ Lo Do _ entertainment
district. My answer: ``I don't know. I never came down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while I was growing up, unless you were a sack of grain
or a transient with a bed pack, or had a railroad or warehouse job,
the Platte Valley now teeming with life was no place for you.
</P>
<P>
   How did it turn around? Three key ingredients: metro
cooperation, historic preservation, public investment. With those
three ingredients, private enterprise got interested big-time. But
``public'' preceded ``private,'' and forever it shall.
</P>
<P>
   Two metro votes _ involving six counties _helped paved the way
for the downtown boom. First, voters approved a 1-cent sales tax
increment for a Scientific and Cultural Facilities District.
Second, voters approved a sales-tax hike to build a stadium _ Coors
Field _ for major league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   To the inner cities that give them life, suburbs can be
bloodsucking parasites. But Denver has demonstrated how joint
investment and cooperation can benefit the whole region.
</P>
<P>
   For the city, one crucial tack was to see historic buildings as
assets and to control development within that framework. The
warehouse district along Wazee and Wynkoop streets, infamous when I
was a kid, was the heart of the early city. The building of Coors
Field nearby spawned an explosion of lofts, restaurants and
microbreweries in once-dead warehouses and rail stations.
</P>
<P>
   Use your assets
</P>
<P>
   This is all easy for Denver, you say. How many cities have major
league ball to dazzle developers? True. But any city has assets at
its heart _ a river, a historic district, a depot _ that can be
more than eyesores.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, any city has assets that it could let decay if it
doesn't have the guts to confront the problem, to improve
infrastructure in its heart, rather than surrender to suburban
flight and do-nothing fiscal impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Denver was in the midst of a brutal recession when former Mayor
Federico Pena went to the voters with a bond issue to restore the
Platte district, with green space, trails and more.
</P>
<P>
   Current Mayor Wellington Webb observes that going to property
owners for a tax increment during a horrific downturn sounds crazy.
But Webb said that a bond issue is a statement about the future,
not the present, and Denver had confidence in its future.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor cannot be ignored: neighborhoods. Denver can't
claim having wiped out neighborhood blight. But it did confront
blight and flight in key areas _ like the Highlands Neighborhood,
the city's oldest, just across the Platte from Lower Downtown. This
included aggressive use of federal aid for housing rehabilitation
with an eye to historic flavor. It also included better parks.
</P>
<P>
   Now Highlands' turnaround is as striking as the downtown on its
front porch. I'd compare it to the Lo Do of my youth, but we never
met.
</P>
<P>
   John Young's column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
