<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web cam watchers can see a lot
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Web cams, one guesses, are a lot like a NASCAR race:
People watch to see something interesting happen.
</P>
<P>
   With a half-day race, it might be a wreck. With Web cams, the
most popular of which broadcasts live shots of a woman's bedroom,
it's nudity.
</P>
<P>
   The October issue of Yahoo Internet Life magazine profiles the
33-year-old woman behind Anacam.com. Since 1997, when Ana put a
camera in her bedroom and broadcast images of her and her boyfriend
having sex, Anacam.com has attracted more and more visitors. She
estimates receiving up to 22,000 viewers every day.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Life issue also includes lists of Web cameras that
aren't trained on people. One site, www.windows2000.com, is a
compilation of Web cameras divided by state. At www.earthcam.com,
things are organized by subject: traffic cameras, weather cameras,
scenic cameras, and weird and bizarre cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The new issue also lists one Web site serving a niche market:
wired truckers. The site, www.drivernet.com, lists each of its 375
e-mail terminals at truck stops in the continental United States.
The service is free, and it gives truckers a free e-mail address to
use while on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Life also examines free Internet connections. Companies
like Microworkz, AltaVista and NetZero offer free connections to
anyone willing to sift through advertising. All you America Online
users might be thinking, ``Hey, I'm already sifting through ads,
and I'm paying $21.95 a month for it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The free ISP service requires you to download software and
register. Once enrolled, a user sees advertisements on his or her
PC screen the whole time they're on the already-ad-riddled
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Europe, the services apparently are selling well. But
Americans have been less likely to be moved to save $10 to $20 a
month while seeing even more online advertising.
</P>
<P>
   _ The magazine also helps you tell the difference between a bad
e-mailer and a good one. A good e-mailer sends you only the files
you asked for. A bad e-mailer sends you the ``Best Net Jokes of
1998'' with a Microsoft Word virus attached. A bad e-mailer catches
up by writing a simple, ``Hi ... what's up? Write me when you have
a chance.'' A bad e-mailer sends ``a tacky e-mail greeting showing
a) a furry white kitten, b) a hot-air balloon, and c) a kitten in a
hot-air balloon.''
</P>
<P>
   RING OUT THE MILLENNIUM AT TIMES SQUARE SITE
</P>
<P>
   If fear of the Y2K bug is keeping you landlocked this New Year's
Eve and you don't feel like driving to New York, the Internet might
be the next best thing.
</P>
<P>
   A site, www.timessquare.com/, which was scheduled to open last
week, hopes to be the gathering place for people who can't make it
to Times Square and can't watch the ball drop on television.
</P>
<P>
   The site will broadcast the New Year's Eve celebration,
including the lowering of the ball. In the spring, the site will
become TimesSquareAlive.com, an entertainment and information site.
</P>
<P>
   The site is expected to feature online auctions, ticket sales
and Times Square merchandise. Earthcam.com will place cameras at
different points on Times Square and broadcast the images on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers also hope to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Broadcast the New Year's Eve midnight celebrations in Paris,
London, Tokyo and Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offer a contest asking the question, ``What are you planning
to do in the last 60 seconds of the millennium?'' Prizes include
New Year's Eve travel packages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offer the ability to chat and message during the New Year's
Eve celebration. Some messages will be broadcast on the big video
screens in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   BUYING PROTECTION FOR ONLINE PURCHASES
</P>
<P>
   Interested in taking advantage of the price and convenience of
Internet shopping but still leery about buying something you
haven't touched? A company, WebAssured.com, is offering purchase
protection for merchants and shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The company, located at www.webassured.com, is offering what it
claims is the Internet's first online purchase-protection program.
The protection offer is underwritten by Lloyd's of London.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes places where people can make laudatory
comments about online retailers as well as post warnings about
shady companies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
