<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7302 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-WEBHEALTH28-COX     09-27 1998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBHEALTH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Health sites are hits - but are they reliable?By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Looking on the Internet for health information?
You may get more than you expect.
</P>
<P>
   Type in the word ``allergy'' at a health Web site, for example,
and in one screen you can get a wealth of information and
advertising, all seamlessly linked together and personalized for
you. Click here for allergy news, there for how to treat them, over
here for a new drug, here to join a support group, here to buy some
Sudafed.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite an electronic house call but more than just a medical
library, the Internet may be the ultimate tool to disseminate
information about illnesses to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   But should you bet your health on Web site advice?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   While the popularity of online health sites is growing steadily,
so is criticism about them. Some experts warn that they can be
riddled with problems, such as unethical advertising, conflicts of
interest or simply bad advice.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including the medical profession's governing body, the
American Medical Association, are suggesting that online health
sites should be held to medicine's standards of trustworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   Leading health Web sites acknowledge that establishing
credibility is one of their toughest challenges, but they say that
consumers hold them to high standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do, it's all about establishing that trusted
relationship in the online world,'' said Don Hackett, chief
executive of Austin's drkoop.com, the most popular health-related
site on the Internet, attracting an estimated 3.5 million visitors
a month. ``In the online world ... all the information glows with
the same intensity, whether it's accurate or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But some say the industry should establish policies for ensuring
accuracy and disclosing the conflicts of interest that come along
with mixing content and commerce, the lifeblood of most Internet
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of those ventures has a profit motive, so the
information is always going to be suspect to profiteering,'' said
Eric Weidmann, an Austin physician who occasionally reviews
health-related Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Weidmann is a proponent of patients' use of the Web to find
health information and support. But like others, he points out that
because most Web sites are businesses that depend on profits, they
are ``suspect to reliability and motive.''
</P>
<P>
   CREDIBILITY CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   For an idea of what's driving some of the medical profession's
concern about health Web sites, hit the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes at most health Web sites, you won't find many
doctors _ or few people with any medical training, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the online health sites are typically operated by
entrepreneurs, former health-care executives, techies and
journalists, bringing together content from a variety of sources
while using their own and others' personal experience to dispense
advice.
</P>
<P>
   At drkoop.com, for instance, co-founder and namesake C. Everett
Koop, the former U.S. surgeon general, has little to do with the
daily operation of the drkoop.com, though his name and reputation
lend credibility to the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had perceived that Dr. Koop had a personal interest in
making sure this was credible information, so we jumped on the
bandwagon to allow our patients to have another source of
information,'' said David Morehead, president of the Scott &AMP; White
Health Plan, part of the Temple health-care system that is paying
drkoop.com $40,000 a year for packaged medical content and a place
on its list of preferred hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Search the major consumer health sites today and you might find
inconsistent answers and advice to questions on typical health
problems. One site might suggest taking vitamins is a good way for
treating a strain of hepatitis, for example, while another site
might advise that vitamins do no good.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the advice some Web health sites give is just plain
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the the August edition of the journal Cancer found
dangerous inaccuracies in cancer data in a sample of 400 health
information sites, nearly half of which had not been subjected to
scientific scrutiny, typically a key step in the publication of
articles in medical journals. The study's author listed only a
handful of sites, including, drkoop.com, that she considered
credible and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Few people _ if any _ are going to get advice on treating cancer
solely off an Internet site. Most sites, in fact, are careful not
to offer extensive advice for any conditions and to always warn
that their information is not a substitute for a physician's
advice.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics say visitors to almost any health Web site
should beware of what is becoming perhaps the most frequent
criticism of Web sites: potential conflicts of interest. Web
companies' methods of linking information and advertising, some
doctors and medical ethicists say, are rife with the potential for
misrepresentation and bias.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a news report revealed that a women's health Internet
site based in California, WomenFirst, had been paid to promote
brand-name prescription drugs written about regularly in its
articles.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, the AMA recently pointed out that drkoop.com had
not detailed to consumers how C. Everett Koop profited from the
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, that Web site did not give full disclosure,'' said
Robert Tenery, a Dallas ophthalmologist who sits on the American
Medical Association's Council on Ethical and Judicial Affairs,
which is examining online medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were profits being made that I would assume the casual
viewer would not recognize,'' he said. ``For someone who's looking
for important medical points, not reading every line, it would be
difficult to determine there was a conflict of interest there.''
</P>
<P>
   Koop, who lives in New Hampshire, was not available for comment.
Executives at drkoop.com say the site has always fully disclosed
its sponsors, but last month it took steps to further separate
advertising and content on the site and change wording to clarify
the nature of paid partnerships with health-care companies,
including hospitals. The company also killed an arrangement to pay
royalties on commercial activity on the site to Koop, known to many
Americans as a tough, unimpeachable advocate for the public's
health.
</P>
<P>
   Koop, meanwhile, is helping form an industry group that will
create a code of ethics for the e-health industry. Other sites are
already posting their advertising policies, hoping to avoid
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're being extremely oriented towards disclosure
now,'' said Dennis Upah, drkoop.com's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   GROWING POPULARITY
</P>
<P>
   Chalk it up to dissatisfaction with rushed doctor's visits or
just our growing reliance on the Internet for information: Health
care is one of the hottest topics on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, 25,000 sites on the Internet offer
information on health and medical conditions. Last month, more than
13 million people logged onto Internet health sites, according to a
study released recently by research group PC Data Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a rapid transition where people have a hunger for
medical knowledge, and I think many of us are frustrated with our
ability to provide that with the level of validity that the
patients want,'' said Morehead of the Scott &AMP; White Health Plan.
``I look at it in a sense as an experiment in society as to how
best to provide valid information to help them make up their
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   The entities behind major health sites vary from prestigious
medical centers such as the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota and M.D.
Anderson Cancer Center in Houston to for-profit companies like
drkoop.com and Healthanswers.com in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin360.com, a sister company to the Austin
American-Statesman, runs health information purchased from a
variety of companies. The Seton HealthCare Network also pays to be
the local sponsor of health content.)
</P>
<P>
   To grow quickly, most commercial sites have built business by
signing up partners, now the established way of expanding your
audience on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Drkoop.com may be the best case study of how to build a
successful commercial health site.
</P>
<P>
   There, partners such as America Online and the GO Network
provide ready audiences of millions of subscribers who want
consumer health information, and they link to health-care sites
from their well-trafficked gateways. With an audience in place,
drugstore chains, insurance companies, pharmaceutical companies and
clinical trials companies rush to sign up as partners and place ads
or sponsorships on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that a site that didn't exist 15 months ago now
has numerous partners promoting it online and off, many of them
paying for the privilege. Local television stations run commercials
for drkoop.com and exchange medical information and health stories
with the site. The maker of Nicorette and Nicoderm, two smoking
cessation products, sponsors the section on ``Tackling Tobacco'' on
drkoop.com. The sponsorships, like those on other sites, are
clearly labeled.
</P>
<P>
   But when about 20 hospitals _ including Scott &AMP; White _ showed
up on drkoop.com's list of preferred ``Community Partners,''
without noting that they had paid to be on the list, the AMA cried
foul. A company spokeswoman said the wording of that page was
changed around Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at drkoop.com say they keep content and advertising
as separate as church and state, won't accept content from
advertisers and routinely turn down advertising from companies they
feel are disreputable. Other sites, such as healthanswers.com,
intelihealth.com and onhealth.com, have similar policies.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA wants sites to go out of their way to delineate paid
advertising and medical information or advice and let consumers
know which is which.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing out there that says that Dr. Koop can't make
money giving advice on a Web site,'' said Tenery. ``That's not the
question. It all goes back to one thing and that's disclosure.''
Major commercial health sites say their content is evaluated by
doctors and noted to show where it came from.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that isn't always the case.
</P>
<P>
   On healthanswers.com, for instance, only the fine print tells
the source of entries in its ``library,'' and there is no mention
of who wrote the content, who reviewed it or when it was updated.
The information is purchased from the medical encyclopedia adam.com
and reviewed by doctors there, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, on drkoop.com, pages about such conditions as asthma,
endometriosis and HIV are credited only to the company and do not
detail who wrote or reviewed them. The company says it is reviewed
by doctors at Dartmouth Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   In online support groups and message boards common on many
health sites, information flows more freely and usually is posted
by lay people, not doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hosts know that they're not an authority, they're not a
counselor, they're not a physician,'' said Todd Woodward,
drkoop.com's executive community producer. ``Whatever you hear here
is not authoritative. But there's always going to be people sharing
Grandma's remedy for a sore knee or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   With health sites treading closer to the territory of doctors,
they know they will have to be more careful because they will be
judged on their content, not their ability to attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we feel our way along some of those bumpy points,
drkoop.com got called on some things that are not way over the edge
but certainly questionable,'' said Bob Pringle, president of
intelihealth.com, an online venture between insurance giant
Aetna/US Healthcare and Johns Hopkins Medical School. ``That
doesn't mean that people couldn't point fingers. You live in a
glass house you have to be careful about throwing stones.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
