<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV03-NY     09-27 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMENCLATURE FOR THE AGE OF UMBILICUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 3)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A full-page color advertisement in respectable newspapers for
the movie ``American Beauty'' zeroed in on a female abdomen.
Staring out at the reader, like the inescapable single eye of a
Cyclops, was the model's  &UR; umbilicus &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Showing that portion of the anatomy was not in bad taste because
 &UR; umbilici &LR;  are omnipresent these days. Fashion models sashay down
the midway with the smooth flesh of their flat stomachs proudly
exposed, and nubile shoppers parade through malls with breezes
causing goose bumps on their midsections. And at the center of
attention is the rounded depression, or the sometimes slight
protuberance, the dialectical synonymy of which we examine today.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking  &UR; bellybuttons &LR; , the focus of fashion at the  &UR; fin
de millenaire &LR; . A post-monokini shock was needed. If the display of
nipples no longer titillated, designers asked one another, could
the showing of bottoms be far behind? But when even the thong lost
its shock value, fashion's eye landed on the center of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between the emotion and the response,'' wrote the poet,
``Falls the Shadow.'' Between the  &UR; halter &LR;  and the  &UR; hip-hugger &LR; , or
between the  &UR; cropped top &LR;  and the  &UR; low-slung pants &LR; , Falls the
 &UR; Navel &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The Romans called the point at which the cord connecting the
fetus with the placenta was cut and tied off the  &UR; umbilicus &LR; , from
 &UR; umbo &LR; , ``knob, projection.'' Speakers of Old High German and Old
English preferred a Greek root,  &UR; omphalos &LR; , which led to  &UR; nabalo &LR; 
and  &UR; nafela &LR; , and then popped up in Shakespeare as ``he unseamed
him from the  &UR; naue &LR;  to the chops,'' and developed into Sir Thomas
Browne's 1646 observation, ``The use of the  &UR; Navell &LR;  is to continue
the infant into the mother.'' From there to James Russell Lowell's
1873 poetry: ``He lifted not his eyes from off his  &UR; navel &LR; 's mystic
knot.''
</P>
<P>
   That notion of self-absorption was picked up by the playwright
Eugene O'Neill: ``I had a mental view of him regarding his  &UR; navel &LR; 
frenziedly by the hour,'' and by the BBC's Listener in 1966: ``One
sits in a New York traffic jam, contemplating, as it were, the
city's  &UR; navel &LR; .'' Those who do this religiously are called
omphalopsychic, from a sect of quietists who induced hypnotic
trances by gazing at their navels.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many continue the introspective study. `` &UR; Bellybuttons &LR;  _
there are two kinds,'' said a character in the 1973 ``Odd Couple,''
``the kind that go in and the kind that go out. I want an  &UR; outie &LR; !
No, no! I want an  &UR; innie &LR; !'' But today, many more of us are
contemplating the navels of other people, forcing synonymists to
consider the varied nomenclature.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bellybutton &LR;  was first noted by John Bartlett in the 1877
edition of his Dictionary of Americanisms. Rudyard Kipling liked
that noun in 1934, scorning fights with those ``who do not come up
to your  &UR; bellybutton &LR; .'' Although Aldous Huxley preferred
 &UR; tummy-button &LR; , J.B. Priestley in 1946 minted a nice trope with
this sign of stomach-tightened nervousness: ``with your
 &UR; bellybutton &LR;  knockin' against your backbone.'' (It's two words in
Merriam-Webster, one word in Webster's New World. I go with the
analogy of  &UR; bellyache &LR; , not  &UR; belly dancer &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   Dialect-delighting Americans, however, have worked out a variety
of names for the same anatomical place. Thanks to the editors of
the Dictionary of American Regional English (now hard at work at
the University of Wisconsin at Madison on their fourth volume,
covering the letters P to S), we can examine a few answers to their
Question X34/1, ``What are some other names and nicknames for the
 &UR; navel &LR; ?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; One-eyed Mabel &LR;  was one response, probably derived from the
popular  &UR; nabel &LR; , a variant of  &UR; navel &LR;  recalling the Old High German
 &UR; nabalo &LR; .  &UR; Button &LR;  and  &UR; buttonhole &LR;  were frequent choices, and a
fair sampling called it a  &UR; belly-hole &LR; .  &UR; Chicken butt &LR;  and  &UR; chicken
peck &LR;  were noted. Those interested in content preferred
 &UR; lint-catcher &LR; ,  &UR; lint-getter &LR;  and  &UR; lint-strainer &LR; . Perhaps a Greek
influence can be found in one respondent's  &UR; oompalikis &LR;  and several
 &UR; piko &LR;  answers. The midriff midrash includes the Yiddish  &UR; pupik &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Many responses to DARE's survey began with the word  &UR; where &LR; . In
the South, it was  &UR; where the Yankee shot you &LR; ; in the West,  &UR; where
the Indians shot you &LR; , and across the country,  &UR; where I got shot in
the war &LR; . Two interviewees eschewed the violent gunfire-bullet-hole
metaphor and replied with the less bellicose  &UR; where you got hit
with a pick &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   CHICOMS
</P>
<P>
   Authors of historical fiction worry about anachronism. ``And now
the clock strikes 1,'' says Dromio of Syracuse, but it was a
Shakespearean comedy of error: Mechanical clocks, not invented
until the 14th century, were not available in ancient Ephesus.
</P>
<P>
   I had the same problem writing a novel set in our Federal
period, and wondered what phrase a man of that era would have used
for what we now call  &UR; hush money &LR; . (Turns out Thomas Jefferson used
the words  &UR; hush money &LR;  in a letter, nearly a century after Steele
and Swift.)
</P>
<P>
   Thus it was when I came to the word  &UR; Chicom &LR;  in Seymour
Topping's ``Peking Letter,'' a riveting novel of the Chinese civil
war, I wondered: Was that word _ a portmanteau of ``Chinese
Communist'' _ in use in the late '40s?
</P>
<P>
   The earliest citation in the OED is 1966; the Random House
Historical Dictionary of American Slang found a 1964 use by Robin
Moore in his novel ``The Green Berets.'' So I called Top, a
longtime New York Times colleague and now administrator of the
Pulitzer Prizes, and put it to him. He was the Associated Press
correspondent in Peking (now spelled Beijing) reporting on that
war; was the word in use at the time?
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet it was, and it was no derogation,'' he recalled. ``The
truce teams of our Military Advisory Group referred to the
Nationalist Chinese as the  &UR; Nats &LR;  and the Communist Chinese as the
 &UR; Chicoms &LR; . I can hear it now _ `The  &UR; Chicoms &LR;  took Mukden, and the
 &UR; Nats &LR;  didn't put up much of a fight.'''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the value to political etymology of the historical
novel. Years from now, our descendants will be reading dramas about
the struggle between today's  &UR; Chicoms &LR;  and their rivals on
politically free Taiwan, the  &UR; Chidems &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7308 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN28-CO     09-27 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome to the new 'hood, and network
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Normally, I hate moving.
</P>
<P>
   But this time it was different: I knew a computer network was
hidden in my walls, and it was just dying to be used.
</P>
<P>
   The Cat 5 cable snaking behind the Sheetrock all but screamed at
me while I puttered around, redistributing the contents of unpacked
boxes, shuffling furniture, hanging towel bars and installing
blinds.
</P>
<P>
   After a few weeks, when we could see parts of the floor between
the piles of belongings, I could contain myself no longer: I had to
test out my wiring and fire up the ethernet.
</P>
<P>
   Without really meaning to, I found myself standing in the
networking aisle of the local CompUSA debating quantity vs.
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Quality won out, in no small part because of the e-mails several
readers sent warning me against the perils of skimping on my NICs
and hub. So, even though they were twice _ and in some cases thrice
_ as much as other products, I stuck with 3Com and Intel for my
hardware, just as you all suggested.
</P>
<P>
   About $300 later, I walked out with a four-port Intel hub, a
3Com 10/100 NIC for my main machine and a 3Com LAN PC card _ which
was the real big-ticket item at $180 _ for the laptop.
</P>
<P>
   When I got home with the goodies, I had a simple plan: Wire up
the P166, take the laptop around to all the network jacks in the
house and check the connections.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I plan to set up a client-server network with a
proxy server to be able to share my Internet connection. But for my
tests I didn't need anything tricky or fancy. Both my machines use
Win95, and by all accounts setting up a peer-to-peer network was
supposed to be a snap.
</P>
<P>
   So I installed my NICs, plugged in the hub and promptly hit a
snag.
</P>
<P>
   I had no Network Neighborhood icon on my desktop.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those annoying icons Windows won't let you remove
from the desktop. So, earlier, I had used a program called TweakUI
to get rid of it almost as soon as I bought my trusty old P166 a
couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Once I restored the icon to its preordained place, the first
step was to make sure I had all the necessary clients, adapters and
protocols installed in my network settings.
</P>
<P>
   The Client for Microsoft Networks, Client for Netware Networks,
and file and printer sharing software was already installed by
default. There was also the dial-up adapter, which was put in when
I configured TCP/IP through Win95, and my new 3Com adapter was
listed as well.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Now to check the protocols.
</P>
<P>
   Small LANs like mine, which could have up to eight ports if Mrs.
Power User lets me put machines in the kitchen and dining room
(yeah, right), only really need to deal with three protocols in the
networking preferences: TCP/IP, for the Internet; IPX/SPX, used by
many games for speedy LAN play; and NetBUI for LAN file and printer
sharing.
</P>
<P>
   A TCP protocol was already set up for the dial-up adapter, and a
second TCP protocol appeared that was bound to my 3Com ethernet
card.
</P>
<P>
   Adding protocols is no more difficult than clicking on ``Add''
and finding them under the subsequent choices for Microsoft. There
can be some confusion when two protocols of each type appear in the
list, but one is for the dial-up adapter and one is for the NIC.
</P>
<P>
   The only real configuration needed is for the TCP/IP protocol,
which requires that each machine on the network have a unique IP
address, such as 10.0.0.1 for computer 1, 10.0.0.2 for computer 2,
etc. If your Internet service provider uses dynamic IP addressing,
which most of them do, you will want to leave the TCP bound to the
dial-up adapter alone and only specify IP addresses for the TCP
bound to your network card. (Also, make sure you don't enable file
sharing on your dial-up TCP protocol, which would open up your
drives _ and printer _ to the Internet.)
</P>
<P>
   Next, click the ``File and Print Sharing'' button and check the
box for sharing files. If you have a printer attached to the
machine, click the other box for printer sharing.
</P>
<P>
   The last step is to click the ``Identification'' tab to give the
machine a name and assign it to a work group, which should be the
same for all machines on a small network.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you will have to set up the network preferences for
each machine on your LAN, but that's part of the fun of being a
systems administrator, isn't it? Some more fun of being a sysadmin
is that Win95 makes you reboot every time you change anything in
your network preferences, which gets real annoying real quickly.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains is to go into Windows Explorer and right click
on each drive you want to share, give it a unique name and set the
sharing permissions to full access. Ditto for each printer.
</P>
<P>
   In my case, the whole process _ annoying reboots and testing all
my jacks notwithstanding _ took little over an hour. It would have
taken less except the laptop couldn't find my printer and I spent
20 minutes before I realized the printer wasn't on. (Hey, calling
this column Power User wasn't my idea.)
</P>
<P>
   Although file and print sharing is nice, the real reason for a
peer-to-peer home network is, of course, multiplayer gaming. (You
need a client-server setup with one machine as a proxy server to
share a modem on a LAN.)
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the first thing I did was to set up network
versions of some of my favorites: ``Quake II,'' ``Hexen II'' and
``Dungeon Keeper.''
</P>
<P>
   But my elation at my in-home game network was quickly snuffed
out ... when I realized the only multiplayer gaming I was going to
be doing was running between room to room making my Paladin punch
my Necromancer and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Because, I am sure Mrs. Power User would take a dim view of
recruiting our daughter Emily into a Hexen Deathmatch ... at least
until she turns 6.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
