<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMPHONY-MANSON-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNE MANSON, KC'S NEW CLASSICAL DARLING, LIKES TO KEEP THE FOCUS ON
MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANTRELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Had the fates decreed differently _ or had Anne Manson been what
most parents would deem a more sensible girl _ she might have been
a physician. As late as her senior year at Harvard University, when
she was looking into study abroad, she was still considering
medical school.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a logical move for the daughter of a
Cambridge, Mass., orthopedic surgeon. But Manson also inherited her
father's other passion, classical music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had music in our house all the time,'' the new music
director of the Kansas City Symphony recalls of her youth. ``My
father constantly played recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was at school during the Second World War in England, and
he had a teacher whose family had a box for concerts at the Albert
Hall. His teacher would bring a group of kids regularly to
concerts, and it made a huge impact on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Manson's father passed along the favor, as it were, by taking
his own daughters to concerts in the Boston area. Libby, the
younger daughter, went on to other things, but Anne would go on to
study music in England, to become the first woman ever to conduct
the prestigious Vienna Philharmonic and now one of only three
female music directors among the 50 largest North American
orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Manson and husband Martin Hansen, a lawyer
specializing in international intellectual property rights, were
tidying up their London home to rent out. Their new home base will
be Kansas City, where this week Manson opens her first fall season
as the new music director of the Kansas City Symphony. Offstage
priorities include shopping for furniture for their new home, south
of the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   A private person
</P>
<P>
   So who is this new mover and shaker on the Kansas City arts
scene _ and, at age 37, one of the youngest music directors around?
(She'll turn 38 on Tuesday.)
</P>
<P>
   Sit down with Manson in a dressing room after a rehearsal and
you'll find a compact, crisply spoken woman exuding well-bred
graciousness. But don't expect Midwestern chumminess or folksiness:
She is a Bostonian, with a certain reserve doubtless reinforced by
a decade and a half of living in England. She admits to wariness at
the People magazine-type interest in the private lives of public
figures.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no interviewing of her parents, both now retired.
There will be no pictures with son Ben, born only a few days before
her Kansas City appointment was announced, in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really very private,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one on one, Manson traces a human interest story with its
share of pivotal decisions _ and some lucky breaks. It's sometimes
easy to forget that this is her first job as an orchestra music
director. She's very much a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   But the Symphony's music director search committee _ and its
board of trustees _ saw enough promise in her that they passed up
considerably older and more experienced candidates for the job. In
a field long dominated by white-maned men, youth and good looks no
longer are deemed evidence of superficiality. The novelty of a
female music director may actually be a marketing asset.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a comfortable, intellectually upmarket family _
her mother taught English and wrote book reviews _ Manson began
studying piano ``as early as I can remember.'' She went on to more
serious study of the viola and singing in church choirs. Sister
Libby, four years younger, played piano and flute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a lot of chamber music at home and with other
people,'' Manson says. ``I really think that's so important for
children, because that's how music becomes a language that means
something to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manson girls were taken to a lot of chamber music concerts,
and Anne remembers seeing a Metropolitan Opera touring production
of ``Don Giovanni.'' But not until she was in high school _ at a
private girls' school bearing the toney name Windsor _ did she
attend her first orchestra concert.
</P>
<P>
   It was a doozie: the Boston Symphony Orchestra and chorus
performing Sir Michael Tippett's oratorio ``A Child of Our Time.''
Composed between 1939 and 1941, it's a powerful, moving response to
Nazi persecution of the Jews _ and a provocative consideration of
inhumanity in general. (Manson will conduct the work here in
November.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was completely knocked out by it,'' Manson recalls. ``It was
an amazing experience. I still remember how the soprano looked and
what she sounded like.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston to London
</P>
<P>
   Still, Manson entered Harvard University with a double major,
pairing a liberal-arts program called history and literature with
pre-med, with some music courses on the side. She ended up with a
music major and pre-med minor.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's music department is known for academic music studies,
not performance training, and Manson graduated with a bachelor of
arts in music theory and analysis. But along the way she took a
course in choral conducting and another in orchestral conducting,
and she got a couple of chances to lead the Harvard orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   With graduation looming, Manson started casting about for
fellowships for foreign study. Ultimately she decided to explore
music, and she landed a Marshall Scholarship for study in London.
She signed up for a graduate program in theory and analysis at
King's College of the University of London. But on the side she
began studying conducting at the Royal College of Music with Norman
Del Mar, a respected conductor as well as composer and writer on
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put me in front of the symphony orchestra at the Royal
College quite a lot,'' Manson recalls, ``and I really wasn't ready
for it. I had done hardly any conducting before. But I learned a
tremendous amount from him.''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing her master's, Manson spent another year in the
opera-conducting program at the Royal College. On the side, she
talked some fellow students into putting together a performance of
Mozart's ``Cosi fan tutte.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in an open courtyard in London,'' she recalls. ``But it
had tall walls, so the acoustic was beautiful. Because none of us
was paid, we worked really hard. There was no limit to rehearsals _
if we needed to do more, we would just get some sandwiches and stay
into the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   That experience stirred Manson's interest in conducting opera,
and she landed an opera conducting fellowship at the Royal Northern
College of Music in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``They left you alone to do your rehearsals,'' she says of the
school's postgraduate conducting program. ``But they videoed a lot
of stuff and you had the ghastly experience of watching yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in London she teamed up with a theater director friend to
form a small opera company to perform off-the-beaten-path
20th-century repertory. The off-and-on company worked its way up to
the Queen Elizabeth Hall, one of the prime performance venues in
London's South Bank performing arts complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's certainly made a name here,'' says Hugh Canning of the
Sunday Times of London, probably the dean of British music critics.
``She's quite well-known for allowing herself very progressive
repertory ideas. I haven't seen her work for some time, but she's
known to be a live wire here.''
</P>
<P>
   Vienna apprenticeship
</P>
<P>
   Still, Manson faced a frustrating period after finishing the
opera conducting program in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hardest juncture when you're a conductor, to get
your first engagement,'' she says. ``No one knows anything about
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a concert in Norway that first season after I finished,
and I was teaching a bit _ coaching chamber music and so forth in
London. But I was getting really fed up and bored.''
</P>
<P>
   She shared her frustration with James Lockhart, who headed the
opera program at the Royal College of Music. He volunteered to
write a letter to Claudio Abbado, then music director of the Vienna
State Opera, to see if Manson could sit in on his rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   Given a green light, Manson headed to Vienna, settled in with a
friend living there and signed up for an intensive German course.
She observed Abbado's rehearsals for ``Don Giovanni.'' Then
Abbado's regular assistant began spending more and more time out of
town and Manson got tapped to fill in. That's how she ended up one
day in front of the Vienna Philharmonic, the orchestra of the
Vienna State Opera, taking the place of an indisposed Abbado in a
rehearsal of ``Boris Godunov.'' Abbado later tapped Manson to
conduct the end of a run of ``Boris'' at the 1994 Salzburg
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the recent controversy over the Vienna
Philharmonic's refusal to admit female players, the sight of a
woman conductor must have raised some blood pressures _ not least
of all Manson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very nervous,'' she admits, ``but I don't think that's
what made me nervous. It was just the whole setting, that audience.
The standard of performance there is kind of the pinnacle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the audience in Salzburg was composer-conductor Pierre
Boulez, who liked what he saw and heard enough to arrange for
Manson to conduct his Paris-based Ensemble InterContemporain. She
began to get other guest-conducting gigs: the London Mozart
Players, the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, the Iceland Symphony
Orchestra, the Vienna Chamber Orchestra. In 1995 she made her
American debut, conducting Samuel Barber's ``Vanessa'' for
Washington (D.C.) Opera.
</P>
<P>
   That's when her sister played Cupid, introducing Manson to
Stanford Law School-trained lawyer Martin Hansen (who also happens
to have studied viola).
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, it was an opera, which means you're in town for a
long period of time,'' Manson says. ``We met around New Year's, and
I was in Washington until the end of February.''
</P>
<P>
   The romance blossomed in trans-Atlantic commute mode, and then
Hansen moved to London, home base for Manson's growing career in
England and Europe. They were married in 1997; son Ben came along a
year later.
</P>
<P>
   Building trust
</P>
<P>
   When the Kansas City Symphony started its search for a new music
director to replace the departing William McGlaughlin, executive
director Roland Valliere sought suggestions from his counterpart at
the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, Henry Fogel. Fogel passed along the
name of this young woman he'd seen in a guest conducting gig with
the Iceland Symphony Orchestra (with which Manson has become a
regular).
</P>
<P>
   ``What struck me is a kind of freshness and vitality in the
music-making,'' Fogel says, ``and a sense of really connecting with
the orchestra. She seems to react to what she hears and to draw the
best out of her players.''
</P>
<P>
   Put on the list of 11 more or less official candidates for the
job, a visibly pregnant Manson conducted her audition concerts in
January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The search committee was impressed with Manson's no-nonsense
ideas for building up an orchestra with little profile beyond its
metropolitan area _ and with a local reputation for erratic
performances. And she seemed to light up virtually everyone in her
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this instantaneous positive reaction which came from
all the different constituencies,'' says Robert Kipp, the Hallmark
Cards executive who headed the Symphony's search committee. ``It
came first from the orchestra, second from those of us involved in
the community and third from the public.''
</P>
<P>
   And the rest is Kansas City history.
</P>
</TEXT>
