<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get the inside scoop on what people read
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More fun than eBay, less expensive than CDNow and far
more entertaining than watching your Net stocks hit another
all-time high is the newest gimmick from Amazon.com designed to
chew up more of your online time.
</P>
<P>
   It's an endless stream of best-seller lists from every nook and
corner of the world called purchase circles.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, which began life as an online bookseller and quickly
morphed into the Web's very own virtual Wal-Mart, has always
published best-seller lists of books, CDs and videos. But looking
at The New York Times best-seller list filled with the usual
suspects like John Grisham legal thrillers and Oprah's book of the
month is about as exciting as watching paint dry.
</P>
<P>
   Purchase circles are totally different. What Amazon has done is
group the items it ships to a particular ZIP code and to a domain
name, such as Microsoft.com. From this pile of data, it is able to
apply an algorithm that builds best-seller lists for cities,
states, universities and major corporations. All the information is
anonymous, so there's no way of knowing what individuals are
reading at each location, but what you get is an interesting,
often-amusing picture of what people are reading in boardrooms,
classrooms and subway trains all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   For example, business is on the minds of Atlanta residents, who
stay local with books by former Coca-Cola marketing guru Sergio
Zyman and ``Built From Scratch,'' the story of Atlanta-based Home
Depot.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the charts is ``The Terrible Truth About
Liberals'' by talk radio host Neal Boortz. Tom Wolfe's Atlanta
epic, ``A Man in Full,'' is also on the list, along with ``The
Sweet Potato Queen's Book of Love,'' an irreverent guide to life by
a legendary group of Southern belles from Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, over in San Francisco, technology dominates the list
of local favorites. Topping the list are books with titles like
``The Silicon Boys and Their Valley of Dreams.'' Po Bronson's ``The
Nudist on the Late Shift and Other True Tales of Silicon Valley''
and Michael Wolff's near-classic Net tale, ``Burn Rate,'' also pop
up on this list. E-commerce wannabes are busy studying ``Why We
Buy: The Science of Shopping.'' Still, a few best sellers such as
``The Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing'' and ``Memoirs of a
Geisha'' did slip into the Bay Area top 10.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't live in a metro area, never fear: Amazon compiles
purchase circles for the most remote village and hamlet, from
Palmer, Alaska (``How to Get Started in Electronic Day Trading'')
to York, Maine (Tom Brokaw's ``The Greatest Generation'').
</P>
<P>
   Isn't this fun?
</P>
<P>
   What's going on in corporate America? Well, let's see what
they're reading. Topping the list over at BellSouth is a book
called ``First, We Break All the Rules: What the World's Greatest
Managers Do Differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Close on its heels are books about dieting, coping and
spirituality. Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli are the big musical
favorites at BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   What does this say about the telecommunications giant? That's
hard to say, but someone's bound to write a term paper about it.
They say you are what you eat; what will they say about what you
read?
</P>
<P>
   Amazon seems to have files on every ZIP code and every company
in America. One click of the mouse and you'll see that history,
technology and genetics texts are hot at Harvard. You can also find
out that they read these books while grooving to tunes from Lauryn
Hill, U2, Madonna and the Buena Vista Social Club.
</P>
<P>
   You can look at a purchase circle and wonder why there is a run
on Italian travelogues at Emory University, but then you don't have
to be a rocket scientist to figure out why George Stephanopoulos'
book, ``All Too Human,'' tops the best-seller list in the U.S.
Senate. Still, folk rocker Lucinda Williams topping the Senate's
musical selections does give you pause for thought.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon doesn't say exactly what it wants to accomplish with
these endless lists of who's buying what, and some people and
corporations don't like their reading preferences splashed all over
the Internet for everyone to see. Amazon provides users with a way
to keep their book purchases to themselves, and there's a number to
call to have a company or university deleted from the published
lists.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the purchase circles are a gimmick, but it works. It's a
voyeuristic peek into the bookshelves of all kinds of people:
students, parents and executives.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably a million uses for purchase circles Amazon
never even thought of. Why not log on to Amazon at your next dinner
party and have people guess what's playing in Peoria? This can be
hours of fun for the whole family. You don't even need your credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
