<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New hand-held games are made for little kids
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Hand-held electronic games are popular with teens
and preteens, but they can be frustrating for smaller children. Big
brothers and sisters hardly ever let the little ones play, and when
they do the games may be too difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro Games added eight games to its hand-held game line this
year, including six games designed to be played by players 8 years
old or younger. Hand-held games, which are produced by several
companies, are available at most toy and discount stores.
</P>
<P>
   Among Hasbro's new games for kids are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pooh Flickering Fireflies, ages 3 to 5: Talking fireflies lead
players on a chase through the 100 Acre Wood of the popular Winnie
the Pooh series. The game automatically adjusts to three skill
levels and features four games. Suggested price: $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ballzerko, ages 5 and older: This is an electronic pinball
game with an electronic voice, lights, music and sounds for three
fast-paced activities. Suggested price: $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   _ Operation: The portable, electronic version of the classic
board game lets players conduct ``operations'' and remove parts
like ``butterflies in the stomach'' from their imaginary patients.
The game has a time to let players race against the clock.
Suggested price: $17.99.
</P>
<P>
   _ Simon, ages 7 to adult: The original version of this game was
hot in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The game plays a series of four lights and accompanying tones,
and players try to repeat the pattern by touching four colored
buttons in the proper order. Hasbro's portable version has four
skill levels and three ways to play. Suggested price: $7.99.
</P>
<P>
   The other new hand-held games in the Hasbro line this year are
Frogger, Bop It Extreme, Trivial Pursuit NFL Edition and Trivial
Pursuit NASCAR Edition.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
