<SLUG> BC-TECH-NOSE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mechanical nose sniffs out trouble
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRBORN, Ohio _ It may not take much to figure out that hog
manure stinks, but Wright State University Assistant Professor
Ricardo Guiterrez-Osuna has an electronic nose that objectively and
precisely measures such odors.
</P>
<P>
   Guiterrez, 31, began working on the electronic nose project as a
graduate student at North Carolina State University in 1996. The
National Pork Producers Association helped fund the project because
``they wanted a device to give an objective sense of smell,''
Guiterrez said.
</P>
<P>
   The human nose is roughly 1,000 times more sensitive but human
olfactory abilities adapt to smells after a while, said Guiterrez.
So a hog farmer isn't as sensitive to the manure smell or a chef
doesn't smell cooking food as strongly after being in the kitchen
awhile, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guiterrez brought the electronic nose project to Wright State a
year ago when he was appointed to the computer science and
engineering department.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic nose can be used to measure food or beverage
quality by sniffing each product as it rolls off the manufacturing
line, diagnose infections by sniffing bacteria cultures and
eventually detect mustard gas or other hazardous compounds used in
warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Research on electronic noses originated in England in the 1980s
but only a handful of scientists in the United States are working
on such projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The machine consists of a power supply, pump, five valves,
electronic circuit boards and chamber with 16 tin oxide sensors. It
sits on a small sheet of particle board and is hooked up to a
laptop computer. Guiterrez is able to fit it into a plastic
container about the size of a toy box when using it outside of his
lab.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate the nose, Guiterrez sprinkles cinnamon into a jar
with a plastic tube sticking out of the lid. He plugs the tube into
a valve on the nose. The air in the cinnamon jar is pumped through
the machine. The surfaces of the 16 sensors react, changing the
conductivity and sending a signal to the laptop. The 16 colored
lines move from straight to up and down on the screen into a
distinct pattern that represents cinnamon's fingerprint. The more
times the machine smells, the better the recognition pattern
becomes.
</P>
<P>
   A 60-second whiff by the device's 16 sensors results in 900
measurements. Guiterrez's computer program uses mathematical
calculations to compress that data down to two measurements that
can be plotted using linear algebra. The program is so precise that
the differences between the smells of Coke and Pepsi can be easily
plotted _ an experiment Guiterrez conducted as part of his doctoral
dissertation.
</P>
<P>
   Guiterrez said he sees the device eventually being used to
control emissions into the environment and helping doctors diagnose
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in making money off it right now. I'm
interested in the research and science of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
