<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: For vacation, a
<TEXT>
friend and I want to visit Indian reservations. I have heard it is
possible to be given an American Indian name. Is this a practice of
any particular reservation? Are there any reservations in Texas? _
L. Ferrell
<P>
   A: Think twice before participating in such an event. If you do
find a reservation with a naming ceremony for tourists, its value
will be pure entertainment, says David Pego, Texas delegate to the
White House Conference on Indian Education. (Sometimes a naming is
done by unscrupulous, fake spiritual leaders who might not be real
Native Americans.) Names are generally given only to tribal
members, and some communities prohibit members from disclosing
their Native American names to outsiders. Four tribes are found on
three federally recognized Texas reservations: the Kickapoos, near
the border city of Eagle Pass; the Alabama and Coushatta tribes,
near Livingston; and the Tiguas, a reservation surrounded by the
city of El Paso. New Mexico has more than 20 reservations, mostly
small pueblo-style villages, technically federal reservations.
While Oklahoma is home to more than 30 tribes, the state contains
no reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that a CD-ROM based on the book ``Native and
Naturalized Woody Plants of Austin and the Hill Country'' has been
developed by a professor and was being given to schools in the
Austin Independent School District. Is this available to the
public? My husband would really like to own one.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lynn McCree
</P>
<P>
   A: The CD-ROM is available at a number of retail locations such
as AusTex Garden and Nursery, Borders, Book People, the Lady Bird
Johnson Wildflower Center, the Natural Gardener (formerly
Garden-Ville), Southwestern University Bookstore, and Wild Basin
Wilderness Preserve (members pay $17.95). A complete list of
locations is available at www.flash.net/(tilde)waittd. CDs sell for
$24.95 ($19.95 for schoolteachers). Green thumbs will enjoy this
interactive guide to the identification of 142 trees, shrubs and
woody vines of Central Texas. A portion of the proceeds from the
Woody Plants CD-ROM goes to the Brother Daniel Lynch scholarship
fund at St. Edward's University. Q: I would like the following
information about the famous Hail Mary pass from Staubach to
Pearson: the team name, the score, the game date. A pound of
Starbucks coffee is riding on this. _ Lee G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ahhhhh the Dallas Cowboys, my team _ even in the lean years.
The Hail Mary pass _ so named by quarterback Roger Staubach in an
interview after this Dec. 28, 1975, game _ sailed 50 yards. Prayers
work wonders. The opposing team was the Minnesota Vikings in this
National Football league division playoff. The Cowboys won 17-14.
Sports aficionados tell me Drew Pearson caught the pass between his
right elbow and hip. Q: I cannot find Evian (eau mineral natural)
``brumisateur'' spray water. I used to get it at Saks Fifth Avenue,
which doesn't keep it anymore. I love spraying it on my face._ Jean
Thagdard
</P>
<P>
   A: Check again. Upscale stores such as Saks, as well as a few
pharmacies, carry Evian spray (5 oz. bottle retails for $8.50). The
spray, powered by ozone-friendly nitrogen oxide gas, can be applied
on or under makeup, and provides cool H20 relief in the Texas heat.
Evian therapy originally comforted burn patients in France.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We recently purchased a house that has a kitchen counter top
set on a rock base. The stone leaves a fine white residue when
touched. It is particularly annoying when we or our guests sit at
the counter, and the residue rubs off on our clothing. How might we
rectify this problem? _ Gilbert L. Blount
</P>
<P>
   A: The rock needs to be sealed and I am surprised the builder
did not do this. Sealing is a fairly simple task. You can do
yourself, says veteran rock worker Carlos Bazan of Renaissance
Stone Design. Pick up a clear, silicone-based sealer at any home or
hardware store. Clean the rock work. Apply the sealer with a paint
sprayer or a sponge. It dries in a couple of hours. Q: Is there
such a thing as a $1 million bill? How would you cash one? _ Sam B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes there is such a thing, but no, you can't cash it.It was
minted by a Canadian firm as a collectible (Canadian for ``worth
nothing''). This certificate, known as the ``One Million Dollar
Special Issue,'' originally sold for $1. The largest denomination
ever printed by the United States was the $100,000 Gold
Certificate. This 1934 bill featured President Wilson and existed
only for transactions in Federal Reserve Banks. Q: I sneeze with
such verve and gusto that people within a 10-foot radius swear they
feel the earth move underfoot. Why don't we sneeze when we sleep?
Can it be to keep our sleeping partners from committing homicide? _
D.R.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Bless you! ``Reflexes are reduced when sleeping, so you do
not sneeze,'' guesses Dr. Neil Miller at Capital Ear Nose and
Throat Clinic. Lots of folks control the sneezing reflex with
various forms of concentration _ staring at a light, rubbing the
nose, pressing on the upper lip. Sleeping sounds better, though.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Readers who appreciated the instructions on how to iron a
shirt (OK, so they sent the item to their children for reference)
will appreciate these tips on pressing pants from Hamilton Beach
small appliance manufacturer. Lay the sides of pockets on the
ironing board to press them (avoid that bulky pocket outline). Next
slide the waistline over the ironing board and iron the top of the
pants. Rotate to cover all sections. Lay the pants legs flat (one
on top of the other). Iron the inside of the pant leg making sure
to align inseams. Fold back the top leg, iron. Flip and repeat.
Finally tackle the outside of the pants legs. For more tips, visit
www.hamiltonbeach.com or call (800) 851-8900.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reader Joyce Wilson reports her husband's success cleaning a
scorched stainless steel pan: Turtle Wax rubbing compound. Add a
lot of elbow grease. The burned-on, scorched metal was once again
shiny bright. Anything to save a favorite pan.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
