<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft's Word 98 a great deal
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You don't often get deals like this from software
giant Microsoft, which is also the largest developer of Macintosh
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The company is offering its popular word processor at a
two-thirds discount. And it's throwing in tons of new stuff to
boot.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Word 98, which is also part of the Microsoft
Office suite, was selling for around $330 in the Mac catalogs as a
stand-alone product.
</P>
<P>
   Now Microsoft is offering the same program, with some added
templates, for $99 (after the mailing of a $30 rebate card). The
marketing pitch is that this version of Word is for iMac and iBook
users. But Word 98 Special Edition, as it is called, will work with
any Power Mac.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect, but don't know as a fact, that Microsoft lowered the
price to compete against a handful of challengers that have lowered
prices or offered free versions of their word processors.
</P>
<P>
   WordPerfect, for example, is now available for free via the
Internet. This program offers about 80 percent of Word's features
and was at one time Microsoft's leading competitor in the Mac word
processing market. You'll find this download at
www.corel.com/products
</P>
<P>
   /macintosh/wpmac35/packfreedownload
</P>
<P>
   .htm.
</P>
<P>
   Nisus Writer, another first-rate word processor, is also
offering a free download of an earlier version of itself. This
program still has features, such as maintaining multiple
clipboards, that the Mac version of Word has yet to offer.
</P>
<P>
   While Nisus Writer and WordPerfect are each excellent programs,
Microsoft's current offering on Word is hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   For one, whether you like it or not, Word is the word processing
standard, especially in the office. Word 98 is probably the best
Mac version Microsoft has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   Word 98 finally supports full drag-and-drop technology. It also
incorporates the look and feel of Apple Computer's latest operating
system, OS 8. It sports OS 8's platinum look, contextual menus and
extensive interactive help.
</P>
<P>
   Word even adds some small but handy innovations of its own.
Among the better ones are buttons that let you easily jump from
page to page, chart to chart or graphic to graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Another powerful feature is the document map, which lets you
easily navigate a book or report through an outline. Other features
include buttons that let you highlight text with a yellow marker
and add comments that appear only when you place your cursor over
marked text.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to sweeten the pot, Microsoft is throwing in with its
special edition of Word thousands of clip art images. There are
also 100 greeting card templates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
