<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Windows challengers moving into spotlight
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The battle over which company will control the desktop
computer _ a battle many experts have long believed Microsoft
already won _ is about to heat up again. Many new challengers are
vying to replace Microsoft's Windows operating system. Read about
these systems and their chances for victory in the October issue of
PC World.
</P>
<P>
   Among the operating systems covered are BeOS 4.5 and Linux. The
magazine also takes a close look at the upcoming versions of
Windows, scheduled for release next year.
</P>
<P>
   It's list time again, and some of Atlanta's top entrepreneurs
have made Digitalsouth magazine's top high-tech entrepreneurs.
Topping the list in the October issue is Bert Ellis Jr., the
45-year-old chairman and chief executive of iXL Enterprises. Other
Atlantans on the list are WebMD founder Jeff Arnold, MindSpring
founder Charles Brewer and Media Metrix Vice Chairman Jeff Levy.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has a great deal for Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   The company released its popular Word writing program in a new
package for iMac and iBook users. Called Word 98 Special Edition,
the package includes thousands of new clip art images and 100 new
greeting card templates, as well as Microsoft's free Web browser
and e-mail programs.
</P>
<P>
   The package retails for $99, about $200 less than previously
released versions of Word 98.
</P>
<P>
   First it was in movie theaters, then on computer screens. Now
you can experience George Lucas' ``Phantom Menace'' on Sony
PlayStation. LucasArts Entertainment has released a video game
based on the latest ``Star Wars'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   The latest news organization to join the Year 2000 bandwagon is
the Public Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   Its member stations have run a series of stories about the
millennium bug and the potential problems it may cause. You can
read transcripts of these stories, view video clips from them and
research general information about Y2K at a special site PBS has
set up.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find the site at www.pbs.org/y2kontarget/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
