<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When HTML fails, there's always solitaire
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Robert Rogers e-mails me with an interesting computer
problem. The reason it is interesting, incidentally, is because (1)
It might happen to you and (2) I happen to know the answer. I get a
lot of questions that aren't of much interest, because although (1)
It might happen to you, (2) I don't have a clue about how to fix
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a Gateway G6-300 computer, equipped with Windows 98 and
the Word 97 word processor,'' Mr. Rogers writes. ``My problem stems
from opening e-mail and other text from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``By opening it, I mean that sometimes I save e-mail news
articles and other information in my computer. Sometimes, it is a
hassle trying to open some of this information, and sometimes, the
documents will not open at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I save a file is that I go to the File function on the
toolbar, and to Save As on the dropdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the save window, I save in `My Documents' and as HTML
files. The files save, but when I try to open them with Word 97, a
lot of them won't open. Am I doing something wrong, or is there a
better way of saving files off the Internet?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Mr. Rogers, the only surprise here is that any of them
open. As best I recall, an HTML reader was an add-on feature for
early versions of Word 97. You had to download it, and it would
attach itself to the word processor. Otherwise, Word 97 would be
unlikely to open any HTML file.
</P>
<P>
   HTML, of course, is hypertext code, the simple language with
which Web sites are written.
</P>
<P>
   All you need do is save the file as text instead of HTML. Then
you should be able to open it as a text file.
</P>
<P>
   You can also, obviously, open an HTML file with the browser that
saved it. Just use the Open command in the File menu.
</P>
<P>
   I am getting more and more message attachments couched in HTML.
It's really an aggravation, because Lotus Notes, perhaps the most
misbegotten program ever inflicted upon an unsuspecting public in
the last few years, won't read HTML. For that matter, I don't
believe the e-mail program I use at home _ Eudora _ reads it
either. Most of these messages, I imagine, come from folks using
Navigator or Explorer to send messages.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still getting the occasional epistle regarding solitaire.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Bunny? She's the lady who told me you haven't lived
until you've run up a big score turning one card at a time. I don't
remember what that score was, but Joy Cawley does.
</P>
<P>
   Joy asks me to tell Bunny that ``I play solitaire against the
clock with the three-card turnover and my best score to date is
8,704 in 87 seconds. She should definitely give it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   I've never played one-card turnover solitaire, which sounds kind
of like shooting fish in a barrel, but neither do I play against
the clock or watch the score. I have other things to do for
excitement, such as remembering the way to work every morning. I
play solitaire to relax and contemplate the nature of the universe
and the question of why, after all, frogs weren't given wings to
avoid all that wear and tear on their posteriors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
