<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take my advice, Kelley, curb your ego
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dear David E. Kelley:
</P>
<P>
   You've come down with a nasty case of Big Head Disease, and you
need to treat it before your considerable talents are wasted.
</P>
<P>
   I know, you probably don't give a hoot what some TV critic in
Texas thinks, but this advice is offered for your own good. Steven
Bochco came down with the same ailment a few years ago and, thanks
to serious critical drubbing, managed to shake it.
</P>
<P>
   What's the problem? You've become so used to people loving your
shows, watching your shows and showering your shows with awards
that you've lost your way. How else to explain Sunday night's awful
season opener of ``The Practice'' and the arrival this season of
``Snoops,'' the closest thing to ``Charlie's Angels'' we've seen in
years.
</P>
<P>
   Usually I like your work, and I think your writing _ lovingly
and laboriously scribbled long-hand on legal pads _ is often
brilliant. Nobody is better at crafting quirky plots and
multidimensional characters. ``Picket Fences'' had its moments, and
in the early going, ``Chicago Hope'' was superb. ``The Practice''
and ``Ally McBeal'' have become appointment viewingfor the adults
in my house.
</P>
<P>
   Last season's cliffhanger for ``The Practice'' was one of the
decade's best _ loaded with suspense, sparkling with humor and
chock full of warm-hearted sentiment. When Lindsay was stabbed in
the opening segment, fans were riveted, peeking at the scene
through trembling fingers.
</P>
<P>
   But this season's opener was disgusting. We wanted to know if
the nun-impersonating George Vogelman really hacked Lindsay or not.
Instead, we got a nauseating case involving Henry Winkler as a man
with a sexual fetish involving cockroaches, masturbation and a
murder victim with grape jelly in her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Snoops?'' What in the world were you thinking? High-tech
gadgets, leather-clad women with pounds of lip gloss are not the
stuff of great drama. They're not even the stuff of mildly
entertaining drama.
</P>
<P>
   That new half-hour version of ``Ally'' isn't such a swell move,
either. It smacks of greed, pure and simple. Hour-long series are
difficult to sell into syndication, so you're slapping together a
re-edited half-hour version to make a few more millions. Shouldn't
you be spending your time working on less disgusting scripts for
``The Practice?''
</P>
<P>
   When writer-producers reach a certain level of mega-power in
Hollywood, as you have _ with five series on the air this season
and two recent best drama and best comedy Emmys in your mansion _
they can do just about anything. You're a 10-ton gorilla if ever
there was one. ABC executives call you a ``brand-name producer,''
meaning even the common couch potato knows you and will watch a
show just because your name is on it. Network execs admit they are
predisposed to buy your pilots and then let you do anything that
strikes your fancy with them.
</P>
<P>
   But just because you can do anything doesn't mean you should.
Steven Bochco, lauded for his groundbreaking ``Hill Street Blues''
and ``L.A. Law,'' got such a serious case of Big Head Disease that
he assumed, correctly it turned out, that the networks would put on
any old thing he concocted. Hence came the dreadful police musical
``Cop Rock'' in 1990 and the odoriferous ``Public Morals,'' a cop
sitcom, in '96. The original pilot for ``Public Morals'' was so
crude it contained an appalling word for the female anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers, it turned out, did not have the same low standards as
network executives. Within a few months ``Cop Rock'' was gone, and
within a few weeks ``Public Morals'' disappeared, too, because
nobody was watching.
</P>
<P>
   You started in Hollywood as a writer for Bochco's ``L.A. Law.''
He's been your mentor, so learn from his mistakes. Don't
underestimate your audience. Don't assume that any old thing you
throw on the screen is art. And don't insult us by thinking we
can't tell the difference between the brilliant work you're capable
of and the shameful stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
