<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hope fades for quake victims
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After almost a week of searching for people buried by
a massive earthquake, Taiwanese officials are focusing on the
survivors. More than 100,000 people were left homeless by the
7.6-magnitude earthquake that struck the Southeast Asian island
last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some people said it could take months, if not years, for their
lives to return to normal. ``We're hoping the government will help
us rebuild our homes,'' said farmer Chen Jung, who lost his home.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese officials said last week more than 2,000 people were
killed in the quake, more than 8,000 were injured and hundreds were
still trapped or missing.
</P>
<P>
   STUDY MEASURES VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows TV shows and movies can be violent, but a new
report tells just how prevalent it is.
</P>
<P>
   If you watched all 50 of last year's top-grossing films, you saw
more than 2,300 acts of violence, according to a study from the
Center for Media and Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   TV programming, both network and cable, averaged six scenes of
serius violence per episode of fiction series. And most movies and
TV series failed to show the physical or emotional harm that would
result from serious violence.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found music videos and feature films averaged a
scene of serious violence every four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA GIRL WINS NEW MODEL CONTEST
</P>
<P>
   First Augusta, then New York, now Paris. Martinez, Ga., teen
Erin McQuatters went from doing her very first modeling job last
spring to the cover of a special section in Seventeen magazine's
September issue. Now, the 14-year-old winner of the Chanel New
Model of the Year Contest is off to soak up all of the haute
couture (French for high fashion) that Paris has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought all of (the contest's eight finalists) had a really
good chance of winning,'' said Erin, who went to New York for the
finals. ``I was surprised, but I'm glad I won.''
</P>
<P>
   She's going to Paris in October, where she'll be treated to
front-row seats at a Chanel fall fashion show and a $1,000 shopping
spree.
</P>
<P>
   PANDAS DELAYED BY COMMUNIST CELEBRATION
</P>
<P>
   Yang-Yang and Lun-Lun are going to be late-late.
</P>
<P>
   But the delay for Zoo Atlanta's panda pair from China is
supposed to be only a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The pandas were scheduled to arrive Oct. 7. However, since the
Chinese are busy preparing for the 50th anniversary of the founding
of the Communist People's Republic of China, they can't meet the
date. Now, the pandas are expected to arrive in late October.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, you can ask questions about the exhibit and see
a video of Lun-Lun at www.accessatlanta.com/pandas/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
