A7330 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-TV-DOCTOR-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      09-27 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DOCTOR-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOW DOCTORS GIVE RETURNING PROGRAM A MAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To the casual observer, the filming of a typical
television show is a slow, repetitive process, unless you happen to
be tagging along with the second unit of the CBS action hour
``Martial Law.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crew responsible for fight scenes and outdoor footage of
the show _ which kicks off (literally) its second season at 8
tonight on Channel 5 _ the second unit moves at least as quickly as
Sammo Hung, ``Martial Law's'' big-boned but unusually nimble star.
</P>
<P>
   Last season the second unit got a lot of credit for bringing the
excitement and tongue-in-cheek flair of the Hong Kong action genre
of films to an American TV series.
</P>
<P>
   But it's what came out of the first unit back at the studio,
where most of the dialogue and interior scenes were filmed, that
concerned executives at CBS. As entertaining as Hung could be to
watch _ backflipping off cars, beating foes senseless with a rubber
hose _ it was nearly as painful to see him attempt office chatter
in broken English with various miscast supporting players.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a popular but troubled program, the network ordered
radical changes to ``Martial Law.'' Those changes may alienate some
viewers at first but CBS believes they will ultimately make the
show appealing to a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   Show-doctoring is a trend. All told, six broadcast networks
introduced just 35 new shows this season, the lowest total in
years. Industry observers cite two key reasons: more hourlong shows
and a dearth of new ideas . So instead, networks are choosing to
overhaul some of their middling programs rather than risk adding
more new shows, 70 percent of which, on average, fail.
</P>
<P>
   At NBC the network ordered surgery on three underperforming
comedies: ``Suddenly Susan,'' ``Jesse'' and ``Veronica's Closet.''
The latter two were actually top-10 shows last season, but only by
virtue of being hammocked between ``Friends,'' ``Frasier'' and
``ER'' on Thursday nights. Each show lost a large part of its
lead-in audience as the season went on.
</P>
<P>
   All three comedies hired new executive producers this summer to
run day-to-day operations. They in turn hired new cast members and
concocted new storylines to take their characters down unforeseen _
and presumably more amusing _ paths.
</P>
<P>
   For NBC Entertainment president Garth Ancier, the overhauls
became a necessity after concluding there were only two new
comedies ready for the fall season: ``Stark Raving Mad'' (which NBC
was contractually obliged to put on the air) and ``The Mike
O'Malley Show'' (which made its premiere Tuesday to disastrous
ratings).
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision I had to make,'' Ancier said, ``was, do we have
less comedy on NBC, which generally has been the heaviest comedy
network, or do we fix some of the shows that are not particularly
doing well and nurture them along for a year or two?''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Suddenly Susan,'' the fix involved pairing former ``Monty
Python'' player Eric Idle with the show's lead, Brooke Shields. On
``Jesse,'' new producers came over from two NBC hits ``Friends''
and ``Just Shoot Me'' and decided that Jesse (Christina Applegate)
should enroll in nursing school. On ``Veronica's Closet,'' the
incoming producers (also from ``Friends'') killed off Kirstie
Alley's love interest from last season.
</P>
<P>
   NBC also had to replace the lead of its Saturday-night thriller
``Profiler'' after Ally Walker asked out of her contract. Former
``Melrose Place'' star Jamie Luner takes Walker's place Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Other shows being retooled are CBS' ``Chicago Hope'' (with half
the medical staff replaced) and ABC's ``Two Guys and a Girl''
(goodbye pizza place).
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Martial Law,'' CBS had debuted the show last
fall with low expectations on a safe night (Saturdays, when
viewership is low and CBS is strong). Another show, ``Touched by an
Angel,'' also was incubated on Saturdays (five years ago) and is
now a top-five show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a kind of a natural evolution of a series,'' insists
CBS Entertainment president Nancy Tellem. ``It has a very solid
core audience. We wanted to build on that, and that's what we've
done in making adjustments to the show. Lee and Bill took it over
and they have some really fresh ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Goldberg and Bill Rabkin, the new executive producers, saw a
lot they didn't like last season on ``Martial Law,'' starting with
the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Two leads, Tom Wright and Louis Mandylor, were dropped. A new
female lead, Gretchen Egolf, was cast to play a by-the-book
supervisor. The other female lead, Kelly Hu, got a new wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   As Rabkin explains, ``Kelly was doing these amazing spreads in
Maxim and other magazines, proving herself one of the sexiest women
on the planet, and yet they'd turn on our show and see her dressed
like an insurance salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, the producers went to work on Hung and his partner, former
talk-show host Arsenio Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arsenio started out as a publicist-turned-cop, which sort of
emasculated him from the start,'' Rabkin says. ``We wanted to make
Arsenio his equal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not so much of a wuss,'' Goldberg adds.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest changes concerned their rotund star and the
storylines involving him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt the show spotlighted Sammo's wonderful
skills, but it did so in a conventional, `T.J. Hooker' format,''
says Goldberg, referring to the 1980s William Shatner cop series.
``We wanted to come in and create a show as big and funny as Sammo
Hung and his fight sequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories they were telling last year were the kind of
stories you could find on `Nash Bridges.' We wanted stories that
you could only find on `Martial Law.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Goldberg cites the episode that will air tonight.
In ``Sammo Blammo'' Hung finds himself attached to a bomb that will
go off if he stops moving. (``It's like the movie `Speed,' only
Sammo's the bus,'' Goldberg says.)
</P>
<P>
   The producers also decided Hung needed to lighten up _ referring
not to his heft but his personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were making Sammo out to be a Detective Sipowicz,'' says
Goldberg, referring to Dennis Franz's character on ``NYPD Blue'' on
ABC. ``No one tunes in to `Martial Law' to see Sammo interrogate a
perp.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the set, Hung says he'll act more like a Chinese cop
resisting the ways of American law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the conflict,'' he says. ``I have my way, Terrell
(Hall's character) has his way, Gretchen has her own way.''
</P>
<P>
   I only get a few minutes at a time with Hung, since the second
unit is changing scenes so quickly. We're on the 28th floor of an
office building in downtown L.A., where the crew is methodically
shooting scenes for another episode in which Hung goes undercover
to bust a burglary ring. Set up, rehearse, take one, take two, pack
up, move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I make a movie, I make one fighting scene a month,'' Hung
tells me during another mini-interview. ``Takes 10 days, 15 days.
Now, takes only three hours, four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The second unit just came off a two-day shoot aboard a train in
which it filmed 138 separate scenes, including 75 on one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``No show I've worked on has been this ambitious, bar none,''
says Jeff Cadiente, the show's stunt coordinator and an 18-year
stunt veteran. ``We're doing feature film stunts on a TV
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our action sequences are better than any light-saber fight in
`The Phantom Menace,' '' says Goldberg. ``You don't need to spend
$7.50 and camp-out overnights. You just need to turn on your TV on
Saturday nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Hung, for one, is counting on it. After more than 25 years in
Hong Kong cinema (he had a part in Bruce Lee's final film in 1973),
the martial-arts star plans to hone his language skills and start a
feature-film career in the States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope everything this season is better than last season,'' he
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
