 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Tuesday, September
28, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is available on Tuesdays after 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0928 _ Wireless begets more wireless. And
technology companies are scrambling to find a way to exploit that
growth. (Kannel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes four
1-column color photos of a cellular phone, Palm computer, laptop
computer and a pager.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ While the Web does not offer a replacement for
college campus visits and sessions with your banker, it can be a
valuable tool in selecting a college. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1 column color sig of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS _ Every state has at least one whipping boy, a
neighboring state that serves as the butt of jokes. The Great
Mobile Homes of Mississippi, www.kelleys.org/mhomes/, is the Web
site that takes aim at Mississippi. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS _ If you want a five-channel home theater sound system,
but you'd rather not clutter your room with big speakers, you might
want to take a look at the Lifestyle 30 Series II, the most compact
home theater system made by Bose Corp. (Cumming, Dayton Daily News)
Art includes 1-column color photo of a couple listening to stereo.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ Record companies are finally dipping their toes into
the uncharted waters of digital music. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 6-pica color illustration of a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   WEBHEALTH _ In the hyperkinetic universe of Internet companies,
health care sites may be the fastest-rising stars. Young startups
such as Austin's Drkoop.com and healthanswers.com are fighting to
be your doctor's office on the Web and grab a share of the $1
trillion Americans spend on health care every year. They are
drawing hoards of money and the endorsement of some of the most
trusted names in medicine. But how useful are these sites?
Consider: They are mostly run by people who don't have medical
training. They offer frequent disclaimers urging that you seek a
doctor's advice if you have questions about a medical condition.
Most of them offer the same warehouses of well-known, general
information on diseases, first aid and prevention. Wire stories and
press releases from General Mills and Gatorade are presented as
``medical news,'' and fluffy stories on herbal remedies and keeping
cool in the summer abound. And in chat rooms and support groups,
Web surfers dispense health advice to each
</P>
<P>
   other without oversight. (Park/Keefe, Austin American-Statesman)
50. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WEBADVICE _ So just what kind of advice do you get off of Web
health sites? We search the sites and pose questions about a
half-dozen maladies and see what kind of advice we get. Do the
sites have conflicting advice? Do they guide us to companies trying
to sell us stuff? Or are their ideas simply wrong? We see.
(Cocks/Keefe, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-NOSE _ FAIRBORN, Ohio _ It may not take much to figure out
that hog manure stinks, but Wright State University Assistant
Professor Ricardo Guiterrez-Osuna has an electronic nose that
objectively and precisely measures such odors. (Bischoff, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GADGETS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ A look at Hasbro Games' new
hand-held games, including six designed to be played by players 8
years old or younger. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE _ Weekly centerpiece on personal technology,
from products to trends to advancements. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Dayton Daily News, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Stop worrying so much about upgrading
and changing your computer. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: Amazon offers a
peek into what other folks _ from boardrooms to college classrooms
_ are reading. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ News on Apple and its products. This week: Word 98
is being sold for a third of its regular selling price through a
new offer. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN _ A regular series of columns for advanced
computer users. This week: Checking the connections in my in-home
computer network. (Yandel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-SHOWS _ MILAN _ Atlanta Journal-Constitution fashion
reporter A. Scott Walton reports from Fashion Week in Milan. Combo
of main runway revue, notes and occasional postcards. (Walton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   BACKPACKS _ Backpacks are getting heavier _ books are bigger and
kids have to haul more of them around. How much should a backpack
weigh? What happens if it weighs too much? (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   CELLULITE _ The skinny on the new herbal remedy that supposed to
make dimpley legs smooth again. What the experts and studies say
about whether it works. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   EATING-DISORDERS _ Q&AMP;A with Geneen Roth, author of ``When You
Eat at the Refrigerator, Pull Up a chair,'' noting eating disorders
expert who will hold a workshop in Atlanta Oct. 8-9. (Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12. WITH PHOTO (mug of Roth).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EATING-DISORDERS
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-WEB _ Internet health site: German Commission information
on herbal products, the best available, can be downloaded from the
internet for a limited period of time. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-GARTH _ A review of Garth Brooks' new CD, ``The Life of
Chris Gaines.'' It's couched as greatest hits of Chris Gaines,
Brooks' alter persona about whom he plans to make a film titled
``The Lamb.'' Grade: D. (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
10.
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY _ Dr. Hap Lecrone's weekly psychology column.
This week: Child abuse. (Lecrone, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-MCBEAL _ Review of new half hour of ``Ally McBeal''. (Kloer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTY-BALL _ Interview with Alan Ball, the first-time
big-screen writer for critically acclaimed ``American Beauty.''
Ball graduated from Marietta High School in metro Atlanta and could
well get an Oscar nomination for his screenplay. (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN _ Observations on the television industry from
a leading commentator. This week: Watch out, David Kelley. You're
catching a case of Big Head Disease. (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
