<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7339 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MOVIE-SPACEY-KANSAS-K     09-27 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SPACEY-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVIN SPACEY RECASTS HIS CAREER WITH COMPLEX ROLE IN `BEAUTY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ ``I believe that you are in control of your own
destiny,'' Kevin Spacey said. ``It may just take awhile to convince
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider us convinced.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the 40-year-old actor's talent is in dispute. The
man already has a Tony Award and an Oscar on his mantel. And now
he's riding a wave of critical acclaim for his starring role, with
Annette Bening, in the film ``American Beauty,'' which opened
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But not too long ago Spacey feared that his movie career was in
a rut, that he'd played one too many of the evil, sleazy,
manipulative creeps who populate films like ``Consenting Adults,''
``Seven,'' ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' ``Swimming With Sharks'' and
``The Usual Suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   His answer was to blow off any more roles that smacked of that
sinister persona and hold out for something that seemed completely
different. When the movie offers weren't to his liking he turned to
his longstanding ``rejuvenation program'' _ he did a stage play.
And not just any play. He tackled the role of Hickey in a London
production of Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh,'' a 41/2-hour
workout that is the acting equivalent of the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   And then in the summer of '98, during the ``Iceman'' run, Spacey
was sent a copy of the screenplay for ``American Beauty.'' He knew
he'd found what he was looking for in the character of Lester
Burnham. Lester is a suburban drone who contends with a job he
hates, a marriage without sex and a daughter who thinks he's the
world's biggest creep. Moreover, Lester entertains sexual fantasies
about a high school cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read it I recognized that this story was filled with
the concerns that lots of people find themselves thinking,'' the
actor said, relaxing recently in T-shirt and jeans in a deserted
hotel ballroom at the Toronto International Film Festival. ``We all
recognize the desire to break free of that kind of stifling
existence, to just one time experience life to its fullest. The
emotional terrain is something we all recognize, whether we'll
admit it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacey's performance in the film is so funny, sad and ultimately
uplifting that it was virtually impossible to find a critic at
Toronto who didn't think he'd get an Oscar nomination. The actor
said he was gratified by the festival kudos but admits he's lousy
at judging his own work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see one of my films for the first time, it's a very odd
experience. I don't see the movie. Instead I remember the day we
shot that scene, or ask why they cut at that point, or wonder if my
best scene is still going to be in the movie. It takes three or
four viewings before I can even approach it simply as a film
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling ``American Beauty'' the ``richest time I've ever had
working on a film,'' Spacey credited Alan Ball's multileveled
screenplay and the work of Sam Mendes, a first-time film director
but an old hand at creating hits for the theater (including the
current revival of ``Cabaret'' and ``The Blue Room'').
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked into this experience with a three-week rehearsal
period utilized brilliantly by Sam. It enabled me to find the level
of love that Lester once shared with his wife'' _ played by Bening
_ ``before it started crumbling. That was crucial to the film's
final moments, when Lester has to summon up all those lost
emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Still angered by a 2-year-old Esquire article in which he was
described as gay, Spacey bristles when questions veer away from his
professional work: ``I never discuss my personal life.'' (For the
record, he was born in New Jersey, grew up in Chatsworth, Calif.,
and went to New York to study acting at the Juilliard School, where
he also got his start with Joseph Papp's Public Theater. He is
unmarried and shares his home outside New York City with two dogs.)
</P>
<P>
   But ask about the acting process and the words pour out. Spacey
particularly enjoys the period of discovery when he's learning
about a character and preparing for a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theater work is much closer to my life experience than
anything I've done in films,'' he said. ``And Lester is closer to
the kind of men I've played in the theater _ interesting and
complex. It was the sort of role that kept me moving to places I'd
never been before. For an actor, that's true joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I much prefer acting on the stage to film. As good as
a film performance may be, that's as good as it's ever gonna be.
With theater, though, you can grow, experiment, change. Every night
is a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' was shot in the break between ``Iceman's''
London and Broadway runs, and Spacey found that Hickey and Lester
rubbed off on each other.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Iceman' was the finest experience I've ever had in the
theater. And in fact I couldn't have done `American Beauty' without
it. First, `Iceman' may be full of tragic elements, but it reminds
us that many of the most tragic things in life are just funny. That
was something I kept in mind throughout the making of this film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither `Iceman' nor `American Beauty' is downbeat despite the
seriousness of the themes they share, especially the search for
some kind of fellowship and humanity. In the end both Hickey and
Lester achieve an inner peace that surprises the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I returned to `Iceman' after making the movie, I really
believe that my Hickey was deeper and richer than before. There was
some Lester in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its art-film sensibilities, ``American Beauty'' was
produced by DreamWorks SKG, the Steven Spielberg-run studio best
known for releases like ``Deep Impact,'' ``Prince of Egypt'' and
``Saving Private Ryan.'' According to Spacey, Spielberg read Ball's
screenplay and announced, ``Let's make it and not water it down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This film shows incredible maturity and honesty in dealing
with hot-button issues, and DreamWorks should be applauded for
tackling it,'' Spacey said. ``It's a watershed because it
establishes the studio not just as a place where you make big
commercial movies but where you can also display an independent
frame of mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
