<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7341 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-THEATER-NIELSEN-KANSA     09-27 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NIELSEN-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McTAVISH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The goofy ``Naked Gun'' guy as dramatic criminal lawyer Clarence
Darrow?
</P>
<P>
   Don't giggle, although fans of Leslie Nielsen can be forgiven if
that's their first reaction upon learning that the deadpan funnyman
in ``Airplane'' and ``The Naked Gun'' movies is performing
``Clarence Darrow,'' a one-man play devoted to the legendary
defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen has encountered audience laughter before in the role of
Darrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened up in Canada about three years ago,'' he said
recently by phone from his hacienda-style home in Paradise Valley,
Ariz. ``They were laughing in crazy places. I realized it had to be
because they expected me to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nielsen won't be thinking about hearing titters at
inappropriate times when he takes the stage as Darrow.
</P>
<P>
   In fact he picked the stage to lessen the likelihood of
audiences connecting inadvertently with his comedic persona. ``If
people get a chance to see directly into my eyes, as they do on the
big screen, it tends to be easier for them to remember the dumb and
stupid guy, and that does provoke laughter. But on stage I'm
removed, and you can't really see my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless his clothes fall off or a flower pot lands on his head,
audiences shouldn't have any trouble getting into Nielsen as
Darrow. The 73-year-old actor, who owns the play by David W.
Rintels, based on Irving Stone's book, Clarence Darrow for the
Defense, will be completely into his character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I supposed I would like to be like Clarence Darrow,'' Nielsen
said. ``I'm happy enough with who I am, but he had this incredible
ability to speak on any subject. Usually in debates he would take
the con side of the debate. He enjoyed facing, as he said, 500 to
1,000 people who were waiting for him to fall on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Utilizing his love of high drama, Darrow made his lasting mark
as an eloquent defender of society's underdogs in courts across the
land, beginning in the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of Darrow, courtrooms were an important form of
theater,'' said Doug Linder, a Darrowphile and professor of law at
the University of Missouri-Kansas City. ``People didn't have movies
to go to. They didn't have television shows to watch. What was
going on in courtrooms was the most compelling drama they could
get. And Darrow appealed to that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clarence Darrow'' exploits its namesake's penchant for broadly
passionate and poetic argument, including Darrow's famous defense
in 1925 of Tennessee science teacher John Scopes, who violated a
state law making it a crime to teach the theory of evolution in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   This summer the Kansas Board of Education decided to remove the
mandatory teaching of evolution in Kansas, making it possible for
schools to avoid the subject in the classroom altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen's take?
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrow would expect that,'' the actor said. ``He didn't hold
out too much hope for mankind in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrow summed up the Scopes trial, Nielsen said, ``when he said,
`If you can ban the teaching of evolution in the schools, then the
next year you can ban the teaching of religion in your church, and
after that you can burn newspapers and books. He said, `If you can
do the one, you can do the other.' And that's the point.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the point of Nielsen tackling stage drama when he
continues to have a lucrative comedy film career? The desire to
stretch himself. If anything, making people laugh has given him
greater confidence in all areas of his craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're doing insane comedy and you find out after the
smoke clears that you're still alive, that being an idiot and
absolutely dumb and stupid and really embarrassingly wacko didn't
hurt you at all, it means that you've broadened your horizons,'' he
said. ``And there's no reason why you can't carry that freedom into
your exploration of any character, including Clarence Darrow.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades Nielsen specialized in serious portrayals, dating
back to such 1950s leading-man movie roles as the spaceship
commander in ``Forbidden Planet'' and the available male in ``Tammy
and the Bachelor.'' In 1971 he was the cruise ship captain in ``The
Poseidon Adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cast as an authority figure because I looked like it,''
he said. ``And maybe I went that direction as a young man because
it was a form of protection. It kept people from talking to me too
much, or they might have found out how dumb I really am.''
</P>
<P>
   But his career and life changed when he agreed to do a
self-parody of his screen image in the 1980 hit comedy
``Airplane!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always been doing comedy,'' Nielsen said. ``I just never
knew that the drama I was doing was comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s and '90s, its been a steady stream of silly films
for Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the comedies that I do, I'm having fun,'' he said. That
makes it harder, Nielsen said, ``to grind away at yourself in
drama. But you grind away because you're trying to find out what
... you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month Nielsen completed shooting the comedy ``The Big Bang
3,'' due in theaters next summer. What happened to the first two
``Bangs''?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just simply said, `Well, we didn't like either one of them,
so we went on to No. 3,' '' he said, kidding. ``It's turning loose
a dumb and stupid law officer, but in this case turning him loose
in space as he investigates a dire plot by the alien to take over
the world. He creates all kinds of chaos as he is confronted by the
new technologies of science and so on, none of which he's equipped
to handle at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does Nielsen place himself on the space-time continuum of
comedy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know,'' he said. ``The only thing I'm happy about
is that I'm on the continuum. It dawned on me one day: `Leslie, you
have been part of ``Airplane'' and ``Naked Gun,'' and they are part
of American motion-picture comedy and will be through the history
of motion pictures.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet because of his comedy success, Nielsen concedes it might be
beyond his box-office reach to land another dramatic film role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be difficult. It would depend on the role. But I do
`Darrow.' My choice today is to have fun and to do things that I
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, being funny on screen has kept him young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm only 18,'' Nielsen said. ``I tell you, I loved
`The Naked Gun' because, as far as the younger people were
concerned who were seeing the pictures, I wasn't over 30 and never
would be to them. And that's quite a compliment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
