<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7347 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FAMILY-SHAREBED-KANSA     09-27 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-SHAREBED-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUST BABIES SLEEP SOLO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For parents of babies and toddlers it's an ongoing debate: Is it
good to allow your baby to sleep in bed with you?
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say co-sleeping fosters trust, intimacy and
self-assuredness.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say babies taught to sleep on their own learn
self-calming skills and self-reliance. Babies who require Mommy or
Daddy to fall asleep develop a bad habit that's hard to break and
is hard on everyone.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   University of Notre Dame anthropologist James McKenna has a
suggestion: Chill out.
</P>
<P>
   Children's temperaments are as individual as the dreams they
dream, he said in a recent interview. What's ideal for one child
may not be for another. What works today may not work tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake. McKenna, who will discuss his 18 years of
research on mother//baby sleep patterns in November at the annual
meeting of the American Anthropological Association in Chicago, is
a strong proponent of what's known as co-sleeping, bed-sharing or
the family bed.
</P>
<P>
   In his studies, he has videotaped and physiologically monitored
more than 110 pairs of breast-feeding mothers and their babies,
ages 2 months to 5 months old. That age often is associated with
SIDS, or sudden infant death syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Among his findings: Co-sleeping babies generally are placed in
safer positions; babies position themselves to look at their
mothers through 90 percent of the night; co-sleeping babies
breast-feed more; babies cry less and sleep more even though they
stir more and spend less time in the kind of deep sleep most
associated with SIDS.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna also supports co-sleeping for older babies and toddlers.
Mother and child co-sleeping is standard in the vast majority of
non-Western cultures, he says. And it's more common in the United
States than most people imagine or admit.
</P>
<P>
   One 1988 study examining sleep patterns in New York and
Cleveland showed that 19 percent of white, 59 percent of black and
26 percent of Hispanic parents allowed babies or toddlers to sleep
with them all night or part of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Western cultures have allowed technology to be
substituted for mother and baby contact, biology is the same as it
was 10,000 years ago,'' McKenna said. ``Babies still need that
contact and comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also recognizes that when it comes to babies and family
sleeping arrangements, ``there are very few purists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents try about everything,'' McKenna said. ``Rarely is
there just one kind of sleeping arrangement that works for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas some babies sleep in their cribs all night, others sleep
in their parents' bed. Whereas some fall asleep in their cribs and
wake in the bed, others start in bed and wake in the crib. As
children grow, preferences change. They go through phases.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna's goal, he said, isn't to convince all parents to bring
their young children into bed with them. Some parents find it's
just too hard to get a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But he does want them to not feel guilty or think they're
harming their child if they allow co-sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of scare tactics about what happens when
children sleep with their parents,'' McKenna said. ``They are not
based on science.''
</P>
<P>
   In his best-selling 1985 book, Solve Your Child's Sleep
Problems, physician Richard Ferber, director of the Center for
Pediatric Sleep Disorders at Boston's Children's Hospital, writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Although taking your child into bed with you for a night or
two may be reasonable if he is ill or very upset about something,
for the most part this is not a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferber provides a list of reasons. It disturbs everyone's sleep,
he says. It may cause problems when parents want to leave the child
with a baby sitter, thus interfering with their social lives. But
his chief argument against co-sleeping is this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleeping alone is an important part of his learning to be able
to separate from you without anxiety and to see himself as an
independent individual. This process is important to this early
psychological development. In addition, sleeping in your bed can
make your child feel confused and anxious rather than relaxed and
reassured. Even a young toddler may find this repeated experience
overly stimulating. If you allow him to crawl in between you and
your spouse, in a sense separating the two of you, he may feel too
powerful and become worried. He wants the reassurance of knowing
that you are in control and that you will do what is best for him
regardless of his demands. If you show you cannot do this and let
him act out his impulses, he may become frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   If, for instance, one partner is away for the night and a child
is allowed in the bed, Ferber writes, a child may feel more fearful
because he may think he is replacing one of the parents and may
cause them to separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ever do, he may feel responsible,'' Ferber writes.
</P>
<P>
   But McKenna thinks this is bunk based on opinion and conjecture,
not science. Indeed, no studies show that children who co-sleep
turn out to be any less independent than those who sleep on their
own. In his ongoing studies of Notre Dame students _ those raised
in co-sleeping homes and those not _ McKenna has found nothing to
support a lack of independence or later sleep difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studies that are coming out now are showing just the
opposite,'' he said. ``Babies who sleep routinely with their
parents have fewer tantrums during the day, handle stress better
than solitary sleeping babies and, on average, get average or
higher reports from teachers and parents on their behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts have weighed in on the subject:
</P>
<P>
   - Ed Christophersen, a professor of pediatrics and an expert in
child behavior at Children's Mercy Hospital in Kansas City, has a
mixed view. He thinks it is important for infants to learn to
soothe themselves to sleep. If he has any problem with bed-sharing,
it is that too many parents rely on it to get their children to
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see all the time is parents with no intention of having
a family bed,'' he said. ``They just don't know what else to do
because they can't get the kid to go to bed. They are not thinking
of the best interest of the child; they are trying to minimize
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ferber, Christophersen thinks the practice doesn't do kids
any favors. He thinks a child's inability to calm himself may cause
difficulties later on. ``The way kids learn self-calming skills,''
he said, ``is by being given the opportunity to calm themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But overall, ``If you want to have a family bed, I don't think
it is unreasonable,'' he said. ``Anything that people will tell you
are the benefits of a family bed, I'm buying.''
</P>
<P>
   - Chicago physician Marc Weissbluth, author of Healthy Sleep
Habits, Happy Child, said: ``The family bed is not good or bad. It
is a family decision in the same way bathing together or not is a
family decision. Just as family bathing has nothing to do with
cleanliness, the family bed in and of itself has nothing to do with
sleep quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is the sleep quality of the child. The sleep
quality of the child is independent of whether the child is
sleeping with the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents, of course, may not like it. Partners may find it
interferes with their intimacy. Weissbluth understands and thinks
the family bed could become a pain if a child can't sleep unless
one or both parents are in bed.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, Weissbluth thinks these are family choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no problem,'' Weissbluth said, ``as long as both
parents want to sleep with their children and their children's
natural sleep schedules are respected. Families have to decide
what's best for their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cultures, the family bed is the norm. And these
children have no problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
