<HEADLINE>
GOOSENECK LAMPS PROVIDE FLEXIBLE LIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The most common light for home tasks or reading
is the gooseneck lamp, named for its flexible neck.
</P>
<P>
   These lamps have been around since the Victorian era and were
also popular in contemporary rooms of the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are so handy, they can be used in any room in the
house, from a home office to a nightstand. They are most commonly
used next to a favorite reading chair and have been a dorm room or
bedroom staple for students.
</P>
<P>
   If table space is scarce, look to a gooseneck floor lamp, but
even the tabletop varieties take up very little space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gooseneck lamps can be streamlined to fit just about any
decor,'' said Denise Maurer, an interior designer in Troy. ``It's a
very utilitarian device.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Trawinski, branch manager of Wolberg Electric in
Schenectady, said the desk lamps cost $15 and up, and gooseneck
floor lamp prices start at $75.
</P>
<P>
   They can come with three-way bulbs and dimmers, and in a variety
of colors. ``You used to only be able to get them in a chrome
finish, but now you can find them in black, white, ivory, red and
brass,'' Trawinski said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of fire safety issues, take care not to place the lamp,
especially one with a halogen bulb, too close to objects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
