<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-VERMONT-AUTUMN-HNS &LR;      09-27 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-AUTUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS NONSEASON, LEMONADE DAYS GIVE WAY TO CIDER NIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GOTTLIEB  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DOVER, Vt. _ The leaves are green still and give mere hints
of fading, but people have been heating with wood for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of September, the morning chill pulls away fast in
southern Vermont and the sun takes over for most of the day,
creating a strong imitation of July. By late afternoon, though, the
sun has dipped below the peaks here, and the autumn part of the day
begins.
</P>
<P>
   Cold air seems to arrive instantly. White birches turn ashen,
blackening pines close in and I wonder whether I will ever see the
bears that my neighbors keep talking about before they _ the bears,
that is _ retreat for the winter. The lawn-mower drone of a few
weeks ago has been replaced by a chain-saw rip _ someone rushing to
finish a house construction maybe, or cutting wood for sale.
</P>
<P>
   On the way here, I had stopped for firewood, being carefully
vague with my order.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, I did not say anything about a ``cord,'' the only
unit of measurement I have heard of, or small logs would have
filled the front porch and living room of my new house. I got by
with ``a few arm loads'' for $10 and wondered what part of a cord
that amounted to so I could request it next time.
</P>
<P>
   Heading north on a favorite stretch of Route 100 outside
Wilmington, where the road swirls ahead like a paint brush
displaying the pastures and mountains to come, I was tempted to
stop at one of the stands advertising ``Maple Syrup'' in red paint.
But I know I'd never use the stuff. The onset of fall just makes
you want to stock up on things before they are gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most beautiful time of year but it's sad,'' said Paul
DiBenedetto, who sees cars rush past year-round from Left Bank
Antiques, the well-appointed shop at the four corners in
Wilmington. ``Summer's gone and now you think about the year gone
by. You didn't climb any mountains, you didn't fly a plane, you
didn't fly a parachute, not that I intended to, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   The sign on Route 9 welcomes visitors who have driven into the
mountains, coming from Bennington to the Mount Snow-Haystack
Region, ``a four-season resort.'' But this time of year would not
be included in any seasonal category and it's my favorite of the
nonseasons, a mellow cider to July's lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   DiBenedetto says we're into one of three or four brief lulls of
the year, but it seems to me the area is showing a bit more spirit
than it did a month ago, when the ground was parched and older
Floridians, frankly, were starting to look bored here in southern
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The Deerfield River, nearly barren until recently, is spritzing
through its rocky beds, and yellowed cow fields are suddenly
verdant thanks to rain. The trees themselves, showing an occasional
spike of orange, are greener than during the height of summer, when
they looked burned. Proprietors seem to be working on their ski
shops, yet there are many weeks left to hike and bike.
</P>
<P>
   Already, traffic gets clogged by traveling homes called ``Four
Winds'' or ``Coachman,'' and I can't be sure whether the explorers
driving them are getting a jump on leaf-peeping or getting out
before the frost.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Left Bank Antiques, a British couple on a bus tour asks
directions to a grocery. I ask where they're going and they tell me
``back to Vermont.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, I had come here for ski weekends, rushing to and
from the area I always considered the New York part of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, fate delivered me an actual residence, my first chance
to join other urban types who play country part time. All summer I
had been filling the house to make it livable and leaving again.
</P>
<P>
   During nearly weekly, neurotic trips to the Home Depot across
the state line, in Albany, N.Y., I'd wonder what I'd do if the
Vermont place was ever completed, and this always scared me. That
time has come this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Now, driving to the house, I pass Hayseed Gifts, the Pampered
Palate and shops selling plastic Canada geese and imagine that I
won't be spending much time at these places. But it's difficult to
imagine where I may actually land in the pecking order of tourists
and the people who wait on them.
</P>
<P>
   I've never be an insider here, where to qualify you'd have to be
native. And, I've been warned, the locals have labels for just
about everyone else. Would I be a ``weekender,'' a ``flatlander,''
or, God forbid, a ``conehead,'' a term of derision that either tars
people from Connecticut or people who wear pointy ski hats. Either
way, I'm nailed.
</P>
<P>
   With very little exploring, it's clear that the area's far more
rural than I'd have imagined during college forays to the ski
slopes and condos. Though situated squarely in a metropolitan
Boston and New York City resort, my little house is on the cusps of
the great Green Mountain National Forest, where the Long Trail and
the Appalachian Trail were conceived and mapped out.
</P>
<P>
   The trails and seasonal dirt roads are as rural and sometimes
barely passable as you'd expect to encounter in the Rockies, and
packed with through-hikers with stories of their elaborate treks.
The last time I hiked here, one of the only times so far, the air
was summery on the bottom, but the winds at the top of Stratton
Mountain blew in with such force and chill that snow felt like the
next step.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby my house this time of year, the mostly empty homes,
California geometric and New England salt box-inspired, are great
monuments to their part-time occupants. Firewood has been delivered
and stacked tight outside some and ``for rent'' signs have gone up
on others, a select few offering seductive views of Mount Snow's
North face.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of a string of vacant homes on Lower Handle Road,
there's a year-round neighbor who introduces me to her chickens,
her horse, her dogs, her kittens, her tractor and her husband. She
insists on giving me a dozen just-laid brown eggs. All summer I'd
never known her spread was there. As Paul DiBenedetto said, you
tend to notice more this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you hear the crows gathering. I can hear them in the
early morning, I guess, preparing to leave,'' he had noted. ``And
it won't be long flocks of geese are filling the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jane Gottlieb is free-lance writer based in Albany, N.Y.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
