<HEADER>
A7364 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-70S-RADICAL-2TAKES-HN     09-27 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-70S-RADICAL-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-WAR RADICAL FINDS SOLITUDE 29 YEARS AFTER DEADLY HEIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD FITZPATRICK  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Susan Saxe _ the quiet kid who penned her high
school class poem in 1966 _ entered a Boston bank on Sept. 23,
1970, wearing a purple dress, carrying a .30-caliber carbine.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Saxe and her accomplices made their getaway in a
1967 Volkswagen, a Boston policeman was lying outside the State
Street Bank &AMP; Trust Co., dying.
</P>
<P>
   Saxe hadn't pulled the trigger. She was one of five
conspirators, a collection of college students and ex-cons. It was
a 41-year-old parolee, William ``Lefty'' Gilday Jr., who fired the
fatal shot, hitting Patrolman Walter Schroeder Sr. as he responded
to the bank alarm.
</P>
<P>
   But soon Saxe, who had made the dean's list at Brandeis
University in Waltham, Mass., was on the FBI's Top 10 Most Wanted
list. And soon the question, in various forms, was asked: How could
this be? How could this bookish, bespectacled poet end up a
militant activist, ready to pick up a rifle in the name of
revolution? How could she take part in an act of such tragic
consequence: a 42-year-old father of nine, with a .45-caliber
bullet in the back?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, if there is one, lies in the turbulent times, in the
Vietnam War that outraged so many, in the student protests and
brutal police responses, and in the unlikely alliances forged at
Brandeis, then center of a nationwide student strike.
</P>
<P>
   To Saxe's parents, the initial reports about the Boston heist
seemed utterly impossible. At their Albany home, they had raised a
model daughter _ a top student at Albany High School, a member of
the Theta Alpha Literary Society, the winner of an Albany Poetry
Society contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember a year of lights and music ...'' her class poem read.
``Gilded moments/ Climaxed by a Senior Ball/ A towering fantasy/ A
last good-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   Saxe went to Syracuse University on a Regents scholarship,
majoring in journalism. ``Susan wouldn't hurt a fly,'' a roommate
recalled. ``She was not a political activist.''
</P>
<P>
   When Syracuse proved too easy for her, Saxe transferred to
Brandeis, graduating magna cum laude in 1970 with an English
degree. She was 21 years old.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, she told people she wanted to go the
University of Oregon to get a master's degree and teach. The
university withdrew its offer, she said, but she was going there
anyway to work in a bookstore and pursue writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan's been living in Portland, Oregon, since Sept. 1,'' her
father, Eliot Saxe, said as news of the Boston holdup broke. ``She
went out there for peace and quiet,'' said her mother, Rose Saxe.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, their daughter's life was on the brink of revolution _
and robbery.
</P>
<P>
   A transformation had begun at Brandeis. Saxe went to campus as
student opposition to the Vietnam War ratcheted to new heights,
interlocking with civil rights, women's liberation and other
causes.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, 1970, President Richard Nixon announced the
invasion of Cambodia. After five years of war, many activists were
worn out, but the invasion, following Nixon's promise not to
escalate the fighting, stoked student furor. Four days later, the
Ohio National Guard fired at student protesters at Kent State
University, killing four.
</P>
<P>
   Strikes spread to 60 college campuses, and Brandeis students
opened the National Student Strike Information Center, with Saxe
among the workers. Saxe also became active in the campus women's
liberation movement. She began to make friends with those who
shared that passion, including Katherine Ann Power of Denver, an
outspoken campus politician and women's activist.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Power said she crossed the line in the spring of 1970,
going from nonviolent protest to clandestine action. She saw
sit-ins and marches as pitiful responses to the war.
</P>
<P>
   Power became involved with Stanley Bond, a Vietnam helicopter
pilot who committed 20 armed robberies after his return home. Bond
was attending Brandeis under the Student Tutor Education Program.
Bond had shared a prison cell with William Gilday Jr., who also
entered the STEP rehabilitation program, planning to attend
Boston's Northeastern University along with ex-con Robert Valeri.
Gilday and Valeri also had been imprisoned on robbery charges.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two students and three ex-cons found common
purpose: revolution. They planned to amass weapons and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Their first strike came Sept. 1, 1970, in Philadelphia. Armed
with a Molotov cocktail, Saxe waited outside the Bell Savings &AMP;
Loan, while Bond entered the office and Power waited at the wheel
of a getaway car. They made off with $6,240.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   By Sept. 15, Saxe was in Portland buying four carbines, an
automatic pistol, a .38 special, plus ammunition. By Sept. 20,
Saxe, Power and the three parolees were back together in
Massachusetts, breaking into the National Guard Armory in
Newburyport, taking 400 rounds of .30-caliber ammunition and
plunger-type dynamite machines.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Sept. 23 bank heist, which netted $26,000.
Afterward, Saxe was upset with Gilday, calling him trigger-happy.
Gilday said the cops had arrived within 30 seconds and the group
would have been caught if he hadn't fired from his lookout post
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   The police nabbed Valeri within 12 hours and Bond and Gilday
within the month. Power wasn't caught until 1993. Under an alias,
she married, had a son, and became a gourmet chef in Oregon. But
the burden of her secret led to depression, prompting her to
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Saxe eluded capture until March 27, 1975, when a Philadelphia
cop spotted her on the street, recognizing her from an FBI photo.
</P>
<P>
   After a mistrial, Saxe pleaded guilty in 1977 to armed robbery
and a reduced charge of manslaughter, receiving a sentence of
12-to-14 years in Massachusetts state prison. She earned ``good
time'' and was released in 1982 after serving about seven years.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, Saxe tutored, set up a playroom for mothers and their
children, and became active in prison reform. ``You can still be a
revolutionary and not be armed,'' she said in a 1980 interview.
``If I give people here hope, then yes, I'm changing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Saxe, 50, is chief operating officer for the Alliance for
Jewish Renewal, a nonprofit group in Philadelphia that blends
spirituality and social action. It publishes the quarterly journal
New Menorah, sponsors a retreat center and coordinates a rabbi
ordination program.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is motivated to help people on the margins _ she is
concerned with the have-nots,'' said Rabbi Shaya Isenberg, the
Alliance board chairman. ``She has a very broad and deep grasp of
people and social systems, and a devotion to Judaism into the next
millennium _ that it be open and oriented to social justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Saxe's past doesn't hamper her on the job, Isenberg said.
``People knew her past, and everyone was very excited she was being
hired.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Isenberg said Saxe and her partner, a woman named Moon Smith,
are raising three children.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a reporter visited the Alliance offices. On the third
floor, at the top of the stairs, stood a short woman with gray hair
and glasses, wearing a purple shirt: Susan Saxe.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said when the reporter identified himself. ``I don't
want to talk to you.'' She turned, fled down the hall and slammed
her office door shut.
</P>
<P>
   So 29 years after that chaotic year and that defining day, what
is the world to make of the poet radical from Albany? Andor Skotnes
_ an associate professor of history at Russell Sage College in
Troy, said people such as Saxe should be supported.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who went further than they thought they should
in the 1960s have found ways to continue progressive courses for
greater democracy and human rights,'' said Skotnes, a member of
Students for a Democratic Society in the 1960s. ``The desperation
and imperative of the times made people take extreme actions that
seem impossible today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know times were different,'' Edmund McNamara, who was Boston
police commissioner when Schroeder was shot, said when Power turned
herself in. ``There were protests and everything. Sure, the country
was coming apart, but what the hell did Walter have to do with
bombing Hanoi? He was just doing his job that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached in Sarasota, Fla., Saxe's mother, Rose, said, ``She paid
her price to society. When someone pays her price and then lives a
good life, you should leave it alone. People who love and care
about her know she's turned around and is living a good life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
