<HEADER>
A7378 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-GEORGE-CLOONEY-IN-THR     09-27 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-CLOONEY-IN-THREE-KINGS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE CLOONEY GOES FOR THE GOLD ON THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of George Clooney with Ice Cube and Mark
Wahlberg in a scene from ``Three Kings.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    George Clooney thinks he's a good actor. Sometimes, anyway.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I am good,'' he explains. ``If I've got a good
script, I can do a good job. A good character can survive a lot of
things. There are things I've done that I like and things I've done
where I go, `Wow, I just missed that completely.'''
 &HT;    Among the latter, the one that he remembers most is ``Batman and
Robin'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``I whiffed,'' Clooney says matter-of-factly. ``I don't take
full heat for that personally. I do publicly. I go, `Hey, it
bombed. I'll take the heat.' I don't know what I could have done _
I saw part of it the other day on cable, and cringed through it.
 &HT;    ``It's a tough one,'' he says, ``because the script wasn't there
at all. For whatever reasons, I didn't get it, either _ I didn't
mesh with it.''
 &HT;    Clooney, the handsome and charismatic former star of
television's ``ER,'' has yet to score big on the big screen. Early
in his career he turned up in the likes of ``Return of the Killer
Tomatoes'' (1988), but since ``ER'' he's appeared in a number of
potential star-makers, including ``One Fine Day'' (1996), ``Batman
and Robin,'' ``The Peacemaker'' (1997) and ``Out of Sight'' (1998).
 &HT;    The actor earned kudos for ``One Fine Day'' and raves for ``Out
of Sight,'' but none of his films made much of a splash at the box
office. Clooney tries again on Oct. 1 with ``Three Kings,'' an
ambitious mix of black comedy, action and drama set amid the chaos
of the Gulf War.
 &HT;    Written and directed by David O. Russell, ``Three Kings'' plops
audiences into 1991 Iraq, where American ground troops sit idly
while jets handle the real fighting. Among the soldiers are
Clooney, Mark Wahlberg, Ice Cube and Spike Jonze _ all of whom,
upon hearing of a cease-fire agreement, can't wait to get home.
 &HT;    When the four discover a map revealing the site of Saddam
Hussein's secret stash of gold bullion, they go AWOL in an attempt
to get rich quick. However, their efforts to grab the gold bring
them face-to-face with the Iraqi people, forcing each man to
grapple with issues of morality and mortality.
 &HT;    Clooney loved the ``Three Kings'' script, but there were several
obstacles to his making the film _ most notably Mel Gibson and
Nicolas Cage.
 &HT;    ``I'm on a list and I'm down on that list, so you have to get
through those other guys,'' Clooney says, charming and honest as
usual during a conversation at New York's Essex House. ``I had to
take Mel, tie him up and keep him in my house.
 &HT;    ``They wanted Nic pretty badly for this, too,'' he adds. ``He
was really interested, but he had commitments to other films, thank
God.
 &HT;    ``I just kept lobbying,'' Clooney says with a laugh. ``I sent
David a letter. I followed him _ to this hotel, actually. I showed
up and said, `Come on, don't be a jerk. Give me the job.'
 &HT;    ``And I eventually got the job.''
 &HT;    As things finally worked out, ``Three Kings'' is a dizzying,
complex achievement, at once entertaining, funny, pointed,
thought-provoking and smart. In other words, it's everything that
``Wild Wild West'' (1999) was not _ which is just as well for
Clooney, who wisely pulled out of that project.
 &HT;    But if ``Wild Wild West'' proved too dumb for many audience's
taste, ``Three Kings'' might be too smart for its own good.
 &HT;    Clooney winces at the possibility _ much the same thing happened
to the engaging-but-little-seen ``Out of Sight'' _ but insists that
audiences will be able to handle ``Three Kings.''
 &HT;    ``When they screened `ER' for NBC,'' Clooney recalls, ``Don
Ohlmeyer and Warren Littlefield looked over at Les Moonves, who was
the head of Warner Bros. at the time, and said, `What the hell did
you do with our $3 million? No one will follow this show. There are
too many story lines _ the audience can't keep up.'
 &HT;    ``We tested it,'' he adds, ``and it tested through the roof.
They accused us of doctoring the testing, and went and brought in a
`Jay Leno' audience to prove us wrong. And it tested through the
roof, and was arguably one of the biggest hits of all time.''
 &HT;    Hollywood errs in assuming that moviegoers want only bland,
easily digested fare, Clooney believes.
 &HT;    ``I think we always underestimate the audience,'' he says. ``If
you play to dumb, you'll get dumb movies out there and people
saying `This is dumb.'
 &HT;    ``A lot of really good movies get made,'' the actor adds, ``and
people see them. I don't think we have to bring the bar down.''
 &HT;    Though Clooney still considers himself an actor for hire _ he
just wrapped the Coen Brothers' ``O Brother, Where Art Thou?'' and
is currently shooting ``The Perfect Storm,'' again co-starring
Wahlberg _ he's also attempting to take matters into his own hands
by producing films through his company, Maysville Pictures.
Maysville, he proudly reports, already has 35 scripts in various
stages of development at the major studios.
 &HT;    ``I can read a script and know whether or not I like it,'' he
says. ``Whether I'm right or not, time will tell.''
 &HT;    Time will tell, too, whether Clooney reprises his breakthrough
role as Dr. Doug Ross on ``ER.'' Recent tabloid stories blared that
producer John Wells would be bringing Clooney back for several
episodes _ including the finale for departing series veteran
Julianna Margulies _ at a staggering $2 million a pop.
 &HT;    ``I have only been asked once,'' Clooney says, ``and I was asked
a general question by John Wells. The question was, `Are you open
to the idea of coming back and getting Julianna off the show at the
end of the season?'
 &HT;    ``That's the only time we've talked,'' he says firmly, ``and
that's the only question that's been posed. All the other things
were completely made up.''
 &HT;    So what about that one question, then?
 &HT;    ``My answer to John was that anything that he could come up with
that would have to do with Julianna, I'd be happy to do,'' Clooney
says. ``These guys are really good friends _ not just the actors,
but the producers.''
 &HT;    That practical, down-to-earth thinking is typical of Clooney. It
might be smoke and mirrors _ after all, he's a good actor, right? _
but he exhibits a realistic sense of self, a drive to succeed and,
thankfully, an in-check ego.
 &HT;    ``Fifteen years from now I could be hit by a bus,'' he says
thoughtfully. ``I could be back on television.
 &HT;    ``People go, `So you're done with television for good?' You go
`Yeah,''' he says with a shrug. ``Everybody says, `For good,' but
there are plenty of people out there who are right back on
television series. Hopefully I won't have to rely just on people's
opinions of me.
 &HT;    ``That's why you have a production company, so you can do other
things,'' Clooney says. ``People get tired of seeing you. So I'll
have to have other jobs to fall back on.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
