<SLUG> BC-ROB-REINER-DIRECTS-THE-STORY-OF-US-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TAKES TWO TO TANGLE: ROB REINER TELLS `THE STORY OF US' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Rob Reiner with Bruce Willis in a scene
from ``The Story of Us.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's been a decade since actor/director Rob Reiner explored
romance and relationships in his hit comedy, ``When Harry Met
Sally'' (1989).
 &HT;    His new film, ``The Story of Us,'' takes that exploration one
long step further. Opening Oct. 15, it's the story of a husband and
wife (Bruce Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer) on the verge of divorce
after 15 years of marriage and two children.
 &HT;    Think of it as ``When Harry Got a Trial Separation From Sally.''
And, oh yeah, it's a comedy.
 &HT;    Reiner _ who directs and also plays Willis' best friend,
co-starring with Rita Wilson and Paul Reiser _ feels he's breaking
some new ground this time out.
 &HT;    ``There are a lot of movies about people falling in love and
people getting divorced,'' he says, ``but there aren't many that
deal with everything in-between _ the day-to-day wear and tear, the
ins and outs of a marriage.''
 &HT;    Writers Alan Zweibel and Jessie Nelson shared Reiner's
fascination with the subject, and the trio _ all married and with
children _ embarked upon a script-writing process which, Reiner
freely admits, drew heavily on their own experiences with ``til
death do us part.''
 &HT;    ``That's the only way you can create a film like this,'' the
director says. ``You only know what happens in your own marriage,
and you hope that other people will relate to what you've gone
through. It can be painful and uncomfortable to share those
details, but how else can you do it?
 &HT;    ``I think we hit on some basic truths that an audience is going
to identify with.''
 &HT;    Reiner was surprised to discover that his stars were quite a bit
like the characters they play _ Willis a not-very-practical writer
and Pfeiffer a hyperorganized control freak, two opposites who
originally attract and then start driving each other crazy.
 &HT;    ``Michelle is the earth mother of her own family, the designated
driver who likes to control everything,'' the director says.
``Bruce, on the other hand, doesn't color inside the lines. He's
all over the place.''
 &HT;    Ironically, while the actors were playing out a marriage on the
rocks in front of the cameras, both were facing similar emotional
challenges offscreen. Willis was engulfed in a tabloid frenzy over
his highly publicized separation from his wife, actress Demi Moore,
while Pfeiffer was coping with the death of her father.
 &HT;    ``It was tough on Bruce to be in the throes of a very difficult
breakup,'' Reiner says. ``We had some private conversations about
it, because he was really struggling with it.
 &HT;    ``You know, they talk about method acting, where you draw on
past experiences to get the right emotion for a scene,'' he adds.
``I think Bruce didn't have to look very far _ it was so fresh from
his life that he brought it right into the film ... I think it
ultimately helped his performance.''
 &HT;    He adds that the turmoil of a breakup is especially hard for a
celebrity on Willis' level.
 &HT;    ``You can hide a lot of the pain if you're an ordinary person,''
Reiner says. ``But you feel like you're sharing the most intimate
details of your life with strangers when the media puts you under a
microscope like he has been.''
 &HT;    Pfeiffer remains happily married to Emmy-winning producer/writer
David E. Kelley, but the death of her father took its toll.
 &HT;    ``It was a terrible loss for her,'' Reiner says. ``She was
struggling with her own demons. Even so, I think that she could use
some of it in her performance, as Bruce did.
 &HT;    ``It was tough for both of them, but they were unbelievably
professional.''
 &HT;    It's hard to believe that ``The Story of Us'' could be funny,
but Reiner insists that the angst and the laughs are carefully
balanced.
 &HT;    ``I think it's realistic,'' he says. ``Marriage is uncomfortable
and difficult, and it's also joyous and uplifting. But the biggest
challenge is to play something that's funny and real at the same
time _ to move people and make them laugh at the same time is the
hardest thing in the world.
 &HT;    ``Bruce and Michelle both have that gift. It's rare.''
 &HT;    Personally, he adds, he found the love scenes the most difficult
to direct.
 &HT;    ``I'm completely embarrassed by those scenes,'' Reiner admits,
``and I wish there was somebody else behind the camera when they do
them.
 &HT;    ``The easiest for me was the scene where they make love on the
kitchen butcher block,'' he says, ``because we played it for
laughs. But there's a moment in the montage at the end of the film
that's pretty much raw sex. That was uncomfortable.
 &HT;    ``But Michelle and Bruce were great,'' he adds, ``and I think
they were a lot less embarrassed than I was.''
 &HT;    Reiner, who many years ago went through his own much-publicized
divorce, from actress-turned-director Penny Marshall, is in a
long-running second marriage to photographer Michele Singer.
 &HT;    ``Since I put some of our own relationship into the film, it was
interesting to sit next to my wife at a screening,'' he says,
laughing. ``I remember the scene where there's this thing about not
replacing the toilet paper when the roll runs out. Michele looked
over at me and shook her head, because she's been on my case about
that kind of stuff.''
 &HT;    The director thinks he's a better husband the second time
around, in part because of his first marriage and even the divorce
that followed.
 &HT;    ``I went through some therapy after I got divorced, which gave
me a better understanding of what I'm bringing to a relationship
and what I can expect from my partner,'' he says. ``Understanding
is realizing that you are probably 50 percent of any problem. You
may not be able to change the other person, but at least you can
work on yourself and your own behavior.''
 &HT;    Reiner, a devoted father of three, readily admits that the
typical marriage's biggest hurdle is children.
 &HT;    ``I think Rita Wilson said on the set one day, `Kids are the
Jack Kevorkian of romance,''' he says with a laugh. ``We all know
what that means _ diaper changes, car-pool pickups ... Who's
picking them up from school? Who's taking them here or there?
 &HT;    ``It doesn't leave very much time for romance.''
 &HT;    He has a little secret to keep romance alive in his own home, he
adds.
 &HT;    ``You have to make dates,'' Reiner says with a chuckle. ``Like
you make a date to go out on Friday night. Otherwise you just get
lost in the day-to-day demands of family life, and you find
yourself disengaging like the couple in the film.''
 &HT;    He stops in thought.
 &HT;    ``What's the secret to a good marriage?'' he asks rhetorically.
``I guess you've got to be good friends. You've got to connect on a
lot of levels, and you really have to work to have a great
understanding of each other.
 &HT;    ``If you can do that, then you can weather any storm.''
 c.1999 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf is a Hollywood-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Story of Us,'' consult the
official Website at www.thestoryofus.net. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
