<SLUG> BC-MOLLY-SHANNON-IN-SUPERSTAR-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOLLY SHANNON, FINDING LAUGHTER IN TEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Molly Shannon in a scene from
``Superstar.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    A hospital waiting room doesn't seem like the place to get your
start in stand-up comedy, but 4-year-old Molly Shannon didn't
choose it.
 &HT;    That choice was made by the driver who killed her mother.
 &HT;    It was raining that day, Shannon recalls _ nearly three decades
later, she remembers the details as if it were only yesterday.
 &HT;    Her father pulled out of a Fourth of July picnic in a car filled
with laughing females _ his wife, their daughters Molly and Mary,
and a niece. He never even saw the speeding car that veered from
the oncoming lane and skidded in their direction.
 &HT;    ``It was just a real bad wipeout,'' Shannon recalls. ``My mother
and my cousin died in front of me.''
 &HT;    Molly, the smallest girl in the car, was the least injured.
While doctors worked over her father and sister, a nurse dumped the
frightened, confused preschooler in the hospital waiting room.
 &HT;    ``I spent my time there trying to make the other kids laugh,
figuring that they had it worse than me,'' she recalls. ``It's
strange what you remember, but I think that's where comedy started
for me.
 &HT;    ``I come from a sad place, and the only way I could make peace
with it was by making others laugh.''
 &HT;    Shannon has kept on making people laugh _ at 33, she's a
``Saturday Night Live'' regular best known for her recurring
character Mary Katherine Gallagher, an overweight, awkward Catholic
schoolgirl who, on Oct. 8, will become the heroine of her own
movie, ``Superstar.''
 &HT;    Over coffee in her suite at Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel,
Shannon doesn't look much like Mary Katherine. Thin and stylish in
a red sweater and black pants, she readily admits that Mary
Katherine and her dreams of superstardom grew out of Shannon's own
tragic childhood.
 &HT;    ``Almost every time you meet a funny person, they've probably
done a lot of crying on the inside,'' she says. ``It's not just a
saying _ it's true.
 &HT;    ``My dream was to feel happy.''
 &HT;    Shannon is currently riding a hot streak _ besides
``Superstar,'' she also has a role in Ron Howard's upcoming
adaptation of the Dr. Seuss classic, ``The Grinch Who Stole
Christmas.'' But she remembers all too well the way things used to
be.
 &HT;    ``My character Mary Katherine loses her parents when the film
begins,'' Shannon says. ``She feels like such a loser _ she feels
like nothing. She also feels like she's waiting for something to
erase the hurt. In her case, it's stardom.
 &HT;    ``I understand her,'' the comedian says. ``I know of her drive
to get to a place where you won't feel like nothing.''
 &HT;    For herself, Shannon adds, she's found that place.
 &HT;    ``I've made peace with my past,'' she says quietly. ``In fact,
the only thing that really depresses me now is that I don't have a
date for the millennium _ but the year is still young.''
 &HT;    Growing up in Cleveland, she recalls, her active fantasy life
laid the groundwork for her career as a performer. Isolated from
those around her _ her father's legs were crushed in the accident,
so for a long time Shannon and her sister were deprived of both
parents _ she turned inward for support.
 &HT;    ``I remember I had a piano teacher who wore a big, flowing
blouse and doused on the perfume,'' she says. ``I'd sit next to her
and she'd be like, `La, la, la-de-da _ play those notes.' But I
wasn't paying attention because her blouse would touch me and I'd
think of my mom.
 &HT;    ``But then I'd actually move away,'' she adds. ``I didn't want
to get too close.''
 &HT;    Distrustful of the outside world, she retreated into a realm of
her own.
 &HT;    ``At home, I went into a fantasy world which was all about me
playing and inventing characters,'' Shannon says. ``It was an
escape hatch into a place where there was nothing wrong. It was
acting.''
 &HT;    Simultaneously, she was unknowingly accumulating material for
Mary Katherine's future routines.
 &HT;    ``On top of my tragic childhood, I had to go to Catholic
school,'' Shannon says, laughing.
 &HT;    ``On the serious side, all that pressure at school to be a good
girl keeps you from getting angry about stuff,'' she adds. ``And I
think it's good to get angry about stuff.
 &HT;    ``At night I'd go to parties and make out and drink,'' she
recalls. ``But if a boy wanted to get serious, I'd be like, `No
way.' If somebody wanted to get too close, I was like, `I'm out of
here.' I dumped them.
 &HT;    ``Fear of intimacy,'' she says with a shrug. ``And I'm still
working on it.''
 &HT;    Shannon even once considered becoming a nun.
 &HT;    ``I did want to become a nun,'' she admits, laughing. ``In fact,
I pretended I was a nun all the time. But the problem is that I
wanted to be a sexy nun, which didn't go over big at school.''
 &HT;    Even now, after she's achieved success with ``Saturday Night
Live'' and laid some of her ghosts to rest, Shannon spends a lot of
time alone.
 &HT;    ``I don't like to go out much,'' she says. ``I honestly think it
makes you a different kind of woman when you're raised by a man. I
always saw things from a man's point of view _ I became very
work-oriented.
 &HT;    ``In fact, I had to find the womanly part of myself recently,''
she adds. ``I had to sort of discover that you can work and have
that other part of yourself.''
 &HT;    As for affairs of the heart, Shannon says with a roll of her
eyes that there's nothing much going on at the moment. In fact, she
says, her romantic life peaked at age 6.
 &HT;    ``I used to go into the bushes with Tommy Sullivan and smooch
with him,'' she says cheerfully. ``It was really nice. We just
kissed and kissed. And it was actually a very healthy relationship.
 &HT;    ``Love went downhill from there.''
 &HT;    Like Mary Katherine, however, Shannon never gives up hope.
 &HT;    ``I hope that I'm in a healthy relationship by the millennium,''
she says, ``because that's important. I want to be enjoying my life
a little bit more.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Superstar,'' consult the
Paramount Pictures Website at www.paramount.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
