<HEADER>
A7385 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-MELINA-KANAKAREDES-IN     09-27 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELINA-KANAKAREDES-IN-PROVIDENCE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE `PROVIDENCE': MELINA KANAKAREDES ADJUSTS TO LIFE AS A STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Melina Kanakaredes with Paula Cale, Mike
Farrell and Seth Peterson in a scene from ``Providence.'') 
 By MICHAEL LOGAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Melina Kanakaredes is either supremely self-confident or
thoroughly lacking in ego. Or perhaps both.
</P>
<P>
   The leading lady of the red-hot NBC drama ``Providence'' is
conducting an early-morning interview in her trailer near the set,
but because she has not yet reported to the hair-and-makeup
department, her famous curls have not been coiffed and her face is
without even a touch of cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   For an actress to appear this way in front of a reporter is a
virtually unprecedented act of daring. But she needn't fret _ even
sans artificial enhancement, she is an incandescent beauty.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, she is the perfect hostess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make these really incredible, really strong, iced Greek
coffees. Would you like one?'' Kanakaredes says, sprinting to the
trailer's mini-kitchen. ``I'm surviving on sugar and caffeine these
days.''
</P>
<P>
   As the actress whips up her concoction, she explains that she's
been working 36 straight days without a break, and doing a lot of
traveling. In addition to the second season of ``Providence,''
which shoots primarily in Los Angeles, she's simultaneously
starring opposite Robert De Niro in ``15 Minutes,'' a psychological
drama that is filming in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she's complaining, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have been crazy,'' she says, ``but it's the best crazy
in the world. The only difficult thing is trying to sleep on
planes, but I discovered the secret to that.''
</P>
<P>
   She pulls out a mouth mask _ the kind Michael Jackson often
wears in public _ from an airline carry-on bag that lies nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing the eyepatch thing and the earplugs, but then
someone gave me this mask to avoid catching germs,'' she says.
``And, when you put it on, everyone thinks you're, like, this
complete lunatic, and they leave you alone. That's how you sleep on
a plane.''
</P>
<P>
   At 32, Kanakaredes is one of the rare few who didn't have to
struggle to win their spurs as actors. Born in Akron, Ohio, she
moved to New York straight out of college and soon landed a job as
Andros Cooper, the Greek heroine on ``Guiding Light.''
</P>
<P>
   During her fourth year on the soap, she began doing double duty
as Jimmy Smits' girlfriend on ``NYPD Blue.'' She followed that with
regular roles on ``Due South'' and in two short-lived series, ``New
York News'' with Mary Tyler Moore and ``Leaving L.A.'' Along the
way, she snagged small but spicy parts in the feature films ``The
Long Kiss Goodnight'' (1997) and ``Dangerous Beauty'' (1998).
</P>
<P>
   Then Kanakaredes signed a series-development deal with NBC ...
and, for a year and a half, turned down every pilot the network
offered her.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day the script for the premiere episode of
``Providence'' landed on her desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it and loved it instantly,'' Kanakaredes says. ``I
thought it was fun, different, very moving. Unlike the other pilots
I'd read, `Providence' was something I was willing to devote years
of my life to.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I sent the script to all my testers _ my family and friends
who are not in show business _ and they had the same reaction,''
she adds. ``Then to have it hit so big with the audience was
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   A midseason replacement relegated to television's dead zone _ 8
p.m. on Friday _ ``Providence'' debuted last January and stunned
the entire industry by becoming an immediate hit and the season's
highest-rated new drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not just a chick show,'' Kanakaredes adds proudly.
``From the beginning we were pulling in millions of men, too. We've
completely changed Friday-night viewing habits _ now people will
stay home and watch `Providence,' then go out at 9.''
</P>
<P>
   After such early success, the producers have adopted an
if-it-ain't-broke-don't-fix-it attitude for the show's second year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we will be more realistic about our characters'
feelings,'' Kanakaredes says. ``This season, we're really delving
into the relationship we all had with our mother, and that maybe
she and Syd really didn't like each other a lot, that maybe the
kids built their mother up to be somebody amazing when she really
wasn't. Or was it our fault that we really didn't get to know her?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be hitting these deep, personal issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Married to her college boyfriend, chef Peter Constantinides,
Kanakaredes is notoriously private about her real-life family
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things I don't want to share with anybody,
and maybe I never will,'' she says. ``I chose a career in the
spotlight. My husband, my parents and my sisters did not.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll break that rule enough to insist that, despite how things
might appear, her hectic schedule with ``Providence'' and ``15
Minutes'' isn't any harder on her relationship with her husband
than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been juggling since Day 1 of our marriage,'' she says.
``The nuttiness never ends. In fact, it's even nuttier when you're
not working, because then you're working even harder hustling,
auditioning, pursuing your goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter learned what show business is all about long ago,'' she
says affectionately. ``He didn't just come into it with my
`Providence' success.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, working with someone of De Niro's stature doesn't happen
to every young actress. Asked about working with the Hollywood
icon, Kanakaredes gasps, rolls her eyes heavenward and lets out a
delirious sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phenomenal,'' she says. ``Just phenomenal. He is a god among
actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my audition for him was the most torturous night of my
life,'' she adds. ``I was supposed to meet De Niro at 6 p.m., so
I'm so nervous and crazed I was all ready by 3. Then they say, `De
Niro's running late. It'll be 6:30.' Then it was 7. Then 7:30. Then
8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't meet him until a quarter to 9, at which point I was
like, `Oh, screw it, I don't care anymore! This sucks!' But when he
walked into the room, my heart stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanakaredes read two scenes from the film, then De Niro and
director John Herzfeld disappeared into another room for what she
says ``seemed like three hours, but was really only about 30
seconds. Then they came out and told me I had the part.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar-winning legend keeps in touch when Kanakaredes is
working on ``Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just sort of calls up and says, `So ... like ... uh ...
howyadoon?''' she says, perfectly mimicking the actor's trademark
voice. ``And I'm like, `Robert De Niro is calling me _ This is too
damn weird!'''
</P>
<P>
   Also weird for Kanakaredes is that, after the success of
``Providence,'' her very complicated last name suddenly seems to
fall trippingly off of every tongue in Tinseltown.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, everybody wanted me to change the name _
agents, managers, friends supposedly bearing good advice,'' she
recalls. ``But I'm not the type to bust my butt to achieve
something this difficult and not have it be me.''
</P>
<P>
   She pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really queer about it,'' she says. ``My father had three
daughters, and there's this Greek tradition about passing on the
family name. Well, that's not going to happen, but at least I can
keep the Kanakaredes name out there this way.''
</P>
<P>
   She sips her really incredible, really strong, iced Greek coffee
and breaks into a smile of really serene contentment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael Logan is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Providence,'' consult the NBC
Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
