<HEADER>
A7400 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-27 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOLD RUSH AT THE NEW MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The next millennium is a few weeks away, and
already it's a bore. And not even a crashing bore.
</P>
<P>
   No, computers won't crash in the numbers we hoped for. The world
probably won't end. If a new Messiah appears, he'll get caught in
traffic because the Golden Gate Bridge will be closed for an
idiotic party.
</P>
<P>
   The future is always a disappointment when it arrives. In an age
of mega-hype, the future is a disappointment in advance. We know
we're never getting world peace, colonies on other planets, food in
convenient squeeze tubes or those personal jet packs we were
promised long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never think of the future. It comes soon enough,'' Albert
Einstein said in 1930, a hard year for the then-future.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing we have is the present, which always gets a bad
rap for not being as good as the past, particularly in
nostalgia-ridden San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The way to think of the present, though, is as the future we
never could have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a century ago, who would have guessed that young
people moving to San Francisco would have short hair and
responsible jobs, while the district attorney would support pot
smoking and both free and paid love?
</P>
<P>
   We never expected that smoking pot would be legal and smoking
tobacco would be punishable by expulsion from office buildings onto
the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Way back in 1974 an economist would have been drummed out of his
dismal science if he predicted the center of the world's economic
universe would shift to Palo Alto, then a sleepy college town with
Ramona's Pizza and a few young guys tinkering in garages.
</P>
<P>
   We never imagined staring into a box that brings the Bay Area
billions of dollars and allows us to communicate with people all
over the world, and that most of them would be pornographers.
</P>
<P>
   Look at this place. We don't have flying Jetsons cars, but we
have things we never imagined. We have companies that make millions
before they've even thought of their products. Trust me, the snake
oil is in the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   We have phone booths that travel the highways at 70 mph. The
phones themselves are getting so small that it takes sidewalk
psychiatric work-ups to tell yuppies with lattes from
schizophrenics with cups.
</P>
<P>
   Women drive tanks and wear army boots. Men wear clown-colored
tights on bicycles. Enough said about gender play.
</P>
<P>
   We have homeless. Twenty-five years ago we didn't even have that
word as a noun. We just had transients, and except for one lady
with balloons in back of the Emporium, they mostly did move on.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us never would have guessed that we'd all be living
in half-million-dollar homes and $2,000-a-month apartments _ or
catching a few winks in them between jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area now has outhouses in front of posh houses. Stock
market profits are being funneled directly into renovation and
expansion of homes, and workers aren't allowed to use the
bathrooms. You might want to invest in Port-a-Potty Inc.
</P>
<P>
   San Franciscans always have been serious eaters, but when I
moved here in the '70s I had no idea how serious food would become.
I imagined eating petrale at the Tadich Grill and onion cakes at
the Hunan for the rest of a short, lipid-filled life.
</P>
<P>
   Never in my wildest dreams did I think that dining out would
become a competitive event, with points scored for beating friends
and critics to the latest palace of attitudinal chow, and points
subtracted for still going there after it becomes easy to get a
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Food never became containers of colored goo like the astronauts
ate in ``2001'' _ except on airliners. Instead we're eating noodles
colored with the black stuff that squid squirt and shrimp entrapped
in gelatin pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me this isn't a civilization at its pinnacle. Waiter, the
hummingbird tongues.
</P>
<P>
   We even can get garlic fries at the ballpark, and soon a
glorious new ballpark to go with the fries. A quarter of a century
ago, we thought we'd always have to watch baseball in a concrete
toilet in gale-force winds.
</P>
<P>
   This week San Franciscans will attend their last Giants game at
Candlestick Park. Many will have tears in their eyes _ and not just
from the cold wind and peanut dust. San Franciscans will get
nostalgic about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I don't like to look back, because the future is
gaining on me.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
