<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
Sept. 28. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FORFIT: Missouri police have lost a test case they filed to
prove they had no choice but to keep money they seize instead of
sending it to public education. That case may come up when
legislators begin statewide hearings on the forfeit mess Tuesday.
Karen Dillon. 30.
</P>
<P>
   GURU _ Thousands have meditated in Fairfield, Iowa, for 25 years
to attain near-supernatural clarity of mind and, while they're at
it, create world peace. These devotees of Maharishi Mahesh Yogi
think his trademarked Transcendental Meditation techniques can
actually make them float on air. Most recently they've constructed
new homes and office buildings, or retrofitted old ones, to face
east because the Maharishi suggests that's the best way to capture
the energy of the rising sun. The locals aren't buying it. ``We're
Midwesterners here,'' said city council member Neil Doyle. ``You
come in here with some fairly crazy philosophy and we don't swallow
it all.'' Yet, Doyle and others note, the past quarter-century has
shown that a small Midwestern town can absorb, if not really
integrate, a sizable immigration of rather unorthodox outsiders.
Particularly when the outsiders bring money and jobs. 50. Scott
Canon. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   DOG: This is the story of three strangers who came together over
one man's grief. An Overland Park man lost his dog last month. That
dog was all he had in the world. He went out at 4 a.m. screaming
and crying through his neighborhood looking for it. No luck. He
called the Lost Dog Registry in Kansas City. This group kept a
lookout for it but was losing hope. Then the dog happened to wander
by the house of an Overland Park woman. Her kids wanted to keep it.
Nevertheless, she turned in the dog to the Lost Dog Registry too.
Man and dog were reunited through the kindness of strangers. 30.
Jeffrey Spivak. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   HODES: Richard Hodes, the physician who heads the National
Institute on Aging, speaks in KC at a conference today. We
interview him about anti-oxidants and other baby boomer concerns.
Kit Wagar. Photo.
</P>
