<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO SUIT HAS POLITICS WRITTEN ALL OVER IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Greg Little, one of the tobacco industry's top
lawyers, didn't mince words when the federal government filed its
huge lawsuit against his clients the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Little called the action ``politically correct extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   I will let the courts _ if this suit goes anywhere _ determine
whether extortion is involved here. But there isn't any question
that the action was politically correct, particularly for a
Democratic administration.
</P>
<P>
   For countless politicians, especially _ but not exclusively _
Democrats, cigarette makers have become a double-opportunity
target.
</P>
<P>
   Americans' increasing health consciousness and mounting evidence
that tobacco companies tried for years to hide the addictive
dangers of smoking from the public have painted the industry as the
evil empire, deserving repeated political assaults.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's huge financial success, moreover, has made it the
ultimate cash cow, something to be milked for more than the
billions of dollars in state and federal taxes it has long been
pumping into state and federal treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   I will reserve comment on the potential merits of the Department
of Justice's suit. But the action certainly has politics written
all over it, coming, as it did, more than halfway through President
Clinton's last term and on the heels of tobacco's
multibillion-dollar settlements of similar state suits seeking
recovery of tax dollars spent on smoking-related health care.
</P>
<P>
   There even may be some truth to the industry's assertion that
one reason the suit was filed was to give Vice President Al Gore a
popular issue in his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The industry immediately vowed not to settle, a declaration that
can't be taken totally at face value given the way the tobacco
companies caved in to the states. A tobacco lawyer made a similar
vow not too many months before his clients agreed to pay $17.3
billion over the next 25 years to end Texas' suit.
</P>
<P>
   But cigarette makers may be ready to draw the line for real this
time. They certainly won't agree to any settlement before next
year's election, which could change the outlook from the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential
front-runner, may be the tobacco companies' least painful
alternative. Bush is a strong opponent of lawsuits against
businesses, even controversial ones.
</P>
<P>
   During his first year in office in 1995, he championed
significant changes in Texas' civil justice laws, and this year he
signed a bill to prohibit local governments from suing gun
manufacturers for damages without the Legislature's permission.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had nothing to do with Texas' anti-tobacco suit, except to
jump in after the settlement was negotiated to fight the high fees
awarded to the outside plaintiffs' lawyers who had helped former
Democratic Attorney General Dan Morales win Texas' big payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting trial lawyers, of course, is a favorite sport for most
Republicans, since trial lawyers are a major source of funding for
Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Texas probably would have never even sued the tobacco industry
if the decision had been left up to the governor or the
Legislature. The suit was Morales' call alone, acting as the
state's top lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan pointed out, after the federal
suit was filed, that Bush ``as a general principle'' doesn't like
lawsuits. But he said it would be inappropriate for Bush to say
more until he learns more about the case.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the tobacco industry already is trying to work on
the governor, as well as other policy-makers and the public.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris Inc., the biggest tobacco company, released its
own economic analysis, claiming that the federal action, if
successful, could reduce Texas' settlement payout by as much as
$213 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco executives also are generously contributing to Bush's
presidential campaign. According to research by The Dallas Morning
News, tobacco executives and their spouses gave Bush nearly $50,000
_ a small part of Bush's overall collections, however _ during the
three months preceding the governor's summer campaign finance
report.
</P>
<P>
   And cigarette companies also are spreading the warning: If our
legal industry can be targeted by the government today, yours can
be tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   That warning didn't work in Texas, where the governor didn't
have any control over an independently elected, anti-tobacco
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   How it might play in Washington, were Bush to find himself in
the White House and in control of the Department of Justice,
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robison is chief of the Houston Chronicle's Austin Bureau and can
be contacted at . clay.robison(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
