<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7449 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-27 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S THE BEEF IN CLINTON-GIULIANI RACE? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The upcoming race between Hillary Rodham Clinton
and Rudolph Giuliani to represent New York in the U.S. Senate is
attracting as much interest outside New York as in.
</P>
<P>
   Even before either the first lady or the mayor of New York has
formally declared as a candidate, people want to know, with a
passion surpassing interest in any other race, including the
presidency, just who is going to win.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't only New Yorkers asking this question. It was posed
wherever I traveled outside the state the last couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls taken regularly about aspects of the
upcoming clash feed the appetite for wanting to discern the winner
long before the one poll that counts: Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   All of which contributes to the much-criticized emphasis by the
news media on the horse race aspect of elections. The argument has
been tirelessly urged on the public that newspapers, magazines and
radio and television focus on who's ahead and shunt aside the
exploration of how the candidates stand on issues that matter.
</P>
<P>
   A recent guest appearance on a radio program in Albany provided
me and opportunity to hear the dynamics of this argument. The host
of the program, Fred Dicker, presented the findings of not one, but
two, public opinion surveys, whose directors he interviewed over
the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Carroll of the Quinnipiac College poll found the
candidates tied, as they had been for a while. The other, Lee
Miringoff of the Marist College poll, had Giuliani with a
substantial lead.
</P>
<P>
   When Miringoff was questioned about whether his extensive
polling so early in the game did not encourage the very behavior of
the media that has been so much decried, some informative answers
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Dicker jumped in with his view that the news media feed on polls
because they are sustenance, they give reporters something to write
about. As those in the news business will have to admit, Dicker
squarely hit the target. The news media are not merely the toy of
forces larger themselves, forced by an insatiable public to focus
on the horse race. Even absent such demand, there is the need for
the news media every day to ``feed the goat.'' As you know, a goat
will eat any rusted tin can that comes along.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Miringoff argued that continued polling, even in
the preliminary stages of the Clinton-Giuliani face-off, was
helping to keep the reporting honest.
</P>
<P>
   For example, by measuring the public reaction to President
Clinton's clemency for the imprisoned Puerto Rican militants, and
the first lady's reaction to it, journalists could not with
impunity make claims contrary to poll findings that it had been
negligible.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, politicians themselves poll extensively. However
much the political insiders help to stir up criticism of media
political coverage because of the horse race emphasis, politicians
constantly poll to learn where their campaign is strong and where
it needs bolstering.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, only favorable findings from these polls will be made
public. Consequently, the public itself has a compelling use for
polling data that are not politically manipulated by the interested
parties.
</P>
<P>
   If the choice were between knowing and not knowing, between
asking too many questions too often and not asking them at all, a
free society is better served by the activism than passivism. That
does not hide the downside. Too much of a supposed good thing helps
overload the public with trivial information. Likely this
overloading dissuades even more people from taking an active
interest in electoral politics.
</P>
<P>
   At their best, all polls are no more than a snapshot of the
moment and the context in which they are asked. Opinions can shift
as quickly as the stock market rises and falls.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton-Giuliani right now is the hottest contest going, because
of its national implications for both Democrats and Republicans. It
is easy to understand why so many people want to know what will
happen in that race. But as it progresses, the need to move beyond
the matter of whose nose is closer to the finish line will become
clearer. After the up and downsides of their personalities, there
looms the more relevant concerns of what kind of policies each
would advocate in office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
