<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-JEKYLL-BOS &LR;      09-27 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-JEKYLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING THE STORY BEHIND `JEKYLL &AMP; HYDE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's no arguing the success of ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde,''
the musical that opens for a one-week run at the Wang Theatre on
Tuesday. It's broken the box-office record at Broadway's Plymouth
Theatre, and there's even a tribe of recidivists called
``Jekkies,'' some of whom have seen the show more than 300 times.
The soundtrack, featuring ``Someone Like You'' and ``This Is the
Moment,'' has sold more than 150,000 copies. In the Wang lobby,
fans can buy posters, CDs, T-shirts, and kitchen magnets. There's a
Web site (www.jekyll-hyde.com) where the latest news, CDs, and
links to cast members' home pages and fan clubs are available.
</P>
<P>
   Director David Warren believes he can explain the musical's
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience doesn't have to work hard,'' says Warren, whose
previous direction includes revivals of ``Summer and Smoke'' (with
Mary McDonnell and Harry Hamlin) and ``Holiday'' (with Laura Linney
and Tony Goldwyn). ``I've been in audiences where they have to work
hard to enjoy something, as if they're taking their medicine after
being told they're experiencing an important piece of theater. In
this one, the response is effortless. And the score is great. The
score is really accessible to audiences. Also, the performers _ and
I know this sounds like a cliche, but it's not _ the performers
give 110 percent every night. Those are the three elements. The
score, the performers and . . .'' Warren pauses. ``Oh, and the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget about the story.
</P>
<P>
   A tubercular Robert Louis Stevenson, under the influence of a
series of dreams in an English beach house in Bournemouth, wrote
``The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde'' in a matter of a
few days in 1885.
</P>
<P>
   According to biographer James-Pope Hennessy, Stevenson awoke
from a nightmare and furiously began writing down the story of a
doctor and a personality-altering white powder. Several critics and
biographers have pointed out that Stevenson's illnesses, which left
him bed-ridden and weak, were also the impetus for his literary
fantasies. Biographer Frank McLynn writes, ``As always, when ill,
he pretended to be another person . . . showing clearly his need to
detach himself from this tubercular alien `thing' that occupied his
body, and pointing once again to the conclusion that the deep
springs of Jekyll and Hyde came from his illness.'' Three days
after the nightmare, Stevenson read a manuscript of nearly 40,000
words to his wife, Fanny, and her son from a previous marriage,
Lloyd Osbourne. Fanny objected to the story's ``sensationalism''
and a fiery fight ensued. However, after cooling off and
considering Fanny's objections, Stevenson tossed the story into the
fireplace and started over, this time emphasizing the more
allegorical aspects of the story. Three days later, he completed
his rewritten version. After six weeks of additional polishing,
``The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde'' was published in
London. It was an immediate hit, selling 40,000 copies in Britain
and about 250,000 in pirated editions in the United States,
according to McLynn.
</P>
<P>
   Five months later, an adaptation appeared as a stage show at
London's L. C. O'Toole's Theatre. Since then, innumerable
productions and movies have used the story of the good doctor and
his mad alter ego as both an allegory for their particular times
and to fill their theatrical coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few decades, the story became a movie staple. John
Barrymore's 1920 version added bits of Oscar Wilde's ``The Picture
of Dorian Gray'' and several female characters. In 1922, F. W.
Murnau made ``Der Januskopf'' with Conrad Veidt. In 1931, Fredric
March won the Oscar for his performance in director Rouben
Mamoulian's version and, 10 years later, director Victor Fleming
gave us Spencer Tracy with Lana Turner and Ingrid Bergman. Tracy
didn't win an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there have been Jerry Lewis and Eddie Murphy as
nutty professors and ``Abbott and Costello Meet Dr. Jekyll and Mr.
Hyde'' in comedy adaptations and ``Dr. Jekyll and Ms. Hyde,'' the
gender-bending version, and Julia Roberts in the title role of
``Mary Reilly,'' or Dr. Jekyll as seen by the maid. Jack Palance
won an Emmy for hamming it up in a TV version and, in what must be
the most outrageous musical version, Kirk Douglas sings and dances
in a 1975 British TV movie. Dr. Jekyll has even been played by the
John Gielgud of canines, Wishbone, in an episode called ``Mixed
Breed.'' And that's just the surface of the interpretive and
commercial windfall that Jekyll and Hyde has become. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something powerful and mythic about a story of split
identity,'' says Warren. ``All cultures have these myths and folk
tales and the universal and lasting appeal of `Jekyll &AMP; Hyde' keeps
striking a chord in ours. We all have good and evil. We're so
afraid of the evil inside us that we're afraid to embrace _ and,
thus, control _ it. Every time the story's been retold there's a
twist added. In our version, Hyde is seductive. It deals with evil
in an attractive package. Hyde isn't an overt monster; he's a
seductive sexual predator.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like that murderer Robert Chambers who killed those women
in New York,'' he says. ``He used his charm. Evil charm.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous incarnations, Barrymore played Hyde as a drug
addict; there were explosions of sexual tension in March and
Tracy's portrayals; and the Hammer Film version, ``The Two Faces of
Dr. Jekyll,'' made Hyde the more attractive figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many interpretations,'' says Warren, ``because
the story is so open to so much. Drug abuse. Alcoholism. Sexual
identity. Schizophrenia. That's why the movies and plays have been
so successful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nabokov's dissent
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not according to some. Vladimir Nabokov, in a piece collected in
``Lectures on Literature,'' advised his Cornell students to
``ignore the fact that ham actors under the direction of pork
packers have acted in a parody of the book, which parody was then
photographed on a film and showed in places called theaters; it
seems to me that to call a movie house a theater is the same as to
call an undertaker a mortician.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases it's bad business to speculate on what a dead
author might think of the post-mortem reaction to his work. But not
in the case of Robert Louis Stevenson. It's easy to imagine that if
Stevenson came back to see the musical ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' or any of
the movies and TV shows, he wouldn't recognize it as his own. The
original story is structurally founded on two letters left by the
late Dr. Jekyll, who, if we are to believe Stevenson, was a rather
corpulent fellow _ a far cry from the matinee movie and theater
idols who have played him.
</P>
<P>
   And Stevenson would most likely resent seeing his story enacted
in a theater. In March 1885, he wrote to his dramaturgical
collaborator, William Henley, ``I have come unhesitatingly to the
opinion that the stage is only a lottery. . . . It is bad enough to
live by an art, but to think to live by an art combined with
commercial speculation _ that way madness lies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
