<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MILOSEVIC-KOSOVO-BOS &LR;      09-27 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILOSEVIC-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APATHY EMPOWERS MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ The nightly demonstrations began last week against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. But, as it turned out, there
was little reason for him to be displeased.
</P>
<P>
   The protests started with crowds smaller than rallies held last
month, and then continued to shrink even more.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic seems secure. Even opposition leaders acknowledge that
their efforts are not likely to topple him. If that is to happen,
it would probably come from some unseen hand orchestrating a palace
coup _ and no one considers that a sure bet.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Milosevic _ who has lost four wars in a row and
oversees a devastated economy _ still so secure?
</P>
<P>
   It could be that his control of the Army and police, combined
with a weak opposition, keeps threats at bay. But ordinary Serbians
say another reason for Milosevic's staying power is their own
apathy, which springs from their sense of powerlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of confused hopelessness has, for many, only increased
after the North American Treaty Organization's 11-week bombing
campaign that ended three months ago; they feel surrounded by
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like mad scientists are conducting experiments on our
country,'' said Srdjan Gojikovic-Gile, 38, leader of the longtime
Yugoslav band Electricni Orgazam, sitting in a
houseboat-turned-restaurant nicknamed Brodich, or Shippy, on the
Sava River.
</P>
<P>
   Here, on one recent night, an artist, a theology professor with
a military-style haircut, a fireman, an importer, and an off-duty
female soldier sat or stood around a table. They drank Serbian
beer. They laughed at each other's jokes, and they talked about
everything but politics.
</P>
<P>
   The subject wasn't avoided out of fear or ignorance _ these
people have keen political instincts _ but because the boat was a
place to escape the realities of their lives. And so the
conversation ranged from the pleasures of reading the postmodernist
philosopher Jean Baudrillard to the rantings of the chain-smoking
cook who wanted to serve only eggplant.
</P>
<P>
   The avoidance of politics is fed by the madness that has invaded
every aspect of life in Serbia, Gile explained later. For instance,
he said, pro-government parties were using at their rallies one of
his songs, ``The Whole Yugoslavia is Dancing to Rock 'n' Roll,''
while opposition rallies were using another one of his songs,
``It's Time for Action, Time for Change.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that wasn't crazy enough, he said, the choice of the song
stolen by the pro-government forces was truly bizarre. ``A big part
of (the song) is about being on an LSD trip,'' Gile said, laughing
as he sang a line:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's pick up the colors, which are falling from the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in a country that only Kafka could create in his
imagination,'' he said. ``We are in a prison colony. I think all
countries are like prisons in a way, but here in Serbia we live in
solitary confinement.''
</P>
<P>
   North of Belgrade, in the picturesque town of Pancevo, Sasa
Rakezic, 36, an artist, said the uncertainty has caused many people
to become sluggish and descend into depression.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rakezic, who draws comic strips under the pen name of
Aleksandar Zograf, said there also was an air of anticipation
around the country. He recently traveled to Budapest, and for a
while became seduced by the simple ease of life there. Then he
returned to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, I had some sort of feeling that there was
some drama going on here,'' said Rakezic. ``I felt I didn't want to
miss it, whatever it is, even if it hurts me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Serbia, perhaps drama is the only certainty left.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the nightly street demonstrations will continue into the
winter. Perhaps the electrical grids, heavily damaged by NATO's
graphite bombs, will collapse when demand rises in cold weather.
Perhaps early elections will be called. Perhaps Milosevic will
emerge even stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is clever, very clever,'' said a longtime diplomat
in Belgrade in a hushed tone, leaning over his coffee in a hotel
lobby that is a favorite of wealthy smugglers. ``Milosevic must
feel as if he were in a cage, and that makes this a most dangerous
time, a disorienting time _ for him and for everyone here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Donnelly is the Globe's diplomatic correspondent.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
