<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUMP-STARTING PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like any good, would-be synthesizer, Senator John Kerry has a
solid understanding of the opposites he seeks to attract in trying
to help public schools change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' he observes, correctly. ``Congress is
dillying and dallying at the fringes of this with code words. It
happens on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   From the right that means the robotic cry of ``Vouchers.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the Democratic world, that means _ in addition to the
necessary opposition to ideas that literally rob Peter to pay Paul
_ a constant refrain about reducing the size of classes and helping
fund the repair and construction of school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Back when Kerry first decided to dive into an effort to forge
consensus, he had a message for his own party that he has never
dropped. As he put it in an address at Northeastern University back
in mid-1998:
</P>
<P>
   ``To my fellow Democrats, let me say simply if we don't come up
with real answers for what ails our schools, then our defense on
public schools will become the defeat of the public schools. We
can't afford to be uncritical apologists for public schools that
work for our bureaucrats but not for our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, he put together a vehicle for change and joined
with a Republican freshman with an interest in working across the
aisle _ Senator Gordon Smith of Oregon _ to promote it. Since then,
support has steadily expanded, thanks to the work of the
new-thinking Democratic Ledership Council and a growing chorus of
Republican moderates.
</P>
<P>
   And now, it's crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Congress is a dysfunctional mess. But it has to forge
some kind of budget agreement with President Clinton before it can
get out of town for the year in about a month. And the president,
Kerry reports and White House officials confirm, is committed to
pressing for a downpayment on the Kerry-Smith reform program.
Within a responsible budget policy, there is no reason that $5
billion to $8 billion can't be found to begin a five-year effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans and Democrats can still battle over the
reauthorization of the government's basic elementary and secondary
school programs next year. But reform needs to start now, and it
can.
</P>
<P>
   As he explained it over breakfast last week and then in a speech
to a DLC forum here, the guiding principle of the plan is the
support of communities that have made the commitment to change.
</P>
<P>
   All but four or five states have made some kind of specific
commitment, 39 of them using the standards of the Goals 2000 effort
begun a decade ago under President Bush (but curiously ignored by
his voucher-fixated son).
</P>
<P>
   It would be, Kerry said, a system of positive reinforcement. The
great irony is that there is no mystery about the components of
reform and considerable consensus about ideas that can make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   The laundry list should be familiar: very specific goals for
educational improvement, the ability to change school officials and
teachers who aren't meeting standards, after-school programs and
longer school days and years, more charter schools and real
parental choice within the public school system, character
education, discipline codes and second-chance schools for problem
kids, and strong links with local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The systems that make these reform commitments will get the aid
and continue to get it as long as they meet those commitments.
Simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to acknowledge that the system that isn't
producing now is essentially a system designed for the people who
work in it, not for the kids it's supposed to educate,'' Kerry told
me.
</P>
<P>
   Tough language, but more descriptive than pejorative.
</P>
<P>
   In selling and shaping what became Kerry-Smith, the Democratic
Leadership Council's president, Al From, has been a critical ally.
A product of the public schools of the '50s in South Bend, Ind.,
with a healthy nostalgia for public school as part of a community's
shared experience, From is operating the party's most important
idea factory by far.
</P>
<P>
   The DLC's origin 15 years was marked by left-right fights as
Democrats struggled to come back from their multiple defeats from
the late '60s on, but today it is a unifying and innovate force.
And From has always had the ear of former DLC chairman Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanism to jump-start public school reform seems odd on
the surface. But shoe-horning it into a budget deal at the end of
this congressional session is in fact brilliant tactics in the face
of Congress' overall gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to break out of the ideological bind we've put
ourselves in,'' Kerry told the DLC last week.
</P>
<P>
   He just might pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
