<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-HEDWIG-BOS &LR;      09-27 1718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HEDWIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING INTO HEDWIG'S INCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The evening starts with a vivacious, tarted-up blond woman
goose-stepping down the aisle, taking the stage. This woman, named
Hedwig Schmidt, explains that she was once a young German boy who
grew up in East Berlin transfixed by American rock 'n' roll, which
he listened to on the radio with his head in the oven, for
privacy's sake. He yearned to be a girl; later he went under the
knife and became that girl, albeit a girl with ``an angry inch'' of
scar tissue remaining between her legs. She and her lover, an
American GI, married and moved to America, but once there, he left
her. She ended up in a Kansas trailer park where she befriended a
rock singer, Tommy Speck, whom she helped groom into a an
egotistical rock star named who called himself Tommy Gnosis. He
left her, too.
</P>
<P>
   And now, up on stage, she is a wisecracking, self-deprecating
cabaret singer, singing her tragi-comic tale for us, a
self-described ``girly-boy who became the internationally ignored
song-stylist barely standing here.'' With a full-tilt rock 'n' roll
band willing to crank away at a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound like a mainstream hit to you?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly surprising,'' says John Cameron Mitchell, the
director, star, and co-creator of ``Hedwig and the Angry Inch.'' It
became an off-off Broadway hit last year and this in New York at
the Jane Theater, garnering a heap of praise from the rock and
theater press, and it opens in Boston at the 57 Theatre Tuesday
night, running at least through Halloween. Musician-actor-celebs
like David Bowie and Madonna have gone and dug it. The buzz keeps
humming right along: This is one rock musical done right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is universal in a way I did not expect,'' Mitchell says, on
the telephone from New York, ``but I think the more specific you
are, the more universal you will be. Hollywood operates on the
opposite assumption, which is the broader and more homogeneous you
are'' the more successful you'll be _ that ``the lowest common
denominator equals universal. But you just don't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The process of creating ``Hedwig,'' a collaboration between
Mitchell and guitarist-songwriter Stephen Trask of the New York
band Cheater, began in 1994. ``I wanted to write something that was
truly rock 'n' roll and truly theater,'' says Mitchell, 36. ``I was
a fan of both and thought they were never fully integrated without
diluting one or the other. I started looking for a composer who
came from the rock world. Then Steve and I met by accident on a
plane, met again through some friends, I went to see his band, he
saw me in a show, and he said that he wanted to write something for
me. And I said, `Well, as a matter of fact there is something I was
starting to write.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Says Trask: ``If there was a mission, it was to be the first
rock musical that truly rocked. It was to make actual legitimate
contemporary-sounding rock music that worked dramatically. It
needed to be intimate, accessible, and have depth. . . . I always
had confidence that in some form these songs could be this
successful, but I didn't know what context that would be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The main way of keeping the rock uncorrupted,'' picks up
Mitchell, ``was to have the band on stage, make it like a rock gig
_ a play in the form of a rock gig. The key was not just making a
collection of songs, but integrating it into a story so that the
themes and metaphors were extended correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   Trask's band Cheater became Hedwig's band the Angry Inch for the
initial New York run. The group has now broken up (Hedwig took over
its identity and, along with poor management, helped caused its
demise, Trask says). Trask was in Boston two weeks ago working with
the hand-picked band he chose for this show. On board is Arlan
Feiles (keyboards/guitar/vocals), Perry Jay (drums, formerly of Big
Catholic Guilt and Rasputina), David P. Meyer (bass), and Jan
Tilley (guitar/vocals, formerly of Rude Girls and Ronnie Spector).
Feiles, Jay, and Meyer attended Berklee College of Music.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only regret is they are not playing my songs,'' Trask says.
``They are so good, with a wonderful personality, tight without
being robotic, expressive _ we've changed arrangements around with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as Cheater was?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the minimum _ at least equal.''
</P>
<P>
   There are four versions of ``Hedwig'' in production: in Boston,
Los Angeles, Germany, and New York (where Ally Sheedy has stepped
into the lead role, with Donovan Leitch, the son of the '60s
folksinger, to follow). In the spring, Mitchell begins work on a
film of ``Hedwig and the Angry Inch,'' with a six-week shoot. It
will leave the confines of the stage. Mitchell, who will direct and
star, is aiming for something along the lines of ``Nashville'' or
``All That Jazz.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Off color and offstage &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's play, which he calls ``sad-funny,'' is, among other
things, about the search for love, for one's other half. There is a
good deal of pathos in it, which does not, says Mitchell ``preclude
a filthy joke or two.'' Hedwig is forever breaking through the
mythical ``fourth wall'' and confronting the audience, sometimes
landing in someone's lap or following a patron into the restroom.
Randy double-entendres and in-jokes are scattered liberally, but
``Hedwig'' is not so insider-ish that it befuddles its audience
with its hipster quotient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted it to be exclusive,'' says Mitchell. ``I think
some drag, some rock, some theater does feel safer in excluding
people from your little in-jokes us-vs.-them situations. I tried
not to dumb it down or G-rate it, but at the same time I tried to
include everyone in the story-telling environment.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Mitchell says, he doesn't think of it as a drag
show. Rather, he says, ``I think of it more as a character using
drag. I watched a lot of drag queens at (the New York club) Squeeze
Box before I did it, and it is not pushed to where Squeeze Box was,
which was a full-drag rock 'n' roll club. . . . I never thought of
it as a gay story either. It was much more about: What am I?''
</P>
<P>
   Trask labored long and hard over the 10 songs. He had role
models for certain songs _ think of Patti Smith, the B-52's, and
Iggy Pop for the title number _ and he knew his task was to write
songs that would click upon first hearing. ``I wanted to have a
combination of that quirky '70s punk thing, but also had to be able
to incorporate a spoken word of some sort.'' For ``Exquisite
Corpse'' and ``Wicked Little Town,'' Trask says he researched Dada
and surrealism, for which he wrote lyrics about found objects and
rebuilding. ``There is that side,'' he says, ``but I wanted `Wicked
Little Town' to be a visceral moment and didn't want the audience
too bogged down in the narrative. I wanted it about feel, so the
song has a few purposes, the words to punch out in a non-linear
way, a barrage of words like `star, body, sewn-up' that you know
what they mean in the context of the play because we are that far
along enough. I also wanted to look at the way rock musicians get
`heavy' in a sophomoric kind of way and I wanted to allow myself to
be sophomoric in the writing at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   The closing song, ``Midnight Radio,'' is a dramatic, Bowie-esque
number that Trask calls ``a bittersweet triumph, a very emotional
song. That was about nine years of trudging around the clubs in New
York, carrying my equipment with duct tape and safety pins holding
it together, living with the electricity turned off, losing friends
to drugs and whatever, watching the scars that were left and also
watching the number of people who are still hanging on for the love
of music or rock 'n' roll culture. That is for me and my friends. I
started thinking about the way songs hit you at night'' when you're
alone ``and the whole night becomes still. A song shuts out the
whole world, but at the same time you are connected to it. And all
of a sudden, the song is over and you're left with the stillness of
the night. It was that image I tried to capture.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rosie futures &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Trask, who says he is ``comfortably middle class for the
first time in my life,'' the play opened doors, some of them pretty
strange. Rosie O'Donnell's people rang up to say Jenna Elfman
wanted to perform ``Wig in a Box'' on her show. Trask is on his way
to join the LA version of the Angry Inch _ which happens to be
Stone Temple Pilots minus jailed singer Scott Weiland _ for a
performance celebrating the soundtrack's release on Atlantic. He
says he was on the verge of giving up making commercial music and
following his boyfriend, an academic, to New Haven and was going to
``build it out from there, working on a smaller, more workable
scale. This has derailed that plan, but I am about to sign a
contract to produce another band who is going to record some of my
songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell says he plans to step back into the Hedwig role before
the movie starts shooting to hone his chops. ``I've been very
lucky,'' he says, ``because I have made a living as an actor since
college _ I've never had to take another job _ but there was a
point after `Hedwig' where I felt that I was not going to act for a
few years. I feel I passed the test and I just want to write and
direct for a while. But the (`Hedwig') movie will be my life for
about a year. I was at Sundance this summer working in the
filmmakers' lab and it was like being in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Before fame came calling, Mitchell was ``a normal actor for 15
years, doing a lot of TV, teen movies, and trashy movies'' as well
as working on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Mitchell continues, ``I feel (`Hedwig') is a
little suffocating, like I really needed to move on to another
project. But I have some friends who became TV stars and did not
quite trust their success because it was not based on something in
their mind that was good. I have no problem saying that we earned
this, so it feels fine. At times it feels like I need to get out of
it and it is too overwhelming _ too many mouths to feed in the
`Hedwig' world _ but other times, my paternal side comes out and I
do want to make sure the understudy is happy and tend to
everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
