<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEROES AND VILLAINS OF US-CHINA TIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A GREAT WALL 
Six Presidents and China: An Investigative History 
By Patrick Tyler 
PublicAffairs, 476 pp., illustrated, $27.50 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a risk of war between the United States and the
People's Republic of China over the issue of Taiwan, maintains
Patrick Tyler in the attention-grabbing prologue to his study of
US-Sino relations. And, he adds as if to hammer home the point,
``it is no longer alarmist to say so.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler makes only a circumstantial case for his claim _ and even
manages to undercut it with an on-the-other-hand comment that there
are ``constant'' back-channel communications between Chinese and
Taiwanese leaders ``from which Americans are excluded.''
Nonetheless, he has provided, in ``A Great Wall,'' an account of
political blunders and Beltway infighting that suggests that
America could all too heedlessly stumble into the conflict he
foresees.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler is a former New York Times bureau chief in Beijing. But
unlike other journalists who have returned from exotic postings and
emptied their notebooks into what-I-saw-over-there books, he has
tried to find out what was going on back home while he was away.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Great Wall'' is based on fresh interviews with the men who
shaped _ or misshaped _ America's China policy over the past 30
years and on a study of newly declassified documents from the White
House, the State Department, and the CIA. And Tyler is a good
enough journalist to turn what could be a ponderous slog through
American diplomatic history into a riveting and endlessly
fascinating story, one that comes complete with heroes and
villains.
</P>
<P>
   And always in the background is Taiwan _ ``where today,'' Tyler
writes, ``Taiwanese and American technicians are erecting the
foundations for a future war'' with China. That risk of war, he
writes, was ``most recently and startlingly apparent'' in March
1996 _ a crisis triggered by President Clinton's ``abrupt
decision'' 10 months earlier to allow Taiwan President Lee Teng-hui
to attend his class reunion at Cornell University. That event
turned out to be not the ``private visit'' Lee had promised, but
the occasion for a flag-waving speech proclaiming the sovereignty
of the nationalist Republic of China on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   China responded on the eve of Taiwan's presidential elections
with the test firings of surface-to-surface missiles into ``target
boxes'' just outside Taiwan's principal harbors. And what appears
to Tyler as the worst aspect of the crisis was that at no time over
the crisis weekend did Clinton or his advisers ``address the larger
question _ to what extent would America defend Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his account, Tyler tracks other instances in which
American leaders were either unprepared or unwilling to address the
questions raised by by events in China _ or diplomatic feelers from
China's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It begins, in Tyler's account, with President Nixon's failure to
give the Soviet Union ``a clear, unambiguous statement of US
opposition to a military attack on China'' in 1968. It continues
with the revelation of CIA involvement in Angola that scuttled an
understanding between President Ford and Deng Xiaoping for mutual
anti-Soviet action there. And on it goes with the CIA's
heavy-handed pursuit of weapons it thought China was shipping to
Iran on the container ship Yinhe.
</P>
<P>
   This lack of coherence marks even the successes, like the
normalization of relations in December 1978, which Tyler writes
came ``as a result of all-out civil war within the Carter
administration,'' between Secretary of State Cyrus Vance and
National Security Adviser Zbigniew Brezinski. Credit for the
success, in Tyler's view, belongs to Ambassador Leonard Woodcock,
an unlikely figure who emerges as one of Tyler's heroes.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes policy verged on farce, as when special envoy
Michael Armacost went to the White House before leaving on a secret
mission to Beijing as a prelude to Clinton's abandonment of his
hardline human rights policy. But rather than the expected
15-minute policy discussion with Clinton, Armacost gets a handshake
and a brief word or two _ because that morning Paula Jones had
filed her sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's Washington-centric approach is at its best in his
account of the Bush administration's reaction to the Tiananmen
demonstrations _ a subject on which it might be thought that there
is litte new to report.
</P>
<P>
   As the crisis built, Tyler writes, ``all Washington could think
about was Mikhail Gorbachev,'' concerned that ``the coming
rapproachment between China and the Soviet Union did not come at
the expense of the United States.'' But in the background was the
hostility between the outgoing ambassador, Winston Lord, a
hardliner who is one of Tyler's villains, and the more
accomodationist Bush State Department. And at least partly because
of that hostility, when the military crackdown came, ``the Bush
administration was unprepared to deal with the horrific truth'' of
the assault on the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Great Wall'' is so riveting an account of what was happening
in Washington that the reader is left with a sense of regret _ that
we are unlikely to get so riveting an inside account of what was
happening in the inner circles of Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
