<HEADLINE>
LAST CALL FOR MORSE, BUT NEVER FOR HIS GENRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, England _ I was having a double vodka and lime at the
White Hart when the word ran through the pub like a bad best bitter
that Inspector Morse was dead. The back room was crowded with
youngish types right out of ``ER,'' maybe because the John
Radcliffe Hospital is just along the road, but calm as they might
all be during their emergency routines, there was a confusion of
rumor that no one could sort out: Morse had been struck down by a
maddened Sergeant Lewis, deranged at last when the skinflint chief
inspector had left him for the hundredth time with the bar tab.
Soon after we had the true word off the telly: Morse had died in a
diabetic coma while in the hospital, the victim of too much drink.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery and detective fiction is alive and well in Britain when
the death of a fictional Thames Valley copper, however beloved he
might be, is the subject of headlines across the land and
breathless television reports. Some pretty dirty journalism _
though for Britain, land of the dirtiest journalism this side of
Djakarta, perhaps not so dirty at that _ on the part of the Daily
Telegraph, a paper with a distinctly conservative bent, had
revealed the ending of author Colin Dexter's 13th, and definitively
last, Inspector Morse mystery.
</P>
<P>
   John Thaw, who has played the morose Morse in far more than 13
made-for-television mystery films (Dexter having written scripts
from scratch, or having adapted some inferior short stories to feed
the demand for more of the lushly decadent Oxford-based films),
professed himself to be very angry and condemned the Telegraph as
spiteful, while Colin Dexter looked on, no doubt a bit pleased with
the extra publicity for ``The Remorseful Day,'' but mainly, if we
are to believe him, happy to have all the killings stop. The crime
rate in Oxford has been enormous since the day in 1975 when Morse
more-or-less muddled his way through to a solution in the debut
novel, ``The Last Bus to Woodstock,'' the dead totaling, depending
on which newspaper one reads, between 77 and 80, and including
three heads of houses, or college masters.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare but not unknown for a writer to grow tired of his or
her own creation and try to put an end to it all. Sir Arthur Conan
Doyle famously tried to be rid of Sherlock Holmes, sending him to
his death (it was widely assumed) over the Raichenbach Falls, and
then had to rethink himself as his fans raged, and bring the
masterful Holmes back from the precipice and a period of quiet bee
farming. Nicolas Freeling gunned down his Dutch detective, Van der
Valk, without any foreshadowing and has never been as popular
since. Hercule Poirot died in Agatha Christie's ``Curtain,'' but
she had the wisdom, or guile, to hold the book back until after her
death. Many readers, I among them, felt that John D. MacDonald was
one book away from killing his Travis McGee, for ``Pale Grey for
Guilt'' betrayed a man no longer able to respond quickly to all of
Florida's mean challenges, but MacDonald died first.
</P>
<P>
   Why should Colin Dexter not have some freedom at last, able to
put on the shelf the satisfaction of having created a most
remarkable, infuriating, and appealing member of the fictional
police fraternity, the ``melancholy, sensitive, vulnerable,
independent, ungracious, mean-pocketed Morse,'' as Dexter himself
described him? The Inspector Morse tours of Oxford, many of them
run by enterprising undergraduates; the use of Morse novels in
courses on the detective story, to illustrate just how intriguing a
clue-laden plot can still be in these post-Christie and Sayers
days; and reruns of the uneven Morse films, which at their best
were seldom equaled and never exceeded on PBS's ``Mystery'' series;
all of this will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone who read the penultimate Inspector Morse
novel, ``Death Is Now My Neighbor,'' could see the remorseful day
coming. Morse is drinking too much, boozing by 10:30 in the
morning, often having three pints of Bass, and clearly suffering
from either prostate cancer or diabetes midway into the novel. Most
of the reviewers appeared to have missed the significance of the
title Dexter gave this novel, and to have been drawn off by the red
herring of the discovery of Morse's first name, which he had
succeeded in keeping even from his ever-patient sidekick Lewis for
21 years (that name was, as any fan knows, Endeavour, Morse's
father having been enamored with the voyages of Captain James
Cook), but that Morse would not be around much longer was clear
enough to anyone who had read the entire series.
</P>
<P>
   I give nothing away here about ``The Remorseful Day,'' which all
can still read with great pleasure as a superb mystery, the
Telegraph having put the allegedly newsworthy item behind us, other
than to say that it is a triumphant if sad conclusion to the
series. In the end Sergeant Lewis visits his old friend and boss in
the mortuary and, bending down, puts his lips to Morse's forehead
and whispers two final words: ``Goodbye, sir.'' A commentator for
the self-important Guardian suggests this may be gay necrophilia.
Compared to this garbage, was the Telegraph's betrayal of Dexter so
bad?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the mystery is thriving in Old Blimey. The Independent has
just revealed that Prime Minister Tony Blair and his wife have hung
a portrait of Baroness James of Holland Park at 10 Downing Street
and suggested this was a ``trendy'' thing to do. Perhaps; the
Baroness James is, of course, the writer P. D. James, the greatest
of all successors to Christie and Sayers. Here at the White Hart, I
raise a glass of Old Speckled Hen and walk down Ethelred Close,
where (it is said) King Ethelred the Unready had his royal hunting
lodge. There will always be an England where the mystery novel is
read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
