<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS BAY AREA'S VIBRANT ECONOMY FACES PERILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A study released Monday said the robust economy
in the San Francisco Bay area is threatened by challenges that
could cripple the region's ability to sustain prosperity and
preserve the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the challenges is a lack of affordable housing for
the work force and escalating traffic congestion, according to the
report, ``The Bay Area: Winning in the New Global Economy.'' The
report, issued Monday by the Bay Area Economic Forum and the Bay
Area Council, said the region's continued economic prosperity and
its national and global competitiveness are not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will depend on the vision and vigilance of its civic
leaders,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, prepared by consultants at McKinsey &AMP; Co. in San
Francisco, working with the sponsors, show that the Bay Area has
completed ``a remarkable transformation from an industrial and
defense-heavy economy to a predominantly knowledge-based economy
that is the most productive in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The report found that productivity ranks first among seven
regions with which the San Francisco area was compared in computers
and electronics, bioscience, telecommunications, multimedia and
environmental technology. The cites used for comparison were
Boston, Charlotte, N.C., Houston, Los Angeles, New York, Phoenix
and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Bay Area also have the nation's highest
personal income, at $38,300 per capita, an improvement over 1995
when the area was second to New York. Today, New York's per capita
income is $35,900.
</P>
<P>
   The study says the area's cycle of economic prosperity is
possible, ultimately, because the region offers unique
opportunities. Its companies attract skilled workers who benefit
from the economic potential the region presents and these workers
are critical to economic success, the study notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future success of the Bay Area hinges on its ability to
continue attracting highly talented entrepreneurs and skilled
workers with business and employment opportunities, high quality of
life and innovation infrastructure,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these entrepreneurs and skilled workers will locate and
remain in the Bay Area only if the value of this opportunity is
affordable. The Bay Area could fall victim to its own prosperity if
rising incomes and prices set in motion a worsening inflationary
spiral,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   It adds that the area's advantage over the other regions in
productivity is being eroded by the cost of doing business,
especially the increasing cost of living experienced by the work
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any other city in the country or the world would love to be in
the position the Bay Area is right now,'' said Sean Randolph,
president of the Bay Area Economic Forum. ``The negatives are not
by themselves from our successes or our prosperity. Housing has not
met the new job creation and population growth, but that is not the
fault of the economy. That is the fault of policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that transportation, which residents
routinely rank as their top concern, is not keeping pace with
growth. It rated the Bay Area 47th out of 350 locations in overall
transportation quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
