<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-2ND &LR;      09-27 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... as well.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Half of all Americans are now considered overweight, and
one-third are obese. Type II diabetes, which accounts for 90
percent of diabetes and is closely associated with excess weight,
is at least three times more prevalent among Americans than it was
in the 1960s, and eight times more common than in 1935. ``Among
people over 65, about 20 percent have diabetes,'' notes Dr. Edward
S. Horton of Joslin Diabetes Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gene pool hasn't changed'' to produce this epidemic, says
Dr. Robert H. Eckel of the University of Colorado Health Sciences
Center, who chairs the American Heart Association's committee on
nutrition. What has changed is the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the average adult male needs about 2,500 calories a day
to meet basic energy needs and the average woman needs about 2,000,
the US food industry produces enough to feed everybody 3,800
calories a day _ and somebody is eating all those extra calories.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are dissecting the chemical controls that govern the
use of glucose and insulin by lean muscle; so far the evidence
underscores the importance of maintaining muscle mass. ``What we've
discovered is that exercise and insulin both increase glucose
uptake by the movement of glucose transporter molecules called
GLUT-4 to the surface of muscle cells,'' says Laurie Goodyear, a
Joslin Clinic researcher. ``Trained'' muscle contains more GLUT-4,
it turns out. Goodyear hopes her research will lead to a drug that
mimics exercise's effect on muscle chemistry _ not to make exercise
unnecessary, but to augment its benefits. ``You can't exercise all
the time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   While we're waiting for an ``exercise pill,'' the current
consensus is that exercise is crucial in simultaneously reducing
weight and lowering the risks of diabetes and other maladies
associated with age and obesity, such as heart disease and
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Even a modest amount of exercise _ and a weight loss of only 5
to 10 percent _ can produce measurable health benefits. Researchers
have found that exercise can increase metabolic rate by up to 15
percent _ enough to give an elder individual the metabolic rate of
a 30-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   By riding the exercise bicycle several times a week in a Joslin
Clinic program, for instance, Ira Phillips has lost 11 pounds and
lowered her daily insulin dose by 24 percent over the past five
months. She'd like to lose another 40 pounds, but experts are
divided on whether that much weight loss is necessary or beneficial
among people in their 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has also begun doing light weight-lifting at home. To
preserve or build lean muscle mass, that kind of ``resistance''
training is increasingly recognized as an important addition to a
regimen of regular ``endurance'' exercise, such as brisk 30-minute
walks.
</P>
<P>
   Muscle-building, researchers now know, is possible at any age.
``We're talking about simple things that anyone can do at home,''
says Miriam Nelson of Tufts, author of ``Strong Women Stay Young''
and ``Strong Women Stay Slim.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson says her older patients are often pleasantly surprised to
find they like weight training. ``I work with a lot of older women
who have never been strong in their lives,'' she says. ``People
love feeling their muscles getting stronger. Everyday activities
become easier. Your body feels different, and becomes firmer.''
</P>
<P>
   And it will probably last longer, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard A. Knox's e-mail address is rknox(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
