<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GARTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKS SEES NO LOSS IN PLAYING GAINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Garth Brooks tired of country music? No way, and he's stung
by any suggestion that he is. Brooks becomes upset when recalling
the words of a country disc jockey who said recently, ``Now that
country music is down, Garth is bailing out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That really hurt,'' said Brooks, calling from his Nashville
home to discuss a new, short-term career move in which he departs
from country to make pop-rock music under the name of Chris Gaines,
a fictitious rocker who is the subject of a Paramount Pictures film
to be released next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooks album, ``Garth Brooks in the Life of Chris Gaines,''
comes out Tuesday (Sept. 28). In it, Brooks indulges his love of
musical influences from the Beatles, James Taylor, Steely Dan,
Fleetwood Mac, the Eagles, and Bob Dylan _ all of whom he heard
growing up, when he was not listening to George Jones, George
Strait, and other country icons.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressively, Brooks pulls it off. The album has a retro
feel _ it's designed to be a ``Greatest Hits'' of tunes from the
fictional character's last 15 years _ and Brooks, though writing
none of the songs and singing in higher keys than his country hits,
sounds entirely believable. He also sounds entirely different _ a
smooth-voiced change from the twangy Garth style that has helped
him sell 95 million albums, a sales record second only to the
Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   The new album was produced by Don Was, the Grammy-winning
producer who worked on Bonnie Raitt's ``Nick of Time'' CD. It was
his idea to get Brooks involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motivation was that somebody had faith in me to cut a
pop-rock album on a ficitious character,'' said Brooks. ``And once
I got into it, it was, `Holy cow, these people have invested their
money and their faith in me. I'd better get off my butt and come
through with it.' It was fun, but in no way did this thing start by
me going, `Oh, I've got to get out of this Garth Brooks thing.' I
don't know why people have kept harping on that, as if there's some
kind of story there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to get out of what I've got,'' he said. ``No,
this was just a compliment and a challenge to do.'
</P>
<P>
   Brooks admitted, though, that some hardcore Garth fans ``may
want to sit this one out.'' He knows some fans have also been
puzzled by his new look for the project _ with hair falling over
his eyes and a hint of chin growth for bohemian effect _ but ``you
do it because you're playing a character, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   That character will soon be on active display. The
Brooks-as-Gaines impersonation hits overdrive with a TV special on
NBC this Wednesday (CBS at 8 p.m.), in which Brooks will sing tunes
from the album. Appearances are also lined up on ``The Tonight Show
with Jay Leno'' Tusday the ``Rosie O'Donnell Show'' and ``Late
Night with Conan O'Brien'' on Tuesday, and ``The Today Show'' on
Wednesday. Also, VH1 is producing a mock-documentary on Gaines for
some time in November. It's in the vein of the cable station's
``Behind the Music'' series, but won't be called that.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount Pictures is readying the film on Gaines for next fall,
titled ``The Lamb.'' A soundtrack album, which Brooks has
contracted for, will be released at that time. It's supposed to be
the ``Sargent Pepper'' of Gaines's career _ and the first track
will be produced by Babyface. ``That should set the tone for it,''
said Brooks, who will perform as Gaines in the film, but won't
otherwise act in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard story to get all the information on, but once you
get it, Chris is just a normal, existing artist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the fictional gist: Gaines was born in 1967 in Brisbane,
Australia, the son of Olympic swimmers. He moved to Los Angeles
when he was 5. His career took off in the late '80s, but he
suffered a car accident in 1992 that led to plastic surgery and a
more reclusive lifestyle. Along the way, his music matured from
rock to R &AMP; B, all reflected in Brooks's treatments of the songs,
which were mostly written by the trio of Gordon Kennedy, Wayne
Kirkpatrick, and Tommy Sims. (They're the team who wrote writing
the Grammy-winning hit ``Change the World'' for Eric Clapton,
though Sims is also known as the bassist on Bruce Springsteen's
non-E Street Band tour in 1992.)
</P>
<P>
   The musicians backing Brooks-as-Gaines are not from Brooks's
band, but include backup singer Crystal Talifero (from Billy Joel's
group), bassist Hutch Hutchinson (from Raitt's band), keyboardist
Greg Phillinganes (who has toured with Clapton), and drummer Kenny
Aronoff (who has toured with Melissa Etheridge).
</P>
<P>
   The album's first single, ``Lost in You,'' was recently the No.
1 most-added song on Top 40 radio. ``I get lost in you _ what is
this feeling?'' sings Brooks, sounding like a cross between Richard
Marx and Smokey Robinson. The tempo picks up in the Dire
Straits-like ``White Flag'' and the song ``Maybe,'' which
incorporates the hippie refrain from the Youngbloods' ``Get
Together.'' It's supposed to show Gaines's idealism even though the
song is old enough that ``he would have had to have written it at
age 1,'' Brooks said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious campy elements to all of this _ and obvious
questions about the public's acceptance of it. Yet the music is
delivered with a straight face, a journeyman's craft, and an
emotional high from Brooks, who clearly has his heart in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you saw what Chris believed in _ he became an easy
character to love,'' said Brooks, who won't tour behind the record,
but is proud of the results. ``When people ask what's the
difference between this and a Garth record, I say, `Man, Garth
records are simple to make. This whole thing is not.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
