<HEADER>
A7495 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NC-FLOOD-BOS &LR;      09-27 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-FLOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN TRIES TO PUT SOGGY PIECES BACK TOGETHER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCEVILLE, N.C. _ Their Bibles are lost in flood waters that
carry the caskets of their ancestors, the carcasses of their pets,
and the remains of their neighbors who defied the unfathomable.
</P>
<P>
   Their churches are buried in the sea of death. So is everything
they scratched together with the dirt-poor wages they earned making
toy Santa Clauses and frozen pastries on factory assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   As heirs to the nation's first black-governed town, chartered by
freed slaves after the Civil War, the homeless refugees from
Princeville fled with little more than faith 10 nights ago when
Hurricane Floyd ripped open a sprawling dike and turned the Tar
River against the townspeople.
</P>
<P>
   Like characters in ``Their Eyes Were Watching God,'' Zora Neale
Hurston's fictitious account of a flood ravaging another small,
black community, ``They seemed to be staring at the dark, but their
eyes were watching God.''
</P>
<P>
   Their eyes still are. With the grace of God and the spirit of
their forebears, the proud souls of Princeville said this week that
they plan to lift up their historic town again as a landmark of
self-determination. They made the vow even as they languished on
borrowed cots in crowded, grimy shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the native sons, the last black princes,'' said George
Harrison, 66, the descendant of Princeville mayors and police
chiefs, as he sat on the edge of a rickety cot in the corner of a
hallway of a high school in nearby Tarboro that now is home to
hundreds of his former neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pride is in us, and it will push us,'' Harrison said.
``This is not the end of Princeville. It will come back greater now
than it has ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Their town is one of scores in North Carolina that have been
altered irreparably by a flood that, metereologists said, was the
worst to strike the region since Columbus discovered America.
Sewage-treatment plants and lagoons of hog waste have overflowed
and contaminated drinking water supplies, while the floating
carcasses of hundreds of thousands of hogs, chickens, and turkeys
embody the $1 billion of farm damages.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's deadliest hurricane in a generation, Floyd has
officially claimed nearly 70 lives _ 42 in eastern North Carolina
alone _ and the toll is expected to grow as the waters recede in
Princeville, where the flood ran deepest.
</P>
<P>
   The last survivors of the deluge escaped from Princeville on
flatbed trucks, boats, and helicopters. Like Eva Gray, 31, a
factory worker, many of them nearly died as they stood helplessly
in shoulder-deep water, gagging as they breathed fumes from
ruptured fuel tanks, and watched the bodies of dead animals float
past them.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said she heard neighbors shriek for help from nearby roofs
as she sobbed and shuddered in the churning waters until a rescue
boat arrived. She abandoned everything she owned inside her home,
including $500 in cash she had ``saved for hard times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nightmares every night,'' Gray said in the high school
library, a sanctuary for those who survived some of the worst
trauma. ``My nerves are so tense. It's going to be hard, but I've
got to get my life back.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeville, too, wants its life back. But the community has
survived many calamities since the town was born in 1885, settled
by newly freed slaves who found refuge there after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   After the troops left, the former slaves built their own homes,
bought their land, and opened their own schools and churches,
including the Mount Zion Primitive Baptist Church, whose
103-year-old altar and pews remained under water Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Princeville's founders survived white supremacists bent on
extinguishing this symbol of black liberation. Later generations
overcame agricultural disasters, the tug of faraway jobs after the
industrial revolution, and a spate of mismanagement that in 1997
caused the state for a year to take over the town's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Princeville also endured floods. Many floods. Though they were
small compared with Floyd's, the floods were supposed to end after
a 3-mile-wide earthen dike was built in 1965 to protect Princeville
from the Tar River's fury. And there was such promise in the air
that town leaders were set to begin offering a historical tour to
celebrate their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is nothing, and rebuilding will first require
restoring a sense of safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us really don't want to go back,'' said Darlene
Spell, 27, who lost her house, two cars, and two dogs in the
disaster. ``There's so many bad memories there, and I feel like if
it happened once, it will happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs of despair and deprivation abound in the teeming shelters
around Princeville. As National Guard units stand sentinel outside
and military helicopters ferry in supplies, the Princeville
refugees sleep nearly shoulder to shoulder, surrounded by food and
secondhand clothes they have scrounged during their 10-day ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   They have no running water. No showers. Only portable toilets.
They use canvas tents for changing rooms. There is a critical
shortage of personal hygiene products and underwear. Many refugees
are wearing the same clothes they wore when they left home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look into people's eyes, and you can see the depression
setting in,'' said Shirley Bell, 45, guarding her family's meager
belongings in the school gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, we are proud people,'' Bell said. ``We are
hard-working people, and we never imagined having to stand in line
for food and clothes. We never thought this could happen to us, in
little Princeville.''
</P>
<P>
   She scanned the gym, as families sat sullenly, waiting for Red
Cross workers to serve their next meal: chili and rice, and canned
peaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tearing us apart,'' Bell said. ``But we're survivors.
Eventually, we'll get it back together.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, after a helicopter tour of the devastated
area, vowed last week to help Princeville and other decimated
communities recover. But the questions remain: how, and when?
</P>
<P>
   Contaminated by raw sewage, fuel, and rotting carcasses,
Princeville may need to be razed before it can be resurrected. In
the meantime, the refugees will be housed in portable trailers, and
many of Princeville's elderly fear they will never again inhabit
the town they helped make a monument to will and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   But the optimists among the town's refugees expect to rebuild
with the help of state and federal grants and loans. Just as
feverishly as they stacked thousands of sandbags against the dike
to fight flood waters, many of the survivors said, they expect
residents to rally to put their washed-out town together again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flood just wiped everything out, and my dream house is
gone with it,'' said Wendy Perkins, 37, a furniture company
secretary. ``But my children and I found a way to get out alive,
and now we're going to find a way to keep our town alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others in Princeville, in the cradle of the Bible Belt, are
also certain they will witness their town's redemption and a
brighter tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flood was the Lord saying, `I'm just going to give them
some water to let them know this is my world,' '' said Geraldine
Parker. ``It was a wake-up call for people who had lost their way.
Now, the Lord will help us make Princeville a better place. We're
all ready for that day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
