<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-27 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME CONVENIENCE CHECKS ARE JUST BAIT FOR CREDIT-CARD TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN and BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We know credit-card companies are in business to make money, but
sometimes they just go too far.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Geoffrey B. Rosenberg, the president of a
South Boston auto and truck parts business. He is bright,
articulate and savvy when it comes to money, but even he didn't see
what was coming with his A T &AMP; T Universal Card.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg, 40, decided to buy a set of bookcases for $2,800 and
wanted to make his money go as far as possible. So he bought the
bookcases with his GE MasterCard, earning card benefits with the
purchase. He then used an A T &AMP; T convenience check, which he had
received in the mail, to pay off the GE balance.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience checks are a popular marketing tool in the
credit-card industry, choking mail boxes across the country on a
daily basis. The checks usually are used for balance transfers from
another credit card, but often can be tapped for any purchase. They
typically carry a low teaser interest rate that remains in effect
for a limited period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg's A T &AMP; T convenience check carried a 4.9 percent
interest rate until February, well below the card's regular rate of
16.7 percent. The pitch letter that accompanied the convenience
check called it a ``practical financial tool we think you'll enjoy
using.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg, who says he closely read all the fine print
accompanying the check, figured he would use it as a bridge. He
planned to pay off the convenience check balance entirely by
February, incurring relatively small interest charges.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, he made his first payment of $379, designating
that $73 should go to pay off the existing, higher-interest-rate
balance on his card with the remainder to go toward the balance on
the convenience check.
</P>
<P>
   But when he got his statement the following month, Rosenberg
discovered that just the opposite had been done. The bulk of his
$379 had been applied to the convenience check balance, and only a
minimum payment had been made on the existing card balance, which
had ballooned during the month because of additional purchases.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the credit-card company was maximizing its revenues,
getting rid of the convenience check balance with the lower
interest rate as fast as possible while making sure Rosenberg paid
the higher rate on his existing balance as long as possible. The
only way he could get rid of the existing balance was to pay off
the entire convenience check balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this albatross that's going to hang around your neck
forever,'' Rosenberg said. ``If more people understood what game
was being run on them, they'd be much more careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg cried foul, but company officials referred him to the
fine print of his credit-card contract. It said: ``We may allocate
payments to amounts owed on your account in the manner we deem
appropriate, including but not limited to, applying payments to
promotional balances, such as balance transfers, before applying
them to purchases and cash advances.''
</P>
<P>
   Most other credit-card companies use similar language in their
contracts. Some, such as Fleet Bank of Boston, spell out the terms
right in the convenience check offer.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Mindler, a spokeswoman for Citibank, which owns the A T &AMP;
T card, said the company chooses to retire the convenience check
balances first because the teaser rate expires fairly quickly. She
said the company doesn't want customers to be hit with a major
interest-rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   The helpful, Big Brother attitude doesn't ring true to us. The
reason the banks allocate payments to the lower-interest-rate
balances first is because that approach makes them the most money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He found a credit trap and fell into it,'' said Edgar Dworsky,
a consumer advocate, commenting on Rosenberg's plight. Dworsky said
the only way around the trap is to pay off all existing balances
before using a convenience check.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to become the credit-card industry's latest victim,
Rosenberg used a home equity line of credit to pay off both A T &AMP; T
balances and secure extra money for home repairs.
</P>
<P>
   He then cut up his credit card and sent it back to A T &AMP; T, a
bit poorer but wiser. ``There are six ways to Sunday to play with
credit cards,'' he said, ``but there are also lots of ways to get
burned.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitfalls of paying in advance
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More and more people pay for their funerals in advance, but some
recent cases in Massachusetts highlight some of the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Board of Registration in Funeral
Services suspended George Williams, who owns three funeral homes in
Arlington and Somerville, for five years for failing to honor
so-called preneed contracts clients had signed.
</P>
<P>
   In one of three instances cited by the board, a woman paid
$3,305 in 1991 to lock in prices for a casket, a burial plot at
Cambridge Cemetery and various funeral services. But when she died
in 1997, Williams allegedly took advantage of her brother's
unfamiliarity with the preneed contract to pad his pocket. He
convinced the brother a more expensive casket was needed, told him
another $1,400 was required to secure a burial plot at Cambridge
Cemetery and that more money was needed to pay for the funeral
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the suspension, the board ordered Williams to
notify all other clients with preneed contracts of his suspension
and allow them to transfer their contracts to other funeral homes.
Williams owns the Daniel F. O'Brien Funeral Home in Somerville and
the Berglund-Williams and the Berglund-Williams O'Brien Funeral
Homes in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, the board suspended the license of Toni L.
Bullock and shut down her Mattapan funeral home for failing to keep
adequate records of preneed contracts. Now her clients face the
task of trying to get their money back.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Blanchard, an official with the Memorial Society of
Boston, a consumer group, said the board's rare disciplinary
actions were a positive sign. But he said the cases illustrate the
risks of paying for funerals in advance. He noted the state has no
fund to guarantee preneed contracts and only one inspector to
watchdog its 700 funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Carlson, in a book on how to make funeral arrangements,
said preneed contracts are great in concept but often not so good
in reality. ``It always pays to plan ahead, but it rarely pays to
pay ahead,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --A big plus of credit cards. After hearing a $1,000 refund tale
from a reader, we're reminded of the wisdom of using a credit card
for major purchases if possible. This past summer, a consumer tried
to return a $1,000 portable air conditioner when it failed to cool
down a room as promised. The unit was charged on his MasterCard.
The merchant balked at a full refund, but later issued a refund
minus a 20 percent (or $200) restocking fee. Still upset, our
reader wrote to MasterCard and invoked the federal government's
Regulation Z. This regulation (the details of which are on the back
of your credit-card statements) enables customers to withhold
payment if they believe a billing error has occurred or if they
dispute the quality of the goods or services received. The
credit-card issuer then investigates. In this case, MasterCard
ruled the Brookline man didn't have to pay the $200.
</P>
<P>
   --Spam clarification. After our column on ways to reduce junk
e-mail, also known as spam, a reader said we should have pointed
out that an Internet service provider can be unwittingly used, or
hijacked, by someone in a spamming scheme. He is right. The codes
in the e-mail message may reveal the spammer's ISP, but also may
indicate the name of an ISP that was an innocent intermediary in
delivering the message.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GENOME-MAPPING-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     09-27 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-MAPPING-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (a and f coding)  
 UNDATED: ... in Cambridge.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But others see reason for enthusiasm. ``There is a risk of us
overselling the usefulness (of the genome), but one doesn't have to
do that, because it's going to be just terrific,'' said Victor
McKusick, the Johns Hopkins University biologist sometimes called
the father of genetic medicine. ``It's not going to come next year
or the year after that, but the coming century is going to be a
very exciting one of profiting from the available information from
the genome.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, information gleaned from the project has become a
valuable resource for thousands of medical researchers, including
many at Boston's hospitals and universities.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all big pharmaceutical companies have refocused their
drug-discovery processes around the new understanding of genes, and
some _ including Pfizer Inc., Amgen Inc., Bayer AG, and Merck &AMP; Co.
_ have set up shop in Boston or Cambridge or have plans to do so.
Together, the two cities are becoming known as ``Genetown.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 people are expected to visit Boston next March for a
biotechnology conference, making it the largest such conference
ever held, according to the Massachusetts Biotechnology Council,
which will host the event.
</P>
<P>
   The new genetic knowledge is also expected to add to the state's
base of 25,000 biotechnology jobs. Not only are companies likely to
spend millions of dollars on using it to develop medical
treatments, but they will likely hire workers and spend money to
sequence the DNA of hundreds of other organisms for the clues they
give to how human genes work. Moreover, the human genome will be
mapped again and again to find the small but significant
differences in the genetic code that make individuals vary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be big changes,'' predicts Jonathan
Rothberg, president of the New Haven, Conn. biotech company
CuraGen. ``The human variations we discover and the associations we
make between human genes and disease will be the basis of medicine
for the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several private companies trying to catalog all human
genes. One of them, Celera Genomics Group of Rockville, Md., says
that it will use a different technique than the Human Genome
Project to sequence human DNA and that it will finish the job two
years before the government's final version is done. However,
unlike the Human Genome Project, Celera will charge others a fee to
see most of its data.
</P>
<P>
   William Haseltine, chairman and chief executive of Human Genome
Sciences Inc., also of Rockville, says his company has already
catalogued 95 percent of the medically useful human genes. Instead
of scanning the chemical sequence of DNA, Haseltine's company found
genes by looking for the telltale signs they leave when they are
active within cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Human Genome Project sequence is completed, it will
be a rather meaningless footnote to a revolution that is well under
way,'' Haseltine said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, pharmaceutical companies are using genetic
research to streamline the creation of new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, developing new drugs was an expensive and tedious
process of trial and error, taking many years and costing hundreds
of millions of dollars. Often the drugs were discovered haphazardly
through their effects on patients who took them for other reasons.
In other cases, it required time-consuming testing of thousands of
compounds, one at a time, in animals, says Robert Tepper, chief
scientific officer of Millennium Pharmaceuticals in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Now, companies like Millennium are developing techniques for
testing thousands of drugs at the same time. Those drugs can be
washed across tiny ``gene chips'' that contain hundreds or
thousands of genes taken from cells of healthy or ill people. All
these interactions are analyzed by computers that quickly report
which drugs had the desired effect on the genes.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect example of the new approach came in an announcement
last week from scientists at the Whitehead Institute in Cambridge
and Millennium Pharmaceuticals. They said they had identified a new
target for obesity therapy, a protein in the small intestine that
regulates how much fat from food is taken up into the body. Having
found that protein and the gene that causes it to be made, the
researchers will try to find a drug that blocks that process,
reducing fat uptake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drugs . . . will be more selective and less toxic, much more
geared to a specific type of a disease that you have,'' said
Tepper. Beyond this, he said, ``we will be able to offer patients
many many more tests that will help them predict their risks and
change their lifestyles'' to help them avoid diseases to which they
are genetically predisposed.
</P>
<P>
   Another goal of the genome project is identifying genetic
variations that dictate differences in the way humans respond to
drugs. The same drug may help some people but not others, and in
still others cause harmful side effects.
</P>
<P>
   In the not-too-distant future, people might be given a DNA test
at birth and then issued a small card or computer chip that
indicates what type of health problems they are likely to
encounter. The hope is that they would be able to make lifestyle
decisions and perhaps take new preventive drugs to forestall those
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, though, predictive tests will arrive before
preventions, creating dilemmas for patients and doctors. ``We are
going to be going through hell, because we'll learn a lot about
biology and physiology'' but there won't be immediate treatments,
said Collins, the genome project coordinator at the National
Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest effect of the genome project could come in cancer
treatment, in which many patients routinely receive chemotherapy
and other painful therapies with no benefit. By studying genes,
researchers are finding that what they thought was a single type of
cancer is really a family of genetically distinct diseases, each of
which might require a different treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Already, doctors are checking the genetic signature of a tumor
before recommending treatment. Breast cancer patients who have an
overabundance of a gene called HER2 now are often given Herceptin,
which blocks the gene and prevents it from overproducing a protein
that prompts tumors to spread quickly. If HER2 is not overabundant,
the woman is not a candidate for Herceptin.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the work is aimed at finding new treatments for
cancer. If researchers could figure out which genes are involved,
they could fashion drugs, like Herceptin, to block a particular
gene or to spur a gene to become more active.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cancer has been a black box,,'' said Dr. Richard Klausner,
director of the National Cancer Institute. ``It's been hard to know
what's going on inside and how to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Studying the genes that cause cancer ``has been like switching
on the lights,'' Klausner said. ``It's that dramatic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
