<HEADLINE>
DEFLATING THE MYTH OF AGE-RELATED WEIGHT GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most elders struggling with a weight problem, 74-year-old
Ira Phillips was once slim.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, when her twins were born, Phillips carried 125
pounds on her 5-foot-5 frame. Back then, her ``body mass index'' or
BMI, a measure that takes height and weight into account, was an
enviably healthy 21. (Anything over 25 is considered overweight,
and over 27 counts as obese.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, though, the pounds crept up until, earlier this
year, Phillips reached. . . well, she doesn't like to say, but it
was more than 200 pounds. That gave her a dangerously high BMI of
35, along with high blood pressure, high cholesterol, and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Age-related weight gain is so common that most consider it a
veritable law of nature. But is it?
</P>
<P>
   Less than most may assume, according to the best emerging
evidence. Some effects of aging on weight gain are unavoidable, but
it appears those are dwarfed by factors that virtually all of us
can influence if we choose to _ how much we eat and, especially,
the amount and type of exercise we get.
</P>
<P>
   Weight gain is fundamentally a matter of metabolism: the process
by which the body converts the calories in food to energy. And by
far the most important determinant of weight gain is basal
metabolism _ the rate at which we burn calories while sitting at
rest. Surprisingly, resting metabolism accounts for about
two-thirds of our total energy expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's basal metabolism slows down with age. In general,
the resting metabolic rate of men sags 2 to 3 percent per decade,
beginning around age 35, says Prof. Eric Poehlman, a metabolism
expert at the University of Vermont. Women have a somewhat lower
metabolic rate to begin with, he adds, but it doesn't drop much
until menopause, when the loss of estrogen somehow results in an
accelerated decline.
</P>
<P>
   The basal metabolic rate of an average 60-year-old is about 200
calories a day lower than a typical 30-year-old's.
</P>
<P>
   Even small declines in metabolic rate add up, in terms of added
poundage, because the balance between food intake and energy
expenditure is so exquisitely sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metabolic control is extremely tightly regulated in the
body,'' says Dr. Ronenn Roubenoff, an expert on metabolism at the
Tufts University-US Department of Agriculture Human Nutrition
Research Center and New England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``A theoretical 155-pound man, our average Joe, eats about a
million calories a year and burns about a million calories a
year,'' Roubenoff notes. ``To gain a pound a year, you only have to
be off by 10,000 calories _ only a one percent variance. So if you
think about it, to gain a pound you only have to eat 27 calories a
day more than you burn. That's a fraction of a cookie!''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you want to lose weight, Roubenoff adds,
you only have to shave a few calories every day from your diet _ or
increase your daily calorie ``burn.''
</P>
<P>
   As every dieter knows, it is supremely difficult to lose weight
and keep it off by restricting calories alone, thanks to humans'
inborn drive to eat whatever is available. But food intake is just
half the story. Scientists are beginning to focus much more on the
other side of the metabolic equation: energy expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say the normal slowing of metabolism with advancing
age is not the main problem. It's the reduction of physical
activity with age, and the accompanying loss of lean muscle mass,
that's the real culprit. It means that, even without eating more
calories, more of what people of a certain age eat will be
deposited as fat _ mostly around the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Phillips is a case in point. Her major weight gain did not
occur, she says, until after age 62, when she retired from her job
as a clerical worker with the Boston School Department. ``When you
retire you change your life,'' she says. ``You're not as active.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a simple matter of burning more calories through
physical activity, although that's part of it. More important,
researchers say, is the gradual loss of lean muscle mass that
occurs throughout middle and old age.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this is inevitable _ even older masters-class athletes
who train hard lose some muscle mass as they age _ but the trend is
greatly accelerated by most Americans' sedentary lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   The reason muscle loss is so important: The amount of lean
muscle humans have is the most important determinant of their
resting metabolic rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest reasons why the way we burn calories slows
down is that we lose muscle as we age,'' Poehlman says. ``It's a
vicious cycle. You lose muscle mass, you become less active,
inactivity leads to more muscle loss. Even though older people
generally eat fewer calories, they're burning disproportionately
fewer calories.''
</P>
<P>
   Lean muscle is so important in metabolism because it's the
biggest ``sponge'' for soaking up glucose, the simple sugar that is
the body's source of all energy. The less lean muscle someone has,
the greater her likelihood of excess blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens to excess glucose? Our bodies efficiently store
it away as fat _ a hedge against a time of starvation that, for
most people these days, never comes.
</P>
<P>
   To make things worse, the fat people accumulate in middle age is
much more likely to be the worst kind, metabolically speaking:
abdominal fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fat in the stomach is very different biochemically than on the
arms or thighs,'' says Poehlman. ``It's more metabolically active,
which means it breaks down more readily, putting more fat into the
bloodstream.'' That interferes with glucose metabolism and the
action of insulin, the hormone that enables cells to use glucose
for energy.
</P>
<P>
   There is a powerful evolutionary reason behind the way humans
store fat. Our prehistoric ancestors evolved to cope with periods
of food scarcity. ``That programmed our whole metabolism,'' notes
Prof. Susan Roberts, a Tufts metabolism expert.
</P>
<P>
   To get through the lean times, Roberts explains, humans
developed a complex system of chemical signals between body and
brain that strongly impel us to eat when we can to preserve fat
stores. Her research suggests that some of these signals ``go
haywire'' with age, as she puts it, disabling the controls of
appetite and energy expenditure that tend to maintain a stable
weight at younger ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just beginning to learn about this system in man,'' says
Prof. Jules Hirsch of Rockefeller University. Only four years ago,
Rockefeller scientists caused a great stir with their discovery of
leptin, a hormone secreted by fat cells. Too little leptin in the
blood apparently warns the brain that starvation is imminent. The
message: Eat more!
</P>
<P>
   Initially, many researchers (and drug companies) thought that
giving fat people leptin would suppress appetite and promote weight
loss. But it hasn't turned out to be that simple. The control of
food intake and energy expenditure ``is going to be a very ornate
mechanism, with lots of little arrows and controls and lots of
redundant loops,'' Hirsch says.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging complexity of this appetite-driving mechanism tells
researchers it's going to be difficult to override. Although we
punish ourselves and others with accusations of gluttony and moral
failing, in reality it is this inborn drive to eat
``opportunistically'' that accounts for the epidemic of obesity and
associated diseases, such as diabetes, that afflicts all developed
nations and many developing nations as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-27 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
80-YEAR-OLD RETIREE SHOULD EASE INTO STOCK MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are 41 and 38, respectively. We have $82,000
in a IRA with $11,300 in International Growth fund, $21,000 in
Vanguard Wellesley, $18,500 in Vanguard Windsor II, $15,200 in
Vanguard High-Yield Bond fund, and $16,000 in the Vanguard Prime
Money Market fund. We also have another traditional IRA invested in
Janus fund, consisting of $2,800. We don't add to either of these
accounts, as they were rolled over from a previous employer's
profit-sharing plan. My husband currently buys $100 a month worth
of his company's stock, and next year he will become eligible for
its 401(k). At that point he will stop buying stock and begin to
contribute $200 a month, with his employer matching with an
additional $50 a month. The only plan where I work is a
deferred-compensation plan, to which I contribute the minimum
amount, representing 7 percent of my salary or $1,000 a year, all
invested in an income fund that usually provides a return of about
6 percent. We have negligible credit card debt and owe about
$109,000 on our mortgage, which has 22 years left. I can probably
manage to save another $200 per month. If we retire at age 65, will
we be in tough shape?
</P>
<P>
   N.R., Foxborough, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Probably not. I'll have to base my response on some rough
estimates, since you didn't supply the current value of either your
husband's shares of his company's stock or the current balance in
your 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   But based only on the current balances in your IRAs and your
husband's anticipated contributions to the 401(k) and your ongoing
contributions to the deferred-compensation plan, you would amass
$1,205,504 over 24 years. If such a sum were invested (at a
presumed fixed-income rate of 6.5 percent) you might expect an
annual income stream of $78,357.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound pretty grand, but after you adjust it to an
estimated annual inflation rate of 3.5 percent during those 24
years, it would have the buying power of about $34,500 in today's
money.
</P>
<P>
   If you were able to add a further $200 a month to your
contributions to the deferred-compensation plan, the accumulation
would be $1,427,654. Under the same assumption, you might then
invest it to provide an income stream of $92,797, equivalent to
about $40,500 in today's dollars.
</P>
<P>
   There are two problems with those projections. Both of the
growth estimates were made using an estimate of 10 percent for
average annual investment returns.
</P>
<P>
   To have a reasonable chance of achieving such a return, both you
and your husband should be investing your savings more
aggressively. Certainly the money market holding in your IRA should
be swapped for a stock fund such as Vanguard Index 500.
</P>
<P>
   I'd also lean toward exchanging the High-Yield Corporate Bond
position for a stock fund, but I'd probably wait for its price to
recover a bit before making that move.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in your deferred-compensation plan you should be
looking for long-term growth rather than current income, and thus
should be invested in whatever stock vehicles are available.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem is that you shouldnt rely entirely on those
income projections I made, since once you retire you will want to
leave some of your money in growth securities, designed to protect
you against the effects of inflation during the later years of your
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   So if you want to be prudent, you might project that you'll have
a level that represents 75 percent to 80 percent of the various
income streams _ provided of course that you are willing to invest
more aggressively now and ride through the inevitable market bumps
of the next quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We recently acquired two Vanguard Variable annuities, with 13
percent of the funds in its Money Market, 15 percent in the
Equity-Income, 19 percent in the High-Grade Bond, 31 percent in the
Balanced, and 22 percent in the High-Yield Bond accounts. The total
value of the accounts was $296,284 on June 30. A brief profile of
our situation: We are able to sustain our lifestyle on our pension
income only. In addition to the annuities, we have approximately
$115,000 in other investments, mostly funds. We own our home, worth
approximately $300,000, and have no foreseeable need of the money
in the annuities. We have both been retired since the early '80s.
My concern is that I am afraid we have too much invested in bonds _
40 percent not including the bond portfolio in the balanced fund,
and 53 percent if that is included. I am thinking we should reduce
the High-Yield and High-Grade bond accounts and move it into Equity
Income, Equity Index, and Growth accounts. What's your thinking?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Escondido, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This one threw me for a few minutes, because I tend to lump
money-market holdings with bonds to represent the fixed-income side
of a portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   So before I put the portfolio on a spreadsheet, I thought that
53 percent bonds meant 47 percent stocks, and that looked pretty
good to me for a person who has been retired for nearly two
decades. But after I got the numbers down, I began to agree with
you: Some more stock might be nice _ but not too much.
</P>
<P>
   You're not specific on the point, but let's guess that you're in
your early 80s. Even though you have no foreseeable need of the
money in the annuity accounts, holding a majority of this money in
stock funds is probably too aggressive for your situation.
</P>
<P>
   This is a point of view that I would likely take in a neutral
stock market. Since I view the current stock market as dangerously
exposed to a downturn, and perhaps a substantial downturn, I'm not
enthusiastic about wholesale changes.
</P>
<P>
   But I do think you might move a little money. Since you have no
foreseeable need for these funds, I suggest you jettison the 13
percent that's in the money-market account.
</P>
<P>
   If I were making the move, I'd put about half of this in the
Equity Index account and divide the balance between the Small
Company and International accounts, which would give you better
portfolio diversification. And this move would take you to that 47
percent equities that I liked at the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My two daughters have each received gifts of $6,000, which I
would like to set aside for college. My older child will graduate
in the year 2002 and the younger in 2005. Since there isn't an
abundance of time until graduation, I am willing to take at least a
moderate risk. What would be the best investment choice for their
money, and would it make sense to invest it separately or keep the
$12,000 together? We have also saved a total of $29,000 for them,
all invested in zero coupon US Treasury securities. Am I correct
that the funds should not be in their names because we will be
applying for financial aid?
</P>
<P>
   V.R., Walpole, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, if you need or think your child may be eligible for
financial aid, it is best to save college money in your own name.
But you also have to follow the rules.
</P>
<P>
   If you have built the zero-coupon bond accounts in your name,
fine. But if you started out with the money in the children's
names, you can't switch back. The same applies to the gifts that
your daughters have received.
</P>
<P>
   If the money was given to them with the direction that it be
used for their education, I don't see how you can avoid putting it
in their names. On the other hand, if it was given to you with the
understanding that it will be used for the girls' education, you're
in fine shape. Keep it in your name and their chances for financial
aid will be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   As for an appropriate investment, you and I disagree completely.
</P>
<P>
   You write that since there isn't a lot of time until graduation,
you're willing to take at least a moderate risk. I think that the
shorter the time span, the lower the risk level you should be
willing to assume.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm reading your letter correctly, the elder daughter is
already in college, and the younger will follow in two years. The
money for your eldest daughter will be spent within three years,
and that of your younger daughter within two to six years.
</P>
<P>
   These savings should be in secure instruments such as money
market funds, CDs, short-term government securities, or _ at the
most risky _ a good short-term bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
