<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ISLAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGIME WITHIN A REGIME: ISRAEL'S ISLAMISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAFR KANA, Israel _ When Sheik Kamal Khatib wants to take stock
of his growing domain, all he has to do is to step outside his
mosque in this small Arab town in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Across the garbage-strewn street is the free Islamic nursery
school, where children fingerpaint and play with dolls, under
pictures of the revered al-Aksa Mosque in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs is the town's only library, with shelves and shelves of
books, most of them related to the religion of Islam, wide wooden
work tables, and two computers that students can use, without fee.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road is the health clinic, where residents get
treatment along with a dose of religious respect.
</P>
<P>
   It is all provided by Khatib's Islamic Movement, a vibrant
organization with roots in almost every Arab town in Israel. And
Israeli Arabs are turning to the group to counter decades of
neglect and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But after four Israeli Arabs, linked to the Islamic Movement,
tried this month to set off bombs in nearby Tiberias and Haifa, the
Israeli government has asked whether the group might have other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The question has been posed in many countries in the Middle
East, most recently in Turkey and Egypt, where Islamic
fundamentalist groups have found easy support among the alienated
poor, then have been accused of trying to overthrow the government
to set up religious rule.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, the issue is more complicated because the loyalties
of the bombers, the first Israeli Arabs to attempt such an attack,
are still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Were the young men working for Hamas, the militant Islamic
group, which is based in the Palestinian-ruled parts of Gaza and
the West Bank? Or was the action incited by radicals within the
Israel-based Islamic Movement, which has condemned the attempted
bombings?
</P>
<P>
   Israeli authorities allege that Hamas, which opposes the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, recruited two of the four men
involved in the failed attempts to bomb buses on Sept. 5. But they
also allege that some people within the Islamic Movement, like
Khatib, indirectly supported the attacks through speeches or
articles that incited followers to act against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers, along with another young Israeli Arab man who in
August killed two Israeli Jewish hikers, ``listened to the Islamic
Movement,'' said Gideon Ezra, former head of Israel's internal
security agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't do it because they are crazy, but because they
believed this country should be an Islamic state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic Movement officials disagree, and have urged Israel not
to blame all Muslims for what a few individuals did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached tens of thousands of people through our
programs, and only four people were involved in the bombing attack.
Why are they accusing the whole Islamic movement?'' Khatib asked as
he sat in his office, with a photo of the local soccer team behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two principles,'' Khatib said, ``we follow Sharia and
we follow Israeli law, and each person decides for himself whether
to operate inside or outside this, but if he steps outside of the
principles he does not represent the Islamic Movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli security services are not so sure. The Cabinet will soon
debate a list of measures aimed at curbing the influence of what
Israeli security officials say are the group's radical elements.
The movement has two factions, and Khatib belongs to what Israeli
officials say is the extremist wing.
</P>
<P>
   Possible measures include shutting down the movement's illegal
TV station, closing its unlicensed college and barring Khatib and
another leader from visiting the West Bank and Gaza. Some
politicians want the entire group dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   But Sammy Smooha, an Israeli Jewish expert on terrorism, said
the fears may be overstated and that the terrorists might have been
isolated members of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear the bombers were members of the Islamic Movement,
but from hard-line statements made you can get the feeling that we
have to do something very drastic or we will have widespread
terrorism in Israel,'' Smooha said.
</P>
<P>
   He and others suggested the bombing reaction by Israeli
hard-liners reflects the belief that Arabs cannot be trusted in the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Arab citizens do not serve in the army and they are rarely hired
in so-called sensitive industries such as the electric company.
They face widespread discrimination in getting building permits or
their share of public funding.
</P>
<P>
   Related to this is the question of whether the inequality
between Arabs and Jews in Israel somehow sparked the young men to
attempt the extremist act, which could have killed dozens of Arab
and Jewish Israelis alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can't be any justification for this, we condemn this
absolutely,'' said Osama Salah, a cousin of the one bomber who
survived the explosions, Ibrahim Salah, 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Osama Salah is deputy mayor in the town of Mash'had, where three
of the four bombers lived: Ibrahim Salah, who was about to start
college in Haifa and is now in custody; Amir Masalha, 25, newly
married and a former mosque preacher; and Krayem Nazal, 27.
</P>
<P>
   Mash'had, a five-minute drive from Kafr Kana, is a pretty town
in Galilee's green hills, but it lacks the services of a Jewish
town _ sidewalks, public parks, community centers, street signs.
Also missing is a sense that things will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make sure these things don't happen again we need to make
sure that there is real equality, that equal services are given to
the people and the towns _ it's not a justification for what
happened, but maybe it's one of the reasons,'' Osama Salah said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The problem is that these boys didn't lack for
anything, they all had work, futures, they were victims of
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
