<SLUG> BC-EU-CABINET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME EUROPEAN CABINET CHOICES SEEM IMPROBABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Having endured Chris Patten's endless lectures about
the virtues of democracy, the Chinese were glad to see the backside
of Patten after the last British governor of Hong Kong handed the
territory back to them two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But when Chinese officials sit down for sensitive talks to forge
closer relations with the European Union, they will find themselves
sitting directly across from Chris Patten.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from his 15-month review of policing in Northern Ireland,
Patten said he relishes his new job as chief of foreign affairs for
the European Union, and the spirit behind his appointment and that
of several others who, by previous standards, have been given
improbable assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are changing in Europe,'' Patten said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Patten is one of 19 commissioners appointed by the new European
Commission president, Romano Prodi, who with his 19-member Cabinet
was confirmed on Wednesday by the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest priority for Prodi and the 19 others who form the
executive branch of the 15-nation European Union is to improve the
commission's tarnished image after the forced resignations of their
predecessors last spring over allegations of mismanagement and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But Prodi, the former Italian prime minister, has chucked
conventional wisdom to the wind by appointing people, like Patten,
to positions that force the commissioner's native country to
confront issues it would rather avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled by record unemployment and fearful that a new influx of
immigrant workers from the east will make things worse, the Germans
are the most squeamish about enlarging the EU. Prodi has put a
German, Gunter Verheugen, in charge of overseeing enlargement.
</P>
<P>
   As the recent protests against American trade sanctions and
attacks on McDonald's franchises in France underscore, the French
are the Europeans most vociferously opposed to liberalizing trade.
Prodi has put a Frenchman, Pascal Lamy, in charge of trade.
</P>
<P>
   According to Patten, this is part of Prodi's vision for
confronting the things that divide Europeans. There has been a
tendency in the past for European leaders to deliver flowery
speeches about the remarkable achievement of bringing together
nations that had spent much of the millennium fighting each other.
It has been less common to dwell on lingering disputes the European
partners have with each other, such as French opposition to free
trade and British skepticism about the wisdom of surrendering
national sovereignty to build European-wide institutions.
</P>
<P>
   David O'Sullivan, Prodi's top aide, said Prodi is determined to
make European policy less parochial. In the past, the Cabinet
staffs tended to be from the commissioner's native country. Prodi
has ordered his commissioners to mix their staffs with different
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to have a truly European outlook,'' said
O'Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Patten, for one, thinks it's a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a different perspective,'' he said. ``If I were
surrounded just by Brits, I wouldn't necessarily see things the way
the French or the Italians do.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if his staff comes from countries that think
enlargement is a good thing, can Verheugen soften German opposition
to enlargement, especially now that the Greeks have dropped their
opposition to Turkey's joining the EU?
</P>
<P>
   Germany is already home to millions of Turks, and EU membership
would entitle millions more to go to Germany in search of work.
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's efforts to reduce Germany's debt has
been rewarded with a precipitous drop in his popularity and
thrashings for his Social Democratic Party in three recent state
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Lamy may have an even more difficult task, getting French
farmers to temper their opposition to free trade. It has been the
willingness of Jose Bove, leader of a small farmer's union, to
crusade against free trade rather than Lamy's mission to end
damaging trade wars that has captured the public's imagination in
much of France.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Patten, meanwhile, brings more to the
European Commission than a seasoned diplomat. Officials both at the
European Commission and 10 Downing St. said Patten could help ease
British skepticism about further European integration.
</P>
<P>
   The British have long been reluctant Europeans. Of the four EU
countries that did not take part in the launch this year of a
single European currency, opposition to the euro is strongest in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   While France and Germany have been the traditional leaders of
the European Union, Prime Minister Tony Blair has said he wants
Britain to take a leading role. Officials in both Brussels and
London hope that Patten's prominent role as Europe's foreign
minister will show there are benefits that offset what most Britons
consider the downside of turning over control of monetary policy to
the European Central Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
