<HEADER>
A7524 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-27 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE POST-GARRITY ERA, DARE WE FORGET THE PAST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The recent passing of US Court Judge W. Arthur Garrity Jr.
marked the end of a symbolic era in Boston, a time of chaos and
controversy over school desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the next round of city elections, we face a choice:
either move the city's educational system forward _ return it to
the days of school segregation that prompted Judge Garrity to order
a massive busing program.
</P>
<P>
   With some merit, critics say Garrity's decision to desegregate
the city's schools was disruptive, if not destructive, to the way
things were. No doubt, busing brought hardship and frustration to
many parents, as well as to the students previously enrolled in
schools close to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there always has been busing in Boston, but the buses
went largely where the parents wanted them to go _ some to
segregated schools far from their own neighborhoods _ and no one
complained.
</P>
<P>
   But Garrity's order caused a racial explosion that exposed to
the nation a major northern city's racism. A spotlight was cast on
our deliberately segregated public schools, and how they rendered
an inferior education to thousands of black students.
</P>
<P>
   But Garrity's critics fail to acknowledge the reason Garrity,
with the full weight of the federal judiciary, made his decision.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the School Committee engaged in deliberate
segregation of the city's schools, and thus violated federal law
based on Brown vs. The Board of Education. As with the South, this
de jure segregation of the city's school system came at a time when
African-Americans had little or no power to overturn it, except in
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   So while Garrity's order may have been disruptive for some, it
was less so than the segregated system had long been for black
families, forced to endure an inferior education.
</P>
<P>
   What the School Committee of pre-busing days did was, quite
simply, to break the law. Judge Garrity ordered that the law be
upheld _ courageously standing against fierce resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, at least two things have happened. The tumult caused
by Garrity's order died down, replaced by a quieter resistance; and
a new plan that required much less busing to maintain school
desegregation was created and adopted.
</P>
<P>
   That plan, called controlled-choice, was the brainchild of
Charles Willie, a sociology professor emeritus at Harvard
University, and Michael Alves, a senior planner at Brown
University. As the plan progressed over the years, the number of
children attending schools in their own neighborhood sharply
increased. Many of the physically and educationally inferior
schools were vastly improved. The plan was working.
</P>
<P>
   But to many critics, the plan did not erase, for once and for
all, the fact that Boston is still under a federal court order to
maintain school desegregation, even when `white flight' left the
city's schools more black than white. Despite the imbalance of the
white-black student ratio, the plan still provides equal
educational opportunities to all students, regardless of color,
which the segregated system never did.
</P>
<P>
   The present School Committee has voted to end the controlled
choice plan, replacing it with the open policy of allowing students
to attend any school they wish, as in the days prior to
court-ordered desegreation. Supporters argue that this return to
neighborhood schools is better for the children and better for the
overall educational system.
</P>
<P>
   The school committee will oversee the transition next year from
controlled choice to neighborhood schools. Whoever is appointed
will serve on that panel. There may be some seeking the appointment
who favor a more racially balanced school system with improved
school facilities, and there may be others who prefer to have
students go to neighborhood schools regardless of whether they are
all white, all black, or all Hispanic or all Asian.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, of course, is that the end of controlled choice,
combined with a school committee majority opposed to racial balance
could bring segregation back to the city's school system. That
would be a legal violation and a moral one, given that it would
again result in an unequal educational system, one that meant
inferior resources for one group of school children.
</P>
<P>
   The new School Committee _ as well as the school superintendent,
the Boston City Council, and the mayor _ can help usher in an era
that guarantees equal education for all. Or it can repeat its own
past and prompt another federal judge to make another ruling such
as Garrity's epochal court order.
</P>
<P>
   This time, more of this responsibility for equal education will
fall on the mayor, who oversees an appointed school committee as
opposed to the elected committee that created a segregated system.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, as other cities have done, can remove the stigma of
court-ordered desegregation by taking positive steps to ensure a
truly integrated school system, once and for all. Ending
controlled-choice without taking these steps was not the best way
to begin a new era.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want an equal opportunity for all students will be
waiting to see what unfolds in the next two years. And the federal
courts, of course, will be watching, too _ ready to move if
necessary, as did Judge Garrity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
