<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICANS-WORK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF A RAISE, GET TIME OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the International Labor Organization
reported recently that Americans now work the longest hours in the
industrialized world, the statistics were a little misleading. The
real situation in the United States is even more extreme.
</P>
<P>
   The study says that the average U.S. worker put in 1,966 hours
in 1997, compared with 1,731 for the British, 1,656 for the French
and 1,574 for the Germans. Even the Japanese, who used to have a
reputation as the world's workaholics, worked only 1,889 hours in
1995, the most recent year measured there.
</P>
<P>
   The statistic is misleading because it includes all adults who
work part time or full time, but not those who are unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider three mythical couples: Couple A, where one spouse
works 50 hours a week and the other stays home; Couple B, where
each spouse works 45 hours; and Couple C, where one spouse works 60
and the other 30.
</P>
<P>
   So which couple works the hardest? According to the ILO, it
would be Couple A, where the average worker puts in 50 hours a
week. Remember: The stay-at-home spouse isn't included in the
figures.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture? America has more Couple B's and
Couple C's than the other industrialized nations. About 60 percent
of working-age American women are employed. In Japan and the United
Kingdom, it's closer to 50 percent; in France and Germany, it's
closer to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because women typically work fewer hours than men, they drag
down the averages. And because the United States has so many
working women, they might well be dragging the average down here
more than in other countries. It's impossible to know for sure
because many countries don't separate the sexes when they determine
how many hours are worked.
</P>
<P>
   What you can tell, however, is that comparing Americans' work
figures of today with those of earlier generations is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot more Couple A's back then, when the husband
might have worked long hours, but then did relatively little when
it came to housework or raising the children.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Employment Policy Foundation, only 28 percent
of married moms were employed in 1960. Now it's more than 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Don't take this to mean that women shouldn't be working or ought
to put in more hours or anything of the sort. Having more women in
the work force has made many lives more fulfilling, strengthened
the American economy and enabled more husbands to bail out of
unsatisfactory jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But do take it to mean that Americans are obsessed with work,
and it's going to catch up with us. While Americans kept piling on
the hours from 1980 to 1997, the ILO report says that productivity
grew faster in many other countries, including Japan, France and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do burn out,'' Lawrence Jeff Johnson, co-author of the
ILO study, told the Associated Press. ``If they keep working this
hard for these long hours, there is burnout and there are
diminishing returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Those diminishing returns aren't limited to the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Parents aren't as involved with raising their kids as they used
to be, and God knows that tons of married and single people spend
their weeknights watching television because they're too worn out
to do anything else.
</P>
<P>
   To put things into perspective, consider this: If you're a
typical American worker and you took your normal vacation and
normal holidays, then took the entire months of November and
December off each year, you would still work more hours than the
typical German.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable that people obsess over the size of their
paychecks, but next time you're tempted to ask for a raise, ask for
more time off instead. It's easier on your employer because it
usually doesn't cost extra money, and you won't lose 45 or 50
percent of it to taxes, the way you would with a raise.
</P>
<P>
   For working parents, if you each had five weeks off, it would
give you time for a real family vacation, not just rushing to a
place for a few days and then rushing back. You could have time to
bond with your children to help make up for all those other harried
weeks, and maybe even have a few days just for yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   If five weeks off sounds ridiculously high, wake up and smell
the French roast. In France and Italy and many other European
countries, it's common for workers to have an entire month off.
</P>
<P>
   How do you get the time off? The same way you get anything else
from your employer: Be one of your company's best workers.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you do get a vacation, make sure it's a real one, not
something when you're called and paged and bothered. If your boss
says you're too indispensable to be left alone, make sure your
paycheck reflects that. If it doesn't, get outta town.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
