r k BC-FERMAN-COLUMN-TEX     09-27 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN WHO DUMPS HIS FIANCEE IS A CAD, BUT IF A WOMAN ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interesting, the perceptions of what it means for a man and a
woman to do the exact same thing.
</P>
<P>
   A man who strays outside a marriage, for example, is a pig being
led around by his ... um ... testosterone, but a woman who sleeps
with someone other than her husband is usually in need of therapy
and compassion _ or just having a good time because (nudge, wink)
her husband doesn't give her what she needs.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a man who leaves a woman at the altar has reached a
whole new level of pond scumminess, but a woman who leaves a man is
_ let's see here now _ the heroine of a movie that has earned more
than $144 million.
</P>
<P>
   I refer to ``Runaway Bride,'' the almost insufferable film
starring Julia Roberts and Richard Gere. Roberts plays a small-town
girl who has left three young men at the altar, and Gere is the
tough, at least slightly sexist New York columnist who writes about
her escapades.
</P>
<P>
   Only he gets a lot of stuff wrong (he says she's gotten cold
feet seven times, not three), gets canned (by his ex-wife, of
course) and goes to her little Mayberry-like Maryland town to do an
expose on her. The two meet and _ well, you get two guesses as to
what happens, and the first one doesn't count.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is horrible, but it's so popular that People magazine
recently ran a cover story on six women who stiffed their
hubbies-to-be at The Big Moment.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the women are portrayed as strong, smart and
resilient, and calling off the wedding is portrayed as acceptable,
if not downright noble.
</P>
<P>
   Each woman has a different reason, of course, but they all end
up happy, whether married or single.
</P>
<P>
   All together now: Awwwwww.
</P>
<P>
   Compare and contrast this, if you will, to the public reaction
in November 1997 to London lawyer Tasos Michael's jilting of Nicole
Contos at the altar. People cheered and toasted her as she danced
to the disco anthem ``I Will Survive'' at the
reception-that-wasn't, while he flew off to enjoy their
honeymoon-that-wasn't in Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   He became Mr. Cad _ the nerve of him, flying off to their
honeymoon destination! She bravely fought back tears while hitting
the talk shows, and sold her story to the tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the outraged response of women _ many of whom could
be seen shaking their heads at the horror of it all when Contos
appeared on talk shows _ Michael had committed something close to a
major felony. He was despicable, a man who cared nothing for anyone
but himself _ and what an awful, awful thing to happen to that poor
girl.
</P>
<P>
   Pity for her, hatred for him.
</P>
<P>
   Easy. Simple.
</P>
<P>
   Only it's not that easy or simple. The truth is, a man who calls
off a wedding is often making an agonizing, heartbreaking decision;
and believe it or not, ladies, he just might _ might _ be thinking
of her, too.
</P>
<P>
   I speak from experience: Back in 1987 I called off marriage with
my girlfriend of nearly two years. It wasn't at the altar _ it was
three months before the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   I simply realized that I did not want to be with this woman for
the rest of my life and that (because of our different views on
children and other issues) she would ultimately not want to be with
me. To have married her would have meant an ugly ending, with at
least one child caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   And that would have been worse than what I did.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, I didn't want to hurt anyone. It wasn't a flippant
decision, it wasn't made in haste, and there was nobody else.
</P>
<P>
   I was simply trying to look down the road and honestly see what
would be best for both of us. That doesn't make me a great guy, but
it doesn't make me a cad, either.
</P>
<P>
   But in return I suddenly had everyone in the world angry at me.
Or so it seemed. Her father, I think, would have hurt me if he'd
gotten the chance. I was in a very lonely place, and I spent a lot
of time riding around in my car, crying, wondering why I ``just
couldn't do it,'' but knowing deeper in my heart that it was the
best thing.
</P>
<P>
   My ex-fiancee remarried soon. She lives in the Midwest and has a
stable marriage, three lovely daughters and an infant son. I truly
believe she is happier than she would have been with me, and I am
sure she has more kids than she would have had we married. (By the
way, I know this because she talks to my mom every couple of
months. But that's a whole 'nother column for a whole 'nother day.)
</P>
<P>
   No, I don't know the in's and out's of the Michael/Contos
relationship. He may be a jerk, and she may an absolute angel.
</P>
<P>
   But more likely, he just realized that leaving now would be
better than leaving later. For everyone. That's not to excuse the
fact that he did it at the very last moment, but, hey, I think his
heart might have been in the right place _ he may have truly been
trying to protect both of them from wasting years in a downward
spiral of unpleasantness and bitter feelings. And give both of them
a chance to find someone with whom they really could happily grow
old.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe he hurt like hell doing it.
</P>
<P>
   All I'm saying is, it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he's a man.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's pop music critic.
You may reach him at (817) 390-7839 or dfer(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
