<HEADLINE>
FACING JAIL, LEFAVE ISN'T BACKING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She has already begun packing for a trip she hopes she
will never take.
</P>
<P>
   Pajamas, a pair of jeans, and underwear all sit in a small pile
on Cheryl Amirault LeFave's dining room floor, waiting for the day
when she is returned, handcuffed, to the prison life she lived for
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly she waits _ for guidance from her lawyers, for decisions
by the courts, for advice from friends and supporters. She meets
with a psychiatrist and a teacher of ``bioenergetic healing.''
</P>
<P>
   In her lengthiest interview since the state's highest court
reinstated her child-abuse conviction last month, LeFave spoke of
the seemingly inevitable, her imminent return to MCI-Framingham,
and the range of emotions she has felt since the Supreme Judicial
Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   She shudders at the thought of another strip-search, another mug
shot, another round of fingerprinting.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave's lawyers have told her they expect the SJC to announce
soon that it has rejected her motion for a new hearing. Some time
on the same day, she expects a call from the Middlesex district
attorney's office notifying her of a date for the reinstatement of
her conviction and sentence.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes her return to prison will last no longer than three
months, the time it would take for the state Parole Board to hear
her case. She hopes it will free her, since she has been free for
nearly four years, living productively and working.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if her freedom depends on her admitting guilt, that she will
not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who in their right mind would fight for 14 years if they were
guilty?'' asked LeFave, 42. ``It's not true, and I have fought for
14 years to be able to say to those children one day, `I never
abused you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the parents of the preschool-age children that LeFave, her
mother, and brother were convicted of molesting in their Malden
day-care center have their own, ongoing anguish, as do the
children, now grown. And just as adamantly, they proclaim LeFave's
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Parents describe how their once well-adjusted children suddenly
had trouble sleeping, began wetting their beds, and were discovered
mimicking sexual acts on friends and siblings.
</P>
<P>
   As one parent said after the SJC ruling, ``These children were
sexually abused, and there are no ifs, ands, or buts about that in
my mind or the minds of any of the people who were involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the children in the case, now young adults, sought
therapy after the ordeal. Some ran away from home, some attempted
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe in 1995, one young woman said
adamantly, ``I know Cheryl molested me and I can remember it as
clear as if it was Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   LeFave's cause has been championed nationally, most notably by
the editorial page of The Wall Street Journal. Dorothy Rabinowitz,
a Journal editorial writer, even had a hand in publicizing a fund
estalished to pay the legal bills of &QL; 
people, like LeFave, who claim they were wrongly convicted of child
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Protected under the glass top of her dining room table is a
handwritten note of support from Harvey Silverglate, the
high-profile defense attorney; ``May 1999 be the year of your
family's victory,'' it reads. Hanging nearby are oversized pictures
of LeFave and her family taken by Silverglate's wife, Elsa Dorfman,
a prominent Cambridge photographer.
</P>
<P>
   It is with a tangled combination of rage, sorrow, and
hopelessness that LeFave prepares to become an inmate once again _
this time without her mother, Violet, her long-time cellmate, who
died of cancer two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they nurtured a prize-winning pumpkin when they were
in a medium-security facility in rural Lancaster. Together, they
shared a cement-block cell where Violet had such violent nightmares
that she smashed and broke her toes on the walls, her daughter
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave was 29 when she entered prison along with her mother in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   Three years earlier, she had married and bought a house in
Melrose. She and her husband, Al, separated after her release in
1995, after a Superior Court judge overturned her and her mother's
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave's brother, Gerald, who also worked at the Fells Acres Day
School and was convicted of child abuse as well, received a 30- to
40-year sentence in 1986 and remains jailed at the Plymouth County
House of Correction.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave has not seen him since the SJC's August ruling because
convicted felons are not allowed to visit prisoners. Instead, they
speak by telephone at least twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   Her house, with its distinctly female touch, is homey,
comfortable and cluttered with knickknacks and family photographs.
One framed picture shows LeFave and her mother at a ``reunion'' of
other nationally known convicted child molesters, including Kelly
Michaels and Bucky McMartin, whose sentences were later overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the apartment, a butterfly motif _ LeFave says she
associates the creatures with freedom _ is strong.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave is more stylish now than when her face first landed on
the nightly news. Gone is the waist-length feathered brown hair;
she now sports a fashionable shoulder-length cut, subtly frosted
blond.
</P>
<P>
   Since last month's ruling, LeFave has been on an unpaid leave of
absence from her job in Charlestown, where she worked in customer
service for John Hancock. Anticipating her return to prison, LeFave
has spent the last several weeks at home sorting out her personal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   She says she hs been promised that her job will be waiting for
her when she is released.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave said last month's ruling ``paralyzed'' her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had such high hopes,'' she said quietly. ``I came to believe
that if you go through the system, it will work for you. I thought,
`How could be this be? How could I, who lived a simple little life,
become a victim of a system that didn't work for me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   LeFave expects a warm welcome by many of the inmates she knew
when she left, particularly the ``lifers and long-timers'' she
gravitated toward, the prisoners who viewed her mother as a den
mother of sorts. But she knows there will be new prisoners who will
dislike her instantly because of the crimes attached to her name.
</P>
<P>
   Facing prison again, she feels emotionally dead, wanting to keep
fighting but rapidly losing the will to do so. She spends most of
her time at home, running errands, writing letters and sharing
e-mail with supporters across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a life,'' she said. ``I can't have fun. I can't place
myself in a group of people who are laughing. I can only think,
`How could this happen to my life?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
