<HEADLINE>
WHY DOES THE ROOM SPIN WHEN WE'RE DIZZY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When we spin around and around, and then stop, why does the
room keep spinning?
</P>
<P>
   D.B. Newton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Even after your body has stopped, some of you keeps going.
Inside your ear are three semi-circular canals, little tubes filled
with liquid and lined with tiny hairs.
</P>
<P>
   When you spin around, the liquid moves, bending the hairs. Those
hairs are attached to nerve endings which send the brain
information about how much the hairs are bending and in what
direction. The message, essentially, is ``We're spinning.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you stop, the liquid in the canals keeps sloshing for a
few moments, and the hairs don't straighten back out immediately.
So the ears keep sending the brain the message even after you've
stopped. Since you know you're not spinning anymore, it looks like
the room is.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes dizziness is accompanied by an uncomfortable feeling
in your stomach. That's because the three inputs of the balance
system don't agree. Your ears say ``We're spinning.'' But your eyes
and the somatosensory system, your awareness of your body in space,
are both telling the brain ``No we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting balance information causes the message ``We're
nauseous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What causes itching?
</P>
<P>
   M.H., Ames Iowa &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This one has the top experts scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Dr. Jeffrey Bernhard of U. Mass. Memorial Health
Care editor of the journal of the American Academy of Dermatology,
and author of the book ``Itch.''
</P>
<P>
   He says itch starts in polymodal nociceptors, tiny nerve endings
just fractions of a millimeter below the surface of the skin which
are also where pain begins. He says there are three initiators of
itch: mechanical, like a scratchy woolen blanket; allergic, like a
mosquito bite or poison ivy or hives; and inflammatory, like skin
diseases such as psoriasis or eczema.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a demonstration of the mechanical stimulation of itch.
Scratch your cheek as lightly as you can. It tickles a bit. If it
was a bug crawling on you, you might identify it as an itch. That's
the polymodal nociceptors responding to a mechanical stimulus.
Scratch harder and it feels more like pain. Bernhard says one
theory is that ``itch'' nociceptors activate before pain ones do
because they're closer to the surface. Pain nociceptors may be
deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``In evolutionary terms, you want a sensitive alarm system that
can quickly tell you if something's landed on you that you don't
want to be there,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Allergic and inflammatory itches are chemical reactions to one
or more of 50 chemicals in the body that have been associated with
itch. These include histamines, released in reaction to allergens,
which dilate blood vessels and let those vessels leak. That causes
swelling, which is often associated with itch. Bernhard says
another class of chemical itch inducers are opioids, which include
endorphins. Some people with certain types of liver disease suffer
terrible itching, which is eased by drugs that block these opioids.
Morphine heroin and cocaine, opioids, also cause itching.
</P>
<P>
   So how does scratch work?
</P>
<P>
   The experts theorize that scratching triggers touch receptors in
the skin that send a stronger signal than nociceptors.
</P>
<P>
   That stronger signal blocks the weaker itch message from making
into the spine and up to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   And how do anti-itch medications work?
</P>
<P>
   Lotions provide a cooling effect and their paste blocks
mechanical stimuli. Anti-histamines dry up some of the offending
histamines ``and they make you drowsy'' Bernhard adds. Topical
anesthetics numb the nociceptors.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhard says as common, and infuriating, as itch is, whoever
figures out just how it works, and how to relieve it, is going to
make a lot of scratch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
