<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE MOUNT CARMEL DUST SETTLES, WILL THINGS BE CLEARER?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes the power I wield over the federal bureaucrats and
politicians in Washington is absolutely scary.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did I write a column insisting that there is no need
for one more investigation of 1993's Branch Davidian fiasco than
the powers-that-be reacted: There will not be one more
investigation of the Davidian affair.
</P>
<P>
   There will be three more investigations of the Davidian affair.
At least three more.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to say that we won't end up with four more? Or five, or
six, or 60? Once these people latch onto something that guarantees
live TV coverage and front-page headlines, they just aren't
inclined to let it go.
</P>
<P>
   So let's see: So far there's John Danforth, the special counsel
appointed by the attorney general; and there's the special Senate
task force headed by Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania; and there's the
House committee chaired by Dan Burton of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's probe will supposedly be limited to the events of
April 19, 1993 _ the day that David Koresh and his Davidian cult
went up in flames after a 51-day standoff with federal law
enforcement officials. Specter's investigation will focus on the
standoff and on Chinese spying and illegal campaign contributions _
a natural tie-in if ever there was one. Burton will apparently look
into anything he wants to look into.
</P>
<P>
   ``My committee has jurisdiction over the whole government,''
Burton said in a recent TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: Humility is not Burton's strong suit.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: We'll know who to blame the next time there's a
government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   With all these probes going on, it should come as no surprise
that the probers are already tripping over each other. According to
news reports, Danforth is complaining that Senate investigators
started interviewing witnesses without checking with him. Burton,
of course, fired off a batch of subpoenas to the White House before
Danforth even had a chance to set up shop.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a question: Will the competing investigations provide the
public with a better understanding of what happened when the
government faced off against Koresh near Waco, or will the multiple
rehash cause more mystery and confusion?
</P>
<P>
   Here's another question: What happens if all the investigations
yield different conclusions?
</P>
<P>
   What if Danforth says Koresh set the fire that killed him and
his disciples, and Burton says the FBI set it, and Specter says the
fire was the result of spontaneous combustion? Which investigator
are we supposed to believe?
</P>
<P>
   Danforth is a man of impeccable integrity, and if he says the
government burned up the Davidians, I guess I'll have to believe
him.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a prediction: Danforth's investigation will produce
the same conclusion that every previous investigation has produced:
The Davidians set the fire as part of a murder-suicide apocalypse
that Koresh had envisioned long before the federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms came knocking on his door.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, on the other hand, loathes President Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno so consumingly that he will be trying
to find some way to blame them for the tragic outcome of the
standoff. His conclusions will be useless, needless to say, because
he lacks so much as one ounce of objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   And Specter? As a former resident of Pennsylvania, I can say
with unqualified certainty that the only predictable thing about
Specter is that he is relentlessly unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, it doesn't really matter what Burton and Specter
come up with because their so-called investigations aren't
investigations at all. The House and Senate are interested in
nothing more than political grandstanding, in hitching a ride on
the latest wave of controversy over the Mount Carmel debacle. Their
findings may have no more validity than the wild-eyed letters and
e-mails I've been getting from anti-government/pro-Koresh
conspiracy theorists who obviously can't distinguish fact from
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   It is truly unfortunate that Congress won't butt out and let
Danforth do his job.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
