<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7563 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     09-27 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAN TO PRAY TOGETHER FOR PEACE MERITS SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Fort Worth clergyman has a proposal as bold as it is
beneficent. The Rev. Scott Colglazier, minister of the 5,000-member
University Christian Church in Fort Worth, wants every cleric in
the country, of whatever denomination, to speak and pray for peace
on the first Sunday of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities stagger the imagination. They are limitless.
An idea so broad, so sweeping in its simplicity, deserves in fact
to be worldwide _ and all-embracing.
</P>
<P>
   Just think. Throughout our aching, weary planet, people yearn
for peace but don't know where to find it. Perhaps _ just possibly
_ if at a given time we all should, even briefly, lay aside our
opinionated certainties, face our inadequacy and pray for mercy and
guidance, something truly quite wonderful might happen to us all.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tower of Babel, we are told, man's celebrated ego left
him babbling but incomprehensible to others. Now comes a clean,
straightforward plea that this human family offer together a prayer
that each could utter and most embrace: God grant that in these
years ahead we learn to seek and practice peace.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the argument that technically the third millennium
will not begin until Jan. 1, 2001. Nor is Colglazier's project
doomed because millions of devout people do not worship on Sunday.
Any day would do. The idea is to get people of good will on the
same wavelength for once. So let it be just as he says. Sunday,
Jan. 2, 2000. If someone wants to start a day early, on a Saturday
Sabbath, welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth, where Colglazier launches his plan, is recognized
most currently across the nation as the scene of that unspeakable
tragedy days ago when the mentally ill Larry Gene Ashbrook stalked
into Wedgwood Baptist Church with a semi-automatic weapon, randomly
killing seven innocent people, including teen-agers, and wounding
others before turning the gun upon himself.
</P>
<P>
   Several things are less known nationally about the city that
spawns this plea for universal New Year's prayer.
</P>
<P>
   One is that on the Sunday after the tragedy, many thousands of
our local citizens, people of almost every religious faith and some
of no formal affiliation, came together in the stands of Texas
Christian University's football stadium to comfort the grieving
families. That day they prayed together, this group of such
heterogeneous ethnic and religious diversity, for healing and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibly surprising fact is an almost unique sense of
religious ecumenicity taking place at Texas Christian University,
the institution to which Colglazier's University Christian Church
is loosely attached.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is TCU the academic home this semester to students from
70 nations representing every continent, but its associated
theological institution, Brite Divinity School, maintains an active
and acclaimed school of Jewish studies.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days ago, TCU hosted the second annual Gates of Chai
distinguished lectureship. Rabbi Harold Kushner, author of ``When
Bad Things Happen to Good People,'' spoke to a standing-room-only
house at the university's Ed Landreth Auditorium. Community leaders
of all faiths turned out to welcome and hear him. The rabbi
remarked upon the singularity of such warm and responsive
ecumenicity anywhere, particularly in the Bible Belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells me,'' said Kushner, that here at least Christians and
Jews have moved ``beyond toleration'' to a higher state of
fellowship and spiritual collaboration. It is altogether
understandable that impetus for an interfaith movement for peace
should spring from this soil.
</P>
<P>
   Is it, then, too utopian to hope that large numbers of
Christians, Jews, Muslims, Buddhists and plain people might unite
nationally on a given day in prayers for peace? Unprecedented,
maybe. But unreasonable to think they might be answered?
</P>
<P>
   The answer could depend upon what meaning we assign to the words
``pray'' and ``peace.'' If prayer be defined as a device to
manipulate God _ to change the cosmic plan, to impress, coax and
cajole the power of the universe to do what we wish _ there might
be very little new except the scale of participation.
</P>
<P>
   But if to pray is to align ourselves with the higher purpose of
One whom we believe already loves his Earth and all his children,
then there's hope in prayer. If its aim be less to change God and
more to change and reconcile ourselves, I believe it has a future
of unbounded potential. This, to the degree I understand, is
consistent with the dogma of all the faiths.
</P>
<P>
   And what is it, exactly, that we mean by peace? Is peace not
more than just the absence of armed conflict, desirable though that
be? Has the word not a positive, active meaning? To be in harmony
with one's universe and one's fellow creatures. To cherish them. To
desire, seek and serve their happiness and best interests. Is this
not the essence of peace?
</P>
<P>
   If we of sundry faiths and nations can come to the dawn of the
next millennium, laying down our own pitiful pretenses at
righteousness, and honestly ask that good things happen for people
who don't seem to like or treat us very well, there may be hope.
For that troublesome neighbor. That unscrupulous business rival.
That rude motorist who squeezed us out of our lane in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   For people who don't have enough to eat, and ones who have too
much. For oppressor and oppressed. For foreigners everywhere so
unlike and yet so like ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   When we can truly pray for these, and mean it, our prayers for
peace may be availing. They may, in fact, be self-fulfilling.
Colglazier's plan deserves support.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
