<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7569 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-PETTIBON-EXHIBIT-2TAK     09-27 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETTIBON-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTRAIT OF A LAID-BACK ANARCHIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By REED JOHNSON 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERMOSA BEACH _ The odyssey begins abruptly, with a thick,
violent slash of black paint that explodes in a blood-red
cloudburst. Next come the words, marching like mutinous conscripts
across the white rectangle of paper: ``Hell! Guns! Army! Kill!''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan J. Flynn, 8 years old, passes this latest sample of his
handiwork to his uncle Raymond Pettibon _ baseball fan, avowed
lifelong anarchist, and arguably one of the half-dozen most
influential U.S. artists of his late-baby boomer generation.
</P>
<P>
   Taking in his nephew's picture at a glance, Pettibon approvingly
notes its aggressive color scheme and freight-train collision of
image and text. The boy is smart, Pettibon knows, always drawing
and thinking. During the summer he comes over most mornings to make
art with the graying 42-year-old man he always refers to as
``Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, I really like the way you did this, Pee-wee,'' Pettibon
says, using the boy's familial nickname as he studies the picture
of an elongated rifle. ``Wanna make another one?''
</P>
<P>
   Pettibon pulls a sheet of construction paper from a small,
groaning table in his bedroom. Then, blinking back the hard Pacific
light, he settles into a plastic deck chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids that age are fascinated with violence and stuff,''
Pettibon says in his soft, sleepy voice. ``I know I was.''
</P>
<P>
   This, more or less, was how it all began for Raymond Pettibon
himself many years ago, when the drawings first started pouring out
of him as if from an open vein.
</P>
<P>
   Rough, emphatic images of steam engines knifing through
anonymous landscapes, framed by cryptic, philosophical inscriptions
(``When I see a train, I want to take it in my arms.'').
</P>
<P>
   Raw, unnerving pictures of Charles Manson, Ronald Reagan and a
crucified Elvis, a comic rogue's gallery of anti-heroic archetypes
culled from the counter-culture detritus of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Pulp-fiction silhouettes, or '50s cartoon characters like Gumby
and Vavoom (Felix the Cat's tiny, voluble sidekick), incongruously
bracketed by quotations that might've come from a Batman comic
book, the Daily Racing Form or a James Joyce novel _ literary
hierarchies be damned.
</P>
<P>
   All through the '70s and '80s, as Pettibon's reputation grew far
beyond the boundaries of his Southern California home, the drawings
kept coming, perhaps several thousand in all. Surfer dudes hanging
ten on undulating pen-and-ink waves beneath double-entendre
captions (``Catch the Drift''). Baggy-panted baseball players
swinging at pitches just out of reach, while behind them Pettibon's
neat handwriting lobs a rhetorical curveball: ``Who am I? What kind
of man am I?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the existentially chilling answer, zinging the viewer like
a 90-mph brushback pitch: ``The .250 man.'' In the law of human
averages, it seems, the best most people can hope for is to connect
with success one out of four trips to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Early viewers wondered: Whose voice (or voices) was behind these
haunting images? For it was Pettibon's ghostly authorial presence,
his extraordinary feel for language rather than his choppy drafting
skills, that transmuted the base metal of his images into pictorial
haiku.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these works _ now virtual icons of contemporary American
art _ were made after Pettibon had become the unofficial house
artist of L.A.'s nascent punk-rock scene, which Pettibon's older
brother, Gregory Ginn, helped invent as galvanizing lead guitarist
for the hard-core punk band Black Flag.
</P>
<P>
   They date from a period when none but a handful of art-world
cognoscente would've dreamed of paying $10,000 for a Pettibon
drawing, let alone honoring him with the massive retrospective,
organized by the Philadelphia Museum of Art and the Renaissance
Society at the University of Chicago, that opens today at downtown
L.A.'s Museum of Contemporary Art (MOCA).
</P>
<P>
   Scabrous and nostalgic, savagely incisive yet strangely tender,
Pettibon's works were as stunning for their sheer volume as for
their disquieting contents.
</P>
<P>
   To many longtime observers, they still are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray seemed to all of us a natural. Gifted, in the classic
sense. A prodigy,'' says MOCA's chief curator, Paul Schimmel, who
has known Pettibon since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could (borrow) from James Joyce and Jackie Robinson and put
'em together and just make something that was absolutely clear and
brilliant and lucid. And it's like, `Where did that come from?' And
that was something that I think (other) artists really were sort of
awestruck by. And in that respect, he is still a natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's deal with first things first: ``Raymond'' sounds too
formal and ``Mr. Pettibon'' (a family nickname Ray adopted years
ago) is simply ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   So call him Ray. Everyone does.
</P>
<P>
   He's a tall, gentle man with a gangly, minor-league pitcher's
build and a Byronic forelock dangling between shy, restless eyes.
His workday attire consists of khaki shorts, a tattered gray
T-shirt and paint-splattered tennis shoes which, depending on the
occasion, are optional.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Pettibon was born Raymond Ginn in Tucson, Ariz., in 1957
on Bloomsday, June 16. That's the date on which James Joyce set his
1922 novel ``Ulysses,'' the epic saga of a Dublin Everyman, Leopold
Bloom, who in the course of a single, 700-page day goes on a
perilous journey into selfhood and, returning home, achieves a
state of heroic grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ulysses'' is one of many, many books strewn like autumn leaves
throughout the Ginn homestead, along with surfer magazines,
videotapes of tennis matches (John McEnroe is one of Ray's
collectors), hundreds of vinyl LPs (Frank Sinatra, Grandmaster
Flash, Donizetti's ``Lucia Di Lammermoor'') and any number of
discarded fast-food containers.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are the drawings, hundreds of them,
stashed in bookcases, buried under mounds of kitchen debris,
peeking out from under furniture. There's an unruly orderliness to
the house, as if its walls long ago had ceased trying to contain
their inhabitants' free-wheeling creative energies, and had
resigned themselves to a kind of benign chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's crazy around here, some in one way, some in
another,'' says Ray's father, Regis Ginn, leading the way through
the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
