</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7575 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-PETTIBON-EXHIBIT-2ndT     09-27 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETTIBON-EXHIBIT-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Los Angeles:  leading the way through the kitchen.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ginn family's faceless beige house sits inland from the
fancy ``ocean-view'' condos popping up around Hermosa Beach. Ray
resides here with his younger brother Adrian; his parents Oie and
Regis, a retired English teacher, U.S. Air Force colonel and author
of spy novels; two cocker spaniels, Vaguely Noble and Ohne Titel
(German for ``Untitled''); and a long-haired dachsund, Barely
Noble, recently salvaged from a rescue shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The dachsund is a particular favorite of Regis Ginn, who wanders
in and out of Ray's room, informing his son whenever he's wanted on
the phone and chattering with his grandson, Pee-wee.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the kids were always hard-working and smart,'' Ginn says.
``Ray was always drawing, just like this little brat (Pee-wee) is
always drawing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginn family conversations tend to richochet at odd angles, like
the verbal fusilades in Pettibon's drawings. Bystanders, unsure if
they're witnessing teasing affection or something chillier,
occasionally may feel the urge to duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know Ray started out at UCLA as an economics major?''
Regis Ginn asks. ``He only did it because he could get his older
brother's books.'' The old man chuckles at this thought.
</P>
<P>
   Pettibon, overhearing, deflects his father's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, is that it?'' he mumbles. ``Oh, OK, whatever. Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Pettibon has lived in Hermosa Beach virtually his
entire life, eschewing the hip artists' colonies of Venice and
downtown, he claims to harbor no deep affection for this aging hub
of working-class anomie, stranded between the Harbor Freeway and
the ocean void.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways it's a really creepy place, the mentality of the
people who live here,'' he says. ``You know the expression `not in
my back yard'? It's pretty intense in that. Here, the way I put it
is, there's no life from the shoulders up. And there's also this
really obnoxious racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Famously generous in his dealings with other artists, dealers
and curators, Pettibon is widely known and liked and receives many
visitors at home. He insists that his surroundings are
``irrelevant'' to his work. ``Being an artist, you're pretty much
on your own,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But MOCA's Schimmel sees a thread between Pettibon's choice of
residence and the youthful, ``unadulterated sort of pureness'' of
his art, which perpetually revisits themes and subjects from
America's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remembers his childhood, I think, better than most of us,
and somehow can, in some way, kind of go back to that place. I
think it's why he likes little kids. I think there's something very
nurturing to who he really is, by staying within the very sort of
specific confines of his childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in this blue-collar crucible, and similar South Bay
enclaves, that the disillusioned younger siblings of beatniks and
hippies wrested rock 'n' roll from its complacency, stripped off
its tie-dyed veneer and created L.A punk.
</P>
<P>
   Black Flag, formed in 1977, forged the template for that angry,
mordantly ironic sound and do-it-yourself aesthetic, first with its
own albums, then through its SST Records label, which popularized
bands such as Minutemen, Husker Du and Meat Puppets.
</P>
<P>
   Pettibon, who contributed political cartoons to a student
newspaper while at UCLA, began illustrating Black Flag album covers
and promotional graphics in the late '70s. He continued through the
band's nihilistic heyday during the Reagan era.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Pettibon also self-published the first of roughly 100
fanzines, including the serial dubbed ``Tripping Corpse,'' one of
whose covers featured a long-haired maniac lunging with
blood-smeared knives at an unseen victim.
</P>
<P>
   With these works, Pettibon articulated an alternative vision of
the Southern California idyll, echoing the ``sunshine and noir''
traditions of Raymond Chandler's detective novels, the Doors'
doom-rock, the besotted, elegiac prose of Charles Bukowski, and the
visual art of such local predecessors as Edward Kienholz, Ed Ruscha
and Mike Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   Pettibon's drawings were notes from a sun-addled underground, a
place where the 1967 ``Summer of Love'' gave way to the 1969
Altamont murder, where the Manson slayings, the Vietnam War, the
Patty Hearst kidnapping and the repression of student protests by
then-Gov. Ronald Reagan cast long shadows across orderly suburban
lawns.
</P>
<P>
   While Pettibon has been an anarchist ``since I was 13,'' he
stresses, ``that doesn't mean I'm some wild-eyed bomb thrower.''
Like others of his half-generation, he seems not to have bought
into the politics of either the left or right, but to endorse an
ideal of the radically free individual, uncensored and ultimately
answerable to his own inner moral compass.
</P>
<P>
   That spririt persists both in his art and in his view of what he
calls the current ``anti-youth mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby boomers who grew up, I think the fact that when they
were children and growing up as (products of) a free love and
politics, etc., they're more suspicious about their own children
than anyone,'' he says. ``You know (the '60s slogan), `Don't trust
anyone over 30'? Now it's the complete opposite. Now you're
considered, if not a criminal, a potential criminal just for being
young.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1980s, Pettibon had already materialized on the
art-world radar screen. But it probably wasn't until the 1992 MOCA
exhibition ``Helter-Skelter: L.A. Art in the 1990s'' that his
underground reputation went above ground for good.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's hard to guess from his modest lifestyle that many of
Pettibon's drawings now fetch 10 or 20 times what they originally
did. Some coveted earlier works have sold for $5,000 apiece, and at
least one has gone for $10,000 at auction _ an enormous sum for a
single drawing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Pettibon has yielded to his dealers' pleas not
to give away any more of his works for free. But his monetary
habits still might appear mercurial.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular morning, Ray has promised to take Pee-wee to
the local 7-Eleven in search of toy airplane gliders. En route,
they stop at another convenience store where Ray opts for a bag of
salted pumpkin seeds and Pee-wee settles on a ``Sudden Force
Military Play Equipment'' set, including a toy submachine gun,
grenade and mask. Ray pays for everything with a crisp $50 bill.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the house, Regis Ginn, now wearing a baseball cap with
the Air Force logo, is complaining about not being able to catch
Vaguely Noble to give him a bath. From the back yard suddenly comes
the pop! pop! of firecrackers being tossed from an upstairs deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray's showing off now, I think,'' Regis says. ``That's why
this kid'll be in handcuffs before he's in third grade.''
</P>
<P>
   He means Pee-wee, who responds by pointing his new toy gun at
his grandfather. He pulls the trigger and spits out an imaginary
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, that's why he belongs in handcuffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Pettibon comes racing downstairs aiming make-believe
karate chops at his nephew. ``Kill the pigs!'' he yells.
</P>
<P>
   Pee-Wee aims and shoots at his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friendly fire!'' Regis Ginn exclaims with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Ray grins. ``It's all friendly fire,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   You may ask yourself: How long can Pettibon maintain his
anarchic energy? How long can he keep seeing the world through
young eyes, now that he's a well-paid leader in the visual culture
of our time?
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed, and it still does, that this guy could wake up and
knock off 20 drawings,'' says MOCA's Schimmel, shaking his head in
wonder. ``It was just a kind of endless supply. I don't think it's
as endless as it once appeared to be _ maybe to him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. For now, however, there is only the endless,
still-summery Pacific. Pettibon is meeting two artist friends to go
sailing to Catalina Island.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrives at the dock, the boat is ready and waiting. With
a half-smile, Raymond Pettibon waves goodbye, off on another
odyssey that, sooner or later, will lead him back home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
What: &LR;  ``Raymond Pettibon'' &UR;  &QL; 
Where: &LR;  Museum of Contemporary Art, 250 S. Grand Ave., Los
Angeles. &UR;  &QL; 
When: &LR;  Sept. 26-Jan. 2. Museum hours are 11 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays
through Sundays and 11 a.m.-8 p.m. Thursdays. &UR;  &QL; 
Admission: &LR;  $6 adults; $4 students and seniors; free for MOCA
members and children under 12. Admission is free to all every
Thursday from 5 to 8 p.m. Call (213) 626-6222. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
