<P>
   The breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   IS LIGHTER SKIN AN ASSET OR A LIABILITY? Being a mestiza can be
a mixed blessing, writes Sabrina Margarita Alcantara-Tan, a
Pilipino American, in this article from A. magazine. Many Pilipinos
look on her paler complexion with envy, believing that it makes it
easier to assimilate into American society and to land a job. In
fact, her mother even encouraged her to marry a white man,
suggesting it would be ``easier on the children.'' On the other
hand, some fellow Pilipinos treat her as if she were ignorant of
her country's language and heritage, or even deny that she is a
``real Pilipina.''
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL FAVORITISM CAN LINGER ON AND ON _ EVEN IF YOU'RE BLACK.
Cheering on Serena Williams as she won the U.S. Open this summer,
Vernon Jarrett was conflicted. Was it racist for him to root for
Serena just because she was black, like him? The match meant so
much to him and other blacks that on the occasion of his son's
wedding they were sitting in front of the television urging her on.
In this column Jarrett recalls sports heroes of the past such as
Joe Louis and Jackie Robinson and how much their achievements meant
to him and other black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   LATINO BOYCOTT, NOT A GOOD TACTIC. When the television networks
announced their new fall schedule, Latino characters and Latino
actors were nonexistent in the 26 new shows. Latino activists and
commentators were startled at the absence of characters and
immediately complained to the networks and were ignored. A caucus
of Latino organizations is currently boycotting network television.
Boycotts by themselves are worthless unless coupled with economic
punishment. Raoul Lowery Contreras comments on the boycott and what
he feels is a better tactic.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S TIME TO EXHIBIT TRUE CHRISTIAN COURAGE. When the Rev. Jerry
Falwell, of recent Teletubby fame, has dinner next month with 200
gay people and their allies in his hometown, one topic of
conversation wills be anti-gay violence. Columnist Chuck Colbert
thinks that's a great idea and holds ``the potential for stemming a
shameful trend: ugly inflammatory rhetoric, leading to violent even
deadly action against people perceived to be gay, lesbian and
transgendered.'' The celebrated October dinner party came about
through the efforts of the Rev. Mel White, who used to be Falwell's
ghost writer. ``Mel sincerely wants to lower the rhetoric on both
sides. That is exactly what we want,'' Falwell told his hometown
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   A DRY WHITE EMMY SEASON. At the Emmy awards, two weeks ago,
several nominees, presenters and winners criticized the new TV
season, which has been dubbed ``a dry white season.'' Of the 26 new
series on ABC, NBC, CBS and FOX, only NBC's ``Third Watch''
features people of color in lead roles. The lack of actors of color
is a perennial problem. It should come as no surprise, then, that a
national coalition of Latino groups is calling for viewers to
boycott the networks from Sept. 12 through Sept. 26. ``It is time
for us all to diversify our lives. If television does not then
reflect that diversity, writers, producers, directors and actors
must try again. The industry and the actors need to start taking
action,'' writes columnist Akilah Monifa.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION ABOUT NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE -- AND TO
RECEIVE THE SERVICE FOR 30 DAYS FOR FREE -- please contact sales
representative Ana Pena by phone, (212) 499-3333, or fax, (212)
499-3382.
</P>
<P>
   Many thanks!
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
