<HEADER>
A7627 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AFFLUENT-BACKPACKER-A     09-27 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFLUENT-BACKPACKER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (i and a coding)  
 ROUGHING IT, '90s STYLE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDHOEK, Namibia _ New Hampshire software consultant Tom Doyle
refuses to spend more than $10 a night for a dorm bed in a hostel,
but he has no qualms about dropping $60 for dinner with a bottle of
dry white wine.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strange pattern of extreme economy and top-of-the-line
luxury that Doyle, 36, has created during a nine-month independent
tour of Africa: He hauls around a muck-covered blue canvas
knapsack, but inside are a pair of shiny black wingtips, a gold
tie, and dress pants for nights out.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Doyle would have been an anomaly; a richer, older outcast
in a rite of passage that lures thousands of twentysomethings to
see the world as completely and cheaply as possible between college
and career.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Doyle often finds himself sharing a dorm room _
and perhaps a cognac _ with those his own age who are taking a
travel break during careers rather than before them. Hostel owners
say they are seeing a marked increase in the number of Americans,
Australians, and Europeans in their 30s and 40s backpacking through
Asia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The shift has led budget guidebooks to introduce pricier
categories, and hostel owners to create more private rooms for the
older, fussier traveler.
</P>
<P>
   These moves have brought new tensions to the adventure of the
backpacker trail.
</P>
<P>
   Younger, more traditional backpackers say the sense of community
they cherish in hostels is being lost as the richer backpackers use
the accommodations only to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new backpackers can take away from the communal aspect
of what these backpacker hostels started out as,'' complained
Lauren Robers, manager of Whale House Backpackers in Hout Bay, near
Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, she said, backpackers used the hostels as a
one-stop social outlet: An inexpensive place to sleep and meet
travelers from around the world to share adventures and traveling
tips. Meals are often cooked communally and conversations about
local customs and culture stretch long into the night. But older
backpackers, she said, often rent cars and flash credit cards to
ditch the hostel and fellow tourists for camel safaris or white
linen wine-tasting evenings in Cape Town's excellent wine regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The double rooms people are building defeat the object of the
backpackers; the dorm rooms get people talking to each other,'' she
said. ``It's sort of a fight in the industry now. You can lose the
whole concept of the hostel. We try to keep it pure here.''
</P>
<P>
   The new backpackers say they want that same purity _ without the
same price restrictions. Doyle, the software consultant who
hitchhiked from a central South African town to Namibia with an
African family, spent one night sleeping in a car, another in his
tent, and the next in a four-star hotel in Cape Town. Still a
little dusty from the sandstorms that whip across the Namib Desert,
he said his trip was too valuable to scrimp on the luxuries when he
occasionally craved them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time I want reality, and it's not in these big
hotels. It took me my entire life to get to this trip, and I'm not
going to count pennies, although I do have to be careful,'' said
Doyle, lounging in his eight-person dorm room at the Cardboard Box
hostel in Windhoek. There for one night, he was searching for a
ride to Botswana.
</P>
<P>
   As people marry later, make more money earlier, and switch
careers more often, many are tapping into savings to have an
extended adventure before going back to the grind. Moreover,
companies that value their employees are bowing to their workers'
wanderlust by granting travel sabbaticals.
</P>
<P>
   Those travel patterns are being catered to by on-the-cheap
guidebooks that increasingly are giving more expensive options to
the more grown-up market. Lonely Planet guidebooks, which started
out by giving backpackers in the 1970s advice on how to travel in
foreign countries on shoestring budgets, now give accommodation and
restaurant advice from ``bottom end'' to ``top end'' which can mean
$150-plus per night room rates and $90 dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``More of our challenge now is getting younger users to use our
books,'' said Carolyn Miller, marketing director of Lonely Planet
guides for the United States and Asia. ``Some people may be able to
afford a little something more . . . that's why we offer the
different options, but many still want that backpacker community
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   These new travelers reject American chain hotels and higher-end
organized luxury tours, opting instead for the rough-and-real,
dormitory-style experience offered by youth hostels.
</P>
<P>
   Hostels, which now accept guests of any age, may not always have
hot running water or private rooms, but guests are virtually
guaranteed interesting conversation over coffee with like-minded
adventurers from Manhattan to Melbourne. The trade-off in comfort
is more than made up for in experience: These travelers would
rather spend big money on river-rafting than room service.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a trip like this, when you are older, you don't have to
totally scrimp. But you do have to choose your priorities on where
you want to spend your money,'' said Carrie Svingen of Somerville,
who left last month for an eight-month backpacking tour of
Indonesia and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   A self-employed publicist in her mid-30s, Svingen went to
Indonesia last year for several weeks and fell in love with it. She
then sublet her apartment, asked her mother to mail her monthly
bill payments, let clients know she will return in mid-2000, and
boarded a plane. ``I didn't have a lot of responsibilities or
encumbrances, it was the right time to fulfill a dream,'' Svingen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hostel owners are taking advantage of the increase in older
travelers and their occasional desire for a slightly nicer room. In
Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe, the Shoestrings hostel still sees plenty
of young travelers, but is building and renovating single and
double rooms for slightly older travelers that may go for $13 a
night instead of $8.
</P>
<P>
   Catching rays of a late African sun on Shoestring's porch
recently, Simon Carles, 23, of London, said he has noticed the
communal kitchen at Shoestrings to be empty at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are older people here and they have their own way of
doing things,'' Carles, traveling for three months through South
Africa and Zimbabwe. ``I'm used to meeting people and learning
about who they are and where they've been. It still happens, but I
notice it's not as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Many older backpackers say the hostels still offer the communal
concept and international culture they seek. An occasional splurge
doesn't take away from that feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get more of the culture in the hostels, people talk to
each other,'' said Wayne Bonnett, 34, an accountant from New
Zealand. He and his fiancee, Rianne Joziasse, 28, of Holland,
traveled for eight months through southern Africa before being
married several weeks ago in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said he needs the hostel to both support the length of
time he is traveling, and his need to meet other travelers and have
the most cultural experience he can find.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford, and don't want, the luxury tour. This way I
have it all. I've had the most amazing time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
