<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARTH-BROOKS-PERSONA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `HISTORY' OF CHRIS GAINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Runs with GARTH-BROOKS mainbar) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just who is Chris Gaines, the fictional rock star
Garth Brooks portrays on his new album?
</P>
<P>
   Well, according to his extensive fake bio, his full name is
actually Christian Gene Gaines, born Aug. 10, 1967, in Brisbane,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   His father was Gene Gaines, a former swim coach for Long Beach
State University and former coach of both U.S. and Australian
Olympic swim teams. His mom was Carolyn Johnns-Gaines, a former
swimmer for Australia's Olympic team and a Commonwealth Games
medalist.
</P>
<P>
   The family moved to Los Angeles when only-child Chris was 5.
While expected to follow his parents in athletic pursuits, he
instead developed an interest in music and dropped out of
Morningside High School in his senior year to pursue it
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   His first success came when Gaines and pal Tommy Levitz, plus
Marc Obed, formed the band Crush, signed by Capitol in 1985. The
band's debut album was released the following year, and the second
single from the record, ``My Love Tells Me So,'' became one of
1986's top sellers.
</P>
<P>
   After Levitz perished in a plane crash that same year, Gaines
began work on his solo debut, ``Straight Jacket,'' released in
1989. The album spent 224 weeks on the Billboard Top 200, earning a
Grammy Award for album of the year. Hits included ``Maybe,''
``White Flag'' and ``Digging for Gold,'' while the album remains
Gaines' most popular effort.
</P>
<P>
   A year after his father's death in 1990, Gaines' dark-themed
sophomore album, ``Fornucopia,'' was issued, spending 18 weeks on
the Billboard charts. The disc included a remake of the 1972 Ramsay
Sellers classic ``It Don't Matter to the Sun'' and ``Main Street,''
which became a hit.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1992, Gaines was involved in a car crash that nearly did
him in. Following six weeks in the hospital, he underwent two years
of plastic surgery on his face, shoulder and hands.
</P>
<P>
   Like a rock-era Garbo, Gaines didn't allow himself to be seen or
photographed, and Capitol released his third solo album,
``Apostle,'' in 1994. It spent two months on the albums chart,
spawning the singles ``Way of the Girl'' and ``Unsigned Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Gaines launched a comeback in 1996 with the album
``Triangle.'' The media dubbed him ``the New Prince'' because of
his look and the r&AMP;b slant in his new music. Hits included
``Driftin' Away,'' ``That's the Way I Remember It'' and ``Snow in
July.''
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us to this Tuesday, when Brooks-as-Gaines
releases the ``greatest hits'' album ``Garth Brooks ... in the Life
of Chris Gaines,'' featuring the hits listed above plus two new
cuts, ``Lost in You'' and ``Right Now.''
</P>
<P>
   The album will supposedly act as a bridge between the early work
and a new solo disc, ``The Lamb,'' already being called the
``definitive album of the new millennium.'' &QL; 
!tag!f &QC; Swis721 BT f-b f-i!tag!!dtpost!_ &UR; Fred Shuster &LR; !off!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ALLY-LITE-LADN     09-27 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLY-LITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF-HOUR `ALLY' EPISODES JUST FILLING TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By DAVID KRONKE 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The most impressive thing about reformatting
hourlong episodes of ``Ally McBeal'' into bite-size, half-hour
chunks called ``Ally'' is that it can be done with any sense of
comprehensibility at all. That it can be done, of course, doesn't
mean it should.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally Lite'' basically extracts one of the subplots that worked
in tandem with other story lines on past episodes of David E.
Kelley's perky, Emmy-winning comic concoction and forces it to
stand on its own. What the people overseeing this prime-time
experiment seem to have overlooked is that the reason such stories
were only used as complements to an overall hourlong episode is
because they don't necessarily hold up alone.
</P>
<P>
   Of three episodes made available for screening, only one _
Ally's wacky confrontation with the Pringles lady and her
subsequent hearing on charges of instability _ passes muster as a
viable tale. The others _ Ally saves an obese man's life, then must
fend off his romantic overtures; Ally referees a romantic spat
between a minister and a choir leader, which causes her to reflect
on her own miserable love life _ simply feel thin and truncated.
What's most noticeable in ``Ally'' is what's missing _ the
accumulation of Kelley-created quirky moments that lead to an
emotional payoff at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to pad the episodes to the appropriate length,
there's all sorts of twee nonsense, from an excess of meaningless
establishing shots, to gobs of footage either choppily edited or
sped up (people were no doubt getting sick of cutesy overuse of
fast-motion back in film's silent era). Music figures in a lot,
too; too much for a half-hour show, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Kelley even bother with this, especially given the
fact that he currently has four other shows on the air? Apparently,
he's noticed that when it comes to syndication, he's getting a raw
deal _ even middling sitcoms pull in bigger bucks than his
acclaimed hour-long series. When average viewers channel-surf,
they're more likely to agree to waste a half-hour of their lives on
an old sitcom they liked than fritter away an entire hour on a
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley's gambit, however, comes at a time when sitcoms are on
the wane _ the only decent new one of the fall season, ``Action,''
is getting awful ratings _ and Kelley himself has been a pioneer in
the hourlong comedy genre. With luck, that may translate into
syndication success down the line, as well.
</P>
<P>
   It boils down to this: ``Ally McBeal'' is a phenomenon that
spoke to the Zeitgeist; ``Ally's'' just a way to kill some time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Ally.'' &QL; 
What: A slenderer ``Ally McBeal,'' if that's possible. &QL; 
Who: Calista Flockhart, Gil Bellows, Courtney Thorne-Smith, Lisa
Nicole Carson, Jane Krakowski, Greg Germann. &QL; 
Where: Fox (Channel 11). &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL; 
Rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
