<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7704 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-BALKAN-BREECH-REBIRTH     09-27 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKAN-BREECH-REBIRTH-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST CONTINUES TO REBUILD BOSNIA, BUT ON A SHODDY FOUNDATION  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 700-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 25 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russia, it seems, is not the only part of the former communist
world where large injections of western money have fostered
corruption rather than promoting reform.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, four years of intensive care by well-wishers, and
over $5 billion-worth of aid, have failed to create either a
self-sustaining economy or the sort of interdependence among its
feuding ethnic groups that would make a return to war unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the American House of Representatives
recently found evidence that hundreds of millions of dollars given
for reconstruction had been misappropriated. Soft loans and corrupt
procurement practices had been used to enrich Bosnia's ruling party
and its cronies, under the noses of western envoys.
</P>
<P>
   Even the money earmarked to provide gravestones for the
thousands of people massacred at Srebrenica in July 1995 had been
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   With criminal revenues like this, there is little wonder that
Bosnia's politicians have shown scant interest in creating an
economy that might one day stand on its own feet.
</P>
<P>
   But the Balkan countries do not have to go on like this. NATO's
victory in Kosovo, and the outside world's well-intentioned, if
sometimes clumsy, efforts to help the province back on to its feet
have opened up some historic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, new economic and geopolitical facts are
being created. Within the next few months, it will become clear
whether the western world is learning from the Bosnian experience
and aiming for something more ambitious than the mere avoidance of
renewed war.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the West has two choices. It can rely solely on
compacts with the region's existing power brokers, which often
means conniving at, or even reinforcing, the corrupt practices by
which they shore up their own authority and squash the emergence of
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Or it can work to undermine the current power structure, with
huge potential benefits for the region's people.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of that structure _ especially in Bosnia, Serbia
and Albania _ lie venal customs services whose inspectors owe more
loyalty to mobsters and warlords than to governments. These
services quite literally create ``barriers to entry'' for
legitimate manufacturers and traders who lack the necessary
connections in the world of politics and crime.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever possible, western governments should be urging Balkan
ones to dismantle all barriers to legal trade, and concentrate
their efforts on forms of commerce that do need be reined in: the
trade in drugs, guns and prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   If that means temporarily compensating governments for the loss
of customs revenue, so be it. But instead of throwing more money at
the region than its economies can honestly absorb, the European
Union, in particular, should think harder about opening up markets:
its own, as well as the region's.
</P>
<P>
   Such a policy could create a virtuous circle. It might be
easier, for example, to stop Macedonia levying huge sums on the
vehicles ferrying reconstruction materials to the Kosovars if its
own industrial products were flowing more freely to European
markets.
</P>
<P>
   It could be easier to stop the farmers of southern Albania
producing drugs if there were some other crop they were allowed to
supply to European consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians and smugglers of Montenegro, a notorious haven
for contraband, may at last be willing to ``go straight'' _ but
only if they have some legitimate outlet for their talents.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing West European governments should worry about is
the ``threat'' posed by cheap Balkan food or industrial
manufactures to their own producers.
</P>
<P>
   In one form or another, the desperation and poverty of the
Balkans will affect the lives of many people in more prosperous
places. They are already doing so in the shape of prostitution
rackets and the proliferation of small arms on the streets of Milan
and London; in southern Italy, convoys of Balkan smugglers brazenly
travel about in armor-plated vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   It is naive to imagine that either NATO's bombs, or huge sums of
poorly supervised aid money, will be sufficient to keep at bay the
potentially malign consequences of Balkan misery for Europe as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   How much better that the ``Balkan effect'' should be felt in the
form of legitimate exports which flow through the region, and
beyond it, without impediment. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 700-word article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7706 &Cx1f; tab-z
