<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSSIE-TIMOR-`THORN'-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR CRISIS BOOMERANGS TO ANGUISHED AUSTRALIA  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 925-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 25 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Officials have long described East Timor as the one
``thorn'' in Australia's relations with Indonesia, its closest
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   If East Timor's independence referendum on Aug. 30 went
smoothly, it was argued, the thorn would be plucked out: Australia
and Indonesia would be headed for a bright future as regional
partners.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughter carried out in East Timor since the ballot by
pro-Indonesia militias, with the blessing of the army, has left
Australia's policymakers shocked and its relations with its
northern neighbor in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of embarking on a new partnership with Indonesia,
Australian soldiers are leading an international force to bring
peace to East Timor. They are facing a possibly hostile Indonesian
army, and Australia is being abused in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 21, Indonesia's president, B.J. Habibie, accused
Australia of being ``excessive and unhelpful,'' and said his
government ``deplores the stance of Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   John Howard, the Australian prime minister, told a special
sitting of Parliament that the country's relations with Indonesia
were under ``great strain.''
</P>
<P>
   This was an understatement. The chaos in East Timor has
presented Australia with its biggest foreign-policy and defense
crisis since the Vietnam War 30 years ago _ some would say since
the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dibb, the head of strategic and defense studies at the
Australian National University, and formerly one of the architects
of Australian foreign policy, says, ``We're now in an era of
discontinuity. All the givens are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The givens for Australia have rested on two blocks: the American
alliance, born of the Cold War, and an engagement with Asia,
stemming from a need to tame old Australian fears about invasion
from the north.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Indonesia has been central to Australia's Asian
attentions, sometimes obsessively so. The overcrowded archipelago _
whose population, the world's fourth-biggest, is 11 times
Australia's _ lies close to the underpopulated expanses of ``the
lucky country.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has never shown any inclination to expand into
Australia, but many Australians remain nervous of the idea, never
more so than now.
</P>
<P>
   Australia turned a blind eye when Indonesia invaded East Timor
in 1975, after Portugal, the colonial power, had bolted. Australia
then became the only western country to recognize Indonesia's claim
of sovereignty over East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Appeasing Indonesia rather than making a fuss about its
brutality in East Timor was the order of the day.
</P>
<P>
   A review in 1986 of Australia's defense capabilities by Dibb
served to reinforce the policy. It argued that any military threat
to Australia was most likely to come from or through the Indonesian
archipelago, which lies across vital air and sea lanes, but that
such a threat was likely to be remote as long as Indonesia was
stable.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's former Labor government put much effort into keeping
Indonesia stable. Paul Keating, prime minister from 1991 to 1996,
counted ex-President Suharto, Indonesia's dictatorial leader at the
time, as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Keating's government signed a security treaty with Indonesia in
1995. It involved a degree of cooperation between the two
countries' armed forces that many Australians found uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   All that now counts for nothing. The fall of the Suharto regime
last year, and the violence that swept through East Timor before
the ballot, caught Australia's conservative coalition government by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   It was Howard who had written to Habibie in December suggesting
a process of self-determination for East Timor. This was seen as a
bid by Australia to expedite the removal of the East Timorese
thorn. It has not worked.
</P>
<P>
   Howard's critics, mainly among the pro-Indonesia lobby, say the
referendum should never have been held, certainly not until
democracy was more strongly established in Indonesia itself.
</P>
<P>
   If the government had been prepared to wait, argues Rawdon
Dalrymple, a former Australian ambassador to Indonesia and the
United States, ``we would not now have found ourselves truly and
definitively the odd man out in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to emphasize how far out, Indonesia on Sept. 16 cancelled
the security treaty that Australia thought would bring the two
countries together in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's adviser on foreign affairs, Dewi Fortuna Anwar, a
young woman educated at an Australian university, said Australian
troops would be ``singled out'' as targets by militias and
Indonesian soldiers in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The debacle has also exposed Australia to a new reality over its
other foreign-policy block, the American alliance. Howard asked
President Bill Clinton to commit ``boots on the ground'' to the
United Nations force, meaning troops.
</P>
<P>
   It was a request more appropriate to the Cold War, when
Australia supported the United States with troops in Korea and
Vietnam, than to an era when the Americans expect allies to pull
their own weight in their own regions.
</P>
<P>
   Australia is stretching itself to the limit by committing 4,500
troops to East Timor; America has offered 200 logistical personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's relations with Indonesia will take years to recover.
Already, Howard has proposed spending more on defense, and he is
cautious about making Australia an Asian power, as Keating seemed
to be ready to do. ``Foreign policy needs to be based on national
interest and on our values,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dibb suggests East Timor will be a turning-point for
Australia's assessment of its place in the world: ``We are now more
alone than we have been probably at any time since the 1930s.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
