<HEADLINE>
SUN, SURF, SEAFOOD _ AND SEX: WELCOME TO CAPE TOWN, SOUTH AFRICA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: Note omitted expletive in 10th graf)   (This excellent 525-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 25 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``t''
travel news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Sun, surf, seafood and sauvignon blanc are not,
it seems, enough. To entice visitors to Cape Town, the local
tourist office has decided to emphasize the city's thriving sex
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that foreign tourists may have been deterred by bombs on
the waterfront and gloomy crime reports, the Cape's official
boosters are letting it be known that those who seek illicit
thrills will find them in Cape Town. This follows an earlier
promotion of the city as a gay-friendly city, which indeed it is.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cape Town has long prided itself on a relatively free,
almost Californian image, none of this could have happened under
apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's old state was not only racist, but also prudish.
Commercial sex, interracial sex, homosexuality and even Playboy
were all suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   The new South African constitution, by contrast, is perhaps the
most protective of gay rights in the world. In fact, the country
has become more permissive than most of its rather conservative
citizens, black or white, find comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Massage parlors and gay bars appeared towards the end of
apartheid, but they have grown more numerous and blatant since
1994, when the African National Congress came to power.
</P>
<P>
   Most ANC members probably disapprove of prostitution; some frown
on homosexuality. But few think it worthwhile to police what
happens between consenting adults.
</P>
<P>
   The new permissiveness affects city-dwellers more than country
people, the rich more than the poor. But it is still a change.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old regime, policemen cruised parks and beaches
looking for homosexuals to entrap; 300 people a year were jailed
for sodomy. Now, same-sex couples openly hold hands in
Johannesburg's mall cafes, and the police are more likely to
protect gay pickup spots from muggers than to persecute those
cruising.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, the censors banned an Iris Murdoch novel with a
Picasso nude on the cover. Now, plays such as ``Shopping and
F------'' (EDITORS: EXPLETIVE REMOVED) enjoy full houses.
</P>
<P>
   The laws against interracial sex were particularly cruel and
stupid, though they had been repealed by the time the ANC took
over. On stage, performances of ``Othello'' were allowed, but only
with an all-white cast and audience, so the Moor left smudges on
Desdemona's cheek.
</P>
<P>
   The speed of change has left many South Africans confused.
Liberals applaud the new tolerance for homosexuals, which contrasts
starkly with the situation in many other African countries, where
they face long jail terms.
</P>
<P>
   But some worry that tolerance for commercial sex may be unwise
when AIDS threatens to kill a third of the population. The Cape
Town tourist office counters that it will direct punters only to
brothels that treat their employees well and encourage condom use.
</P>
<P>
   Not all attempts to cash in on South Africa's new permissiveness
succeed. Not long ago a farmer tried to organize a ``hooker hunt,''
in which punters were to pay to stalk naked prostitutes in the
bushveld, and shoot them with paint balls. This proved unappealing
to all but a tiny handful of oafs. So the ladies kept their shirts
on, while the farmer lost his. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 525-word article, it must be purchased _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
