<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FERMAN-POPMUSIC-TEX     09-27 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERMAN-POPMUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARTH BROOKS' ROCK ALTER EGO AIN'T A PRETTY SIGHT ... OR SOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Garth Brooks assumes the fictitious persona of Chris Gaines,
an Australian-born pop singer who hit it big in the mid-'80s and
was seriously hurt in a car wreck in 1992, which led to four years
of recuperation. Gaines ``emerged'' in 1996 and was dubbed ``the
new Prince'' upon the release of his CD ``Triangle.'' And now, in
1999, he's releasing a greatest-hits CD.
</P>
<P>
   He faces us now with long hair flopping into his dark-blue,
piercing eyes _ Trent Reznor's big brother, bloodied but not bowed.
And according to the cover, the CD hitting stores this week is a
``pre-soundtrack'' to a movie called ``The Lamb'' _ which,
according to industry sources, has not begun filming yet.
</P>
<P>
   Got all that? Good. ``Garth Brooks In ... The Life of Chris
Gaines'' is that greatest-hits collection: 13 tunes by a man who
never lived, taken from CDs that never existed.
</P>
<P>
   And man, is it lame. Brooks has always name-dropped the most
mainstream rock acts as his favorites: Styx, Billy Joel, the
Beatles. His appropriation of pop is, thus, quite vanilla _ there's
nothing singular about his foray into rock, no compelling voice.
</P>
<P>
   This CD arrives with liner notes from Gaines, photos of old
records (two of them amazingly sexist), and a shot of his old band,
Crush, looking a lot like a trio version of Loverboy _
eeeeewwwwwww. Most worrisome, though, is a photo of Garth/Chris in
a black-and-white leotard.
</P>
<P>
   Scary. Very scary.
</P>
<P>
   And so is the music. You know how you listen to someone and they
remind you of someone else and you can't think who that someone
else is? It took me a few minutes, but I figured out who
Garth-as-Chris sounds like: Kenny Loggins and Richard Marx.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly soulful white-bread vocals. Softer-than-soft rock. Wimpy
guitar solos. Yep, it's all here. Unfortunately. Brooks makes a big
bid at pop/rock stardom, and he emulates two incredibly mediocre
guys who were never memorable solo artists in their own right? What
was he thinking?
</P>
<P>
   And to give Loggins and Marx credit, they've both done songs _
such as Marx's ``Don't Mean Nothing'' _ that are better than
anything here. Then again, so has Loverboy _ I'd trade ``Hot Girls
in Love'' for any cut here.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Loggins/Marx references aren't always there.
There are some equally limp funk-rock touches, as on ``Snow in
July,'' and a smooth Babyface-ish R&AMP;B ballad, ``Lost in You.'' None
of them holds a candle to 99.5 percent of Prince's output. And then
there's ``Main Street'' (breathe a sigh of relief, it is not the
Bob Seger tune), which sounds like something John Mellencamp wisely
decided against releasing.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the worst moment of the CD is ``Right Now,'' which
mixes Gaines' alternating rap _ sample lyrics: ``Maybe it's the
drugs/Maybe it's the parents/Maybe it's the gangs with the colors
that we're wearin' '' _ with the chorus to the Youngbloods' ``Get
Together'' _ you know, the ``smile on your brother'' tune. This is
perhaps the worst attempt at rap I've ever heard, bar none, and a
horrible stab at social consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   These songs seem to evaporate as they're being listened to:
There's nothing compelling or particularly memorable about any of
them _ and at several points, such as ``Right Now,'' the urge to
laugh becomes nearly overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   As a personal reinvention, this CD is mildly interesting at
best, if you don't ask too many questions _ such as why put the CD
out now, so far in advance of the movie, and why Brooks' '80s look
(and those CD covers) go so far to try to emulate '80s hair-metal
bands, without any of those acts' sometimes successful merging of
pop and glam-derived rock.
</P>
<P>
   If I want to hear Loverboy _ or Kenny Loggins, or the Beatles,
or Prince _ I can hear them. They're as close as my CD collection,
or the local store. Why anyone would want to hear Garth Brooks do a
bad approximation of them, and others, is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
