<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7733 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-GARTHBROOKS-INTERVIEW     09-27 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARTHBROOKS-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO CALLS HIMSELF GARTH NOW CALLS HIMSELF GAINES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's Chris Gaines, bad haircut and all, staring dolefully
from the cover of his retrospective CD, ``Garth Brooks In ... The
Life of Chris Gaines,'' hitting record stores this week. The hungry
and embittered look, pouting lip, smudged eyeliner all bespeak a
rough life.
</P>
<P>
   Only thing is, it's a life that's never been lived.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a wildly successful and lucky guy like Garth Brooks
want to quit being Garth Brooks for a while and instead be this
mercurial ``Chris Gaines?'' Doesn't the feds' Witness Protection
Program have the patent on creating identities?
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, why is this a surprise? He has been talking about
the film project for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad you get this,'' Brooks says indulgently in a phone
interview earlier this month. ``It's a character in a movie I was
hired by Paramount to do the music for. It's not a career move,
it's just a character.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is ``The Lamb,'' and it won't be released until late
summer 2000. The script is being written by Jeb Stuart. ``He wrote
`The Fugitive,' which is basically what this is, with a female
lead,'' says Brooks, who has had the original idea ever since he
started his Red Strokes film production company in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Gaines may make appearances in controlled environments such as
TV guest spots and on his own TV special at 7 p.m. Wednesday, but
he'll never appear live.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we tour, it'll be as Garth. You know what's going to happen
if I tour as Chris Gaines,'' Brooks says. ``Somebody in the crowd
will stand up and yell `Come on, do ``Friends in Low Places''' and
it will all get started from there. But we might do the Youngbloods
thing (from the Gaines album) as an encore or something.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the prospect of perhaps seeing Brooks hosting an
upcoming ``Saturday Night Live'' with Chris Gaines as the musical
guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure one of the smart-(aleck) questions is gonna be,
`Which one is the act, Garth or Chris,' '' says Brooks, who often
pointedly refers to his stage self in the third person. (And, yes,
that was one of our first smart-(aleck) questions.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ONCE AND AGAIN: It's not the first time Brooks has taken on a
fictional identity. In January 1993, he and his band did some
small-club dates under an assumed name, at a time when he was
selling out large arenas several times over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were Yukon Jack back then and nobody said anything,'' he
says. ``We were on our way to (perform at) the Super Bowl. It would
be nice to do that again, but no.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chris Gaines is being given unusual latitude. Brooks is
introducing him a full year before the movie comes out, in TV
specials and late-show appearances. The object is for us to get to
``know'' Chris, better than we knew Spinal Tap, as well as our kids
knew Ginger Spice. Gaines will be with us for at least a year,
until the movie comes out. Brooks calls it ``an education
process.'' He maintains that the music will stand on its own,
without the film. Two singles, ``Lost in You'' and ``It Don't
Matter to the Sun'' have been released to pop and country formats,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this thing is based on the music, it'll be a huge
success,'' he says. ``But if it's because it's Garth Brooks, then
it won't get very far.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has other Red Strokes film projects on the table, too,
like the ongoing ``Revelations'' project, which he plans to
produce. He has been toying for several years with the idea for the
story of ``an average guy that ends up with the destiny of the
world in his hands.'' Then there is ``Samuel's Box,'' a political
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks says it surprises and disturbs him that people treat him
as something of a snake-oil salesman with every new project and
expect defection from Nashville at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is that? It seems like they really expect me to, as soon
as they turn around, stab them in the back or something,'' he says.
``Every time we bring something out, you hear `He's turning his
back on country!' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOING IT FOR MOM: Brooks, the real guy, has other non-Gaines
projects afoot. They include a Christmas album that will be tied
into a TV project, a duet album in the works with Trisha Yearwood,
and his work as producer on old bud Ty England's new Capitol album.
</P>
<P>
   Which is all pretty much puttering for a man who has sold more
than 60 million albums this decade and taken country music farther
than its council of elders ever dreamed possible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his personal life, coupled with a self-imposed two-year
hiatus from touring, has left Brooks at a crossroads. His mother,
Colleen, died of cancer Aug. 6. A onetime country singer herself,
she recorded in the 1950s with meager success. She married and left
show business, then got to ride in limousines and live large when
her youngest child became famous. He has virtually taken control of
the label for which she had recorded, Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also getting to a point where it (the prospect of touring)
scares me,'' he says. ``I'm getting older (37), my girls are
getting older. They're 7, 5 and 3, and this is the first time
they've all been in school together.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, then, is obvious: Does Garth Brooks still have
fire in the belly?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about this, when it was all happening,'' he says
in a dramatic whisper. ``Because the music, it was always about my
mom, more than it was for me. Now that she's gone, I don't know if
I have that fire, that motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll see if Chris Gaines does.
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins writes on country music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
