<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7735 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     09-27 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF-HOUR `ALLY' TURNS UP THE NEUROSIS A NOTCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why has David E. Kelley bisected episodes of his hourlong Ally
McBeal to create the 30-minute show ``Ally?'' The answer is not
that a powerful producer does ``whatever he wants'' simply because
he can. It is instead that Kelley is a talented, shrewd competitor
whose self-exaltation prevents him from being less than perfect at
anything.
</P>
<P>
   When asked recently why he decided to pitch ``Ally,'' a
collection of previously aired scenes edited to have a beginning,
middle and end, Kelley gave the honest answer, ``Because it would
play better in syndication.'' Not that it's about money, of which
he and wife Michelle Pfeiffer have plenty.
</P>
<P>
   He's right about comedies being better sellers and therefore
revenue generators for the production companies that own them, the
local stations that run them and the producer who creates them _
Kelley is two of those three. But later in the conversation, Kelley
revealed that nothing irks him more than syndication types actually
saying that his ``Ally McBeal'' is less desirable than any
run-of-the-mill comedy. Not because the sitcoms are pleasingly
snappy and crack us up, but because half-hours play so much better
in rerunville, period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rankled me,'' Kelley said. ``It just didn't sit well.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't sit well because Kelley is the consummate competitor,
a publicly gentle, accommodating soul privately driven to extremes.
His drive is not only to be creative in a business where that
quality is undervalued, but to be at the top of every measurable
aspect of the business. Whether it's the quantity of shows on
network television (five series with the Kelley imprint are on this
season) or the quality, which means having his series ``Ally
McBeal'' and ``The Practice'' capture best-series Emmys in their
respective comedy and drama categories in the same year, Kelley
wants it all.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Ally'' is yet another top-of-the-mountain achievement that
will leave us bowing to his royalness.
</P>
<P>
   In understanding the potential here, you must consider that
rabid fans of this witty dramedy will find a new series designed to
provide any Calista Flockhart fix they might need in addition to
the regular series airing Monday nights. As for anti-Allys, they'd
better run and hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally'' is Flockhart's spastic character on overdrive. Kelley
has cut out and condensed a story line (he usually has a main story
and ``B'' and ``C'' plot lines), which he follows to completion.
</P>
<P>
   He promises that new footage or outtakes that didn't make the
cut the first time will be added to enhance story lines or give
them common-sense context. What we'll get is an even more
pronounced Ally in all her scatterbrained, desk-tripping,
self-analyzing glory, which is sometimes hard to take, even when
viewers are given a rest by the shenanigans of Fish (Greg
Germann),) Elaine (Jane Krakowski) and the Biscuit (Peter
MacNicol). But this works, too, particularly if you saw subplots as
a nuisance anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, ``Ally'' moves along quickly, thanks largely to the
editing, and a speed-up device Kelley uses as if he's playing
around with the fast-forward button on a VCR. It's used when the
show is returning from commercial breaks and for scene changes, and
it's no more distracting than those dream sequences that have been
an ``Ally McBeal'' signature.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley says he's doing all the editing, which shouldn't surprise
us, since he is known for his reluctance to delegate writing
chores. (Kelley's answer to that is that complex characters are
difficult to write for.) But even at a half-hour, he has managed to
vary the pace of scenes, allowing dialogue to dictate mood and
motive. Also, the early word that the series would be comedic Ally
with none of those thorny moral dilemmas was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Ally in practically every scene over a 22-minute span
(subtracting time for commercials) offers not a different
perspective so much as a stronger one about the character's sanity.
Is, for instance, Elaine right in the upcoming episode ``100
Tears'' that Ally is ``two-thirds away from a Rice Krispy. She's
already snapped and crackling, and she's close to the final pop.''
</P>
<P>
   She was telling this to the State Bar Review Board after Ally
tripped a shopper at the supermarket and practically slugged a guy
after he accidentally bumped into her on a crowded sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think I'm nuts?'' Ally asks Whipper (Dyan Cannon), the
judge who has her own issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she answers. ``But I'm not sure you have two feet on the
ground, either.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the surprises at this year's Emmys was that ``Ally
McBeal'' won, and that it shouldn't have, considering that last
season its quirkiness turned to wackiness, which turned to
silliness.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit to not rushing home on Monday nights to catch
it, even to forgetting that it was on. But many of the people who
said it had fallen and shouldn't get up were those who weren't
watching it on a regular basis anymore, and who figured, wrongly,
that no one else was, either.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley's ego aside, watching ``Ally'' did a couple things. It
showed me what a gloriously prickly, multidimensional character the
producer has given us, and that all the talk that ``Ally McBeal''
no longer matters is premature.
</P>
<P>
   Laugh all you want when Ally falls into a toilet or dives for
that Dancing Baby. I'll watch to see the upcoming episode ``The
Promise,'' when the fiancee of the overweight attorney questions
her romantic future because of her own obesity, saying that ``if
you hold out for everything, sometimes you end up with nothing.''
Or ``Fools Night Out,'' in which Ally confronts her client, a
minister trying to get his scorned lover to stop putting their
business in her gospel lyrics, about how he could fall ``out'' of
love.
</P>
<P>
   Ally brings into full view a character who could cross the line
into neurosis at any moment. I don't call that weak. I call it
being strong, alive and unafraid of rolling in the mud with your
pain.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
