<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-DRINKING-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M BATTLES SCHOOL SPIRITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: Graphic available on NYT database) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Parents of 22,400 Texas A&AMP;M University
students got sobering letters from administrators last week,
warning them of an epidemic of underage drinking on campus _
especially among wide-eyed freshmen enjoying their first taste of
freedom away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking you to partner with us in addressing the
increasing use and abuse of alcohol and other drugs by college
students,'' said the letter from student life director Brent G.
Paterson, sent to the parents of all Aggie students under age 21.
</P>
<P>
   If they're lucky, the parents won't be getting a second letter
that goes something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently, I received information your son/daughter was found
in violation of a Texas A&AMP;M University Student Rule regarding
inappropriate possession and-or use of alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Research studies, campus arrest reports and other indicators
suggest that chances are good that any given Aggie has abused or
illegally used alcohol. One university survey found that 73 percent
of males and 71 percent of females at A&AMP;M use alcohol, and nearly
half admitted going on a drinking binge within the past two weeks.
One in three had missed class because of a hangover, and 40 percent
confessed to driving under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking-related consequences and dangers aren't unique to A&AMP;M,
but this year's two alcohol-related deaths of Aggie students drove
home the seriousness of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent letter to parents, A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen said he
wants the university to be ``free of alcohol abuse and its effects
in the classroom, in student residence communities on and off
campus, in our time-honored traditions and in those activities that
are the social fabric of our campus.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M is the first public university in Texas to opt for parental
notification of liquor and drug violations on campus. The notice
says that ``although we understand students are adults and need to
assume responsibility for their actions, we know that parents still
play a very important role in their development.''
</P>
<P>
   The message urges parents to talk to their kids about
inappropriate drinking behavior, which could jeopardize ``their
health, their academic performance, their relationships with others
and their future.'' It also advises parents about available
counseling, treatment, assessment and education programs, including
``Alcohol 101'' lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that parents retain the most influence over
their children, even in college, when it comes to health-related
behaviors, said Kristin S. Harper, associate director of the
Department of Student Life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing we know from talking to parents is they ...
often didn't find out until a student was removed from school or
their residence hall, and then it was too late,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas officials said they notify parents of rules
violations only if a student asks them to do so. They have no
immediate plans to adopt a policy like A&AMP;M's.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Christian University in Fort Worth is the only other
campus in the state that has joined the nationwide initiative to
make parents of minors aware of their infractions. Last year,
Congress changed the privacy protection law forcollege students
under age 21 to allow parental notification of disciplinary
violations.
</P>
<P>
   A survey in April of the 64 public and private colleges
participating in the National Core Drug and Alcohol Survey
indicates that at least 10 public universities, including A&AMP;M,
planned to begin parental notification this fall. Michigan State,
Kentucky and Virginia Tech also joined the trend.
</P>
<P>
   At least 15 private colleges, including TCU, Drake and
Georgetown universities, have adopted similar policies, although
notification isn't always automatic. Some colleges do it only after
multiple offenses or after case-by-case consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But at A&AMP;M, parents will be notified upon an underage drinker's
first offense _ once the allegation runs through the university's
nonjudicial disciplinary process and results in a guilty finding.
The first such letters will be mailed this week, based on
violations that have occurred since classes resumed a few weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you drink, you're going to have Mommy and Daddy, in
addition to other people, coming down on you,'' warned Bob Wiatt,
director of A&AMP;M security and university police.
</P>
<P>
   He applauded the administration's decision to target the drunken
``debauchery'' that accompanies some Aggie events and traditions,
especially the bonfire and pep rally preceding the annual football
game with Texas. This year, the bonfire will be on Thanksgiving
night.
</P>
<P>
   Of equal concern, Wiatt said, is the everyday drinking in
dormitories and off-campus bars, aided by computer-generated, bogus
identification cards used by those under the legal drinking age of
21.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know from high school this is a sin,'' Wiatt said. ``What
you have is a bunch of youngsters, who, for the most part, have
been protected by Mommy and Daddy, and they are now free _ free at
last. They are on their own at a university where they are
unfettered.''
</P>
<P>
   Eager to experiment and to fit in with others, under-age
students have little trouble obtaining booze, either through older
friends or with fake ID cards, according to university officials.
</P>
<P>
   While many, if not most, violations go unreported and ignored,
in each of the last four years campus police have arrested more
than 200 students for illegal possession of alcohol, public
intoxication and driving while intoxicated. That tally doesn't
include arrests made by Brazos County sheriff's deputies or police
in College Station, Bryan and other nearby jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge problem. People have died,'' said the campus
security director.
</P>
<P>
   In January, an intoxicated student fell to his death while
sliding down a bannister in a campus parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt said the young man's parents couldn't believe their son
would abuse alcohol, so he presented them with the student's fake
ID to help them comprehend the reality.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a student celebrating on the eve of his 21st
birthday died of alcohol poisoning at his off-campus residence.
</P>
<P>
   UT has had two alcohol-related deaths in recent years. Last
year, a 23-year-old student died of alcohol poisoning following a
fraternity hazing ritual. In 1995, an intoxicated 19-year-old
student drowned in the Colorado River in another hazing-related
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   While parents may be unaware of their children's drinking, A&AMP;M
students likewise have been caught unaware by the new notification
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the first-year students who I have talked to were,
quite honestly, surprised that parents hadn't been notified
before,'' said Lorna Breault, who leads the alcohol education
program tailored for Aggie freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, their parents know'' about their drinking,
she said, adding that ``parents still do have a great deal of
influence. If parents can set standards ... that will help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Police aren't the only officials trying to arrest the problem.
Professors occasionally report drunken students in class, and
residence hall advisers have turned in students found drunk in
their dorm rooms. In training sessions, university personnel are
urged to no longer ignore drinking offenses.
</P>
<P>
   This fiscal year, A&AMP;M will spend almost $225,000 for alcohol and
drug education programs, including an upcoming campaign to
discourage drinking before, during and after the annual bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to notify parents followed the recommendation of a
task force set up in 1997 to examine an ``environment for alcoholic
abuse'' on campus. Students, faculty, staff, community members and
representatives of the Federation of Aggie Mothers Clubs
participated in the dialogue, said Harper, who chaired the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notifying the families is one way we address this issue,'' she
said, ``but it's part of a very big picture of our concern about
what we think is an appropriate environment here at A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
