<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT TOO LATE FOR A MILLENNIUM TREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANIELLE FURFARO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hype isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   With the millennium a few weeks away, travel agents and tourism
officials say there are still plenty of openings for hotels and
cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, there was a flurry of demand for vacation
packages as the excitement mounted. But then prices started to
climb, travel agents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They priced themselves right out of the market,'' said Gwynne
Balson, president of All Destinations travel agency outside Albany,
N.Y. ``I've had so many customers throw up their hands and say,
`Forget it. I'll just stay home.'''
</P>
<P>
   This New Year's Eve may be more ``home alone,'' then party
central.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the anticipated boom, many places did not roll out
much advertising. Now, many wish they had.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry thought there would be a huge demand,'' said
David Wood, co-owner of Wood Travel in Albany, ``but they scared
everyone away.''
</P>
<P>
   Circus Circus, the Las Vegas casino, is charging $399 a night
with a three-night minimum at its hotel. Rates at the hotel for the
following week are as low as $49 a night with no minimum stay. They
have vacancies for New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Most hotels and real estate agencies are requiring some sort of
minimum stay. However, as New Year's Eve inches closer, some are
thinking of dropping the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Disney required a refundable deposit to get to be in a lottery
for a spot on a cruise _ even before they announced a price, Wood
said. The company reported that thousands of people made a deposit
for a 1,000-person millennium cruise.
</P>
<P>
   When the price finally was announced _ $3,000 for a four-day
Caribbean cruise that would normally be about $700 _ almost
everyone asked for their deposit back. Now, Disney is struggling to
fill spots on the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Balson said that several companies already have begun to bring
down their prices and hotels and other in the industry will get a
better grip on reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be profitable, no doubt,'' said Grant Flowers,
associate editor of Travel Weekly, a U.S. Trade Publication.
``Customers just do not want to be gouged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
