<HEADER>
A7767 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SUBARU-TELESCOPE-     09-27 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SUBARU-TELESCOPE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A STEP BACK, A TELESCOP PROPELS JAPAN AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT MAUNA KEA, Hawaii _ On the final ascent up this volcanic
mountain, the gleaming white housing of Japan's new national
telescope, which looks vaguely futuristic with its cylindrical
shape, immediately sets it apart from the more traditional domes
that sprout nearby in the cold, thin air.
</P>
<P>
   But it is only upon closer inspection of the device, named the
Subaru, that one begins to see that the design of the telescope
responsible for Japan's great leap forward in deep-space
observation commences with what would seem to be a decided step
backward: the use of a single huge piece of glass as its primary
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Since the completion of the revolutionary 200-inch telescope on
Palomar Mountain in 1948, telescope designers have been confronted
with a seemingly intractable problem preventing the design of ever
larger light-gathering mirrors: the gradual distorting effects of
gravity on massive pieces of suspended glass.
</P>
<P>
   Telescope designers in recent years have resorted to a variety
of tricks to overcome this problem. For example, the primary
mirrors in Subaru's closest neighbors on the mountain, the twin
400-inch Keck telescopes, the two largest in the world, are each
made up of many joined segments with a common focus.
</P>
<P>
   Several other new telescopes have featured very thin ``floppy''
mirrors, combined with computer-controlled supports that can
constantly adjust the shape of the mirror to compensate for
gravity's sag and even atmospheric blur.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy, being used by the European Southern
Observatory for its array of four 320-inch telescopes at La Serena
in Chile, is to combine the light from separate telescopes to
obtain the resolving power of a vastly larger lens. The Kecks are
designed to be so linked eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has long suffered the image of being a nation of
scientific followers. In astronomy, for example, the country had
long been limited to the use of an 80-inch device built decades
ago. But when it came to designing a new telescope, the country's
small astronomy establishment shed the follower image and wagered
boldly that the magic of the single-mirror approach _ something of
a classical ideal among telescope builders _ was far from played
out. The result was the Subaru. (The name does not indicate a
connection to the car company; instead, it is the Japanese name for
the constellation Pleiades.)
</P>
<P>
   In pulling off its creation, Japan has applied the nation's
exquisite skills in engineering, design, construction and
miniaturization in ways that experts say will strongly influence
the future course of building very large telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the features that will be looked at most carefully are its
flexible, relatively thin, seven-inch-thick mirror and an enclosure
that is of a piece with the telescope itself and rotates to change
views of the sky. Scientists say that the enclosure design, once
criticized for its cost, has already proven its superiority in the
critical areas of temperature and wind-flow control.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the system of servo-controlled active optics,
which uses 264 motors to adjust the mirror, to correct for minute
distortions.
</P>
<P>
   All of this cost Japan $400 million at current exchange rates,
or several times the price of the first Keck telescope. But
astronomers say that Japanese telescope builders, unlike those in
the United States and Europe, had to build virtually everything
from scratch, something that must be taken into consideration in
evaluating the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a couple of years, a conventional wisdom will form as
to which approach to big telescope construction is most
advantageous and most economical,'' said Dr. Robert McLaren,
interim director of the University of Hawaii's Institute for
Astronomy. ``Right now, most people expect that the single-lens
approach will prove superior.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though it is not yet equipped with the devices that
astronomers will need to take full advantage of its powers, the
Subaru telescope has already exceeded many of its designers'
expectations. It has, for example, already broken the resolution
record for ground-based telescopes, with the ability to see angular
details as small as 0.196 arc seconds, about five times better than
conventional telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   When a new adaptive optics system is installed, allowing for
correction of atmospheric distortions, the resolution is expected
to increase to 0.06 arc seconds. Such sharpness, scientists say, is
the equivalent of being able to see a baseball clearly from 180
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of space-based telescopes are expected to
take decisive advantage of the dark vacuum of space to offer
resolution superior to any Earth-bound telescope. For now, though,
Subaru's astronomers readily offer side-by-side comparisons of
their device's images with those taken by the Hubble Space
Telescope, and believe many of their images are clearly better.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers who will operate Subaru say the telescope's
ultra-high resolution, its superb light-gathering capacity and its
so-called prime-focus view, which permits the capturing of images
of wider sections of the sky than most other telescopes, will make
the device a leader in astronomical research. Two particular areas
of expected strength are deep-field research and the quest to find
other solar systems.
</P>
<P>
   Deep-field research involves collecting information on the
darkest, most remote regions of space in an effort to understand
the evolution of the universe and predict its future. The search
for new planets outside of our solar system, meanwhile, requires
the spotting of extremely faint objects that on the scale of the
universe are not only distant, but like our own solar system's
planets, are relatively tiny.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview during testing of the telescope last March,
Subaru's director, Dr. Norio Kaifu, who previously directed
research at Japan's large radio telescope at Nobeyama, fairly
brimmed with confidence about these capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been many reports of the discovery of planets
outside of our solar system, but no one has yet produced clear
images,'' said Kaifu. ``Clearly this represents demanding work, but
we want to show these planets.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Japanese name might be given to the first planet
discovered by Subaru, Kaifu laughed. ``We don't plan to discover
only one,'' he said. ``We will find many.''
</P>
<P>
   And in making the search, many are betting that the Subaru team
will reinvigorate Japan's interest in astronomy, and indeed, its
investment in science generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the history of Japan, you realize that we
imported science from the Western world only about 100 years ago,
so it is quite natural that we are behind in many ways,'' said
Kaifu. ``With Subaru we have reached a very high peak, but there is
still not much of a base beneath our feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps our biggest impact will be in encouraging the future
scientists of Japan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
