<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THERAPIES: New Blood to Treat Multiple Sclerosis
</P>
<P>
   A new Mayo Clinic study has found that a treatment known as
plasma exchange can help end severe attacks of multiple sclerosis
that do not respond to standard medications.
</P>
<P>
   In plasma exchange treatment, a patient's blood is removed, and
the blood cells are separated from the fluid in which they are
carried, known as plasma. The plasma is then replaced with an
artificial substitute before the blood is returned.
</P>
<P>
   Most multiple sclerosis patients suffer periodic attacks of
inflammation of central nervous system tissue, during which they
can lose the ability to move, talk and even breathe. Most get
better on their own, or through treatment with anti-inflammatory
steroids, said Dr. Brian G. Weinshenker, a neurologist at the
clinic who was the lead investigator on the study. But not all
patients respond to steroid treatment, and repeated acute attacks
eventually lead to nerve fiber damage and progressive
deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was presented earlier this month at a
conference in Switzerland, involved 22 patients with multiple
sclerosis or closely related diseases. Half the patients began with
plasma exchange, and the other half with a sham treatment; the
double-blinded study design called for any patient not responding
to two weeks of their initial treatment to switch to the other, so
as not to deprive desperately ill patients of a chance at recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Two patients died during the study, and one improved while
receiving the sham treatment. Of the 19 others who received plasma
exchange, 8 showed moderate to marked improvement, regaining use of
their arms and legs and their ability to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Weinshenker cautioned that plasma exchange is not a treatment
for chronic severe multiple sclerosis, but rather a potential tool
for those whose serious acute attacks are beyond the reach of
steroid treatment. ``The story as we see it is that it gives some
patients a chance to be rescued by removing something in their
plasma that was sustaining the attack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Heeding Doctor's Orders on Gun Safety
</P>
<P>
   Pediatricians routinely counsel families about the importance of
seat belts and smoke alarms. The American Academy of Pediatrics has
long urged its members to add gun safety to that list _ but with
less success, according to a new study reported in the September
issue of the journal Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   The study finds that although pediatricians are willing to
discuss the topic with their patients, they may not be good judges
of which families need the information. In a survey of 66
pediatricians, virtually all agreed that they should discuss gun
safety with families who own guns. But when it came to identifying
those families, the doctors often missed the mark: when 169 of
their patients were surveyed, it turned out that nearly a third of
the families judged least likely to own guns reported owning at
least one.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, Dr. Elise Becher of the Mount Sinai School of
Medicine and Dr. Nicholas Christakis of the University of Chicago,
concluded that rather than relying on their own judgment,
pediatricians should ask all families whether they own guns. The
two doctors noted that research has suggested that when
pediatricians do offer advice on gun safety, families are likely to
take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   And some of them can offer firsthand advice: 14 percent of the
pediatricians surveyed reported owning guns themselves.
</P>
<P>
   -MICHAEL PORTER
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION: Eat Your Onions and Save Your Bones
</P>
<P>
   An onion a day could help keep osteoporosis away, suggests a
study reported in the current issue of the journal Nature. Drs.
Roman C. Muehlbauer and Feng Li of the University of Bern in
Switzerland found that 14 vegetables common in the diet can
significantly alter bone metabolism in rats and perhaps decrease
the incidence of osteoporosis in humans.
</P>
<P>
   When male rats were fed one gram of dry onion per day, bone
resorption _ the process in which calcium is released from bone
stores, thereby weakening the bones _ was inhibited by 20 percent.
That was slightly higher than the effect of calcitonin at doses
used to treat osteoporosis in women past menopause.
</P>
<P>
   Because osteoporosis occurs most frequently in postmenopausal
women, the researchers performed the same experiments on rats with
their ovaries removed.
</P>
<P>
   In these rats, bone resorption was 32 percent higher than the
normal rat but also was inhibited by onion intake.
</P>
<P>
   The results suggest that in addition to a moderate intake of
dairy products or a calcium supplement, the diet should include a
good mix of vegetables, Muehlbauer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that once the effects have been confirmed in humans,
it will be possible to slow down bone loss and, ultimately, reduce
the incidence of osteoporosis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ALISA TANG
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
