<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: DETECTING COLON CANCER WHEN IT IS CURABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a famous person is found to have a serious and potentially
fatal disease, it often serves as a wake-up call for the rest of
us. Just as Nancy Reagan's breast cancer stimulated a rush for
mammography, the recently diagnosed colon cancer of Justice Ruth
Bader Ginsburg of the Supreme Court should jolt all women (and men)
over 50 _ and some younger people as well _ to take advantage of
the tests that can detect this disease while it is still curable,
perhaps even before it has become cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the colon and rectum is the second leading cause of
cancer deaths in the United States, after lung cancer. It is also
one of the most curable of cancers, but only if it is found in its
early stages. Because colorectal cancer usually develops over many
years and has a long precancerous stage, it can be detected early
and even prevented if people adhere to the screening guidelines
recommended by the American Cancer Society, among others.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of people survive colorectal cancer when it
is detected and treated while still confined to the site where it
arose. But only 37 percent of cases are discovered that early. In
its early stages colorectal cancer is often a silent disease,
producing no symptoms at all, which is why periodic screening to
detect hidden disease is so important.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ginsburg's cancer was found only after she experienced
significant symptoms, which were initially misdiagnosed as
diverticulitis and which suggest she may have a more advanced stage
of the disease. It is not known whether Justice Ginsburg had ever
had any of the recommended screening tests, but by her age, 66, the
guidelines suggest she should have had at least two colon exams as
well as 16 tests for hidden blood in the stool.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, women tend to think of colorectal cancer as a
man's disease, and even those women who regularly have mammograms
and Pap smears tend to ignore their colons. But the disease shows
no sex discrimination; if anything, it hits women slightly harder
than men. This year about 67,000 women _ 4,600 more women than men
_ will be found to have colorectal cancer, and 28,800 women _ 1,000
more women than men _ will die of this disease. And while overall
death rates from colorectal cancer have been dropping in this
country, among African-Americans they have risen by 9 percent in
the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986 the incidence of colorectal cancer has been declining
by more than 1 percent a year. Researchers at the University of
Illinois at Chicago recently attributed this decline to an
increased use of screening tests and to the removal of precancerous
polyps found as a result. Their study indicated that changes in
diet and life style have played only a minor role in the decline.
But a survey conducted in 1997 among 52,754 men and women ages 50
and older by the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
revealed that only a minority of Americans in that age group have
ever taken advantage of the available screening tests.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons why such life-saving measures are not
better used: the preparation is off-putting, there is often
discomfort and embarrassment, and the screening costs money.
Insurance rarely covers the cost of the most comprehensive tests
when used as screening tools. In a typical insurance Catch-22, only
those people who already have suspicious symptoms of cancer would
be covered.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest and cheapest of the tests _ a digital rectal exam
by the doctor and a self-test for hidden blood in the feces _ are
also, unfortunately, the least accurate, although the occult blood
test can reduce the risk of dying from colon cancer by more than 33
percent, according to the Harvard Center for Cancer Prevention. The
occult blood test can help detect a problem because colorectal
cancers and precancerous polyps often _ but not always _ bleed
slightly, depositing tiny amounts of blood on the surface of bowel
movements.
</P>
<P>
   The most commonly used version, Hemoccult II, involves smearing
a bit of feces on test cards for three consecutive days, then
mailing the cards for chemical analysis.
</P>
<P>
   For two days before the test and during the three test days you
are advised to avoid certain foods and drugs that may distort the
results. Drugs like aspirin, ibuprofen and other nonsteroidal
anti-inflammatories as well as iron, reserpine and persantine can
cause slight gastrointestinal bleeding and should not be taken.
Doses of vitamin C greater than 250 milligrams, which can mask the
presence of blood, should also be avoided. You may also be told to
refrain from consuming red meat, citrus juices and fruits,
cantaloupe, radishes, broccoli, cauliflower and turnips and not to
have any dental work done until after the test.
</P>
<P>
   There are two other fecal tests on the market, EZ Detect and
Colocare, that have few dietary restrictions and do not require
direct handling of feces. But they have not been tested as
thoroughly and are subject to other sources of inaccuracy.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining tests, which allow the doctor to examine the
lining of the colon and rectum, require a thorough cleansing of the
bowel beforehand via enemas and laxatives. The old rigid
proctoscopes have been replaced by a more comfortable instrument
called a flexible sigmoidoscope, which allows the doctor to
directly view the bottom third of the bowel, where about 40 percent
of colorectal cancers arise. Of course, this means that in nearly
two-thirds of cases, a cancer will be missed. Still, this test,
which can be done in the doctor's office and requires no sedation,
can be used as an indicator: if any abnormality is found, a more
thorough exam can be done of the entire five or six feet of large
intestine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The two most thorough exams are the colonoscopy, which uses a
lighted scope to examine the entire length of the colon and is done
in a hospital or clinic under mild sedation, and the
double-contrast barium enema, an X-ray exam in which the colon is
filled with barium and air.
</P>
<P>
   Colonoscopy has the advantage of enabling the doctor to biopsy
suspicious lesions or remove polyps during the exam. However, it
typically costs $700 to $1,100, and is usually not reimbursable by
insurance when used for screening in a person without symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Testing Guidelines
</P>
<P>
   Any of the following symptoms, if otherwise unexplained, warrant
a complete colon exam:
</P>
<P>
   A change in bowel habits _ diarrhea, constipation or narrowing
of the stool _ that lasts more than a few days.
</P>
<P>
   A need for a bowel movement that is not relieved by doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Rectal bleeding or blood in the stool.
</P>
<P>
   Cramping or steady abdominal pain.
</P>
<P>
   But no one should wait for symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society, which for years has cautioned
people not to ``be embarrassed to death'' by avoiding colorectal
screening tests, recommends that beginning at age 50, both men and
women should follow  &UR; one &LR;  of these three screening options:
</P>
<P>
   -A yearly fecal occult blood test plus flexible sigmoidoscopy
every 5 years.
</P>
<P>
   -A colonoscopy every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   -A double contrast barium enema every 5 to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, at every colon exam, a digital rectal exam should
also be performed.
</P>
<P>
   For people known to be at unusually high risk of developing
colorectal cancer, there is a different guideline. High-risk
individuals include anyone with a strong family history of
colorectal cancer or polyps (in a first-degree relative before age
60 or in two first-degree relatives at any age); a personal history
of colorectal cancer or adenomatous polyps or a history of chronic
inflammatory bowel disease (ulcerative colitis or Crohn's disease),
and all those in families with hereditary colorectal cancer
syndromes (familial adenomatous polyposis and hereditary
nonpolyposis colon cancer). Such people are usually advised to
begin colorectal screening by age 40 and to be tested more often,
ideally with a colonoscopy.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Medicare coverage was expanded to include colorectal
cancer screening, as follows: for people 50 and older at average
risk of developing the disease, coverage is provided for an annual
occult blood test and for sigmoidoscopy every four years; for
people at high risk, Medicare covers colonoscopy every two years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to regular screening, which can detect precancerous
lesions in the colon and rectum, several behavioral adjustments can
reduce your risk of developing a cancer of the bowel. Studies of
many thousands of people indicate that the risk is increased by
obesity, diets high in red meat, smoking and having more than one
drink a day. And it is lowered by regular physical exercise, diets
rich in vegetables and possibly whole grains, and multivitamins
with folic acid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
