<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7776 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-LEARNING-BASKETBA     09-27 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LEARNING-BASKETBALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 TAKING TO THE COURT FOR BASKETBALL 101hedline  
 (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(jt) 
 By AIMEE BERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I have a pretty odd sports closet. For one thing,
it's an armoire. For another, it's crammed with gear more suited to
mountains, rivers and ``Rocky'' than the asphalt playground known
as New York City. Open it and out tumbles a rock-climbing harness,
ski wax, a headlamp and a mouth guard. And that's just the first
wave. But you'll never be bonked by bats, clubs or balls; I've
never been much for conventional sports.
</P>
<P>
   Still, strangers always assume I play basketball.
</P>
<P>
   I wish.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 10 and 33, I'm fit and agile. I can guide a raft down
the hairiest whitewater, I can run and ski faster than most men I
know, my backhand rips, and in 1996 I won the Golden Gloves of
boxing in my weight class. But make me dribble a basketball without
looking at it, and suddenly it's, ``Danger, Will Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it has always been so. In fifth grade, while
enthusiastically trying out for my middle school basketball team, I
publicly failed dribbling and badly improvised my first layup ever,
only to become acutely aware that coaches were not seeking untapped
potential. Even at that level, coaches wanted those who showed
talent.
</P>
<P>
   So why open the old wound?
</P>
<P>
   Ever since I moved to the basketball capital of the world, I
have wanted to play pickup without being laughed into oblivion. Who
hasn't? But where do you get game in this city? Every nearby gym I
called offered an adult league, but no adult instruction. And you
hate to beg pals to sacrifice their sunny weekends, or worse, risk
ruining perfectly civilized friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Never Too Late Basketball. For $219 and 10 consecutive
Tuesdays, I could join other strangers in need of dire remedial
help. We would cover ball handling, shooting and elementary
strategy, and for no additional fee, devise ways to deke around the
traffic to arrive at the West 70th Street gym on time.
</P>
<P>
   Day 1 arrives, and it feels more like a test than a lesson. The
emphasis: ball handling. I already know I am a miserable dribbler,
but I quickly learn that I am miserable at so much more: dribbling
between my legs, for example. I presume (naively, in retrospect)
that every drill we are asked to perform must be within our
capabilities and must be crucial to the game or we would not be
covering it in a novice class. Still, the keys to mastering these
moves remain mysterious, especially how to bounce the ball under
your legs without having it hit you in the crotch. Viewed en masse,
this must be hilarious, but no one laughs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we seven students don't chat much at all at first, but
I am thankful that the group comprises men and women, tall and
short, athletic and nonathletic.
</P>
<P>
   The first few weeks, during the summer, feature an assortment of
instructors while we await a permanent coach, and we glean the
benefits of their diverse wisdom. Still, I am forever chasing
errant balls and apologizing every time mine caroms off my
classmates. Somehow, I've turned basketball into dodgeball.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, we meet our permanent coach, Dave Olson, who
also coaches a high school team. Olson is patient, humorous,
good-natured and, though he doesn't say it, probably has an easier
time teaching teen-age boys.
</P>
<P>
   However, one beauty of learning a sport late in life is that
coaches may employ a cerebral approach, complete with mnemonic
devices. To improve our shooting, Olson recommends BEEF. B means
``Balance your weight'' evenly over both feet. E is for elbow, as
in ``Bend your elbow 90 degrees'' so your upper arm is parallel to
the floor. The next E means ``Eyes on the rim,'' and after you
shoot, remember to F, ``Follow through,'' by letting the ball roll
off your fingers. We try to shoot with one arm behind our back.
Later, we incorporate the other hand as a guide (or in my case, to
block my view).
</P>
<P>
   We also spend part of every week untangling our unwieldy layups.
Step-step-launch: This is basketball's jete as well as its bread
and butter. I expend tremendous effort on this effortless-looking
move, mostly trying to finesse the approach. And finally, when I am
able to stride up to the net with confidence and speed, I freeze
under the basket, stunned that I've just lifted the wrong arm and
leg or stepped off the wrong foot.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the layup is not only alien, it's physiologically
counterintuitive to the sports I've played. From running and
cross-country skiing, I've learned to coordinate my left arm with
my right leg, none of this same-side synchrony. From heading soccer
balls and ski racing, I've learned to jump with both feet at once,
not to make this one-legged launch.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, who also coaches track and field at Hackley School in
Tarrytown, N.Y., said, ``Think high jump.'' Once you get the
two-step approach and know which foot to take off on, just whip
your knee skyward (the quicker the better) and off you go.
Sometimes it actually works.
</P>
<P>
   Then he mercifully ends our layup circus to suggest a little
full-court four-on-four. ``Any questions?''
</P>
<P>
   I have so many, I'm momentarily mute. The coach tosses the ball
to my teammate. Belatedly, I blurt, ``Do we have to worry about
rules or anything?'' Gales of laughter echo off the floorboards. I
guess that's a no.
</P>
<P>
   So I defer to soccer, the only other team sport I've played. I
mark my man, trying to steer him out of bounds. I have good
footwork from boxing, and I'm fast. Better yet, I discover that the
faster you run, the less you have to dribble. I'm not afraid to
steal the ball, and my errant shots occasionally sink. I quickly
realize that basketball is just fancy keep-away. I can do this.
</P>
<P>
   In the next session, Olson shatters that myth. He teaches us the
only play that seems to matter (because we rehearse it every week
thereafter), and I'm immediately plagued by the pick-and-roll
blues. What is a pick and a roll? To find out, I poll more
experienced players. They all know it when they see it, but
definitions vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   Here's mine: It's offensive defense. If your teammate has the
ball, you run toward him hoping to stymie his defender. That means
you also drag your own defender into the fray. Then, somehow, amid
all the commotion, your ball-holding teammate magically eludes all
three of you and trots down the open lane for a layup. Of course,
it's effective only as long as you can read the court and your
teammate understands what you're doing when you're suddenly in her
face. It also helps if your teammate can actually do a layup.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that we learn this fundamental play, Coach Olson
offers us several creative drills. Usually, it involves a
give-and-go to the pick-and-roll, but since there are only seven of
us on a good day, and because we change lines after each attempted
drill, the pick becomes a knot and the roll becomes a revolving
door.
</P>
<P>
   Before you can say WNBA, 10 weeks are over. A few people
actually grasped the pick and roll, and by now, even I can
recognize a pick. It's the play in which I try to ram through a
three-person wall.
</P>
<P>
   My classmates are already discussing returning for the fall
session. As much as I'd love to re-enroll, a full-time job beckons.
But I've been playing weekly pickup in the meantime, learning the
rules the hard way, and though I don't completely have game yet, I
at least have the tools. Not to mention a nubby orange ball in my
armoire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
