<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-TRANSPLANT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STROKE VICTIM MAKES PROGRESS AFTER FETAL PIG CELL TRANSPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A champagne cork popped as a dozen
family members and friends gathered around Maribeth Cook to toast
the homecoming of the world's first stroke patient to receive an
experimental fetal pig brain cell transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all been so amazing. I can't believe it was that quick
and easy,'' said Cook, 39, as she sipped from a flute of bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   Cook showed off how quickly her thick, curly brown hair had
grown in over a small surgical scar and swapped pig jokes with her
guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been walking on air since she got home,'' said her
husband, Paul Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maribeth is an inspiration,'' said her father, Charles
Verdile.
</P>
<P>
   Six days earlier, on Sept. 1, Cook was in Brookline, Mass., at
Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, with a metal frame bolted to
her head and a foot-long needle inserted deep into her brain
through a nickel-sized opening bored in her skull. Cook's results
on post-surgical tests have exceeded her doctors' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dramatic, new procedure, and she did terrific,''
said Dr. Louis Caplan, neurologist at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center, co-investigator of Cook's clinical trial and an
internationally renowned authority on stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Caplan considered the experiment into uncharted medical
territory already something of a success. ``What's most important
at this point is that her condition didn't get any worse,'' Caplan
said. ``That's significant.'' In fact, Cook's post-operative
progress was so strong that Caplan deemed unnecessary a scheduled
follow-up visit in Boston in three weeks. Instead, he will see her
at the scheduled one-month checkup on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Caplan cautioned that periodic follow-up tests, over the next 18
months, remain to determine whether the 30 million fetal pig brain
cells Cook received actually work as intended: to repair Cook's
stroke-damaged brain and to restore lost function on her partially
paralyzed left side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go, and there's a lot to learn,'' Caplan
said. ``But this is potentially a very important advance for stroke
patients.'' An estimated 550,000 Americans suffer strokes each
year, with about 160,000 people dying as a result, making stroke
the third leading cause of death in the United States and the
leading cause of disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cook's homecoming party was a celebration about her
future hopes for recovery, the memories of a long, difficult
struggle could not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Cook took a photo of her 1992 wedding off a shelf and studied
the radiant bride. ``That's when I had two arms and two legs, and I
want that back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cook, 51, who has a college-aged daughter in New Mexico
from a previous relationship, met his future wife in the dentist's
chair. He was her patient when she worked as a dental hygienist in
Clifton Park, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maribeth is one of those special, dynamic people who could
make a trip to the dentist fun,'' said Cook, a sixth-grade math and
science teacher for 29 years. ``You're just drawn to her energy.''
</P>
<P>
   After their marriage, the Cooks, who do not have children,
traveled extensively and enjoyed cycling and playing tennis and
golf together. Both made a point of keeping fit. She took aerobics
classes and was in excellent physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the perfect life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Their world was shattered on Oct. 4, 1994, when Cook, then 34,
suffered a severe stroke that left her partially paralyzed on her
left side. Doctors have not been able to determine a cause for that
debilitating stroke, or a milder one in 1993 that had left few
noticeable effects.
</P>
<P>
   Almost five years of intensive therapy and workouts with a
personal trainer restored some of the lost function in Cook's
paralyzed left side. With the help of a brace on her left calf, she
can walk with a halting, limping gait. Her left arm and hand remain
rigid.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's husband, her brothers and sister and her parents, Marie
and Charles Verdile of Mechanicville, N.Y., rallied around Maribeth
during her long rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and family have pulled me through. If it wasn't for
them, I would have given up long ago,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's stroke strengthened her parents' Catholic faith. ``My mom
prayed enough for all of us,'' Maribeth said.
</P>
<P>
   That faith was tested again on May 31, 1998, when a devastating
tornado destroyed their neighborhood in Mechanicville. Her parents'
home suffered only minor damage and was one of just four on the
street left standing. A house 100 feet away was leveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't know why Maribeth suffered her stroke or why we
were spared in the tornado,'' her father said.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Verdile recalled that ``ever since Maribeth was a little
girl, she's been tough and full of determination. Her fighting
spirit has brought her back this far.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook has wasted no time in her current rehabilitation. She spent
a 45-minute session with her occupational therapist, Amy Porter,
the morning after her homecoming party. The news was upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Porter compared pre-surgery measurements on Aug. 26 with
post-surgery measurements on Sept. 8 and found modest improvements
in range of motion of Cook's partially paralyzed left shoulder and
elbow, and better tone in her rigid left arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still tight, but there was a noticeable improvement in
tone,'' Porter said. Before and after tests confirmed a 5-percent
to 10-percent increase in Cook's range of motion. ``That's pretty
significant in therapy circles,'' Porter explained.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the surgery, Cook started a part-time job
answering phones and taking reservations at the Saratoga Spa State
Park Golf Course, where her father works as a cashier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me a place to go and a purpose,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook has increased her therapy sessions to six per week. She
said she seemed to have more control and walked less rigidly and
flat-footed three weeks after the surgery. Friends have noticed a
new spark of optimism in her voice, too. ``I've got hope now.
Before, I didn't,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
