<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLAUCOMA-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIMENTAL TREATMENT MAKES STRIDES IN TREATING PATIENTS WITH
GLAUCOMA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC BERGER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A new treatment for glaucoma, one of a growing arsenal
of therapies, may offer hope to the millions of Americans affected
by the painful and incurable eye disease.
</P>
<P>
   The South African physician who developed the new therapy early
this decade, Dr. Robert Stegmann, boasts it has succeeded in
stopping the progression of the disease for 80 percent to 90
percent of his patients, but only in the last few years have other
ophthamologists begun to practice the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment, called a viscocanalostomy, offers a number of
advantages over traditional surgical techniques _ it does not cut
as deeply into the eye as other procedures _ but has yet to win
universal acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still experimental,'' said Dr. Amy Coburn, a clinical
associate professor of ophthamology at Baylor College of Medicine
in Houston. ``I don't think it's something necessarily offering a
distinct advantage over other treatment methods.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, glaucoma specialists say the technique provides an
alternative for cases in which medicines are ineffective and other
surgical techniques fail or are too risky.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas-Houston Medical School's Dr. Robert M.
Feldman, believed to be the first to offer the new surgery to
Houston-area patients, has successfully performed
viscocanalostomies since November.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no long-term data,'' Feldman said. ``So we need to
make sure we have a little caution before we come out and say,
`Hey, this is a great thing.' But it may be.''
</P>
<P>
   About 3 million Americans have glaucoma, a disease in which the
normal fluid pressure in the eyes slowly rises, possibly leading to
blindness.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is five times more likely to occur in blacks than
whites.
</P>
<P>
   At least half of those affected don't know they have glaucoma
because the disease initially lacks noticeable symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Recent public information campaigns on the disease have been
bolstered by former President Bush's admission that he has
glaucoma. The disease also blinded performer Ray Charles.
</P>
<P>
   If glaucoma is diagnosed early enough, doctors can use topical
or oral medication to control the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, however, laser or conventional surgery, in which
physicians essentially cut a hole in the eye to drain excess fluid,
is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an unnatural thing,'' said Dr. Alan L. Robin, an
ophthamologist who teaches at Johns Hopkins University and the
University of Maryland. Robin has traveled to South Africa to study
Stegmann's work. ``We're trying to find a safer way of getting the
fluid out of the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional surgery carries several complications, such as
irritation on the eye's surface, infection and a greater likelihood
of developing a cataract. In addition, the operation may need to be
repeated after several years as the hole closes up.
</P>
<P>
   Although viscocanalostomies take about as long as conventional
surgery, about 35 minutes, they do not require an incision that
cuts entirely through the eye and so have shown fewer postoperative
complications, doctors said. And if Stegmann's results hold up, it
should prove to be equally effective as traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback to the procedure is its technical difficulty, said
Feldman, noting the surgery has ``a steep learning curve.'' There
are few peer-reviewed studies on the procedure, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman hopes his success will generate funding from the
National Institutes of Health for a five-year study of the
technique. If the study is successful, he said, it would likely
lead to wider acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard of a non-penetrating approach to glaucoma
surgery, I was quite curious and very skeptical,'' wrote Dr. Gavin
Bahadur, a Santa Monica, Calif., ophthamologist in the July 15
issue of Ophthamology Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with any new technique, many experts remain quite guarded
about viscocanalostomy,'' added Bahadur, who, like Robin, has
traveled to South Africa to see Stegmann's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonetheless, this procedure promises excellent results with
few complications and is clearly worthy of additional
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
