<SLUG> BC-CELL-TECHNIQUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THEORY BEHIND PIG BRAIN CELL IMPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: THIS SIDEBAR accompanies story slugged CELL-TRANSPLANT)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 30 million fetal pig brain cells injected into Maribeth
Cook's stroke-damaged brain on Sept. 1 were expected to begin
changing and growing immediately in the initial phase of the
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Dinsmore, senior director of cell transplantation
research for Diacrin Inc., provided this chronology:
</P>
<P>
   _ Once injected into Maribeth Cook's brain, the cells, stored at
36 degrees F., will begin to warm up to body temperature. At body
temperature, the cells begin to metabolize and to consume the
glucose (sugar) in the injection solution for energy.
</P>
<P>
   _ After two days, the fetal pig brain cells, also known as
neurons, will grow an axon extension, a tiny tail-like appendage
capable of conducting impulses away from the cell body.
</P>
<P>
   _ The fetal pig brain cells will continue to grow and divide.
(In laboratory experiments with rats, some recovery from stroke
symptoms was detected after one week following transplant, but
researchers could not determine if that was specifically
attributable to the cell transplant.)
</P>
<P>
   _ An unknown percentage of the fetal pig brain cells will die in
Cook's brain, but researchers have factored in the mortality rate
with the size and shape of Cook's stroke damage and determined that
30 million cells is adequate. The fetal pig brain cells are known
for their ``plasticity,'' meaning they can grow and transform into
several types of cells.
</P>
<P>
   _ The fetal pig brain cells, placed into precise locations of
Cook's stroke-damaged brain, are expected to take their cues from
Cook's own living brain cells in surrounding areas and to follow a
normal human progression.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the weeks and months after the transplant, the fetal pig
brain cells will continue to grow and form tissue indistinguishable
from human tissue. The tissue will form connections with the
healthy and functioning human cells in Cook's brain and begin to
reconnect the burned-out circuitry.
</P>
<P>
   _ The fetal pig brain tissue will eventually stop growing after
it fills in the deadened ``black hole'' of Cook's brain and
receives messages that there is no room left to grow. This natural
cell process is known as ``contact inhibition.'' Humans have
billions of brain cells and each neuron, or brain cell, connects to
hundreds of other neurons, creating trillions of cell connections.
</P>
<P>
   If the fetal pig brain cells successfully complete each of these
stages and restore enough of the cell connections destroyed by
Cook's stroke, theoretically she should regain some of the lost
function in her partially paralyzed left side.
</P>
<P>
   Since Cook is the first stroke patient in the phase-one human
clinical trial, there is no past history to suggest a time frame
for detectable improvement. Some Parkinson's patients transplanted
with fetal pig brain cells showed measurable improvement within 90
days.
</P>
<P>
   The next stroke patient has not yet been scheduled for the
transplant procedure, although discussions are under way with
several other patients who meet certain requirements. Six patients
are being sought for the phase-one trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
