<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-MAIL-SNOOPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS CONSIDERS BILL ON E-MAIL EAVESDROPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California Gov. Gray Davis is considering a
bill that would outlaw the monitoring of employee computer e-mail
unless management first produces a written policy everyone is told
about. It would be the first such law in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Like an increasing number of U.S. businesses that rely on
e-mail, the Davis administration has scrutinized the electronic
messages of its employees and reprimanded staff members who spend
too much time goofing off.
</P>
<P>
   Although the administration insists it looked at employee e-mail
in only two cases, several Capitol staff members said they feel
they are being constantly watched.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses regularly _ and legally _ snoop on their
employees. But staff members in the Legislature say they are
offended that high-level administration officials would even think
about tracking anyone's e-mail. Many of them write to friends in
the administration to discuss legislation, send jokes or just vent
about their pressure-cooker jobs.
</P>
<P>
   After taking office in January, Davis hired several former
employees of the Legislature to shape policy and monitor important
bills. Now some worry the relationship between the Legislature and
Davis could be further chilled because the administration might
read what they write to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said the administration has a
``trigger'' system that sends out an alert when too many messages
are passed back and forth in a short period of time. One employee,
he said, was reprimanded for sending 70 messages, some of them
risque, in a single four-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's something out of the ordinary,'' Bustamante said,
``then we need to remind people why they're here, which is to work
for the governor and the taxpayers of California.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said everyone in the administration knows about the
e-mail policy.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said that a top Davis aide not only counted the
number of e-mails by the employee who sent 70 messages, but had
them printed out and read some of them. But Bustamante said
``nobody is being monitored,'' except when computer staff notice an
``odd amount of usage.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Davis staff director Vince Hall or other top officials
reading e-mail on a regular basis, Bustamante said: ``They have too
much work to do to concern themselves with trying to do what some
people are erroneously suggesting. ... There is no Big Brother
sitting around reading e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill on Davis' desk, written by state Sen. Debra Bowen,
D-Marina Del Rey, would require businesses to inform their
employees about their electronic eavesdropping policy by March
2000. Otherwise, the practice would be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   If Davis doesn't veto the bill before his Oct. 10 deadline, the
new law would be the first such protection against secretly reading
e-mail in the nation. A federal attempt failed a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The business-friendly California Employment Law Council opposed
the bill, saying it would require ``overwhelming proof and
mountains of paperwork'' to get every employee to sign a form, as
required by the bill, saying he or she had read the eavesdropping
policy.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the American Management Association found that
45 percent of large businesses monitor employee e-mail, computer
files and phone calls, an increase of about 10 percent in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 27 percent of the companies surveyed said they
specifically review e-mail messages of their employees, still a 15
percent increase since 1997. The vast majority _ 84 percent _ said
they informed employees about policies regarding reading e-mail or
listening to phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   In the few lawsuits involving office e-mail, the courts have
ruled that even secret monitoring is allowed because the company
owns the computer equipment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
