<HEADER>
A7859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-WILLIE-McCOVEY-HN     09-27 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WILLIE-McCOVEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     WILLIE McCOVEY RETURNS TO THE S.F. GIANTS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN SHEA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Willie McCovey is coming home.
</P>
<P>
   Before an enthusiastic Candlestick crowd. As an employee of his
longtime team. As arguably the most popular Giant in San Francisco
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past decade, McCovey and the Giants have been at
a distance and, sometimes, at odds. It's been a painful time for
the Hall of Fame first baseman _ and not just because of his
separation from the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Once seen as the epitome of youth and strength, McCovey isn't
walking these days. He isn't playing golf. Or driving from his
Woodside home to catch a Giants game. The things he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only get around on crutches and walkers,'' said McCovey,
who has undergone more than a dozen knee surgeries in four years
and has three more scheduled, the first in early October.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my last hope of being able to walk on my own and play
golf again. I'm hoping by next season I'll be up and walking. At
least that's my hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are in his corner again, and rehiring the 61-year-old
McCovey to the front office, a move that will be announced at a
Tuesday press conference. His specific duties aren't yet defined,
but more significant is that the sides have reunited and McCovey is
back where he played 19 of his 22 big-league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to be at Tuesday night's Giants-Dodgers game, the
opener to a series that will serve as Candlestick's last hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a pregame ceremony, he'll present the Willie Mac
Award, given annually to the most inspirational Giant.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, fans will be informed of the aptly named
McCovey Cove, the area of the China Basin Channel beyond the
right-field wall at Pacific Bell Park, which opens in April. Home
runs to right field will splash into McCovey Cove, where Big Mac
himself would have hit 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Given the magnitude of the moment _ Giants-Dodgers, the last
series, his return to the organization _ McCovey may likely hear
cheers rivaling those of Sept. 18, 1977, when he beat Cincinnati
with a ninth-inning single on Willie McCovey Day at the 'Stick.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year McCovey returned to the Giants following three
seasons with San Diego and Oakland, and now after another absent
stretch, ``Stretch'' is a Giant again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to reassociate myself with the organization,''
McCovey said. ``I know Dusty (Baker) has always wanted me to do
something with the team. There are a lot of things now possible,
now that I'm officially back.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time McCovey presented the Willie Mac Award, but
he's been relegated to congratulatory phone calls in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   He said his knees have worsened, but he's determined to make a
personal appearance to greet the fans and say farewell to the
'Stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it'll be a little sad,'' McCovey said. ``But not as
sad as if they were tearing it down. As long as the 49ers play
there, I know I can drive up the Bayshore Freeway and see
Candlestick right there.''
</P>
<P>
   With memories intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of Seals Stadium, all my memories are of
Candlestick,'' McCovey said. ``But it's funny. I always thought
that we should be playing downtown. Even early on, I thought it was
a mistake to build a park so far from the city. With Seals Stadium,
I liked the idea of office people taking a break and coming down
and watching the Giants. But we settled at Candlestick and made the
best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least McCovey did. When the curtain closes on Candlestick
following the Dodger series, McCovey will be the stadium's all-time
leader in home runs (236), RBIs (698), hits (925), games (1,085)
and at-bats (3,369).
</P>
<P>
   It's one reason he's regarded as the most popular San Francisco
Giant. Willie Mays and others had played in New York, but McCovey
was San Francisco's very own, beginning in the city, ending in the
city and enjoying a Hall of Fame career in the city.
</P>
<P>
   During his years away from the team, McCovey was sentenced to
two years probation and fined $5,000 by the federal government in
1996 for tax evasion on unreported card-show income, though he says
now the experience was ``more positive than negative. So many
people, from the mayor on down, rallied behind me. I don't think it
was as big of an issue as it was in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   McCovey's biggest setback, of course, has been his knees. He had
trouble late in his career but blames ``ill-advised surgeries'' for
his recent woes. He said procedures designed to help actually hurt,
and artificial replacements were inserted. But a staph infection
has developed, requiring doctors to remove a replacement. After six
to eight weeks, they'll redo the replacement.
</P>
<P>
   McCovey said he pushed back his next surgery to early October so
he could attend the Candlestick functions. He also was voted by
fans to the all-time San Francisco Giants team, which will be
honored at Sunday's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
