<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7874 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-POPE-REVIEW-SFCHRO     09-27 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-POPE-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY, FAITH EMERGE IN NUANCED PORTRAIT OF THE POPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once, Karol Wojtyla seemed the perfectly modern pope. He zipped
through cities in his ``Popemobile.'' He skied. He played stadiums.
He welcomed rock stars to the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frontline'' quickly dispels that old pop pope business Tuesday
night. In time, it also nicks the contrary notion that John Paul II
is hidebound and angry in his confrontation with modernity.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Whitney, the producer who sought meaning in the lives of
Bill Clinton and Bob Dole for the award-winning ``The Choice'' TV
biographies in 1996, puts the pope under the same sort of
microscope in ``John Paul II: The Millennial Pope.'' She finds him
tough to pigeonhole.
</P>
<P>
   She finds too that John Paul II is Polish. Very Polish.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't a facile conclusion. Over two hours, Whitney shows just
how deeply his nationality affects the pope and the Roman Catholic
Church. It's Poland's blanket of melancholy. The palpable presence
of mysticism and faith. The Polish church's sanction of
anti-Semitism, which stung the future pope. The totalitarian double
whammy of Nazism and communism.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney sees these themes revealing themselves in John Paul II's
rapprochement with Judaism, in his suppression of ``liberation
theology'' as too chummy with Marxism in Latin America, and in his
opposition to contraception, abortion and capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   She also seeks roots for the pope's fervent devotion to the
Virgin Mary, and for his refusal to accept the ordination of women
as priests. The suggestion here is that after the death of his
mother when he was a boy, the future pope transferred his feelings
for her to the Virgin Mary _ and to what Mary represents about the
function of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deeply believes, in a way that I think is simply difficult
for the modern sensibility to grasp, in the reality of the Virgin
Mary,'' says Tony Judt, a New York University professor. ``This
makes him peculiarly sensitive to what he thinks of as the crossing
over of roles ...''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary is remarkable for Whitney's ability to find the
right person with the right quote at the right point in the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``The Millennial Pope'' may be too much of a slog for any
viewer who isn't rabidly interested in the subject. That is, until
it soars heavenward in the final 30 minutes or so.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney seems to step out from behind a biographical program and
addresses John Paul II's powerful faith. In fact, ``The Millennial
Pope'' suddenly becomes a paean to religious faith, period, and one
of the most extraordinary segments of TV programming I've ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   With deep feeling and uncommon articulateness, four people talk
about the experience of the divine. Or about the quest for it.
They're physicist David Berlinski, feminist writer Germaine Greer,
singer Andrea Marcovicci and Romanian priest Raymond Braga, who was
imprisoned for 11 years by the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   A show that was thoughtful and good, if pokey and limited in
viewer appeal, abruptly transforms itself into something else
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost like witnessing a miracle. Can you find that
anywhere else on your TV tonight?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
