<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW OAKLAND RAIDERS ARE EQUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Lance Johnstone was asked if he could have
seen any of his previous Raider teams committing five turnovers and
nine penalties and winning. It didn't take him long to dismiss the
notion as madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the Raider defensive end said almost dismissively. ``But
this is a different team.''
</P>
<P>
   That much, we established a week ago. The Raiders showed what
they can do in Minneapolis last week. Sunday, against the far more
mundane Chicago Bears, they showed what they must do.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, win a game they seemed hell-bent on losing.
</P>
<P>
   True, we speak here of the Bears, who for all their newfangled
looks play pretty much as the same old Bears have, which is to say
ineffectively. For all the pregame yap about the new Chicago
offense with its hurried tempo and extravagant formations, it is
still a team with no discernible running game (Curtis Enis? Please)
and a practiced inability to keep the officials happy (17
penalties, including seven holding calls, one by the marvelously
named Warrick Holdman).
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, a really good NFL team would have beaten this Chicago
team half-stupid. The Raiders are not a really good NFL team, but
as we look at today's standings, we find that there are no really
good NFL teams out there, making the Raiders anyone's equal for the
first time in years.
</P>
<P>
   In short, these Raiders are not the old Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can compare this team to previous years,''
linebacker Greg Biekert said. ``To 1995, or '96, or whatever you
want to do. There just aren't a lot of guys left from back then.
There have been a lot of changes here, players, and character.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if the choice is whether this was a win by virtue of
talent or a win by virtue of character, you'd be better off taking
option (b). This was, after all, a win based on defense, and the
Raider defense has carried this team long enough to be considered
its spine, and therefore its character.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears and their fancy-schmancy new offense managed two
concerted drives all afternoon, and each of them resulted in a
missed field goal by the strangely unpopular former Raider, Jeff
Jaeger. The two Chicago touchdowns came as a result of two former
Stanfordites _ a 92-yard kickoff return by Bear Glyn Milburn in the
first quarter, and Raider Darrien Gordon's fumble on a punt return
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The old Raider defenders might have thrown up their hands (or
worse, just thrown up) and prepared themselves for another tour
through football hell, let down by the underdeveloped half of the
depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   The new Raiders didn't give it a thought. Indeed, they were more
annoyed with the Bears and their attempts to bluff a victory they
plainly hadn't the skill to achieve on their own.
</P>
<P>
   We turn now to defensive tackle Darrell Russell, who thought the
Bears far more talky than walky, especially Enis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a professional, so act like it,'' Russell said of Enis,
who carried 15 times for 35 yards and had no impact on the day.
``He's talking all the time, pushing people in pileups, and I
finally just had enough. We were walking up the tunnel, and I told
him, `I want you to run the ball more. I want you to run it at
me.'''
</P>
<P>
   We'd like to report that Enis did just that, but frankly,
watching him carry the ball is too tedious an exercise to analyze
in any depth. If he did run at Russell, good on his father. If not,
well, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking like that, it's just something I don't respect,''
Russell said, the contempt staining his shirt. ``It's just not
called for.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Bears were more circumspect, but not much more
enlightening. Even the much-vaunted hurry-up offense with all the
pretty formations yielded the same plays every other team runs,
only not quite as well.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Eric Turner dismissed it as ``window dressing . . . they
didn't do anything we hadn't practiced against all week.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed. The Bears lost 1 yard in total offense in the fourth
quarter, which is hardly the way to close out what under normal
circumstances would be a very winnable game. The NFL keeps
statistics on a team's record when turning the ball five times, and
while the numbers are not readily available to us, it is believed
to be a galactically horrible figure.
</P>
<P>
   And, at least in this case, irrelevant. The Oakland Raiders, the
team with the spine-snapping schedule, the limited offense and the
proud decade of non-achievement, are tied for the AFC West lead,
and have a two-game edge on the defending Super Bowl champion
Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone figured on that,'' Biekert said with a
laugh. ``But I think that's something for when we play them (in two
weeks). It's not something we need concern ourselves with right
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
