<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIZABETH-DOLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE FAILS TO IGNITE REPUBLICAN CONVENTION IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole likes to
tell the story of a young girl, maybe 10 or 11, who came up to her
recently with a complaint: ``But I wanted to be the first woman
president,'' the girl said, worried that Dole would steal her
dream.
</P>
<P>
   Some political strategists and Republican Party insiders say the
young girl may have nothing to worry about. Dole is coasting, they
say, when she really needs to be snapping at the heels of
front-runner George W. Bush, taking advantage of favorable poll
numbers and making bolder statements about policy and national
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she doesn't do it soon, the momentum will fade and her
ability to do so will diminish,'' Ed Gillespie, a Republican
strategist, said recently. ``She's going to lose the chance to
strike while the iron is hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole attended the California Republican Party convention on
Saturday in Anaheim, delivering a campaign speech and mingling with
the party faithful. She told a few jokes, spoke about cracking down
on drug smuggling, about the proliferation of pornography in public
libraries and about a general decline in values as the country
grows more prosperous.
</P>
<P>
   But her half-hour speech contained many elements the same party
faithful had heard her say word-for-word at their last meeting,
including a long story about riding a motorcycle with Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Bush, the Texas governor, and Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, Dole has been virtually invisible in vote-rich California,
except to Republican insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates at the weekend convention said Dole doesn't really
stand much of a chance against the well-funded Bush campaign, which
has collected $52 million in contributions and could easily take in
an unprecedented $75 million before the primaries begin early next
year. The brief campaign stop in Anaheim didn't convince everyone
Dole was ready for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a canned speech that was very low on specifics,'' said
Adam Sparks, chairman of the San Francisco Republican Assembly.
``She was entertaining and she certainly had that talk-show
quality. She'd probably make a good talk-show host. But we're sort
of in the 11th hour and we want to know where she stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks said the party appears ready to back Bush, even if he
thinks Dole, Steve Forbes or McCain may be qualified candidates
with good ideas. ``I think the Republicans in this state have been
so beat up after the big defeat in '96, they are going to ride any
train out of Dodge.''
</P>
<P>
   Others liked Dole's style, but weren't so sure she could make it
the whole way. Gale J. Enderlin, who attended the convention from
Castro Valley, said of Dole: ``I'm still thinking of her as a
running mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the former president of the American Red Cross and a
member of the Cabinet in the Reagan administration, said she would
return to California for two days in early October and is raising
money in the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
