A7882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BOOKS-EATING-DISORDER     09-27 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EATING-DISORDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    READ OF THE WEEK: Eating Disorders
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ ``When You Eat at the Refrigerator, Pull Up a Chair'' by
Geneen Roth. Hyperion. 1998. $15.95 hardback.
</P>
<P>
   This petite volume of 50 tips aimed at helping people cope with
compulsive eating might conceivably blend in with all the other
petite self-help books crowding bookstore shelves these days. Pick
this one up, whether or not you know what it's like to consume an
entire half-gallon of ice cream in a single sitting and then hate
yourself for it. Roth's sixth book includes suggestions such as
``Be willing to lose the suffering contest'' and ``Begin to gently
let go of friends who don't want the best for you,'' which apply to
a much broader audience than just those who struggle with their
weight or feelings toward food. Part of Roth's appeal is that she
doesn't advocate any particular eating plan or diet method; on the
contrary, the book's first tip is, ``Whatever you do, don't diet.''
She reminds readers to eat enough protein but adds that how much is
``enough'' varies from person to person; she stumps for a daily hot
meal but doesn't stipulate when or how large it should be.
(Interview on this page.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Surviving an Eating Disorder: Strategies for Family and
Friends'' by Michele Siegel, Ph.D., Judith Brisman, Ph.D. and
Margot Weinshel, M.S.W. HarperPerennial. 1997. $13 paperback.
</P>
<P>
   This book is an excellent resource for those affected by the
eating disorder of a friend or family member. It provides a basic
overview of the symptoms of anorexia, bulimia and binge eating, as
well as suggestions on how to deal with people with disordered
eating.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Eating Disorder Sourcebook'' by Carolyn Costin, M.A.,
M.Ed., M.F.C.C. Lowell House. 1997. $17 paperback.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat clinically written but extremely informative, this book
describes eating disorder symptoms in detail and outlines treatment
approaches, including individual therapy, medication and
hospitalization. Those with eating disorders as well as their
relatives and friends will find this book helpful in telling them
what to expect from treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
