<HEADER>
A7883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-EATING-DISORDERS-COX     09-27 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EATING-DISORDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A with Geneen Roth
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Compulsive eating expert Geneen Roth will host a
workshop Oct. 8-9 at the Atlanta Airport Hilton. ``The New Breaking
Free,'' an updated version of her popular ``Breaking Free''
workshops, focuses on the emotional reasons behind compulsive
eating.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, 48, battled anorexia and compulsive eating in her teens
and 20s. At 28, she stopped trying to diet and instead began
searching for the emotional roots of her relationship with food.
</P>
<P>
   She has since published several best-selling books, including
``Feeding the Hungry Heart'' and ``When Food Is Love.'' Her latest
book, ``When You Eat at the Refrigerator, Pull Up a Chair,'' offers
esteem-boosting suggestions for people battling poor self-image and
eating problems.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, who lives in Northern California, spoke recently with The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Compulsive eating doesn't seem to get as much attention as
bulimia and anorexia, even though obesity is a national epidemic.
Why do you think that's the case?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think (anorexia and bulimia) are more dramatic, and in some
cases more urgent. But what I call emotional eating, the
run-of-the-mill dieter who binges, is just as much if not a bigger
problem. It doesn't get addressed very much.
</P>
<P>
   The sad part is, many, many people are in pain about their size.
They're putting their lives on hold until they get thin.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can one overcome compulsive eating?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely and without a doubt. I think I am a perfect
example. I was a tortured, crazed being. There is nothing that
people can tell me they've done with food that I haven't done. I
never thought I would spend a day in my life where I wasn't
obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I can't even remember the last time I binged or overate. It
is an amazing thing.
</P>
<P>
   My basic message is that you don't have to suffer with this for
the rest of your life. In order not to suffer with it, it's
important to see that it's both a physical and an emotional
process.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You emphasize that people should eat when they're hungry, and
stop when they're full. It seems like common sense, but you mention
that people have reacted angrily to this suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   A: People were furious with me. They thought it was just another
fad diet. We're so accustomed to these fad diets, and people are so
removed from that initial and instinctive reason to eat, that when
someone says to tune into your hunger, it sounds like another diet.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Geneen Roth or her workshops:
</P>
<P>
   Call 831-685-8601 or visit her Internet site at
www.geneenroth.com.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
