<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-FACTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fast facts about the new inhaled flu drug
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Friday, Relenza will be available for sale by prescription in
U.S. pharmacies. Relenza, also known as zanamivir, is the first
anti-viral drug approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
to treat both major strains of influenza.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a substitute for a flu shot. Relenza has not been
approved for preventing the flu, although a recent study shows that
the drug can greatly reduce your chances of catching the flu from
another household member. Glaxo Wellcome, Relenza's manufacturer,
plans to seek FDA approval for preventative uses of the drug by the
end of the year. Until then, a flu shot remains the best defense
against the illness.
</P>
<P>
   People with flu symptoms should begin taking Relenza within the
first two days after symptoms start. The drug is taken twice daily
for five days and reduces the duration of sickness by an average of
1 1/2 days.
</P>
<P>
   Relenza is inhaled through a plastic inhaler device called a
Diskhaler. The device holds a disc-shaped blister package
containing a powder mixture of Relenza and lactose. When the disc
is loaded into the inhaler, the blister is punctured. The user
inhales the released powder.
</P>
<P>
   People with asthma or chronic heart or lung disease should
consult their doctors before taking Relenza. Relenza's wholesale
cost for a five-day treatment course is $37.
</P>
<P>
   Another anti-flu drug, Tamiflu, probably will be approved soon.
Tamiflu will be available in pill form, also for flu treatment but
not prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
