<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-ZWICK-COX     09-27 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ZWICK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Once and Again' team tackles angst of divorce, dating
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're at it again: Ed Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz are back
digging into baby boomer family life _ or what's left of it. Just
as the writer-producer team did with ``thirtysomething'' and ``My
So-Called Life,'' Zwick and Herskovitz have created a drama that
heads to the heart of baggage-heavy lives _ this time of
40-somethings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again,'' which debuted last Tuesday, stars Sela Ward
and Billy Campbell as divorced parents in their 40s who fall in
love again _ a complicated enterprise with teens and exes around.
It's airing in the coveted ``NYPD Blue'' time slot, where it will
stay until ``Blue'' returns in November. ``Once and Again'' is then
scheduled to go on hiatus until January, when it slips into the
slot vacated by ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a complicated arrangement that shows ABC's excitement in
airing the drama as soon as possible (last week's premiere had the
highest ranking among viewers 18 to 49 of any network's premiering
drama in four years), and its frustration in finding it a perfect,
permanent home in an era when news magazines rule. The drama also
repeats Friday nights at 11 on Lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Zwick, 46, and Herskovitz, 47 _ friends since film school _ sat
with us recently on a crowded veranda at the Ritz Carlton hotel in
Pasadena, Calif., and did what they do best: talk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A lot of people in their 40s have the same reaction to ``Once
and Again'' that they had in their 30s to ``thirtysomething'': You
have a camera trailing my life?
</P>
<P>
   Zwick: It's about a willingness to look inward and try to make a
very scary leap that what you see will not only be understood by
you, but by many others. It's coming to understand that one's own
experience is not singular, but universal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is this show a 40-something version of ``thirtysomething''?
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz: ``thirtysomething'' came out of our concerns and
interests, this show came out of our concerns and interests, so of
course there can be some similarity.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You guys have tapped into the psyche of baby boomers the way
Pottery Barn tapped into their tastes...
</P>
<P>
   Zwick: He's calling us the Pottery Barn of TV! How do you feel
about that, Marshall?
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz: I like to think we're the Restoration Hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is this a particularly interesting generation to dramatize?
</P>
<P>
   Zwick: We're a much more self-conscious culture _ you had the
president talking about his marriage. It's the legacy of so many
things _ leisure time, money, social opportunity. So it is more
verbal and self-conscious, and in that way we're only reflecting
the time in which we live. Q: How was the idea for the series born?
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz: It had been running around our lives and brains for
years _ it's almost impossible to spot when it was born, and I was
there. We're always talking about the aspects of life you can
dramatize. That's what we do every day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``thirtysomething'' was criticized by some viewers as ``too
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz: After the pilot of ``thirtysomething,'' my best
friend from high school called and said, ``I am so sorry. I just
found out that show I turned off last week after 10 minutes because
I turned to my wife and said, `I'm living this, why do I have to
watch it on TV?' turned out to be your show.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will that happen with ``Once and Again''?
</P>
<P>
   Zwick: We'll see. What better opportunity: You got them
(viewers) in the house, alone in the dark _ it's too ripe.
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz: We felt when we started to do ``thirtysomething''
the paradox was TV is so intimate, and yet usually not emotional.
We gave a lot of time to what were the ways we could draw someone
in to the experience of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How?
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz: There's the craft we learned in film school, the
craft that the great classical directors used, starting in the
'20s, what we call generosity. Giving gifts to the audience of
being entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Zwick: Gifts of perspective, humor, unexpected turns.
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz: In ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' in the scene near the
end where Jimmy Stewart is in despair and he's come home after the
$5,000 is missing and he's throwing things in his house and
screaming at his kids, and the little boy follows him around,
tugging at his leg, going, ``'scuse me, 'scuse me,'' and Jimmy
Stewart finally goes, ``What!'' And the kid goes, ``I burped.'' Why
put that in there? Because it's what life is.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What traits define baby boomers?
</P>
<P>
   Zwick: There are two rivers. One is the river of writers,
comedians, monologuists, that voice of the internal monologue of
novels, the stream of consciousness. The other river is therapy.
Therapy has had an effect on a generational voice. It presumes to
say that the examined life is worth living.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much has therapy effected your work?
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz: It's deeply imbedded in our world view. In my
family, my mother and brother are therapists. I believe in it
philosophically. I believe in the romantic illusion that we can
change and grow.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-GARTH-COX     09-27 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GARTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The alter-Garth: What's it all about, anyway?
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's going to be a hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Brooks' much-hyped pop CD as the fictional rock star Chris
Gaines, arrives in stores today, reintroducing the country
superstar to the world as a pop artist. It's followed by a week
packed with ceaseless promotion, from a prime-time concert on NBC
to a series of talk show couches where Brooks will no doubt explain
(and explain and explain) what the project is all about.
</P>
<P>
   In the CD and television special, however, Brooks' alter ego
turns out to be a bit of a letdown, an adult-contemporary performer
with lots of energy but little spark in his material. Even with
studio wizard Don Was (Bonnie Raitt, the Rolling Stones) at the
boards, Brooks-as-Gaines seems like a passionless version of Kenny
Loggins, alternating between forgettable acoustic ballads and
charged-up rock anthems.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' distinctive voice is intact, but even the
million-selling pipes can't keep ``Gaines'' from sounding
contrived. Perhaps that's because it is. By adopting an alter ego,
creating a fictionalized bio and then writing a greatest hits
package to span two decades of changing style and music forms,
Brooks has approached his leap over the country fence like an
assembly line draftsman.
</P>
<P>
   The companion NBC television special (8 p.m. Wednesday), in
which the country star performs the new material in a live-on-tape
concert, has a little more soul simply because Brooks is so
bizarrely fired up about Gaines. We hear not only the songs, but
are invited into an elaborate and detailed fantasy world. There are
video clips of a 15-year-old Gaines (played by an actor) performing
an early hit with the band Crush. At one point, Garth, wearing dark
shirttails over black jeans (sans hat), even flips a finger into
the camera only to quickly apologize, saying ``That wasn't me doing
that; it was Chris.''
</P>
<P>
   As you follow the story, keep in mind that the character of
Chris Gaines comes from a movie, ``The Lamb,'' that has yet to be
written. The project might have made much more sense if it had been
a soundtrack, for at least we could connect to a plot. But with no
film to support the premise, it gets weird and out-of-touch.
</P>
<P>
   What's even stranger is that Brooks has already proven to be a
passionate, provocative rocker. One of his biggest hits,
``Shameless,'' was penned by Billy Joel. ``Ain't Going Down 'Til
the Sun Comes Up'' is better arena rock than anything by Chris
Gaines. The only tune that even remotely rattles around the brain
is ``Right Now,'' where Brooks lays down walkie-talkie rap protest
about guns and parents over Buffalo Springfield's classic '60s
tune.
</P>
<P>
   Should Brooks be condemned for working outside the country box?
No. But his transition should have come more naturally than this.
Let the music do the talking, Garth, not the publicity machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garth Brooks in ... The Life of Chris Gaines''
</P>
<P>
   Garth Brooks. 13 tracks. Capitol Records
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   A one-hour TV special of the same name airs at 8 p.m. Wednesday
on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
