<HEADLINE>
'TIS THE SEASON FOR LAKE TAHOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH LAKE TAHOE, Calif. _ Every hotel room in town has been
full on weekends for months at South Lake Tahoe, the roads jammed,
with some of the drivers certifiable lunatics.
</P>
<P>
   But from Angora Peak, looking down across cobalt-blue Lake
Tahoe, circled by miles of forest and the granite mountain rim, it
can seem as if you are the only person on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only a few miles separates these two universes.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the sterling beauty, gambling and nearby recreation,
especially driving tours, hiking, biking, golf and boating, Tahoe
is approaching Yosemite and Disneyland as the regional two-day
vacation of choice. For months on end, there have been so many
people here that it resembles feeding time at the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   But with the first cool nights just starting to arrive here and
so many in the Bay Area and Sacramento paying more attention to the
49ers and work rather than Tahoe and play, the best time of year to
venture out here is now at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Though autumn is still more than a month off in the Bay Area,
it's arrival is imminent at Tahoe. The aspens are just about to
start turning color, with full color likely within two weeks and
temperatures expected to drop into the 30s at night for the first
time of the season. The cool mornings give a pristine feel to go
with the long-distance views, then give way to Indian summer days
in the 70s.
</P>
<P>
   From South Lake Tahoe, it is only a short drive to the best
launching point to take it all in.
</P>
<P>
   From the Y, as they call it here, the intersection of U.S. 50
and Highway 89, it is only a few miles north on Highway 89 to
Fallen Leaf Lake Road. From here you turn left, then take the
narrow, often-bumpy two-laner up along the ridge (follow the signs
at two turns), past a fire lookout and to a small parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   It is only a half-mile walk to Angora Lake, one of the prettiest
easy-to-reach lakes anywhere in the Sierra. It is set at 7,400
feet, nestled in a small granite bowl backed by a dramatic high
wall. The water is clear, fresh and pristine.
</P>
<P>
   It is only a start. There is a small resort here with eight
cabins available for rent, complete with a 10-year waiting list,
where folks who have signed up make a few prayers each year for
cancellations. That operation closed last weekend. For those who
desire less traffic in a beautiful setting, it is just what they
have been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   The swimming here is best described as ``refreshing,'' that is,
the water is not warm, yet not yet frigid. For all partaking, it is
cold enough to activate distinct anatomical changes. The swim is
best taken after exploring the area, by foot or bike, on a warm
afternoon. By bike, there is a network of excellent mountain bike
trails below Lower Angora Lake, as well as near-flat bike routes
near Fallen Leaf Lake (another parking lot is available directly
off Fallen Leaf Lake Road).
</P>
<P>
   But the best of adventure and views comes for the enterprising
few who make the climb to Angora Peak, 8,588 feet elevation,
overlooking the entire Tahoe Basin. From the shore of Angora Lake,
there is a route that follows the ridge above the lake in a
counter-clockwise direction, with a few steep spots, a few
scrambles, with a 1,150-foot climb over the course of about a mile.
</P>
<P>
   As you clear the trees, the expanse of Tahoe suddenly comes into
view, the Lake in the Sky. Directly below is little Angora Lake,
small, round and glowing, and beyond is Fallen Leaf Lake, Emerald
Bay and the giant cobalt-blue Tahoe, edged by a tourmaline tint
along its southern shore. The sweeping beauty is simply
eye-popping.
</P>
<P>
   Because of forest, most of the development and roads are
well-hidden from view, and other than the distant white streaks of
power boats at Tahoe and perhaps a few jumping swimmers at Angora,
it feels as if you have the place to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   To get this experience, I used to think you had to make the
butt-kicking, six-mile, 6,500-foot climb to the top of Mount Tallac
(9,735 feet). Nope. Tallac is very special, but the view here is
similar, just as breathtaking. Note that Angora Peak is not quite
atop the Sierra crest. Beyond to the west across a few miles of
sculpted granite is the crest, topped by Echo Peak at 8,895 feet.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, I have wondered how the Tahoe experience could
be improved. How can the divine beauty and recreation be guaranteed
into the forever? Yet without having to fight off the crowds to get
it, especially the encounters with the handful of maniac drivers?
The best suggestion is that perhaps the entire Tahoe Basin could
become a national park, without barring any of the current industry
and development, with an entrance fee charged to pay to keep Tahoe
blue, and provide for stellar recreation opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   To get on the waiting list for Angora Lakes Resort, write to
P.O. Box 8897, South Lake Tahoe, CA 96158; For a map of Eldorado
National Forest, send $4 to Maps, Forest Service, 1323 Club Drive,
Vallejo, CA 94592.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
