<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-PEANUTS-COX     09-27 1908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEANUTS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   50 year-old ``''Peanuts'''' still worth devouring
</P>
<P>
   By Gary Schwan
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What is the perfect ``Peanuts'' comic
strip?
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schulz has an opinion. He's allowed, since he created
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drawing a strip where Linus is sitting under a tree, and
he's got his blanket,'' Schulz said from his studio-office in Santa
Rosa, Calif. ``Snoopy's cuddling up under the blanket with him.
Linus says he doesn't remember inviting him _ `but I have to admit
you are kind of warm and fuzzy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was the perfect punch line,'' Schulz added.
``Everybody brings something to the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Through his gentle, all-too-human comedy, Schulz has brought the
world to the ``Peanuts'' party for half a century. The world-wide
anniversary celebration is being kicked off at the International
Museum of Cartoon Art in Boca Raton, Fla., on Saturday with ``50
Years of ``Peanuts: The Art of Charles M. Schulz,'' which runs
until Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peanuts'' has been ``explained'' by everyone from Christian
evangelists to the brainy semiologist Umberto Eco, who loves the
strip he once translated for Italian newspapers. He calls Schulz a
Poet, with a capital P. The artist, a notoriously modest man, seems
largely unaffected by the musings of the intelligentsia.
</P>
<P>
   But he's passionate about the perils of ``growing up.'' He talks
as if he knows first-hand the sort of insecurities and anxieties
that Charlie Brown and his pals often display.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a kid is not easy,'' he said. ``It's a fearful world out
there, and the playground is a dangerous place. Going to school
every day is not easy. If it isn't the teacher, it's the bully.
Most adults forget about these struggles, and ignore the problems
little kids have. As an adult, you learn how to get around these
problems and how to survive. But little kids are struggling with
that survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz said he's ``always accused of putting adult things in
kids' mouths. But they come up with the most remarkable statements.
I just give a slight exaggeration to what is real life.''
</P>
<P>
   The first strip, from Oct. 2, 1950, had a rather _ good grief! _
snarky tone: Two kids, Shermy and Patty, watch a smiling Charlie
Brown stroll down the street. ``Good ol' Charlie Brown . . . Yes
sir,'' Shermy says. ``Good ol' Charlie Brown . . . How I hate
him!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That first strip is the only one Sparky wishes he could take
back,'' laughed Brian Walker, using Schulz's childhood nickname,
taken from the horse Spark Plug in the comic strip ``Barney
Google.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, son of ``Beetle Bailey'' cartoonist Mort Walker, has
known Schulz for years and curated the exhibition at the cartoon
museum. (When the museum began raising money for its Mizner Park
building, Schulz became the largest private donor, plunking down $1
million. The 76-year-old cartoonist won't attend the show. ``Only
because I have no interest in visiting Florida.'')
</P>
<P>
   Although not a retrospective, the show will have a ``timeline''
tracing ``Peanuts''' impact on popular culture _ from the first
strip, to the 1999 Broadway revival of ``You're A Good Man, Charlie
Brown,'' which won two Tony awards. There will be artifacts,
posters, toys, dolls and blow-ups of historic strips.
</P>
<P>
   A second section will feature original art and comic strips. A
third will be a sculptural re-creation of the world of ``Peanuts''.
Visitors will encounter life-size characters. They can visit Lucy
at her psychiatry booth, or spot Linus in the pumpkin patch with
his security blanket. ``With cartoons, a cultural context should be
addressed,'' said Walker. ``A comic strip hanging on the wall with
a light on it is meaningless to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Christina Orr-Cahall, director of the Norton Museum of Art,
worked closely with Schulz on a ``Peanuts'' exhibition at the
Oakland (Calif.) Museum and marvels at his output. ``He's very
self-effacing, very modest,'' she recalled. ``He doesn't see
himself as an artist, which I would disagree with. He has never
really lost his working class roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Walker: ``Despite the riches and worldwide acclaim, he's
still the same awkward kid that he probably was when he was
young.'' (But not the real-life Charlie Brown. Schulz's hero was
modeled after a boyhood friend.)
</P>
<P>
   Schulz simply calls himself a cartoonist _ a rare one who still
creates the entire strip, from the gag to the drawing to the
lettering. He's known as a stickler for quality control, but he
sounds rather nonchalant about the workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cartooning is just something you do,'' he said. ``It's just
something I always wanted to do. I'm not obsessed by traveling. I'm
not obsessed by getting everything done in this lifetime. I draw
comic strips for the same reason people do watercolors, or go
bowling. I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in St. Paul, Minnesota in 1922, Schulz used to discuss
comic strips over breakfast with his beloved father, a barber. ``I
always drew, but I didn't know it was possible to be a cartoonist
until my teens,'' he recalled. ``When I began professionally, the
only vague ambition I had was to do a comic strip as good as
(George Herriman's) 'Krazy Kat'.''
</P>
<P>
   During his senior year in high school, Schulz enrolled in a
correspondence course in cartooning. After serving with the Army in
Europe during World War II, he returned to St. Paul and got a job
as a letterer for a Catholic comic magazine. In 1947, his panel
cartoon ``Li'l Folks,'' the forerunner of ``Peanuts,'' appeared in
the St. Paul Pioneer-Press. It ran for nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Schulz hand-carried some strips based on L'il Folks to
United Feature Syndicate in New York. The syndicate snapped them
up, renaming the strip ``Peanuts'' because of copyright
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz couldn't come up with a name for the new strip, and
thought ``Peanuts'' sounded ``dumb. I was afraid people would think
that 'Peanuts' was the name of the lead character. I'd never heard
of kids being called 'Peanuts.' I had to give in, of course. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Peanuts'' debuted in seven newspapers. Today, it appears in
more than 2,600 newspapers in 75 countries. The ``Peanuts''
franchise generates $1 billion a year in retail sales alone. Each
year, more than 20,000 new products appear bearing ``Peanuts''
character art. There are some 800 licensees throughout the world.
One out of every five Hallmark greeting cards sold has a
``Peanuts'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   And every item must pass Schulz's inspection. In between, he
also finds some time for cartooning. ``The strip is not what you
would call a chore. I work on one strip at a time, seven days a
week. Finishing three a day is pretty good for me. Two kind of
empty. One very empty. I've never done more than six a day a half
dozen times in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz freely acknowledges that his once precise drawing style
has become scratchier over the years. ``It's age. Simple as that.
Sometimes I have to prop one hand in the other. Some days it's
worse than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz said the ``Peanuts'' strip will die with him. ``I can
quote my daughter, Amy. We were meeting with lawyers and such, and
she said, `I don't want anyone drawing Daddy's strip.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There's a practical consideration, as well. ``Another artist
might be able to duplicate it _ bring the strip up to the level it
is now. But he wouldn't be able to take the strip forward,'' Schulz
said. ``This is an extremely personal medium. A comic strip
shouldn't just lay there. It should always advance.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Schulz isn't going anywhere. He plays center for a
hockey team in the annual seniors tournament that he hosts each
year at the beloved ice arena he built for the community of Santa
Rosa. Shulz's day usually begins with coffee and an English muffin
at the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see kids skating in the morning. It's a nice, pleasant way
to start the day.''
</P>
<P>
   He then walks to his office a few blocks away, reads the papers
and works until about 11:30. Then it's lunch back at the arena,
talking to the locals. His workday ends around 4 p.m. Lately, he's
been doing his Sunday strips at home. Schulz has five children from
a previous marriage. His second wife, Jeannie, has two.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz said the day-to-day grind isn't a problem. ``The most
difficult part of cartooning is finding a theme around which you
can do variations,'' he said. ``The Red Baron. Charlie Brown losing
the ballgame. The Great Pumpkin.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz avoids becoming too ``deep'' when talking about his
famous characters. For example, what would the ``Peanuts'' gang be
like if they ever grew up? ``People have been trying to force me to
think about that for a long time, but I wouldn't have the slightest
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Schulz calls himself politically concerned, politics
rarely, if ever, appears in his strips. ``Political humor is too
easy,'' he said. Causes do show up on occasion. For example, Schulz
once did a series of strips on the ``lazy eye'' medical problem in
children. And ``Peanuts'' was an advocate for Title IX _ women's
equality in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``His cartoons had a lot to do with making that happen,'' said
the Norton's Orr-Cahall. ``He could bring the issue into everyone's
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulz is generous in praise of younger cartoonists. Two of his
favorite strips are Patrick McDonald's ``Mutts'' because ``it's
just funny, that's all. The writing is funny, the drawing is funny,
and he's not trying to save the world.'' He also admires Mark
Tonra's ``Top of the World.'' ``It's about two funny guys in
prison, and I like the stylized drawing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Schulz's drawing style may have changed over the past
15 years, its virtues remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sparky has an uncanny ability to tap into the emotions that
other people leave behind,'' said Brian Walker. ``By varying those
lines and the position of the eyes, he can make a character happy,
wistful, sad _ all those subtle emotions from those simple lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker compares Schulz to Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   ``His contributions to American culture are just as significant
as Tom Sawyer and Huck Finn. He created Charlie Brown and Snoopy.
This show may remind us how much they've become a part of our
collective consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   BOX
</P>
<P>
   If the ``Peanuts'' gang grew up, we wondered how they would be
spending their modern maturity years:
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Brown: Now on his second marriage (after that fling with
``the little red-haired girl''), he works as assistant manager for
product services at Consolidated Kite Co., where his kite still
gets stuck in a tree at the company's annual picnic. Has been named
``Good Employee of the Month'' twice in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy: Married three times, divorced three times. An abusive
radio shrink, she's desperately trying to get her Judge Lucy show
in syndication.
</P>
<P>
   Linus: Major Trekkie, X-Files fanatic and conspiracy theorist.
Despite intensive psychotherapy, he still believes in the Great
Pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Pigpen: Learned to play guitar, joined the Grateful Dead,
overdosed.
</P>
<P>
   Peppermint Patty: Currently shooting a 76 on the LPGA tour.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder: Keyboardist for the Boca Pops. Confirmed bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   Snoopy: If he was 50 in dog years, that would make him 350 in
human years. What do you think happened to him?
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schwan writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: GarySchwan(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
