<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves still feel there's something to prove with MetsBy Thomas
Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ With the heavy-lifting finished, the NL East champion
Braves have just two reasons for breaking a sweat in the season's
last week.
</P>
<P>
   First, by going 4-2 over the last six games, Atlanta can assure
itself of the best record in the league and assume home-field
advantage in the first two rounds of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the Braves get another chance to trash the New York
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   And don't underestimate inspiration No. 2. They won't admit to
it publicly, but the Braves' relationship with the Mets has
darkened. Atlanta's current dominant status, 14-4 the past two
seasons, spiced with New York charges that Chipper Jones was tipped
off on pitches last week, has made for hard feelings. With the Mets
reeling in a six-game collapse, the three-game series beginning
tonight offers the Braves a chance to make an uncomfortable
situation nastier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to protect the integrity of the baseball,'' Jones
said. ``When we take the field, we're going to try to win. What
nine players are going to do it? I don't know. But if I take the
field in New York, I'm not going out there to tune up for the
playoffs. I'm going out there to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people expect us to take the last week off, they're badly
mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets caused some of that attitude with the tipping charges.
But as with almost every other team in the league, Mets manager
Bobby Valentine has managed to inspire an opponent by his mere
haughty presence. In some ways, the Mets' swoon is the worst in the
franchise's 38-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say it can't get any worse,'' catcher Mike
Piazza said. ``I really don't want to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves would not mind contributing to their troubles. The
club was incensed about the charges against Jones, who has hit .448
with seven homers and 14 RBIs in nine games against the Mets.
Valentine has become a lightning rod for the Atlanta response.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say those things sounds like you're crying,'' right fielder
Brian Jordan said. ``His job is on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a weird few days for the Mets manager, who over the
weekend pledged that the Mets would make the playoffs or management
should replace him. Mets co-owner Fred Wilpon had to shoot that one
down personally, leaving Valentine to return to his recurring chirp
that the team's bad luck is bound to change.
</P>
<P>
   With Cincinnati beating St. Louis on Monday, New York enters
play today 1 1/2 games out of playoff contention. When Philadelphia
completed last weekend's sweep over the Mets, the P.A. system at
Veterans Stadium blared ``Taps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets are still in it,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said.
``You can't go up there and just lie down. We'll go as hard as we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
