<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Sept. 28. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS (Jerusalem) _ In its first three months,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's government has authorized new
construction in the West Bank's Jewish settlements at a pace
exceeding that of the right-wing administration of Benjamin
Netanyahu. Palestinians had hoped that Barak would curtail
Netanyahu's expansion plans for the Jewish settlements to create a
better climate for peacemaking. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ARRESTS (Mitrovica, Kosovo) _ Twenty-six men from one
street in this town have been missing for over five months, ever
since Serb police forced them out from their apartments and
separated them from their wives and children in the street below.
On Monday, their relatives were called to the main police station
here and were told by French gendarmes of the men's fate. It seems
that minutes after the women and children were ordered to flee on
that terrible day, April 14, the men were all executed. The news
brought to an end the families' long search for their menfolk, and
a conclusion to the extensive three-month investigation by the
French. The case is seen as a first in Kosovo where foreign
investigators have conducted a complete investigation, working from
the first reports of missing people to finding a mass grave and
arresting suspects. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NEXT (Beijing) _ China after 50 years of communism
(anniversary is Friday): A look at six up-and-coming Chinese in
their 30s and 40s. By Erik Eckholm and Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ A $500-billion confrontation is
building between the White House and Congress, with President
Clinton vowing to veto nearly half of the spending bills that the
Republicans in the Senate and the House are trying to finish
passing this week. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, in a
keynote address for the IMF-World Bank meeting, discusses lessons
learned from the Asian financial crisis. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN (Nashua, N.H.) _ Sen. John McCain formally
announces his candidacy for the Republican presidential nomination.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE-CAMPAIGN (Phoenix) _ Dan Quayle, the former vice
president who hoped to overcome long odds and ridicule to step up
to the Republican presidential nomination in 2000, gave up his
White House dreams on Monday. He was the latest victim of
Republican front-runner George W. Bush's juggernaut. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HMOS (Los Angeles) _ Gov. Gray Davis signed a package of
HMO reforms that includes a guarantee of patients' rights to a
second opinion and a requirement for mental-health coverage. The
reforms make California, a leader in the HMO movement, the state
with the toughest regulations. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   NY-VIRUS (New York) _ The outbreak of a mosquito-borne illness
that killed at least three people in New York was not caused by St.
Louis encephalitis at all, but rather a form of the West Nile virus
that has previously never been diagnosed in the Western Hemisphere,
government health officials said. The number of confirmed cases of
the disease more than doubled; over a dozen cases that health
officials had ruled negative for encephalitis proved to be the West
Nile virus in weekend testing. There are now 25 confirmed cases _
at least three of them fatal _ of confirmed West Nile virus in New
York City. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-SCREENS (Mobara, Japan) _ Business is booming for
computer screen manufacturers across Japan, South Korea and Taiwan,
fueled by strong sales of personal computers and devices with
screens that provide brilliant color images and graphics. But
demand is so strong that Asian producers cannot keep up, creating a
worldwide shortage of screens and big headaches for computer makers
like IBM, Dell and Toshiba, which are scrambling to satisfy
consumers' enormous appetite for notebook computers and large
desktop monitors. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BANKS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ There are no shortage of
things to be angry about in today's Indonesia -- a country
suspended uneasily between dictatorship and democracy; economic
ruin and recovery. Yet of all the outrages in Indonesia these days,
the one that rankles people most is a financial scandal known as
Baligate. The scandal, involving Bank Bali and millions of dollars
that were to be funneled into the reelection campaign of
Indonesia's president, B.J. Habibie, has become a touchstone for
those who say Indonesia must shed once and for all its culture of
corruption. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUAKE-RISK (Undated) _ More bad luck is coming, experts
agree. Even though the rate of earthquakes over time seems to be
more or less unchanging, the world's population explosion means
that more people are moving into quake zones, which are often near
coasts. The result is the prospect of continuing trauma as urban
areas erupt with what seems like nearly endless bursts of
destruction. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
