A7941 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-LONDON-TUBE-HNS &LR;      09-27 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-TUBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON SUBWAY MAP LEADS TO CONFUSION ABOVE GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It's all Harry Beck's fault. On my recent visit to
London I realized, once again, that I still don't have the foggiest
idea where anything is. I have absolutely no clue whether
Westminster Abbey is within walking distance of Piccadilly Circus
or whether Covent Garden is east or west of Trafalgar Square or
whether Soho is close to Big Ben or not.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the London I know isn't the London of clock
towers and double-decker buses and leafy green parks. The London I
know is an alternative, underground London, with its own
idiosyncratic coordinates and geography. The London I know is the
London of Harry Beck.
</P>
<P>
   One of the underappreciated geniuses of this century, Beck was
an unemployed draftsman who devised the London Underground map in
1931 (for which he was paid the sum of five guineas.) In a leap of
transcendent brilliance, Beck realized that as long as he put all
the tube stations and transfer points in the correct sequence,
scale didn't matter at all. He was free to expand the crowded city
center and shrink the outlying suburbs and bend and stretch lines
this way and that, so they all ran horizontally, vertically or
diagonally. The result was a schematic diagram so intuitive and
easy to read that it is still in use, with updates, today.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't make the mistake of confusing it with above-ground
London.
</P>
<P>
   When I'm in London I ride the Underground everywhere, popping up
here and there like a gopher blinking in the harsh sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, I have absolutely no spatial orientation of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   As Bill Bryson pointed out in ``Notes From a Small Island,'' an
out-of-town visitor using Beck's map to get from, say, Bank Station
to Mansion House would quite understandably board a Central Line
train to Liverpool Street, transfer to the Circle Line and continue
for another five stops to Mansion House _ and emerge 200 yards down
the street from where he started.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's easy to make the mistake, as I once did,
of assuming that Hounslow West and Hatton Cross must be quite close
to one another, because they're cheek-by-jowl in Beck's London.
Twenty minutes into my trek I realized my error and backtracked to
the tube station.
</P>
<P>
   The other problem with Beck's alternative London is that the
station names are so enchanting and fanciful that above-ground
London, beguiling as it may be, can never live up to their
suggestion. As you rumble through the dark, dank bowels of the
city, your mind conjures up the fairy-tale world of Elephant &AMP;
Castle, Swiss Cottage, Chalk Farm and Pudding Mill Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Some stations seem to be echoes of long-ago London: Shepherd's
Bush. Parson's Green. West India Quay. Mudchute. West Ham. Others
sound straight out of a P.G. Wodehouse novel: Finchley Road &AMP;
Frognat, Chorleywood, Ickenham. Tooting Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that the world above these underground
stations seems sadly mundane compared to your fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   But the underground stations, built like Victorian catacombs,
are fascinating worlds unto themselves. They're peopled with
world-class musicians cheerfully ignoring the ``No Busking'' signs
and decorated with advertising posters displaying dry British wit.
A sign on a candy machine said: ``Cadbury's chocolate inside.
Please remain calm.''
</P>
<P>
   A billboard for the London Dungeon museum proclaimed: ``Now
worse than ever!''
</P>
<P>
   On my next visit perhaps I'll give myself over completely to
Beck's London, riding the Piccadilly Line from Hammersmith to
Cockfosters, or the Metropolitan Line out to Harrow-on-the-Hill and
back, never emerging into the sunlight of above-ground London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
