<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7949 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      09-27 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Pathfinder mission beamed images from the surface of
Mars two years ago, Yogi, Stimpy and Flat Top were among the stars
of the show. They were not characters in some Three Stooges remake;
they were rocks at the landing site, and the mission's
remote-controlled rover spent a lot of time photographing, X-raying
and otherwise examining them.
</P>
<P>
   The three rocks and others are back in the limelight, the
subject of new studies by scientists from NASA's Johnson Space
Center in Houston. Poring over Pathfinder photos, the scientists
have found evidence that impacts from small objects from space may
be altering rocks on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Such landscaping occurs on the moon, where there is no
atmosphere to burn up objects and thus every Tom, Dick or Harry of
a meteor _ even specks of dust _ helps sculpt the surface. But the
thin atmosphere of Mars, by burning up the smallest objects, was
thought to have limited those that get through to ones that would
make a crater of about a yard in diameter or larger.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, writing in Science, observed an impact crater of
about a quarter of a yard in diameter on Stimpy. As for Yogi, they
suggest that it too was hit by something that decapitated it. And
Flat Top got that way, they say, from a similar collision. In these
cases, the colliding object had to be small, or else the rocks
would have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, wind and water were thought to be largely
responsible for shaping the Martian landscape. But the scientists
say that the Pathfinder evidence points strongly to small
extraterrestrial impacts as having a role.
</P>
<P>
   Dangers for Birds
</P>
<P>
   It may be an open question whether modern communications
technology is changing peoples' lives for the better, but there is
little doubt that birds are worse off. All those towers for
cellular telephones, television and radio are potential killers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as presented last month at a meeting of the
American Ornithological Union at Cornell University, is
particularly acute in bad weather at night, when birds are
attracted by tower lights. One of the worst incidents occurred on a
snowy night in January 1998 in western Kansas, when about 10,000
migrating birds died at the site of a television tower. Some hit
the tower directly, but others became disoriented and circled,
eventually hitting guy wires or dying from exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is not new, the ornithologists say, but with the
increase in the number of towers in recent years it appears to be
growing worse. Of particular concern, they say, are digital
television towers, which can easily reach 1,000 feet and which are
just beginning to be built around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some steps can be taken, however. In Canada, a power company
found that bird kills at generating station smokestacks were cut
significantly when spotlights were replaced by flashing strobes.
</P>
<P>
   The Iceberg Cometh
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have had their first close encounter with a giant
iceberg that is adrift off Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   The iceberg, about 48 miles long and 24 miles wide, is a remnant
of one that calved off the Thwaites ice tongue into the Amundsen
Sea in West Antarctica nearly a decade ago. (And quite a fatted
calf it was: It was originally more than 100 miles long.)
</P>
<P>
   The iceberg was locked in pack ice for several years, then split
into two pieces in 1995, and it is the larger piece, named B-10A,
that is being tracked.
</P>
<P>
   A National Science Foundation research ship encountered the
iceberg earlier this month, taking photographs, sizing it up with
radar and collecting ice samples. At a speed of 10 knots, the ship
took 12 hours to circumnavigate it.
</P>
<P>
   B-10A will eventually go the way of all icebergs, but because it
is so large there may be enough left as it drifts into warmer
waters to pose a threat to shipping around Cape Horn, the
southernmost tip of South America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
