<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MILAN-SHOWS-COX     09-27 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-SHOWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funk, rubber eyewear and a $2 million dress
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Punk and funk collided Sunday when designers
Domenico Dolce and Stephano Gabbana presented looks from their
spring/summer bridge collection, D&AMP;G. Their models, outfitted
frequently in garb embellished by chains, crucifixes and safety
pins, strutted to a soundtrack of rap diva Missy Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   It was a show of decadence and extravagance. The D&AMP;G skirts were
tiny enough to be mistaken for belts. Eyelets made the leather
goods that much lustier, and pinstriped blazers were paired with
stretch lace leggings. The runway space adjacent to Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana's inner-city villa was decorated to look like a tropical
retreat: a good setting for the animal-, floral- and postcard-print
separates.
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't enough to chew on, the designers also
announced the launching of two new D&AMP;G licenses: a rubberized
eyewear collection called Gum, and a chewing gum brand by the same
name (which tastes like Juicy Fruit in designer wrapping). Both
should reach stores by month's end.
</P>
<P>
   Wedded bliss: If Antonio D'Amico learned anything during his
long love affair with the late designer Gianni Versace, it's that
fashion is as much about theatrics as anything. So, for his show
that brought the first day of Milan's Fashion Week to a close,
D'Amico rented space at the Teatro Des Artes and capped off his
spring/summer show with a wedding dress that even the richest women
can only dream about.
</P>
<P>
   The white satin gown, with an asymmetrical zipper running up the
front, was festooned with 350 diamonds weighing a total of 140
carats. Its $2 million price tag makes it the most expensive
garment ever manufactured in Italy. (The queen of Belgium
reportedly is interested in buying or borrowing it.) After spending
a respectable length of time mourning Versace, D'Amico, who
formerly co-designed the lower-priced Versus collections, opened
his own firm last year. His latest warm-weather collection is sleek
and simple _ a stark departure from the ostentatious looks for
which Versace was renowned.
</P>
<P>
   A prairie home companion: While some designers sketched their
collections with jet-set or space age clienteles in mind, Alberta
Ferretti brought her Philosphie line down to earth. Her
handkerchief-headed models wore clothes the color of moss, grass,
dirt, wildflowers and spent dandelions. Except for ruffles around
the necks, sleeves and hemlines, Ferretti's frocks were mainly
fuss-free. Pristine cottons, crocheted knits, ginghams, suedes and
leathers were her key fabrics. To drive home the modern-milkmaid
mind-set, models were outfitted in knee-high mud boots.
</P>
<P>
   High karate: New York-based designer John Bartlett always has
fanciful females in mind for inspiration. Backstage Monday, after
showing his collection for the Milanese label Byblos, Bartlett said
his muses are ``Jackie Kennedy on acid,'' ``Western geishas'' and
``Judy Jetson at the prom.'' Virginal white dresses, suits and
separates _ all sheer, slit at the hems and asymmetrically wrapped
_ started off the show. They were followed by black-and-gold
ensembles, souped up with jet beading. Then Bartlett showed Asiatic
satin ensembles in pastel colors. Key details included martial arts
belts encircling coats, blouses and dresses, and origami folds of
fabric on his skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity sighting: R&AMP;B diva Mary J. Blige was at Sunday
afternoon's D&AMP;G preview, in exceedingly tight red leather and
close-cropped hair.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
