<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-QUAKE-RISK-ART-2N     09-27 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUAKE-RISK-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: long time.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the lull, experts say the dangers will rise as more
people inhabit cities near coasts and quake belts. Today, a third
of the earth's population lives within 60 miles of a coast, experts
say, and that fraction is expected to grow, increasing their
vulnerability to both earthquakes and hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Bilham of the University of Colorado wrote a pioneering paper on
the rising quake hazard that was published in the journal Nature in
1988 and he has explored the field ever since. He said that the
world currently has 27 megacities, which the United Nations defines
as holding at least 8 million people, and that more than a third of
these dense urban regions were located near quivering plate
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The major cities at risk, he said, in addition to Los Angeles,
Tokyo and Taipei, the capital of Taiwan, include Athens, Greece;
Istanbul, Turkey; Tehran, the capital of Iran; Islamabad, the
capital of Pakistan; Calcutta, India; Jakarta, Indonesia; and
Manila, the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability of any one megacity being hit is quite low,''
Bilham noted. ``But if you take a plate boundary that has 10
cities, then the probability increases and I would not be surprised
if one of those went quite soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Seih, a seismic expert at the California Institute of
Technology, said the overall risk was rising. ``There are a lot of
big cities around the world that are going to be eaten in the
coming century,'' he said, ``unless we pay better attention'' to
erecting stronger homes and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``These earthquakes in the last year of the millennium are going
to be an interesting test,'' Seih added. ``Do we go on with
business as usual, and fatalistically accept that we're going to
lose tens of thousands of people a year? Or do we say, `No, we have
the know-how to survive more completely'?''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had just returned from Turkey, where he had examined
a jumble of devastated buildings. ``A lot that collapsed were
new,'' he said, noting that many deaths occurred in such buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Both Turkey and Taiwan have building codes similar to
California's, which are meant to let people get out alive in a
major earthquake even if a structure is seriously damaged.
Protective measures include reinforcing concrete walls and pillars,
digging deep foundations and adding special joints to ease internal
stresses on buildings that suddenly start to shake and sway.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the codes are better enforced in Taiwan than in
Turkey. That discrepancy, they say, added to the size of the
Turkish disaster, which killed more than 15,000 people, and perhaps
as many as twice that number. The total is unclear because of the
slow recovery from the ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Bilham of the University of Colorado, who recently returned to
his sabbatical at Oxford from inspection trips to Turkey and
Greece, said he was optimistic for the new century because so many
new buildings would be constructed that in theory would be much
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's buildings that kill people,'' Bilham, a geophysicist,
said, ``not earthquakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Retrofitting to modern earthquake standards is very expensive,
he said, costing upward of half a building's value. But in new
construction, quake precautions add just 10 percent to 20 percent
to building costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the good news is that if we come to grips with the reality
that earthquakes will keep hitting planet earth, and acknowledge a
certain future of shaking in cities, then we'll build buildings
that don't fall down,'' Bilham said. ``By acting now, we can save a
lot of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he added, is that developing countries, which have
the greatest need of safeguards, are often mired in economic
conflicts exacerbated by exploding populations. For instance, in
one part of India, he said, planners faced a choice of whether to
erect 150 buildings that were quake-resistant or 200 that were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``They built 200,'' Bilham noted. ``That's the kind of decision
that's going on around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, he added, probably after a series of urban disasters,
and surely by the year 3000, ``I'd be very surprised if we don't
build buildings that don't fall down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
