<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOCS-LITERATURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PATIENT'S NOT CRAZY, JUST LITERATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(lb) 
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before your next hospital stay, you might want to ponder a
question raised in last week's New England Journal of Medicine: Do
the doctors and nurses on staff know their literature?
</P>
<P>
   Not medical literature. Just literature, of the type studied in
English classes.
</P>
<P>
   A letter to the journal described the case of a 51-year-old high
school teacher who entered the hospital for treatment after a heart
attack. Surrounded by tubes, wires and machines, the patient
remarked that he felt as if he were ``in Peter Coffin's inn.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Coffin was the proprietor of Spouter-Inn, the lodging
house in Herman Melville's 1851 novel, ``Moby-Dick,'' where Ishmael
had to share a bed with the magnificently tattooed Queequeg.
</P>
<P>
   The nurse, however, heard the word ``coffin,'' and immediately
called in psychiatric consultants, who interviewed the patient for
several hours to determine if he was suicidal. He was not.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the hospital ``seemed to recognize the reference to
`Moby-Dick,''' lamented Dr. Howard Fischer of Detroit in the letter
to the journal. ``No one had read the novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer concluded that two lessons could learned from the case.
``Medical personnel,'' he wrote, ``need to listen more closely to
patients' remarks and ask about unfamiliar phrases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Second (and less readily changed),'' Fischer continued,
``physicians and nurses need a broader education in the
humanities.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, one can imagine other misunderstandings that
might occur when medical personnel are deficient in literary
expertise. In the course of having his blood drawn, for example, a
patient might say: ``Though I am not splenetive and rash / Yet have
I in me something dangerous'' (``Hamlet,'' Act V, Scene One), and
be whisked off to see an oncologist.
</P>
<P>
   Or a patient might borrow a line from ``Henry VI'': ``The first
thing we do, let's kill all the lawyers,'' sending hospital
administrators into an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the man who opines: ``I grow old, I grow old, I
shall wear the bottoms of my trousers rolled'' (T.S. Eliot)? Should
he consult a geriatrician?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
