<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c .1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flight of the Monarchs
</P>
<P>
   Q. In mid-September, I saw many monarch butterflies headed south
down Sixth Avenue in Manhattan. Is this unusual? Do they congregate
around New York City somewhere?
</P>
<P>
   A. This is the right time of year for the Eastern monarchs'
migration, and they do congregate in Cape May, N.J., by the
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The monarchs seen in and around New York City are flying through
on the way to their wintering sites in the mountains of central
Mexico, according to the Monarch Project, a clearinghouse for
information on their migration. The butterflies seek out
microclimates congenial to an overnight rest and are off again in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The migration happens every year, but is much more noticeable in
some years because insect populations are highly variable. Factors
like wind patterns may influence the exact route. However, each
year there are reports of sightings in Manhattan, even of big
groups flying by office windows 30 floors up.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern population of monarchs overwinters in the
Transvolcanic Range in Mexico, on the border of the states of
Michoacan and Mexico. The site, 10,000 feet above sea level, was
discovered in 1975. The Western population overwinters on the coast
of California.
</P>
<P>
   General information on the monarchs' migration and their
overwintering sites, but not on their specific travel plans, is
available from the Monarch Program at (760) 944-7113.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New York, N.Y.
10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
