<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7965 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-QUAKE-WAVES-ART-5     09-27 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUAKE-WAVES-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS FIND NEW CLUES TO QUAKES' VIBRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dr. Yehuda Ben-Zion visited Turkey three days after the
recent earthquake there, he saw the deadly capriciousness that is
familiar to survivors of such cataclysms. The dividing line between
a seemingly untouched building and a pile of rubble might be no
more than a few yards wide, said Ben-Zion, a seismologist and
geophysicist at the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could find a house that was destroyed standing next to a
house that is not,'' Ben-Zion said. Similar stories were told by
survivors of last week's earthquake in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   What looks like the skipping finger of fate can partly be
explained by a combination of mundane factors like variations in
construction quality and fault lines in the underlying rock. But
increasingly, scientists like Ben-Zion are finding those factors
inadequate in explaining the spotty nature of the destruction and
are making an effort to understand why the seismic fury of an
earthquake is focused on one spot and not another.
</P>
<P>
   Hints are turning up in simple laboratory experiments in which
containers of granular materials like sand, beads, powders, poppy
seeds and even peanuts are shaken, vibrated or otherwise agitated.
Vibrating a shallow dish containing sand or beads, for example,
does not simply spread particles randomly.
</P>
<P>
   Under certain conditions, the vibration produces rising and
falling bumps called oscillons and moving structures that resemble
``little Loch Ness monsters,'' said Jay Fineberg, a physicist at
The Hebrew University of Jerusalem in Israel. Fineberg and other
scientists suspect _ although they still cannot prove _ that
something similar happens when an earthquake shakes the soil and
sediments on the earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   A team led by Fineberg will soon publish the results of
experiments showing that the oscillons and Loch Ness structures
occur in an even wider range of materials than had been known. The
experiments, which will be described in the journal Physical Review
Letters, vibrated what in technical jargon are known as colloidal
suspensions. ``It's essentially mud,'' said Fineberg, who mixed
potter's clay with water.
</P>
<P>
   The experiments, Fineberg said, show that the oscillons do not
just occur in granular media.
</P>
<P>
   Fineberg's work could lead to explanations of why some of the
greatest destruction from earthquakes often occurs in swatches of
land reclaimed from the sea, like the Marina District in the San
Francisco earthquake of 1989. Such land, when shaken with extreme
violence, can liquefy and begin to flow. ``In several places where
earthquakes caused damage, there have been clear indications of
this liquefaction phenomenon,'' Ben-Zion said.
</P>
<P>
   Fineberg's laboratory experiments could have an impact on how
buildings are constructed and reinforced in regions prone to
earthquakes. But because scientists are still far from pinning down
the connection between Fineberg's laboratory experiments and actual
earthquakes, they are pushing for an understanding of the basic
physics of oscillons and the Loch Ness structures.
</P>
<P>
   Fineberg's experiments offer promise, said Paul Umbanhowar, a
physicist at Northwestern University. ``The exciting thing about
the system is that this is a material that's a lot closer to water
than to a granular material,'' said Umbanhowar, meaning that its
properties should be similar to those of a substance that is well
understood.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The oscillons and the Loch Ness structures are related to
humplike waves discovered in water confined by a canal, and found
in a variety of natural settings _ including the electrified gases
surrounding the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Umbanhowar and two colleagues discovered oscillons in a
vibrating dish of beads in 1996. ``No one predicted it,'' said
Sidney Nagel, a physicist at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Fineberg went looking for the structures in colloidal
suspensions both because of Umbanhowar's work and because of
anecdotal reports of earthquakes producing large terrestrial
ripples. In one case, a farmer reported such a wave rumbling across
a cornfield ``kind of like if you shook a rug,'' Fineberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The muddy suspensions were also expected to share a crucial
property with the granular materials that is similar to the way a
glob of peanut butter retains its form but flows easily when it is
pushed with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the oscillons can bounce up and down in a
vibrating dish while the material around them stays in place.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what the Hebrew University team observed when
they vibrated shallow, mud-filled dishes the size of large saucers
up and down at frequencies from 10 to 60 times a second. Once the
experimenters induced oscillons to form, in some cases by blowing
on the surface of the mud, the structures remained in one place,
rising and falling from a hill shape to a crater shape and back
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Loch Ness structures also rose and fell, but also moved
around in the dish. ``They're kind of neat critters,'' Fineberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   If structures like these were generated during earthquakes,'' he
said, it would mean that some buildings should be protected not
only against drastic side-to-side motions, as many are now, but
also against vertical jolts. Areas that are most at risk from these
structures might be identified in advance.
</P>
<P>
   For all the apparent similarities between the laboratory
experiments and nature at its most destructive, other scientists
caution that such analogies go only so far, and that there is
probably more than one way for seismic waves to concentrate their
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of the `spherical horse' approximation,'' Nagel said
of the tendency of physicists to make highly idealized assumptions
about nature. He was alluding to a joke about a physicist hired by
a dairy to increase milk production. To simplify his calculations,
the physicist assumed all cows to be spherical. ``None of this is
presumably the right prescription that takes into account the full
complexity of the situation,'' Nagel said.
</P>
<P>
   But those who have lived through a devastating earthquake must
surely hope that science can at least turn the uncontrollable into
the comprehensible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
