<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Tropical air streaming northward along the southeast and middle
Atlantic coasts will be laden with rain clouds. On Monday, over 2
inches of rain fell in Raleigh, N.C., raising the September total
to 18.5 inches, their wettest month ever.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, showers will spread as far north as central
Pennsylvania as humid air flows inland from the western Atlantic. A
large high-pressure system near Nova Scotia will circulate dry and
mild air into New England where intervals of clouds and sunshine
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The leading edge of a very cool air mass will push quickly
southward into Texas and very slowly eastward across the
Mississippi Valley. A widening band of showers will attend the cold
front from Kansas and Oklahoma to Michigan. A wedge of sultry air
will precede the front in the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, perhaps
leading to the development of strong thunderstorms later Tuesday or
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite high pressure cresting over Wyoming, low clouds and
mixed showers will persist along the east slopes of the Rockies
from the Laramie Mountains to the Sangre De Cristo Mountains in
southern Colorado. It will be much cooler in western Texas on
Tuesday. Most of the plains will be dull and rather cool.
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening winds will blow off the Pacific coast as surface
pressures rise over the central Rockies. Record heat and gusty
canyon winds will aggravate the forest-fire problems in California.
It will be very chilly Tuesday morning in the interior West with
ample sunshine bringing milder afternoon conditions. The Northwest
will be bright and warmer in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The State of Contrast
</P>
<P>
   At daybreak on Saturday, the mercury slipped to a record low of
30 degrees at the Alpena airport in northern lower Michigan.
Shortly after 3 p.m. on Sunday, the temperature tied a record high
of 82 degrees at Muskegon in southwest Michigan. These contrasts
stem from the rapid temperature changes associated with an
increased vigor in the jet stream. A polar air mass brought a touch
of autumn chill to northern Michigan at the start of the weekend,
but its return circulation was strong enough to draw very warm air
back into the Great Lakes by late Monday. A more active jet stream
may bring record chill back to the region this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
