<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP SUES WHITE HOUSE, DEFENSE DEPARTMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Accused phone-tapper Linda Tripp sued the White
House and Defense Department on Monday, alleging that federal
officials illegally used confidential records to discredit her
during the Monica Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses the Clinton administration of misusing
Tripp's confidential personnel records, FBI files and security
forms to obtain and spread ``embarrassing or damaging information
... for partisan political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   It names only two Pentagon officials individually as defendants,
then lists 11 White House figures, including first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, as having ``engaged in communications ... about
Linda R. Tripp.'' The lawsuit does not allege that the
communications by Hillary Clinton and others close to the president
were unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, a former White House employee who was transferred to the
Pentagon, swore in several documents during her 25-year government
career that she had never been arrested, when in fact she had been.
Her lawsuit alleges that information from those documents was
disclosed to the news media in violation of the federal Privacy Act
as part of a campaign to discredit her in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Tripp was accused of grand larceny in the alleged theft
of $263 in cash and a $600 watch, charges that her lawyers say were
dropped. Tripp said the items were planted in her handbag by
friends as part of a teen-age prank.
</P>
<P>
   Named as defendants in Tripp's lawsuit are the White House, the
Department of Defense, Assistant Secretary of Defense Kenneth Bacon
and former Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense Clifford Bernath.
At the time of the disclosure, Bacon and Bernath worked in the
Pentagon's public affairs department.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court in Washington, asks for
unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's lawsuit says the effort to smear her reputation and
intimidate her began immediately after she gave independent counsel
Kenneth Starr tapes of secretly recorded telephone conversations
with Lewinsky. In those tapes, Lewinsky described her affair with
Clinton and their efforts to hide the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes prompted Starr to expand his investigation of Clinton
to include his affair with the former White House intern, a line of
inquiry that led to the president's impeachment by the House in
December 1998. Clinton was acquitted by the Senate in February.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a state grand jury in Maryland, where Tripp resides,
indicted her on charges of illegally taping a December 1997
telephone conversation with Lewinsky. Tripp also was charged with
illegally directing her attorney to disclose the contents of the
tape to Newsweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's lawsuit was assigned to U.S. District Judge Royce
Lamberth, who was appointed to the bench by President Reagan.
Lamberth also is handling several other lawsuits in which the
Clinton administration is accused of misusing FBI files of various
Republicans, including Rep. Bob Barr, a Georgia conservative and
frequent Clinton critic; Billy Ray Dale, who was fired from the
White House travel office; and M. Dennis Sculimbrene, a former FBI
agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration declined comment. ``Since there is
litigation pending, this is not something we should comment on in
any respect,'' said Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House
counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
