</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLASTIC-RISK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEBATE OVER SAFETY OF SOFTENERS FOR PLASTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are called phthalates, and their job is to make plastic
flexible so it can be used in tubes for blood transfusions,
intravenous feeding and other life-support systems at hospitals and
clinics around the world _ and in some children's toys.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with these chemicals, some scientists and consumer
advocates say, is that they may be dangerous: small amounts can
leach into the bloodstream and have been shown in animal studiecs
say.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists say phthalates (pronounced THAL-ates) are
perfectly safe, and the chemicals won a significant ally in June,
when a panel of scientists led by Dr. C. Everett Koop, the former
Surgeon General, backed that view. But instead of quieting the
critics, the panel's findings have provoked an outcry.
</P>
<P>
   Health Care Without Harm, an international coalition of 180
organizations of health workers, advocacy groups and
environmentalists, has issued its own report sharply critical of
the Koop panel's findings, calling them ``an incomplete, deceptive
and misleading analysis of the scientific literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ted Schettler, director of the Science and Environmental
Health Network, a group of doctors and research scientists that is
a member of the coalition, accused the panel of omitting
significant scientific work, reporting findings not made in the
studies it cited, and misrepresenting data from others.
</P>
<P>
   The American Council on Science and Health, the nonprofit group
that organized the Koop panel and paid for the study, denied that
the findings were in any way deceptive. Dr. Elizabeth M. Whelan,
president of the council, said it ``stands firmly behind the
conclusions drawn from the weight of the scientific evidence by Dr.
Koop and his distinguished colleagues,'' and added, ``As Dr. Koop
has said, `Consumers can be confident that vinyl medical devices
and toys are safe.'''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is under investigation by the Federal Food and Drug
Administration, the National Institutes of Health and National
Academy of Sciences. They are all looking at human risks associated
with two phthalates studied in the Koop report: Di(2-ethylhexyl)
phthalates, or DEHP, the primary plasticizer in medical devices,
and diisononyl phthalates, or DINP, in toys.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the Consumer Product Safety Commission asked
manufacturers to stop using the DINP phthalates to make plastic
teethers, rattles and nipples because of safety concerns. The next
month, the National Environmental Trust and 11 other consumer
groups sought a ban of phthalates from toys for children under 5.
Previously, eight European countries had banned or regulated the
substance in toys.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Whelan says that at that point Koop suggested that she
organize a panel of experts, which he would ultimately head, to
evaluate the concerns. In December, the Consumer Product Safety
Commission urged parents to throw away nipples and pacifiers
containing DINP, but said it did not have enough evidence to issue
a ban.
</P>
<P>
   In February, after Health Care Without Harm reported on apparent
risks in medical equipment, the American Council on Science and
Health expanded its study.
</P>
<P>
   Schettler did not analyze the toys portion of the Koop report.
But he said the section on medical devices had several problems.
Among them, he said was that in reviewing whether the chemical
exposures caused reproductive problems in animals, it cited studies
of animals too old to prove or disprove the question.
</P>
<P>
   The damage, he said, appears to occur in fetuses or infant
animals, and at much lower doses of exposure than those the panel
used for evaluating risks to humans _ particularly in testicular
development.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the Koop panel's report, Daland R. Juberg,
director of the International Center for Toxicology and Medicine in
Rochester, disputed those criticisms. For one thing, he said, the
panel ``clearly indicated'' that young animals appear to be more
sensitive than older animals.
</P>
<P>
   And he said the panel had indeed been interested in whether
testicular effects had been observed in various species, and
specifically noted that species like hamsters and marmoset monkeys
had not shown a similar sensitivity to phthalate exposure.
Moreover, he said, nonhuman primates are relatively resistant to
testicular effects.
</P>
<P>
   Schettler said Koop and the other panelists made no mention of a
study of three premature babies whose poorly oxygenated blood
needed mechanical ventilation. The infants developed lung disorders
while they were being ventilated with oxygen through a vinyl tube
in the trachea attached to a respirator, and phthalates in the
tubing were transported to the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   One died of complications from the ventilation; the other two
recovered after the tubing was replaced with a phthalate-free
material, ethylenevinyentilation, the very small number that this
case involved and the thousands of infants that received artificial
ventilation on a daily basis without evidence of health effects,
that a causal relationship between DEHP exposure and effects in
these infants could not be inferred from this study.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among Schettler's other complaints was that the Koop panel
was deceptive in stating that no harm to kidneys were reported in
one study, because, in fact, the study was not done on kidneys at
all but rather on liver, cardiac and lung effects.
</P>
<P>
   Juberg replied that the panel ``was not deceptive in any way,
but rather assessed all of the evidence available to render a
conclusion as to possible renal effects in humans.'' He cited a
review of the animal and human toxicology literature, published in
1990, concluding that there was no evidence to support the
hypothesis that phthalates caused of kidney cancer in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Until the federal agencies weigh in on the issue, the debate is
likely to rest there, leaving consumers to wonder whether what gets
under their skin is safe for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
