<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS28-COX     09-27 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons try to pinpoint reasons for slow startBy Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves fiddled with an empty cup
Monday, avoiding as long as possible the team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 p.m., as players filed inside, Reeves, most of his staff
and even general manager Harold Richardson waited outside, where _
fittingly _ it was gray and gloomy.
</P>
<P>
   After an 0-3 start, the Falcons are shocked and melancholy. Last
year's dream ride to the Super Bowl is starting to fade, just as
the 1999 team seems to be making a hauntingly similar return to
Atlanta's pre-1998 history, when the franchise had just seven
winning seasons in 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a win bad,'' Reeves said. ``When you are losing, you
never have confidence. Losing brings the wrong kinds of things _
people second-guessing you, people talking about how bad you are
playing. That is constantly all you read and all you hear.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's 35-7 loss at St. Louis, the Falcons have many
more questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   The most basic is, when will quarterback Chris Chandler's
strained right hamstring allow him to play again? Don't bet on
Sunday's game against Baltimore (1-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel good,'' Chandler said Monday after
re-aggravating the injury a day earlier and then wondering if he
should have played at all. ``It doesn't feel like (he should have)
today.''
</P>
<P>
   On a bigger scale, how can the Falcons turn things around? They
are going through more problems than the injuries alone.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves noted that the Rams `` looked like they were playing a
different speed than what we were.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what is going on,'' second-year right tackle
Ephraim Salaam said. ``All I've known as a Falcon was 14-2, when we
got on a good roll and felt good about ourselves. There's a lot
more pressure on us. Every game is a playoff atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams get real jacked up to play us,'' Salaam said. ``We just
played slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting off to a slow start didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   The season-opening 17-14 loss to the Vikings _ a game in which
Atlanta had three turnovers, Minnesota none, and Morten Andersen
missed two field goals under 40 yards _ is three weeks old. But
it's still fresh in the minds of the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been in the league, if you win early, you go
farther,'' nine-year strong safety Marty Carter said. ``Teams that
lose games they had a chance to win, it seems like their attitude
and morale change. You're trying not to lose instead of win.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries _ especially a season-ender to All-Pro running back
Jamal Anderson and to Chandler _ have been painful. But healthy
players aren't executing, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably was not anybody . . . that didn't have at least
one or two plays that we really bad,'' Reeves said. ``You know,
bone-head type plays. I didn't see the intensity, the flying
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The players have not held their own meeting, just several
informal gatherings. ``Talking ain't going to get it done,'' Salaam
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can play,'' running back Byron Hanspard said.
``It's an individual mental process right now. Everybody has to
look in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can read stuff, Hanspard said, ``and . . . get discouraged
or upset. Or, if you know who you are, you won't allow that to
affect you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ray Buchanan said the end is not as near as some
might think. It would help, he said, if the Falcons could get back
to opportunistic football.
</P>
<P>
   They led the NFL last year with a plus-20 turnover ratio. This
year, they are minus-six and haven't recovered a fumble, after
leading the league with 25 last season. Atlanta also has only two
sacks in there games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't no real biggie right now,'' Buchanan said. ``I've
been beaten before. We got to get heat on the quarterback. We got
to get turnovers; that's how we won games last year.''
</P>
<P>
   If over-reacting is not a concern, Reeves also said he doesn't
believe under-reacting is, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our guys take it seriously,'' he said. ``Again, it is
the mental aspect of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
