<HEADLINE>
POP REVIEW: TWO FRIENDS ROCKED IN THE BOSOM OF COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For Linda Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris, sisterly
solidarity means harmony: a sweet, close, carefully aligned blend.
Their concert at the Beacon Theater on Sunday night, part of a tour
promoting their new duet album, ``Western Wall'' (Asylum/Elektra),
was a night of ballads, full of promises of nurturing affection. It
was also a reflection on their long friendship and a valedictory
for the country-rooted rock that built both women's careers.
</P>
<P>
   They are as different, as Ms. Harris said onstage, as a city
mouse and a country mouse. Since 1980 Ms. Ronstadt has applied her
big, torchy voice to Tin Pan Alley standards, Mexican mariachi, new
wave rock and Gilbert and Sullivan operettas as well as the
soft-rock songs that made her one of the most consistent hit makers
of the 1970s. Ms. Harris, with her wiry soprano, has stayed closer
to bluegrass and country-and-western music; keeping an Appalachian
twang in her voice, she helped create country's new-traditionalist
movement and provided a template for the alternative country of the
1990s. They looked back to straightforward country when they made
albums with Dolly Parton as Trio; recording as a duo, they found
common ground in folk rock and country rock.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harris, who is 52, and Ms. Ronstadt, 53, have nearly stopped
singing about youthful passions. The songs they chose were
reflective, wistfully looking back on lost romances and offering a
maternal kind of love, directly in Sinead O'Connor's ``This Is to
Mother You'' and in ``The Sweetest Gift,'' a bluegrass chestnut.
The music clung to 1970s style, except for ``Sweet Spot,'' a song
by Ms. Harris and Jill Cunniff of Luscious Jackson that relies on a
terse bass riff. Most of the songs were steady-strummed folk-rock,
rising methodically from lone voice and guitar to stately full-band
arrangements; Ms. Ronstadt and Ms. Harris traded lead vocals and
sang self-effacing harmonies. They rocked, mostly, like a cradle.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the songs from ``Western Wall,'' like David Olney's
``1917'' (a French-cabaret-tinged song about a woman's night with a
doomed soldier) and Rosanne Cash's ``Western Wall,'' had a dulcet
grace. But too often, their determined cooperation and restraint
made the music too careful, with more effort expended on shaping
perfect syllables than in telling the songs' stories. The band held
back, too, sparking briefly in a speedy banjo solo by Bernie Leadon
and in hints of honky-tonk from Buddy Miller and Greg Leisz on
guitars.
</P>
<P>
   When Phoebe Snow stepped up for the last encore, she revealed
what the concert had lacked: a sense of risk and rivalry. Singing
``Bring It on Home to Me,'' Ms. Ronstadt swooped down to the melody
from above, and Ms. Snow set out to top her, whooping a few
gospelly phrases. Then they harmonized, having dared to cut loose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
