<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-BOOKSTORE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODWILL'S BOOKS-ONLY STORE WILL BE SECOND IN COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TOM BAYLES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Sarasota's newest bookstore stocks national
best sellers, including novels by Tom Clancy and Stephen King, all
with a deep discount.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not one of those new megastores, and there's no coffee
shop or reading room with comfy chairs. This scaled-down operation
comes from Goodwill Industries, where operating on a lean budget to
make a few bucks to help others is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people think of Goodwill, books are not the first thing
that come to mind,'' said Mary Lou England, manager of the new
Goodwill Centergate Bookstore. ``But if you need a Turkish-American
dictionary, we've got it.''
</P>
<P>
   The store, which will open Friday, is the second Goodwill store
in the country to be devoted entirely to books. The first store
opened in Lakeland, Fla., nearly seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The stock includes about 16,000 softcover and 2,000 hardcover
books. Each donated book is inspected, cleaned and shelved
according to category. Area Goodwill outlets have been sending all
of their books to the new location for two months, and nearly 300
titles are expected to arrive daily from collection sites
throughout Southwest Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Sarasota store is expected to raise $500,000 annually, which
will go toward Goodwill ManaSota's $8.5 million budget. The
nonprofit agency has 36 other retail outlets in Sarasota, Manatee,
Hardee and DeSoto counties that raise the bulk of the funds for its
programs. Goodwill teaches jobs skills, fosters educational
opportunities and helps people with physical and mental challenges
improve their housing conditions, among other programs.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
