<HEADLINE>
`FRONTLINE': PORTRAIT OF THE POPE, CONFRONTING THE TIDES OF
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday night's thoughtful ``Frontline'' portrait of John Paul II
presents the popular pope as a man resisting, in the name of the
church he leads, many of the century's movements of which he
despairs. He has been a triumphant force against Communism, a
somewhat embattled opponent of church reforms, particularly as they
might affect women, and a critic of capitalism run amok. In
powerful exhortations that sometimes cut across the usual
ideological lines, he has become the world's voice against what he
calls a prevailing ``culture of death,'' whether it be in the form
of capital punishment or abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Whitney, the producer of ``John Paul II: The Millennial
Pope,'' begins with sensitively evoked scenes of the Poland in
which Karol Wojtyla grew up and the religious traditions that in
time drew him to the priesthood. Anti-Semitism was prevalent, and
although the young man had many Jewish acquaintances, during the
Nazi occupation, says Arthur Hertzberg, a professor of Jewish
studies at New York University, ``He did not defy the Nazis in any
overt way,'' and did nothing to save their victims.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after the war he earned a reputation for helping Jews, and
as pope he has made several gestures, like declaring anti-Semitism
to be a sin, that suggest a recognition that his church had failed
during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Although the young priest remained apolitical when Poland was
dominated by the Soviet Union, he later added a forceful voice to
the anti-Communist Solidarity movement. His message to his
countrymen was, ``Be not afraid.'' Without his support of Poland's
nonviolent revolution, the program goes so far as to suggest, the
Soviet empire would not have collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   But his anti-Marxism also carried the day when it came to
dealing with despots in Latin America. He opposed liberation
theology among the Roman Catholic clergy and did what he could to
destroy that revolutionary movement and suppress its supporters.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly telling passage connects the pope's devotion to
the Virgin Mary with his steadfast opposition to birth control and
the ordination of women as priests. It is as though such changes in
the role of women offend his deeply held vision of the purity of
Mary.
</P>
<P>
   In his most important encyclical, ``The Gospel of Life,'' John
Paul II denounced not only contraception and abortion but also
euthanasia. In his dark vision abortion and capital punishment are
linked as the sins of a materialist culture that is willing to end
life for the convenience of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whitney concludes her otherwise illuminating biography with
the purported spiritual experiences of Robert Stone, Germaine
Greer, the cabaret singer Andrea Marcovicci and others. Whatever
one makes of them, they tell little about the Pope. but the rest of
these insightful and provocative two and a half hours easily make
up for that lapse.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FRONTLINE: John Paul II: The Millennial Pope'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday at 9 p.m. (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Helen Whitney, producer. Written by Ms. Whitney and Jane Barnes.
Ted Winterburn, editor; Will Lyman, narrator; Michael Sullivan,
executive producer; David Fanning, senior executive producer. A
Frontline co-production with Helen Whitney Productions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
