<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VOLS-CHEATING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT officials respond to ESPN report on possible violationsBy
Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tennessee will investigate a report that tutors wrote
papers and did other academic work for football players, athletics
director Doug Dickey said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the allegations are not proved, the school might
have violated NCAA rules by failing to follow procedures when the
possibility of academic fraud was raised.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN reported Sunday night that its Internet web site, ESPN.com,
had posted a copyrighted story detailing possible violations of the
Tennessee honor code and NCAA rules, dating back to 1995. ESPN's 11
p.m. ``SportsCenter'' show aired a version of the story, which was
based on confidential memos and a six-week investigation
</P>
<P>
   The story claimed that as many as five athletes and four tutors
were involved in situations that could constitute academic fraud.
The charges came from memos written by Robin Wright, a former
coordinator for academic programs. The charges range from tutors
writing papers for athletes to tutors actually going to the classes
and taking notes for Volunteer players. Wright has since Tennessee
and is working at Stephen F. Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the players involved in Wright's memos have left the
school, and at least two of the tutors were fired.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee officials learned about the ESPN story Saturday
morning, just hours before the Volunteers' game with Memphis. The
school then held redshirt freshmen Leonard Scott, Reggie Ridley,
Keyone Whiteside and Ryan Rowe out of the game, pending an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Head football coach Phillip Fulmer was not named in any of the
allegations. Fulmer said Monday he will defer comment to Dickey and
University president J. Wade Gilley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of facts right now, and, until we get
them, we have to do what's best for these young men and what's best
for the university,'' Dickey said. ``We have to deal with the
eligibility of these players in the short term and then we have to
turn our attention to the larger issue.''
</P>
<P>
   That larger issue is whether the claims in the ESPN piece are
true and whether they represent a more widespread problem of
academic fraud involving Tennessee athletes. Earlier this year, a
former tutor at Minnesota claimed she had written more than 400
papers for athletes. After an investigation, basketball coach Clem
Haskins was forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allegation is that some of this goes back three or four
years, which is something we can't deal with in a week,'' Dickey
said. ``We need some time to get all the information we need. Then
we will deal with the specifics of the allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the allegations are not proved, Tennessee still could be
in trouble with the NCAA. The ESPN story said that Wright sent
copies of all of her memos to Carmen Tegano, the school's assistant
athletic director of student life, but that the information never
was forwarded to Tennessee officials in charge of NCAA rules
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Malcolm McInnis, Tennessee's NCAA compliance officer,
nor Carl Asp, the faculty athletic representative, knew about the
situation until contacted by ESPN for the story. Dickey said he,
too, was not aware of the charges until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA requires that all alleged rules violations, no matter
how insignificant they might appear to be, be subject to specific
university reporting procedures.
</P>
<P>
   At Georgia, for example, all senior members of the athletics
staff must sign compliance forms stating that they have reported
all known violations to responsible university officials. In UGA's
case those officials are athletics director Vince Dooley, president
Michael Adams and Hoke Wilder, the assistant athletics director for
compliance and legislative services.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to send information on alleged rules violations up the
chain of command is in itself an NCAA violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very basic requirement at every school,'' said Wilder,
Georgia's compliance director since 1991. ``You have an obligation
to disclose and report any violation or potential violation. The
procedure has to be followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey said, ``If we had a procedure that broke down, then we'll
fix that procedure and move on. But right now, we don't know the
scope of what we're dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
