<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-2000-HNS &LR;      09-27 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENCY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN ISSUES `NEW PATRIOTIC CHALLENGE' IN ANNOUNCING RUN ATBy GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Conceding that his campaign will be an uphill
battle against money and the son of a former president, Republican
Sen. John McCain of Arizona officially opened his bid for the
presidency Monday, promising to restore dignity and honor to a
``corrupt'' national political system he described as ``a spectacle
of selfish ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   Issuing what he called ``a new patriotic challenge,'' McCain
called on Americans to join him in his crusade to overhaul campaign
finance laws and eliminate ``pork-barrel spending,'' which he said
has drained precious resources away from the nation's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, I won't ask how much security we can afford.
I'll ask, how much security do we need,'' said McCain, a former
Navy pilot who was shot down over North Vietnam and held prisoner
for 5 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will find the resources to pay for it. But I won't tolerate
one dime of our defense budget being wasted to re-elect
shortsighted politicians who put their own ambitions before the
national interest,'' McCain added in a reference to many of his
fellow lawmakers caught up in the quest for special interest money
to finance their political careers.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain has been the leading champion of eliminating
unlimited and unregulated ``soft money'' from the political system,
his repeated efforts to push campaign reform through Congress have
failed.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted Monday that the cause of reform must be won to
help restore Americans' faith in their government.
</P>
<P>
   McCain set his speech in Greeley Park, where John F. Kennedy
formally announced his run for the presidency 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized his positions on a host of issues, including his
support for education vouchers, preserving Social Security, free
trade, and giving tax cuts to low- and middle-income individuals
over corporations. But it was his hard-line stand against what he
called the corruption of the nation's political system through
campaign donations and for strengthening the nation's military that
roused the hearts of 500 of his supporters who showed up to cheer
his announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our government has been taken from us by the special
interests, the big-dollar donors, pride is lost to shame. When our
politics are corrupted by money and lies, trust is lost to
cynicism,'' McCain said to heavy applause. He declared the current
campaign finance system to be ``nothing more than a sophisticated
influence peddling scheme,'' where government is ``auctioned to the
highest bidder.'' The result, he said, is wasted spending that
drains precious resources from defense and other important
programs.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Americans to join him in reclaiming ``our
government'' from ``the power-brokers and special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our new patriotic challenge ... Restoring honesty to
our political system is the gateway through which all other policy
reforms must pass,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's announcement in New Hampshire, site of the nation's
first primary next year, was delivered shortly before former Vice
President Dan Quayle formally withdrew from the Republican
presidential contest. Quayle's departure narrows the Republican
field to eight, and could help McCain or other GOP hopefuls,
including Elizabeth Dole, in their effort to stop Texas Gov. George
W. Bush from steamrolling his way to the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has already raised $55 million and remains the preferred
choice among likely GOP voters in New Hampshire and most other
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But a Boston Globe poll last month showed McCain up from single
digits among New Hampshire Republicans to 16 percent against Bush's
40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky said the senator's ``challenge
now ... is to get better known, and that's what we're going to be
focusing our efforts on in the coming weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Nashua speech was the beginning of a four-day campaign
swing through the three states where he plans to focus his campaign
before the primary season begins early next year.
</P>
<P>
   But before climbing aboard his campaign plane Monday morning,
McCain visited his alma mater, the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis,
Md. Aides said he had breakfast there with 4,000 midshipmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began this day as I began my career of service to our nation
_ in the company of United States Naval Academy midshipmen,''
McCain told the Nashua crowd. ``There is no more appropriate place
for me to have begun this mission than Annapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the son and grandson of Navy admirals, did begin his
military and government service at the academy, where, he often
notes, he finished next to last in his class. He went on to become
a Navy flier in the Vietnam War. In 1969, on a bombing mission over
Hanoi, he was shot down and imprisoned until the end of the war.
McCain endured torture and refused an early release on several
occasions, adhering to the military's tradition of ``first in,
first out.''
</P>
<P>
   He won election to Congress in the early 1980s along with other
Reagan Republicans. He was elected to the Senate in 1986, where he
says the discipline and pride in country he learned as military
officer has guided his decisions as a lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on his military record, McCain sought in his speech to
distinguish himself from Bush, who served in the National Guard in
Texas. Although he did not mention Bush by name, he said no other
candidate running has been as well-prepared as he to assume the job
of commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a president makes life-and-death decisions he should draw
strength and wisdom from broad and deep experience with the reasons
for and risks of committing our children to our defense. I am not
afraid of the burden. I know both the blessing and the price of
freedom,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   And in a reference to President Clinton, McCain vowed to restore
dignity to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do everything in my power to make you proud of your
government,'' McCain said, adding that ``something has gone
terribly wrong'' when parents no longer want their children to grow
up to be president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
