<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-PROFILE-COX     09-27 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profile of Bill Bradley
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Bill Bradley joined the Senate in 1979 after
10 years with the New York Knicks, he turned down interview
requests that focused on his storied basketball career. Bradley
said he wanted to be known as a senator, not a basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he campaigns for president, Bradley usually works in one
or two jokes about his basketball playing days, particularly to
audiences in the Northeast where the Knicks-Boston Celtics rivalry
is hot.
</P>
<P>
   The stories help remind voters that Bradley was a star, and they
feed into the fascination that many voters have with the 6-foot-5
forward as he campaigns for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But hoop jokes aside, playing basketball helped transform
Bradley into a fierce competitor and a disciplined, focused
athlete. It made him rich and famous years before he entered
politics. Bradley also credits basketball with shaping many of his
views on life, especially on race relations in America.
</P>
<P>
   Tall for his age, Bradley enjoyed an immediate height advantage
when he began playing basketball in his hometown of Crystal City,
Mo. But it was his discipline and relentless devotion to practice
that made him the best player on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I took a shower, he'd be up there shooting, 10-15 shots
from different places on court,'' says Tom Haley, his former high
school teammate. ``He'd make them all before he quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had more than 70 scholarship offers from around the
country, but chose to attend Princeton, an Ivy League school.
</P>
<P>
   ``By physical standards, he was an average player, and yet he
was an all-American for three years,'' says Bill van Breda Kolff,
his former coach. It was all done by practice, practice, practice,
hard work and dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff says he told Bradley one year to stop using an
ineffective left hook shot. The next year, Bradley made sure van
Breda Kolff was watching during one of the first practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw in a lefty hook and it went right in,'' van Breda
Kolff says. ``And I said, `You must have worked on it all summer,'
and he said, `Yup.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's greatest knack, van Breda Kolff says, was his ability
to make his teammates play their best game, a talent that helped
him succeed in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not as big, not as strong, couldn't run as fast,
couldn't lift as many weights, but he was smarter, so smart about
the game,'' says van Breda Kolff.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was a member of the 1964 U.S. Olympic basketball team
that defeated the Soviets in Tokyo. He was featured extensively in
Sports Illustrated and was the subject of a book by John McPhee,
``A Sense of Where You Are.''
</P>
<P>
   He signed a $500,000 contract with the Knicks in 1967, a huge
sum for the time, and began his pro career with intense
expectations. His first two years were disappointing. Instead of
cheers, Bradley frequently was booed.
</P>
<P>
   Those two years seem to get lost among all the records Bradley
set and the championships he won. But he recalls them as among the
most difficult in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down awhile, because I was failing and people were
throwing coins at me and booing and spitting and accosting me on
the street,'' he says. ``It wasn't a pleasant time.''
</P>
<P>
   All the early hype was tough for Bradley, says Willis Reed, his
former Knick teammate. ``He did not want all the limelight,'' Reed
says. ``I think he kind of wanted to live his own life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won the NBA championship in 1970 and 1973, and
Bradley was inducted into the Basketball Hall of Fame in 1982, his
first year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, writing about his basketball days, Bradley said his
experience with the Knicks made him more sensitive to racial
inequality in America. He turned down product endorsements, because
he felt they were coming to him instead of his more talented black
teammates because he was white.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, however, shared none of these views with his teammates
at the time, says Reed. ``There was no indication of that,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone on the team, however, joked that Bradley would one day
become president, calling him ``Mr. President'' and demanding White
House jobs when he got elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always used to say I want one of those no-show jobs,'' says
Reed. ``But he was always reserved and would kind of blush a little
bit about it. He said to me that he didn't know what he wanted to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
