A7992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TUTU-COX     09-27 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUTU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To forgive is divinely human, Tutu tells youths
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Archbishop Desmond Tutu looked into the rows of young
faces and saw a powerful army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people are among God's greatest collaborators,'' the
Nobel Laureate told students at Holy Innocents' Episcopal School in
Atlanta Monday. ``God has a dream of a society that is kind and
gentle. God has no one except you to help accomplish that dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, the former Anglican archbishop of South Africa and a
visiting professor at Emory University, talked about the horrors of
apartheid, intolerance and violence in society. Yet his address was
uplifting, interwoven with humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knock-knock,'' he said, beginning his story of the immaculate
conception of Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's there?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabriel, the archangel. Hi, Mary. God would like you to be the
mother of his son.''
</P>
<P>
   His eyes twinkling, Tutu continued with Mary's response.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? You want me to be what? An unmarried mother? Sorry, I'm
a decent girl. Try next door.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu's slight frame shook with laughter, but the lighthearted
story had a serious point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that had been the response of Mary, we would have been up a
creek,'' he said. ``Mary was a teenager. It is interesting how we
see God looking to young people for those who would be God's
special partners. God looks to you.''
</P>
<P>
   In his role as chairman of South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission, Tutu said he was ``quite shattered at
the awfulness of evil human beings can visit upon other human
beings.'' But he was also moved at victims' ability to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the testimony of the daughter of a murdered
activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her whether she might have it in her to forgive,'' he
said. ``You could have heard a pin drop as this woman said, `Yes,
we would like to forgive. We need to know who to forgive.' If we
are to have reconciliation and forgiveness in South Africa, it is
going to be because people who have suffered are willing to be
magnanimous and forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that racial strife in the United States will never be
obliterated without similar forums where people can share their
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it is traumatic to open those wounds that appear to be
healed,'' Tutu said. ``We thought it was important that those
wounds be opened, cleansed, and a balm put on those wounds so this
time when those wounds heal, they will not be festering.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu told the students they have important roles in making the
world better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes there may be a bully on the playground,'' Tutu said.
``God doesn't usually send a lightning bolt to dispense the bully.
He depends on some of you to stand up to that bully.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu told the students to think happy thoughts and closed with a
prayer. After his remarks, students surrounded Tutu. He shook their
hands and blessed them and looked delighted to be in the midst of
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great fun, aren't they?'' Tutu said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Brett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
