<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON UNVEILS ESTIMATED $115 BILLION BUDGET SURPLUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton unveiled a projected $115 billion
surplus Monday, hailing it as a ``landmark achievement'' and
calling on Congress to work with him on Social Security, Medicare
and a modest middle-class tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The new estimate, which would be the largest in history, likely
will be revised again by the Office of Management and Budget after
the 1999 fiscal year ends Thursday. The previous estimate was $99
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The White House sought to use the new financial figure to
underscore its budget battle with Congress. The Republican
leadership has shown no indication of working with Clinton since
the president last week vetoed the GOP's $792 billion tax cut bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a landmark achievement for our economy,'' Clinton said
of the nation's first back-to-back budget surplus since 1957.
``When you consider where we were just seven years ago, it's as
great an American comeback as the Ryder Cup was,'' he said,
referring to the U.S. victory over European golfers Sunday . ``It
is further proof that we're on the right road to prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lower debt service costs helped lead to the higher projected
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on Congress to work with him to extend the life
of Social Security by 32 years to 2050, to bolster the solvency of
Medicare and provide a prescription drug component. He also wants
investments in education, the environment and agriculture and to
provide incentives for economic development in rural and urban
areas overlooked by the nation's thriving economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do all that and still have an affordable tax cut for
the middle class and pay down our debt so that by 2015, we are
debt-free for the first time since 1835 when Andrew Jackson was
president,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again asked Congress ``not to throw in the towel'' but
to negotiate with the White House and congressional Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, continued to press Clinton on the issue of tax cuts.
Archer, R-Texas, championed the $792 billion, 10-year tax relief
bill that the president dismissed as ``too big and too bloated''
and a danger to the nation's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``More surplus money for Washington means less money for
families and workers across our country, and tax relief is the only
way to balance the scales,'' Archer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``But since President Clinton killed tax relief, Republicans
will guard these funds to protect Social Security and Medicare and
pay down the debt - and stop Washington from spending them on a
smorgasbord of government programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The president announced the revised budget estimate during a
Rose Garden ceremony in which he wrote the new figure on a chart as
cameras whirled. Clinton told reporters he remained optimistic
about negotiating a budget agreement that addressed many of his
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or the other the taxpayers are going to be all right,
because we can do pretty well by conflict, I suppose, and
eventually drag this out to where we've at least got a decent
education budget and we're still paying down the debt,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton added that if the nation is going to address
other important issues, such as extending the life of Social
Security and Medicare, then the Republican leadership must work
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still plenty of time to do this and I hope they'll do
it with me,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress this week will work on a resolution to keep government
operating after the 2000 fiscal year begins on Friday. A temporary
spending measure will give Congress time to complete work on the 13
appropriations bills that fund the government.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also issued a press statement decrying the House
appropriation subcommittee's work on the spending bill for the
Departments of Labor, Health and Human Services and Education.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said the Republican bill ``would devastate
critical investments in education and training and other
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want to eliminate many specific federal programs
such as Clinton's plan to place 100,000 new teachers in the
classrooms, place the program money into block grants and allow
states to decide how to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   While campaigning later for Rep. Bill Jefferson, a Democratic
candidate for governor in Louisiana, Clinton blasted Republicans
over their education measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wrong to blame the kids and it's wrong not to give the
schools a chance,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MUSEUM-OFILI-ART-2NDT     09-27 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-OFILI-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: kill people.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This fall is to be a big moment for Ofili in the United States.
He has been chosen as one of the 41 artists whose work will be
shown in the Carnegie International, a survey of contemporary art
that opens at the Carnegie Museum of Art in Pittsburgh on Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 16 Brown is mounting a second show of Ofili's work, five
new paintings that are together being called ``Afrobiotics.''
</P>
<P>
   Ofili said he was concerned about his notoriety. ``I find it
off-putting that people judge you before they know you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While he liked being included in ``Sensation,'' he said he
worried about being seen as one of the Young British Artists and
not as an individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see me as part of a package,'' he said. ``It scares
me.''
</P>
<P>
   During an interview in his London studio in August, Ofili worked
on two paintings at once. The larger of the two was of a character
he calls ``magic monkey'' holding up an empty turquoise vessel. He
said the monkey was trying to capture the three powerful elements
of life: sex, money and drugs, which are represented by three
separate clumps of elephant dung bearing the three words formed out
of straight pins with colored tops that he buys at his local
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   The painting's surface was thick with beads of paint applied
with a thin stick that is actually a brush that has no hairs on it.
Using the kinds of aluminum containers that Chinese takeout food
comes in, Ofili mixed the paint to a consistency he described as
cream. He spread layer upon layer of glitter, besides the painted
dots. On top of that he applied coats of translucent resin to give
the surface a transparency.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's to make it seem that in some ways it's more imagined
than real,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room was another painting, its background
three-quarters finished. Ofili applied large black and white
spirals with a thin brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I roughly know what I'm doing,'' he said, moving from
the magic monkey to the black spirals. ``It might be a female
portrait. I need a princesslike figure.''
</P>
<P>
   He likened the process to writing a song. ``You know the
lyrics,'' he said. ``Then you want to get the right rhythm and base
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the entrance to his London studio that day, several
teen-agers huddled together smoking crack. Above their heads was a
sign warning, ``This area is being constantly watched and patrolled
by the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Ofili said he made the sign because he wanted the addicts who
regularly used his doorway to think about what they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up a Catholic and was an altar boy,'' he said.
``I believe in God, but I'm not dominated by it. We all studied
math, but we don't go around spewing numbers. Religion should be
used in the appropriate way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is not made up of one person but a whole
congregation, and they should be able to interact with art without
being told what to think,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about control,'' he added. ``We've seen it before
in history. Sadly, I thought we'd moved on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
