<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PROJECTS RECORD SURPLUS, BUT U.S. DEBT CONTINUES TO
CLIMB
 &HT;    500&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government will post a record $115
billion budget surplus this year, President Clinton estimated
Monday, thanks mainly to a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of last year's $69 billion surplus, the
performance for the 1999 fiscal year _ which ends Thursday _ marks
the first time since 1957 that the federal government has balanced
its books two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a landmark achievement,'' Clinton told reporters at the
White House. ``It is further proof that we're on the right road to
prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   But behind the rosy talk, the government remains, strictly
speaking, in the red.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called surplus includes payments workers made into the
Social Security program, money that by law cannot be used for other
government programs. Not counting money from Social Security _
which ran a sizable surplus this year _ the government still spent
roughly $4 billion more than it took in, according to the latest
Congressional Budget Office estimates.
</P>
<P>
   And the federal debt piled up during a generation of budget
deficits _ a whopping $5.6 trillion _ continues to grow. Clinton
inherited a $4.4 trillion debt when he took office in 1993; the
government hadn't been in the black since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The debt is projected to continue rising to as much as $5.7
trillion next year.
</P>
<P>
   It's an expensive problem. Servicing the debt is one of the
largest single expenses in the federal budget. It cost taxpayers
roughly $235 billion in interest payments this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is not awash in excess cash,'' said Robert Bixby,
policy director for the Concord Coalition, a Washington think tank
focused on budget issues. ``They still have a way to go before they
can balance the budget without getting into the Social Security
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton isn't the only one touting good fiscal times.
Congressional Republicans said Monday that the surplus provided
more evidence to support their call for tax cuts. Clinton last week
vetoed a $792 billion GOP tax cut package, claiming that the plan
would put future budgets at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by one of the strongest economic booms in history, the
government balance sheet has been moving in the right direction
since Clinton took office.
</P>
<P>
   The year before that, the budget deficit hit a record $290
billion. More red ink was projected.
</P>
<P>
   This year's numbers are decidedly better, owing to continuing
growth in an economy that has expanded by 40 percent since Clinton
first took office.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment down and more Americans working than ever
before, income tax receipts are up, as are the fees and taxes that
businesses pay on their swelling profits and expanding activities.
</P>
<P>
   Government spending continues to increase. Spending this year
alone is up some $55 billion over 1998 levels _ but revenues grew
faster.
</P>
<P>
   The result: this year the government took in roughly $115
billion more than it spent_ a turnaround of $404 billion as
compared with the 1992 ledger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's unquestionably good news for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``By balancing the budget, we put in motion a virtuous cycle of
budget surpluses, low interest rates and low unemployment,''
Clinton said. ``For business, this makes it easier to invest, to
create jobs, wealth and opportunity. And for working people, lower
interest rates makes it easier to own a home, afford a car, send a
child to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years into the economic expansion, however, the deficit
dragon has yet to be slain.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress views budget matters, folding Social Security into
the overall calculus is mixing apples and oranges.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction goes beyond accounting jargon.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Social Security is essentially a government-run
insurance program, providing retirement payments to workers who pay
premiums during the years they're employed. Congress treats that
differently from taxes paid to fund government programs such as
defense, highways, education or foreign affairs. Lawmakers have
erected something of a fiscal firewall between Social Security and
other government programs.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Social Security program will take in an estimated
$125 billion more in premiums than it will pay out in retirement
checks, according to a CBO report issued Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   That's the source of the surplus Clinton crowed about on Monday.
Strip it out and the budget remains well into deficit territory.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Office of Management and Budget differs slightly
with the CBO on such estimates. Using CBO numbers, however, the
government remains $4 billion in deficit this year, if the Social
Security surplus isn't included.
</P>
<P>
   That money is being counted on to fund a rising tide of Social
Security benefit checks once the Baby Boomer generation begins
retiring en masse a dozen years from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Social Security surplus is really supposed to be used
like a savings account,'' said Bixby. ``We shouldn't be using it to
pay our grocery bills.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
