<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LOBBYIST SAYS HE CALLED GUARD ON BUSH'S BEHALF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
and STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin lobbyist Ben Barnes said Monday that as
speaker of the Texas House more than 30 years ago, he recommended
George W. Bush for a pilot's position in the Texas Air National
Guard at the request of a Bush family friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes, in a statement issued by his lawyer, said he was not
contacted by a member of the Bush family and had ``no knowledge''
that either the future governor or his father, former President
Bush, who was then a congressman from Houston, knew of his
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether Gov. Bush received preferential
treatment in securing a National Guard spot to avoid going to
Vietnam during the Southeast Asian conflict has surfaced in Bush's
presidential race. The governor joined the Guard in 1968, at the
height of the war, and served until 1973 as an F-102 pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has repeatedly denied that he joined the Guard to avoid the
draft or that his family intervened on his behalf at a time when
many young men seeking Guard slots in Texas found long waiting
lists.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated those denials Monday during an appearance in
Brazoria County to announce a land conservation initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Ben Barnes did or not, but he was not asked by
me or my dad,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also noted that Houston oilman Sidney A. Adger, the Bush
family friend whom Barnes said contacted him, is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' role in helping Bush was raised in a federal lawsuit
filed against Gtech, the company that operates the Texas Lottery,
by former lottery director Lawrence Littwin.
</P>
<P>
   Littwin, who was dismissed as lottery director in 1997, contends
Gtech, for whom Barnes used to lobby, was responsible for his
firing. And, according to court records, Littwin's lawyers wanted
to question Barnes about whether Gtech was allowed to keep its
lucrative state contract in exchange for Barnes' silence about
helping Bush get into the Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, a former Democratic Texas House speaker and lieutenant
governor who was once considered presidential material himself
until he lost a 1972 race for governor, was questioned by lawyers
in the Littwin-Gtech suit for more than five hours at his Austin
office Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes did not speak with reporters afterward, but his lawyer,
Charles Burton, issued a written statement on Barnes' behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said Barnes answered all the questions in the deposition
but could not discuss his answers because of a federal judge's
confidentiality order. But, he added, the order did not prevent
Barnes from ``setting the media record straight on events occurring
more than 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Burton's statement, Barnes was ``contacted by Sid
Adger and asked to recommend George W. Bush for a pilot position
with the Air National Guard. Barnes called General Rose and did
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. James Rose, who also has since died, was in charge of
the Air National Guard at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither congressman Bush nor any other member of the Bush
family asked Barnes' help,'' Burton's statement continued. ``Barnes
has no knowledge that Governor Bush or President Bush knew of
Barnes' recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer also said that Barnes met with Don Evans, a longtime
friend of the governor and his chief presidential fund-raiser, and
told him of Adger's request in September 1998, when the governor
was running for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush wrote Barnes a note thanking him for his candor
in acknowledging that Barnes received no call from any member of
the Bush family,'' the statement added.
</P>
<P>
   Evans told The Associated Press that he met with Barnes on his
own initiative, without informing Bush in advance. At the time,
Evans was Bush's gubernatorial campaign chairman and was concerned
only about any potential effect on the re-election race.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are relying on whether a man who is deceased tried to
help, and I can just tell you from my perspective, I never asked
for (and) I don't believe I received any special treatment,'' Bush
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Any allegation that my dad asked for special favors
is simply not true. The former president of the United States has
said that he in no way, shape or form helped me get into the Guard,
and I didn't ask anybody to help me get in the Guard either.''
</P>
<P>
   Any accusations to the contrary are ``just politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
