<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S FORTUNES SOARING, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Growing diversity in Boston's population has coincided
with an economic renaissance that has lifted the fortunes of its
black and white populations, according to a study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, the Boston area was predominantly a white community,
with a small black population. Three decades later, after a period
in which the city was torn apart by a controversy over race and
busing, the minority population in the Boston area has jumped to 41
percent amid a historic influx of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty, housing shortages, and wage disparities continue to
affect many of the city's minority residents, according to a report
released Monday by Barry Bluestone, professor of political economy
at Northeastern University, and Mary Huff Stevenson, professor of
economics at the University of Massachusetts at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But with unemployment at new lows amid a high-tech and financial
services boom, the report found that members of minority groups in
Boston, particularly blacks, have fared much better than those in
other large US cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is stunning about Boston is how quickly this history of
decline and distress has been reversed,'' Bluestone and Stevenson
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is rare to find the wholesale deprivation and hopelessness
that describe large parts of Detroit, Gary, Philadelphia, Los
Angeles, or Chicago,'' the authors said.
</P>
<P>
   The study was released at an economic summit on the Boston
campus of Northeastern University as US Labor Secretary Alexis
Herman stressed the need to close the yawning wage gap that exists
between college-educated workers and high school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   College graduates once earned about 30 percent more than those
without a degree, who tend to be disproportionately drawn from
minority groups. That gap has widened to 71 percent ``and it is
growing,'' said Herman, who attended the summit with US Senator
Edward M. Kennedy and Mayor Thomas M. Menino.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is particularly acute in cities such as Boston that
are enjoying an economic boom due to a large presence of
knowledge-based industries, she said. ``We don't have a worker
shortage in this country, but we do have a skills shortage.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such problems, Boston fared better than many other
metropolitan areas. Its economic renaissance has lifted the
fortunes of some minority residents, according to the five-year
economic study, ``Greater Boston in Transition,'' which was based
on surveys of 128,000 families.
</P>
<P>
   The metropolitan area had the fastest-growing family income
during the 1980s, and the income gains ``have not been restricted
to white families,'' the study noted. For example, household
incomes of blacks rose 40.2 percent during the decade, the fastest
of any urban black population in the United States, according to a
1996 report cited in study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been absolutely an amazing turnaround, and it has
turned around so fast,'' Bluestone said.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty is high in Boston, with the city ranking 32d among US
cities. But less than a quarter of the city's black population is
in poverty, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   What has kept overall poverty high in Boston is the fact that a
third of Hispanic and Asian residents fall below the poverty line,
the report said. White poverty is 14 percent in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Bluestone also said that one of the most surprising results of
the study was that the labor participation rate among blacks,
whites, and Hispanics is the same. But, he added, ``we still have
large earnings gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   High poverty rates, low wages, and soaring housing costs have
been particularly burdensome for new immigrants, which have
accounted for much of the sharp rise in the city's minority
population. Bluestone said one family's rents in a Roxbury
apartment rose from $450 a month to $800 in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the standards of the countries they left, they are doing
well,'' the study said. ``By the standards of their newly adopted
home, they are impoverished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
