<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-ADULTS-NYT &LR;      09-27 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ADULTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ADULTS, A FRISSON: TV SHOWS FOR GROWN-UPS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ ``Hallelujah! Forty-year-olds are sexy!''
</P>
<P>
   The exuberance of Stuart Bloomberg, co-chairman of the ABC
Entertainment Group, is probably overstated. After all, the new
series he was talking about, ``Once and Again,'' about divorced
middle-aged people who find one another, appeared last week on
television only for the first time as the new season began.
</P>
<P>
   But what seemed evident, at least early on, was that the
overabundance of teen-age and ``let's-share-an-apartment in New
York'' television shows was being challenged by some grown-up
series that seek to appeal to _ perish the thought _ viewers over
30.
</P>
<P>
   In their initial week, such series as ABC's ``Once and Again''
as well as NBC's ``West Wing,'' about the White House staff, and
CBS's ``Judging Amy,'' starring Amy Brenneman (``N.Y.P.D. Blue'')
as a judge who is also dealing with her bossy mother (Tyne Daly),
have lured large television audiences despite the absence of the
kind of 20-something angst that dominates many shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is obviously a hunger on the part of audiences that
might have felt ignored,'' said Ed Zwick, who created ``Once and
Again'' with his partner, Marshall Herskovitz. The critically
acclaimed show gave ABC its highest rated drama premiere since
1995, when Steven Bochco's ``Murder One'' began.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moonves, president and chief executive of CBS Television,
put it another way. ``The fascination with youth, as everything on
network television, is probably overdone this season,'' he said.
``And some of the shows that appeal to baby boomers suddenly have a
great deal more appeal than Madison Avenue first thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves' network deliberately courts older viewers, giving it
often hefty ratings. But advertisers, seeking youth audiences, have
not been as enthusiastic as viewers in seeking out such CBS shows.
``We're going a different road,'' Moonves conceded. ``The shows
that are glorifying the 18-year-old will cancel each other out and
will not appeal to a broad enough audience to work on network
television. They're fine for niche programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Even creators of some of the more successful new shows appealing
to adults were cautious about the early results. ``We've been on a
first date, and we're looking forward to a second date,'' said
Aaron Sorkin, creator of ``The West Wing,'' whose audience ``skewed
fairly old,'' according to Variety and was especially popular in
larger markets like New York and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Sorkin said: ``I'd be very cautious about calling this an
early success. It's a surprise, a terrific surprise. For me, I'm
always a little surprised when someone other than my mother and
father watch one of my shows.'' (The show's premiere drew 16.9
million viewers.)
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not all the new series appealing to older audiences
fared as well as ``Once and Again'' and ``The West Wing.'' Some of
the initial disappointments included Fox's cutting-edge series
``Action,'' about an out-of-control Hollywood producer, ABC's ``Oh
Grow Up,'' about men sharing an apartment in Brooklyn, and ABC's
``Mike O'Malley Show,'' about a still-adolescent 30-year-old man
who realizes he has to change his ways.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Berger, executive vice president at International Creative
Management and a television agent, said that while highly
anticipated and well-reviewed shows like ``Once and Again'' and
``West Wing'' were first-rate, it was probably a bit early to make
judgments about the success and failure of the new programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of these and some other shows got off to a good start
because they're well done,'' Berger said. ``But overall, people
were just hungry for new shows, hungry for the new network season.
It's been a long summer and people were ready to get back to seeing
new shows on television.''
</P>
<P>
   But some television executives saw deeper meaning in the notion
that some television series, with older actors, had struck a nerve.
Especially ``Once and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful that there's a successful drama out there about
a relationship that's not just the domain of 20-somethings,'' said
Bloomberg, who is 50.
</P>
<P>
   His partner, 40-year-old Lloyd Braun, co-chairman of the ABC
Entertainment Television Group, said: ``This really gives you hope
that there's a broad audience out there who will come to a show
that does break a few of the established rules about what people
will watch. There are people in their 40s, or older, who can be
romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   To executives and writers, the network's near-obsession with
youth shows has threatened to turn into a self-fulfilling prophecy:
As shows aimed at younger audiences proliferate, older audiences
drift off to cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain blindness out here: If something is
successful, everybody tries to copy it,'' said Alan Ball, who wrote
the film ``American Beauty'' and created the ABC series ``Oh Grow
Up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What may be happening now is encouraging,'' he said. ``I'm 42.
I'd rather watch television shows I relate to than shows about
teen-agers, most of whose problems seem insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that television's obsession with youth would hardly
disappear anytime soon. ``I have a friend, an actor in his late
30s, who's on a new show and plays the venerable old senior
partner,'' Ball said with a laugh. ``He's not old at all but the
rest of the cast is, like, 17-year-old models. It's absurd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
