<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A PLACE FOR PERSONAL PEACE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest problem with getting into the routine of daily
meditation, writes Berkeley's  &UR; Oscar London &LR;  of healthcentral.com,
is finding a place to do it. Office and home are accessible by
telephone, not peaceful enough.
</P>
<P>
   A nearby hospital, however, has a ``small, nondenominational
chapel which would be perfect, except that I have to share it with
people who use the sanctuary of the chapel to cheat on their diets.
These closet gluttons huddle in the darkest corner of the chapel
and painstakingly unwrap their candy bars and Doritos Nacho Cheese
Chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deafening crinkle of paper drowns out my mantra. Even God
cannot hear the prayers of the few devout chapelgoers through all
that crackly static.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Readers in search of a more serene way of life may turn to
Natural Health magazine, which suggests the following aids to
Mother Nature:
</P>
<P>
   The battery-operated Oralgiene Electric Tongue Cleaner, $20 to
$30; UltraScent Quattro Aroma Diffuser, that changes scents ``with
the flick of a switch,'' $49.95; Color Investment Cosmetics Feng
Shui makeup, including a $45 kit with eye shadow, blush and
lipstick; and the $24.95 No Danger Electromagnetic Mobile Phone
Shield, purported to prevent electromagnetic fields ``from entering
through the ear canal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DRESSING WELL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ What's it like to work at a snazzy fashion magazine? New York
magazine says that at  &UR; Anna Wintour &LR; 's Vogue, lower-level employees
are forbidden to talk to top-level editors unless they are spoken
to first. And the New York Post reports that  &UR; Kate &LR; 
 &UR; Betts &LR; , who jumped from Vogue to follow the late  &UR; Liz Tilberis &LR;  as
editor of Harper's Bazaar, has brutally fired staff members deemed
faithful to her predecessor, &LR;  and castigated the rest for such
crimes as decorating their cubicles with family pictures, ``like a
sorority.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Now praise famous people not so jaded that they don't get a
kick out of being famous: Designer  &UR; Geoffrey Beene &LR;  was so pleased
with getting his name in the New York Times crossword puzzle that
he faxed copies to his pals, including  &UR; Carole Shorenstein Hays &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Eat your heart out if you've watched the trends and tossed
away your faded jeans in order to wear brand-new, dark blue, raw
denim. The menswear journal DNR says that ``Spring will highlight
the softer side of jeans, with heavily abraded finishes ... for a
vintage look.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MISSING LINK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sharp-eyed readers have been sending clips from the Marin
Independent Journal police log, amusing but too numerous to use. To
thicken the plot, players are asked to link events. For example,
these two were cited by  &UR; Adrienne Biggs &LR;  and  &UR; Vicky &LR; 
 &UR; Cunningham &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   _ A pair of ruby earrings and a machete were found in a Novato
motel room on the morning of September 15. Police placed them
``into property.''
</P>
<P>
   _ That same afternoon, a Sausalito resident ``called police upon
finding a portable toilet blocking his driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   Were these random crimes or was there some insidious link?
</P>
<P>
   Threatened by her machete-waving lover in the course of an
argument over whether to watch ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' or ``Maury,'' the
Porta-Potti delivery woman tore off the ruby earrings (``Take Back
Your Mink'') he'd given her, told him to get the heck out of the
motel room, &LR;  and went back to work so angry that she dumped her
cargo in his driveway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BROKAW IN BERLIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, Va., after the showing of a video of the fall of
the Berlin Wall in conjunction with a Freedom Forum exhibition on
the topic, former NBC president  &UR; Michael Gartner  &LR; dissed its
portrayal of newsman  &UR; Tom Brokaw &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``That was wonderful,'' Gartner said of the video. ``But if it
ever gets on the best-seller list, I don't know if it should be in
the nonfiction or fiction category.'' Gartner said that he and  &UR; Tim
Russert &LR;  had persuaded Brokaw to go to Berlin, after the anchor's
initial hesitance to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw told the Washington Post he was ``surprised'' by his
former boss's &LR;  statement. ``Anybody who knows me knows that I've
never had to be kicked out of my chair to cover a big story.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a horrific lesson to learn, but boys are smarter than
you think. ... If they live in a house where inappropriate
scratching is tolerated, they will go on scratching themselves for
the rest of their lives. These are simple truths and no mother's
tears can change them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Child-rearing advice from John Bridges, author of ``How to Be
a Gentleman'' (Rutledge Hill; $12.95 cq), in Traditional Home
magazine. Bridges mentions in the story that he lives alone and
doesn't have any children.
</P>
</TEXT>
