<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8033 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FIDELITY-ONLINE-BOS &LR;      09-27 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY TURNS TO LYCOS TO SPIFF UP ONLINE INVESTING ARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a bold move that reflects a growing trend among
Web-based brokerages to offer information on just about everything
under the sun, Fidelity Investments has given its burgeoning online
investing service a makeover through an alliance with Lycos Inc.,
the Internet portal company.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, the nation's biggest mutual fund firm, joins a pack of
competitors in betting that cyberinvestors want sports scores and
weather reports as well as stock quotes and financial data.
</P>
<P>
   Under a deal announced Monday, Fidelity customers can use Lycos
to create personalized Web pages that display their investment
portfolios alongside links to Web sites on everything from health
and travel to sports and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have long been able to trade stocks on line at
Fidelity, whose discount brokerage, which includes a Web-based
unit, is the nation's second largest.
</P>
<P>
   But starting next month, investors can use their Lycos-fashioned
pages to trade stocks directly from their Fidelity accounts while
keeping tabs on, for example, the latest hurricane. The all-in-one
page, aimed at investors who trade often, makes Fidelity the latest
electronic bazaar, with a potpourri of information and data. Lycos'
dozens of directories have links to scores of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Fidelity's revamped Web brokerage, now called Powerstreet,
comes at a time of fierce competition for the pockets of a trader
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is going head-to-head with Charles Schwab and Co.,
which in May launched a similar service with Excite, a leading
Internet portal that competes with Lycos, of Waltham, Mass. ETrade
Group Inc., an online-only brokerage, also offers personalized
investor pages.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-changing world of on-line investing has jolted
traditional Wall Street brokerages and forced other financial
services firms to come up with new strategies fast.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's ``product is clearly designed to encourage active
trading, and is targeted to what investors are likely to look like
in the future,'' said James Lowell, editor of Fidelity Investor, an
independent newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Lured by the do-it-yourself ethic, bargain-basement trading
prices, and a record bull stock market, about 12.5 percent of all
US investors now buy and sell stocks on line _ a figure expected to
quadruple in the next two years. The trend has brought products and
services once reserved for professionals into the homes of ordinary
investors and spawned a sub-culture that is increasingly
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   At Fidelity, customers now conduct nearly four in five stock
trades through the firm's online brokerage. Fidelity is most
interested in keeping its active traders _ those who buy and sell
securities at least 36 times a year _ on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is becoming more central to the way we serve our
customers,'' said Gary Burkhead, who heads Fidelity's brokerage
services, adding that the company was making ``very major
investments'' to develop its Internet capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Kobren, who publishes the independent Fidelity Insight
newsletter, speculated that Fidelity was less able to attract
active traders than Web-only brokerages such as ETrade because of
its image as a mainstream fund firm. By keeping the Fidelity name
off Powerstreet, he said, the firm might draw new customers more
easily.
</P>
<P>
   Kobren also said privately held Fidelity might be tempted to one
day spin off its online brokerage as a publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity and Lycos declined to discuss the financial terms of
their deal. Fidelity did not say when it would start charging
customers for the Lycos service, which for now is free.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, the arrangement will benefit Lycos, now the
third-largest portal service, by leading scores of wealthy Fidelity
investors to Lycos' sites and advertising. Fidelity, whose mutual
fund assets total $849 billion, and whose brokerage assets are
around $455 billion, will include Lycos' name and logo in a blitz
of advertising for Powerstreet.
</P>
<P>
   Powerstreet, which is accessible through Fidelity's Web site,
fidelity.com, will offer free Nasdaq Level 2 quotes _ live buy and
sell prices, and a hot commodity for individual investors _ next
month. It will also provide customers access to CBS'
Marketwatch.com, a financial Web site. Fidelity already provides
corporate research from Lehman Brothers, the investment bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
