<HEADER>
A8047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LONDON-FASHION-ART-NY     09-27 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LONDON, THE REBELS FIND THEIR CAUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With some pride, British fashion designers used to be
the most commercially inept in the world. They were too wayward and
eccentric to do much more than, in effect, blow marvelous soap
bubbles across the water at the French and the Italians, who
instantly exploited their playpen ideas. And even now, one can't
say that John Galliano and Alexander McQueen are bona fide English
successes, since their money comes from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   So there was something very ironic about going to a show last
week in the East End here and seeing a Polish immigrant named
Arkadius Weremczuk, who already is a minor star even though he just
finished design school, pretend to be giving birth on a stage
spotlighted with the logo of his corporate sponsor, Ebel, the Swiss
watchmaker. And Ebel wasn't in it strictly for art's sake. When a
model who had been lying under a sheet for most of the show rose up
and began wobbling like a new lamb _ well, you could see that in
addition to being covered in body paint, she had a wristwatch on.
</P>
<P>
   Ebel wasn't the only company putting its name and money behind
the London spring 2000 collections, which ended on Friday. A lot of
designers had corporate sponsors _ Topshop, Marks &AMP; Spencer _ or at
least they had sacks of corporate goodies to give out. ``Official
deodorant!'' chimed a trio of women in the rain outside the Jasper
Conran show.
</P>
<P>
   What with the roll-on, the logos and the softening rain, it
didn't seem like London at all, but rather the infield of a
Southern stock car raceway fluttering with Coca-Cola banners.
</P>
<P>
   One can argue that British designers need sponsors, because
otherwise many could not afford to have shows. Yet, the presence of
so much corporate swag, as the British put it, seemed to heighten
the banality of many presentations. It's one thing if you are as
boldly original as Hussein Chalayan, who put on one of the best
shows seen  &UR; anywhere &LR;  in the last few years, or as gloriously
nonconformist as Boudicca, which showed laced white leather with
Flash Gordon pantaloons, crash helmets and strangely bulbous
footwear.
</P>
<P>
   Those designers have such an instinctive need to tweak the
Establishment _ which, after all, is what has kept London fashion
swinging for 40 years _ that you can't imagine anything really
affecting them. But for newcomers like Anthony Symonds or even
Elspeth Gibson, who owns a store and has a following, the perky
attempts to make the London collections seem commercially with-it
just had the effect of reducing their shows to nice, homogeneous
balls of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the better shows were away from the official tent in
South Kensington, or off the schedule altogether. Preen, which is
designed by Justin Thornton and Thea Bregazzi, cleverly mixed
prissy dotted swiss with its signature ragged leather and caught
the wave for girlish clothes with their baby rompers and puckered
strapless tops. Luella Bartley, a former British Vogue editor, put
across a similar look one night in Notting Hill. Cosmopolitans were
served, people got drunk, and some models pranced around in rompers
and campy versions of ladylike town-and-country shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Smith went to a garden in Chelsea. This was the bookish,
posh England of Lawrence (T.E. and D.H.), with models in Turkish
slippers traipsing about in caftans and crisp men's shirts wrapped
with vivid sarongs. It was a lovely idyll, modern in its
uncomplicated use of the past, and now and then on the soundtrack
there was a drowsy meadow hum of insects and English motorbikes.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Williamson went abroad, too, with a collection he called
Exotikarma. It was neither. A reprise of familiar shapes, like
beaded cashmere shells, long flounced skirts and coin-embellished
tops, it was all colored in a predictable sari palette. Williamson
knows how to put together a cool, worldly mix, but this time it
didn't say ``open sesame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clements Ribeiro show was disappointing. Colors were fresh _
buttercup, pistachio mixed with chocolate, natural linen spritzed
with big rainbow paillettes. But a program-note promise of ``a more
complex femininity'' yielded blouselike strapless tops and
voluminous halter dresses that might be endearing _ to pregnant
women.
</P>
<P>
   In her notes, Tracey Boyd described a regenerated Eve on a
``fruitful encounter with her sexuality.'' That was just a sly way
of Ms. Boyd having fun. She has a knack for taking fabrics like
lacquered lace and dotted swiss right to the tacky edge, and then
pulling back with something arcane, like a top of tucked white
batiste. Electric pastels amplified the collection's good, clean
sinfulness. And very fruity it was, too.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Burberry looks more Italian than English since
Roberto Menichetti took over the design is to ignore the realities
of a global brand. Menichetti would likely admit to being
obsessive, given how he likes to point out every detail _ from new
plaids in lilac, green and ashy gray to the modern fit of a stretch
raincoat. ``It took 32 fittings to get that coat right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All that is wonderful, but it's not what one comes to London
for. Arkadius _ that's how he likes to be called _ left Poland
seven years ago, he said, with nothing but a rucksack. In London,
he met someone who became his benefactor, paying for his tuition at
Central St. Martin's. Isabella Blow, the stylist, discovered him
and made the introduction to Ebel, which, he said, has agreed to
finance him for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the front row at the show was Gary Djanogly, an Ebel
brand manager. It was obvious Djanogly didn't know a lot about a
raw talent like Arkadius' _ the paint-slathered white leather tops,
the bell-bottoms ballooning out with bean-bag stuffing, or what it
means, as the designer said, ``to give birth to my own self.'' And
when asked if he was aware of the risks involved with supporting a
new designer, Djanogly looked nonplused and said, ``Ask me a
question about geography.''
</P>
<P>
   But he could see that Arkadius generated buzz, the way McQueen
did, and he added, ``We're hoping he's going to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion is a long-term proposition, and designers should have
the luxury of expressing ideas, especially in their raw vitality.
Five years ago, Chalayan was burying clothes in his backyard, to
see how they'd decay, and not long ago he was designing T-shirts.
He has never made a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday night at Sadler's Wells Theater, he sent out a
collection that was as personal and brilliant as it gets. He didn't
look to history books or vintage rags for inspiration. It all came
out of his head. Here were dresses of marigold, sea foam and light
blue cotton, or voile cut closely on top and left to fall in soft,
funnel-like ripples to the knees. Ruffles trickled down the front
of simple chemises, but they looked refined.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the collection was a rare combination of refinement and
childish innocence. At one point, a young boy came out holding a
remote control, which he aimed at a model in a pale plastic cone of
a dress. Slowly the back of her dress opened, like a car port, to
reveal a frisky layer of tulle. Other gestures were more grown-up,
like white chemises printed with the sort of abstract trees Philip
Johnson might sketch from his glass house.
</P>
<P>
   When the show was over, three rounds of applause could not bring
Chalayan out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
