A8052 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BACKPACKS-COX     09-27 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKPACKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Backpacks to backaches: Kids toting moreBy Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anthony Williamson, 11, likes his nickname: ``Short
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 72-pound sixth grader said his stature works against him
as he hauls an 18-pound backpack from class to class. This year, he
asked his mom for a book bag with wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to hurt,'' he said. ``It seemed like a smart
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To see beasts of burden, visit a middle school _ where the
children lug around as heavy a load of books as college students.
In a random sample Monday of eight students at Atlanta's Inman
Middle School, the weight of their backpacks ranged from 13 pounds
to a whopping 29 pounds. Five of the bags exceeded health experts'
recommendations that they weigh no more than 10-15 percent of
bodyweight.
</P>
<P>
   The students are prime candidates for aches and pains, experts
say. And although doctors and chiropractors hotly debate the
seriousness of the complaints, the American Academy of Pediatrics
and the American Chiropractic Association have issued warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got patients, young kids _ in second and third grade _
complaining of back and neck problems,'' said Steven Katz, a
chiropractor. ``And I link it back to those doggone backpacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission estimates children
make up 64 percent of all patients treated for injuries related to
carrying a book bag _ with about 5,500 Americans treated annually
for backpack-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Some orthopedic specialists dispute the seriousness of the
backpack syndrome. ``I don't perceive this as much as a problem as
the public does,'' said Dr. E. William Schmitt, chief of pediatric
orthopedics at Children's Healthcare of Atlanta at Egleston.
</P>
<P>
   But talk to kids, and they'll tell you it can be a real pain.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Anderson, 13, weighs 120 pounds and was hauling a
29-pound bookbag around Inman. ``It really hurts in my shoulders
and back after I've been walking for a while,'' she said. ``It's no
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
