<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLY-IOC-COX     09-27 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC to investigate Atlanta Games bid
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The International Olympic Committee said Monday it
will investigate improprieties by its members during Atlanta's bid
for the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   However, the investigation, which will be conducted by the IOC's
new ethics commission, is not likely to exact any more changes in
what a U.S. congressman calls a ``culture of corruption'' within
the bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the most flagrant offenders of IOC edicts in Atlanta
already have been expelled or have resigned in the wake of the Salt
Lake City bribery scandal. And other rule benders have been accused
of less serious offenses than some IOC who were let off the hook
earlier by the ethics panel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ethics commission has no choice but to study the
report on the Atlanta bid submitted to the U.S. House Commerce
Committee by former Attorney General Griffin Bell. Rep. Fred Upton
(R-Mich.) said the report showed that ``votes were for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The report detailed gifts and travel, and offers of college
scholarships, job assistance and other perks to IOC members and
their families by the Atlanta bid team.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the report was sent last week to IOC President Juan
Antonio Samaranch after he asked the U.S. Olympic Committee to
provide details on any abuses related to the bid.
</P>
<P>
   Six IOC members were expelled and four resigned in connection
with the Salt Lake City vote-buying scandal. IOC members and their
relatives received $1.2 million worth of cash payments, college
scholarships and other favors from that city's bid team.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Atlanta's biggest beneficiaries, for example, Agustin
Arroyo of Ecuador and Jean-Claude Ganga of the Congo, already have
been ousted.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo and his wife made at least three trips to Atlanta and
received $14,682 in travel and gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga and various family members made three trips to the city,
with a side trip to New York, ringing up travel expenses of
$15,702. The bid committee also spent $35,216 for sports equipment
and tennis camps for Congolese athletes at Ganga's request.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC at the time only allowed one visit to bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the eight-man ethics panel, IOC Vice President
Keba Mbaye, a former vice president of the World Court at The
Hague, will examine the Atlanta report, according to IOC spokesman
Franklin Servan-Schreiber.
</P>
<P>
   If Mbaye finds ``anything meaningful,'' he will submit the
information to the full commission for review.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC received a letter from Upton asking Samaranch to testify
Oct. 14 during a House hearing on the Atlanta bid excesses. The
spokesman said he did not know if Samaranch would attend.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics commission is composed of three IOC members and five
from outside the IOC. The outside members include former U.S. Sen.
Howard Baker and former U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de
Cuellar.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has demonstrated leniency before, dropping the
cases of Australia's Phil Coles and South Korea's Kim Un-Yong.
</P>
<P>
   Coles had been cited for accepting travel perks from Salt Lake
City.
</P>
<P>
   And his ex-wife also claimed that representatives of Athens,
Greece's, unsuccessful bid for the 1996 Olympics gave the couple
jewelry worth $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Coles could come under scrutiny again. Coles made two visits to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   One was a trip with his then-wife and daughter, which included a
six-day stay at Disney World, for a total bill of $13,326.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, the highest-ranking official implicated in the Salt Lake
City affair, was cleared when the commission said it couldn't prove
he knew that the Salt Lake City committee paid for his son's salary
at a telecommunications company. His son, John Kim, and his
employer have been indicted for their roles in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
