<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS REBOUND SLIGHTLY BUT CONDITIONS REMAIN UNSETTLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices rebounded a bit Monday, as investors
became selective buyers of shares that were particularly hard-hit
by last week's steep sell-off. Still, major market averages closed
well under their session highs and some analysts said conditions
were still unsettled, suggesting that prices could fall a bit
further.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a little bounce that was not as convincing as I would
have liked,'' said Henry Herrmann, chief investment officer at
Waddell &AMP; Reed of Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   By the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 24.06, or
0.2 percent, to 10,303.39. Earlier in the day the Dow was up more
than 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the blue-chip index recorded its worst one-week point
drop ever, falling 524.30, or 4.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Broader market averages did a bit better.
</P>
<P>
   Paced by gains in big technology stocks like Intel, Lucent
Technologies and America Online _ stocks that were hammered last
week _ the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index gained 5.95, or 0.5 percent,
to 1283.31.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the NASDAQ composite index rose 21.34, or 0.8
percent, to 2761.75. And the Russell 2000 index of small company
stocks gained 4.77, or 1.1 percent, to 421.86.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with recent Mondays, activity was a bit more brisk.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 780.8 million
shares. On the NASDAQ stock market, 932.6 million shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Signs from Japanese officials over the weekend that Tokyo will
take steps to bolster the value of the dollar against the yen
provided a brighter backdrop for the stock market Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus for the last two weeks has clearly been on the
dollar/yen relationship,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst
at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``We finally got a breather on that, and that is
probably why we ran up today.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from selected technology companies, gold stocks had a very
good day.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks rallied after European central banks said they will
limit bullion sales. Following the announcement, bullion prices
shot up 4 percent, the biggest gain for the metal in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Newmont Mining jumped 4 7/8, to 27 13/16. And Homestake Mining
rose 1 5/8, to 9 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which was battered last week, was the most active stock
Monday. The leading computer-chip manufacturer rose 2 33/64, to 78
3/16. Meanwhile, Lucent rose 1 9/16, to 66 5/16. And America Online
gained 3 5/8, to 101 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Proctor &AMP; Gamble was the Dow's biggest gainer. The consumer
products giant rose 2 1/16, to 99 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Other Dow winners included General Electric, which was up 2, to
120, and Johnson &AMP; Johnson, which closed at 91 13/16, up 1 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a good day for interest-sensitive financial stocks.
American Express dropped 1 7/16, to 134 15/16. Citigroup lost 1, to
42 1/16. And BancAmerica fell 1 15/16, to 55 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Concern that the Federal Reserve Board will vote to raise
short-term interest rates at a policy-making meeting next week has
dissipated, Hogan of Jefferies &AMP; Co. said. The concern has been
replaced by a widespread belief that a tightening will occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed can't hurt us because the market has corrected for
another tightening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can start to focus on third-quarter earnings, which are
going to look terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all technology stocks gained.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, a Dow component, fell 2, to 123.
</P>
<P>
   And Rambus Inc. slid 12 1/16 to 59 1/16, extending a loss of
more than 16 points that it suffered on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
