<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-2000 _ (Nashua, N.H.) _ Arizona Sen. John McCain formally
opens his bid for the Republican presidential nomination, promising
to return dignity to the White House, strengthen the military and
bring honesty to a government that is now ``a spectacle of selfish
ambition.'' By GREG McDONALD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BARNES (Austin, Texas) _ Austin lobbyist Ben Barnes says
that as speaker of the Texas House more than 30 years ago, he
recommended George W. Bush for a pilot's position in the Texas Air
National Guard at the request of a Bush family friend. The question
of whether Gov. Bush received preferential treatment in securing a
National Guard spot to avoid going to fight in Vietnam has surfaced
in Bush's presidential race. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET (Washington) _ President Clinton announces that
the this year's projected federal budget surplus has grown to the
largest in history _ $115 billion, up from the $99 billion
predicted over the summer. He urges Congress to work with the
administration on Social Security, Medicare and education. By NANCY
MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ Accused wire tapper Linda Tripp
sues the White House and Defense Department, alleging that federal
officials illegally used confidential records to discredit her
during the Monica Lewinsky investigation. By JOHN C. HENRY.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DRUGS (Austin, Texas) _ Organizations that are hoping to
decriminalize some drug offenses are asking Gov. George W. Bush to
examine the cases of an estimated 28,000 people imprisoned in Texas
for nonviolent drug offenses. The aim of the organizations is to
get Bush to commute some sentences or grant pardons. By KATHY WALT.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GLAUCOMA-SURGERY (Houston) _ A University of Texas at Houston
Medical School researcher is one of three doctors in Texas
performing a new non-penetrating glaucoma surgery, called
viscocanalostomy. Although it promises excellent results, some
experts remain skeptical. By ERIC BERGER.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-DRINKING (College Station, Texas) _ Texas A&AMP;M becomes
the first public university in Texas to use parental notification
of liquor and drug violations on campus. A survey shows students at
the College Station campus have a higher rate of drinking than the
national average. By JOHN GONZALEZ. (Graphic available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   INSANE-KILLER (Undated) _ Claude Eric Maturana's lawyer says
he's a schizophrenic, while the Arizona Attorney General's office
says the convicted killer is faking it to avoid execution. The
Supreme Court says a person must be mentally competent at the time
he is executed, but the staff of the Arizona state hospital refuses
to medicate him in sufficient dosages to make him clear-headed
enough to meet the standard to die. By KIM COBB. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-SERIES (Houston) _ The Astrodome is going out in style with
one of the biggest series in Houston Astros' franchise history to
kick off the Dome's final week. Starting Tuesday night, the Astros
and Cincinnati Reds will go head-to-head in a two-game series that
could decide the National League Central Division title. By DAVID
BARRON.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Despite losing seven of their past 10
games, the Houston Astros say they remain confident that they will
hold off Cincinnati and claim their third consecutive division
title. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-REDS (Cincinnati) _ They have done it with a patchwork
pitching staff and a bullpen by committee. But the Cincinnati Reds
have somehow found a way to win 93 games and put themselves in
position for their first playoff berth since 1995. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER (Brookline, Mass.) _ We look at the United States'
dramatic comeback victory over Europe in the Ryder Cup. By EDDIE
SEFKO.
</P>
<P>
   With: GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN.
</P>
