<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8060 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-QUAYLE-CAMPAIGN-ART-(     09-27 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-CAMPAIGN-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING REALITY, QUAYLE ENDS DREAM OF RETURNING TO WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ His voice firm but his eyes glistening, former Vice
President Dan Quayle bid farewell Monday to a national political
career that has made him a household name _ and occasionally a
household laughingstock _ for more than a decade, announcing that
he would abandon his quest for the Republican presidential
nomination for lack of money and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a time to stay and there's a time to fold,'' Quayle
said quietly as his wife, Marilyn, stood beside him at a hotel news
conference in his adopted home state here. ``There's a time to know
when to leave the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle endorsed none of his rivals, but pledged to work for the
Republicans' eventual nominee, which he said appears all but
certain to be Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He took pains to note that at 52, he is hardly over the hill,
and referring with a twinkle to Richard Nixon's famously premature
farewell, said: ``I seriously doubt if this will be my last press
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was an air of poignancy to the occasion, as Mrs.
Quayle seemed to struggle to hold back tears and misty-eyed aides
lined the wall of an elegant Frank Lloyd Wright ballroom at the
Arizona Biltmore Resort &AMP; Spa. It is always possible that Quayle,
who was a senator from Indiana, could run for lesser office
someday, but even longtime aides said his days as a national
candidate were effectively over, a casualty of his lingering _ if
in their eyes often unfair _ reputation as a lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of a sad moment today, though in some ways perhaps
an inevitable one,'' said William Kristol, Quayle's
vice-presidential chief of staff and now the editor of The Weekly
Standard. By chance Kristol watched his old boss' announcement from
the Bush campaign headquarters in Austin, Texas, where he had gone
to interview the Republican front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he underestimated how much damage had been done from
the vice-presidential years, and that he couldn't just sit out a
few years and then come back,'' Kristol said. ``I think if he were
on a successful second term as a governor, things would look
different.''
</P>
<P>
   In his news conference, and in a telephone interview afterward,
Quayle expressed no bitterness over the image problems that dogged
him from the moment of his debut as George Bush's running mate in
1988, from questions about his national guard service during the
Vietnam war, to doubts about his spelling ability when he put an
extra ``e'' on potato with a group of New Jersey school children.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he sounded only optimistic notes of gratitude for the
help of his family and friends, blended with frustration at his
inability to raise enough money to compete in the string of
front-loaded primaries next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, there's about 15 different ways you could conclude
a campaign,'' Quayle said in the interview. ``This would've been
No. 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said that his New Hampshire campaign chairman, former
Gov. John H. Sununu, who was chief of staff in the Bush White
House, had convinced him that he had a reasonable shot at winning
the primary there, and his own polls showed him gaining, aides
said. But even if he won New Hampshire, Quayle said, he concluded
he could not afford to compete with Bush in the 18 contests that
will occur within 30 days afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality set in,'' Quayle said, and in discussions over the
weekend, he decided winning the nomination would be ``virtually
impossible.'' For months, he had said he would not go through the
exercise of running if he did not think he could win, and so made
his announcement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first six months of this year, Quayle raised about $3.5
million, to about $37 million for Bush, but aides said that was not
the former vice president's only problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money's a part of it but it's not all of it,'' said Quayle's
poll-taker, Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, who noted how sped-up the
current election cycle seems. ``At this point in the fall of 1991,
George Stephanopoulos was just making his first acquaintance with
Bill and Hillary Clinton,'' she said, adding that so much has
changed since then in how the nation judges and selects its
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say to be nominated as a Republican, you need cash,
conservatism, character and chits,'' Ms. Fitzpatrick said, ``but
you also need chatter, and this year the emphasis on buzz-building
has surpassed so many of these other nuts and bolts.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Quayle, who had sought to define himself in
large measure by his support for traditional family values, was at
pains to compete against other candidates, like Steve Forbes and
Pat Buchanan, for the support of the party's more conservative
voters. And indeed he said Monday that the way to win elections was
to offer a clear contrast to the Democrats, not try to soften
Republican positions to mimic them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Like former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, who with Rep.
John R. Kasich of Ohio and Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire preceded
him in dropping out of the Republican race, Quayle said he would
favor increasing the $1,000 individual limit on presidential
campaign contributions, to make it easier to raise money. But he
said he remained opposed to any proposals for more
taxpayer-financed matching funds for campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fitzpatrick and other aides said Quayle had also been
handicapped by having to run against Bush, whose father plucked
Quayle from comparative obscurity in the Senate to run for vice
president. She said Quayle was ``too much of a gentleman to take a
chain-saw to the front-runner.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Quayle also reflected on the challenges of
facing the son of his old patron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never imagined in my wildest dreams that I would be running
against George Bush's son,'' Quayle said. ``Things would have been
a lot different had that not happened. A lot. It was very awkward.
I was very loyal to President Bush and the whole family.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, George W. Bush said of his rival, ``I wish him all the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the White House, Quayle has written books,
appeared on the lecture circuit and served on corporate and
charitable boards. He said Monday that he and his wife planned to
take some time off ``to decompress,'' but that it was too early to
talk about what he might do next, except that he would ``continue
to fight for those ideas that I believe in, fight for the
philosophy of smaller government, lowering taxes, strengthening the
American family and reinvesting in our national defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the ideas of the Republican Party as well,'' he
added. ``I'm going to work to unite this party.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like Bush, Quayle said he hoped that Buchanan would not bolt to
the Reform Party, saying, ``I don't think we ought to write anyone
out of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristol said he thought time had already vindicated some of the
views for which Quayle was once roundly mocked, like his broadside
against the plot-line celebrating single motherhood in the TV
sitcom ``Murphy Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was willing to take abuse for saying something that
everyone now acknowledges was pretty important,'' Kristol said.
``In that respect, he will have a kind of intellectual and moral
vindication.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Kristol added, ``One of the odd things about politics is
when you get out, you get treated more fairly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
