<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UTILITIES-COX     09-27 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GUC workers start recovery process
 &HT;    By Dawn Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Greenville Utilities has traded in the soggy
sandbags for cleanup gear.
</P>
<P>
   With the city's electric and water services stabilized after
last week's record flooding, GUC has shifted its attention to
salvaging what it can from its soaked Operations Center off Mumford
Road.
</P>
<P>
   Workers had to evacuate the building _ which houses the
emergency center during storms _ Sept. 17 after record-high Tar
River levels started seeping in the doors and windows.
</P>
<P>
   Employees raised all computers to the desktops thinking that
would keep them safe. It didn't. Papers, maps, pictures and
vehicles were left behind, and are likely ruined.
</P>
<P>
   It could take months before the cleanup is finished and normal
activity resumes there.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 275 employees have been relocated to GUC's main
office. Officials are searching for rentable space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now they are just trying to find somewhere,'' said Sue
Bizzaro, GUC's public information officer. ``People are doubled up
at this site (downtown).''
</P>
<P>
   More than a week after the hasty evacuation, two 30-ton off-road
dump trucks shuttled workers through the receding waters to the
center to pick up what was left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a bomb went off. I try to warn everybody. If you
can live without it, don't go get it,'' said Gilbert Smithwick of
Sawyer's Land Developing, which is shuttling workers. ``Go buy
another one. It's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   One worker took a large plastic container with him to gather
belongings. He came back in tears with everything salvageable in
his pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The 4- to 8-foot floodwaters wiped out files, maps, furniture
and every vehicle parked in the GUC lot, including some workers'
personal cars. Damage estimates for heavy equipment only totals
nearly $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came so fast, and we were so busy responding to emergency
needs, they had no time to rescue the commission vehicles or their
own,'' said Ed Askew, GUC's director of support services. ``When we
went in there (last week), the only thing we could see was the
antennae sticking up above the water.''
</P>
<P>
   A disaster recovery firm from Memphis, Tenn., hired by GUC for
$120,000, arrived Monday to salvage irreplaceable files. GUC crews
hope to retrieve information from computer hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also have ordered more vehicles after nearly half the
fleet _ 75 to 90 trucks and vans _ fell victim to the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   During an emergency meeting Thursday, the GUC board approved
spending $764,017 for vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Costs for cleanup and damage likely won't cause any rate hikes,
said Malcolm Green, GUC's general manager/CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't envision that being the case,'' he said. ``A lot of
what we are doing is going to be covered by insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   What insurance doesn't cover, the Federal Emergency Management
Agency should, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, workers _ donning waders, green rubber gloves and
face masks _tried to rescue what they could from the center, the
garage and the warehouse. The engineering part of the building
opened just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nasty,'' said Rodney Sutton, a GUC load management
technician for five years. ``Our office is destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton was one of several workers loading cardboard boxes with
whatever wasn't ruined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that the water didn't get to, and that ain't much,''
Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the center, warped desks sit lopsided in the offices;
bookshelves have collapsed, spewing the contents, and clumps of
waterlogged papers are strewn across the gray carpet, which sloshes
as workers step on it.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-foot water mark taints the light-colored walls, and
everything is coated in a brown film. A strong stench makes the
cleanup task more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to gather up what we can,'' said Howard Corey,
GUC's water resources engineering coordinator. ``There are 22 years
worth of work here I've been working on in my career. It is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs of employees' hurried exit held up through the flood. In
Corey's office, a can of Pepsi and a snack still sit on a table. In
another office, a ruler sits on a soggy map spread across the desk.
</P>
<P>
   Officials don't have a damage estimate, in part because so many
items and cars are still submerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still discovering things that are missing,'' Askew
said.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup has been more challenging because so many telephone
numbers, insurance records and equipment descriptions were kept at
the center. Askew's office also was in the operations center.
</P>
<P>
   Now working from the MIS director's vacant office downtown, he
has tried to organize what few papers he has. On Friday he
frantically searched for the little things he needed to do that _
file folders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Askew said. ``You have nothing. You don't
have phone numbers. There's so much work to do and you have
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   GUC's downtown office is expected to remain closed through the
week. GUC Express, 509 S.E. Greenville Boulevard, is open from 7:30
a.m. to 5:30 p.m. weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll clean up everything we've got. We'll have to,'' Corey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Bryant writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
