<SLUG> BC-ENDOSTATIN-TRIALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS TESTING ENDOSTATIN BEGIN ENLISTING VOLUNTEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Volunteers can begin signing up Tuesday for the
long-awaited first human trials of endostatin, the tumor-starving
cancer drug from the laboratory of Dr. Judah Folkman.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin, an angiogenesis inhibitor, has demonstrated in mice
a striking ability to shrink tumors by cutting off the blood supply
they must have to grow and spread. But until now it has not been
given to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 to 30 patients will receive the drug during the first
phase of testing, whose purpose is strictly to determine if
endostatin has harmful side effects and to establish what doses can
be safely tolerated. It is called a Phase I trial, and there will
shortly be two more of them opening at M.D. Anderson Cancer Center
in Houston and at the University of Wisconsin in Madison.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston trial is being sponsored by EntreMed, a Maryland
biotech company that has licensed the rights to develop the drug
from Children's Hospital, where Folkman and his colleagues have
been studying angiogenesis _ the formation of new blood vessels _
and ways to block it for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The development of endostatin as a drug has been surrounded by
enormous publicity, stock market speculation, and some controversy
because of the difficulty some other researchers have had in
duplicating Folkman's results. Officials involved with the clinical
trial are braced for an avalanche of volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the high visibility of Endostatin and the small size of
this study, we have done everything possible to make our procedures
open, impartial and objective,'' said Dr. Donald Kufe, a physician
at Dana-Farber Cancer Institute who is the principal investigator
of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Written with a capital ``E,'' Endostatin is the trade name of
the drug being made synthetically by EntreMed. The name endostatin
refers to the substance that is made naturally as part of the
body's blood-clotting system.
</P>
<P>
   As volunteers call or access the Web sites, their names will be
put into a computer database, from which names will be chosen at
random for further screening. Those who are picked will be invited
to one of the participating hospitals to determine if they are
clinically eligible for the study.
</P>
<P>
   Those who pass the screening will be selected, in the order in
which they were determined eligible, to receive the drug.
</P>
<P>
   The names of those who passed the screening but were not chosen
for the trial will go back into the database, together with those
who apply later.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer patients wanting to participate in the Boston trial can
call a telephone hotline, visit any of three Web sites, or call a
service that will send information by fax.
</P>
<P>
   Participating medical centers are Dana-Farber/Partners Cancer
Care (which includes Brigham and Women's and Massachusetts General
hospitals) and the Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone hotline number is (617) 632-5100. It will be
answered between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern Standard Time by nurses
who specialize in cancer care.
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites' addresses are
http://www.dana-farber.net/endostatin at Dana-Farber;
http://www.cancer.mgh.harvard.edu at Mass General; and
http://www.bidmc.caregroup.org/endostatin/default.asp.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible, volunteers must satisfy a number of criteria.
They must be 18 or older and have a solid malignant tumor that is
not reponsive to any form of therapy. The trial excludes patients
with leukemia, lymphoma or myeloma or a primary brain tumor or
involvement of the central nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers must be expected to live at least six months and are
required to be mobile and able to carry out normal life activities.
</P>
<P>
   Other criteria are available in the information that is on the
Web site or can be obtained on the hotline.
</P>
<P>
   The study is expected to run for nine months to a year, with
small groups of patients (3 to 6) taking the drug in succession.
The first group of patients will receive daily intravenous
infusions of endostatin for 28 days, then will simply be observed
for 14 days. The next group, then, will be given a higher dose for
28 days while the first group continues on its initial dose, and so
on.
</P>
<P>
   If the drug proves tolerable in the Phase I trials, it will then
enter Phase II and Phase III testing which includes greater numbers
of patients and is designed to look for beneficial effects.
</P>
<P>
   Other, less potent angiogenesis inhibitors are in early testing
in human patients, and reports suggest the drugs are well-tolerated
by patients and appear to combat tumors, though there remains too
little evidence to say how valuable they might be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
