A8074 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CHINA-$ADV03-6     09-27 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CHINA-$ADV03-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 DESTINATION IN 2020? TRY CHINA, THEN FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 3)  
(lb) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not be too soon to start brushing up on Chinese. Why?
Because by 2020, China is expected to become the world's top
tourist destination with 130 million annual visitors, and 100
million Chinese are expected to visit other lands.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, China had a relatively modest 24 million visitors
last year, good enough for sixth place, while the 8.4 million
Chinese visitors to other lands (``outbound tourists'') ranked
ninth. But its 100 million outbound tourists will account for
almost a quarter of the 405 million Asian travelers expected by
2020, a staggering increase from the region's 84.4 million outbound
travelers in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   These forecasts are from the World Tourism Organization, a
worldwide group of 138 countries and territories, based in Madrid,
Spain, that gathers tourism statistics and publishes reports.
</P>
<P>
   At the International Tourism Asia trade show in Hong Kong last
month, the organization also predicted that by 2020 France will
drop from first to second place in arrivals (even though its
visitors will increase to 106.1 million by 2020, up from 70 million
last year) and the United States will remain third (102.4 million
visitors, up from 47.1 million currently).
</P>
<P>
   Spain, with 47.7 million visitors last year, will have 73.9
million in 2020, but will still drop a notch to fourth place. Hong
Kong, currently 18th with almost 9.7 million visitors, will vault
to fifth place with 56.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining top 10 positions are expected to be occupied by
Britain (currently in fifth place), Italy (currently fourth),
Mexico (seventh), the Russian Federation (13th) and the Czech
Republic (12th).
</P>
<P>
   The tourist organization also predicted that the ubiquitous
Germans, who have long led in outbound travelers, including 82.9
million last year, will continue to lead the list with almost 153
million in 2020. Japanese travelers, who numbered 16.8 million in
1997, the latest figure available, will soar to 141 million, for
second place, while the 123.3 million outbound Americans in 2020
will be more than twice the 52.7 million who traveled in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions, of course, are informed guesses at best, but World
Tourism Organization forecasts have often been on target or close
to it. Two years ago, for example, it forecast that China would be
the world's No. 1 destination by the year 2020, and it stuck to
that prediction despite the recent economic crisis in East Asia and
the Pacific, which draws many of its tourists from the region.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hong Kong meeting, the organization said that to prepare
for the expected influx, the Chinese government is investing a lot
of money in promoting tourism and relaxing laws governing the
tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism organization also predicted almost a year ago that
tourism to East Asia and the Pacific would bounce back stronger
than ever after 2000, barring any new major incident. And at the
Hong Kong conference, Deborah Luhrman, a World Tourism spokeswoman,
told delegates that the economy of the region seems to be
stabilizing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economic battering, East Asia and the Pacific still
drew a respectable 87 million tourists last year, according to
Francesco Frangialli, the organization's secretary-general. Much of
the shortfall in Japanese tourists, he said, was offset by
Europeans and North Americans attracted by lower prices and good
package deals.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of a comeback are already apparent in several Asian
nations. Tourist arrivals to Hong Kong, for example, increased 11.1
percent for the first seven months of this year, compared with the
same months of 1998. Thailand posted an 11 percent increase through
June of this year over the first six months of 1998. And Singapore
tourism rose 9.5 percent through July, compared with the same seven
months of 1998, even though visitors from Japan fell almost 13
percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is important to remember that many predictions
about tourism are as fleeting as the life span of the mosquito. Two
years ago, for example, the World Tourism Organization predicted
that ``the tourists of the 21st century will be traveling further
afield on their holidays, with the percentage of long-haul travel
increasing from 18 percent in 1995 to 24 percent by 2020.''
</P>
<P>
   But 13 months later, in November 1998, the WTO's Business
Council (a group representing the private sector within the larger
organization) released a study saying that because the amount of
leisure time available for many people is likely to decline, the
trend to shorter, more frequent holidays closer to home will
accelerate _ a trend that has been pronounced in the United States
for almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the periodic warnings _ the first more than a year
ago from the World Congress on Snow and World Tourism, the most
recent a report for the Worldwide Fund for Nature in Britain _ that
global warming could erode beaches, reduce snowfall over ski areas
and otherwise play havoc with tourist areas, and the future is
probably as uncertain as ever. But barring widespread economic,
political or climatic upheaval, one thing seems certain _ tourism
will continue growing at record rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our results for 1998 confirm that people do not stop traveling
altogether, even during tough times,'' Frangialli said. Instead,
they underscore that tourism ``has become a deeply rooted part of
our culture at the end of the 20th century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
