<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8078 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CALIF-HMOS-ART-930&AMP;AD     09-27 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HMOS-ART-930&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA MAKES SWEEPING CHANGES IN REGULATION OF HMOS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gov. Gray Davis signed on Monday a package of
bills that will make radical changes in the relationship between
patients and health maintenance organizations in the state and
could well influence managed health care coverage across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The broad set of bills, hammered out between advocates on both
sides over several months, will give patients in HMOs the right to
sue their health insurers for punitive damages and entitle patients
to an external review of decisions denying medical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will also require managed care providers to pay
for second opinions on some treatments, require coverage for the
testing and treatment of breast cancer, require coverage of
contraceptives and expand coverage for serious mental illnesses. It
will create a new state Department of Managed Care to regulate the
massive industry, which covers about 23 million people in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The provision that gives patients the right to seek damages when
they have suffered substantial harm provides a way around a
25-year-old federal law that prohibits many such suits. It has been
championed by consumer advocates for years and was the most
contentious part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   A battle at least as contentious over the issue is also under
way in Congress as part of the debate on a Patient Bill of Rights.
Representatives of health care insurers have long criticized this
provision, saying that its potential costs would outweigh its
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no guarantee that the changes in California will
adopted by other states or be a decisive factor in the
congressional debate, California has long been a leader in the
development and regulation of managed care, and many of the
country's largest insurers are based here.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many other states look to California for guidance
on regulatory issues, and it was clear that Monday's signing was
being watched closely. Texas has, for two years, had a similar law
allowing patients to seek damages, and the experience there has
also pushed reform elsewhere, in part by demonstrating that the
avalanche of lawsuits some insurers warned against has not
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   But both consumer advocates and HMO industry leaders ultimately
found something to praise in the package of 21 bills, the product
of a series of compromises that have created what many
characterized as landmark legislation in the struggle on the
slippery financial and ethical terrain of managed care to make it
both profitable to the insurers and responsive to patient needs.
</P>
<P>
   At one time Davis, a centrist Democrat, was perceived by
consumer advocates as resistant to giving patients such broad
rights to seek punitive damages, but on Monday he hailed the bills
as a solid middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``None too infrequently, Californians fighting for their lives
are forced at the same time to fight HMOs,'' Davis said at the
signing, held at the Family Medical Center in North Hollywood.
``It's time to make the health of the patient the bottom line with
California HMOs''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I want to make sure managed care is more about
quality care than it is about managed cost, and that's what these
reforms will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Zelman, president of the California Association of Health
Plans, a trade group that represents most of the HMOs in the state,
said: ``This is going to be a shot in the arm for those advocating
reform bills in Congress and in other states.'' He said that he
felt the cost of law suits would drive up premiums for consumers,
but that, overall, ``this was a good package of bills.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the industry particularly supported the bill providing
for external review of decisions by HMOs denying coverage to
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Court, the advocacy director of the Foundation for
Taxpayer and Consumer Rights, which sponsored the bill creating the
right to punitive damages, said that the threat of lawsuits would
help patients, even if they never have to go to court, by
pressuring the companies to put medical concerns first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat of lawsuits and of substantial damages forces HMOs
to give better care and it shifts the balance of power over medical
decisions to the people who really have the medical knowledge,''
Court said.
</P>
<P>
   One did not have to go far to hear some of these views from
patients. Ira Horn, 69, was at the signing at the medical center
and said the law would hurt people like himself who cannot afford
an H.M.O.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the measures signed into law on Monday were fought
successfully by Davis' predecessor, Gov. Pete Wilson, a Republican.
But the political ground has shifted in recent years with more
patients and consumer groups criticizing the way financial
considerations were being used to limit access to medical care by
HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, despite the federal prohibition against certain
kinds of suits against HMOs, some suits have succeeded, putting
further pressure on legislatures to put regulations in place.
Earlier this year a jury in California gave a record punitive award
of $116 million to the widow of a former prosecutor who died
because of what were said to be delays in providing treatment for
his stomach cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Court explained that federal law prohibited suits in disputes
over benefits, but not if the basis of the challenge was the
quality of the care provided. That interpretation, he said, had
already been tested in Texas and the courts upheld the state law,
thus giving a green light to California and other states.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The right to sue for punitive damages has been the most prickly
provision in the Patient Bill of Rights that the Congress has been
working on. The Senate passed its version of the bill earlier, and
it has a measure providing for independent, external review of
decisions denying medical care, but does not permit suits for
damages. The measure appears to have a better chance of passing in
the House, which is expected to take up the measure next month.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, the president of the American Association of
Health Plans, the national representative of the HMO industry,
called much of the California package a model, saying, ``This is
the first process we have seen where all sides have come together
to do the real work.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she criticized the provision on law suits, saying it
would prove expensive and unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
