<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-SUIT-BO     09-27 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS SOURCE IDENTIFIED BY EX-REPORTER SUES PAPER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   In a move with serious implications for the relationship between
reporters and sources, former Chiquita Brands lawyer George Ventura
filed suit Monday against The Cincinnati Enquirer and its owner,
Gannett. Ventura, who faced criminal charges for providing the
Enquirer with inside information on Chiquita, said the paper
violated an agreement to treat him as a confidential source, by
revealing his identity to law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century after ``Deep Throat'' contributed to the
toppling of a president, the Cincinnati case was further evidence
that whistle-blowers, the lifeblood of investigative journalism,
seem to be an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   In November Disney will create shock waves with the release of
``The Insider,'' a film detailing how a tobacco-industry
whistle-blower, Jeffrey Wigand, risked health and happiness trying
to get CBS executives to let him tell his story on ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   A former CNN producer, April Oliver, who was dismissed for her
role in the ill-fated Operation Tailwind story, recently identified
retired Major General John Singlaub as her confidential source in a
countersuit she filed against him.
</P>
<P>
   And the judge in the libel suit by the former Olympic Park
bombing suspect, Richard Jewell, is threatening to jail two Atlanta
Journal-Constitution reporters unless they identify the sources who
discussed the Jewell investigation with them.
</P>
<P>
   The Ventura controversy is another ``example of where ethics and
law cross each other,'' said a University of Minnesota media
professor, Jane Kirtley. ``It's got more issues than a law
school.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit stems from the Enquirer's series, published in 1998,
on Chiquita's business operations. Shortly after it ran, the paper,
acknowledging that it had illegally obtained Chiquita voice-mail
messages, fired Mike Gallagher, the reporter who had broken into
the system; publicly apologized; and paid Chiquita at least $10
million in reparations.
</P>
<P>
   The purloined voice-mail messages spawned a criminal case.
During that investigation Gallagher struck a deal with the
prosecutor in which he agreed to disclose his sources. Ventura _
who is now unemployed _ ultimately pleaded no contest to charges
connected to providing access to the voice mails.
</P>
<P>
   In his breach-of-contract suit filed in US District Court in
Cincinnati, Ventura states that his cooperation ``was predicated
strictly upon the numerous, explicit and unconditional
representations of these reporters . . . that his identity as a
source of these documents and information would forever remain
anonymous and confidential.'' He claims that his ``identity as a
source'' was subsequently revealed, subjecting him to criminal
prosecution and ``great harm in his personal and professional
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher's attorney Patrick Hanley said Monday that ``as far as
Mike Gallagher is concerned, we've always maintained that there's
no breach of contract to Mr. Ventura on his behalf.'' Enquirer
president Harry Whipple issued a statement saying: ``The Enquirer
has never disclosed any information that would identify a source.
This case is without merit.'' Gannett had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a purely legal matter, (Ventura's) on good ground,''
declared Gregg Leslie, acting executive director of the Reporters
Committee for Freedom of the Press, referring to the Cohen vs.
Cowles Media precedent. In that case, public relations consultant
Dan Cohen successfully sued after he provided two Minnesota papers
with documents on a rival candidate on the condition of anonymity
and they later published his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly is a significant decision with respect to the
rights of sources,'' said Ventura's attorney Marc Mezibov.
</P>
<P>
   Mezibov says a victory for Ventura would be a boon to journalism
by reinforcing ``the integrity of relationships between sources and
newspapers. It will encourage sources to be more forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say the suit creates a dicey tradeoff between
the need to protect sources and the desire to keep the courts from
intervening in the reporting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reporter-source agreement is not something that should be
enforced by a court of law,'' said Leslie, who is uncomfortable
with the courts ``playing editor.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosenstiel, director for the Project for Excellence in
Journalism, worries that the effort to ``make the negotiations with
(sources and) journalists a part of the contract law'' is part of a
growing trend for litigants ``to address press misdeeds through
legal means.''
</P>
<P>
   But even among those concerned about the court's role, there is
a recognition of the sanctity of the confidentiality agreement.
Leslie said that Ventura is ``certainly a very sympathetic case.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rosenstiel noted that that ``one fundamental public good is
that the press be able to keep watch on the powerful. To chill that
would have dire consequences. . . . If the press lies to sources,
what good are we?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
