<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8087 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HUFFY-COX     09-27 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUFFY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huffy halts manufacture of bikes in U.S.
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Even as Huffy Corp. cedes its longstanding battle
with low-cost Chinese imports, Mexico now stands to become the
United States' next major importer of low-cost bikes, industry
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Huffy announced Monday it will stop domestic bike production by
Dec. 31, closing plants in Farmington, Mo. and Southaven, Miss.,
and instead relying on Asian and Mexican imports.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after years of Huffy slugging it out in an
increasingly competitive market that pitted the local
manufacturer's products against those made overseas by companies
with lower labor costs. Now high-end bicycle producers comprise
most of the domestic bike-making market.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 years, the Peoples Republic of China has become
a low-cost bike-making center for Taiwan manufacturers because
Chinese workers will labor for lower wages, said Michael
Gamstetter, editor of ``Bicycle Retailer and Industry News.''
Chinese plants turn out mostly low- and mid-priced bikes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to industry estimates, the U.S. ranks as Taiwan's
biggest customer, receiving 43.5 percent of Taiwan's bicycle
imports during the first 10 months of 1998. In total, Taiwan during
that period shipped an estimated eight million bikes worth $717.8
million, experts said. Japan, Holland, England, Germany, Belgium,
Sweden and France also rank as heavy consumers of Taiwanese
products.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration over low-cost imports in the mid-1990s prompted
domestic manufacturers such as Huffy and Roadmaster to accuse China
of dumping cheap bikes into the U.S. market, said Huffy Chief
Financial Officer Thomas Frederick. The Federal Trade Commission
found some evidence to support these claims, but the International
Trade Commission later overturned that decision and refused to
level any duties, he said.
</P>
<P>
   European bicycle makers have launched similar campaigns against
imports from Taiwan. The European Union recently enacted
``anti-dumping'' duties against Taiwanese manufacturers, a move
some saw as legalized protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. bicycle companies increasingly rely on imports, Mexico
could become a hotbed for bicycle manufacturing by Taiwan
companies, Gamstetter said. Mexico is close enough to supply U.S.
companies with bicycles quickly. In addition, trading with Mexico
presents fewer language barriers and lower tariffs than trading
with Taiwan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Huffy to import more bikes from Mexico because its competitor,
Brunswick Corp., already has done so, he said. Industry experts
have estimated Huffy and Brunswick have enough capacity in Mexico
to make four million bicycles. Brunswick has two plants in Mexico
and Huffy buys more than half of its bikes from plants in Mexico
and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Gamstetter said Huffy enters the international market with
greater buying power than its competitors because of the sheer
volume of the company's purchases. Buying from foreign
manufacturers also will give Huffy better bikes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a smart business move,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tresslar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
Lynn Hulsey contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8088 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-SUIT-BO     09-27 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS SOURCE IDENTIFIED BY EX-REPORTER SUES PAPER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
