</P>
<P>
   In his breach-of-contract suit filed in US District Court in
Cincinnati, Ventura states that his cooperation ``was predicated
strictly upon the numerous, explicit and unconditional
representations of these reporters . . . that his identity as a
source of these documents and information would forever remain
anonymous and confidential.'' He claims that his ``identity as a
source'' was subsequently revealed, subjecting him to criminal
prosecution and ``great harm in his personal and professional
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher's attorney Patrick Hanley said Monday that ``as far as
Mike Gallagher is concerned, we've always maintained that there's
no breach of contract to Mr. Ventura on his behalf.'' Enquirer
president Harry Whipple issued a statement saying: ``The Enquirer
has never disclosed any information that would identify a source.
This case is without merit.'' Gannett had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a purely legal matter, (Ventura's) on good ground,''
declared Gregg Leslie, acting executive director of the Reporters
Committee for Freedom of the Press, referring to the Cohen vs.
Cowles Media precedent. In that case, public relations consultant
Dan Cohen successfully sued after he provided two Minnesota papers
with documents on a rival candidate on the condition of anonymity
and they later published his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly is a significant decision with respect to the
rights of sources,'' said Ventura's attorney Marc Mezibov.
</P>
<P>
   Mezibov says a victory for Ventura would be a boon to journalism
by reinforcing ``the integrity of relationships between sources and
newspapers. It will encourage sources to be more forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say the suit creates a dicey tradeoff between
the need to protect sources and the desire to keep the courts from
intervening in the reporting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reporter-source agreement is not something that should be
enforced by a court of law,'' said Leslie, who is uncomfortable
with the courts ``playing editor.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosenstiel, director for the Project for Excellence in
Journalism, worries that the effort to ``make the negotiations with
(sources and) journalists a part of the contract law'' is part of a
growing trend for litigants ``to address press misdeeds through
legal means.''
</P>
<P>
   But even among those concerned about the court's role, there is
a recognition of the sanctity of the confidentiality agreement.
Leslie said that Ventura is ``certainly a very sympathetic case.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rosenstiel noted that that ``one fundamental public good is
that the press be able to keep watch on the powerful. To chill that
would have dire consequences. . . . If the press lies to sources,
what good are we?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
