<SLUG> BC-DNA-EVIDENCE-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES PROSECUTORS TO REOPEN DNA CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A high-level study commission appointed by Attorney
General Janet Reno urged prosecutors across the United States on
Monday to be more amenable to reopening cases where convictions
might be overturned because of the use of DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   The National Commission on the Future of DNA Evidence, in
effect, urged prosecutors to drop their adversarial stance in cases
in which suspects have already been convicted and sent to prison,
cases they would traditionally resist revisiting. In addition, the
commission urged prosecutors and judges to allow such cases to be
reopened even if the legally prescribed time for appeals has
expired.
</P>
<P>
   Using DNA is a ``fundamentally different proposition'' from the
usual efforts to reopen convictions with new evidence, said
Christopher Asplen, a federal prosecutor and executive director of
the commission. Prosecutors, defense lawyers and judges are
suddenly being exposed to something they have had little experience
with, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The use of DNA as a tool to acquit the innocent has produced
dramatic results, sometimes setting free people who have been
imprisoned wrongfully for years. Jane Siegelgreen, the executive
director of the Innocence Project at the Cardozo School of Law,
which tries to reopen questionable convictions, said that her group
has tallied 67 cases (62 in the United States and five in Canada)
since 1988 in which the use of DNA technology resulted in
overturned convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report suggests that prosecutors might
themselves initiate DNA testing in cases where it might overturn a
conviction. But in the typical case, in which the request comes
from a defense lawyer, the commission said that a prosecutor
``should make every effort at cooperation'' and be especially
helpful in locating and preserving tissue samples for testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutors have an interest not only in exonerating the
wrongly accused but in bringing the guilty to justice,'' the report
said. ``A groundless conviction means that the real perpetrator is
still at large.''
</P>
<P>
   The message to prosecutors to accept the reopening of cases
after convictions may appear at odds with the well-established goal
of finality and closure in criminal proceedings. In practice that
means there has always been a presumption of a high threshold to
reach before cases are reopened.
</P>
<P>
   But the use of DNA technology is relatively new. Sophisticated
devices can determine whether microscopic samples of tissue, such
as skin, blood and semen, may be positively identified as coming
from a specific individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science involved is blind to the adversary system,'' said
Lisa Forman, a scientist who is the deputy director of the study
commission. ``This is the most dispassionate type of evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, DNA testing has been most commonly used in cases
involving rape where there is a usable semen sample available from
the victim or her clothing, Ms. Forman said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has identified different categories in which the
use of DNA testing may be used. One category that it considers the
most appropriate would involve cases like one in which a sexually
inactive girl, say 6 years old, is raped by one assailant. In such
a case, if there is a residue of semen, it could only have come
from the single rapist. And if it does not match the person
convicted, that should prove innocence.
</P>
<P>
   A different, more ambiguous scenario might involve a sexually
active woman who is raped by more than one man. The absence of the
convicted person's semen does not then conclusively prove his
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   It is in the instances identified by the commission as belonging
to category one, those in which it could be agreed in advance that
the absence of someone's DNA would prove innocence, that the
commission has urged prosecutors to be especially cooperative.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Siegelgreen of the Innocence Project said that some
prosecutors retain a traditional mind-set that once someone is
convicted, it is overwhelmingly difficult to then declare that
person innocent. She cited the case of Vincent Jenkins, who served
nearly 17 years of a life sentence in a New York state prison for a
rape he did not commit, as shown recently by DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Erie County district attorney's office did not oppose his
release but has tried to block any action to undo the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is also working on a model law to recommend to
states, obliging prosecutors to reopen cases in which DNA might
overturn a conviction. Currently only New York and Illinois have
such statutes, Ms. Siegelgreen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois law has led to six overturned sentences, including
some for murder, according to Larry Marshall, the Northwestern
University Law School professor who wrote the law.
</P>
<P>
   When the measure was being debated in the Illinois Legislature,
some lawmakers raised concerns that allowing for DNA-based appeals
would start an avalanche of prisoners demanding such tests. But
Marshall said that there has not been an excessive number of such
motions. Prisoners who were justifiably convicted of crimes, he
said, know that DNA tests would only underscore their guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous use of DNA was in the O.J. Simpson trial.
Prosecutors in that case said that blood of Ronald Goldman, one of
the victims, was found in Simpson's vehicle, and blood from his
former wife, Nicole Brown Simpson, was found on his socks. The
defense did not challenge the theory of DNA testing, but rather
raised doubts about how the samples were collected and tested by
the Los Angeles police crime lab.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is also urging better collection and testing
techniques.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
