<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8090 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      09-27 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAINTY OVER SAFETY KEEPS EAST TIMOR REFUGEES IN HILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARE, East Timor _ Bendito Freitas' daughter was born 12 days
ago in the thickly wooded mountains above East Timor's capital,
where her parents fled to escape the bloody backlash following the
landslide vote for independence. Freitas' wife gave birth on a
tarpaulin shaded by dried palm leaves, and when it was clear the
baby would survive, her parents named her Patricia, to remind them
of ``patria,'' which means ``nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia was born a couple of days after the United Nations
agreed to send peacekeepers to quell the one-sided violence
fomented by pro-Indonesia security forces. Her healthy birth at a
hidden campsite away from the smoldering ruins of Dili was a clear
omen to her parents that they and their homeland would get a fresh
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Indonesia forces ``said if they lost, blood would flow like
a river, they would destroy everything. And they did. But this is
the cost for freedom, and now that we have independence, we will
start again,'' said Freitas, 35, rural development coordinator here
for the Catholic relief agency Caritas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as of Monday, when Indonesia's army said it transferred
power to a multinational peacekeeping force that arrived a week
ago, there were still an estimated 63,000 people like Freitas
hiding in the hills a day's hike above the capital. Distrustful of
the Indonesian military since the brutal 1975 invasion of this
former Portuguese colony, the people in the mountains _ many of
them in the same hiding places they used 24 years ago _ are too
nervous to go home, even with more than 3,000 international troops
here.
</P>
<P>
   There is reason for their skepticism. Monday, the commander of
the international force contradicted his Indonesian counterpart,
saying Indonesia remained in control of security in the province
until East Timor becomes independent, a transfer expected in
November. Indonesia's commander said he had only 1,000 troops left,
but many have disputed the constantly changing figures.
</P>
<P>
   Retreating troops have torched barracks, government offices and
utilities. Monday, patches of Dili could be seen burning from the
hills above.
</P>
<P>
   The mandate of the international force is to ensure a safe
environment so that people can return home and start rebuilding
their lives. But with Australian-led troops just beginning to move
out from the capital and Baucau, the second-largest city, it is
unclear when it will be safe for people to go back to depopulated
areas, particularly those in the volatile western part of the
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The resilience of the refugees, who have survived by foraging on
roots, leaves and flowers for a fortnight, is striking by any
measure. But the success of this peacekeeping mission will be
judged by how quickly these people feel secure enough to come down
and start constructing their new nation.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Freitas and his family are staying put, like most of
those concealed between terraced coffee plantations and wild palm
trees above the hill station of Dare. Many families started sending
down teams of men to scope out the capital and scrounge for food in
the days after the peacekeepers deployed. But most have returned,
lugging sacks of rice and telling tales of a city of burned-out
shells and new fires every day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, every day also brings good news for some: those who
venture into their charred homes or into the refugee camp in Dili's
stadium and find relatives who they feared were slaughtered by
militias and Indonesian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers have been anxious about conditions here in the
hills, but early search teams say that most people seem to have
survived, apart from the weakest elderly and already malnourished
children. Relief workers marvel at the organization of the
resistance movement centered around the Falintil guerrillas, who
have been waging a struggle from these mountains for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Falintil resisted the urge to fight back, telling people instead
to burrow in and survive as best they could. Its system of sentries
and regional commanders made it impractical or impossible for
militias to penetrate the hills. Pro-independence political leaders
used satellite phones throughout the two-week bloodbath to
communicate information to reporters and diplomats overseas. Even
now, the disciplined network is coming in use, as regional Falintil
commanders take charge of aid dropoffs and coordinate
distributions, using their loyalists to carry food to the neediest
in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the seeming impossibility of accounting for everyone,
the coordinator in charge of counting heads in the campsites said
foot patrols and list-takers have ticked off 63,339 people from the
farflung towns of Dili, Aileo, Liquica, Ermera and Suai who are
still in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   An hour's hike off the switchback roads that snake up from the
smoking remains of Dili, one finds around every corner huts
fashioned of woven palm leaves and tarpaulins. Strikingly, these
people seem safer and more at ease than those who have been camping
on the beach by Dili's main street or stubbornly remaining in the
burned hulks of their homes in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Independence leaders said they are concerned about tens or
hundreds of thousands of East Timorese who were forcibly moved to
West Timor and other Indonesian islands by marauding troops. There
are documented reports of East Timorese men being seized from
refugee camps and killed. And it is unclear how those who want to
return among the 200,000 people, or a quarter of the East Timorese
population now believed to be in West Timor, will be able to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Francisco Barreto, 47, the head of Caritas and a priest
whom the Vatican reported was slain, was actually secreted away in
these hills, walking miles to say Mass twice a day to refugees, and
moving camp every night.
</P>
<P>
   Barreto said he heard that the Indonesian military offered 20
million rupiah (about $2,500) to the assassins of Catholic priests,
many of whom were seen as moral pillars of the independence
movement. After men in military uniforms stormed his tiny church in
a clearing in Dare, destroying his office and killing a middle-aged
woman called Inocencia Ribeiro, Barreto guessed he was reported
dead so that some military commander could collect his bounty.
</P>
<P>
   It was reported Monday that nine people, including a priest and
two nuns, were slain on Saturday on the road from Baucau to Los
Palos, in eastern East Timor. A man who identified himself as
Father Martins told Portuguese radio that the killings were
confirmed by Baucau's bishop.
</P>
<P>
   It is stories like this that make people like Father Barreto and
the Freitas family reluctant to emerge from their hiding places
anytime soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
