<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ON THE NEWSSTANDS: `Filtering' future of book recommendations
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a special issue on fall books, The New Yorker ($3) predicts
that the era of the blockbuster best seller may be over. What we
read will be determined more by the Internet and ``collaborative
filtering,'' Malcolm Gladwell writes in ``The Science of the
Sleeper.'' With collaborative filtering, a Web site collects data
you provide about your taste in books, movies or jokes. The Web
site compares your preferences with those of thousands of other
people and suggests fresh books, movies or jokes you might like. In
effect, the Web takes the place of friendly bookstore owners. ``The
phenomenal success in recent years of Oprah Winfrey's book club,''
Gladwell writes, ``suggests that, in this age of virtually infinite
choice, readers are starved for real advice, desperate for a
recommendation from someone they know and who they feel knows
them.''
</P>
<P>
   George's future: The late John F. Kennedy Jr.'s magazine, George
($3), will wobble into the next year, but with 10 issues instead of
12 and a slowly declining circulation, now at 405,153. The October
issue, basically a tribute to the founder, features excerpts from
interviews Kennedy conducted with evangelist Billy Graham, North
Vietnamese Gen. Vo Nguyen Giap and other prominent figures. A
companion article by Inigo Thomas describes Kennedy's meeting with
Fidel Castro two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly machines: For years, science fiction writers have
dreamed of robots' acting as helpful servants and concerned
companions. Now, says Discover ($4.99), that dream is closer to
reality than we may have imagined. In MIT's Artificial Intelligence
Lab, engineer Cynthia Breazeal has created a robot that responds to
bright colors and movements with humanlike emotions. At some point
robots won't just be appliances, Breazeal says; they'll be friends.
``What we're doing is putting humanity into the humanoid.''
</P>
<P>
   Centennial scrapbook: Life ($9.99) pays tribute to the 20th
century in a special-edition book, ``The Way We Were,'' a
photographic journey through everything from Adm. Robert Peary's
polar expedition to the first man on the moon. Amid the historic
pictures are ordinary images _ the first McDonald's, hot rods,
school vaccinations _ that will surely jog the memories of baby
boomers.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Communicator: Newsweek ($3.50) pairs an excerpt from
Edmund Morris' ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' with an
interview with the author, who defends his technique of using a
fictional narrator to tell the story. ``The narrator of `Dutch' is
only semifictional,'' Morris says. ``Indeed, for most of the later
parts of the book, the narrator is me, and my observations of
Ronald Reagan are direct and documented.'' Time ($3.50), however,
doesn't buy that argument. In a review of ``Dutch,'' John Stacks
criticizes Morris for resorting to ``dramatic trickery.'' The
writing is dazzling, Stacks says, but in the end ``the fact/fiction
bipolarity erodes some of the book's brilliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Like mother, like daughter: When U.S. News &AMP; World Report
($3.50) polled juvenile justice agencies in 21 states, it found
some troubling statistics. In Iowa, 64 percent of female juvenile
delinquents have mothers with criminal records. It has long been
known that sons of criminal fathers often follow them to jail, but
police and prosecutors are now seeing the same trend among women.
``A major culprit is crack,'' says reporter Toni Locy. ``It didn't
just make addicts of women; it made them criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick reads: Stuff ($3.95), a magazine for men, features
articles on the latest fashions and the newest high-tech gear, such
as waterproof CD players and vibrating shavers, and an eye-catching
photo layout of TV star Alyssa Milano. . . . And, speaking of sexy
TV stars, Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) devotes a big chunk of its
issue to Sarah Michelle Gellar and TV's ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer.'' Included are reviews of all 56 episodes and a sneak peek
at the new season.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
