<SLUG> BC-U.S.-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUES DISAGREEMENT COULD COST U.S. ITS U.N. ASSEMBLY SEAT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With fewer than 100 days left before the United
States faces losing its General Assembly vote for not paying its
dues, some members of Congress said on Monday that sufficient
support exists on Capitol Hill to pay much of what is owed to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But they said that President Clinton as well as the Republican
leadership in Congress had to give the problem higher priority in
negotiating a budget that would begin releasing the nearly $1
billion in payments that already has been appropriated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president is going to have to be a little more
outspoken,'' Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., said.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton presses Congress on the arrears, Shays said, ``his
efforts will pay off.'' But Shays added: ``He's going to have to
make it clear that this has to be in the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita M. Lowey, D-N.Y., said that Congress needs a wake-up
call. ``To be the biggest deadbeat at the U.N. is wrong, is
embarrassing, is outrageous,'' Ms. Lowey said.
</P>
<P>
   Shays and Ms. Lowey visited the United Nations on Monday to
focus attention on paying the American debt to the world
organization. They were joined by Rep. Eliot L. Engel, another New
York Democrat, and Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of August, the United States had run up $1.739
billion in unpaid dues and other assessments, according to Joseph
E. Connor, the U.N. undersecretary for management. By the end of
September, he said, he expected some American payments to trim the
arrears to $1.546 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Washington estimates that it owes $1.025 billion, the amount
that Congress and the administration agreed to set aside.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $521 million in dispute includes $324 million in
differences over how much the United States should be assessed for
peacekeeping missions, $97 million in costs that the United States
has refused to pay for its own policy reasons, and $100 million
tied up in a dispute about double taxation of Americans employed by
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Charter says that member states whose arrears total
more than their assessed dues for two years automatically lose
their vote in the General Assembly, which could happen on Jan. 1,
2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS28-COX     09-27 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL's new OT policy not a favorite among ThrashersBy Jeff
Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The reaction was what you would expect from a
goaltender just subjected to an NHL-aided two-on-one break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real happy with the new rule,'' the Thrashers' Damian
Rhodes said about the break by the Rangers' Theo Fleury and Valeri
Kamensky. ``I like five on five better.'' The latest rule change
designed to open up the game and increase scoring borders on
gimmick. Teams tied at the end of regulation will play the
five-minute, overtime with only four skaters each, plus the goalie,
creating more room on the ice and presumably more scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams will be guaranteed a point in the standings, perhaps
making them less fearful of losing that point in the overtime and
more willing to go for the win.
</P>
<P>
   NHL commissioner Gary Bettman orchestrated the change after 27
percent of the games that went into overtime last season _ 60 of
222 _ ended in one team winning. In the past five seasons, 28.6
percent of overtime games concluded in a victory, down from 34.5
the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL experimented with the four-on-four rule in the American
Hockey League for the final 44 games last season, and the change
was significant. The AHL had 33 percent of its overtime games
decided before the rule, 61.4 percent after it. The AHL already had
been awarding one point to each team tied after regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction among players generally is mixed. Rhodes, who
allowed a goal to Kamensky two minutes into overtime of an
exhibition game at Philips Arena, understandably felt safer under
the old rules.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers center Ray Ferraro also said he the league went too
far. ``I don't like it,'' he said. ``I understand why they're doing
it. But to me, if you're trying to gimmick it up for a little more
excitement, play a five-minute overtime five on five. Then if it's
still tied have a shootout. Fans like that better, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But wing Andrew Brunette said, ``It's going to make things a lot
more exciting. If you didn't do something, the overtimes were going
to be just like killing penalties for five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rule probably will favor teams deep in skill players,
such as Colorado, or with enough superstars to carry them for five
minutes, such as the Rangers. Colorado and Dallas, whose forwards
also are excellent defensively, could play four forwards.
</P>
<P>
   But the rule seemingly does not help the Thrashers, given the
apparent lack of goal-scorers on the roster. Ferraro did not say
that the rule would hurt the team, but he said, ``We're going to
have to work for our goals, whether it's five on five or four on
four. We don't want to get into a situation where we're trading
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers have played two overtime games in the preseason _
the 3-2 loss to New York and a 3-3 tie in St. Louis. In the
newfanged NHL standings, their record is 3-2-1-1 _
wins-losses-ties-regulation ties _ for eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's strategy in overtime games, and that of most teams,
will depend on the opponent. If the Thrashers are playing an
Eastern Conference opponent, they probably will lean toward
conservatism, for fear of giving an extra point in the standings to
another team in the playoff race. But those concerns would be
erased against Western teams, given the postseason format.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play the Western teams, we'll probably go for it,''
coach Curt Fraser said. ``You figure you've got the point already
and you've got nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers right wing Kelly Buchberger said he would prefer that
the NHL merely have two teams play a five-on-five overtime ``until
somebody scores.'' But then he thought better of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``With scoring down,'' Buchberger said, ``I guess we could be
playing all night.''
</P>
<P>
   NHL TRYING TO BREAK TIES
</P>
<P>
   _ The rule change: Beginning this season, teams that are tied at
the end of regulation will be assured of one point in the
standings. The teams will play a five-minute, sudden-death overtime
period with a goalie but only four skaters, instead of five. If
neither team scores, the game will end a tie. If one team scores,
that team will be awarded a win and two points in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ramifications: League officials say that assuring teams at
least one point by reaching overtime will lead them to be more
aggressive in the extra period. And the four-on-four skating is
expected to make the overtime more open.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who it helps or hurts: The fast-skating, highly skilled teams,
such as Colorado and Toronto, and those with a handful of talented
scorers, including the New York Rangers, figure to do well in
overtime. The slower teams and those short on scoring talent might
have difficulty keeping pace four on four. The Thrashers could fall
into the second category.
</P>
<P>
   _ New look for standings: The NHL standings this year will have
four categories for a team's record: wins, losses, ties, regulation
ties. For example, the Thrashers are 3-2-1-1 in exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
