<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CREW MAKES A BOAT A YACHT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basically, what I am is a matchmaker,'' said Sandy Carney, who
manages yacht charters for the Alden Group in Jamestown, R.I. Ms.
Carney, whose venerable organization sells and charters the output
of many builders along with designing and building Alden yachts,
regularly visits the major charter shows here and abroad, checking
out the boats and most particularly their crews. She wants to be
sure crew personalities will fit with those of her clients.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced yachters often want to sail and navigate themselves,
but others may want someone else to set the course, do the cooking
and rev up the dinghy. The charterers can decide to moor in one
agreeable harbor or visit many; the crew's task is to get them
there enjoyably.
</P>
<P>
   Bad chemistry between passengers and crew can sour a charter
faster than almost anything. If you rent a house in the Caribbean
and do not like the gardener, avoid the garden; on a yacht charter,
there is no way to walk away. Ms. Sanderson spends a big proportion
of her time talking to boat owners or the professionals whose
services are part of the charter price.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Stewart of Roswell, Ga., president of the Charter Yacht
Brokers Association, said that crew quality was so important that
contracts permitted cancellation by the broker if the crew was
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a ``bare boat,'' one without a crew, there should be a
local presence to help in difficulty. A few years ago, my sister,
brother-in-law and two friends chartered a 40-foot sailboat in
Greece, using the Moorings, a broker with offices around the world.
When the two weeks were nearly up, my relatives, experienced
sailors, found themselves on Mykonos in high winds that they could
not handle.
</P>
<P>
   They called the broker in Athens, who took the ferry over. They
met him on the dock, turned over the keys and rode the ferry to
Piraeus. There was no extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   The yachts offered by brokers sleep 2 to 20. Some boats can make
long ocean passages, but typically they go island-hopping in the
Caribbean or the Bahamas. Family groups are common. Charter brokers
do not put together groups; chartering is like renting a beach
cottage for yourself and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Rates vary widely, but a boat under 75 feet, with a crew of two,
is likely to cost $10,000 a week. In August, I looked at luxurious
``megayachts'' offered by Bob Saxon Associates. These 100-foot
villas of the ocean, white carpets and all, run $55,000 to $60,000
a week for 10 passengers. Whether these prices include provisions
mostly depends on the custom of the area of the charter.
</P>
<P>
   The yacht charter business is unregulated. But three major
associations of brokers have set criteria for membership and
recommendations for keeping the clients' money safe, usually in
escrow accounts. These are the Charter Yacht Brokers Association,
with 65 members, of which Ms. Stewart is president; the American
Yacht Charter Association, with 22 members, who sell only crewed
charters, of which Tina Hinckley of Southwest Harbor, Maine, is
president, and the Mediterranean Yacht Brokers Association, with 82
members, whose president, Alex Braden, is based in London.
</P>
<P>
   The membership criteria require that the broker have been in
business for a certain time: three years for the Mediterranean
group, five for Charter Yacht Brokers, seven for the American Yacht
Charter Association. The broker must have a good reputation among
colleagues who approve the membership.
</P>
<P>
   The most important requirement is that brokers offer only
vessels they have seen. All three groups require that the brokers
attend several major charter shows a year _ in Europe, the
Caribbean and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yacht brokers say they seldom deal with travel agents, even
though they are willing to share the 15 percent commissions. The
brokers deal directly with clients, usually by phone and fax,
coaxing out details on preferences.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ms. Stewart said, she would not charter a boat for
herself if the crew members smoked. She likes to dive; her husband
hopes the owner will let him steer the boat for a while. The
abilities of the chef are more important to some clients than to
others.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ms. Carney's favorite boats is the Shellette, a 55-foot
catamaran sloop in the British Virgin Islands that is almost
completely booked for the winter. Shellette has four cabins to
accommodate eight and is sailed by the owners, Mike and Pam
Donnelly, the captain and first mate-chef. In winter, the boat
costs $11,900 a week, including all expenses except for phone
calls. In the low season, the price is $10,900.
</P>
<P>
   Food and liquor, except for champagne and exotic liquors, are
part of the Caribbean contracts. Crew tips, usually 15 percent of
the cost, are not, said Ms. Carney, whose company has been around
since 1909. In the Mediterranean, the 54-foot sloop Daphne's Smile,
as an example, costs $9,100 a week for six, but few expenses are
included.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a charter requires a 50 percent payment in advance _
how far in advance depends on the popularity of the vessel. The
rules for protecting clients' deposits vary, and Ms. Hinckley said
that her group was pressing the Caribbean yacht organizations not
to release all the escrowed money to the boat owners before the
charter starts.
</P>
<P>
   These customs can vary even by country, so it is important for a
client to learn these details and to ask about trip-cancellation
insurance. Cancellation by the client will probably mean forfeit of
the deposit, although if the boat can be rebooked, all but the
broker's commission will probably be returned.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a year, in September and March, Yachting magazine
publishes a long list of brokers. All are either members of at
least one of the trade groups, or are Yachting advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the magazine is putting out a separate publication,
Vacations Afloat, with broker and boat listings and articles,
costing $5. Yachting also has a Web site, www.yachtingnet.com,
which Kenny Wooton, editor in chief of the magazine, said was being
upgraded. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is how to reach the brokers and organizations mentioned
above:
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Carney, Alden Yacht Charters, 1909 Alden Landing,
Portsmouth, R.I., 02871; www.aldenyachts.com; (800) 253-3654 or
(401) 683-4200, fax (401) 683-3668.
</P>
<P>
   Mediterranean Yacht Brokers Association, c/o Alex Braden,
Yachting Partners International, 28-29 Richmond Place, Brighton,
East Sussex, BN2 2NA, England; (800) 626-0019;
www2.yachtworld.com/myba.
</P>
<P>
   Charter Yacht Brokers Association, c/o Elaine Stewart, Caribbean
Sailing Charters, 3883 Andrews Crossing, Roswell, Ga. 30075; (800)
824-1331, fax (770) 992-0276; www.cyba.net.
</P>
<P>
   American Yacht Charter Association, 18 Market Square, Newport,
R.I. 02840; or Tina Hinckley, Hinckley Crewed Charters, Post Office
Box 6, Southwest Harbor, Maine 04679; (207) 244-0122, fax (207)
0156; www.hinckleyyacht.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Saxon Associates, 1500 Cordova Road, Suite 314, Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. 33316; (954) 760-5801, fax (954) 467-8909,
www.bobsaxon.com.
</P>
