<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 DOLE TELLS STUDENTS ABOUT HER FOREIGN POLICY PLATFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ The seats were taken and so the
undergraduates plunked down in the center aisles, and when those
filled they lined up along the walls and then across the back. A
heavily female crowd turned up Monday to hear Elizabeth Dole
outline her foreign policy platform in an auditorium at the College
of Charleston, drawn more by the marvel of a woman running
seriously for president than by the subject of her speech.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking a week after Gov. George W. Bush of Texas delivered his
own foreign policy address at the Citadel, the city's legendary
military academy famous for its efforts to bar women, Mrs. Dole
covered many of the same themes as Bush, the front-runner for the
Republican Party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking former President Reagan, whom she credited with
bringing down communism, Mrs. Dole proposed a kind of post-Cold War
weapons buildup to reinforce the country's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   She described the current administration as being taken in by
the ``empty promises'' of weak treaties, and by ``rogue and outlaw
nations'' threatening the United States with weapons of mass
destruction. She criticized aid to Russia, saying the money had
``disappeared into offshore accounts and the wallets of Russian
officials,'' while ``the Russian people suffer.'' Her own
administration, she said, would work with ``policies, not
personalities,'' an implicit slap at the White House for propping
up the increasingly discredited president of Russia, Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Coming a few days after Mrs. Dole delivered a policy speech on
education, the foreign policy speech Monday appeared to be an
attempt to lend heft to a campaign in which Mrs. Dole keeps
soldiering on despite Bush's daunting financial advantage. The Bush
campaign has so far collected $52 million; Mrs. Dole would not say
how much she had collected.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, Mrs. Dole vowed to increase military spending and
abandon the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, criticizing an
administration that, she said, ``failed to develop a strong
national or theater missile defense system.''
</P>
<P>
   She also opposed the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which she
called ``neither effective nor verifiable.'' The treaty, which bans
nuclear test explosions, was signed by President Clinton in
September 1996, but has not been ratified by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole also criticized the administration for treating China
as a ``strategic partner'' despite its human rights violations and
its development of advanced weapons systems that, she said, could
threaten the United States. She said China ``imprisons and
persecutes dissidents and religious believers. It employs prison
labor. It steals our nuclear and other military secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it was not clear how the ``two-track policy'' she
proposed, to promote open markets and political reforms in the
communist nation, would differ from current policy objectives. She
pledged that, under a Dole administration, ``throughout the world,
the United States will treat authoritarian and totalitarian states,
such as North Korea, as rogue regimes, not as our equals,'' and
that ``We will encourage and strengthen democratic oppositions
within these countries wherever possible.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush attempted to build credibility for his foreign policy
platform by listing experts he consulted in preparing it, Mrs. Dole
spoke of a trip she made to Poland in 1989 when she served as
secretary of labor for her rival's father, President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   She reminds audiences that as secretary of transportation under
Ronald Reagan, she became the first woman to head a branch of the
armed forces _ the Coast Guard. And on Monday, she spoke of trips
she had made to Somalia, Bosnia and Croatia as head of the American
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Several women who turned out to hear Mrs. Dole said they did not
normally keep up with political issues, but grew interested when
teachers mentioned that Mrs. Dole would be speaking here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the whole idea of her being the first woman running
for president,'' Laura Bogan, a senior majoring in business and
marketing, said. ``I think it's just kind of neat that she's
running.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, however, Ms. Bogan said she did not usually keep up
with foreign affairs, and so did not understand much of Mrs. Dole's
speech. And though she voted for Bob Dole in 1996, she remained
unconvinced after listening to Mrs. Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Several students apparently had not been told that the speech
would focus on foreign policy, and so appeared disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Sharniqua Austin, a sophomore studying biology who recorded the
speech, said she wanted to hear Mrs. Dole talk about domestic
issues. ``I was wondering about the state of the U.S., like what
she thought about things here, as opposed to things in other
countries,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
