<SLUG> BC-MARC-ANTHONY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALSA IDOL MAKING HIS MARK IN POP, ACTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER AND BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In places where Spanish is spoken, Marc Anthony is
held in a regard that approaches reverence. In Spanish Harlem, he's
been referred to as ``a flame that walks.''
</P>
<P>
   But the largest-selling salsa singer in the world didn't catch
fire immediately. Growing up in New York City, Anthony got started
singing in English as a teen in underground clubs specializing in
the minimal electronic dance music known as house, in which a
singer, used merely as another textural instrument, repeats a
phrase over and over with slight variations to the accompaniment of
a pre-recorded rhythm track.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, percussionist and band leader Tito Puente asked Anthony
to open his revue at Madison Square Garden. After appearing in
front of such a large crowd, Anthony lost his appetite for clubs
and a year later transformed a song made popular by Latin superstar
Juan Gabriel into a salsa number.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he began recording a string of
multi-million-selling salsa albums, ``Otra Nota (Another Tune),''
``Todo a Su Tiempo (All in Time)'' and ``Contra la Corriente
(Against the Flow),'' which snagged the best tropical Latin
performance Grammy this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other audiences took note of Anthony in 1997 when he was the
first actor cast in Paul Simon's short-lived Broadway musical,
``The Capeman.'' Simon had gone to a Latin record store and asked
for examples of the best young salsa singers around.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me two or three guys and I listened to (Anthony) and
thought, `This is good ... really good,''' Simon said. ``In fact,
he was clearly the best.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the skinny kid from a crowded working-class home in
East Harlem is about to explode. Last year, Columbia signed Anthony
to a multirecord contract worth more than $30 million. He's
returning to singing in English, and his hotly anticipated
self-titled collection of love songs goes on sale today.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the 31-year-old singer has a high-profile role
with Nicolas Cage in Martin Scorsese's ``Bringing Out the Dead,''
opening Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just great,'' Scorsese said. ``He has this great face
and eyes, a very small build. He'd never done anything quite like
(the part as a deranged street person) before. It was a very
physically demanding performance.''
</P>
<P>
   We met Anthony while he was in town to talk about the Scorsese
film.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your take on the number of Latino performers,
including Ricky Martin and Jennifer Lopez, who've suddenly been
anointed hot?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know what we're crossing over from or to. We've been
here all along. It's so disappointing the lack of education as far
as our culture is concerned. Latin music is Latin music, and what I
recorded on this album and what Ricky recorded on his album and
what Jennifer recorded on her album does not represent Latin music
at all. It's pop music and the only common denominator is we're all
Puerto Rican. And I've heard it all, starting with, ``Wow, you
people are ...'' Like we're aliens or something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you think this trend has been portrayed?
</P>
<P>
   A: If I see another article with a jalapeno pepper next to my
name or a set of maracas or a sombrero or the words muy caliente
... you know what I'm saying?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has too much been made of the ethnicity of these performers? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A: I don't want to be known as ``that Puerto Rican pop
singer.'' What does Puerto Rican have to do with it? I'm proud to
be Puerto Rican, but it's not all there is. You have to be in my
shoes to know what it feels like. It's almost like you don't belong
in your own back yard. Or you're stepping into someone else's
world. It's like, ``Here they come, here they come.'' But it's all
a matter of educating people. We're all Latin performers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does your new ballads album represent your taste in music? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A: I was born and raised Puerto Rican _ very Puerto Rican _ and
American, so I'm bicultural. For the last 7{ years, I've been
tapping into the Latin side of it. And it's been a trip. I've seen
some amazing things. I've also tapped into other influences _ being
born and raised in New York as American as the next one. This album
truly represents my taste in music and where I'm at as a man, an
artist and a father (of a 5-year-old girl) _ as everything.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who have been your main influences musically? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A: Paul Simon and Ruben Blades, who's my absolute all-time
idol. I was his water boy when I was 15 on tour. I was in charge of
the water. And I sat back and had the pleasure and honor to be in
the same room as Paul Simon as he wrote the songs (for ``Capeman'')
and he'd throw ideas at me. We developed this rhythm where my
opinion became important. He became one of my closest friends. It
was amazing. The realization that I'd learned enough to be
respected by those I respected was sobering. I have nothing but
incredible things to say of the whole experience.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How was your acting experience in ``Bringing Out the Dead''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Acting and singing come from the same place. It's all about
storytelling at the end of the day. It just takes different
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's been predicted your latest album will do very well in
terms of sales. Does that part of it concern you? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A: I handed in the record and said, ``I'm in the business of
making records. You guys who sell records, do what you've gotta
do.'' But you're looking at one satisfied human being. I couldn't
be happier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's next for you? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A: I'm going to record two albums _ a salsa one and a
Spanish-rock album. And a world tour.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
