<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-EXTRADITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL OPENS FOR PINOCHET WITH LISTING OF 35 CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Lawyers arguing that Gen. Augusto Pinochet should be
extradited to Spain to stand trial on torture charges said at a
hearing Monday that he faces ``some of the most serious allegations
of crime ever to come before English criminal courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35 charges, which took the clerk of the court 15 minutes to
read in a steady monotone, include allegations of beating, burning,
caging, binding, starving, sodomizing and suspending victims when
he was the Chilean dictator.
</P>
<P>
   The list covers the enforced use of hallucinogenic drugs,
threats of rape and disfigurement and the use of electric shocks on
a 17-year-old youth, leading to his death. In one case, a woman was
said to have been interrogated while she was naked, and threats
were made to attack her 9-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, 83, who is under house arrest in the London suburbs,
was not at Bow Street Magistrates Court for the start of the week
of hearings, but he will be required to appear next month when the
judge, Ronald Bartle, issues his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet has said he was not responsible for what others might
have done, and a Scotland Yard official testified Monday that the
general rejected allegations of torture read to him at his rented
house in April during the presentation of a formal arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with this,'' the police officer, Detective
Inspector Andrew Hewitt, quoted Pinochet as saying. ``I had
absolutely nothing to do with any of these charges. All these
charges, I completely negate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt said that Pinochet continued: ``I am being humiliated. I
am a general, 64 years' service. I'm a gentleman who knows about
honor. Don't worry, I'm not going to comply with this. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chanting and flag-waving supporters of Pinochet outnumbered
opponents outside the court in downtown London, but it was the
anti-Pinochet faction that took heart from the day's proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is that for the first time a head of
state is the subject of an extradition hearing,'' said Juan Garces,
55, a Spanish lawyer who was an adviser to Salvador Allende, the
president ousted in the 1973 coup that brought Pinochet to power.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Brody, advocacy director of Human Rights Watch, said many
victims of the Pinochet years had waited 25 years for this moment.
``For the Crown prosecutors to formally read out the charges of
torture and conspiracy against General Pinochet and to utter the
names of people who were killed, tortured or disappeared by his
regime has given them a form of justice for all their suffering,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   All the alleged crimes were said to have occurred after 1988,
the period declared relevant for the extradition case by England's
highest court in a March decision that threw out nearly 3,000
charges of murder, kidnapping and crimes against humanity and
reduced the scope of the case to torture and conspiracy to torture.
It was in 1988 that torture overseas became a crime punishable in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was arrested in London last Oct. 16 on an extradition
request by Baltasar Garzon, a Spanish magistrate investigating the
so-called dirty wars in Latin America in the 1970s. The case has
been through a number of rulings and appeals involving this
country's highest tribunal, the Law Lords of the House of Lords,
and leading to Monday's session.
</P>
<P>
   Bartle will rule solely on whether the Spanish petition is in
order and whether the alleged crimes are extraditable ones under
British law. Under the European Convention on Extradition, Spain
does not have to offer any evidence to support the charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Alun Jones, the British lawyer representing the Spanish
prosecutors, noted that the 1984 Convention Against Torture _ which
Britain has ratified, as has Spain and Chile _ was incorporated
into the law of the United Kingdom in December 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not engaged in these proceedings in consideration to
some broad, sweeping rhetorical declaration of international
intent,'' he said. He declared that the matter under consideration
was now ``black-lettered U.K. law.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, he added, it was ``simply facile'' to contend
that the charges are a matter for Chile and no one else. The
general's supporters contend that Chile is the proper place for him
to be judged, and in his only court appearance since his arrest,
Pinochet told a bail hearing in December that he did not recognize
any court other than a Chilean one to pass judgment on him.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' assertion of international law and jurisdiction in the
case anticipated a challenge from Pinochet's lawyers later this
week of Spain's right to try him because none of the alleged
victims were themselves Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allegations against General Pinochet do indeed constitute
some of the most serious allegations of crime ever to come before
an English court,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   He also argued that the court could consider ``disappearances''
that occurred before the 1988 date as conspiracy to torture
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our case that the continuing offense of conspiracy to
torture after December 1988 has, as one of its objects, that the
fate of these people would continue to be concealed from families
causing severe mental pain, suffering and demoralization,'' Jones
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
