<HEADER>
A8109 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-MUSIC-OPERA-495&AMP;ADD-S     09-27 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OPERA-495&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SAN FRANCISCO OPERA'S NEXT DIRECTOR, A HOMECOMING OF SORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &LR;   &LR; _ Pamela Rosenberg has spent her entire career
in Europe, but when she becomes general director of the San
Francisco Opera in August 2001, she'll be returning to the company
where she first fell in love with opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is where my roots are,'' she said Monday from
her office at the Stuttgart Opera, where she's been co-director
since 1991. ``From 1962 to 1966 I saw every single production
there, and it's where I got my first taste for opera.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days the Los Angeles-born Rosenberg was an
undergraduate at the University of California at Berkeley, studying
history while pursuing a burgeoning interest in music. Now, at 54,
she's poised to become the only woman running a major American
opera company.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment became official Monday, when the board named
Rosenberg the company's fifth general director. She will succeed
Lotfi Mansouri, who has held the post since 1988 and in February
announced his decision to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Board President William W. Godward said the board had approved
the appointment without reservation. ``We were looking for someone
with artistic knowledge and experience in actually putting opera on
stage, and (Rosenberg) had them both,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, a large part of Rosenberg's appeal was her
combination of American background and European experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a European administrator, I have something to bring to the
American scene _ particularly when it comes to showing some of the
visual and psychological exploration that has been going on in
Europe over the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm also an American, and I'm tuned in to American
sensibilities. So even though I'm known for having done some
adventurous theatrical work, they know that I will be sensitive to
what I bring to San Francisco. I'm not going to come in and shove
radical things down their throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Mansouri, Rosenberg started her career as a director,
although she gave it up when she became an administrator (``I was
solid, but to direct you have to be better than that''). She went
to Europe in 1966 to study at Bayreuth, then at the Guildhall
School of Music and Drama in London.
</P>
<P>
   Her formative experience, though, was her stint from 1977 to
1987 at the Frankfurt Opera under the innovative music director
Michael Gielen. That was where she acquired her commitment to the
adventurous theatrical style that has marked her Stuttgart tenure
and that she considers a distinctively European value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about being in Europe, and Germany in particular, is
that there are so many opera houses. Within one hour's train ride
of Stuttgart there are seven houses, and within an hour's flight
there are too many to count. And the fact that you can see so many
different productions of `Fidelio,' say, means that you can comment
on the piece or explore different aspects of it, instead of
producing something definitive that will stay around for the next
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American approach is more like preserving a piece frozen
in time, whereas exploration in Europe tends to develop much more
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rosenberg's track record in Stuttgart extends to repertoire as
well, with productions of operas by such modernist masters as Luigi
Nono and Wolfgang Rihm, as well as commissions to younger
composers. ``I do think this is a living art form, and part of our
mission is to present the substantial works of our time. But I also
have the full intention of tapping the artists and composers of the
Bay Area, most obviously John Adams.''
</P>
<P>
   She also expressed interest in trying to pull off the
long-overdue American stage premiere of ``Saint Fran &LR; c &LR; ois
d'Assise,'' the towering 1983 magnum opus of the late Olivier
Messiaen.
</P>
<P>
   A project like that, of course, depends on financing, which is
where Rosenberg _ accustomed to the generous artistic subsidies
provided by the Germans _ may face her stiffest challenge. But she
sounds undaunted. ``It's true that I haven't had to go out and do
lots of fund raising here,'' she says, ``but I know what I'm
facing. I'm an American _ I know my Californians.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
