<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-TRENDS-     09-27 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-TRENDS-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T DRESS FOR DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Oct. 3)  
(jt) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a fall and winter cruise season in which discounts
abound, in which more ships will sail from more ports than ever and
in which there will be a plethora of new ships, it may not seem
especially newsworthy that beginning this month Silversea Cruises
has revised its dress code for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the revision also explains why, as the year 2000 draws
nearer, there are so many discounts, so many new ports and why when
Royal Caribbean's new Voyager of the Seas begins it Caribbean
cruises from Miami in November, it will have berths for 3,100
passengers. It is also the reason industry officials speak
hopefully of attracting 6 million passengers this year, up from
last year's record 5.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first. And for most cruise aficionados, that
means anything in the way of discounts and new ports of call. This
fall, winter and spring there are plenty of both. Crystal Cruises
alone is adding new calls in 60 countries and territories,
including Easter Island, Pitcairn Island and Abidjan, Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   As for discounts, Cunard and Seabourn Cruise Line, both owned by
Carnival Corp., are offering big reductions this fall on business
class air fare for select Mediterranean cruises. In addition,
Cunard is offering free passage between New York or Miami and San
Francisco via the Panama Canal for passengers who buy the New York
or Miami segments to Hong Kong, Bombay or Singapore. And fares for
most Cunard cruises next year will average 20 percent less than in
1999, to bring them more in line with prices at resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Couples sailing on Costa Cruises' seven-night Caribbean cruises
can save up to $1,000 if they book at least 120 days ahead.
Passengers who book any cruise of a week or more in the new year on
the Delta Queen, Mississippi Queen or American Queen will receive
free round-trip air fare. Discounts of up to $2,000 off published
rates are available on two World Cruise Co. voyages beginning next
March, including $500 a person for a 110-day cruise from the
Antarctic to the Arctic.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller ships are also offering a variety of discounts. Lindblad
Special Expeditions will take 20 percent off the total voyage cost
for passengers who book any two consecutive voyages next year
aboard its Caledonian Star. Silversea Cruises will give repeat
passengers 15 percent off both its millennium voyages, as well as
free first-class air fare for certain other cruises. The Radisson
Diamond and the company's new Seven Seas Navigator are offering 50
percent savings off the second-person fare for an array of cruises
between Nov. 20 and May 10. And Clipper Cruise Line's 17-day
cruises from Australia and New Zealand include free round-trip air
fare from Los Angeles to each country.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that cruise discounts are not always what they
seem. While most advertised discount fares doubtless result in
savings, most are also larded with restrictions, and markdowns are
generally off fares listed in the brochures, which few passengers
pay.
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure why there are so many discounts so far in
advance of the sailings, especially with the strong economy. But
there is some concern that without them, many people will wait to
book until well after the millennium, when prices return to normal.
There is also industry concern that another mild winter will dampen
enthusiasm for sailing to the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Others attribute the discounts to fear of a delayed backlash
resulting from the $18 million fine imposed on Royal Caribbean this
summer for having dumped hazardous chemicals and oil from nine
ships in coastal waters around the United States, then trying to
cover up. Worse, the $18 million fine came just two years after
Royal Caribbean was fined $9 million after pleading guilty to nine
counts of dumping, and after promising to stop polluting. This
summer also, Carnival Cruise Lines disclosed in court that in the
five years ended last August, members of its crews had been accused
of sexually assaulting passengers or fellow workers 62 times _ a
number since raised to more than 100. In addition, Carnival's
Tropicale was disabled by a fire in the engine room Sept. 18 in the
Gulf of Mexico, forcing it to return to Port Manatee, 30 miles from
Tampa. (The cruise line said it planned to resume sailings of the
vessel Oct. 18; passengers were offered alternative cruises,
refunds, future discounts and transportation.) This fire followed
one on Carnival's Ecstasy last year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the more significant changes in the industry is the
expansion to nontraditional cities and ports. In just a few years
Boston has grown from a mini-cruise port to the home port for the
Norwegian Majesty. Last year it received 62 ship visits; this year
it will receive 80, by ships large and small _ from the Royal
Caribbean's Splendour of the Seas with more than 2,000 passengers
to the Silversea's Silver Cloud with 296 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The Carnival Destiny has scheduled three cruises from Boston
next spring, as well as a one-night cruise and a five-day cruise to
the Bahamas from both Charleston, S.C., and Newport News, Va.
Carnival will also sail from Texas for the first time, beginning
next October, with year-round cruises from Galveston to the western
Caribbean on the 1,486-passenger Celebration. Next May, Premier
Cruises' Island Breeze will sail to Veracruz, Cozumel and Playa del
Carmen from Houston, which is also the home port for the Norwegian
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Also in May, the Norwegian Sky will begin seven-day cruises to
Alaska from Seattle, while Royal Caribbean's 2,000-passenger Vision
of the Seas will offer a total of six cruises between Seattle and
the Canadian cities of Victoria and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   When Commodore Cruise Lines' new Crown Dynasty begins cruises to
Bermuda next spring, 18 will depart from Philadelphia and the
remaining four from Baltimore. More than 22 ships from nine lines
will call at San Diego next year, including Holland America's
1,260-passenger Statendam and Carnival's first ever cruises from
San Diego to the Baja peninsula (or, as the cruise industry insists
on calling it, the Mexican Riviera). The main reason for this
expansion is to attract passengers within a driving distance of
about 200 miles, and to be able to schedule more of the shorter
cruises that are so popular. Two million passengers are expected on
more than 1,300 cruises of five days or less this year, according
to the Cruise Lines International Association, compared with 1.7
million passengers last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises to Europe and the Mediterranean continue to grow in
popularity, largely because of the chance to combine a cruise with
visits to many cultural and historic treasures. This year's
sailings to the region will number 1,730, 16 percent more than
last, and Crystal Symphony's Mediterranean sailings this month will
include lectures on art and architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Theme cruises also remain popular, including jazz and big band
themes, lectures about nutrition and almost anything about sports.
The Norwegian Sea's baseball cruise to the Western Caribbean
beginning Nov. 28 will include such former greats as Bob Feller
(Cleveland Indians), Ralph Kiner (Pittsburgh Pirates) and Billy
Williams (Chicago Cubs). For the first time, it will include two
former greats from the All-American Girls Professional Baseball
League _ Pepper Paire and Lefty Hohlmayer _ that was the subject of
the 1992 film ``A League of Their Own.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, about Silversea's revised dress code. Women will still be
required to wear gowns or cocktail dresses during ``formal''
nights, of which there are three on a typical 11-day sailing, and
men will still have to wear tuxedos, dinner jackets or dark suits.
But on the five ``informal'' evenings on such a cruise, women can
opt for short dresses, or pants suits, while men can dispense with
the tie, and on ``casual'' nights, of which there are typically
three, women might wear separates, and men resort attire. The
revision, the cruise line explained, is in response to ``a national
trend toward a more casual approach to attire for both business and
vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the age of elegance has ebbed, on the high seas
as elsewhere. The great majority of Americans who have been on a
cruise or intend to go on one have made it known they prefer
informality. So most cruise lines have responded by adding dining
options where neckties and dresses are not required and rarely
encountered.
</P>
<P>
   The Voyager of the Seas, for example, will have three main
dining rooms, each named for (and its decor patterned after) an
opera; three casual dining rooms (including a '50s-style Johnny
Rockets); an Italian restaurant; a patisserie, and a caviar bar.
The Carnival Triumph, which entered service in July, has two main
dining rooms plus a casual dining area with a New York-style deli,
Asian specialties and a 24-hour pizzeria _ plus a South Beach Club
bistro and a Vienna coffeehouse.
</P>
<P>
   There will always be some passengers even on megaships who will
continue to dress, and Cunard hopes to preserve a slice of elegance
with its advertising campaign that speaks of the time, as one ad
puts it, ``when gentlemen on Queen Mary dressed for dinner, and
passengers wore T-shirts  &UR; under &LR;  their clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But for better or worse, the abundance and variety of discount
fares, the likelihood of attracting six million passengers and the
race to build new ships to sail to more and distant ports are
intimately bound up in the ``more casual approach to attire'' that
even Silversea Cruises, one of the handful of luxury lines, has
found irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
