<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8115 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRY-ART-10     09-27 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRY-ART-1020(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY SHOWS RUSSIANS LAUNDERED MONEY THROUGH U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic and map are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIMINI, Italy _ A two-year criminal investigation in Italy has
turned up evidence that alleged Russian organized-crime operators
have funneled millions of dollars through the Bank of New York in
what Italian prosecutors called a money-laundering scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Through an examination of bank records and telephone wiretaps,
investigators in this seaside town in northeastern Italy say they
have uncovered the first concrete examples of illicit funds moving
through a group of accounts at the Bank of New York that are under
investigation by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors here say criminal gangs were raising money in
Italy through a mixture of legitimate business activities as well
as extortion and tax fraud. The funds, investigators suspect, were
regularly routed to Moscow and New York, where, bank records show,
they were transferred to Italian bank accounts belonging to
suspected organized-crime operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be assumed that part of large sums of money that have
been transferred into Italian bank accounts are the proceeds from
protection racketeering with regard to Russian businessmen,'' said
Daniele Barberini, an investigating magistrate here, in an arrest
order issued in February for the leader of the reputed Russian
crime gang.
</P>
<P>
   The case appears to involve small-time racketeers who allegedly
demanded payments from Russian traders in Italy who exported
consumer goods to Russia. Those payoffs, investigators believe,
went to the Bank of New York, passing through accounts of Benex
Corp. and winding up in Italian bank accounts belonging to
suspected organized-crime operators.
</P>
<P>
   Benex and a group of related accounts at the New York bank are
at the center of a federal money-laundering investigation. The
Benex network of accounts was the pipeline through which at least
$7.5 billion moved from Russia into the Bank of New York in the
last three years, according to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   So far there have been two arrests in Italy and international
arrest warrants have been issued for 10 more people.
</P>
<P>
   The examination uncovered three accounts in which money flowed
through the Bank of New York to bank accounts in Italy. In one
case, $5.5 million went from Benex to the Italian bank account of
Boris Rizner. Rizner, 34, is a Ukrainian and a reputed member of a
local gang for whom an arrest warrant for racketeering has been
issued in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, Vladimir Zabolotsky, another alleged Moscow
gang member, had a bank account in Italy that received money from
the Benex and Torfinex Corp. accounts at the Bank of New York. An
international arrest warrant has been issued for him.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man could be reached for comment. The Bank of New York,
which is cooperating with the U.S. authorities, said it would have
no comment on the transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation here was triggered in October 1997, when a
Russian businessman, Pavel Markovitsev, complained to the Italian
police of harassment by Russian and Ukrainian racketeers in Moscow
and in Italy, Barberini said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Markovitsev's testimony to the Italian investigators led to the
arrest in February of Yossif Roizis, a 52-year old native of
Ukraine and a naturalized U.S. citizen, who is considered by the
Italian officials to be the head of a crime gang operating in this
part of northeast Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Roizis faces trial on extortion, kidnapping and racketeering
charges. He could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeds in this extortion racket, investigators said, were
considerable, but they could not specify an exact amount. Its
activities appear to have continued from the early 1990s until
1998, when it was effectively broken by the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Markovitsev was one of thousands of small-time businessmen who
began landing in towns around Rimini on Italy's eastern Adriatic
Sea coast for a mix of beach and business after the collapse of the
old Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   These small-time traders, armed with bundles of cash ranging
from several hundred dollars to $70,000, bought Italian consumer
goods with the intention of sending them back to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The region around Rimini is dotted with small family-run
companies that produce a range of goods, including apparel items
like shoes and hosiery, but also home furnishings and furniture.
The companies supply their products to big European name brands but
also sell goods under their own label through private channels.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the suppliers were known to the Russians from business
deals during the final years of the Soviet Union. And their
reputation for high quality at attractive prices lured Russian
importers here as demand for Western goods soared in the early
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak in the mid-1990s, Italian officials said, some
60,000 to 70,000 Russians were arriving at Rimini's tiny airport
each year. Today the international arrivals gate is marked in
Italian and Russian. Posters around the airport advertise, in
Russian, companies offering services for Russian businessmen
looking for Italian wholesalers. On the tarmac, Russian-built
Antonov cargo planes are often seen loading goods headed for
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators, Roizis had grown powerful in the
Rimini area organizing the export of Italian consumer goods. His
legitimate businesses included trading in these goods, but he and
his associates boosted their income by offering to introduce
Russian traders to Italian manufacturers _ for a commission.
</P>
<P>
   Russians who refused to go along, like Markovitsev, soon found
themselves subjected to beatings and the tires of their cars were
slashed. Some were taken to local hotels, held for hours and
subjected to threats, a practice that qualifies under Italian law
as kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Another money-making ploy was to demand that the Russian
businessmen hand over the invoices for the Italian goods they
bought. Armed with these, the racketeers went to Italian tax
authorities and wangled reimbursement for the value-added tax that
the Russian businessmen had paid on the goods. Such levies are
routinely reimbursed to exporters who can prove the products were
not sold in Italy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Italian prosecutors have focused on twelve gang members,
thanks to telephone taps that were made possible by information
provided by Markovitsev.
</P>
<P>
   But before the arrests were ordered, investigators had set about
reviewing the bank accounts of the suspected mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   Barberini said that records of bank transactions between April
1997 and May 1998, brought to light numerous smaller transactions
that came out of the Bank of New York to Italy and that totaled
about $5.5 million. That included a series of transactions in which
about $700,000 was paid into an account at a local bank, the
Credito Cooperativo Ospedaletto, belonging to Rizner, an associate
of Roizis, the reputed gang leader who is under arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian investigators have been unable to trace the movement
of the money back beyond the Bank of New York, though Barberini
said he hoped the FBI would be able to help find out how the money
got to the bank and where it originated.
</P>
<P>
   His suspicion is that the proceeds from both the gang's
legitimate activities and its illegal ones were regularly
transferred to Moscow, from where it was laundered by passing
through the Benex accounts at the Bank of New York and returned to
the gang in Rimini. There the money was then used to buy fresh
Italian goods for sale in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In other transactions through the Bank of New York, over $1
million went into an account at a local branch of the Banco di Roma
in the name of Zabolotsky, another gang member, in the same period
of 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The money was traced back through the Bank of New York to
several companies in the United States, Barberini said, though the
largest amounts came from Benex and two related companies, Torfinex
Corp. of New York, and BECS International LLC, a New Jersey
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Berlin, a Russian-born businessman, is suspected of having
opened at least one account at the Bank of New York on behalf of
Torfinex, a money-transferring firm that shared offices with Benex
in New York. Berlin is married to Lucy Edwards, a Bank of New York
vice president who has been fired since the the federal
investigation surfaced last month.
</P>
<P>
   BECS has been known to the FBI since 1998, when Russian
investigators asked it for help in tracing a $300,000 ransom
payment made to racketeers in Moscow for the release of a Russian
kidnapping victim.
</P>
<P>
   Italian investigators are continuing their inquiry and are now
looking into whether the Rimini gang's sources of income extend to
other illegal activities, like prostitution or trafficking in drugs
or arms.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, the history of the gang leader, Roizis, gives them
reason to believe there may be more to discover.
</P>
<P>
   As early as the 1980s Roizis had been detained in Italy on
suspicion of drug trafficking between Italy and the United States,
but he was released on bail by the Italians.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1995, in a raid that Italian investigators made on
Roizis' home in Fano, a resort south of Rimini, police seized
Roizis together with Monya Elson, the reputed head of a Russian
emigre crime gang in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Elson had earlier fled to Italy to hide out with Roizis after
narrowly surviving several unsuccessful attacks on his life,
including a 1993 shooting attack in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Elson, who is believed by the FBI to have close ties to another
Russian gangland figure, Semyon Mogilevich, was indicted in New
York on charges of masterminding a five-year reign of violence in
the United States that included at least three gangland murders
related to drug trafficking, racketeering and extortion. In an
interview in May with the Village Voice, Elson called himself a
``partner'' of Mogilevich.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian police arrested Roizis and Elson on charges of money
laundering and smuggling jewelry in and out of Italy, but later
extradited Elson to the United States, where he is being held
pending trial on the racketeering and murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Roizis faces trial in Italy, on charges of money laundering and
smuggling. He may also stand trial separately for racketeering,
extortion, threats, and kidnapping of Russian businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Barberini, the investigating magistrate, said Roizis had
occasionally cooperated with Italian investigators. Two years ago
he supplied information that led to the arrest of 13 Russian
mobsters operating in Italy, including Yuri Essin, a reputed
Russian gang leader, and an Italian businessman who was a former
executive of the large Italian oil company Eni, on charges of
racketeering and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russians, including Essin, and the Italian executive
were acquitted when the wiretap evidence on which the case rested
was declared inadmissible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
