<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8118 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CHILE-2TAKES-$     09-27 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CHILE-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLACIAL COCKTAIL PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 3) 
(jt) 
 By SHIRLEY CHRISTIAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To sense the delight of a cruise on the Skorpios III along the
southern coast of Chile, imagine this scene the day we returned to
the ship for lunch after a morning spent gazing in awed silence at
the sapphire beauty of a mile-wide glacier. As some of us competed
to find the right superlatives to describe the experience, the
Colombian priest on my right raised his wine glass and toasted the
captain, Constantino Kochifas, at the other end of the table with
the words: ``Captain, you have brought us to the gates of Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutting through the waters surrounding the natural ice
sculptures in front of San Rafael Glacier at almost 47 degrees
south latitude was the high point of the six-day cruise, but every
day in the fjords, lakes and gulfs seemed made for postcards, right
up to the 10 p.m. sunsets we watched through the dining room
windows as we ate. The trip was half adventure and half lazy
pleasure, a few parts funky and a few parts luxury.
</P>
<P>
   I had traveled and lived in Chile, and had long dreamed of
taking a trip on one of the vessels of the family-run Skorpios
line. It was a special thrill to fly out of the Midwest on a
January afternoon with snow in the forecast and land 12{ hours
later in Santiago, the capital, at the height of summer.
</P>
<P>
   From Santiago, I flew almost 600 miles farther south to Puerto
Montt, the main port in the Chilean lake region, to board the
Skorpios III, a bright orange and white vessel with three sun
decks. Dinner was nearly over that Friday night when I arrived from
the airport, and a waiter put me at a table alone, but Mimi de
Kochifas, the captain's wife, walked over and set the easy,
gracious tone that was to mark the cruise. She said that because I
spoke Spanish she would to put me at her husband's table starting
at breakfast the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   I was pleased with the comfort of my twin-bed cabin. At 195
square feet, it felt roomy, and the porthole was a real window, a
good three feet wide. I was on the Acropolis Deck, the second of
five levels. Fine paneling, made from the beautiful woods for which
the south of Chile is known, went halfway up the walls. The bath
was small, sleek and modern, with a walk-in shower and an adequate
vanity. There was an ample closet, a mini-safe, two chairs and a
small table, television and internal telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The Skorpios III is the newest of the line's three passenger
vessels. Built in 1995, the 1,210-ton ship is 230 feet long and can
carry 125 passengers and a crew of 34. Its sister ship, Skorpios
II, built in 1988 with similar dimensions and room for 35 more
passengers, made the same cruise on the same schedule, usually
dropping anchor at ports just before or after we did.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, after a late breakfast, we sailed south out of
Puerto Montt, lounging on the sun decks and waving goodbye to the
snow-topped volcano in the distance. The waiters brought us festive
aperitifs, including pisco sours, the Chilean national cocktail,
made of a strong grape-based liquour, lemon juice, powdered sugar
and egg white. Our voyage was taking us to the San Rafael Glacier
and back, a distance of about 400 nautical miles each way. We would
be sailing through interior coastal waters, among the hundreds of
islands, islets and peninsulas that make up the far south of Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Chile's weather, terrain and flora have much in common with the
West Coast of the United States and Canada _ but with the seasons
in reverse. It is a skinny country that stretches for nearly 3,000
miles along the west side of South America. The desert is in the
far north, the central region has a temperate climate, and the
south is similar to the Pacific Northwest _ a green and often rainy
area with vast forests and good fishing.
</P>
<P>
   We spent all of the first day sailing, passing through the
Llanquihue Archipelago, the Gulf of Ancud and the Gulf of
Corcovado. The scenery was a blend of tranquil farm scenes, an
occasional fishing village and, in the distance, the lower Andes,
dwindling down to a mere 7,000 to 8,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, as the waiters generously poured fine Chilean wines,
we all introduced ourselves and learned that we came from 14
countries. Argentines and Brazilians were the most numerous,
followed by Chileans. Others came from elsewhere in Latin America.
A few came from Europe and Japan, a family of three from Australia;
I was the only passenger from the United States. Several children
were aboard, ranging in age from 7 or 8 to the early teens. An
English-speaking interpreter helped those who didn't speak Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Kochifas told us his family's story. His father immigrated to
Chile from Greece and eventually settled in Puerto Montt and set up
a tailoring business. The sons, growing up surrounded by water and
fishing boats, learned to sail. Starting from scratch, the captain
first built and ran a series of small cargo ships, then some 20
years ago built his first passenger vessel and began to bring
passengers to the island-studded seas and secret fjords. His older
brother, Demostenes, was the second pilot on our ship. A son was
the pilot of the Skorpios II. Other Kochifases were working behind
the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The captain promised us a cocktail called a 12 and 30 once we
reached the glacier. The ingredients: 12-year-old Scotch over
30,000-year-old ice _ the estimated age of the glacier. All of the
ice we consumed on the ship came from the huge chunks that
continually broke from the glacier and slipped into the surrounding
lagoon. The glacier and lagoon are in a national park whose unique
biosphere is recognized by Unesco; the ice is formed from snow
falling on a peak seldom visited by humans.
</P>
<P>
   We quickly settled into a pleasant routine of four meals a day _
breakfast, lunch, tea and dinner, plus morning and evening
aperitifs with nuts and chips in the Apollo and Zeus bars. The
menus ranged from haute cuisine to sturdy Chilean peasant fare, and
it was all very good. Salmon, which is farmed along the coast in
the area, was a staple along with other local fish including sea
bass, and there were heaping platters of shellfish hauled aboard
mid-voyage from small fishing boats. One night, the Chilean college
student on my left put away almost six dozen oysters on the half
shell. We also had steak and chicken, and the kitchen staff
accommodated special requests made a few hours ahead.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The weather was ideal. It felt much warmer under the midsummer
sun and cloudless skies than the projected 54 to 72 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   On our third day out, however, I awoke and looked out the window
to something awesomely different. The glacier was rising out of the
surrounding gray mist as a steady rain beat down on the ship and
the waters of the lagoon. The mass of ice glistened white and
crystal blue. Two small ice cutters had been lowered from the ship
and were waiting to carry us closer to the glacier. The rain was
going to make our excursion rather cold and uncomfortable, but it
lent drama to the day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I put on layer upon layer of clothing; as we stepped onto the
ice cutters, the crew handed out life jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the glacier, we first noticed floating around us the
huge chunks of ice, pieces that had broken off as if an artist had
been wielding a chisel, creating free-form sculptures in strikingly
varied shades of blue, gray, green and stark white.
</P>
<P>
   San Rafael Glacier, the centerpiece of a national park of the
same name, is part of an ice field created by ice and snow tumbling
down Mount San Valentin, which towers 13,300 feet above the lagoon.
The captain told us that the glacier was first seen by Europeans
some 400 years ago and that, at the rate it was crumbling, would be
gone in 200 years. The ice field extends well inland from the
lagoon into an area virtually inaccessible except by foot across
rugged terrain. On maps of the region, the ice appears to cover
about 60 miles north-south and roughly half that east-west. What we
saw was a section an estimated 7,300 feet wide that forms an icy
path between mountain peaks, rising to a height of 230 feet above
the water and reaching a depth of more than 750 feet into the
lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   As promised, while we circled before the glacier, crew members
jumped up onto one of the chunks of ice and chipped off enough to
fill several ice buckets, then brought out fine glassware and
poured everybody a hefty amount of Scotch over those crystal-clear
rocks. They opened a hamper filled with small sandwiches and
followed with hot coffee. With the food and drink gone _ along with
most of our film _ we began to feel the chill and were more than
ready to return to the comfort of the Skorpios III.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, as a whisper of sun began to peek through the
clouds, Demostenes Kochifas guided the ship closer to the wall of
ice, and some of us crowded around him on the bridge to watch as,
every few minutes, a piece would split from the front of the
glacier and cascade into the lagoon. Those of us with cameras tried
capturing the moment when the ice splashed into the water.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m., we turned our backs on the glacier and sailed back
north toward sunny skies and warmer weather.
</P>
<P>
   We reached Quitralco Fjord, jutting deep into another national
park, this one covered with forests and fields of wildflowers. We
dropped anchor at a dock beside a dining hall and thermal baths
that the cruise line operates on the edge of the wilderness, and
some passengers went ashore for a quick dip in the 90-degree
waters.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, we raced in small boats through the fingers of
water branching off from the main fjord, then returned for what
Latin Americans call a parrillada _ a mixed-grill feast. We began
with the tasty meat pies, empanadas, followed by steak, sausages,
potatoes, salad and the usual good wines. On the wall behind our
table were models of the nearly dozen boats and ships the captain
had built, from his first tiny cargo vessel. There were also old
family photos and a big one of the captain and Gabriel Garcia
Marquez, the Nobel Laureate in literature, together at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   From Quitralco, our ship continued lazily north, through
countryside that had the look of Switzerland _ black and white
cattle grazed in neat pastures on rolling hillsides, framed by vast
stands of trees. We were back to basking in the sun in our bathing
suits. On the west lay the large island Chiloe, some 125 miles long
and one of the places identified with Darwin's voyage to the area
on the Beagle in the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   Our last stop before returning to port was Castro, Chiloe's
principal town and a significant fishing and artisan center. It
also marked our return to the money economy. The night I boarded, I
simply stashed my money in the mini-safe, and then enjoyed the
unusual sensation of not having to spend any for the next five
days. But now, it took cash to satisfy my urge to buy the hand-knit
woolen cloche hat I found in the handicrafts market for $4. And
then $30 more to buy a hand-woven woolen jacket. But the true
souvenir of the trip was that first sight of the glacier _ fixed in
my mind, as a glimpse of what Heaven should be.
</P>
<P>
   Booking a trip on Skorpios III
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   I flew American Airlines nonstop from Dallas to Santiago, then
bought a round-trip ticket on Ladeco, a Chilean airline, to Puerto
Montt, about 600 miles to the south. There is a flight every few
hours on Ladeco or LAN Chile. By waiting until I got to Santiago to
buy the ticket, I paid $250, while the price to buy it in advance
in the United States was $376.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the Line
</P>
<P>
   The Skorpios III and her sister vessels, Skorpios I and II, sail
between Puerto Montt and the San Rafael Glacier in the far south of
Chile from September through May _ which covers the Southern
Hemisphere's spring, summer and fall. For the 1999-2000 season, the
weekly cruises began Sept. 4 and continue through the week of May
27.
</P>
<P>
   Prices vary according to the month and the ship. High season
runs from mid-December through mid-March, which is the Chilean
summer. Everything else is low season.
</P>
<P>
   On the Skorpios III, the newest of the three vessels, built in
1995, high season prices for a double cabin range from $3,400 to
$5,000 a cabin, with suites at $5,300 and $5,800 a cabin. Low
season prices range from $2,600 to $3,700 double and $3,850 and
$4,100 for suites.
</P>
<P>
   The Skorpios II, built in 1988, has prices ranging from $2,800
to $4,200 for double cabins in high season and from $2,100 to
$3,220 in low season. She also has three- and four-person cabins
with bunk beds, plus suites. The Skorpios I, built in 1978 and with
bunk beds in many of the cabins, has doubles ranging from $2,100 to
$3,240 a cabin in high season and $1,600 to $2,400 low season. It
also has three-person cabins and some junior suites.
</P>
<P>
   The prices cover everything on board _ four meals a day,
cocktails and wine _ and the mixed grill at the cruise line's
dining hall near Quitralco Fjord. I needed money during the cruise
for taxis at a couple of fishing villages where we stopped,
handicraft purchases and tips for the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant as the cruise is, making arrangements for it from
outside of Chile requires some tenacity. The cruise line has a Web
site at www.skorpios.cl, where I found useful information on the
schedule and itinerary, but when I used the e-mail address to ask
about availability of particular dates, I got no response, even
after a couple of proddings. Eventually, I called the cruise line's
agency in Santiago, (56-2) 231-1030, fax (56-2) 232-2269, and
quickly got answers and made a reservation. Telephone numbers for
the Skorpios headquarters in Puerto Montt are (56-65) 255050, fax
(56-65) 258315.
</P>
<P>
   I was asked to pay by direct transfer to a bank in Miami, for
which the agency in Santiago faxed me the necessary forms. But an
Australian traveler on my voyage said he was able to pay by credit
card at his hometown travel agency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
