<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL REPUBLICANS CONCEDE THEY WILL NOT ENACT SPENDING
BILLS ON TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With four days left before the start of the new
fiscal year, Republican leaders in Congress formally conceded on
Monday that they would not meet the deadline for passing the annual
spending bills, and the White House laid down a new deadline, three
weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   That set in motion a $500 billion confrontation between Congress
and the Clinton administration, which has vowed to veto half of the
Republicans' spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is sitting back and watching Congress fail to
complete its appropriations work before the fiscal year ends at
midnight on Thursday, hoping and expecting that when negotiations
over spending begin next month, President Clinton will once again
outmaneuver the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The president appeared to step up the pressure on the
Republicans on Monday when he announced that the surplus for the
1999 fiscal year ending Thursday will be a record $115 billion. The
surplus, which had been projected at $99 billion, grew because of a
surge in tax revenues, Clinton said in a Rose Garden statement
before departing for New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   October will be a month of ``pretty contentious'' arguments
between the White House and Congress over the way the government
will spend more than half a trillion dollars, predicted Jack Lew,
the White House budget director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you that we're not going to be facing
brinksmanship,'' Lew said.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, in a previous bout over spending bills, Clinton
won almost every round. The Republicans were bruised, and Congress
wound up lashing together a 4,000-page omnibus spending bill
replete with billions for pet projects. Almost no member of
Congress read that bill before it was passed.
</P>
<P>
   The fight, members say, was not ennobling, and few Republicans
are looking forward to a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   The result was even worse for them in 1995. When the White House
and the newly elected Republican Congress failed to strike a deal
then, much of the government shut down. Voters blamed Congress for
the closing of national parks and Washington's museums and the
snarling of federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the next fiscal year rapidly approaching, Congress has
yet to complete work on 9 of the 13 spending bills needed to
finance government agencies. Further, Clinton and his senior
advisers say he will veto seven of the bills if Congress passes
them in their current form.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the absence of an organizational miracle this week to
speed final congressional passage of the outstanding bills, and
unless the president changes his mind about the vetoes, the new
fiscal year will start with 10 of the 13 spending bills either
incomplete or unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, formally acknowledging that they could not complete
their work on time, Republican leaders in Congress began preparing
a ``continuing resolution,'' a stopgap bill that will finance
government agencies at the current year's spending levels for three
weeks, until Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials struck an impatient posture on
Monday, calling for a two-week continuing resolution, and implying
that Congress should hurry up and get to the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
