<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLD-MARKETPLACE-ART-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: RESCUING GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The central banks of Europe, which own nearly half of the gold
held by governments and institutions, have begun a rescue mission
for gold, which slid to a 20-year low earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing on Sunday to limit the annual sales of their
reserves, the banks eased fears that they would flood the market.
Now that they have taken this OPEC-like step to support prices, it
may be hard to explain why they did not do so earlier. Since 1996,
when fears of massive selling by central banks really began to
drive down prices, gold has lost nearly 40 percent of its value.
And the banks' gold reserves plunged in value as well.
</P>
<P>
   Initially at least, the belated effort worked. The price of gold
soared $14 to end Monday at $281.90 an ounce on the New York
Commodity Exchange, after jumping as high as $288 an ounce. The
stocks of gold mining companies, in turn, got a big lift. Newmont
Mining jumped 21 percent and Barrick Gold 16 percent, as both
companies hit new highs for the year and wiped out all their losses
since May.
</P>
<P>
   What the rescue effort means for the price of gold over the
longer term is hard to know since the details of the banks'
agreement were not announced. In addition, buyers may thin out in
response to a big spike in gold's price. Many analysts expect that
to happen around the relative stratosphere of $300 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Further increases will depend on how the agreement is carried
out, what other central banks do, and whether the limits on gold
lending in the agreement discourage speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devil is in the details,'' said Peter Beaumont, head of
precious metals at Warbug Dillon Read. ``The impact is not clear
and forecastable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the announcement by 15 central banks was a victory for
gold producers. The producers also won a round with the
International Monetary Fund, which announced over the weekend that
it would not sell a big portion of its reserves on the open market
to raise money to help the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   The producers had lobbied to block the IMF gold sale and for an
orderly process for gold sales by central banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a coordinated effort to control the flow of central bank
gold to the market, and you wouldn't want to underestimate how
powerful that could be,'' Beaumont said. ``This is a very
significant change.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the price of gold has fallen on the threat of yet
another central bank announcing it will or has sold millions of
ounces of gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has not been the central bank sales that have been the
problem,'' said George Milling-Stanley, the manager of gold market
analysis at the World Gold Council, which represents the world's
major gold producers. ``It has been the perception of central bank
sales coming down the pike that has been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, central banks have sold 2,053 tons of gold, equal to
half of last year's total supply, which includes mine production,
scrap recycling and central bank sales, according to Gold Fields
Mineral Services, a London-based precious metals research firm. The
effective coup de grace came in May, when the Bank of England
announced that it would sell 415 tons of gold over several years.
The price of gold plunged nearly $7 on that day.
</P>
<P>
   According to the agreement, which was announced Sunday night
during the semi-annual meeting of the IMF and the World Bank in
Washington, the 15 central banks have agreed to limit their annual
sales to 400 tons of gold, or 10 percent of the total supply, for
five years. That amounts to a little more than the 315-ton annual
average over the last 10 years of net sales _ sales minus purchases
_ by all governments and their institutions, like the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the 2,000 tons in sales outlined for the next five
years includes the 1,300 tons the Swiss plan to sell and the 365
tons the Bank of England still has to dispose of to complete its
announced program. So very little more can be sold by the other
banks, including the European Central Bank, which represents the 11
nations joined in the euro currency, the Swiss National Bank and
the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
   The central banks also said they would limit their lending of
gold to current levels. Speculators, who want to sell borrowed gold
and profit on its decline by buying gold back at lower levels, and
gold producers, who want to lock in prices by hedging, need to
borrow gold. Transactions by both groups have put significant
downward pressure on gold.
</P>
<P>
   Wim Duisenberg, the president of the European Central Bank,
acknowledged that the rescue effort was self-serving. Referring to
the 16,200 tons held by the group of central banks, he said the
agreement was aimed at ``keeping the value of that gold where it
is.'' He also said ``the purpose of this action is to give
certainty to the gold market.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how much higher can the price of gold go.
The answer will depend on how other central banks, speculators and
producers respond to this initiative.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Philip Klapwijk, managing director of Gold Fields Mineral
Services, said that Gold Fields' price forecast of $240 to $270 an
ounce ``has already been punctured.'' But he also said that if
investor uncertainty over central bank gold sales was ``the only
thing holding back the market, the price would have risen more
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia, Venezuela and other major gold owners not part of the
agreement could disrupt the market if they decide to sell now.
Kevin Crisp, vice president and precious metals strategist at J.P.
Morgan in London, said: ``Admittedly, there are plenty of central
banks that weren't part of the announcement. One wonders what they
will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Sokalsky, the chief financial officer of Barrick Gold
Corp., a major producer and hedger of gold, said he expected that
many of the hedge funds and speculators who had sold gold to profit
on its decline have reversed their bets buy buying back gold and
may be on the sidelines for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The five percent jump in the price of gold last week, he said,
seemed to be powered, in part, by this reversal of speculators'
positions to protect their profits or limit their losses. The rally
was set off by strong demand at the Bank of England's sale of 25
tons of gold last Tuesday, the bank's second sale since May. If the
speculators have largely left the market, much of the punch has
already been felt.
</P>
<P>
   But Sokalsky said the lending limit would not hinder gold
producers who want to hedge. ``There is not going to be a squeeze
as a result of this announcement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a word of warning from Lawrence Kudlow, chief
economist at Schroder &AMP; Co. and a longtime believer in gold,
especially as an inflation barometer. He says that gold is still
signaling that inflation is contained or moving lower. And that
leads him to calculate that a ``normal'' gold price is around $288
an ounce, not very far from where it is now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
