<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CANDIDACY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S SEN. JOHN MCCAIN FORMALLY ANNOUNCES CANDIDACY FOR
PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, a political maverick who spent five
years as a Vietnam war prisoner, formally launched his bid for the
White House on Monday with a rebuke of pork-barrel spending, a call
for renewed patriotism and a vow to restore military greatness.
</P>
<P>
   An outspoken champion of campaign finance reform, the Republican
lawmaker said removing the corrupting influence of special interest
money from politics is the linchpin of virtually every important
government reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must eliminate the special-interest loopholes and
pork-barrel spending that are the result of a campaign financing
system that is nothing more than a sophisticated influence-peddling
scheme,'' McCain said at a rally in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Giving the broad outlines of his presidential agenda, McCain
said he would push for middle class tax cuts by expanding the
lowest income tax rate of 15 percent to couples earning up to
$70,000.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he'd push for vouchers allowing parents to send
their children to private school at taxpayer expense, and vowed to
return 90 percent of federal education dollars to local communities
instead of ``wasting it on Washington bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would pay for his programs by using a projected
surplus and by cutting fat. He promised never to touch a dime of
the Social Security trust fund to offset government spending, ``no
ifs, ands or buts.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain began running for president months ago but waited until
Monday to formally announce his campaign for the GOP nomination. It
is likely to be an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   He has raised an estimated $10 million, respectable under the
old rules but only about a fifth of what record-setting fund raiser
George W. Bush has pulled in.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor is also far ahead of McCain and his other
Republican rivals in opinion polls. In New Hampshire, the
first-test primary where McCain has concentrated his resources,
Bush is beating McCain 45 percent to 12 percent, according to a new
University of New Hampshire poll.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the odds, McCain said he is running for president
to help ``reinvigorate our sense of national purpose'' and restore
America's standing in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the world's only superpower,'' he said. ``We must
accept the responsibilities along with the blessing that comes with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, McCain blasted President Clinton, saying he
has failed as commander-in-chief by ``weakening our defenses.'' But
he also blamed ``both parties in Congress'' for wasting money on
unneeded weapons systems while thousands of rank-and-file soldiers
subsist on food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a disgrace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The son and grandson of admirals, McCain drew upon his own war
and military experiences as he issued a ``new patriotic challenge''
to fight cynicism and return to the ``noble cause of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   A Navy pilot shot down over Vietnam in 1967, McCain was a
prisoner of war for more than five years. Released in 1973, he
counts the Silver Star, Purple Heart and Distinguished Flying Cross
among his military honors.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year Navy veteran was elected to the House of
Representatives in 1982 and has been a senator since 1987. In 1992,
the Senate investigated McCain and four other senators for their
ties to savings and loan executive Charles Keating.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was cleared of any wrongdoing, but says the episode still
embarrasses him.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking his own party's leaders, McCain went on to lead the
fight for campaign finance reform, an effort that has not endeared
him to many of his colleagues in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he warned he would punish any member of Congress who
overrides his veto in order to ``waste your money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make sure you know who they are,'' he said to raucous
applause. ``Every single one of them.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
