<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS OVER CONTROVERSIAL ART EXHIBIT BREAK DOWN AT CITY HALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In negotiations with senior City Hall officials on
Monday, the chairman of the Brooklyn Museum of Art discussed
various ways to end a dispute with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani over a
controversial art exhibition _ including the possibility of
removing a dung-stained portrait of the Virgin Mary _ but the talks
quickly fell apart after City Hall officials spread word of the
proposals to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I discussed is now off the table,'' Robert S. Rubin,
chairman of the museum's board of trustees, said on Monday night,
clearly upset that word of his negotiations had been made public
before he had discussed them with other top museum officials.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, City Hall officials told reporters that
Rubin had tentatively offered _ subject to approval from the
museum's board _ a package of concessions aimed at overcoming
Giuliani's objections to the exhibition, and at ensuring continued
public funding to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The package, city officials said, included removing the Virgin
Mary painting by artist Chris Ofili, segregating five or six other
controversial works from the rest of the exhibition, and accepting
a 20 percent reduction in the city's subsidy to the museum during
the length of the show, which is scheduled to start on Saturday and
run through Jan. 9. The 20 percent reduction corresponds to the
amount of floor space the museum is devoting to the exhibit, city
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a major concession on the part of the Brooklyn
Museum, and a significant victory for Rudy Giuliani,'' said Joseph
J. Lhota, deputy mayor for operations, who did not attend the
meetings but described them to reporters. ``On the money issue, in
fact, if that's true, its important that taxpayer dollars will not
be spent on a painting which desecrates religion, plus other pieces
of art which glorify a child-murderer and the other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin acknowledged discussing the three ideas with city
officials, but he vigorously disputed their characterization of the
talks, and he emphasized that he engaged in the negotiations on his
own initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am chairman of the museum, and I _ without authorization
from the board, or without discussion with the staff of the museum
_ did raise certain ideas, that if they were acceptable to the
city, I would attempt to get agreement of all the relevant
parties,'' he said. ``Several ideas were on the table without any
commitment on my part that they could be implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said he had merely asked city officials to select one of
the three ideas as the basis for a possible compromise he would
then attempt to sell to his board. But the very fact that he was
discussing the removal or segregation of art works angered museum
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Lehman, the director of the museum, declined to comment
on Monday night, although several of his aides were stunned by word
of the negotiations and vehemently denied that the museum had
agreed to withdraw the Virgin Mary painting, which has been
condemned as blasphemous by several Catholic leaders in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not withdrawing any of the works in the exhibition,''
said Sally Williams, a spokeswoman for the museum. ``None of the
works are being withdrawn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
