 &UR; TEENS _ &LR;  Financial-service companies have begun reaching out to
schoolchildren on the Internet in an effort to teach them how to
save and invest wisely. Educating young people about money matters
certainly makes sense in this era of 401(k) plans, Individual
Retirement Accounts and other self-managed pension vehicles. Most
of today's kids will need to become savvy investors if they hope to
remain solvent through their sunset years. The educational outreach
also makes sense from a business standpoint. If a broker or
mutual-fund group grabs the attention of kids now, the kids might
become customers later when they are earning money and looking for
ways to invest. By Arthur M. Louis
