<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Willing Your IRA to a Charity 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Q: If I were to assign my individual retirement account to a
charity in my will, would that eliminate the requirement that I
must begin to withdraw funds from the IRA after I reach age 701/2?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm afraid not. You must obey the tax laws that apply to your
IRA during your lifetime, no matter who eventually will inherit
your account, says Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller.
</P>
<P>
   I assume, by the way, that you are referring to a traditional
IRA. With a Roth IRA, there is no withdrawal requirement no matter
how old you are.
</P>
<P>
   With a traditional IRA, you must begin withdrawing money no
later than April 1 of the year following the year in which you
reach age 701/2. The minimum size of your annual withdrawals will
be based on life-expectancy tables that you can obtain from the
IRS. The charity will get only whatever is left in your IRA after
you die.
</P>
<P>
   There have been proposals before Congress from time to time that
would change the withdrawal requirement to give charities more
money. But that's not the law yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Retirement Payout
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband works for Chevron and will be taking early
retirement either in January or June. He will come away with a
$700,000 retirement fund, consisting entirely of Chevron stock. We
know that we ought to diversify our holdings when we roll over this
fund.
</P>
<P>
   A friend referred us to a financial planner from one of the big
financial-service firms who says she would charge us either a large
fee up front or a significant annual fee to manage our money.
Should we go this route? We are pretty clueless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: It may be that this financial planner is an incredible
investment whiz, well worth whatever she charges. However, you
ought to ask her to state in writing exactly how well she has done
for her clients in each of the past several years. Also, ask her to
show how her performance compared with the principal investment
benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Because you don't say exactly how much she charges and because I
have no idea how good she is, I can't say whether you should try
her.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you decide not to use a planner, then the logical
move for someone who is ``clueless'' would be to invest in mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to reduce your exposure to stock-market fluctuations
_ as a retired couple probably should _ you might consider putting
some of your money in mutual funds that invest in U.S. Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   As for the portion that remains in stocks, your best bet might
be to use index funds, such as those that track the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index or the broader-based Wilshire 5000 index.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, your investments in index funds will do as well
as the market in general _ and in recent years, that has been very
well indeed. In the past 10 years, for example, the S&AMP;P 500 has
averaged roughly a 17 percent gain annually, including reinvestment
of dividends. Only a small percentage of actively managed funds did
better than that.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no guarantee that the stock market will
continue to soar, nor is there any guarantee that the market will
continue to outperform managed funds.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of index funds is that they charge substantially
lower fees than actively managed funds _ generally less than 0.2
percent of your invested assets per year. With a $700,000
portfolio, the annual fee would be less than $1,400. With an
actively managed fund, you probably would have to pay several times
that much.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Figuring Estimated Tax
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sometimes I sell stocks at a capital gain, other times at a
capital loss. These sales _ and the amount I gain or lose _ can't
be predicted far in advance. This makes it difficult for me to
figure my expected income for the year when I am making my
quarterly estimated tax payments. How can I make sure that I don't
get penalized for underpaying my estimated tax?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: The law states that to avoid a penalty, you must pay in
advance an amount equal to at least 100 percent of the previous
year's tax, or 90 percent of your eventual tax bill for the present
year _ whichever is less.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose the 100-percent method, you can leave your capital
gains and losses out of the equation. Just make sure that your
estimated tax payments, combined with any money your employer
withholds from your wages, amount to at least 100 percent of last
year's tax.
</P>
<P>
   For example, suppose you paid income tax of $5,000 last year and
you expect your employer to withhold $4,000 from your wages this
year. Then you would make quarterly tax payments of $250 each time
the estimated tax falls due _ in April, June, September and
January.
</P>
<P>
   The rule is slightly more stringent if you are married filing
jointly with an income of more than $150,000, or you file
separately with an income greater than $75,000. In that case, you
would have to pay 105 percent of last year's tax bill, rather than
100 percent, to avoid a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-percent method is more complicated, but it would be
preferable if you had an unusually large tax bill the previous year
and don't expect to approach that amount this year. In that case,
you certainly wouldn't want to prepay 100 percent of last year's
total.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you would add up your total income to date at the end
of each quarter and assume that your income will continue at that
pace to the end of the year. You then would pay enough estimated
tax each quarter _ based on the projected annual income figure _ to
cover at least 90 percent of the year's projected tax.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if after the year is half over and you are
projecting a $6,000 tax bill, you would make sure that your
estimated tax payments plus withholding totaled $2,700 at that
point. (That's $6,000 times 90 percent divided in half.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
