<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8138 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TEENS-TEENS_SFCHRON &LR;      09-27 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-TEENS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Netting Young Investors Through the Internet  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Financial-service companies have begun reaching out to
schoolchildren via the Internet in an effort to teach them how to
save and invest wisely.
<P>
   Educating young people about money matters certainly makes sense
in this era of 401(k) plans, individual retirement accounts and
other self-managed pension vehicles. Most of today's kids will need
to become savvy investors if they hope to remain solvent through
their sunset years.
</P>
<P>
   The educational outreach also makes sense from a business
standpoint. If a broker or mutual-fund group grabs the attention of
kids now, the kids might become customers later when they are
earning money and looking for ways to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Internet to connect with the next generation of
investors is essential for any financial-services company, says
James Punishill, an analyst with Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation doesn't know life without the Net, just like
you don't know life without a car,'' he observes. ``If you are a
financial institution that does business strictly the old-fashioned
way, you are dead with these consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The full-service brokerage firms have been quickest to recognize
the importance of reaching kids through the Internet, notes Dan
Burke, a senior analyst with Gomez Advisors. Among online discount
brokers, he says, such efforts appear to be practically
nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't really realized yet the value of these potential
customers,'' Burke says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the firm doesn't try to establish a relationship with the
children, and if something happens to the head of the household,
the account will go somewhere else,'' he observes. ``This is not
rocket science. We're just talking about keeping the relationship
open, so you don't have to constantly go out and look for new
accounts to replace ones you've lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke says kids are most likely to sample the Web sites of
financial-service firms with which their parents do business.
However, some firms attract attention to their sites by actively
marketing to kids, for example, by sending representatives to
schools to give lectures or to conduct seminars on investing.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the financial advice on youth-oriented Web pages
tends to be bland and superficial. Nobody is likely to emerge from
an online session armed with the investment wisdom and skills of a
Warren Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, which operates what it calls a SaveLab at &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.plan.ml.com/family/kids, exhorts children to ``curb the
spending impulse.'' It advises them to raise their own fruits and
vegetables and to go get their pizzas rather than paying tips for
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   On the Strong Funds Web site _ at www.strongkids.com _
youngsters are asked: ``Do you baby-sit or mow lawns? Maybe you
wash cars or paint picnic tables. These are all good ways to
exchange services for money.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the kind of economic theorizing that wins Nobel
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the sites encourage youngsters to test their investing
skills by putting together make-believe stock portfolios. This lets
them experience the thrills of investing without the financial
risks.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters can use the A.G. Edwards &AMP; Son site _ at &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.agedwards.com _ to participate in monthly stock-picking
contests.
</P>
<P>
   They must choose five stocks from a list of 25, most of them
with names and products familiar to kids, such as Disney, Gap,
Kellogg, Mattel, McDonald's and Reebok. A.G. Edwards promises that
the contestants whose stocks do best each month will receive
``cool'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Another leading broker, Salomon Smith Barney, lets young people
create a mock portfolio of up to eight stocks _ any ones they
choose _ on its Web site at www.salomonsmithbarney.com/yin. They
can track its progress from day to day to gauge their investment
talents.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Ross, a Salomon senior vice president for marketing, says
the youth-oriented Web program was designed to combat some common
misconceptions kids have about the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research among young people indicates that they know a lot
about savings banks because their teachers took them there on field
trips,'' she observes. ``Kids think that savings accounts or U.S.
savings bonds are the best investments.''
</P>
<P>
   What kids do know about the stock market seems to center on the
highly volatile Internet stocks, which get a lot of publicity in
the newspapers and on television, Ross remarks. ``What we're
telling them is that you should adopt sensible investment
strategies that match your personal and financial goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Some financial-service companies insist that they aren't trying
to sell anything to the kids who surf their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch spokeswoman Katie Hynes emphatically denies that
her firm's motives are anything but selfless. '`Our main objective
is to provide financial education, which encourages better savings
habits later in life,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms will admit _ after a little prodding _ that they
have a business motive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drawing new investors wasn't the main objective, but if it
happens, that's wonderful,'' says Stephanie Troug, a spokeswoman
for the Strong Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Clem, manager of the Internet Services Group at A.G.
Edwards, says: ``Sure, we hope they will become customers. If we
demonstrate good corporate citizenship by providing education,
there's a hope these folks will become familiar with us and become
clients down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, none of the financial Web sites subjects the kids to
the kind of shameless, clamorous product pitches they get from toy
manufacturers and soft-drink purveyors on Saturday morning
television. You won't find any out-and-out advertisements on the
sites.
</P>
<P>
   However, most of the sites do contain a certain amount of
soft-sell mixed in with the investment text. If you are interested
in investing, the message usually goes, you could do worse than put
yourselves in our hands.
</P>
<P>
   A.G. Edwards, for example, laces its Web site with gentle
reminders that its research department provides ``many value-added
services,'' and that ``an A.G. Edwards financial consultant can
help you determine the best investment plan to meet your needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Financial, whose subsidiaries include the Stein Roe &AMP;
Farnham mutual fund group, ``thought it would be a great kind of
public service to go out and teach kids about investing,'' says
Jeremy Jaffe, vice president for electronic commerce. ``It had less
to do with selling our own mutual funds.''
</P>
<P>
   However, anyone who scrolls through the Liberty Financial Young
Investor site _ at www.younginvestor.com _ quickly will discover,
from repeated references, that the company sells mutual fund
shares.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
