<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKE-NIKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Fogdog Nabs Nike in One Fell Swoosh 
 &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Fogdog Sports scored the Internet-partnering equivalent of a slam
dunk, hole in one and hat trick yesterday. The Redwood City firm
won an exclusive contract to sell Nike Inc.'s full line of sporting
goods on Fogdog's Web site.
<P>
   Until now, Nike had resisted joining forces with a Web retailer,
preferring to confine its online sales to its own Web site. That's
because the company did not fully trust the Internet as a retail
medium and feared that the Nike name could be tarnished through its
association with new and untested ``e-tailers,'' according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement will not come cheap for Fogdog. The company,
which filed to go public on Friday, has agreed to sell a 12 percent
stake to Nike.
</P>
<P>
   According to the filing statement, Nike will acquire about 6.2
million shares of Fogdog stock at $1.03 per share. Fogdog did not
disclose at what price it would offer shares to the public, but
judging from other Internet IPOs, the listing price should be well
above that figure.
</P>
<P>
   Nike chief executive Phil Knight said in a conference call that
he decided to partner with Fogdog because ``in our view, Fogdog is
the best and most aggressive sports retailer on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   John Taylor, an analyst with Arcadia Investment Group, said Nike
needed to give consumers wider access to its products and could not
continue to limit Internet sales to its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, Nike probably thought they could go it alone on the
Internet,'' he said. ``But then they decided it was better to be
part of something bigger. I think it was just a matter of
determining which horse to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike will continue to sell its products on its own site at
www.Nike.com as well as on the sites of its traditional retail
partners, such as Nordstrom. But under the terms of the deal,
Fogdog is the only ``pure play'' Internet company with the rights
to sell Nike's complete product line on the Web. The exclusive
agreement is for six months, after which time the two companies
will reassess the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Fogdog now sells about 150 Nike products on its www.fogdog.com
Web site, but that number could balloon to many thousands under the
agreement. In the past, Fogdog consumers only had access to a
limited number of Nike's soccer products, but now, they can shop
for much more popular items such as Air Jordan basketball shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time in and time out, our customers ask us for the most
complete selection of sporting goods,'' said Fogdog chief executive
Tim Harrington. ``Nike is clearly the No.1 brand in sports
retailing. To provide a true consumer experience on Fogdog, we knew
we had to offer more than just a limited selection of Nike stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the six-month exclusive arrangement is more than
enough time to give Fogdog a leg up on its competition. Harrington
said he also would consider taking investments from other sporting
goods giants, such as Reebok and Adidas.
</P>
<P>
   Fogdog was founded about five years by three Stanford students.
Originally, the company designed Web sites for sporting goods
companies, but last November, the founders changed the name to
Fogdog and began selling products online.
</P>
<P>
   According to Media Metrix, Fogdog received more visits in July
than any other online sporting goods retailer. It competes online
against the likes of the Sports Authority and Global Sports
Interactive. But the company is still unprofitable. It lost $6.6
million on revenue of about $1 million in the first six months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   According to its registration statement, Fogdog expects that it
will continue to incur ever-increasing operating losses for the
next several years.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, which had 1999 revenue of $8.8 billion, rose $2.56, to
$56.38, in yesterday's trading.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
