<HEADLINE>
PARTY CHIEF CHANGES MIND ON GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now you see it, now you don't. Mayor Edward Rendell
of Philadelphia, the new chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, has un-endorsed Vice President Al Gore in the
increasingly heated campaign against former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago Rendell had endorsed Gore, and he has raised hundreds
of thousands of dollars for him. Rendell was installed Saturday as
the new party chairman at the behest of Gore and President Clinton
so that the vice president would have an effective fund-raiser at
the top of the party hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   But Rendell soon began to say he wanted to be fair to both
candidates. On Sunday, Rendell was asked on the ABC News program
``This Week'' whether he still supported Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I think the vice president understands that
the _ I told the president I'd have to be scrupulous and neutral.''
</P>
</TEXT>
