<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATONAL-NATIONAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Free-Lance Writers Win Electronic Victory 
 &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A union representing free-lance writers has won a federal appeals
court ruling that print publishers cannot freely reproduce their
work in electronic media.
<P>
   National Writers Union President Jonathan Tasini hailed the
court decision reversing a lower court ruling as a victory for &LR; 
thousands of &LR;  free-lance writers and photographers around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of writers who can step forward and get
the industry to do what is right,'' said Tasini, the lead plaintiff
in the case. ``That's all we're after, trying to get our fair
share.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade union, which has two main offices in New York and
Oakland, represents about 5,500 members throughout the country. The
union sued six publishers, including the The New York Times,
Newsday Inc. and Time Inc., on grounds that free-lance work
purchased for print publications could not be reproduced without
permission in electronic databases or on CD-ROMs without infringing
on the writers' copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   The case covered work published between 1990 and 1993 and did
not include work published on the Internet, which flourished after
that period.
</P>
<P>
   The recent ruling does not prevent free-lancers from signing
contracts that allow publishers to use their work in any medium,
including electronic ones. Today, free-lance contracts frequently
include rights to use the material in electronic media, although
the writers' union opposes such contracts without extra
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, U.S. District Judge Sonia Sotomayor of New York
ruled in favor of the publishers, saying that electronic versions
were revisions of the original work that did not require extra
payments to the free-lancers.
</P>
<P>
   The writers' union appealed the ruling, contending that
electronic reproduction on CD-ROM encyclopedias and databases like
NEXIS constituted an entirely new publication.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, a three-judge panel from the Second District Court
of Appeals in New York reversed the lower-court ruling, saying
copyright laws cover free-lance material published in their
original form, but do not extend to electronic versions.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected the publishers' argument that the electronic
versions were merely `'revisions'' of the originals.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago attorney Patricia A. Felch, who represented the writers'
union, said the ruling ``draws a very clear line in the sand and
makes it easier for writers to understand what their rights are.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Keller, the lead attorney representing the publishers,
said the ruling flies in the face of previous court rulings and
laws passed by Congress that automatically gave publishers the
electronic rights to free-lance materials.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the latest ruling could affect electronic archives
of newspapers and magazines that used stories and photographs
produced by free-lancers. He said publishers may have to seek
permission to use any free-lance story or photograph stored in
electronic archives going back several decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impractical to suggest we go back and acquire these
rights by contract,'' Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
