<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8143 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-VIRUS-780&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      09-27 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS WARN OUTBREAK COULD SPREAD SOUTH AS INFECTED BIRDS MIGRATE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., the Southeast)   (nk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Health and wildlife officials said Monday that a mosquito-borne
illness had stricken nearly twice as many people in the New York
region as previously recognized, and they said the virus might be
present in a far larger geographic area than they originally
suspected.
</P>
<P>
   The new assessment came as experts confirmed that the virus was
not St. Louis encephalitis, as first believed, but a strain called
West Nile virus that had never been reported before in the Western
Hemisphere. Officials also attributed a fourth death to the
outbreak: a woman in her 60s from New Rochelle, N.Y., in
Westchester County, just north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is transmitted to humans from mosquitoes that have
bitten infected birds. That fact has led experts to suspect that
the virus may exist in many parts of the region, since scores of
dead crows have been turning up from Connecticut to Suffolk County
on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen crows dying in this kind of pattern in 30
years of studying them,'' said Ward Stone, the wildlife pathologist
for the New York state Department of Environmental Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, as birds continue their fall migration, some
scientists are concerned that birds carrying the virus will take it
with them as they move south. ``I think this is something we need
to be very concerned about,'' said Duane Gubler, the director of
the division of vector-borne infectious disease at the federal
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 37 confirmed cases of the West Nile virus in the
region, 25 in New York City, eight in Westchester and four in
Nassau County on Long Island. Officials had previously put the
total number of confirmed cases at 18 _ 14 of them in the city _
and no confirmed cases had been reported in Nassau before Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are still studying human tissues and blood of eight
other New Yorkers who died since the outbreak began in August for
traces of the illness. Further, 162 cases remain under
investigation in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   One bird from Westport, Conn., has tested positive for the
illness, as has one crow from Scarsdale, N.Y., officials said. Last
Friday, health officials from the CDC confirmed that several birds
from the Bronx Zoo and its surrounding area were infected with the
West Nile strain. The state has received 523 reports of dead birds
around the region; many more are being reported among birdwatchers,
conservationists and the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``These viruses do travel with birds and bird migration has been
in process now for a better part of the month,'' Gubler said.
``There is a good possibility that this virus has already been
taken to areas further south. We are going to rethink our whole
surveillance approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Other federal agencies have put states bordering the
metropolitan region on alert to look for large pockets of dead
birds.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Monday that the change in diagnosis,
and the rise in the numbers of sick, would not change the city's
plans to spray for mosquitoes periodically as the need arises, nor
should it worry New Yorkers, because the illnesses are similar and
are prevented the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should emphasize that this is just reclassification,'' said
the mayor said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms of the illness, including fever and headache, are
usually mild. But in rare cases the virus can cause neurological
disorders and even death. Elderly people, young children and people
with weakened immune systems are most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Experts attributed the original mistaken diagnosis to several
factors. For one thing, scientists were not specifically looking
for West Nile virus, since it had never appeared in this part of
the world. Further, the two viruses are very much alike, and can
produce similar results in diagnostic testing.
</P>
<P>
   State officials, who had not publicly commented on the outbreak
until last Friday, appeared to be taking a more active role on the
issue Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The state held its first news conference on the matter, and
Health Commissioner Antonia C. Novello announced that a
multi-agency response would now be made to an illness that is weeks
old and that the the city and other municipalities have already
responded to with mosquito spraying and other measures.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the state Department of Health quietly enlisted
the help of a laboratory at the University of California at Irvine,
but state officials did not inform New York City or the CDC until
Sunday that the California lab had found a West Nile-like virus in
humans. ``It was not normal,'' said Gubler of the CDC, adding that
multiple labs are often called in on major health investigations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The story of the changing diagnosis has been a fascinating one
for epidemiologists and other health experts. In early August, the
city announced that scores of people were suspected to have
contracted St. Louis encephalitis, an illness that had never been
diagnosed in New York City before and is more often found in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, wildlife experts in Albany, N.Y., and at the
Bronx Zoo, as well as birdwatchers and various other people, began
to notice the deaths of large numbers of crows around the state and
in New Jersey. Over Labor Day weekend, alarmed by the death of
birds at the Bronx Zoo, a pathologist there sent samples to the
U.S. Department of Agriculture as well as to the CDC and an Army
lab in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, state Health Department scientists
conferred with a group from the Emerging Disease lab at the
University of California at a conference in Albany, and told them
about the deaths in New York City. Officials were concerned that
although a diagnosis for St. Louis encephalitis had been made in
several cases, there will still many people who had turned up sick
and then tested negative for the illness.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, Dr. W. Ian Lipkin, who heads the California lab,
agreed to test New York's samples with some advanced equipment that
is used to diagnose rare and emerging illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Almost simultaneously, but without talking to each other, the
CDC was discovering a West-Nile strain in bird samples, and
Lipkin's lab was discovering it in a human brain. Although the lab
came up with its findings late Friday night, it did not immediately
alert the CDC or the city. ``Their procedure was such a novel one,
they wanted to present a credible case before presenting it,'' said
Kristine A. Smith, a spokeswoman for the state Health Department.
``And it made no difference from a public health stand point.''
</P>
<P>
   The city Department of Health stressed that public health
initiatives will not change as a result of the new diagnosis.
``This is question of two very, very rare diseases and there was
just some confusion about it but it has no impact at all,'' said
city Health Commissioner Neal L. Cohen. ``If anything, the disease
we are dealing with now is somewhat less severe than the one we
were dealing with before, so nothing about this is particularly
positive, but I guess that's movement in the right direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
