<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO SHUFFLES BRUINS LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The secondary is UCLA's primary concern as its
season reaches a critical juncture. The Bruins are one loss from
Rose Bowl elimination and desperately seeking a solution after
their porous performance at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be blind not to see it,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
``The secondary played horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal passed for 465 yards _ a UCLA opponent record _ and
averaged a stunning 17 yards per attempt. As a result, the Bruins
have moved senior safety Ryan Roques to cornerback to replace
freshman Joe Hunter. Senior Eric Whitfield will fill Roques' spot
at strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were starting two freshmen cornerbacks, and (Stanford)
exploited us,'' Toledo said, referring to Hunter and Ricky Manning
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins don't have many options _ in part because of injuries
and suspensions, in part because of poor play.
</P>
<P>
   Junior cornerback Marques Anderson has been suspended for the
fall quarter and senior cornerback Jason Bell is out indefinitely
with a heel injury. Without them, the Bruins have four freshman
cornerbacks: Hunter, Manning, Lovell Houston and Paul Nelson.
Houston and Nelson aren't ready to play, Hunter performed poorly
and Roques isn't in top form after missing two games for the
disabled-parking suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   The safety situation is equally dire. Joey Strycula is solid but
limited athletically. Jason Stephens, an opening-game starter,
botched several assignments and was benched. Whitfield hasn't
played to his talent level. Sophomore Julius Williams is a
converted cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got what we've got,'' Toledo said. ``There's no quick
fix. We can do patchwork stuff, but there's no quick fix.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Heel of misfortune: Bell doesn't expect to return for at
least two weeks and could miss the season if his heel does not
heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he'll ever be healthy,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell had surgery in the spring to remove bone spurs from the
inside of his right heel and it was sore throughout training camp.
To compensate for the pain, Bell placed excessive stress on the
outside of the heel, which is now the problem area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a specialist and he said I could play with pain, but if
it's not healed, I could snap the Achilles or have chronic
damage,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   He won't return until he's fully recovered, both for his
football future _ he wants to play in the NFL _ and fear of
permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not coming back at half speed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell is eligible for a medical redshirt if he doesn't return.
</P>
<P>
   __ A new man? If Bell's right, the Bruins will see a new,
improved Anderson when he returns from suspension in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Marques this weekend and this thing has opened his
eyes,'' Bell said. ``It's one of the greatest things that's
happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was suspended in August by the dean of students for his
involvement in the handicapped-parking scandal and a prior
infraction with the dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking five or six classes at Compton College,'' Bell
said. ``He's not playing around. He's lifting weights and working
out (at Long Beach Poly). He's not taking any time off. It's a
totally different Marques.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
