<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8149 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-     09-27 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-970&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONCEDES DEAL ON SPENDING WON'T BE ON TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout; story is now complete in
one take)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With four days left before the start of the new
fiscal year, Republican leaders in Congress formally conceded on
Monday that they would not meet the deadline for passing the annual
spending bills, and the White House laid down a new deadline, three
weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   So began the final act in a $500 billion confrontation between
Congress and the Clinton administration, which has vowed to veto
half the Republicans' spending bills. The fight is one that
President Clinton has reason to relish, and Republicans in Congress
have cause to dread.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is sitting back and watching Congress fail to
complete its appropriations work before the fiscal year ends at
midnight on Thursday, hoping and expecting that when negotiations
over spending begin next month, Clinton will once again outmaneuver
the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   October will be a month of ``pretty contentious'' arguments
between the White House and Congress over the way the government
will spend more than half a trillion dollars, Jack Lew, the White
House budget director, predicted in a discussion with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you that we're not going to be facing
brinksmanship,'' Lew said.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, in a previous bout over spending bills, Clinton
won almost every round, from the standpoint of both politics and
policy. The Republicans were bruised, and Congress wound up lashing
together a 4,000-page omnibus spending bill replete with billions
for pet projects. Almost no member of Congress read that bill
before it was passed.
</P>
<P>
   The fight, members say, was not ennobling, and few Republicans
are looking forward to a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   The result was even worse for them in 1995: when the White House
and the newly elected Republican Congress failed to strike a deal
then, much of the government shut down. Voters blamed Congress for
the closing of national parks and Washington tourist attractions
and the snarling of federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the next fiscal year rapidly approaching, Congress has
yet to complete work on nine of the 13 spending bills needed to
finance government agencies. Further, Clinton and his senior
advisers say he will veto seven of the bills if Congress passes
them in their current form.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the absence of an organizational miracle this week to
speed final congressional passage of the outstanding bills, and
unless the president changes his mind about the vetoes, the new
fiscal year will start with 10 of the 13 bills unsigned, some not
even complete.
</P>
<P>
   In formal acknowledgment that they could not complete their work
on time, Republican leaders on Monday began preparing a
``continuing resolution,'' a stopgap bill that, with the
president's signature, will finance government agencies at the
current year's spending levels for three weeks, until Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials struck an impatient posture, calling
for a continuing resolution of only two weeks and implying that
Congress should hurry up and get to the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in the end Congress insists'' on a three-week continuing
resolution, Lew said, ``we have the expectation that Congress will
complete its work by the end of the continuing resolution. There
should be no expectations of a willingness to go on with extensions
beyond that, to just have it extended by weeks and weeks and
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Rose Garden appearance on Monday, Clinton took credit for a
record surplus in the current fiscal year that the White House now
estimates at $115 billion _ $16 billion more than was projected
over the summer. Although that surplus for the current year has no
financial bearing on the debate over next year's spending, it may
increase the pressure on Congress to strike a bargain closer to the
president's position. That might allow for more spending.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, once the bargaining begins, it can end in either
compromise or chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Congress could agree on a package of
spending bills, perhaps including tax cuts far smaller than the
$792 billion, 10-year Republican package that Clinton vetoed last
week. The Republicans might bend to the president's will and
approve some of his favorite programs, in areas ranging from
foreign policy initiatives to elementary-school education. Or the
president and the Republicans could fail to strike a bargain, which
could bring a new government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Republicans assumed control of Congress in January
1995, they have completed the appropriations process before the
deadline only once. This year the disarray and dissent in
Republican ranks over spending has been particularly strong. Fiscal
conservatives have stopped several appropriations bills in their
tracks, objecting to any increases in spending. They have warned _
and they may be proved right _ that Congress will once again spend
surplus Social Security revenue to finance government operations,
despite the solemn vows of Republican leaders not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy in the House, where spending bills originate, has
been run in large part by the majority whip, Rep. Tom DeLay of
Texas. DeLay has said that his plan was to pass as many spending
bills as possible, try to hew to the spending limits that Congress
imposed on itself in 1997, keep away from the money in the Social
Security trust fund and then ``negotiate with the president, after
he vetoes the bills, on his knees,'' requiring him to dip into
Social Security if he wanted any new spending.
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if this strategy may fail. Most of the bills have
not passed, the spending caps are busted, and Congress is on course
to drain billions of dollars from the Social Security surplus, a
course that could have political repercussions for the Republicans
in the coming election year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stan Collender, who advises corporate executives on government
spending as head of the Federal Budget Consulting Group at
Fleishman-Hillard, a public relations firm, said: ``There's almost
no way the Republicans can come up with a plan for the coming
fiscal year without tapping into the Social Security surplus. They
clearly have opened themselves up to a whole new level of
criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In each of the seven bills Clinton threatens to veto, the
Republicans have either cut billions of dollars for his favorite
programs, or attached policy amendments that offend the White
House, or both.
</P>
<P>
   They include the House measure financing the Labor, Health and
Human Services, and Education departments, which cut close to $3
billion from Clinton's initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill for the Veterans Administration and the
Department of Housing and Urban Development kills Clinton's
Americorps job training program. Bills financing the Interior
Department and federal energy and water programs include provisions
that the White House deems anti-environmental.
</P>
<P>
   The bills for foreign operations and for the State Department
contain too little money for diplomacy, the White House argues. And
the bill financing the operations of the District of Columbia
unfairly restrict the principle of home rule for the city, the
White House contends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
