<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTIC-MONTHLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTIC MONTHLY IS SOLD TO PUBLISHER OF NATIONAL JOURNAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mortimer Zuckerman has sold the venerable,
140-year-old magazine, The Atlantic Monthly, to David Bradley, a
Washington millionaire who has been trying to raise the profile of
a fledgling media empire, it was announced Monday night. The sale
was for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the magazine, which is known for its political and
social commentary, has been in the works for months, but came to
fruition suddenly in the last week. Bradley, who broke into the
media publishing world just two years ago by buying The National
Journal Group, approached Zuckerman about the deal, executives on
both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   Zuckerman, who made a fortune in real estate, made the magazine
his first media purchase in 1980 and since then bought U.S. News
and World Report, The Daily News and Fast Company, a rapidly
growing business magazine. Zuckerman said that the decision to
sell, which he called ``painful,'' was based on personal
considerations. ``In part, I want to spend more time with my family
and focus on fewer properties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is apparent that Zuckerman is having a tough year in some
parts of his media empire. The Daily News is faced with a labor
arbitration ruling that could cost it tens of millions of dollars,
and the stock of Applied Graphics Technologies, a preproduction
publishing firm in which Zuckerman owns a significant stake, has
been trading at a fraction of its price two years ago. According to
a Conde Nast executive, Zuckerman was in serious discussions
earlier this year to sell Fast Company to Conde Nast for more than
$200 million, but the talks came to naught.
</P>
<P>
   According to both Zuckerman and Atlantic Monthly sources, the
owner and pundit did not have his heart in the relationship
anymore. A person inside Zuckerman's organization said the
magazine, which did not make a profit, had become eclipsed by Fast
Company. Morale at the magazine was down, the executive said,
because upper management had let it drift like an orphan.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, the magazine has been edited by William Whitworth
and has won nine prestigious National Magazine Awards as well as
dozens of lesser citations for editorial content and design. Among
the stories that garnered the magazine high praise was a detailed
history of a gun used in a murder and an article called ``Dan
Quayle Was Right,'' supporting the then vice president's attack on
single motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   But the publication, whose circulation was 459,000 at the end of
1998, does not have the stature in intellectual circles that it did
two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's interest in the publication seems to stem from a
desire to increase his new empire's media profile. A come-lately to
the publishing game, Bradley, 45, made his fortune by developing
Corporate Executive Board Co., which does management and operations
research for industrial firms. Bradley netted $142 million when the
company had a public offering, according to The Washington Post.
Bradley, who was traveling, could not be reached for comment Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The National Journal Group is well known within Washington, but
not beyond. Its glossy flagship publication, The National Journal,
has a tiny circulation of 6,600 and a reputation for serious,
nitty-gritty, policy-focused coverage. In addition, it owns several
online ventures that offer in-depth coverage of the political
machinations in the capital, including Congress Daily and The
Hotline.
</P>
<P>
   National Journal editor Michael Kelly said Bradley was buying
media properties ``primarily because he loved magazines and was a
passionate reader.'' He added that he did not believe that Bradley
was looking to be ``some kind of glitzy media player.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, serious magazines like The Atlantic and The National
Journal are hardly as lucrative as corporate consulting. ``If you
look at the history of thought-leader magazines, you do not find a
history where people have made much money,'' admits John Fox
Sullivan, The National Journal's president and publisher. Sullivan
said he expects some advertising synergies from the acquisition.
The two magazines already share a lot of the same advertisers,
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan said that neither he nor Bradley are expecting any
easy surge in revenues. He acknowledged that to maintain such
magazines costs money, but said Bradley was committed to the task.
``We joke about having a `Field of Dreams' strategy: If you build
quality, they will come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although National Journal makes a small profit, Bradley had used
his own resources to bolster editorial coverage. In the last 18
months, the magazine has increased the editorial budget by 60
percent, paying for a growth in staff from 125 employees to 200
</P>
<P>
   William Whitworth, The Atlantic Monthly's editor, will step down
from the helm. Bradley has not named his replacement, but Kelly is
seen as the favorite for the job. The rest of The Atlantic Monthly
staff has not be asked to move on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
