<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8152 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     09-27 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A CHALLENGE FIGURING OUT WHO TO BELIEVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are living in the era of the Big Lie.
</P>
<P>
   Who to believe?
</P>
<P>
   No one.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, it seems, takes the cue these days from our beloved
Prez, who, with grave solemnity, peered into the television cameras
a while back and swore to an entire country, ``I did not have sex
with that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnists are booted off major newspapers for fictionalizing
their prose. CNN has to recant a phony report alleging the U.S.
Army used chemical weapons during the Vietnam War. The FBI, after
six years of denial, finally admits to using pyrotechnic tear gas
canisters against the Branch Davidians. Pulitzer Prize recipients
turn out to be fabricating frauds.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in these politically correct times when the most
innocuous pronouncement can be perceived by some uptight cultural
partisan as being offensive, one has to be extremely cautious even
if what one is relating happens to be the truth, or if it happens
to be anti-establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the case of the esteemed right fielder for the Los
Angeles Dodgers, Mr. Raul Mondesi, reviled by the media for such a
dastardly deed as airing publicly his feelings about Davey Johnson
and Kevin Malone in a most colorful, X-rated manner.
</P>
<P>
   How dare Mondesi speak his mind!
</P>
<P>
   How dare he not utter those practiced, homogenized,
monosyllabic, trite quotes favored by most modern athletes!
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, a contrite Mondesi has apologized for his unseemly
outburst, and I doubt he ever again will be so rash as to betray
his innermost thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   There are those in the media who are loudly applauding Mondesi's
mea culpa
</P>
<P>
   in what smacks of blatant hypocrisy on the media's part.
</P>
<P>
   It's the media that feeds hungrily on jocks like Mondesi bold
enough to speak out, and then too often it's the media that
prissily winds up demeaning them for such candor.
</P>
<P>
   The latest person on the sporting scene to give his unvarnished
views amid controversy is the manager of the New York Mets. Mr.
Bobby Valentine, who has gone on record as saying he deserves to be
fired if the Mets fail in their pursuit to qualify for the National
League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the fact that Valentine should
</P>
<P>
   be unhinged if the talented Mets continue their fascinating free
fall they have lost six straight and now find themselves a game
behind the Cincinnati Reds in the wild card race is quite
irrelevant in the context of Valentine's startling statement.
</P>
<P>
   After all, who in these deceitful times admits culpability?
</P>
<P>
   I think Pete Rose belongs in the Hall of Fame, and, for sure,
he'd have been there by now had he come clean on his past baseball
gambling sins. But he won't do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Prez blithely continues his verbal acrobatics and outrageous
parsing, no matter what the subject, or scandal, is.
</P>
<P>
   We should all follow the noble example of Valentine, who, in
voluntarily serving his noggin up on a platter, might be breaking
revolutionary new ground in tell-like-it-is ethics.
</P>
<P>
   I don't ever recall a major league manager coming out and saying
that he should be fired if his team doesn't fulfill expectations,
and Valentine should be saluted for such a gallant gesture.
</P>
<P>
   It's hoped here that Valentine has started a trend, and that
others will be as forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kevin Malone, the Dodgers' general manager, will be moved
to say during the off-season, ``If the Dodgers are as lousy and
disappointing next season as they have been this season, I will
hand in my resignation to Rupert Murdoch and even hand him over
back pay for all the senseless money I've blown on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the moronic coach at Baylor, Kevin Steele, who recently
cost his team a victory over UNLV when he failed to have his
quarterback take a knee on the final play of the game, will say,
``I should be banished forever from the coaching fraternity and
held up to lasting ridicule for allowing my team to lose a game it
had won.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Oscar De La Hoya, recently involved in the greatest
retreat since Dunkirk, will say, ``I embarrassed my country, my
sport and myself by running for 12 rounds against Felix Trinidad
and accepting $24 million for engaging in less serious combat than
you see in a WWF match.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Al Davis will say, ``The Raiders are finally winning now
because I'm not interfering with Jon Gruden (Raiders' head coach)
or any of the other coaches on my staff as I did so often in the
past with such disastrous results. I do nothing now but dream about
returning to L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jerry West will say, ``I never wanted to trade Elden
Campbell. I knew how valuable he was. But the Busses (Jerry &AMP;
Jimmy) wanted him out of here, and so I got rid of him. We
certainly could use him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Terry Collins will say, ``We should have signed Randy
Johnson and let Mo Vaughn sulk in Boston. What a pain in the
posterior Mo turned out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Paul Tagliabue will say, ``I've promised the networks L.A.
because they know this area has far greater visibility and
marketability than Houston. And I'll do whatever it takes for L.A.
to get an expansion team except stick it at the Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be refreshing if people began following Valentine's
course and began bearing their souls honestly?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it won't happen because to do so might not only set a
person up for wide-spread stricture as Mondesi discovered but, even
worse, might also cost a person enormous amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
