<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUOTE-OF-THE-DAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUOTATION OF THE DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: This quotation refers to BC-QUAYLE-CAMPAIGN-NYT, which moved
in ``p'' news file.) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There's a time to stay and there's a time to fold. There's a
time to know when to leave the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   _Dan Quayle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8159 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u f BC-PHOTO-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      09-27 2297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 09/27/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Editors note:
</P>
<P>
   We have eliminated NYT12 from today's report which showed Dan
Quayle and his wife Marilyn leaving a press conference where the
former vice president announced his withdrawal from the Republican
presidential race on Monday. The photo was provided by another wire
service and moved inadvertently.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) ATLANTA -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- OBIT-MCCARTY, 09-27 --
Oseola McCarty hoped to help others avoid a life as hard as hers.
Miss McCarty, who gave away a life savings of $150,000 to help
complete strangers get a college education at the University of
Southern Mississippi, died Sunday in the little frame house in
Hattiesburg, Miss., where she took in laundry and ironing and made
her small fortune a dollar or two at a time. She was 91. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- MUSEUM-MRSCLINTON, 09-27
-- Hillary Rodham Clinton, with Rep. Charles B. Rangel in Harlem on
Monday. ``Our feelings of being offended should not lead to the
penalizing and shutting down of an entire museum,'' says Mrs.
Clinton of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's threat to cut funds for the
Brooklyn Museum of Art. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) KEY WEST, Fla. -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- KEY-WEST-SEWAGE,
09-27 -- No swimmers, just a single observer, on Smathers Beach,
where signs nearby warn that the water may be contaminated by human
waste. In Key West, antiquated, leaking sewage lines are allowing
raw sew age to seep into the shallows, and work crews are tearing
up streets all over the city to repair the sewer system, a project
that the state ordered the city to complete by 2002. (Lonnie
Schlein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) HEBRON, West Bank -- Sept. 27, 1999 --
ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS, 09-27 -- Water towers atop Israeli settlements
are painted in the colors of the Israeli flag in this November,
1998 file photo. The Palestinian area of the city is in the
background. In its first three months, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
government has authorized new construction in the West Bank's
Jewish settlements at a pace exceeding that of the right-wing
administration of Benjamin Netanyahu. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- DIARIO-PUBLISHER, 09-27 --
Rossana Rosado, 38, the newly named publisher of El Diario-La
Prensa, during an interview last week. Ms. Rosado was raised in the
Bronx, her father a truck driver and her mother a hospital clerk.
Ms. Rosado is the only female publisher of a major Spanish-language
paper in the United States. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NORTH HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CALIF-HMOS,
09-27 -- Gov. Gray Davis of California shakes hands with Maury
Weiner, administrator of Tarzana Treatment Center, after signing a
pioneering package of compromise HMO reform bills on Monday. The
bills, which among other things, make it easier for patients to sue
an HMO for punitive damages, require the health insurers to pay for
second opinions and to justify denials of treatment, could have a
strong influence on health care coverage in the U.S. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SICHUAN, China -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-6, 09-27
-- Lu Zhi, a leading light in China's nascent conservation
movement, is distinguishing herself as a scientist and an awesomely
hardy field researcher who may know more than anyone about China's
most famous species, the giant panda. Last year, a government group
named her one of China's ``Top 10 Young Intellectuals.'' (Lu
Zhi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-5, 09-27 -- Liu
Junning attending an international conference of scientists in
Beijing recently. As one of China's most influential liberal
intellectuals - that's liberal as in ``Western liberal democracy''
- Liu, 38, operates right on the boundaries of the permissible
here, disseminating ideas he thinks are vital to the country's
progress. ``The Chinese need to know how 'liberal democracy'
differs from 'people's democracy,' `` he says. (Mark Leong/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-4, 09-27 -- At a
reception announcing an ``entertainment gala'' featuring Chinese
and Russian classical performers in the Kremlin, destined for
broadcast on Chinese television, Sun Jianjun, center, darts among
the celebrities and executives, making sure that the right
introductions get made. Jianjun, 43, pulled off a similar event in
the Hollywood Bowl two years ago. (Mark Leong/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-3, 09-27 --
Among the many start-ups trying to emulate everything from Yahoo to
Ebay, three-year-old Sparkice I-Com Ltd. is already the Old Guard,
and its 36-year-old founder Zeng Qiang - Edward Zeng to foreigners
- is already famous. All this before his company has made a dime or
seriously begun carrying out its plan for global e-commerce. ``We
want to be the cyber-bridge between East and West,'' he says. (Mark
Leong/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-2, 09-27 -- Dong
Yunhu does not fit the stereotype of a tow-the-line Communist. Yet
at just 37, he is a prime architect of China's sensitive human
rights policy. As founder and director of the China Society for
Human Rights Studies since 1993, Dong organizes human rights
exchanges with other countries, publishes articles on the topic and
advises the government on how to mold and present its ideas. (Mark
Leong/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-1, 09-27 -- Zhao
Shujing only became a feminist only in 1994, after she read ``The
Second Sex'' by Simone de Beauvoir, then recently translated into
Chinese. Today, she is the executive producer of China's most
influential women's show, ``Half the Sky,'' which broadcasts three
times a week on state television. (Mark Leong/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- NY-VIRUS, 09-27 -- Joseph
Dunne, left, and pilot John Sondgeroth, prepare the insecticide
Malathion for spraying from helicopters earlier this month. The
outbreak of a mosquito-borne illness that killed at least three
people in New York was not caused by St. Louis encephalitis at all,
but rather a form of the West Nile virus that has previously never
been diagnosed in the Western Hemisphere, government health
officials said on Monday. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TAIPEI, Taiwan -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- SCI-QUAKE-RISK,
09-27 -- Rescue workers, elevated by a crane, right, direct
operations over what is left of the Sung-sam Hotel last week. Even
though the rate of earthquakes over time seems to be more or less
unchanging, the world's population explosion means that more people
are moving into quake zones. The result, experts say, is the
prospect of continuing trauma as urban areas erupt with what seems
like nearly endless bursts of destruction. (David L. Ryan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- PATTERNS-FASHION, 09-27 --
Thomas Brunzell, left, and Jeffrey Weiner cater to the younger man
at their shop in SoHo. ``We are relevant for professional men who
want clothes that go from day to evening,'' says Brunzell. (Don
Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LONDON -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- LONDON-FASHION-2, 09-27 --
From left, Burberry's cream leather coat, asymmetirical dress in
its signature plaid and molder leather shoes with anklets; Clements
Ribeiro's polka-dot chiffon blouson top and brown an sage sequin
skirt; from Arkadius, a ripped white leather dress with a doll's
head and red paint added right on the spot. (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LONDON -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- LONDON-FASHION-1, 09-27 --
Five variations of Hussein Chalayan's white chemise with an
abstract tree print. The small boy used the remote control to open
one of the dresses like a garage door, revealing layers of tulle
beneath. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CAPE MAY, N.J. -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- BIRD-WATCHING, 09-27
-- Dorothy and David Scheiman, of Frederick, Md., follow a Peregrin
falcon overhead from a platform set up at Cape May Point State Park
for viewing migrating birds on Monday. It is the peak of the season
to watch birds heading south for the winter and, according to
bird-watchers, Cape May is considered one of the best areas to view
migrating birds in the Northeast. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- MUSEUM-OFILI, 09-27 --
Chris Ofili's ``The Holy Virgin Mary,'' his 1996 painting of a
black Madonna with a clump of elephant dung on one breast and
cut-outs of genitalia from pornographic magazines in the
background, has caused quite a stir. Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani
threatened to cut off the Brooklyn Museum of Art for hosting the
show in which the piece appears, ``Sensation: Young British Artists
From the Saatchi Collection.'' (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MAUNA KEA, Hawaii -- Sept. 27, 1999 --
SCI-SUBARU-TELESCOPE-2, 09-27 -- Humans are dwarfed by the Subaru
telescope on Mount Mauna Kea, which uses one giant piece of glass
to capture celestial images. When it came to designing the new
telescope, Japan's small astronomy establishment shed the follower
image and wagered boldly that the magic of the single-mirror
approach was far from played out. (Michael Darden/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MAUNA KEA, Hawaii -- Sept. 27, 1999 --
SCI-SUBARU-TELESCOPE-1, 09-27 -- Japan's Subaru telescope, at top
left, takes its place among the other powerful telescopes arrayed
on Mount Mauna Kea. In pulling off its creation, Japan has applied
the nation's exquisite skills in engineering, design, construction
and miniaturization in ways that should strongly influence the
future course of building very large telescopes. (Michael
Darden/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- PIMPERNEL-THEATER-REVIEW,
09-27 -- Carolee Carmello and Ron Bohmer leading the cast in a
scaled-down version of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel.'' After a summer
hiatus from New York, ``Pimpernel'' has resurfaced in its trimmest
of three incarnations; contrary to the ruling wisdom on Park
Avenue, however, it really is possible to be too thin. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- GOLD, 09-27 -- An undated
photo of gold bullion. A group of European central banks triggered
the biggest one-day increase in gold prices in 13 years Monday with
a surprise plan to put a cap on their planned sales of gold
bullion. Gold peaked at $285 an ounce in London Monday, more than
$16 above the price of $268.60 in late trading Friday. The price
fell back to $278.90 in late London trading and was $281.90 in New
York late Monday. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- COMPUTER-SCREENS,
09-27 -- Aliya and Ahsen Khan listen to Robert Malone, a salesman,
while shopping for a computer earlier this month. Fueled by strong
sales of personal computers, business is booming for computer
screen manufacturers across Asia. But demand is so strong that
Asian producers cannot keep up with demand creating a worldwide
shortage of screens and big headaches for computer makers like IBM,
Dell and Toshiba. (Evan Richman/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MITROVICA, Kosovo -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ARRESTS,
09-27 -- Relatives of people who disappeared during the Kosovo
conflict weep as French gendarmes inform them of the results of
their investigation on Monday. NATO peacekeepers arrested four
Serbs and charged them with killing 26 people from this town during
the Kosovo conflict in April. The remains of the massacre victims
were found some 10 miles outside of the town. (Andrew Testa/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SOMERVILLE, Mass. -- Sept. 27, 1999 --
AFFLUENT-BACKPACKER-BOS, 09-27 -- Carrie Svingen, a self-employed
publicist in her mid-30s, gets ready to embark on an eight-month
backpacking tour of Indonesia and Southeast Asia. Hostel owners say
they are seeing a marked increase in the number of Americans,
Australians, and Europeans in their 30s and 40s backpacking through
Asia and Africa. (Bill Brett/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- GENOME-MAPPING-BOS,
09-27 -- Robert Tepper, chief scientific officer of Millennium
Pharmaceuticals in Cambridge, in one of the company's labs. Now,
companies like Millennium are developing techniques for testing
thousands of drugs at the same time. ``Drugs . . . will be more
selective and less toxic, much more geared to a specific type of a
disease that you have,'' says Tepper. (John Blanding/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER, 09-27 --
Venders remove unsold beverages from the site of the opening and
closing ceremonies for the Ryder Cup at The Country Club on Monday.
The American team completed the greatest comeback in the 72-year
history of the biennial matches on Sunday when, trailing 10-6, they
won 8 points from the 12 singles matches against Europe to win the
Ryder Cup for the first time since 1973. (Frank O'Brien/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
