   (NYT23) SICHUAN, China -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-6, 09-27
-- Lu Zhi, a leading light in China's nascent conservation
movement, is distinguishing herself as a scientist and an awesomely
hardy field researcher who may know more than anyone about China's
most famous species, the giant panda. Last year, a government group
named her one of China's ``Top 10 Young Intellectuals.'' (Lu
Zhi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-5, 09-27 -- Liu
Junning attending an international conference of scientists in
Beijing recently. As one of China's most influential liberal
intellectuals - that's liberal as in ``Western liberal democracy''
- Liu, 38, operates right on the boundaries of the permissible
here, disseminating ideas he thinks are vital to the country's
progress. ``The Chinese need to know how 'liberal democracy'
differs from 'people's democracy,' `` he says. (Mark Leong/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-4, 09-27 -- At a
reception announcing an ``entertainment gala'' featuring Chinese
and Russian classical performers in the Kremlin, destined for
broadcast on Chinese television, Sun Jianjun, center, darts among
the celebrities and executives, making sure that the right
introductions get made. Jianjun, 43, pulled off a similar event in
the Hollywood Bowl two years ago. (Mark Leong/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-3, 09-27 --
Among the many start-ups trying to emulate everything from Yahoo to
Ebay, three-year-old Sparkice I-Com Ltd. is already the Old Guard,
and its 36-year-old founder Zeng Qiang - Edward Zeng to foreigners
- is already famous. All this before his company has made a dime or
seriously begun carrying out its plan for global e-commerce. ``We
want to be the cyber-bridge between East and West,'' he says. (Mark
Leong/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-2, 09-27 -- Dong
Yunhu does not fit the stereotype of a tow-the-line Communist. Yet
at just 37, he is a prime architect of China's sensitive human
rights policy. As founder and director of the China Society for
Human Rights Studies since 1993, Dong organizes human rights
exchanges with other countries, publishes articles on the topic and
advises the government on how to mold and present its ideas. (Mark
Leong/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BEIJING -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CHINA-NEXT-1, 09-27 -- Zhao
Shujing only became a feminist only in 1994, after she read ``The
Second Sex'' by Simone de Beauvoir, then recently translated into
Chinese. Today, she is the executive producer of China's most
influential women's show, ``Half the Sky,'' which broadcasts three
times a week on state television. (Mark Leong/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
