<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8164 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-27 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A BIRDIE IN THE BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know where you were Saturday night, but it now becomes
clear that a small segment of the American population _ tiny in
number but mighty in per capita income _ was worrying about whether
our golf team could win the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup tournament is a contest between Europe and the
United States that happens every two years. Despite the
disadvantage of having to say things like ``I'm honored to be
playing for my continent,'' the Europeans won in 1995 and 1997. The
Americans had hopes that this time things would change, despite
their own burden of having to wear team shirts silly enough to have
been cribbed from ``Gilligan's Island.'' But on Saturday night,
with one day's play to go, the United States was far behind. Hope
was dwindling that our guys would be able to take home this
prestigious prize for getting a ball in the hole with the fewest
shots. Our national honor, already shaky since the Senate began
trying to balance the budget with a 13-month calendar, was on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Then George W. Bush saved the day. The Republican candidate for
president, a friend of team captain Ben Crenshaw, came to visit the
team meeting Saturday night and read our golfers a letter from the
Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   This letter, from Col. William Travis to the American people, is
a famous, but decidedly mixed message, written by a man who was
making a valiant but unnecessary stand against an enemy that was
about to kill every person in the fort. Almost every nation
cherishes a story about a handful of brave men who willingly ride
into certain death on behalf of their country. The Alamo is our
Charge of the Light Brigade, our Siege of Thermopylae. It is sort
of hard to see it as a useful metaphor for golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have sustained a continual bombardment and a cannonade for
24 hours and have not lost a man ... Our flag still proudly waves
from the wall. I shall never surrender nor retreat ... VICTORY OR
DEATH,'' wrote Travis. As Bush read, the golfers listened intently,
perhaps imagining themselves either sinking the winning shot or
winding up impaled on their putters.
</P>
<P>
   Amazed by the incredible number of similarities between the
plight of the Texans facing death at the hands of a mass of angry
Mexican soldiers and that of the golfers facing the possibility of
entering a Cupless new millennium, the Americans rallied. Perhaps
seeing himself as Jim Bowie, firing from his sickbed at the
oncoming hordes, the final player, Justin Leonard (a Texan!), made
a 45-foot putt that put the Americans ahead. It was, as a friend of
mine remarked, an extraordinarily rare example of ``the
juxtaposition of golf and the word exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the secret of George W. Bush's success.  &UR; Things work out
for him. &LR;  Bush had stiffed the California Republican Party
convention to go to Brookline, Mass., to watch the tournament. At
first, the Texas governor's staff claimed he had a prior commitment
to attend a dinner for the Republican National Hispanic Assembly.
When it turned out later that the real scheduling conflict was
golf, Steve Forbes raced into Anaheim to remind the Californians
which candidate had blown them off and challenge Bush to about 187
debates. But by then, Bush was already part of the great victory
story. Thank heaven he went where he was needed. Otherwise those
Europeans might have marched out of Brookline with the Ryder Cup,
and Monday morning would have dawned a little dimmer from sea to
shining sea.
</P>
<P>
   Even though golf is still burdened by a long history of racial
bigotry, and frequently carried on in country clubs that make an
absolute life style out of discriminating against somebody, it's
hard to argue that it's a symbol of Bad Republicanism when
practically every politician in the country plays. Richard Nixon
forced himself to learn so he could bond with President Eisenhower,
who nevertheless continued to dislike him. Bill Clinton is probably
out on a course right now, getting a few gimmies, in the company of
Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   What I am worried about, however, is this indiscriminate use of
the Alamo pep talk. If George W. wastes it on a golf game, what
will he save for the Olympics, let alone a war?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
