Quayle and his wife Marilyn leaving a press conference where the
former vice president announced his withdrawal from the Republican
presidential race on Monday. The photo was provided by another wire
service and moved inadvertently.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) ATLANTA -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- OBIT-MCCARTY, 09-27 --
Oseola McCarty hoped to help others avoid a life as hard as hers.
Miss McCarty, who gave away a life savings of $150,000 to help
complete strangers get a college education at the University of
Southern Mississippi, died Sunday in the little frame house in
Hattiesburg, Miss., where she took in laundry and ironing and made
her small fortune a dollar or two at a time. She was 91. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- MUSEUM-MRSCLINTON, 09-27
-- Hillary Rodham Clinton, with Rep. Charles B. Rangel in Harlem on
Monday. ``Our feelings of being offended should not lead to the
penalizing and shutting down of an entire museum,'' says Mrs.
Clinton of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's threat to cut funds for the
Brooklyn Museum of Art. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) KEY WEST, Fla. -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- KEY-WEST-SEWAGE,
09-27 -- No swimmers, just a single observer, on Smathers Beach,
where signs nearby warn that the water may be contaminated by human
waste. In Key West, antiquated, leaking sewage lines are allowing
raw sew age to seep into the shallows, and work crews are tearing
up streets all over the city to repair the sewer system, a project
that the state ordered the city to complete by 2002. (Lonnie
Schlein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) HEBRON, West Bank -- Sept. 27, 1999 --
ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS, 09-27 -- Water towers atop Israeli settlements
are painted in the colors of the Israeli flag in this November,
1998 file photo. The Palestinian area of the city is in the
background. In its first three months, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
government has authorized new construction in the West Bank's
Jewish settlements at a pace exceeding that of the right-wing
administration of Benjamin Netanyahu. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- DIARIO-PUBLISHER, 09-27 --
Rossana Rosado, 38, the newly named publisher of El Diario-La
Prensa, during an interview last week. Ms. Rosado was raised in the
Bronx, her father a truck driver and her mother a hospital clerk.
Ms. Rosado is the only female publisher of a major Spanish-language
paper in the United States. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NORTH HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- Sept. 27, 1999 -- CALIF-HMOS,
09-27 -- Gov. Gray Davis of California shakes hands with Maury
Weiner, administrator of Tarzana Treatment Center, after signing a
pioneering package of compromise HMO reform bills on Monday. The
bills, which among other things, make it easier for patients to sue
an HMO for punitive damages, require the health insurers to pay for
second opinions and to justify denials of treatment, could have a
strong influence on health care coverage in the U.S. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
