<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-NOTEBOOK-BO     09-27 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED REVIEWS ON THE US TEAM'S GAUDY SHIRTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER AND MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The Americans made a statement with their
play on the final day of Ryder Cup competition, and they also a
statement with their uniform tops. Justin Leonard's putt and the US
shirts remained the two major topics of conversation Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The shirts, manufactured by Jeff Rose &AMP; Co., feature photographs
of victorious Ryder Cup teams from the last six decades. The
photographs are framed in antique Burlwood and silver and arranged
on a burgundy background. &UR;  &LR; It took 14 different screens to complete
the print.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story behind the shirt is that when (Ben) Crenshaw won the
1995 Masters, he was in a Jeff Rose &AMP; Co. shirt with antique Bobby
Jones photographs printed on it,'' said Preston Piermattei of the
company. ``He felt like it was a good-luck piece for him. So when
he went to decide players' uniforms, he asked for a Ryder Cup
evolution to that shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Rose &AMP; Co. printed 33 shirts for team and PGA officials,
and they're not for resale. If they were to retail, the shirts
would cost approximately $150, slightly more expensive than the
manufacturer's regular line.
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains, would golf fans buy them? A survey of
Ryder Cup spectators Sunday found the shirts unattractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the shirt very much at all,'' said Fred Wahlers
of Charlestown. ``Something in red, white, and blue would have been
appropriate. I think the wives are dressed superbly. I can
understand the concept of past champions, but it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   But others were willing to sacrifice good taste for the sake of
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all right,'' said Mike Lindsey of Lake View, Mich. ``I
wondered at first. They're a little different from your stripes and
colors. But look at the scoreboard, they're working.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Please Mr. Postman
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to carry hundreds of dollars of merchandise around 18
holes? Looking for a convenient post office open on a Sunday? A
tent along the first fairway housed a full-service post office
during the tournament. You could mail letters and buy stamps, but
most patrons were mailing home large loads of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little unusual to be open Sunday,'' said Carolyn Derby,
manager of retail for the Boston postal district, ``but when people
have special events, they need you through the course of the
events.''
</P>
<P>
   Derby estimated the office mailed 800-1,000 packages each day of
the tournament, with the parcels costing an average of $4 to ship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hold the tuna
</P>
<P>
   The fan outburst that ticked off Colin Montgomerie and sent
security scrambling and Payne Stewart into a fit on the fifth hole
Sunday was a cry of, ``Tuna!'' During Montgomerie's backswing on
his second shot on the par-4 hole, a fan yelled out the nickname of
Jets coach Bill Parcells, who bears a resemblance to the Scot . . .
Football was on the mind of a few fans at the fifth. When
Montgomerie paused after being heckled, a fan shouted, ``Come on,
Monty, hit the ball. We've got to get home for the Sunday night
Patriots.'' . . . Inappropriate fan before was not limited to
catcalls. As Leonard and Jose-Marie Olazabal walked up the 18th
fairway, a spectator donned a plastic mask, ran across the first
fairway, and belly-flopped into a sand trap. He got up and said,
``That was fun,'' then wobbled away as a marshal pursued him.
During the Americans' victory celebration on No. 18, a few fans
received a Brookline Police escort off the premises, but no arrests
were made.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Using the drivers
</P>
<P>
   The traffic nightmare that organizers and local residents feared
never became reality. Public transportation ended up working out
better than anyone expected, according to operations overseer Mike
Gilligan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was such a community effort like I've not seen before,''
said Gilligan. ``I think that was the whole key here. We really
showed why the PGA of America goes into communities and customizes
our events to the community. The T service was unbelievable and so,
so, so successful. It was our biggest success story as far as
public transportation at any event we've ever come across, without
question.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem Gilligan and his staff had not anticipated was
a shooting in the Jamaica Plain area that diverted Ryder Cup
traffic as police searched for the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember this?
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, a Texan through and through, recalled Texas's greatest
scene of bravery _ the Alamo _ to motivate his nearly dispirited
team for the decisive singles matches in the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And Gov. George W. Bush of Texas just happened to be in
Brookline to add the final touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush came in and read us the speech of the Alamo that
William Barrett Travis wrote before the Alamo fell in 1836,'' said
Crenshaw. ``And it was a great speech, great words.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first line of it: `We were beieged by the enemy . . .,'
and we were at that time, against some pretty insurmountable
odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, his wife Julie, and other members of the entourage
also put together a video (``part of it funny, part of it
serious,'' said Phil Mickelson), for that team meeting Saturday
night, which was described by all the US golfers as emotional.
Player after player spoke to the team. ``From the heart,'' said
Crenshaw. ``They all spoke from the heart. It was very emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   The team, Crenshaw went on, ``already had a closeness in spirit
and bond. And it's very strong when you put together those feelings
in writing to do something, put them together.''
</P>
<P>
   And the result of the emotional motivational meeting . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty powerful machine out there,'' said Crenshaw,
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The matchup game
</P>
<P>
   When that precious final half-point had been earned by Leonard,
US assistant captain Bruce Lietzke shouted out, ``It was the
pairings.'' Lietzke jumped around the 17th green repeating those
words over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how much we agonized over our pairings,''
said Lietzke. ``And it was agony since we kept moving guys around,
changing the pairings, and moving a guy up or bringing a guy down.
It was hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The US captains had two tasks: front-load their pairings so the
team could gain a quick edge during the early matches Sunday to
build momentum. But, said Lietzke, ``We also had to try and guess
what (the Europeans) would do.'' The US brain trust didn't know
about its final pairings of the day _ aside from Jeff Maggert _ and
kept juggling names.
</P>
<P>
   If Tom Lehman was a natural to start out the day, in case the
Europeans started with a Colin Montgomerie, for instance, ``We were
also pretty sure we wanted to go with Jeff in the final match,''
said Lietzke. ``He's our most solid ball-striker and we were
confident with Jeff there. Of course, it didn't turn out that
way.'' Maggert was beaten by Scotland's Paul Lawrie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real agony was over the middle pairings,'' said the
assistant captain. ``Ben and the rest of us wanted to do this and
then we wanted to move it around. We kept moving guys back and
forth until the very last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   And the name of Leonard?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was around the eighth or ninth pairing but we moved him a
few times,'' said Lietzke. ``He'd be up one or down one or two. And
then we put Justin ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, was the perfect slot for the Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
