<SLUG> BC-NY-ART-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RAPS GIULIANI ON ART THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton criticized Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani Monday for threatening to close down the Brooklyn Museum
of Art if it goes ahead with an exhibition that he finds offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Giuliani lashed back, saying Clinton's
comments meant that ``she agrees with using public funds to bash
the Catholic religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a source close to the mayor said the museum had
agreed to a compromise that would let the show go on, but a museum
spokesman denied this claim.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and the first lady, the likely candidates in the race
for US Senate, have not clashed so intensely on any issue until
now.
</P>
<P>
   A Giuliani-Clinton race is predicted to be close one, and close
races in New York are often decided by the Catholic vote, which is
particularly crucial ``upstate.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Clinton way ahead of Giuliani in New York City, where
Democrats outnumber Republicans 4 to 1, and Giuliani way ahead of
Clinton in the city's suburbs. Upstate, which is what city and
suburban New Yorkers call everyplace else in the state, is where
the race is likely to be particularly intense. It is no coincidence
that, in her pre-campaign ``listening tour,'' Clinton spent most of
her time upstate.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the Brooklyn Museum was sparked last week,
when Giuliani became aware of its much-publicized show of British
art, called ``Sensation,'' scheduled to open Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which drew vast crowds and controversy in London and
Berlin two years ago, includes a shark in formaldehyde, a cut-up
pig, and _ most provocatively _ a painting of the Virgin Mary
smattered with elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani took offense and issued an ultimatum to the museum:
Cancel the exhibit or he will terminate city financing of the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of New York City's cultural centers, the Brooklyn
Museum is in a city-owned building and receives heavy subsidies for
routine operating expenses: $7 million a year in the Brooklyn's
case, plus $14 million for a capital-improvement project.
</P>
<P>
   Without the city subsidy, these centers, which also include the
Metropolitan Museum, the Natural History Museum, and the
avant-garde gallery P.S. 1, could not function.
</P>
<P>
   This may explain why every other cultural director in the city
has remained uncannily silent in the face of the mayor's attack.
``They're shaking in their boots,'' said a lawyer, who spoke on
condition that he not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton worded her criticism of the mayor very carefully Monday.
Asked about the dispute, she said outside a school in Harlem, ``I
share the feeling, that I know many New Yorkers have, that there
are parts of this exhibit that would be deeply offensive. I would
not go to see this exhibit.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she noted that Peter Vallone, the speaker of the New
York City Council, ``is a devout Catholic who attends Mass every
day,'' and yet Vallone ``understands that it is not appropriate to
penalize and punish an institution such as the Brooklyn Museum that
has served this community with distinction over many years, that
employs more than 500 people, that had over 500,000 visitors last
year, and provided a lot of services to citizens of New York and
especially the people of Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she agrees with Vallone, and added, as an extra jab
at the mayor, ``That is the position that everyone who thinks about
this issue should be taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has said that while the First Amendment protects free
expression, it does not guarantee taxpayer dollars for expression
that many people find ``disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Some constitutional lawyers disagree, arguing that the
government does not have to subsidize art but, once it does, it
cannot withdraw the money for reasons having to do with the art's
content.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the mayor, have not yet formally announced their
candidacies for senator, but she recently said she is leaning very
heavily in that direction, and she now seems to be attacking her
likely foe with new enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   She also attacked the mayor Monday for allowing the
deterioration of New York public schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
