<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8174 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-JUDGES-CARDINAL-BO     09-27 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-JUDGES-CARDINAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL LAW TROUBLED BY SJC NOMINEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Cardinal Bernard Law has raised objections to two of
Governor Paul Cellucci's nominees for positions on the Supreme
Judicial Court, saying their records leave them ``open to serious
charges of anti-Catholicism.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone call and private letter to Cellucci, Law said
past legal actions taken by Supreme Judicial Court Justice Margaret
Marshall and Superior Court Judge Judith Cowin give him a ``sense
of unease'' about the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern has to do with an attitude and mentality, which I
find troubling,'' Law said in the Sept. 22 letter to Cellucci, a
copy of which was obtained by the Globe. ``I fear that in both
these nominees there has been evidenced a certain mindset which at
times is open to the serious charge of anti-Catholicism.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is seeking to elevate Marshall from associate SJC
justice to chief justice, and appoint Cowin to fill an SJC vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Law stopped short of asking Cellucci to withdraw the
nominations, but urged him to investigate what he said is evidence
of the judges' negative feelings about Catholicism. Neither
Marshall nor Cowin is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Objections from the cardinal, who commands respect and clout on
Beacon Hill, could signal the most serious challenge the jurists
will face as they seek confirmation from the eight-member
Governor's Council. Marshall's nomination to lead the court will be
taken up Wednesday, while Cowin will be considered in the weeks
ahead. A majority of council members are Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   John Walsh, a spokesman for the archdiocese, said Law was out of
the country Monday and unavailable for comment. Walsh refused to
confirm the cardinal had sent a letter to Cellucci and would not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Law referred to a complaint Governor's Councilor
Edward O'Brien received this month from a Springfield attorney who
said Cowin displayed anti-Catholic bias in a 1997 case involving
Carney Hospital. In the case, a Norfolk County Superior Court jury
found the employee was wrongly fired because managers at the
church-affiliated facility thought he was gay. He was awarded $1.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said Cowin increased the award the plaintiff received
from the hospital, which is part of the archdiocese-run Caritas
Christi network. The lawyer, John J. Egan, quoted Cowin's
justification for the increase on the problems ``inherent in suing
a respected Boston Charitable institution . . . (and) the strength
of the Catholic Church.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe such a stereotype exists in a Judge's mind,''
Egan wrote in his letter to O'Brien. ``The church was not a party
to this case. The idea that it is a strong public force advocating
discrimination is offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan also cited another case in which Cowin allowed for the
cross-examination of a Catholic woman's religious views in an
employment termination case. ``The whole situation is outrageous,''
said Egan.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci spokeswoman Sean Feddeman said the governor was not
available to comment on the letter Monday. The governor's chief
counsel, Leonard L. Lewin, who oversees judicial nominations, did
not return a phone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cowin, whom former Governor William F. Weld appointed to the
bench in 1991, did she not return a phone call late Monday. O'Brien
confirmed Monday that he had received the letter from Egan, but
would not comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   Law said his concern with Marshall stems from a letter she wrote
while general counsel at Harvard University to Mary Ann Glendon, a
Harvard law professor and leading American Catholic intellectual
who is an antiabortion advocate. The cardinal did not detail the
contents of the letter, but he told the governor that Councilor
David Constantine has a copy of the letter and urged him to review
it.
</P>
<P>
   Constantine, a Democrat from New Bedford, did not return calls
made to his office and home Monday. Marshall was not available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Law's letter to Cellucci surfaces as Marshall faces opposition
on another front from several members of the Governor's Council,
which much approve her nomination.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, the council's longest-serving member and father of
state Treasurer Shannon O'Brien, said he would oppose Marshall
because he feels that she does not have enough courtroom experience
on the SJC to be its chief. Marshall was appointed by Weld in late
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned she hasn't had the time in service,'' said
O'Brien, an Easthampton Democrat. He said he has reviewed her
opinions and has no ``quarrels'' with her judicial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Brien also denounced Cellucci for suggesting that his
opposition to Marshall and his questioning of Cowin is based on
their gender. On several occasions since he nominated Marshall,
Cellucci has denounced the opposition to her and other appointments
of women as gender bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very unhappy the governor would stoop to that kind of
language,'' O'Brien said. ``If I disagree with him, I disagree with
courtesy.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said his daughter had called him urging him to support
Marshall's elevation, which would make her the first woman to lead
the court.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not budged. He is expected to be joined by
Constantine and Councilor Michael Callahan, a Democrat from
Medford, in opposing Marshall's elevation. Lieutenant Governor Jane
Swift can cast the deciding vote if there is a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's nomination of Appeals Court Judge Francis X. Spina to
the SJC is also before the council. Spina is expected to be
confirmed, despite concerns raised about his hiring a paralegal who
is a convicted murderer serving a prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Law and Cellucci have sparred over issues involving the Catholic
Church in the past, including the death penalty and abortion.
Cellucci favors the death penalty, which Law has opposed as not in
line with Vatican teaching on capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1991, Law said Cellucci should not be permitted to
deliver a commencement address at Hudson Catholic High School,
Cellucci's alma mater, because the then-lieutenant governor
supported abortion rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
