u f BC-NETSOLVE-IPO-COX     09-27 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETSOLVE-IPO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NetSolve plans IPO for Wednesday
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Amid a renewed flurry of initial public
offerings, another Austin company is planning to go public this
week, solidifying what has already been a record year for IPOs in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   NetSolve Inc., which provides computer network management and
security services, is expected to raise $38.5 million in an IPO
planned for Wednesday, offering more than 3.5 million shares in the
$11- to $13-per-share range. The final price should be set today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another Austin company solidified its IPO plans on
Monday. Crossroads Systems Inc., which announced its IPO plans last
month, filed documents with the Securities and Exchange Commission
that sets its offering at 3.5 million shares priced between $11 and
$13 apiece. Crossroads Systems makes servers and systems aimed at
reducing congestion on computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   NetSolve will be Austin's seventh IPO in as many months, and
comes during a renewed interest in high-tech offerings _ despite
the fact that the stock market dropped precipitously last week.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the NetSolve, as many as 30 companies are planning
IPOS this week, which would make it the busiest week of the year
for IPOs. So far, the busiest week this year for initial sales was
the week of July 26, when 27 companies went public, said Rich
Peterson, spokesman for Thompson Financial Securities Data Co.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in planned offerings comes after a lull of a few
months for Internet IPOs, during which many companies postponed
sales rather than brave a lackluster market.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 22 IPOs were postponed amid market volatility,
including Austin's Garden.com Inc. For the first time ever, four
Internet IPOs declined from their offer price by the close of trade
on their first day in August.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Austin companies have generally fared well with their
IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Only one, Hoover's Inc. has seen its shares decline from their
offering price. Monday, Hoover's closed at $13 a share, down $1, or
7 percent, from its offering price.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Vignette Corp. _ the first Austin Internet company
to go public _ has been one of the most successful IPOs this year.
It s stock is up about 354 percent from its offering price, closing
Monday at $86.25.
</P>
<P>
   The continued strength of Internet and other high-tech IPOs will
depend on the strength of the broader market for Internet and
technology stocks, said Steven Disanctis, head of small-cap
research at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the market holds up, then we can see a lot of these deals
get done . . . but it all depends,'' Disanctis said. ``If we see
poor performance by the overall equity market, by the overall
Internet stocks, then we may see a slowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Cocks writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
