<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VISITS POOR SCHOOL TO VOICE EDUCATION THEME 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: La.) (nk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ A week after the Sophie B. Wright Middle School
was labeled ``academically unacceptable,'' President Clinton used
the school's aging, overcrowded campus Monday as a backdrop for his
call for beefed-up education financing.
</P>
<P>
   The president criticized congressional Republicans for unveiling
a spending bill last week that would cut White House initiatives to
modernize school campuses, reduce class sizes and improve the
quality of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The congressional majority in the other party in the House
unveiled an education budget that was $3 billion below what I asked
for: no money to finish hiring the 10,000 teachers, no money to
help modernize or build 6,000 schools,'' Clinton told several
hundred students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the president, the Wright Middle School stood as an
example of the need for attention. The roof of the 87-year-old
school leaks when it rains. The average class size hovers at 32
students. And last week, Louisiana's first statewide performance
rating put Wright Middle and numerous other New Orleans schools
near the bottom academically.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte L. Matthew, the principal of Wright, said the problems
included pupils several grades behind in their reading levels and a
building rife with safety hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a leaky roof,'' Ms. Matthew said. ``We have ceiling
tiles falling. We have floor tiles buckling.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House said a House bill for labor, education, health
and human services programs would not do enough to improve such
needy schools. The spending bill provides no financing to reduce
class sizes and no guarantee that 30,000 teachers hired last year
can continue teaching. The Republican tax bill would modernize only
644 schools, vs. 6,000 in the president's plan, White House aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans maintain that their approach to education would
send money to local schools and not the Washington bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the grim status of Wright Middle School, which is named
after a New Orleans educator, the president found plenty to praise.
</P>
<P>
   He complimented the students on their school uniforms, a concept
he has been promoting in districts nationwide. He singled out a
young girl who scored in the 95th percentile on the science portion
of an achievement test. And he told students they could succeed
even in a less-than-ideal environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have visited more schools than any president in
history,'' Clinton said. ``And I have never met a child that
couldn't learn or a school that couldn't do better and be turned
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides its need for attention, Wright Middle fit the
president's itinerary for another reason: It is just across the
street from Clinton's next stop.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton visited St. Elizabeth's Orphanage, now an art gallery,
to address a $2,500-a-person fund-raiser for Rep. William J.
Jefferson, a New Orleans Democrat who is seeking to become
Louisiana's first black governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
