<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Legendary Opera House Rises Again in Spain &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After its opening in Barcelona in 1847, the Gran Teatre del
Liceu quickly became one of Europe's most highly regarded opera
houses. After it burned down in 1861, the handsome neo-classical
building was reconstructed, and its reputation continued to grow
until another fire destroyed it in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 11, the theater _ once again rebuilt _ will reopen with
a performance of Puccini's ``Turandot,'' starring Sharon Sweet,
Maria Bayo and Jan Blinkhof and conducted by the Gran Teatre del
Liceu's musical director, Bertrand de Billy.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999-2000 season, which runs through July, features
``Lohengrin,'' staged by Peter Konwitschny; ``The Marriage of
Figaro,'' staged by Robert Carsen; Verdi's ``Requiem'' and
orchestral music of Richard Wagner; recitals by Montserrat Caballe,
Marilyn Horne and Jane Eaglen; and performances by the Frankfurt
Ballet, Bolshoi Theater Ballet and Spain's Compania Nacional de
Danza.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was decided to update the theater and go beyond the demanding
task of recreating the original building _ with its Italian
Renaissance entrance hall, with blue silk-covered walls and marble
columns leading to the majestic curved staircase, and lavish
putti-filled murals. To preserve the auditorium's intimacy, its
former dimensions were kept, but the seating, acoustics and
lighting were greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the 2,320 red-velvet seats with their elaborate
cast-iron bases now have better sightlines; a new foyer under the
stalls, with space for 800 people, allows dining during
intermissions. The building is accessible by wheelchair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the Gran Teatre del Liceu, 51-59 La Rambla, (34-93)
417-00-60, range from $19 to $1,260.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Gladstone &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Samovars and Borscht: A Russian Star Returns &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If a restaurant can have a soul, the Russian Tea Room's must be
that of Rasputin. The jewel box on 57th Street has shrugged off
everything from Prohibition to nouvelle cuisine as New York City
has expanded and evolved around it for the better part of the
century. This month, after an extensive redesign by the new owner,
Warner LeRoy, who also owns Tavern on the Green, the restaurant
will open once again, with a modern Russian menu by Fabrice
Canelle, formerly of the Brasserie Savoy in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Although the entrance level is in the restaurant's famous
original style, replete with red leather banquettes, samovars and
perpetual Christmas ornaments dripping from the lights, as one
ascends, the fantasy quotient rises, too. On the second floor, upon
a jeweled base, there is a 15-foot revolving bear that functions as
an aquarium filled with sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   The third story, with a double-height ceiling, has a ballroom
that continues the motif with glass bears etched on mirrors and
brass bears dangling from chandeliers. On the fourth floor there's
a diorama of pre-revolutionary Red Square in which special effects
depict the changing seasons, a moving river and tiny Russian troops
awaiting the czar. Throughout the restaurant, vodka will be
distributed from a 700-pound ice castle on a trolley.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant will serve updated traditional Russian dishes
such as Georgian spiced, seared cod, served with plum sauce, and
such Asian dishes as pelmeni, a dumpling filled with ground veal
and beef, onion, Dijon mustard, mint and cilantro. Dinner entrees
are $22 to $34, lunch $13 to $24.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Tea Room is at 150 West 57th Street. Reservations:
(212) 974-2111.
</P>
<P>
   Caitlin Lovinger &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Designer Show House Opens in Delaware &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delaware's First Lady, Martha S. Carper, is helping preserve a
slice of Dover history. Under her guidance, Hall House will open
its doors and grounds Sunday as a designer showcase. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1886 by Thomas Wilson Jr., Hall House was purchased in
1983 as a guest annex to Woodburn, the governor's residence. Named
for Delaware's 46th governor, John Wood Hall, the 20-room Victorian
combines elements from several styles popular during that era
including Eastlake, Stick and Gothic. Victorian furnishings, from
the collections of the state's museums, will remain in place after
the show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eleven Delaware design firms were chosen to refurbish the house
in styles consistent with the period. Richard Scott from J. Conn
Scott in Selbyville, for example, has selected a soft salmon-toned
Scalamandre damask fabric to cover the walls in the West Parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Thomas from Little Creek Inn in Dover will incorporate
framed needlepoints, period portraits and pastoral tapestries along
with Jacobean furniture in a third-floor bedroom. In addition,
three local landscape designers are redoing the grounds in a
Victorian style. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hall House, at 181 Kings Highway, (302) 739-3610, will be open
daily through Oct. 31. Tickets: $12 in advance, $15 at the door.
Proceeds benefit the Boys and Girls Clubs of Delaware and Friends
of Woodburn, which oversees the restoration and upkeep of both Hall
House and Woodburn. A gift shop features the work of local artisans
and vendors. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   London Bans Cars On Some Soho Streets &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several streets in Soho, one of central London's busiest areas,
are now closed to traffic every afternoon and evening in a one-year
trial period. The plan, which includes new one-way traffic routes
and bicycle lanes, will be monitored, and the findings discussed at
the end of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Soho is a neighborhood of narrow streets with many restaurants,
bars and clubs as well as small shops, markets and media-industry
offices. It is bounded by Shaftesbury Avenue, home to many West End
theaters; Charing Cross Road, known for its bookshops; and Oxford
and Regent Streets, two of London's main shopping areas.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, drawn up by the Westminster City Council and Central
London Partnership, aims to reduce congestion in an area that has
become increasingly crowded. The street closings are from noon to 4
a.m. (to allow for deliveries) and include parts of Old Compton
Street and Frith Street, as well as Fareham, Moor and Soho Streets.
More street closings in Soho and around Regent Street are planned
for March.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Rooms Scarce for Sydney's Games &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to attend the Olympic Games in Sydney in September
but have not yet ordered tickets, they are still likely to be
available, although the hardest to find are those for the opening
and closing ceremonies, diving, the basketball finals and certain
swimming and gymnastics events.
</P>
<P>
   Cartan Tours, the official United States agency, said that
Olympic committee rules decreed giving priority to those who
applied by April 30, then to those applying between May 1 and Sept.
15 and then to those who apply now through next Jan. 31. In all
cases, Cartan said, ticket distribution for particular events is
determined by a ``lottery'' _ a random selection by computer.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have room reservations or family or friends in
Australia, do not be surprised if you wind up in anything from a
college dorm to a campground. But even that will be expensive, and
probably a long commute to the event.
</P>
<P>
   Although 11,000 new hotel rooms are expected to be ready by
September, including the new 417-room Westin Sydney, there will be
only 35,000 rooms for the expected 250,000-plus visitors. And 80
percent of those are reserved for Olympic officials and visitors on
packages that usually include games tickets, air fare and lodging.
The cheapest such package from Cartan, at $4,900, includes six
nights at a private home. Visitors who go on their own will be
lucky to find a room in a private house, and if they do, they can
expect to pay $1,800 to $2,500 a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
