<HEADLINE>
WORLD WAR I CEMETERIES  
 AWAITING VAT REFUND  
 THE MILLENNIUM IN HONOLULU  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics) My husband and I plan to visit the World War I
battlefield graves in France of two relatives, one at the Ste.-Olle
British cemetery in Raillencourt, the other at the Bois-Carre
military cemetery in Haisnes. We hope to see both in one day and
then go to Scotland and Ireland. How can we get from one cemetery
to the other? What's the most direct way to go to Edinburgh? _
Diane S. Gaffney, Jackson Heights, N.Y.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The cemeteries are 40 miles apart so they can, indeed, be
visited in a single day. One way to minimize the constraints of
timetables is to take a train to Arras and then rent a car to get
to the cemeteries, which are near the Belgian border. Leaving the
Gare du Nord in Paris at 7:22, 8:22 or 9:22 a.m., for example, it's
a journey of about 40 minutes to Arras. Avis, (800) 331-1084,
Budget, (800) 472-3325, and Hertz, (800) 654-3001, have branches in
or near the railroad station.
</P>
<P>
   If you want more frequent service, take the train to Lille;
Avis, Budget and Hertz have branches at one or both of the rail
stations there. The fares to Arras are $49 first class and $42
second class; to Lille they are $68 and $52.
</P>
<P>
   The Bois-Carre cemetery is near Haisnes, a village that remained
in German hands until the final advance, mostly by British units,
in 1918. Bois-Carre is about a mile and a quarter south of La
Bassee village. You can walk or reserve a taxi by calling Taxi
Allard, (33-3) 20.49.99.44. Many of the more than 200 soldiers
buried there were members of the 16th (Irish) Division. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To drive from Haisnes to Raillencourt, take the D947 to Lens,
then the A21 east to Henin-Beaumont, where you pick up the A1/E17
toward Paris. Get off at exit 8 and follow the signs to
Raillencourt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer public transport, you will have to go to La Bassee
train station and take the regional train to the Flandres Station
in Lille and change there for Cambrai. Raillencourt can also be
reached by bus from the Cambrai depot, 1 Rue Vauban. Information:
(33-3) 27.82.28.55. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ste.-Olle cemetery is 500 yards south of the village of
Raillencourt, near the Chemin des Vignes. The village was liberated
by the Canadian Corps in the Battle of the Canal du Nord in 1918.
Most of the 97 Canadian soldiers with graves at the cemetery
belonged to the 116th Battalion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Raillencourt, it's a 45-minute drive to the Lille Europe
Station, where you can board a Eurostar train. It leaves for
Waterloo Station in London daily except Sunday at 10:12 a.m., 12:45
p.m. and 6:45 p.m. Travel time is two hours. The fare is $199 first
class, $129 second. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you continue by rail, remember that the train to Edinburgh
departs from Kings Cross Station. Rail Europe suggests allowing an
hour for transfer between the terminals. Information: (800)
438-7245 or www.raileurope.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first-class train fare to Edinburgh is $185 one way ($315
round trip); the standard-class fare is $130 one way ($185 round
trip). Travel time is four hours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you would rather fly, British Airways, for example, has 12
flights a day on weekdays from Heathrow alone. The flight takes an
hour and the advance-purchase round-trip fare is as low as $77.
Information: (800) 247-9297.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Web sites that you may want to consult is that of the
Britain-based Commonwealth War Graves Commission, www.cwgc.org. It
lists the names and military units of the 1.7 million commonwealth
troops who died in the two world wars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)In May on my way back from Charles de Gaulle Airport
in Paris, I stopped at the tax-free counter and handed over two
envelopes for purchases made in Paris and Florence. I am still
waiting for a refund, not knowing how to proceed. How long should
one wait? _ Milka S. Burstein, New Smyrna Beach, Fla. (end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The largest VAT refund service is Global Refund so chances
are that's the company that handled your paperwork. It is
affiliated with 130,000 stores in 25 countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you asked that your refund be credited to your charge card,
the entry on your monthly statement would read ``tax refund'' and
be followed by the name of country where the purchase was made.
Sometimes such entries are overlooked, according to Julia Ryan,
Global Refund's director of marketing for North America. In any
event, the refund should have shown up in two to three billing
cycles, she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are several ways to get in touch with Global Refund: Call
(800) 566-9828, the customer service line, and leave a message;
call (203) 674-8145 to speak to a representative; send a fax to
(203) 674-8709, or write to Global Refund, 707 Summer Street,
Stamford, Conn. 06901.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you made a purchase elsewhere, Global Refund may be able
to suggest where to turn for help. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)We will be in Honolulu to celebrate the year 2000,
but cannot find information about festivities and programs. The
Hawaii Visitors Bureau Web site calendar.gohawaii.com, has nothing
about that period. We are interested in a public celebration, under
some official auspices, so it will not be too wild. Can you help? _
Joan Margol, Newport Beach, Calif.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Like you, we struggled to find year-end events at that site.
An official of the Hawaii Visitors and Convention Bureau said that
after checking ``Oahu'' and ``all categories,'' users should enter
``millennium'' in the box labeled ``Title/Description.'' Or one can
click on ``Special Events.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the dawning of a millennium, one cannot expect calm to be
the order of the day _ or night. Among the quieter events will very
likely be Starlight MADDness, an alcohol-free event at Ala Moana
Beach Park from noon to midnight. Sponsored by Mothers Against
Drunk Driving, Hawaii, and the city and county of Honolulu, the
event will offer free entertainment, food booths and children's
activities and, at midnight, a pyrotechnic salute to 2000.
Admission is free. Information: (808) 532-6232.
</P>
<P>
   At the Aloha Tower Marketplace, a shopping-entertainment complex
on Honolulu harbor, the new year will be celebrated as it begins in
each of five time zones, starting with New York at 7 p.m. At
midnight, there will be a Grucci fireworks display. Information:
(808) 528-5700.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-minute drive away, there will be yet more fireworks at
midnight _ from barges off Waikiki Beach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At major hotels, leading musicians and dancers will perform
contemporary and traditional Hawaiian works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
