u f BC-JAPAN-YEN-450&AMP;ADD-NYT     09-27 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-YEN-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEN POLICY STAYS THE SAME, JAPAN INSISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese monetary officials have spent the last few days
trying to dispel the impression that they changed monetary policy
to weaken the yen as a result of foreign pressure at a weekend
meeting of rich industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts by the Bank of Japan and the Ministry of Finance
came after the Group of Seven countries issued a surprisingly frank
statement Saturday night that they considered the yen's recent
strength undesirable.
</P>
<P>
   The statement from the meeting, which was held in Washington,
went further than financial markets had been expecting, and the yen
plunged in value against the dollar when markets reopened Monday on
speculation that central banks of the G-7 nations might act
together to weaken the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently worried that the statement might have sent a wrong
signal about possible concessions, Japanese officials said Sunday
and Monday that they had made no policy changes.
</P>
<P>
   But the dollar, which hit a series of three-and-a-half-year lows
last week, still ended the day higher. In late New York trading,
the dollar cost 106.00 yen, up from 104.17 yen late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The yen has risen over 15 percent in value in recent months on
evidence that Japan's long-stagnant economy is finally expanding.
But a stronger yen could threaten that recovery by making Japanese
exports more expensive, hurting sales and profits in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has said that Japan must take more aggressive
steps to weaken the currency, like expanding the supply of money in
the banking system _ a proposal the Japanese central bank rejected
last week. So the G-7 statement of unity concerning the yen
suggested that Japan had changed its position.
</P>
<P>
   As headlines around the world crowed that the bank had caved in
to pressure, Masaru Hayami, the bank's governor, hastily summoned
reporters to a news conference on Sunday in Washington, where he
told them they were misconstruing what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed,'' he said in response to reports that the
bank planned to print yen to spark inflation; that it had declared
foreign-exchange rates would play a role in setting monetary
policy, and that it had otherwise amended its recent hard-line
opposition to further easing its already loose monetary stance.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when the statement Hayami issued at the G-7 meeting is
compared with the one issued after the bank's policy board met last
Tuesday and voted not to change monetary policy, it seems nothing
has shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distinctions in what the bank has been saying have been
lost in the very high level of politics between it and the Ministry
of Finance,'' said Jeffrey Young, an economist at Nikko Salomon
Smith Barney in Tokyo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Washington, the bank said its policy of maintaining
short-term interest rates at zero percent has ensured enough
liquidity in the banking system _ the same thing it said last
Tuesday. It said it was concerned that the yen's rise might
negatively affect the Japanese economy _ which it also said last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the bank said it would use what flexibility its
current monetary policy offers to respond to changes in the economy
and in the financial markets. Hayami made a similar statement at a
news conference last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And the bank said it was considering how to change its money
market operations to increase the money supply, something it has
also previously said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that matters about that is by how much _ and
Hayami has never said how much,'' said a senior bank official here.
``I'm afraid the press has been fooled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
