Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT (moved on Friday, Sept. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Sept. 24,
about United Nations sanctions against Iraq misattributed the
accusation that the United Nations has taken most of the money from
Iraqi oil sales in the last three years and used it to subsidize
arms inspections and to compensate Kuwait for Iraq's invasion of
that country. The charge was made by Iraq's Foreign Minister,
Mohammed Said al-Sahaf, not by James P. Rubin, the spokesman for
the United States State Department.
</P>
<P>
   BC-RUSSIA-FIGHTING-NYT (moved on Sunday, Sept. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Sept. 26,
about Russia's bombardment of Chechnya misstated the number of
Chechen refugees who officials said have crossed into the
neighboring region of Ingushetia in the last few days. It is more
than 20,000 _ not 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   BC-YACHT-RACE-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Sunday, Sept. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Sept. 26,
about books on the Sydney-Hobart racing disaster misstated the
ownership of the publisher, Pocket Books. It is part of Viacom's
Simon &AMP; Schuster unit _ not of Pearson, which purchased some of
Simon &AMP; Schuster's education publishing operations last year.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-GOFF-NYT (moved on Friday, Sept. 24)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Ivan Goff sent by the New York Times News
Service on Friday, Sept. 24, misidentified a star of ``The
Rogues,'' a television series he created in the 1960's with his
partner, Ben Roberts. The series starred David Niven, Charles Boyer
and Gig Young. Dick Powell was not in the cast.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OPERA-RECORDBREAKER-NYT (moved on Sunday, Sept. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Sept. 26,
about the record for which Placido Domingo was headed, for the most
opening-night performances at the Metropolitan Opera _ 18,
surpassing Enrico Caruso's 17 _ misidentified one of Mr. Domingo's
previous opening-night tenor roles. It was Wagner's Siegmund, not
Siegfried.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incorrectly to Ezio Pinza, who is in
third place for Met opening nights, with 9. He was a bass-baritone,
not a baritone.
</P>
</TEXT>
