<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-100-MEMORABLE-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSET SPECIAL ONLY BLEMISH ON MAN O' WAR'S CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Jus' da mostest hoss.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the way Will Harbut described the horse he groomed and
cared for _ the powerful Man o' War.
</P>
<P>
   Though the memory of Secretariat capping his 1973 Triple Crown
by 31 lengths in the Belmont remains with many of today's sports
fans, a horse racing magazine, ``The Blood-Horse'', recently listed
Man o' War the greatest horse to race in the 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable career: 21 starts. Just one loss. But loads and
loads of controversy over it, and a term that entered into the
language forever.
</P>
<P>
   Man o' War was showing tremendous promise as a 2-year-old in
1919. With six easy victories in as many races, the
chestnut-colored colt was in upstate New York as the odds-on
favorite in Saratoga Race Course's Sanford Memorial Stakes for
2-year-olds on Aug. 13. So the track's racing office assigned ``Big
Red'' to carry 15 pounds more than his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Racetracks then had no starting gate. Horses were brought onto
the track and led behind a tape that was stretched across the
starting line.
</P>
<P>
   Their energy and anticipation often got the best of them. Horses
often false-started. The start of a race could be delayed by a
half-hour before the official starter could maintain order.
</P>
<P>
   But for reasons most historians have lost, Saratoga starter Mars
Cassidy was not on the job that day. A replacement _ a man in his
70s named Charles Pentingill _ tried to line up the field for a
start.
</P>
<P>
   Under jockey Johnny Loftus, Man o' War broke through the tape
early at least five times. An energetic horse rarely could be
backed up perfectly. His return trip consisted of alternating
sideways moves.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was with Man o' War _ sideways when Pentingill pulled
the tape. Since it was a 6-furlong sprint (three quarters of a
mile), there wasn't much ground for a horse to come back.
</P>
<P>
   But Loftus' ride was the next questionable move. He placed Man
o' War down by the rail behind a horse named Golden Broom to
apparently wait for an opening.
</P>
<P>
   In contact with the field at the top of the stretch, Loftus was
still looking for an opening. With just an eighth of a mile to go,
Loftus angled Man o' War off the rail.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was on. And down the stretch he came. Man o' War _
beaten. Second, by a half-length. To a horse named ... Upset.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing's importance in that era of sports _ U.S. society
was yet to depend on the horseless carriage _ caused Man o' War's
loss to reverberate forever in the language.
</P>
<P>
   So the Jets beat the Colts 50 years later? It was an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Overconfidence may have done in the Colts. But what got the best
of the ``Big Red'' colt?
</P>
<P>
   The 15 extra pounds he had to carry? But Man o' War later
spotted rivals as much as 32 pounds and still won easily; he set
three world records and once won a race by 100 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Pentingill, it turns out, was hardly a suitable replacement as a
starter. It once took him 40 tries _ a delay of an hour and a half
_ to get the horses started for the American Derby in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Did the jockeys fix the race? There was no official ruling, but
The Jockey Club later refused to license Loftus and Upset jockey
Willie Knapp, though both eventually were named to racing's Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Man o' War's induction to the hall went without question. Even
with his Upset, he was ``jus' da mostest hoss.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8210 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CHANNEL-ISLAND     09-27 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CHANNEL-ISLANDS-3TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPING ON AN ISLE OF MENACING MICE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BARBARA STRAUCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was near the end of our two-hour boat ride off the California
coast when we finally got our show.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, Meryl, 11, and I were near the bow when she spotted
them _ off to the left _ not one, not two, but dozens of dolphins,
their sleek, gray-black bodies leaping out of the green ocean. They
jumped in pairs, in unison, playing in the wake. One cruised
alongside the boat in the full force of the foam _ getting a
massage? just showing off? Others pirouetted only feet away, so
close and so many it was thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're jumping really high,'' shouted Meryl over the boat
engine's roar. ``They're so cool!''
</P>
<P>
   Her delight, however, would not remain undiluted. My husband,
Richard, Meryl and my other daughter, Hayley, 14, and I were on our
way in July to spend two nights at one of the newest additions to
the National Park system, the campground on Santa Cruz Island in
the Channel Islands National Park. This family adventure proved
decidedly mixed, both glorious and _ at certain dicey moments _ a
bit grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   The first hint of the latter came just after our dolphin show
with the arrival of a park ranger, Derek. Our boat, the 65-foot
Vanguard, dropped anchor in the harbor and Derek paddled up in a
yellow kayak. With his long blond hair, shorts and sandals, Derek
looked suitably beachy. But after gathering would-be campers on the
deck, his message was tinged with grimness.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, the island was still digging out from an El Nino
storm in 1997 that sent a four-foot wall of water and mud down the
canyon, destroying the campground and upending historic ranch
houses. We might, he said, ``see a lot of heavy equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   OK
</P>
<P>
   Second, to restore the island's ecosystem, the park service was
removing thousands of feral sheep, left from the days of ranching,
that were now wild and eating the island naked. So, he said, we
might hear a lot of helicopters dropping noise devices to scare
sheep into corrals.
</P>
<P>
   OK
</P>
<P>
   Third, he said, there were the deadly mice.
</P>
<P>
   Oh dear.
</P>
<P>
   With recent rainy winters and few predators on the island, the
deer mouse population, he said, had exploded. And many of the mice
were infected with sin nombre hantavirus, the same lethal virus
that in 1993 killed about two dozen people in the Four Corners area
of the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot emphasize enough,'' said Derek, his California-sunny
face in a stern frown, ``you must secure all your food _ away from
the mice. Once the sun goes down, the island belongs to the mice.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not absolutely news. Planning the trip beforehand, I'd
found local newspaper articles that mentioned the problem. The
campsite receipt from the park service said ``... bring own water
... pit toilets ... hantavirus in mice.'' But a park service worker
whom I had spoken to on the phone emphasized, as Derek later did,
that no one had ever been infected with the hantavirus on the
Channel Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I thought, every place has something wrong. At least there
were no bears. I wanted to camp on an island. How many mice could
there be?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, as Derek also told us, by way of a brighter
afterthought, ``you have come to a remarkable place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Channel Islands are, indeed, remarkable. Formed by volcanic
and plate tectonic activity beginning about 14 million years ago,
they rise in steep, sheer cliffs from the Pacific. They consist of
eight islands 11 to 60 miles offshore, between Santa Barbara and
San Diego. Growing up in California, I was well aware of one of the
islands, the populated Santa Catalina. But few Californians, myself
included, ever gave much thought to the others in the chain.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some have a rich history. One, San Nicolas, was the
setting for the popular children's book ``Island of the Blue
Dolphins'' by Scott O'Dell, based on the true story of a lone
Indian woman found on the island in 1853 living in a whale rib
house and wearing a cormorant feather dress.
</P>
<P>
   All the islands were inhabited by Chumash or Gabrielino Indians,
who fished, paddled canoes and traded with mainland Indians
starting about 13,000 years ago. A Spanish conquistador, Juan
Rodriguez Cabrillo, came across them in 1542; he died a few months
later when he fell off an island cliff.
</P>
<P>
   The islands passed through Spanish and Mexican ownership, then
to various private owners who engaged in a whole range of
activities from running hunting safaris (with imported wild pigs,
which remain on Santa Cruz), sheep and cattle ranches and wineries.
</P>
<P>
   The islands are rich scientifically, too. The rare blue whale
(the largest creature on earth with a heart the size of a
Volkswagen Beetle) feeds off its shores, as do sea lions and huge
elephant seals.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore, Darwin would have been happy. Because of their
isolation, the islands have endemic plants and animals that don't
exist anywhere else. The island fox is as small as a cat and the
island blue jay is huge compared to its mainland counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a Channel Islands National Park came up in 1938
when President Franklin Delano Roosevelt proclaimed two islands,
Santa Barbara and Anacapa, national monuments. In 1980, Congress
designated five of the islands a national park and later protected
six miles of ocean surrounding each as a marine sanctuary. Then, in
1997, the park service acquired the last sliver of land it wanted,
our destination, the campground and old ranches on the east end of
Santa Cruz Island.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of all the islands, Santa Cruz is perhaps the most romantic.
It's the largest, 22 miles long, four times the size of Manhattan.
Today, the western 90 percent is owned by the Nature Conservancy, a
private environmental group, while the rest is owned by the
National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1800s, a Californian, Justinian Caire, developed a
nearly self-contained community with cattle ranching and wineries.
Later, there was a popular inn, and Hollywood used the island as a
backdrop in silent movies, including ``Adam and Eve'' in 1918 and
``Male and Female'' in 1919, starring a young Gloria Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful, however, that Miss Swanson ever had to contend
with what we found at Campsite No. 33 on Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little past sundown when we saw the first one. After
hauling our gear a half-mile in Park Service wheelbarrows, we had
set up our tent in what we thought was a perfect spot, under a
stand of eucalyptus trees facing a stunning yellow-gold canyon with
clumps of green oaks and a crayon-blue sky.
</P>
<P>
   We spent the afternoon hiking along high white cliffs, walking
for hours without seeing anyone. It felt far away, like trekking
through Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after a pasta dinner, we were putting the food away when
Hayley said, ``There's a mouse!'' and then, ``There's another
one!''
</P>
<P>
   They were scurrying across a log. As I looked, more arrived _
not one, not two, but dozens. It was like some perverse inverse of
the dolphin show. All at once, tiny gray mice were everywhere,
under the picnic table, around the fire ring.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we thought, we're not ninnies; we can beat this. We put
the food in a strong bag in the tent, as the ranger had advised,
zipped the tent and lay back to go to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, we heard them. It was dark now and they were
rustling in the leaves, first a few feet from the tent, then
inches. Richard started making Alfred Hitchcock jokes; Hayley
thought they sounded cute. I was horrified.
</P>
<P>
   I had to concede my own wishful thinking. Before coming, hearing
about the mice, I thought they would be mostly in the fields,
perhaps a few around campsites, numbers we could avoid. But they
were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the rest of the family fell asleep and it was only me
listening. The mice were getting bolder, flinging themselves at the
tent, then sliding down, making a terrible scratching sound. Deadly
mice were using my tent as a ski slope. I felt ill: I was a bad
mom.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the moon was full and bright, and I glanced up at the
closed screen on the front of the tent. One big dark mouse, a
stalwart one that had made it to the top, slid all the way down the
netting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard,'' I said, jabbing my husband, ``I want to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, of course, the sun came up. When we ventured out of
the tent, there were no mice, not a peep. An informal poll of the
few campers nearby found they had not had as much of a problem as
we did. They had heard mice, but none had used their tents as ski
jumps.
</P>
<P>
   We decided to go down to the pristine beach, where lone campers
and a family with small children were kayaking around sea caves. We
played and swam a bit in the clear, chilly water. We could see
giant kelp growing 35 feet below, and only yards away, around some
rocks, sea lions popped their heads up through a tangle of seaweed.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, we decided to move the tent to a campsite farther
into the canyon without as many logs. And on the second night,
there was, as far as we could tell, not one mouse.
</P>
<P>
   That second afternoon, we hiked up into the canyon, scrambling
over boulders, watching hawks circle, feeling better.
</P>
<P>
   The island at this time of year was sunbaked dry, its parched
hills covered with golden grass. Aside from the occasional oak or
eucalyptus, the yellow fields were broken only by rows of giant
coreopsis _ a five-foot-tall island version of the mainland plant _
that in spring produce brilliant flowers but in summer stand brown
and bare, like scraggly cactus. Near barren, the island had the
calming beauty of a desert.
</P>
<P>
   Since many of the animals are nocturnal, we saw no wild pigs or
foxes, but climbing the quiet, steep trails we'd often startle
quail. One morning, we watched, a bit sadly, as park workers and
dogs herded dozens of wild and frightened sheep onto trucks to be
taken off the island by barge.
</P>
<P>
   Later, back in New York, I found out that while we were on
vacation, the Channel Island mice had been the focus of a
mini-political dustup. When an Oxnard family returned from a visit
to Santa Rosa Island and reported that their 7-year-old son had
been playing with a mouse, which later tested positive for
hantavirus antibodies, a California Republican, Rep. Elton Gallegly
convened a hearing in late June before the House subcommittee on
National Parks and Public Lands asserting that notification was lax
for the more than 60,000 tourists who visit the islands each year.
</P>
<P>
   James Mills, chief of the medical ecology unit for special
pathogens branch at the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta, who participated in the hearings, said that
the situation was being taken seriously and that it had now been
decided, if funds were available, to start routinely sampling mouse
populations for the presence of the virus in a number of western
national parks. Mills said the National Park Service would also
increase education efforts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But he, too, stressed that the disease is rare _ there have been
only 227 cases since it was identified in 1993, but 42 percent of
those ended in death _ and that there is a lower risk of infection
outdoors because wind dissipates the virus and sunlight deactivates
it.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, which can spread to people through bites or
feces-tainted dust, has been mostly found in western regions of the
nation, with its prevalence varying greatly from year to year. At
one point, as many as 70 percent of the mice on Santa Cruz were
found to have been infected, but now the exact prevalence in the
park is unknown. In the last couple of years, the park says, the
highest prevalence on any island was 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't hesitate to go to the park myself,'' Mills said.
``But you have to take certain precautions. Tell children that even
friendly deer mice can be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Spears, a spokeswoman for the park, agreed, adding that
visitors have a chance to see an unusual and beautiful place.
``This is one of the least visited and most unique parks in the
system,'' she said. ``Here you have completely undisturbed islands
so near an area with thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the boat back to the mainland, those two sides of this
national treasure were aptly summed up. A middle-aged man from
Santa Barbara who had spent two days camping near us and showing
his niece how to kayak talked of what the Channel Islands offer.
``It is,'' he said, ``like California was 100 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' agreed a woman from Connecticut, sitting nearby who had
been to the island for the day, ``I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' she said, turning to me, sitting on the deck with my
children. ``I hear they have a lot of mice _ and that virus. Don't
you have to worry about that?'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Far from the freeways &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Channel Islands National Park comprises five of the eight
California Channel Islands: San Miguel, Santa Rosa, Santa Cruz,
Anacapa and Santa Barbara. Information is available from the park's
Visitor Center, 1901 Spinnaker Drive, Ventura, Calif. 93001; (805)
658-5730, fax (805) 658-5799, and at www.nps.gov/chis. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting There &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Transportation to the islands, including for activities like
snorkeling and whale-watching, is provided year round by three
concessionaires, Island Packers, Truth Aquatics or Channel Island
Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Island Packers, 1867 Spinnaker Drive, Ventura, Calif. 93001,
(805) 642-1393, fax (805) 642-6573, runs boats daily between
Ventura and the park islands. Each way, the trips take from an hour
to Anacapa to five hours to San Miguel. Round-trip fares are $37 to
$90; campers pay $54 to Santa Cruz, ages 12 and under $40.
</P>
<P>
   Truth Aquatics, Sea Landing, 301 West Cabrillo Boulevard, Santa
Barbara, Calif., 93101, (805) 963-3564, fax (805) 564-6754, charges
campers $60 ($45 for 12 and under) round trip to Santa Cruz. Among
other offerings, a three-day trip to Santa Cruz, Santa Rosa and San
Miguel, with dorm-style accommodations and food on the boat, costs
$393.
</P>
<P>
   Channel Island Aviation, 305 Durley Avenue, Camarillo, Calif.
93010, (805) 987-1301, fax (805) 987-8301, flies daily to Santa
Rosa and Santa Cruz. Day trips, including a tour with a park
ranger, are $98, $78 for ages 12 and under. Drop off and pick up of
campers is $150 a person. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Camp &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camping is permitted on all the park's islands. A year-round
primitive (no water, pit toilets) campground with 45 sites is
operated by the Park Service at Scorpion Ranch on Santa Cruz
Island. Camping on the islands require reservations from the Park
Service, $2.50 a night from (800) 365-2267, but there are no other
fees to visit the park.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About the Virus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hantavirus pulmonary syndrome is a respiratory disease, for
which there is no cure, caused by sin nombre virus and carried by
the common deer mouse. Since it was identified in 1993, there have
been 227 reported cases nationwide, 42 percent of which ended in
death. The virus has been detected in 30 states, mostly in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service says that mice infected with the hantavirus are
on Santa Cruz, San Miguel and Santa Rosa Islands in the park, but
none have been found on Anacapa or Santa Barbara. There have been
no human hantavirus infections linked to the Channel Islands.
</P>
<P>
   People become infected by breathing air contaminated by the
feces or urine of mice that carry the virus, being bitten by an
infected mouse, or ingesting food or water contaminated by the
urine or droppings of infected mice. The virus initially causes
flu-like symptoms, and eventually causes the lungs to fill with
liquid.
</P>
<P>
   If symptoms appear, you should seek medical help immediately.
The only treatment, according to the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention, is to support a patient's respiration, with a
ventilator, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid infection, the Park Service recommends avoiding all
contact with rodents and burrows, using tents with floors to avoid
sleeping on bare ground, keeping food in rodent-proof containers,
and promptly discarding garbage in rodent-proof containers.
</P>
</TEXT>
