<HEADLINE>
OFFENDING PORTRAIT'S REMOVAL BROACHED BY MUSEUM OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs byline; subs complete story for new material, including
reaction of Hillary Rodham Clinton, and for rewriting throughout)  (See also MUSEUM-OFILI, an interview with the artist, with photo,
NYT10) 
(ART ADV: Photo of Hillary Rodham Clinton with Rep. Charles Rangel
in Harlem _ NYT28 _ has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW and DAVID M. HERSZENHORN c.1999 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeking to end a dispute with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
over a controversial art exhibition, the chairman of the Brooklyn
Museum of Art on Monday discussed with city officials the
possibility of removing the painting that had become the flashpoint
of the controversy _ a dung-stained portrait of the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   But after the officials disclosed the discussions to reporters,
other museum officials responded with dismay and the museum
chairman said on Monday night the exhibition would proceed as
planned.
</P>
<P>
   The development appeared to only deepen a battle that the mayor
has embraced with gusto and that on Monday spilled into his likely
Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton, who was forced to
speak out on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I discussed is now off the table,'' Robert S. Rubin,
chairman of the museum's board of trustees, said on Monday night,
clearly upset that word of his negotiations had been made public
before he had discussed them with other top museum officials.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, City Hall officials told reporters that
Rubin had tentatively offered _ subject to approval from the museum
board _ a package of concessions aimed at overcoming Giuliani's
objections to the exhibition, and at ensuring continued public
funding to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The package, city officials said, included removing the Virgin
Mary painting by the artist Chris Ofili, segregating five or six
other controversial works from the rest of the exhibition, and
accepting a 20 percent reduction in the city's subsidy to the
museum during the length of the show, which is scheduled to start
on Saturday and run through Jan. 9. The 20 percent reduction
corresponds to the amount of floor space the museum is devoting to
the exhibition, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this offer is true, it represents a major concession on the
part of the Brooklyn Museum, and a significant victory for Rudy
Giuliani,'' said Joseph J. Lhota, deputy mayor for operations, who
did not attend the meeting. ``On the money issue, in fact, if
that's true, it's important that taxpayer dollars will not be spent
on a painting which desecrates religion, plus other pieces of art
which glorify a child-murderer and the other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin acknowledged discussing the three ideas with city
officials, but he vigorously disputed their characterization of the
talks, and he emphasized that he engaged in the negotiations on his
own initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am chairman of the museum, and I _ without authorization
from the board, or without discussion with the staff of the museum
_ did raise certain ideas, that if they were acceptable to the
city, I would attempt to get agreement of all the relevant
parties,'' he said. ``Several ideas were on the table without any
commitment on my part that they could be implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said he had merely asked city officials to select one of
the three ideas as the basis for a possible compromise he would
then attempt to sell to his board. But the very fact that he was
discussing the removal or segregation of art works angered museum
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Lehman, the director of the museum, declined to comment
on Monday night, although several of his aides were stunned by word
of the negotiations and vehemently denied that the museum had
agreed to withdraw the Virgin Mary painting, which has been
condemned as blasphemous by several Catholic leaders in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not withdrawing any of the works in the exhibition,''
said Sally Williams, a spokeswoman for the museum. ``None of the
works are being withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hillary Rodham Clinton joined on Monday in denouncing
Giuliani's threat to cut city financing to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feelings of being offended should not lead to the
penalizing and shutting down of an entire museum,'' said Mrs.
Clinton, who is likely to run against Giuliani for U.S. Senate next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, appearing at a news conference in Harlem, added:
``I share the feeling that I know many New Yorkers have that there
are parts of this exhibition that would be deeply offensive. I
would not go to see this exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani seized on Mrs. Clinton's remarks, suggesting to
reporters that the first lady, who is Methodist, was countenancing
attacks on Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, then she agrees with using public funds to attack and
bash the Catholic religion,'' Giuliani said outside Hunter College
in Manhattan.``There is no way out of this. These public funds are
being used to aggressively bash the religious views of a
significant number of people in this city and state and country.
And the question is, can taxpayer dollars be used for this kind of
disgusting, anti-religious _ in some ways really aggressively
anti-religious _ kind of demonstration?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement on Monday, Rubin said that ``the ideals
of the institution are not on the bargaining table.'' But later, in
an interview, Rubin said he had indeed broached the possibility of
removing the painting, something other museum officials had vowed
for days would never happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the mayor had selected this painting by Chris Ofili as
the symbol of his disagreements with this exhibit, I felt that it
might be possible from his point of view that removing the symbol
of his disagreement with the museum might satisfy the city's
requirements to let us proceed with the exhibit,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting took place late Monday afternoon in the office of
Corporation Counsel Michael Hess. Also at the meeting was Schuyler
Chapin, commissioner of the city's Department of Cultural Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a meeting with Schuyler Chapin and Mr. Rubin, and we
discussed how to possibly resolve this dispute, and Mr. Rubin came
up with three separate ideas upon how to resolve this and I told
him that we would consider it if it was all three ideas,'' Hess
said. ``Not one, not two, but all three ideas. He said that was
okay and I discussed that with some of my staff and I came back to
him and said that those three ideas that he had come up with
together made up a proposal that I could live with. He said fine
and that he would take it back to his board members.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess added: ``I asked him, `Are you proposing A, B and C?' He
said yes, and I said I am telling my client about that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to city officials, if the museum board agreed to the
three provisions, Giuliani would then agree to abandon any efforts
to assume control of the board. The mayor would also end efforts to
cut all city funding to the museum, which this year amounts to
about $7 million a year toward operating expenses and another $20
million toward capital improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said city officials misinterpreted his remarks at the
meeting. He said he left without giving them a firm commitment to
make any recommendations to the museum board. ``What did I agree to
do when I left the meeting? I agreed that I would think about how I
could sell this to the relevant parties,'' he said, adding that ``I
have offered nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stressing that ``each one of these three items was my idea,''
Rubin said he thought, ``based on my 40 years experience as an
investment banker,'' that one of them ``might fly'' with both the
mayor and the members of his board, who are scheduled to meet at
the museum on Tuesday at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the discussions followed days of intense debate
throughout the city about freedom of expression and whether the
mayor has the right to withhold public funding from artistic
institutions that display art he finds offensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
