<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-COLLAPSES-NYT     09-27 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-COLLAPSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' DIVE: HISTORIC (HYSTERIC?) PROPORTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If squandering a one-game lead with five games to
play is considered a collapse and blowing a four-game lead in a
five-game span represents a collapse, the New York Mets would
appear to be the first team ever to suffer collapses in consecutive
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It makes for a striking epitaph.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets aren't dead yet, are they? With six games to play,
they can still catch Cincinnati and win the wild-card spot in the
playoffs, can't they? Or is it Houston the Mets have to catch now
that the Reds have tied the Astros for first place in the National
League Central?
</P>
<P>
   Since the Mets can't control what the Reds and the Astros do in
the next six days, they have to attend to their own business.
Theirs will not be funny business. They play the Atlanta Braves the
next three nights.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are the guys who began the Mets' problems, beating
them three times in Atlanta last week and sending them skidding
down a slippery slope that knocked them out of the NL East race.
The Braves have won the division championship, their eighth in
succession, and now can help determine which team they meet in the
first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They did that last year, defeating the Mets in the final three
games of the season. The Braves didn't let down in that series
because they didn't want the Mets to be the wild-card team. They
don't want the Mets to be the wild-card team this year either. Poor
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets are the wild-card team, the Braves can't play them
because the wild-card team can't play the champion of its own
division in the opening round. The Braves would have to play the
Arizona Diamondbacks or the Central Division winner.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to play the Diamondbacks in the three-of-five-game
division series because Randy Johnson can dominate it. The Astros
can match the Braves' good starting pitchers with good pitchers of
their own. The Reds, as resourceful as they have been, would seem
to be the best match for the Braves. The Reds have the league's
best road record (49-27), but they lost all six games they played
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Because they want to help determine their opponent next week,
the Braves are using their regular starting pitchers in this
series, Tom Glavine, Greg Maddux and Kevin Millwood. No break there
for the Mets, whose two-runs-a-game average in their six successive
losses represents their low point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, the Braves' manager, has another incentive for
keeping the Mets out of the playoffs. Like many managers, he
doesn't like his Mets counterpart, Bobby Valentine, and would be
delighted to help send him home for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have been as remarkable as the Mets have been dreadful.
Two days ago they beat St. Louis, 7-5, with a 12th-inning three-run
home run. Monday they overcame a 6-1 deficit and beat the
Cardinals, 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are playing relaxed, they're confident, they're
playing hard,'' Jack McKeon, the Reds' unlikely manager, said by
telephone from Cincinnati after the team's latest victory. ``We're
not thinking about anything but today. We're not thinking about the
Mets; we're not thinking about the Astros. Let the pressure be on
those guys. We weren't supposed to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   About a week and a half ago, McKeon expressed a ``gut feeling''
that the Reds would win the division title or beat the Mets for the
wild-card spot. The Mets thought his comments were good enough for
their bulletin board. So much for manufactured motivation.
</P>
<P>
   As well as McKeon has done in managing a low-payroll team to the
brink of the playoffs, his employer has not rewarded him with a
contract for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they'll talk after Oct. 1,'' he said. ``I guess I
have to show them I can do a good job. I guess they're still
evaluating me.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Mets' owners, in contrast, has said that no matter
how the Mets finish the season, their manager will be back next
year. Many people find it hard to believe that Valentine could
survive two consecutive collapses, but that's the word from Fred
Wilpon. Then again, if Valentine returns next year and manages at
least 135 games, he will move to No. 2 on the list of most games
managed without finishing in first place.
</P>
<P>
   And to think that the Mets went into their game in Atlanta a
week ago a mere game behind the Braves, and now the Braves come to
New York championship already in hand.
</P>
<P>
   If they do lose their chance to be the wild-card team, the Mets
will take their place alongside teams like the 1962 Los Angeles
Dodgers, the 1964 Philadelphia Phillies, the 1978 Boston Red Sox,
the 1987 Toronto Blue Jays and the 1995 California Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The '62 Dodgers had a four-game lead with seven games to play,
but the San Francisco Giants caught them when the Dodgers lost the
last four games. They also lost a three-game playoff to the Giants,
the pennant-deciding run scoring on a bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   The '64 Phillies led the N.L. by 6{ games with 12 to go but lost
10 in a row and the pennant. The '78 Red Sox squandered that
infamous 14-game lead over the Yankees and lost to the Yankees in a
one-game playoff for the division title.
</P>
<P>
   The '87 Blue Jays held a 3{-game lead with seven games to play
and lost all seven, including the last three to the Detroit Tigers,
who finished first.
</P>
<P>
   The '95 Angels forced a playoff for the division title by
winning their last five games, but that was after they had lost an
11-game lead they had in the second week of August.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections usually appear on page A2 of The New York Times, but
one correction would be more appropriately made here. Three weeks
ago in this space, it was written, with neither qualification nor
equivocation, ``The Mets will open one of two National League
division series four weeks from today.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of those words acknowledges the error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
