<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-ADS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GOOD, BAD AND UGLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ Turn to the pages of the thesaurus where synonyms for
``sexist,'' ``demeaning'' and ``stereotype'' are found. Dust off
the airbrushes for obscuring or deleting gratuitous pulchritude and
smarmy double-entendres. And cue the CD of movie theme songs by
Ennio Morricone. It's time for another annual installment of what
are called the Good, the Bad and the Ugly Awards, meant to
encourage improvement in how women are portrayed in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The awards, to be announced at a luncheon Tuesday at the New
York Hilton, are being presented for the third time by an
organization known as Advertising Women of New York. The effort
represents the first sustained attempt by women who work on Madison
Avenue to influence their colleagues to counter what the
organization calls ``the images we love to hate,'' among them ``the
babe, the superwoman, the be-bopping queen of everlasting
housework.'' &UR;  &LR;  The awards are also an effort by women in
advertising to offer ``attaboys'' _wait, better make that
``attagirls'' _ to marketers and agencies deemed to produce
campaigns that are more sensitive, inclusive and contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging by the entries submitted, the creative juices are
flowing in the right direction,'' said Jane Talcott, co-chairwoman
of the 1999 awards. ``But I would say we're not out of the woods
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be the media police,'' said Ms. Talcott, who
is also an executive vice president and creative director at the
New York office of Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising. ``We simply want to
say that someone's watching _ and consumers are watching, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter point is underscored with the release Tuesday of a
study of 556 young women conducted on behalf of Advertising Women
of New York by Smart Girl Internette Inc. in New York. For
instance, when the respondents were asked whether they had ``ever
seen an ad that made you feel like you needed to go on a diet,'' 55
percent replied, ``Yes, I see them all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's frightening,'' said Ellen Flahive, president of
Advertising Women of New York, adding that the study ``points to
the power advertising has to influence young women.''
</P>
<P>
   And the respondents, ages 12 to 19, described 13 ways that ads
``insulted'' them, ranging from portraying women as if they ``only
care about their looks'' to depicting models as ``too skinny'' to
skewing camera angles to ``focus on sexy body parts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there are marketers who are portraying women in a way
I'd like my son or daughter to see, but there's room for growth,''
said Ms. Flahive, who is also publisher of the American Park
Network in New York, a unit of Meredith &UR;  &LR; Corp.
</P>
<P>
   That seems clear from the ads declared ``bad'' by the judges, a
panel of 26 women that included an 18-year-old student in addition
to executives from agencies, consumer product companies and media
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The award for a single ad considered negative, the Grand Bad, is
being given to the Frito-Lay unit of Pepsico Inc. and BBDO New
York, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group, for a
television commercial for a barbecue-flavored Doritos snack chip.
The spot showed a library packed with male students studying human
anatomy in the form of the model Ali Landry as she sashayed by in a
slinky dress.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Bad for a campaign will go to Victoria's Secret, a
unit of Intimate Brands, and Tarlow Advertising in New York, for a
series of commercials that depicted pouty models strutting and
fretting in particularly revealing lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   Other ads being singled out for condemnation include a Super
Bowl commercial for the World Wrestling Federation, created
in-house, which featured female characters behaving like, well,
wrestlers, and a spot for Anheuser-Busch by Leap Partnership in
Chicago, a unit of Leap Group, which showed a man expressing his
love for his special lady by calling her ``Michelob.''
</P>
<P>
   The award for a single ad judged to be positive, the Grand Good,
is being given to a commercial by the Chicago office of FCB
Worldwide, part of True North Communications, that brought together
Michael Jordan and the soccer star Mia Hamm to enact a modern-day
version of the Irving Berlin song ``Anything You Can Do I Can Do
Better.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Women's World Cup soccer tournament, which was won
by Ms. Hamm and the other members of the U.S. team, generated
several ads that were praised by the award judges.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were two commercials centered on the U.S. team done
for Nike Inc. by Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore. The spots
carried the theme ``We will take on the world together,'' which was
exaggerated for comic effect; in one, a member of the team who
finds out from her dentist that she needs two fillings is joined by
her teammates who each proclaim, ``Then I will have two fillings.''
By the end, even the dentist's nurse-receptionist joins in.
</P>
<P>
   And the Grand Good for a campaign will go to the San Francisco
office of Leagas Delaney for four spots for Adidas, part of
Adidas-Salomon AG, which celebrated the players in the World Cup
tournament with humorous re-creations of their childhoods.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Apart from the awards ceremony and the release of the results of
the survey, the luncheon is also to include the showing of a
videotape from Leo She, a unit of Leo Burnett USA in Chicago _ part
of the Leo Burnett Co. unit of Leo Group _ that asked female
residents of Peoria, Ill., to respond to the judges' choices of
good, bad and ugly ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``They agreed on most counts, especially on the `goods,''' said
Denise Fedewa, vice president and planning director at Leo She,
``but they differed on some of the `uglies.'''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the New York women, Ms. Fedewa said, the Peoria women
``did not think it necessarily bad if the ads had strong sexual
aspects'' _ if the women were also ``portrayed as sexually
confident, using their sexuality as a source of power.''
</P>
<P>
   That was true, she added, even if, as in the Doritos commercial,
the models or actresses ``were in scanty clothes or bathing
suits.''
</P>
<P>
   So to advertisers asking the old vaudeville question, ``Will it
play in Peoria?'' the answer could be yes, if your female models
make up in self-confidence around men what they may lack in
clothing. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
