<HEADLINE>
HOW TO KEEP METS' SEASON IN PERSPECTIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-COLLAPSES, BBN-METS) 
(nk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fred and Judy Wilpon celebrated their 41st wedding
anniversary Monday. The Wilpons celebrated with a romantic dinner
and pleasant thoughts about all the beautiful things they shared: a
good marriage, a long marriage, three children and their
grandchildren. For at least an evening the Wilpons could put the
dismal events of the last week behind.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day Fred Wilpon, co-owner of the Mets with Nelson
Doubleday, conceded that he could not entirely stop thinking about
a disastrous stretch of six days that began last Tuesday in Atlanta
and ended, six consecutive losses later, in Philadelphia. The worst
was a devastating loss on Sunday that ended when Rickey Henderson
hit into a game-ending double play with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit here and tell you I didn't think about
it,'' Wilpon said. ``I thought about it all last night, in the
middle of the night. I replayed the game 100 times. But we'll get
up and play tomorrow. Yesterday is yesterday. Today is the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The lightning rod question is the fate of the Mets' manager,
Bobby Valentine. After the club's fifth consecutive loss on
Saturday, Valentine, in an emotional, unsolicited post-game
interview, said that if the Mets failed to make the playoffs he
should be removed as manager.
</P>
<P>
   For Valentine critics, the comment illustrated the manager's
fragility under pressure and a self-centeredness.
</P>
<P>
   For Valentine supporters _ and Wilpon says he is in this group _
the manager's comments underlined a deep emotional commitment to
his team, to winning and, yes, to pursuing a goal that has eluded
him for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not just in this for the paycheck,'' Wilpon said. ``The
way Nelson and I judge personnel is on productivity and the way
people handle themselves. Bobby has executed his job beautifully.
He cannot hit, he cannot run. He managed them well. He's coach them
well and prepared them in every way. He's done a good job. A week
ago we wouldn't be having this conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Shea Stadium Monday afternoon, a trickle of fans stood
at the ticket window to buy post-season tickets. Despite the recent
tumble the Mets are sold out for the first playoff game, if there
is one.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Meyers said he was keeping the faith, but barely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this point it's a bit of a long shot,'' he said.
Meyers blamed the Mets' tumult on Valentine. ``The players are
really struggling; they definitely look scared. But I think the
manager looks more scared than the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely seems that the manager has been panicking a
little bit also.''
</P>
<P>
   ShoAQ &QC; 59Me
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
