<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-ART-NYT     09-27 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORCED TO STAND ALONE, U.S. TEAM STANDS TALL
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ben Crenshaw awoke Monday morning, the United States had
still won the Ryder Cup. Crenshaw, however, should be excused if he
pinched himself.
</P>
<P>
   So many visions will linger from Sunday. Who will forget
Crenshaw kissing the 17th green at The Country Club in celebration?
Or the normally placid David Duval pumping his fist, holding his
hand to his ear, urging the already delirious crowd to cheer
louder? Or the 45-foot birdie putt at No. 17 by Justin Leonard, a
putt that will be shown over and over into the next millennium?
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup brings out the best in golfers. It moves them to
tears, unites them toward a common goal, and elevates their games
to heights that create compelling theater. The United States pulled
off the greatest comeback in Ryder Cup history, overcoming a 10-6
deficit to win by 14{-13{. A team that had been criticized for
being disjointed and underachieving rose to silence its critics
with each roar from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick and tired of hearing everyone saying we weren't a
team,'' Duval, who made some poignant comments during the Saturday
night team meeting that helped galvanize the United States, said.
``I said: `I think we're better. Let's go show it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Duval and company did show it, and in a memorable way. Despite
the inspired nature of the victory, two hard facts also led to
Sunday's turnaround. The United States had the stronger and deeper
team. And in the singles format, when every player was forced to
stand alone, the Americans' edge in talent finally showed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the matches that looked like mismatches on paper were
also mismatches on the course. As expected, Davis Love III beat
Jean Van de Velde, Phil Mickelson handled Jarmo Sandelin and Tiger
Woods beat Andrew Coltart. Van de Velde, Sandelin and Coltart had
been benched by the European captain, Mark James, until the
singles, and it was easy to see why. James knew his team wasn't as
deep as the United States' team all along, so he rode his top
players and tried to build a lead big enough to last during
Sunday's final round. It nearly worked.
</P>
<P>
   As dominant as the Americans were on Sunday, winning the
singles, 8{-3{, Europe still came within a half-point of retaining
the cup. Had the Europeans gotten just a half-point from Sergio
Garcia, Lee Westwood, Darren Clarke, Jesper Parnevik or Miguel
Angel Jimenez on Sunday, they would be celebrating instead of the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, America's top players lifted a heavy burden, bringing
the United States its first Ryder Cup victory since 1993. It was
easy to gauge how badly the Americans wanted to win, not only by
how hard they played, but also by how hard they celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   No one should blame the Europeans for being angry about the
celebration scene on the 17th green after Leonard's putt. Jose
Maria Olazabal was still facing a birdie putt that would have kept
Europe's chances alive had he made it, and it was premature for the
players and the wives on the U.S. side to mob Leonard as if the cup
had already been won.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone with a pulse probably would have reacted the same
way. It was such an improbable putt, at such an opportune time,
that it was impossible for the Americans to hold their emotions in
check. The celebration had no impact on the outcome. But the
Europeans will certainly remember it, giving them even more
motivation for the 2001 Ryder Cup at The Belfry in England.
</P>
<P>
   No player is happier that the next Ryder Cup will be in England
than Colin Montgomerie, who showed not only talent, but heart,
playing superb golf while being rudely heckled by American fans.
The sooner that kind of behavior ceases, the better. Perhaps the
only drawback to golf's increasing popularity is that a few
ignorant fans have been drawn to the sport as well. Montgomerie
showed restraint by not reacting to most of the comments, but
Parnevik, who lives in Florida, could not believe some of the
things he heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of the American on the European team, and I had a lot
of friends in the crowd,'' Parnevik said. ``They were embarrassed
to hear some of the heckling that happened to Monte. I can
understand the Americans root for the Americans. But it should
never get personal, not in golf anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the actions of the minority did not spoil a
memorable weekend for the majority. And not only will the 1999
Ryder Cup be remembered as one of the greatest, but the year in
golf has been one of the greatest as well. All four majors had
riveting finishes.
</P>
<P>
   At the Masters, it was Olazabal, proving he was all the way back
from health problems that threatened his career, outlasting Greg
Norman, who showed resiliency by almost winning a tournament that
has caused him major heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Open, it was Payne Stewart making the putt of his
career to beat Mickelson, who played a brilliant tournament knowing
that his wife was due to deliver their first child.
</P>
<P>
   At the British Open, it was the incredible collapse by Van de
Velde at the 72nd hole, who tripled-bogeyed to set the stage for
Paul Lawrie's victory, yet handled a crushing defeat with grace and
humor.
</P>
<P>
   At the PGA Championship, it was the classic back-nine battle,
won by Woods, who continued to be the world's best player, over
Garcia, who is certainly the world's best teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ryder Cup may have topped them all. The Europeans may
grow tired of hearing and seeing Leonard's putt. But Leonard and
his teammates never will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
