<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-BRIDE-SLAIN-NYT     09-27 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BRIDE-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAIL IS $5 MILLION IN KILLING OF BRIDE-TO-BE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Agustin in 2nd graf cq.) 
(nk) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ A prominent businessman charged with
murdering his former girlfriend on her wedding day was ordered held
on $5 million bail Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As sheriff's deputies escorted the suspect, Agustin Garcia, 47,
into court here, his friends and business clients in the
Dominican-American neighborhood of Washington Heights in Manhattan
said they were shocked at the charges against him. The authorities
say that on Sunday, he fatally shot the woman, Gladys Ricart, 39,
as she was about to marry another man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh God, oh man, I can't believe this, Agustin,'' Fernando
Mateo, a Dominican businessman in New York, said after he learned
of the charges in a call to the Dominican-American Chamber of
Commerce in Manhattan. ``I'm in a state of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo and others who have known Garcia for years said he
immigrated to the United States in poverty as a teen-ager and then
spent his adult life developing businesses that helped other
Dominican immigrants in New York City. He owns a multipurpose
service center called Ilusiono, in Washington Heights, that helps
Dominicans with taxes, legal problems, airline tickets and
immigration problems.
</P>
<P>
   The center was closed Monday. Some of the customers who stopped
by were in tears. ``I feel bad for this woman, but I'm crying for
Garcia,'' Dulce Minior, 49, said.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pagan, 23, said: ``I'm shocked and very depressed. I believe
that everyone who knows him here feels that way. He's a decent,
hard-working, honest man.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this decade, Garcia, of North Bergen, N.J., served on a
committee that advised New York Gov. Mario M. Cuomo on relations
with Dominican residents. He is executive vice president of the
Dominican Associations, a nonprofit center in Manhattan that
provides immigrants with computer training and English-language
instruction. He is also president of the Dominican-American Chamber
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a hard-working, amicable guy with lots of energy,'' said
Apolinar Trinidad, who served on the Cuomo advisory board with
Garcia. ``There was no indication he had any personal problems or
that he would react violently like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Until early this year, he and Ms. Ricart were fixtures at social
and political gatherings in Washington Heights, friends said. They
apparently began their relationship in the late 1980s or early
1990s, after he was divorced and began raising his children, a
daughter, now 19, and a son, 15, as a single parent, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Ms. Ricart, an accountant at a Manhattan travel
agency, broke off their relationship and began seeing a Brooklyn
man, James L. Preston, 36. They were to be married on Sunday in
Queens. Ms. Ricart, her bridal party and family members were
minutes away from leaving her home in Ridgefield, N.J., when Garcia
arrived at the house uninvited. He entered the living room as Ms.
Ricart was posing for pictures in her wedding gown, took a
.38-caliber pistol from a leather bag he was carrying or from a
pocket in his suit and fired two shots at Ms. Ricart, an assistant
prosecutor, James V. Santulli, said Monday in court. Santulli said
the authorities believe that both shots hit her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ricart's brother, Juan, began grappling with Garcia,
Santulli said. As they struggled, three more shots were fired, and
the authorities believe that one of those bullets also hit Ms.
Ricart, he said.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy showed that bullets struck Ms. Ricart in the right
arm, back and head, and she died instantly, Santulli said.
</P>
<P>
   During Garcia's court appearance, Santulli told Judge William C.
Meehan that the prosecutor's office was considering seeking the
death penalty. Santulli said the suspect had stormed into Ms.
Ricart's home and started shooting in a room full of adults and
children. ``This was a person who was out to kill the victim,''
Santulli said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's lawyer, Fernando Oliver, said that his client did not
intentionally shoot Ms. Ricart. Oliver said that the shots were
fired after Garcia and Ms. Ricart's brother began struggling and
said, without elaboration, that ``certainly some self-defense
issues are involved.''
</P>
<P>
   As he granted Santulli's request for bail of $5 million, Meehan
called the shooting a ``horrendous event.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This should have been one of the happiest days of her life.
Instead, it was the last day of her life,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
