<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-KEY-WEST-SEWAGE-ART-2     09-27 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEY-WEST-SEWAGE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEWAGE POLLUTION TAINTS PARADISE IN FLORIDA KEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. _ For a minute or two, as the tall, tanned,
beautiful woman from Norway splashed and laughed in the shallows,
it was just another picture-postcard moment in the blue-green
waters of Key West.
</P>
<P>
   The vacationing Norwegian, Linda Eng, had not seen the signs on
George Smathers Beach that warned that this water she was wading in
was swimming with potentially deadly bacteria, and she was still
flashing a 60-watt smile when a passerby told her that the placid,
inviting water was contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Human feces, she was told.
</P>
<P>
   Her smile turned upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take a shower now,'' she said, looking stricken.
</P>
<P>
   Signs warning of that hazard have been posted most of the summer
on beaches on this coral rock island of Key West, perhaps the most
storied and romantic tropical hideaway in the eastern United
States. Earlier this month, health officials posted more signs on
beaches on Marathon and Tavernier Keys, after water there showed
fecal contamination.
</P>
<P>
   In Key West, antiquated, leaking sewage lines are allowing raw
sewage to seep into the shallows, and work crews are tearing up
streets all over the city to repair the sewer system, a project
that the state _ even before this crisis _ordered the city to
complete by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials are still trying to determine why the
human waste showed up in the Upper Keys off Marathon and Tavernier,
closer to the Florida peninsula. Probably, Keys residents reason,
it is coming from old septic tanks and sewer lines there, too,
overwhelmed by overdevelopment, and never compatible with the high
water table and porous limestone ground in the first place. It is a
serious health risk. E. coli bacteria, found in human waste, can
kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young children and the elderly are at the most risk,'' said
Stephanie Walters, administrator for the Monroe County Health
Department, ``especially children, because they tend to drink the
water while they are swimming.'' The bacteria in the water can
cause nausea, diarrhea, ear and eye infections and respiratory
illness, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The contamination has had only a minor impact on tourism _ in
part because vacationers usually learn about the hazard only after
they have arrived, in part because most people who come to Key West
are more interested in diving in cleaner reef waters offshore _ but
the hazard has prompted some to cut vacations short, hotel managers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come all this way, just to find a sign on the beach with
a skull and crossbones,'' said Carl Hiaasen, the best-selling
novelist whose books on South Florida, beginning with ``Tourist
Season'' and, more recently, ``Lucky You,'' have harpooned
politicians and developers for their ruination of Florida's
ecology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a toilet is flushed in the Keys, these E. coli
paddle out on their little surfboards,'' said Hiaasen, who lives in
Islamorada in the Upper Keys and writes a popular, politically
acerbic column for The Miami Herald. ``We're poisoning it,'' he
added, more seriously. ``It's heartbreaking.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the Key West Hotel and Motel Association, expected
soon, will determine how much contaminated beaches are costing the
Keys in tourism dollars, said Jack Smith, the association's
executive vice president. But more than money is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the thing that kills the Keys if we don't do
something about it,'' said Nora Williams, the Monroe County
commissioner who called for water testing earlier this year. She
did that, she said, because the water looked dirty, something other
Keys residents have noticed with increasing dismay. Water is what
lures people here, to live or to play.
</P>
<P>
   Although the city of Key West has an airport that can handle
commercial jets, many people choose to drive down from Miami,
across a connect-the-dots highway of bridges, more than 120 miles
in all, that link the island chain with the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Look to the west, driving from the peninsula to Key West on
Route 1, and small, green islands stretch across the shallows
toward Florida Bay and the Gulf of Mexico. Look to the east, and
the Atlantic shimmers blue toward a seemingly endless horizon, but
with Cuba just 100 miles away. Some islands are barely wider than
the road, with just enough room between asphalt and open water for
tiki bars, charter-boat businesses and, of course, real estate
offices.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to believe, floating in such beauty, that it is still
paradise, residents here say, but for a long time, it has been
changing. Route 1 creeps with bumper-to-bumper traffic, even on a
weekday afternoon, the convertibles and rental mini-vans of
tourists sandwiched by trucks hauling mobile homes and concrete. At
night, on Marathon Key, it is possible to hear the electricity hiss
and buzz through the power lines as it travels from the peninsula
to the bars on Key West's Duval Street, where the venerable Sloppy
Joe's, where Ernest Hemingway drank, now shares the street with the
Hard Rock Cafe and Planet Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bureau of Economic and Business Research at the
University of Florida, the 1990 population of Monroe County, which
includes the Keys, was 78,000 people, and environmental groups were
screaming that the chain of islands, with so little dry ground, was
overdeveloped. In 1998, the population of the islands had swelled
to 85,646.
</P>
<P>
   In April, there were 27,698 people living in Key West, compared
with 24,832 in 1990. But in Key West alone, more than 18,600
visitors a day, on average, fill the island, according to the Key
West Planning Department.
</P>
<P>
   To see the impact, just stroll to any canal. ``In the past
couple of years, I've seen largely reduced visibility and increased
murkiness,'' said Ms. Williams. ``Most visitors would not notice it
_ people thought it was so clean they could drink from it _ but it
has become pretty noticeable to natives and residents.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Key West City Commission voted unanimously last week to put
a bond referendum on the Nov. 2 ballot, asking voters to decide if
the city should borrow up to $23 million to accelerate work on the
sewer lines and upgrade the city's sewage treatment plant.
Elsewhere in the Keys, county officials have a block-by-block plan
to repair damaged and obsolete sewage systems, said Jack Teague,
environmental administrator for Monroe County.
</P>
<P>
   What is really needed is a new waste-water treatment plant for
the Upper Keys, some residents and environmental groups say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother Nature is saying, `Enough is enough,''' said Lynne
Cameron, who heads a privately financed social service agency in
Miami, but lives part of the week in Tavernier.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Decker, who lives in Marathon and heads the local advisory
council to the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary, has seen the
canal behind her home grow murky, and the fish and lobster
populations there have dwindled. ``I feel like many people were in
denial,'' Ms. Decker said. ``They didn't feel like it could happen
here. It kind of contradicts what the Keys are about.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It only became a real issue, said Hiaasen and others who live
here, when it became an economic one. ``The sad truth is, this had
been around for a long time,'' Hiaasen said. ``They only just
started testing for it. Some people were actually upset that the
news was published before Labor Day. God forbid we should warn
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But even then, city and tourism officials have put a positive
spin on it. ``I've read that the beaches here are closed, but none
of the beaches are closed,'' said Smith, of the Key West Hotel and
Motel Association. Sunbathing, he said, is perfectly safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he added, ``going in the water is another story.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoteliers are taking the threat seriously, posting the warning
at front desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our grim days this year,'' with cancellations, said
Mike Proimos, general manager of the Marriott Casa Marina Resort in
Key West. But like many others here, he points out that Key West
has much more to offer than beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Diving trips to the coral reef that runs alongside Key West have
been mostly unaffected, because that water is not tainted with the
feces, and the Key West bars _ the real reason many people come
here _ are still open. Like New Orleans, Key West is one of those
cities where it is common, if not acceptable, for people to be
dog-drunk at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come down here because they like the atmosphere, the
landscape, the partying,'' Marshall of Sloppy Joe's said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would still go swimming. It wouldn't bother me,'' he said.
``You don't see raw sewage floating around beside you or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   At night, people still gather to watch the sunset, drinks in
hand. But Smathers Beach was recently deserted, except for a
middle-aged couple who were very careful not to get their feet wet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-27-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990927.0499 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-27 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8337 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PATAKI-NYT &LR;      09-27 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP MORRIS LINKED TO GROUP THAT PAID FOR GOVERNOR'S TRIPS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four years ago, Gov. George Pataki took a widely
publicized trip to Hungary to promote trade and trace his roots in
the homeland of his paternal grandparents. Newly elected, the
governor cut a triumphant swath through the country, meeting
political leaders in Budapest and distant cousins in ancestral
villages. A year later, he visited again.
</P>
<P>
   The governor emphasized at the time that the trips did not cost
the taxpayers a cent. A nonprofit group called the
Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce of New York and New Jersey
agreed to shoulder the costs for him and a handful of family
members and aides, and Pataki dismissed criticism about accepting
such a gift by asserting that the chamber had no business before
the state. A state ethics panel, working with information from the
governor, concurred and gave its blessing.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, though, never learned that before the trips, the
chamber had gained a benefactor: Philip Morris, the cigarette
giant, which has long been a powerful lobbying force in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the first trip in September 1995, the company
contributed $10,000 to the chamber, having never given to the
3-year-old group before, according to Philip Morris. A few weeks
before the second trip in October 1996, the company contributed
$10,000 more, and it gave another $10,000 a year later.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Philip Morris sent a senior executive who was
overseeing the lobbying of New York and other state governments to
attend a dinner for Pataki in Budapest on the 1995 trip.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki declined to be interviewed for this article. His press
secretary, Michael McKeon, said the governor and his aides were not
aware of the donations and had not asked the chamber about its
backers. ``Did we know about the chamber's fund-raising or who was
giving?'' McKeon said. ``An emphatic no.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the trips has never been made public. McKeon said
the governor would not disclose how much the chamber paid and would
not ask the chamber to make its finances public. He said Pataki and
his aides had not helped the chamber raise money and had strictly
adhered to the ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber would not discuss its finances, the cost of the
trips or whether the Philip Morris money had been spent on them.
But the group's tax records show that it financed few other major
events or functions in those years and that Philip Morris' $30,000
in donations amounted to nearly 30 percent of the chamber's entire
revenues in that period.
</P>
<P>
   The tax records also show that the chamber was spending nearly
everything that it took in: After receiving the $30,000 and paying
for the trips and other expenses, the chamber had $543 in the bank
at the end of its fiscal year on Sept. 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The donations would be in violation of the ethics rules if it
could be shown that they were linked to the trips. A spokeswoman
for Philip Morris, Tara Carraro, said the company did not give the
donations to underwrite the trips, adding that it routinely
contributed to such trade groups.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carraro said she did not believe that the company had taken
part in any other chamber functions besides the 1995 dinner in
Budapest.
</P>
<P>
   While the state Ethics Commission permitted the trips, one of
the members who voted on it said after being told of the Philip
Morris donations that they were troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ethics Commission should at least go back and see if
having known that, they would have voted differently,'' said the
member, the Rev. Robert E. Eggenschiller, a Republican who was on
the panel from 1992 to 1997. ``Why was there this sudden infusion
of cash? What was the purpose? Were they just being generous? Or
was there some ulterior purpose? Were they, in a sense, lobbying?''
</P>
<P>
   The ethics rules prohibit administration officials from
accepting gifts of $75 or more from companies with business before
the state. The rules also bar officials from directing that a
nonprofit group receive a gift that they cannot legally accept. A
separate state law requires that companies disclose all spending on
lobbying of state officials, including funds funneled through third
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, the maker of Marlboro and other cigarettes, has
vigorously opposed anti-smoking measures in Albany, and some health
groups contend that its lobbying explains why New York's
anti-smoking programs and laws lag behind those in some other big
states. In July, The New York Times reported that from 1993 to
1996, at least 115 members in the 211-member State Legislature had
accepted gifts from the company, including meals at expensive
restaurants and tickets to sporting and cultural events.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, in response to a state inquiry prompted by
the Times article, the company acknowledged that it had not
disclosed all its spending on lobbying the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carraro, the Philip Morris spokeswoman, said the donations
to the chamber did not violate any ethics or lobbying rules because
they were unrelated to the company's activities in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the governor's trips, Philip Morris was trying to
win passage of sweeping measures in Albany that would have repealed
smoking restrictions in New York City and other localities,
replacing them with weaker statewide rules.
</P>
<P>
   The less restrictive statewide measures generally had the
support of Pataki, a Republican, and Republican lawmakers, who have
maintained good relations with the tobacco industry. In the end,
Democrats blocked the measures.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki revealed little about the costs or financing of the trips
to Hungary, other than to say that the chamber of commerce was
paying for it. He said he did not want the state government to pay
for the travel _ even though, he said, New York would benefit from
the increased trade ties with Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having the Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce pay
for the trip makes perfectly good sense,'' Pataki said at the time.
``We could justify it as a government expense, but I wouldn't do
that. And I think this is a better way for taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   He did tell the state Ethics Commission how much the chamber was
paying, but under the law, the commission does not release that
information.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Founded in 1992, the chamber says it promotes the interests of
American companies doing business in Hungary by sponsoring trade
missions, forums and other activities. Its officials say it now has
roughly 125 members, many of them small companies and individuals
paying dues of under $1,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris was different. For instance, the $10,000 it gave
on Sept. 15, 1995, about a week before the first trip, was 26
percent of the chamber's total revenues for its fiscal year _
$38,287, according to its tax filings.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Monika Szarka-Elling, the chamber's
president, would not discuss its membership, budget or the
financing of the two trips. She said that she did not know why
Philip Morris contributed but that the Pataki administration had
not helped the group to raise money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
