<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TAMPA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRABU FAILS TORRE'S CHALLENGE AS YANKS FALL, 10-6 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was nothing Hideki Irabu could do Monday night
to force himself into the rotation for the post-season. The Yankees
will use four starters and Irabu has been the fifth option for more
than a month. What Irabu is trying to prove to Manager Joe Torre is
that he deserves to be on the 25-man roster as a long reliever.
Even that possibility is looking rather dubious now.
</P>
<P>
   Torre basically challenged Irabu to approach the start against
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays as a game the Yankees desperately needed
to win, but the pitcher lasted only two dreary innings. While Irabu
almost certainly could have pitched longer, Torre did not want him
on the mound any more. Torre appeared to be tired of Irabu's
pitches straying out of the strike zone after he was seemingly in
control of both innings and tired of Irabu's sluggish body
language.
</P>
<P>
   That the Yankees lost to the Devil Rays, 10-6, for the third
straight game at Yankee Stadium was not as meaningful as Torre's
strong message to Irabu. Torre wants a starter he can trust to
relieve one of the other starters if there is an injury or a
disastrous playoff outing, but Irabu has not shown that he can be
that emergency arm and is in a perilous position after allowing
five earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Ed Yarnall's second major league start Monday night
has become more than an innocent outing in the last week of the
regular season. The 23-year old Yarnall is supposedly going to face
the Baltimore Orioles in order to give the other starters extra
rest. But Yarnall has impressed Torre and a stellar outing could
move the left-handed rookie ahead of Irabu as the 10th pitcher for
the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (94-62) slipped one game behind the Cleveland
Indians (95-61) for the best record in the American League and the
right to the home field edge during the playoffs, and they are only
one game ahead of the Texas Rangers (93-63). When Torre was asked
about Irabu's struggles before the game Monday night, he stressed
the importance of the outing for the pitcher and the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see him tonight,'' said Torre. ``We need this game.
I know our magic number is three. It's like we don't need a lot. We
need this game. We want to win. We want to win three games. We
can't rely on anybody else to do this for us. We need this game. I
hope he comes out of the bullpen with that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre was speaking with reporters, but this was as much of a
challenge as the shrewd manager will ever make to a player. Irabu
did not meet the challenge. With two out in the first, Irabu had an
0-2 count on Jose Canseco. The Yankees have implored Irabu to
continue attacking when he is ahead in the count, but he stopped
challenging Canseco and walked him. Fred McGriff followed by
smashing a 1-0 fastball over the center field fence for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Irabu repeated himself. With two outs, he walked
No. 8 batter Mike DiFelice on five pitches. After Aaron Ledesma
blooped a single to center, Miguel Cairo looped a single to shallow
right. Paul O'Neill made a one-bounce throw home, but it was
slightly to the right of the plate and DiFelice barreled into
catcher Jorge Posada and knocked the ball loose to score the third
run.
</P>
<P>
   As the inning unraveled, Irabu remained stoic. The streak of
bloop singles reached three when Dave Martinez dropped a 150-footer
in front of Ricky Ledee in left to score two more and put Tampa Bay
ahead, 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   How irked was Torre with Irabu? He summoned Jeff Juden, a
journeyman who had a 5.56 earned run average at Class AAA Columbus,
for his Yankee debut in the third. Juden's first warmup sailed to
the backstop, which seemed fitting. The Yankees, who trailed 5-0
and then 8-2, briefly made the game entertaining with a late rally,
but the early damage against Irabu (11-7) was too much to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in Irabu's last four starts that Torre
removed him after two innings. Torre lamented that the Yankees do
not know why the Japanese pitcher has sputtered in the second half
of the last two seasons, but he is 2-4 with a bloated 7.30 ERA over
his last 10 starts. Torre was searching for reasons to trust Irabu
in October. He is still waiting and time might have expired.
</P>
</TEXT>
