<SLUG> BC-FREE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEOWNER RELEASED FROM JAIL AFTER VOLUNTEERS CLEAN YARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 by DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Frances Jane Todd, the 76-year-old
grandmother jailed for a trashy yard, is out of the poky.
</P>
<P>
   For that she can thank Joe Rawie, a man she had never met.
</P>
<P>
   On a rainy Monday morning, Rawie sent his construction crew _
and a few borrowed workers _ to clean the woman's south Kansas City
yard. In a steady drizzle, they hauled off three dump-truck loads
of trash and debris. They trimmed trees, fixed windows and mowed
weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Todd was released about 5 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could see the moon, I would jump over it,'' said Todd,
who had been incarcerated at the Kansas City Municipal Corrections
Institution since Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Free Frances'' effort began when Rawie, 35, a construction
contractor from De Soto in Johnson County, woke up Monday and read
about Todd in The Kansas City Star.
</P>
<P>
   He also listened to radio station Q-104's Randy Miller, who put
out a call for volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Todd, who had a long history of property-code violations, had
been sued by the city. She lost the case, and 90 days later, with
the yard still trashed with old tires, boards and concrete blocks,
a judge found her in contempt and sent her to jail until the work
was done.
</P>
<P>
   Five adults who live at the house or stay part time _ a
daughter, a son, two grandchildren and a family friend _ had been
slow to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Rawie got on the phone to his crew members, who typically do not
work in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing something special today,'' he told them. Then he
called other contractors. D.F. Freeman Contractors of Shawnee
volunteered two tandem dump trucks and drivers. Shawnee Mission
Tree Service sent trucks and workers.
</P>
<P>
   By 8 a.m. the convoy was rolling. It soon arrived at Todd's
house on a narrow, tree-lined street in the Ruskin Heights area.
</P>
<P>
   The job took four hours. As the group worked, more volunteers
arrived to help.
</P>
<P>
   Rawie gave Todd's relatives a new lawn mower. And then, he said,
he gave them ``a little preaching.''
</P>
<P>
   He told them they should do more to take care of Todd, that they
should not take her for granted. Keep her yard mowed and trash
picked up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do this one time,'' he told them. ``I don't want to have
to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Vassey, the family friend who stays at the house, said he
and others helped with the work. Shirin McCormick, Todd's daughter,
offered thanks to everyone who wanted to help.
</P>
<P>
   Rawie started Blacktop Paving and Construction, based in Eudora,
Kan., four years ago. Business has been good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it was time to give something back to someone who
needed a little help,'' said Rawie, who estimated the job cost him
$1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Don't call him a hero, he said. Plenty of other people would
have done the job had he not.
</P>
<P>
   From the number of telephone calls and e-mails received at The
Star, it appeared that Rawie was right.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors, social clubs, individuals, senior citizen groups,
college students and families called to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Some were outraged at Holly Steinhauser, an assistant city
attorney, for pursuing Todd. But most blamed Todd's relatives for
not working harder to get her released.
</P>
<P>
   And some pointed the finger at Todd. It's about time the city
cracked down on those who do not keep their property clean, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City is a great place to live, and we all have to get
along,'' Martha Sharp said. ``Sometimes, it takes somebody like
Holly Steinhauser to come along and make tough choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd has promised to keep her place neater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do my darndest,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
