<SLUG> BC-BBN-SERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS WILL PLAY FOR KEEPS AS THEIR ERA ENDS IN THE DOME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Today is cq in lede) 
 
By DAVID BARRON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Today begins the final week in the final season of
Astros baseball at the Astrodome, but who cares about nostalgia
when there's a playoff race afoot?
</P>
<P>
   It is the sharp reality of the here and now, rather than warm
fuzzies from 35 years of Astrodome memories, that consumes the
Astros and their fans with the Cincinnati Reds coming to town for
two games beginning Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the Astros spent their day off Monday at pitcher
Shane Reynolds' benefit golf tournament in Fort Bend County, the
Reds threw the National League Central race into a flat-footed tie
with a 9-7 win over the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's sixth victory in seven games, coupled with the
Astros' six losses on a just-completed nine-game road trip, put
both teams at 94-63 entering Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing. They (the Reds) don't want to go away,'' said
pitcher Jose Lima, who starts for the Astros tonight. ``They're
playing with heart, and when you do those little things, you're
going to win ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly catching them with a lot of momentum, and
hopefully they might play themselves out,'' said Astros manager
Larry Dierker. ``We have to turn it around. We haven't been playing
well, and I'm sure they will come out foaming at the mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros ran off a team-record 12-game winning streak earlier
this month, but Cincinnati stayed afloat with a 10-3 record over
the same time frame. And since that time, the Reds have won eight
of their last 12 while the Astros have dropped seven of 10.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, the idea of celebrating Houston's baseball
history must take second fiddle to preserving Houston's baseball
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought is not that the Dome is leaving. It's us getting
into the playoffs,'' said Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell. ``I'd
rather have a three- or four-game lead, and if we had played a
little better on the road, we would have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've backed ourselves into the position that we're in
right now. We knew it was going to be a big series. Now it's going
to be a bigger one.''
</P>
<P>
   It's appropriate that in the final year of Astros baseball at
the Astrodome, the team concludes with two games against the Reds
and three against the Los Angeles Dodgers on Friday, Saturday and
Sunday. Both teams have played critical roles against the Astros in
Septembers past.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1979, the Astros built a nine-game lead over the Reds in
July, only to have Cincinnati pitcher Tom Seaver predict they would
fall like a ``lead balloon'' in September.
</P>
<P>
   They did. The Astros lost the lead, pulled back within 1 1/2
games with a 3-2 win Sept. 19, 1979, before 46,178 fans, split the
next two games at home, then went on the road and stumbled again.
They eventually finished a game behind Cincinnati and missed the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nineteen years ago Monday during the magic season of 1980, the
Astros celebrated the return of J.R. Richard to the Dome for the
first time since he suffered a stroke in July. The Reds were in
town for the game, and Houston beat Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the Astros took to the road for a three-game trip
to Los Angeles needing just one victory to clinch the NL West
title. They lost three in a row to the Dodgers, how-ever, and
required a one-game playoff win over L.A. for the first playoff
berth in team history.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1981, the Astros held off the Reds down the stretch to win
the second-half division championship during a strike-interrupted
year. However, they lost the divisional playoff series to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   September has been kinder to the Astros the last two years, with
back-to-back division titles. Both, however, were clinched with
several days left in the season and were followed by playoff
collapses against Atlanta and San Diego, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, whose annual tournament last year raised more than
$100,000 for the Epilepsy Foundation of Southeast Texas, said the
closer race could benefit the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won it kind of early in the past and had some down time
going into the playoffs,'' he said. ``This year we'll see what
we're made of. With the Reds playing well and coming in for two
games, we'll see how hard we play and see what we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell suggested the day off could give the Astros a chance to
recuperate mentally from recent setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get away a little bit,'' he said. ``We didn't
play well on the road, so to take a day off and to realize what's
going on, where we have to go and how to get there will be a nice
reflection and get us ready to strap it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game is a sellout except for general admission seats
in the outfield pavilion, but a few tickets remain for Wednesday's
game against the Reds. Tickets also remain for the Friday and
Saturday games against Los Angeles. The Dome regular-season finale
on Sunday is a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have worked at the Astrodome for 35 years will be
honored Friday night. Sunday afternoon will feature pre-game and
postgame ceremonies, and gates will open at 10:30 a.m., an hour
earlier than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can purchase a commemorative 150-page souvenir program and
have their program or game ticket embossed as an authentic souvenir
of the final regular-season Dome game. They also can purchase a
commemorative photograph to go with their ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Charley Pride will sing the national anthem Sunday, and a
90-minute postgame celebration will include a video tribute,
introduction of the Astros' all-time team and a performance by
Willie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, celebration may not be the operative word if the
Astros can't stop their tailspin beginning tonight against the
Reds. But 20-game winner Lima seems to think they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the situation, and I'm going to do it in front of
everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He will be followed on the mound Wednesday by the Astros' other
20-game winner, Mike Hampton. On their performances, and those of
their teammates, hinge a season of baseball and the chance to
celebrate 35 years of memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two guys have to go out there and pitch for the day.
What they've accomplished earlier doesn't mean anything,'' said
outfielder Carl Everett. ``The goal is to win. I don't put any
emphasis on anything else. I go out there to win for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
