r s BC-FBC-SCNOTE-LADN     09-27 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT SAYS HE'LL MAKE CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC coach Paul Hackett promised there would be
changes in playing time after Saturday's loss to Oregon, thanks to
the Trojans' school-record 21 penalties.
</P>
<P>
   So what changes are planned for this week's game against Oregon
State?
</P>
<P>
   Hackett wouldn't be specific, but one of the more noticeable
differences is expected to be a larger role for freshman linebacker
Troy Polamalu.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Sultan Abdul-Malik was flagged for a personal foul
against Oregon after clearly making a tackle out of bounds. And he
had three penalties the week before against San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   Polamalu had a forced fumble, sack, broke up a pass and recorded
four tackles against Oregon. Abdul-Malik had two tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Another area ripe for change is the secondary, where cornerbacks
Antuan Simmons and Kris Richard each had three penalties against
Oregon. True freshmen Darrell Rideaux and Kevin Arbet are healthy
and figure to get an opportunity this week.
</P>
<P>
   The offense is a more dicey proposition. Nearly every offensive
lineman was guilty of a false start, so it's hard to single out one
target. Likely players to benefit from changes are tackle Matt
Welch and guard Faasea Mailo.
</P>
<P>
   __ Practice makes perfect: Kicker David Newbury and long-snapper
Pat Swanson worked on their timing Monday, after Swanson had
several poor snaps against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat and I talked about that and he said he was sorry, and we
decided we were going to get in extra practice,'' Newbury said.
</P>
<P>
   Especially damaging was a poor snap that cost USC an extra point
after the Trojans took a 23-20 lead in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat said he gripped the ball too tight,'' Newbury said.
</P>
<P>
   Newbury took the blame for the missed field goals, however, and
said he knew something was wrong leading up to the Oregon game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This past week, I could tell something was there,'' Newbury
said. ``I was hitting the ball with a funny rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he is leaning against reopening the kicking job and
letting kickoff specialist David Bell have a chance to win the
position.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rough weekend: It was an injury-marred three days for the
family of USC quarterback Carson Palmer. Before Palmer broke his
collarbone against Oregon, his younger brother Jordan suffered a
concussion Thursday playing quarterback for the Santa Margarita
High junior varsity team.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fox is No. 2: Senior John Fox, who started nine games in
1997, is back at quarterback full-time thanks to Palmer's injury.
He has also been practicing at linebacker this year.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on game circumstances, Hackett said he might try to
give Fox playing time against Oregon State behind starter Mike Van
Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 3 quarterback is walk-on Matt Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nervous,'' Hackett said about the Trojans' quarterback
depth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
