<HEADLINE>
THE GUGGENHEIM PROPOSES GEHRY MUSEUM FOR NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL with CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum has submitted a
proposal to the city for a dramatic new curvilinear building
designed by Frank O. Gehry that would rise as high as 45 stories on
a platform over four East River piers near Wall Street in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The project, larger than one the museum had envisioned last year
for a West Side pier, has been budgeted at about $850 million and
would contain large exhibition wings, a theater, a skating rink and
other public amenities, according to an internal financial
memorandum and accounts from officials familiar with the plans.
More than a third of the cost has already been privately pledged,
said the officials, who estimated that the complex could take six
years to build.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Krens, the director of the Guggenheim, declined to
publicly discuss the proposal, one of nine for the site. The city's
Economic Development Corp. is expected to select one within the
next few months, but a spokeswoman, Bernadette O'Leary, declined to
give detailed descriptions of the proposals, which include a hotel,
a cruise-ship dock and an aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim complex would be substantially larger than the
$100 million free-form museum that Gehry built for the institution
in Bilbao, Spain. Opened in 1997, the 250,000-square-foot Bilbao
museum with its rakish silhouette and titanium skin has been widely
hailed as one of the 20th century's architectural marvels and draws
more than 1.4 million visitors annually to the revived Basque
riverfront city.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry fended off questions about the project as premature.
``We're studying the way you build a building over the water and
need some input from City Planning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph B. Rose, chairman of the City Planning Commission, said
the proposal had not come before the panel and that he could not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   A model of the Gehry design has been on display in Krens'
office. It showed a cloudlike shape out of which the building rises
irregularly to a maximum height of about 45 stories. The structure
is on a platform above the piers.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-page Guggenheim financial memorandum, sent anonymously to
The New York Times and authenticated by the museum, also cites
plans for two other Guggenheim projects, an arts and technology
center on piers in Brooklyn Heights and exhibit space on Governors
Island, which the city has been seeking to redevelop since the U.S.
Coast Guard abandoned the island a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Cox, a deputy director of the museum to whom the June 24
memorandum was addressed, acknowledged receiving it from its
author, Beverly M. Wolff, a museum consultant, but said that Ms.
Wolff merely ``speculated on the potential development of related
sites, including Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cox added: ``That memo represents purely internal ideas that
emerged from a brainstorming session. They were entirely
speculative and have not been developed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wolff did not respond to a message left on her home
telephone Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Krens has taken the Guggenheim into a vigorous expansionist
phase, adding far-flung branches to its core location on Fifth
Avenue at 89th Street. Last year he explored building a
Gehry-designed museum on Pier 40 on the Hudson River off Houston
Street. But other groups had already made recreational proposals
for the site, and with city and state officials miffed that the
Guggenheim had not cleared its plans with them beforehand, the idea
languished.
</P>
<P>
   The new concept for the East River site was submitted to the
Economic Development Commission in February in response to a
request for proposals inviting bidders interested in developing the
site. The property includes three piers: 9, which is decrepit; and
13 and 14, with tennis bubbles on them. A fourth pier, 11, is being
retained by the city as a ferry terminal, but would be integrated
into the Guggenheim plan.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials have briefed some outsiders on aspects of the
plan on a confidential basis, and Newsweek published a short
account of the project on Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Wolff's memorandum was titled ``Naming Opportunities for the
Manhattan Projects.'' While suggesting how big donors might be
attracted to a $700 million fund-raising campaign, Ms. Wolff
enumerated the features of the proposed Gehry building, which would
serve as a largely autonomous branch to the museum's flagship,
designed by Frank Lloyd Wright. The Guggenheim already has a SoHo
annex, which the museum has periodically considered closing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to exhibition wings and galleries, she wrote, the
building would include a theater that could be sponsored by an
entertainment giant like Sony, Samsung or Warner Bros.; a grand
entry hall and visitor's center; an arts education center; a
sculpture or photography gallery; a film department; a library and
study center; an entertainment hall or boardroom, and a members'
lounge. The memorandum also cited a new department of architecture
and design, suggesting that the Guggenheim might be moving into a
field long identified with the Museum of Modern Art. Outside there
would be a promenade, sculpture garden, park and skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   The other projects mentioned were a proposed Center for Arts and
Technology envisioned for piers 1 through 5 in Brooklyn Heights,
and eight ``pavilions'' on Governors Island, where the Guggenheim
would display art.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wolff urged the museum to seek three ``founders'' who
together could put up $450 million, just over half the latest
anticipated cost. Although the Guggenheim has not approached the
city for money, the Museum of Modern Art has been promised $65
million in city money for its $650 million expansion and the
Guggenheim could be expected to request the same 10 percent
contribution, or about $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wolff argued against seeking to name each project for one
large donor. ``Rather,'' she wrote, ``I would recommend that
serious consideration be given to using generic names for each
complex, with naming opportunities relating only to parts of the
complex.'' Thus, she noted, the wings and each gallery within them
could be separately named.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Goldstein, the district manager of Community Board 1 in
lower Manhattan, said that residents primarily sought parks and
open space. ``We didn't want any kind of structure more than a few
stories,'' he said. Forty stories, he said, was ``huge.'' But he
perked up at the mention of Gehry, whom he called admiringly ``that
architect with the great reputation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
