<HEADLINE>
GROWING COMPETITIVE PRESSURE FUSES 2 GERMAN CONGLOMERATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In one of the most dramatic signs of the
pressures on European industry, the German energy and chemical
conglomerates Veba A.G. and Viag A.G. agreed Monday on a $14.1
billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Though big, the merger itself was not the big news. Perhaps more
significant was the context: a competitive new market for
electricity in Germany that has driven prices down by 30 percent in
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Equally startling were the two companies' plans for structural
overhaul. Their executives plan the biggest single sell-off of
``non-core'' businesses that Europe has ever seen. All told, the
plan calls for selling off almost everything outside of energy and
chemicals _ businesses ranging from aluminum production to trucking
and mobile telephone service _ with combined annual sales of nearly
$30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover still requires approval by German competition
regulators, who have already warned that the companies must do more
to open the electricity networks to rivals.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger is approved, Veba, based in Dusseldorf, and
Munich-based Viag would become the third-largest electric power
utility in Europe, after Electricite de France and Enel of Italy.
The new electricity company would have sales of about $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On the chemical side, the two companies would have combined
sales of $13 billion and be the world's third-largest chemical
producer. Veba owns Degussa-Huels, itself the product of a long
restructuring that included the sale of numerous subsidiaries and
the acquisition last year of Degussa. Viag owns SKW Trostberg.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, company executives said Monday that they will
keep the chemical companies separate but have them work together.
</P>
<P>
   A key impetus for the merger is the intense competition now
underway in the German electricity market. More than any other
country, Germany has deregulated the electricity market and
produced a wild spree of price-cutting as former regional
monopolies attack each other's markets with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   The competition has sent prices and revenue tumbling at most
major utilities _ including Veba's Preussen Elektra and Viag's
Bayernwerk, which serves Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Size matters, especially in the energy sector,'' said Ulrich
Hartmann, chairman of Veba, at a news conference Monday. ``It's
only by growing and by exploiting synergies that we will be able to
compensate for declining earnings brought on by increasingly
vigorous competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed merger, Viag shareholders will receive on
Veba share for every 2.8 Viag shares they own. Though the new
company will be run by both Hartmann and Viag's chief executive,
Viag's Wilhelm Simson, Veba will have control of the supervisory
board with seven out of ten seats on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Veba shares jumped 3.2 percent Monday to 55.2 euros, while Viag
shares declined 3.8 percent to 19.48 euros.
</P>
</TEXT>
